<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIALLO-SHOOTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICER CHARGED IN DIALLO SHOOTING IS CLEARED IN A '97 KILLING
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Brooklyn district attorney said Monday that one
of the police officers charged with murdering Amadou Diallo in the
Bronx two months ago had acted properly when he fatally shot
another man in Brooklyn in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Saying that he was closing the investigation of Officer Kenneth
Boss' shooting of Patrick Bailey without presenting the case to a
grand jury, District Attorney Charles J. Hynes said that ``the
facts of this case demonstrate it was reasonable'' for Boss and
other officers at the scene ``to believe that Bailey posed an
imminent threat to them and to others.''
</P>
<P>
   This was so, Hynes said, because Bailey, who was 22 and was shot
in a hallway of his building in East New York, pointed a shotgun at
a civilian witness and the police.
</P>
<P>
   The shotgun turned out to be unloaded and inoperable, but those
facts ``could not have been known to the police officers'' in their
confrontation with Bailey in October 1997, the prosecutor said.
</P>
<P>
   Hynes' conclusions, after a long-delayed investigation, were
denounced by a spokesman for Bailey's family. The spokesman,
Charles Barron, a community organizer in Brooklyn, said the
prosecutor's decision not to present the case to a grand jury was a
``gross miscarriage of justice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To have District Attorney Hynes act as prosecutor, grand jury
and determinator is insane,'' Barron said. He said Hynes' report of
the investigation contained contradictions that Bailey's family _
whom Barron described as ``outraged'' _ would point out at a news
conference Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Boss' lawyer, Steven Brounstein, said Hynes' action ``was
expected, and we're pleased.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All along we were aware that my client acted in a reasonable
manner,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting of Bailey took place on the night of Oct. 31, 1997,
when Boss was among four officers approached by a man who said
Bailey had menaced him with a shotgun during a dispute, according
to Hynes' report.
</P>
<P>
   When the officers went with the man to the front of Bailey's
building, they saw Bailey ``holding a shotgun in his hand'' and
followed him when he ran into the building, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the officers with Boss said they saw Bailey point the
26-inch sawed-off shotgun at the officers. The report quotes Boss
as saying that he fired three shots after he saw Bailey ``pausing
in the hallway of the house with the shotgun still in his hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of the shots struck and killed Bailey; the third missed.
</P>
<P>
   Boss and three other officers are charged with murder in the
death of Diallo, a 22-year-old unarmed immigrant who was killed in
the lobby of his building in early February.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
