A7264 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MENTAL-HEALTH-NYT &LR;      04-06 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MENTAL-HEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUBWAY DEATH MAY PUSH NEW YORK TO MANDATORY MEASURES 
</HEADLINE>
  (With NY-SUBWAY-ATTACK) 
(mk) 
 By SERGE SCHMEMANN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The case of a schizophrenic man who is accused of
pushing a woman to her death under a subway train in January has
generated new interest in proposals authorizing involuntary
treatment for mental patients in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The measures include one initiated by Attorney General Eliot
Spitzer, who took office immediately after the Jan. 3 incident in
which Kendra Webdale, 32, was pushed off a subway platform.
</P>
<P>
   On videotape and in written statements, Andrew Goldstein, 29,
confessed to having pushed Ms. Webdale. Goldstein told police that
a psychotic episode caused him to believe that a ``spirit or
ghost'' had entered his body and forced him to commit the act.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday in state Supreme Court in Manhattan, Goldstein was
found competent to stand trial on a charge of second-degree murder.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer's proposal would enable relatives and doctors to compel
the mentally ill to receive treatment and medication. As state laws
stand now, involuntary treatment is largely limited to patients who
are considered a threat to themselves or others.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Connelly, an Assembly member from Staten Island, has
introduced a bill to extend and expand a five-year-old pilot
program at Bellevue Hospital Center for involuntary outpatient
treatment. The state Legislature is not likely to embrace changes
in the system fully during this session, lawmakers say. But there
is support for extending the Bellevue program.
</P>
<P>
   James Brennan, a Democrat from Brooklyn who is chairman of the
Assembly's Committee on Mental Health, said the Bellevue program
had not demonstrated that it was necessary now to authorize
statewide involuntary treatment for mental patients.
</P>
<P>
   But he added that the Bellevue program did provide one important
lesson: that mentally ill patients, once released from hospitals,
would maintain their treatment regimen so long as they have support
services, like intensive case management and occasional home visits
by a nurse. ``So my position is that it should be incrementally
expanded to see if there is further value to it,'' he said. Brennan
said he has proposed legislation that in addition to extending the
Bellevue program by a few years would start similar programs at
four unspecified institutions.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is also being carefully considered by Gov. George
Pataki. Chuck Deister, a spokesman for the governor, said the
administration was in the midst of drafting a proposal but offered
no details other than to say it was intended to provide a sound
approach to involuntary treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The effort to change state laws is strongly supported by many
mental patients' families, who now are powerless to initiate
treatment for relatives too ill to recognize they need it. The
proposals are fiercely opposed by a small but vocal number who see
any enforced treatment as a violation of fundamental civil rights
and a regression to the thinking that fostered the insane asylums
of the past.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of the new measures invoke images of people like
Goldstein, who drifted from treatment to treatment until a ``ghost
or spirit or something like that,'' as police reported he said, led
him to push a total stranger to her death. In the parlance of
mental treatment, Goldstein was noncompliant: He did not stay on
his medication.
</P>
<P>
   The supporters include an unlikely combination of psychiatrists
who believe in the efficacy of new medications, and law-and-order
conservatives who want to get the mentally ill off the streets.
Their group also points to the large number of people with mental
disorders among prison inmates and the homeless, arguing that many
of them might be safer if they were compelled to take medication.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past 10 years, it's been firmly established that mental
disease is a neurobiological condition,'' said Carla Jacobs, a
director of the National Alliance for the Mentally Ill, the largest
group advocating involuntary commitment. ``So we have to start
looking at mental illness like any other disorder. If I have a high
fever, people would take me to the hospital and give me medication
until I could continue or discontinue it on my own. But we don't do
that in mental illness. We put a special shroud on the ill, we
treat them like lepers, and we cloak inaction with false ideas of
human rights.''
</P>
<P>
   The opponents invoke the images of the cruel asylums of the past
_ images that generated a powerful movement in the 1960s against
the enforced institutionalization of the mentally ill and emptied
many state institutions. Many also cite reports of patients who
suffered terrible side effects from medications, or were abused in
public institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an assumption on the part of psychiatrists and the
mainstream and family members that if a person doesn't take
medication, they `decompensate,''' said Rosary Marinaro, mocking
the term used in psychiatric treatment to describe patients who
revert to unstable behavior. Miss Marinaro, a woman with
schizophrenia, has campaigned against the proposed laws, and is a
leader of the Coalition to Stop Outpatient Commitment
</P>
<P>
   ``There are alternatives,'' she said. ``But the alternatives
challenge the medical professions _ things like peer support,
peer-run services. I have chosen not to take medication. They told
me to take lithium. But my friend is dead, she went into renal
failure, she died last year. I choose. That's the point. I
choose.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the late 1970s, 37 states have enacted widely varying laws
on involuntary treatment. But New York has remained without one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason people reacted against institutionalization of the
mentally ill in the 1960s was the realization that you want to be
compassionate,'' said Brian Stettin, the assistant attorney general
who drafted the law proposed by Spitzer. ``But it's a heck of lot
more compassionate to realize their need for treatment, rather than
the `freedom' to destroy themselves. What we're trying to find is a
common-sense happy medium.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
