<SLUG> BC-GIVING-INCREASE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUOYED BY STOCKS, FOUNDATIONS INCREASE THEIR GIVING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By REED ABELSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The nation's foundations, reaping the benefits of a
robust stock market, gave away a record amount of money last year,
according to a recent study.
</P>
<P>
   Foundations made an estimated $19.5 billion in grants in 1998 to
not-for-profit organizations, up from $16 billion in 1997,
according to the Foundation Center, a New York group that tracks
foundation giving.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last two years, giving has climbed by about 41 percent,
resulting in an additional $5.6 billion in grants, according to
Foundation Center estimates. The center, which follows more than
44,000 grant-making foundations, based its 1998 estimates on survey
responses from about 1,000 foundations. The figures from 1997 and
earlier are based on all of the foundations' financial records.
</P>
<P>
   The increase in giving is largely a result of the huge growth in
the stock market over the last few years, which has fattened
foundation assets and made donors increasingly generous, according
to Sara Engelhardt, the president of the Foundation Center.
Foundation assets reached a record $329.9 billion in 1997, while
gifts and bequests from donors were at near-record levels of $15.8
billion.
</P>
<P>
   While foundations have been criticized for not spending enough
of their money, they are starting to give away their new-found
gains, Ms. Engelhardt said. ``This is the money that is not just
being stockpiled,'' she said. ``This is money that is being turned
around to benefit society.''
</P>
<P>
   By law, most foundations must give away at least 5 percent of
their assets, and they are giving away slightly more than that, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's largest foundation is the Lilly Endowment, whose
assets have soared to $11.5 billion in 1997 from $6.8 billion in
1996 with the rising price of Eli Lilly &AMP; Co. stock. The
endowment's giving climbed to $254 million in 1997, an increase of
about half over the previous year. In 1998, its beneficiaries
included the United Negro College Fund, which received $41.7
million, and an assortment of private colleges in Indiana, which
received $90.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Community foundations, which give money at the local level, are
also ``gaining a lot of steam,'' Ms. Engelhardt said. In 1998, they
gave away about $1.5 billion, compared with $1 billion two years
ago. They, too, have benefited as donors have felt more generous
and have been able to pass on that largess. ``It is being spread
out to more communities,'' Ms. Engelhardt said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
