<HEADER>
A7273 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PALESTINIAN-BONDS-NYT     04-06 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PALESTINIAN-BONDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALESTINIANS PLANNING TO OFFER BONDS ON EUROPEAN MARKETS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAMALLAH, West Bank _ The Palestinian Authority hopes to cover
part of a $150 million budget deficit this year by selling the
first Palestinian bonds, the authority's financial affairs chief
said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the so-called sovereign debt markets would represent a
breakthrough for the Palestinian Authority, which has been unable
to raise money on the markets with its ambiguous status as a
semiautonomous territory controlled militarily by Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The finance official, Mohammed al-Nashashibi, said the
Palestinian Authority expected to pay most of its bills with tax
revenue, including income from official import monopolies that had
gone unreported in previous budgets. Nashashibi spoke as he
submitted his 1999 budget to the legislative council here Monday.
But a projected 10 percent increase in tax revenue is not keeping
up with a 25 percent jump in the state payroll this year, and
foreign donors are no longer willing to bridge the gap.
</P>
<P>
   Nashashibi said in an interview that governments, which he would
not name, were prepared to provide backing for Palestinian bonds,
which would be sold in European financial markets. He said he was
now negotiating the size and pricing of a bond issue with major
investment banks that are prepared to serve as underwriters. The
bonds, to be denominated in either dollars or euros, could be
issued as soon as June, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian Authority's leader, Yasser Arafat, is expected
to postpone a long-discussed declaration of independence from May
4, which falls in the closing weeks of an unanticipated Israeli
election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Routine expenses in the Palestinian region are met largely from
sales taxes and customs levies collected by Israel but passed on to
the Palestinian treasury under an agreement. But the authority,
with no uncontested claim on sovereign property or financial
assets, cannot provide collateral for a commercially viable bond
issue on its own.
</P>
<P>
   There is some precedent for securities from poor nations to be
backed by wealthier creditors, such as the Brady bonds from Brazil
and Mexico, which carried repayment guarantees from the U.S.
Treasury. But these were still bonds issued by independent states,
with their own national assets and formal standing in the World
Bank and the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians face several hurdles to selling bonds,
including getting a credit rating and ironing out all the legal
complications of a bond issue. An emerging markets analyst in
London, who spoke on the condition of anonymity, said that if these
problems were overcome, it was possible there might be a group of
Middle Eastern investors interested in buying such an issue,
despite the risks involved.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that Lebanon has sold small Eurobond issues at more
favorable interest rates than many Latin American countries because
there is a large number of Lebanese and other Middle East
expatriates willing to buy such debt securities.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the way to a bond issue would presumably be eased
if the United States or other countries decided to offer
guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian critics, echoed by overseers from Western aid
donors, have demanded a public accounting of hitherto-undisclosed
revenue from state agencies with exclusive rights to import and
distribute fuel, cement, tobacco and other goods. ``There is a
serious problem with fiscal transparency, or rather the lack of
it,'' said an expert with an international financial institution,
who also spoke on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Nashashibi did not mention plans for a foreign bond issue in his
address to legislators, who have two weeks to review the budget
plan. Arafat has already approved the spending plan, he said.
</P>
<P>
   With Arafat's supporters holding a solid majority on the
legislative council, approval is expected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
