<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PLAY-BALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: PLAY BALL! 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, April 6,
1999:
</P>
<P>
   If the 1998 season proved anything, it is that good baseball can
erase a lot of bad feelings. When the season began, the sport
seemed adrift, torn from its old moorings by too many labor
disputes, too many greedy owners, too many inflated salaries. Then
came the thrilling late-summer home run duel between Mark McGwire
and Sammy Sosa and the magisterial performance by the New York
Yankees, and all of a sudden baseball's disaffected fans came back.
</P>
<P>
   The new season that began in earnest Monday will not easily
replicate last year's heroics. Still, there are good young players
everywhere, a raft of slick-fielding shortstops and maybe a dozen
or so sluggers not named McGwire or Sosa capable of hitting 40 home
runs. For New Yorkers, there is at least a plausible chance of a
city series.
</P>
<P>
   If baseball has any problem that needs prompt attention, it is
the growing disparity between the rich and poor teams. Of the 13
teams with payrolls above $48 million last year, only one had a
losing record. Of the 17 teams below $48 million, only two had
winning records. Something is clearly amiss when the Los Angeles
Dodgers are paying one player, Kevin Brown, $15 million _ just
slightly less than the $17 million Montreal is paying its entire
team.
</P>
<P>
   The highest payroll, not surprisingly, belongs to the Yankees,
who are paying $85 million to a supremely talented group of players
who are early favorites to repeat as World Champions. The only
question mark surrounding the Yankees is whether their unflappable
manager, Joe Torre, can recuperate quickly enough from cancer
surgery to rescue the team from a nasty feud between the crusty
interim manager, Don Zimmer, and the volatile owner, George
Steinbrenner.
</P>
<P>
   The other day, after a spring training game, Steinbrenner called
one of Zimmer's pitchers, Hideki Irabu, a ``fat toad,'' then
reversed himself and brazenly suggested that Irabu start the
Yankees' third game in Oakland Wednesday night. Zimmer exploded,
telling Steinbrenner to stop the ``double talk'' while insisting
that he would run the team the way he wanted to. Nobody could
remember anyone challenging Steinbrenner like that before.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner's meddling has distracted the Yankees before. The
rest of the league should hope that he keeps it up. The Yankees
must hope for Torre's early return.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-99 0039EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990406.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 00:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7284 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     04-06 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONDESI SENDS BALL FOUR A LONG WAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ On the first home run, the one that tied the game,
the fastball was up around the chest, at best a marginal strike.
Which is right where Raul Mondesi likes it.
</P>
<P>
   On the second homer, the one that ended the game, the fastball
was on the inside corner, a pull-hitter's pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Which, as it happens, also is right where Raul Mondesi likes it.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, hell, ``I like anything,'' the right fielder admitted after
rescuing the Dodgers in an 8-6, 11-inning victory over the Arizona
Diamondbacks on opening day.
</P>
<P>
   That has long been the Mondesi story _ he's just a hitter who
can't say no.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers coaches have tried to train his eye for a pitch, to
teach this five-tool talent a little patience, but he has remained
a free swinger, theoretically to his detriment. In six major-league
seasons, Mondesi has drawn fewer walks (159) than Mark McGwire drew
last year alone (162).
</P>
<P>
   The team has lately seen progress. Mondesi did walk more
frequently this spring in Florida. And Monday afternoon he had
moments that suggested a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   In his very first plate appearance of the season, Mondesi worked
Randy Johnson to a full count, fouled off a pitch to stay alive,
then grounded an RBI single to left. In his third time up _
hallelujah! _ he walked.
</P>
<P>
   ``He stood there and made people throw strikes,'' Dodgers bench
coach Jim Tracy said later. ``If he does that, he's one of the most
dangerous hitters in baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   So must it not be a trifle disconcerting to the club braintrust
to know that Mondesi hit the big home run of the game _ which could
be as big a home run as any Dodger hits all season _ on ball four?
</P>
<P>
   It was the ninth inning, two out, runners on first and second,
Dodgers down 6-3. Arizona closer Gregg Olson had just struck out
Gary Sheffield.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi took, took, took. A 3-0 count.
</P>
<P>
   In the dugout, manager Davey Johnson, the man Mondesi calls
``(begin ital)Jefe(end ital) (Chief),'' twice flashed the
swing-away sign to third-base coach Rick Dempsey.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then,'' Johnson recounted, ``I turned and said, `Watch
this bomb.' ''
</P>
<P>
   If Mondesi had taken the letter-high pitch, he probably could
have walked to first base, and maybe Devon White would have been
the hero. But Mondesi swung and clubbed the pitch into the
left-field bullpen. After trailing 6-2, the Dodgers had made it
6-6.
</P>
<P>
   Only later did Mondesi reveal that he hadn't seen Dempsey's
sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it (the pitch) was anything close, I was going to swing,''
said the 28-year-old Dominican, who hit 30 home runs each of the
past two seasons and went 4 for 5 with six RBI Monday. ``I was
looking for something to hit hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, with two out and Sheffield on first in the 11th inning,
Mondesi yanked a 1-0 pitch from John Frascatore halfway up the
left-field bleachers.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi was greeted at home plate by everybody in a Dodgers
uniform. Nobody, presumably, was there to congratulate him on that
sixth-inning walk.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to belittle the Dodgers' effort to drum patience
into the 1994 National League Rookie of the Year. Look what
selective hitting did for the New York Yankees last year. More to
the point, perhaps, look what it did for Sammy Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   There are some in the Dodgers camp who believe if Mondesi does
finally take the advice to heart, it will be because of the example
set in '98 by Sosa, a fellow Dominican.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of similarities between the two players,'' Tracy
said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, before Sosa's 66-homer season, asking which of the two
was the better ballplayer was a good way to start an argument in
the Dominican Republic. Of that subject, Mondesi has heard just
about enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to think about Sammy,'' he said. ``I have my job
to do. He has his job to do.''
</P>
<P>
   And for most of the spring, Mondesi was plenty worried about
exactly what his job would be. Johnson _ (begin ital)El Jefe(end
ital) _ tried batting him third; but Mondesi's low on-base
percentage made such a spot so high in the order impractical. So
Johnson dropped him to fifth, with Sheffield third, Devon White
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi lobbied against fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Davey, `I want to hit third or fourth, because I want
to drive in runs.' ''
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, before the Dodgers faced the St. Louis Cardinals in
an exhibition at Jupiter, Fla., Mondesi got the good word: cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   It just might work.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by opening day, he should be under strict orders: Swing
at nothing but strikes _ or, if you prefer, swing at anything
close. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-99 0045EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990406.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 00:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7285 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LA-OPENINGDAY-LADN     04-06 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-OPENINGDAY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGER FANS HAVE A BALL IN OPENER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DOUGLAS HABERMAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Fidel Plascencia was tied up in court all day
Monday, fighting a traffic ticket. Victor Martinez flew up to Santa
Rosa in Northern California for a wedding. Karina LaFarga fell
gravely ill.
</P>
<P>
   At least their bosses thought so.
</P>
<P>
   All three were actually among tens of thousands of enthusiastic
Dodgers fans attending the sold-out opening game of the baseball
season at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``You gotta come up with your excuses ahead of time,'' said a
grinning Plascencia, of Whittier, 14 miles east of downtown.
</P>
<P>
   To the delight of 53,109 fans in attendance, the Dodgers needed
no excuses. Although the expected pitching duel didn't develop
between superstars Kevin Brown and Randy Johnson, outfielder Raul
Mondesi's two-out, three-run homer in the ninth and two-run homer
in the 11th carried the Dodgers to a dramatic 8-6 victory over the
Arizona Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   For Plascencia and hundreds of other fans enjoying tailgate
parties in Lot 37 east of the stadium, getting to the game way
ahead of time was part of the fun.
</P>
<P>
   Year after year, Dodgers die-hards gather in Lot 37 to toss back
a few beers before the first game, munch on food, reminisce about
seasons past and talk about the team's pennant chances.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's tailgaters were eager to catch the beginning of a
season they hope will end with the Dodgers in the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the year they are going to go all the way,'' said Pico
Rivera resident LaFarga, who wore a Dodgers shirt, as did many in
the parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   Miguel Salazar of San Gabriel, east of Los Angeles, said the
team owes a pennant to the fans this year, after several years of
less than optimal performance. ``They gotta be in the World Series
_ and they got a good chance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While some truant workers had to lie to see the game, many
didn't, including Krista Ebrecht of neighboring Orange County.
</P>
<P>
   ``My supervisor wanted to come with me,'' she said, standing
near a group of friends playing cards around an ice chest. But her
boss was unable to come. ``Couldn't get the day off,'' Ebrecht said
with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   While signs in the stadium parking lots prohibit tailgate
parties, security officers cruising Lot 37 didn't enforce the
prohibition. But they did keep the partying within limits, which
annoyed some fans.
</P>
<P>
   Tailgate beer-drinking before games is an American tradition at
every other stadium, said longtime fan Ed Stone. ``Out here it's
all Perrier,'' he sneered.
</P>
<P>
   Even as they hid their beer bottles, fans still managed to cook
up a good time.
</P>
<P>
   Savory smoke drifted skyward from a truck's tailgate as Adonis
Belt of Azusa barbecued about 10 lobsters as well as marinated
chicken and beef for 20 to 30 friends from the San Gabriel Valley.
They cut the meat up into chunks and rolled it into tacos with
lettuce, tomato and avocado.
</P>
<P>
   ``The food is too expensive inside the stadium,'' groused Jaime
Quintero of Rowland Heights. ``They're trying to price us out of
the games.''
</P>
<P>
   David Moreno of Yorba Linda said since Fox bought the Dodgers,
the team has been looking for any and every way to make an extra
buck while forgetting the loyal fans. ``It's a business, but still
...,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other fans expressed dismay that the Dodgers signed opening-day
pitcher Kevin Brown to a major league record $105 million,
seven-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's worth that,'' said Steve Martinez of La Verne.
``However, that's the way things are now.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on a plastic chair with another group, Victor Martinez
saw it differently, saying, ``As long as he can get the job done
...''
</P>
<P>
   Getting the job done for his friends meant no beer drinking _
cigar smoking only _ for Chuck Argelander of Glendora, who would be
driving home 13 other men in a friend's motor home. His
beer-chugging buddies said they forgave Argelander his rooting for
Arizona, as well as for the time after last year's first game of
the season when he sent about eight of his friends into the front
windshield when he braked suddenly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chuck's the designated driver _ we gotta be tolerant,'' said
Ron Weyant of Alta Loma.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his unhappiness over food prices and stadium security
officers, Jaime Quintero ultimately was tolerant of the Dodgers _
remaining a fan even though his family was forced out of Chavez
Ravine to make way for Dodger Stadium. And he loves opening day, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can take our hill,'' said Quintero, ``but they can't take
our partying.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
