<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 00:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7286 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-     04-06 1356
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS OPENING-DAY DIARY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Dodger opening day diary:
</P>
<P>
   11:30 a.m:
</P>
<P>
   I'm introduced to the new Dodgers manager, Davey Johnson, and he
tells me he and his wife are living in the hills above La Canada.
``The first thing I did when I started house-hunting in L.A. was
ask what were the busiest freeways,'' he confided. ``I was told the
busiest were the 5, the 10, the 101 and the 405. So I picked La
Canada, and it takes me only 15 minutes to get to Dodger Stadium on
the 134.''
</P>
<P>
   11:33:
</P>
<P>
   Another reporter walks in, and wonders if he can ask Johnson a
few questions. ``It's my policy to deal with the press while we are
out taking batting practice and even before that,'' says Johnson.
``But once I come back into the clubhouse, I gotta concentrate on
lineups and scouting reports.'' ``We used to talk to Tom Lasorda
almost up until the game started,'' someone said. ``I'm not as
smart as Lasorda,'' cracked Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   11:50:
</P>
<P>
   I run into my brand new pal, Kevin Malone now don't get mad,
Fred Claire and he admits to me that what I wrote several months
ago about Kevin Kennedy being his choice to be Dodgers manager
ahead of Davey Johnson was true. ``But I also wanted Felipe Alou,''
acknowledged the Dodgers general manager. As you might know, Alou
didn't want the Dodgers and Bob (Don't Call Me Rocky) Graziano, the
Dodgers president, didn't want Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Noon:
</P>
<P>
   Malone gives me a brief spiel on the glories of God, and how he
has been devoted to Him since 1979. The Dodgers are so different
now under Fox with World Wrestling Association music interspersed
with Nancy Bea Hefley's classic organ standards and the outfield
signage. But they also just might have a closer connection with
Somebody Up There because of the divine presence of the God-fearing
Malone.
</P>
<P>
   12:20:
</P>
<P>
   I chow down, but not exactly with ravenous delight. I've blown
five dollars on a lot of useless things in my life, but never on
food that was as nauseously bad as that chicken sandwich they were
serving in the pressbox Monday that, for sheer skimpiness and
putridness, is truly unrivaled in culinary history. How bad was it?
I would have a crisis of conscience feeding it to one of my
neighbors' dogs, much less a sportswriter.
</P>
<P>
   12:55:
</P>
<P>
   Someone purportedly named Randy Newman sings the National
Anthem. Alas, he sounds more like Kermit the Frog. The Randy Newman
I remember sang ``I Love L.A.'' with style and enthusiasm. This guy
impersonating Newman sounded as though he were auditioning for a
Godfather role on ``The Sopranos.''
</P>
<P>
   1:05:
</P>
<P>
   The old left-hander, Vin Scully, throws out the ceremonial first
pitch. Eric Karros, standing with teammates along the third-base
line, charges out and intercepts Scully's toss halfway to home
plate. It's one of the nimblest defensive plays I've seen Karros,
not exactly Mr. Twinkle toes, make.
</P>
<P>
   1:14:
</P>
<P>
   Play ball!
</P>
<P>
   1:16:
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Brown falls behind 3-0 on Steve Finley, but gets his
former San Diego Padre teammate on a fly to center.
</P>
<P>
   1:21:
</P>
<P>
   Eric Young works Randy Johnson for a walk to become the first
Dodgers base runner of the 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   1:22:
</P>
<P>
   Eric Young promptly steals second base, putting him on a pace to
break Maury Wills' team record of 104.
</P>
<P>
   1:28:
</P>
<P>
   Two outs later, Raul Mondesi smokes a single to left to make it
1-0 and make Davey Johnson look like a genius batting Mondesi
cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   1:30:
</P>
<P>
   Uh-oh. Diamondbacks seriously threatening against the $105
Million Man after Luis Gonzalez doubles, Bernard Gilkey singles and
Tony Batista walks to fill the bases with one out.
</P>
<P>
   1:34:
</P>
<P>
   No problem for a sinkerball master like Brown, who induces a
double play grounder out of the Arizona catcher, Kelly Stinnett.
</P>
<P>
   1:41:
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever happened to Tom Lasorda?'' the venerable pressbox
wise guy, Joe (The Big Nasty) McDonnell, cracks. Reportedly,
Lasorda was seen on the field before the game, but there was no
independent confirmation of such a sighting.
</P>
<P>
   1:47:
</P>
<P>
   Still another rare phenomenon. With two outs, Eric Karros steals
second against Johnson. And beats the throw easily! And you must
not forget I can out-run Karros. Rupert Murdoch can out-run Karros.
Why, that old codger Stu Nahan can out-run Karros!
</P>
<P>
   1:58:
</P>
<P>
   The $105 Million Man isn't exactly fooling the Diamondbacks.
After Jay Bell singles, Travis Lee rips a double that should score
Bell, but the team's super cautious third base coach, Brian
Butterfield, holds him up for reasons not discernible to the naked
eye. But Brown once again escapes a crisis by getting Gonzalez on a
groundout.
</P>
<P>
   2:00:
</P>
<P>
   Eric Young, who had walked, steals third base, putting him only
102 behind Wills. Gary Sheffield ends third inning Dodger threat by
grounding into double play.
</P>
<P>
   2:07:
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Gilkey rips one into the left-field pavilion to tie up
matters in the top of the fourth. In three plus innings, the $105
Million Man already has been touched for five hits.
</P>
<P>
   2:19:
</P>
<P>
   Who said that Devon White is old and washed up and not worth all
those millions the Dodgers showered on him in the off-season? Not
Randy Johnson after White touches him for a fourth-inning homer to
make it 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   2:33:
</P>
<P>
   Brown is under duress once again with two base runners on for
the Diamondbacks, but once again gets Gonzalez this time on a popup
to catcher Todd Hundley to escape trouble.
</P>
<P>
   2:39:
</P>
<P>
   The first reverberating boos of the season are heard when
Johnson plunks Young. Alas, Young's drive to overtake Wills is
stymied momentarily when he's finally caught stealing by the
Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   2:43:
</P>
<P>
   Gilkey hits another one off Brown, who's not exactly bewildering
the mighty Diamondbacks, only in their second season of existence.
</P>
<P>
   2:47:
</P>
<P>
   First beach ball hits the field. It lands in rightfield.
</P>
<P>
   2:53:
</P>
<P>
   Brown is in trouble again and this is a recording. He's facing
the dangerous Jay Bell with two runners on base. How long can he
keep walking such a tightrope without falling off?
</P>
<P>
   2:57:
</P>
<P>
   Not long. Jay Bell sends a towering fly ball into the left-field
pavilion for his team's third home run against Brown, and the $5
Million Dollar Man is gone to his $3.8 million Beverly Hills
mansion, having given up 10 hits in 5fr 2/3 innings of forgettable
work. The score is 5-2 when the new Dodger stopper makes his
ignoble exit.
</P>
<P>
   3:04:
</P>
<P>
   Gary Sheffield grounds into his second double play of the
afternoon. Obviously, Sheffield hits better playing in right field
instead of left, which he detests.
</P>
<P>
   3:23:
</P>
<P>
   Seventh-inning stretch time. Many in the crowd of 53,109 head
for the parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   3:25:
</P>
<P>
   With the count 1-1 against Hundley, Randy Johnson suddenly calls
a timeout, and repairs to the dugout for a few minutes to have his
strained groin re-tapped. I can't recall a baseball game ever being
interrupted for such a reason.
</P>
<P>
   3:28:
</P>
<P>
   Natch, Johnson strikes out Hundley when play finally resumes.
It's the third time in the game that Hundley has gone down
swinging.
</P>
<P>
   And we were all worried about his arm.
</P>
<P>
   3:56:
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers catch a huge break. Randy Johnson is pulled after seven
innings. Johnson's relieved troops quickly pull to within three
(6-3) on Eric Karros' one-out single against Darren Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   4:00:
</P>
<P>
   Guess what? Todd Hundley strikes out yet another time. I'm
wondering if Todd's dad, Randy Hundley, has been up there doing the
swinging for him. One thing already is apparent Todd Hundley is no
Mike Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   4:24:
</P>
<P>
   What a cleanup hitter Raul Mondesi is! His dramatic two-out,
three-run homer ties the game at 6, much to the delight of the
25,000 or so fans who are still in the stands and much to the
distress of those of us who've been pounding on computer keys for
more than four hours.
</P>
<P>
   4:30:
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, Todd Hundley actually can put his bat on a
baseball. He loops a single into left field, to avoid striking out
for the fifth time.
</P>
<P>
   4:58:
</P>
<P>
   Please, Raul, do it again.
</P>
<P>
   4:59:
</P>
<P>
   He does! Raaaoooooooool!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
