<HEADER>
A7288 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LB     04-06 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW DODGERS, OLD DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 53,109 who came out to see what's new at Dodger Stadium on
Opening Day on Monday went home talking about what's old.
</P>
<P>
   There was Kevin Brown to see, the free agent pitcher the
Dodgers' signed in the offseason to a baseball-record $105 million
contract. He showed enough to warrant a second look at his pay
rate, Dodger management is counting on it but left in the sixth
inning after allowing his third home run.
</P>
<P>
   There was Todd Hundley, the latest replacement for Mike Piazza.
The catcher struck out swinging four times in five at-bats. That
was one more strikeout than gangly, 6-foot-10-inch Randy Johnson,
Arizona's free agent answer to Brown, who handles a bat as if it
has thorns. One Johnson swing sent the bat flying foul over third,
but that was one swing better than Hundley had in his first four
at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   There was the new manager to see, Davey Johnson, who ran four
new relief pitchers to the mound after Brown, all of them
successful. There were the new murals of old Dodgers on the
outfield walls, strategically positioned to make the advertising
signage less noticeable. After the game, the song blaring in the
home locker room even had the refrain ``Change.''
</P>
<P>
   But at day's end, the fans were cheering one of the two lineup
regulars left over from days of yore, 1997. Raul Mondesi hit a
three-run home run with two outs in the ninth inning to tie the
game, then won it 8-6 with a two-run home run in the 11th inning.
</P>
<P>
   With Piazza the new Cover Boy for the Mets (a smoldering GQ
shot, presumably leading to many insightful articles in the New
Yorker) and Tommy Lasorda shoved so far in the background that you
can't even hear him (now that's deep background), (set ital) new
(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   has become the operative word Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   subu UF7 Old school
</P>
<P>
   So Mondesi's home run heroism was a pleasant reminder that new
doesn't necessarily mean improved, and that old isn't necessarily
bad.
</P>
<P>
   His game-tying home run in the ninth came on a 3-0 pitch. As any
regular fan of the Dodgers know, Mondesi has never been on speaking
terms with the base on balls. He has averaged one every five games
in his career. He was the Dodger least likely to leave the bat on
his shoulder in such a situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to wonder what (Arizona reliever Greg Olson) was
thinking,'' said first baseman Eric Karros, the other leftover.
``How many times have you seen Mondy take a walk? I think everyone
in the park except Olson knew he was swinging.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good pitch to swing on,'' said Mondesi. ``In that
situation, 3-0, two outs, it was my only chance to hit a home run
(in that at-bat). I was looking for the kind of pitch I could hit
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Even amid this nostalgia, there were new interpretations.
Mondesi has been so impatient and aggressive in the past that
managers like Lasorda and Bill Russell often forced him to take a
3-0 pitch, fearful he'd swing at any pitch in the same ZIP code.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson does not agree with this strategy. Having grown up
learning baseball from Hall of Fame manager Earl Weaver, whose
favorite strategy was the three-run homer, Johnson has instructed
his power hitters Mondesi, Karros, Gary Sheffield to be selectively
aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I flashed the swing sign twice to (third-base coach Rick)
Dempsey so he'd be sure to see it,'' said Johnson. ``And I told
someone in the dugout `watch this bomb.'''
</P>
<P>
   Mondy said he didn't even look at Dempsey, he was swinging if it
was anywhere close. ``If they gave it (the hit sign) to me, I
didn't see it,'' he said. Whatever. Olson's pitch was a high
fastball, and Mondesi crushed it into the back of the Dodgers'
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   subu UF7 Come from behind
</P>
<P>
   The other point is that the Dodgers rallied from a 6-2 deficit,
the kind of deficit which has dogged them the last few years (as in
rolling over like a dog). Whether it was Johnson giving Mondy the
hit sign or Mondy's own initiative, the Dodger rally was, well,
new.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Johnson) is the type of manager who will not take the bat out
of your hands,'' said Karros, who had an important RBI single in
the eighth. ``He's offensive-minded. And Mondy's an aggressive
hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, Karros cautioned everyone to take a deep breath and
remember that there are 161 games left in the season. To go with
any hype that one rally is a trend would also force one to say the
Dodgers misspent on Brown.
</P>
<P>
   subu UF7 Not all bad
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' new ace had his moments in his debut, working his
way out of bases-loaded jams in the second and third innings. He
was an out away from working out of another in the sixth when Jay
Bell hit a wind-aided fly ball just over Duke Snider's picture on
the outfield mural for a three-run home run.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Brown allowed just eight home runs in 257 innings.
Bernard Gilkey's two solo home runs impressed Brown more than
Bell's. ``I made a couple of bad pitches to Bernard,'' Brown said.
``I didn't think (Bell's) was a home run.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the few boos that met his departure bothered him, Brown
said he would have booed himself. Beyond that, there was no insight
to be learned. ``The pitches weren't winding up in the (catcher's)
glove as much as I wanted them to,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown isn't very tolerant of the deeply meaningful, wide-angle
question, those that try to wrap heavy fiscal pressure around a
couple of fast balls that stayed up on opening day. Frankly,
everyone, those asking and those answering, are a bit tired of
them.
</P>
<P>
   From diversity to global expansion to Iron John-type of manly
reflection on the essence teamwork and The Dodger Way, the Dodgers
have spent way too much time on the shrink couch the last few
years.
</P>
<P>
   Better that the effort speaks for itself. ``I've had bad days
before,'' Brown said, ``and I'll probably have another down the
line.'' The Dodgers didn't sign Brown for his quotability. They
signed him because he's mean on the mound and he wins.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven years removed from their last World Series, that may be
all anyone cares about around Dodger Stadium. That goes for new
players and old players, new manager and old manager, old fan who
hates the rock music between innings or new fan who has no idea who
Duke Snider is.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-99 0057EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
