<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7292 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-RANGERS-FLYERS-NY     04-06 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-FLYERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS TOP FLYERS, 5-1 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The New York Rangers are not out of the playoff
picture, not just yet. They eluded elimination on Monday night with
a 5-1 victory over the Philadelphia Flyers, who were playing
without several star players and in front of one shaky goalie.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers got goals from Kevin Stevens, Chris Tamer, Mathieu
Schneider, Adam Graves and Brian Leetch against Ron Hextall, who
backs up John Vanbiesbrouck and sometimes plays poorly against the
Rangers. The victory, breaking a two-game losing streak, left the
Rangers at 32-35-10, good for ninth place in the Eastern Conference
of the National Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   With 74 points and 5 games remaining in the regular season, the
Rangers trail both Boston and Buffalo by 9 points in the race for
the last two playoff berths in the East. Those two teams are tied
for seventh. Because the Rangers could finish with a maximum of 84
points, one more defeat would eliminate them, as would one more
victory by both the Bruins and the Sabres.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to try to win every game,'' said Stevens, who
opened the scoring in the opening minute with his 23rd goal of the
season. ``We hope some teams help us out.''
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia's Mikael Renberg ruined Mike Richter's shutout bid
with a power-play goal at 12 minutes 55 seconds of the third
period. Richter stopped the other 36 Flyer shots.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Gretzky of the Rangers got two assists but was knocked
down hard by a big check into the boards from Luke Richardson late
in the game. Gretzky was not available for comment afterward, but
John Rosasco, a team spokesman, said Gretzky felt soreness near the
protruding disk in his neck that caused him to miss 12 games this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries and missing players were a big theme on Monday night.
Petr Nedved of the Rangers missed his second consecutive game with
a strained rib cage muscle. Nedved's injury came against the New
York Islanders last Monday, one game after Eric Lindros and other
Flyers had worked him over with several hard hits before Lindros
cut Nedved with a high stick and earned a two-game suspension.
</P>
<P>
   After serving his suspension, Lindros returned for only one game
and sustained a collapsed lung that has left him in a Nashville
hospital since Friday. Lindros might be released on Wednesday, the
Flyers said, but he is out for the rest of the regular season, and
the playoffs are uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   Also missing for the Flyers was Mark Recchi, a forward who
played one game after returning from post-concussion syndrome. He
was out with a headache, the Flyers said. Eric Desjardins, their
top defenseman, was out with a left knee sprain. John LeClair, left
wing on the Lindros line, was out with a sore back.
</P>
<P>
   John Muckler, the Ranger coach, seemed irked when someone
suggested the Rangers had taken advantage of Philadelphia's
injuries. ``Our best player wasn't in the lineup,'' he said,
referring to Nedved. ``Their best player wasn't in the lineup,'' he
said, referring to Lindros.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Gary Dorshimer of the Flyers' staff said on Monday that he
had spoken by telephone with both Lindros and the doctor in
Nashville who is treating him. Lindros slept about five hours
Sunday night, Dorshimer said, and his pain is ``well controlled''
with medication. Although Lindros became ill in his hotel room
after the game in Nashville, it was unclear what caused the injury
or when it occurred. Dorshimer said Lindros may have had a broken
rib that went undetected and caused the bleeding in the chest
cavity that led to the collapse of the lung.
</P>
<P>
   ``His blood count continued to remain stable,'' Dorshimer said
in Monday's medical update, ``telling us any active bleeding is no
longer present.'' Lindros still has a tube in his chest.
</P>
<P>
   Whether they were capitalizing on the Flyer injuries or not, the
Rangers held a 2-0 lead after one period on two fluke goals, the
first by Stevens, the second by Tamer. Stevens scored with a
backhander from the right-wing corner at the 32-second mark after a
poor clear by Hextall, who could not get back to his line in time
to set up properly.
</P>
<P>
   In his previous appearance here, Stevens scored over the
shoulder of Vanbiesbrouck with a deflected blooper that the goalie
did not see until he fished it out of the net. ``I've had some
beauties here,'' Stevens said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers made it 2-0 at 4:27 on Tamer's first goal of the
season, a long backhander from the center red line that Hextall
touched with the catching glove on his left hand but failed to
stop. ``I flipped it up in the air and got a little lucky,'' Tamer
said. ``Ten years from now, I'll embellish the story a little bit.
They're all pretty, as long as you get to celebrate.''
</P>
<P>
   New York made it 3-0 at 10:14 of the second when Schneider
converted a rebound of a Gretzky shot. Graves made it 4-0 at 15:07
on the power play with his 37th goal of the season, most on the
team, off a rebound of Leetch's shot. Leetch scored his 11th, on
the power play at 16:18 of the third, his second goal in two games
after not scoring in the previous 23.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
