<HEADER>
A7295 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LA-GORE-LADN     04-06 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-GORE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN L.A., GORE ASSAILS HEAD OF YUGOSLAVIA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY RICK ORLOV  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Vice President Al Gore brought his presidential
campaign to California on Monday, offering strong words for
Yugoslav leader Slobodan Milosevic and sympathy to Albanians and
the East Los Angeles family of POW Andy Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's 10th visit to the state as a presidential candidate also
found him announcing with Gov. Gray Davis that waivers will free up
$129 million in federal money to reduce high school math and
English class sizes in California.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the crisis in Kosovo that drew most of Gore's
attention during a day where he met with a dozen reporters in
round-table discussions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard to imagine in the closing years of the 20th century
that we would see this level of misery and evil,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy (Milosevic) cannot begin to imagine what we will do
to destroy his dictatorship. These crimes against humanity cannot
be allowed to stand. We will make sure they aren't.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said the Clinton Administration has no plans to send ground
troops into the troubled region that has been beset by hundreds of
thousands of refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Gore met Monday with Albanian-Americans to offer assurances the
United States is doing all it can to provide relief and is
committed to making sure the refugees are allowed to return to
their homes once the war is concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Gore talked with the family of Staff Sgt. Andrew Ramirez
in East Los Angeles. Gore said he wanted to protect the family's
privacy and would not disclose any details other than to say the
government is doing all it can to ensure his safety and that of two
other POWs and seek their early return.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president also mixed in some presidential politics
during his visit with a $1,000-a-person fund-raiser at the Beverly
Hills Hotel on Monday night prior to similar events scheduled today
in the Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Gore fended off a question regarding criticism of him for
continuing to raise money for his campaign during the Kosovo
fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am out here meeting with people, talking to reporters, to
discuss our goals in Kosovo and explain why this is so important,''
Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore picked up the endorsement of Rep. Xavier Becerra, D-Los
Angeles, who said: ``The vice president has led California into the
good times. More importantly, during the rough times, he has been
at our side.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore acknowledged the importance of an endorsement from Becerra
and his effort to reach into the Latino community _ particularly
with the possible opposition of Republican Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas, who has strong support from Latino voters.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking into Spanish for various phrases, Gore said he believes
he will be able to keep Latino voters in the Democratic Party based
on the administration's efforts to improve the economy and steer
money to Latino entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who joined Gore at an event at Hamilton High School, said
the waivers announced by Gore will allow California more leeway in
determining where and how to reduce 10th-grade class sizes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am frankly amazed at people who say we should eliminate the
Department of Education or that the federal government has no role
in education,'' Gore said. ``I believe that we should not have a
top-down approach with the federal government telling states how to
spend their money. You should have the leeway to decide how it is
best spent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
