<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAQ PUTS IT ON THE LINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ Shaquille O'Neal has no illusions about the state of
his free-throw shooting and understands why his coach is concerned
about opponents sending him to the foul line in the fourth quarter
of a tight game. But he wants badly to overcome both his deficiency
and his coach's worry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like the chance to prove myself,'' O'Neal said Monday.
``I've been in that situation before, and I've knocked 'em down. If
I miss a shot and we lose, I'll take the blame. And I'll come back
and try to do better the next game. But I'd like to be put in that
position.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an issue because O'Neal, a career 53.5 percent shooter from
the line (53.9 percent this season), has been left on the bench
twice recently down the stretch of close games _ against Sacramento
on March 26 and Friday at Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   After the Phoenix game, coach Kurt Rambis said he pulled O'Neal
partly for defensive purposes but also because he feared the Suns
would try to send O'Neal to the line. O'Neal openly questioned the
decision, saying, ``it shows what type of confidence people have in
me.''
</P>
<P>
   But the two chatted afterward and cleared the air, and the next
day Rambis said he had changed his mind _ O'Neal would play down
the stretch from now on.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fine, he's fine. I know where he's coming from, he knows
where I'm coming from,'' Rambis said. ``I've got no problems
talking to my ballplayers. They know they have the freedom to speak
their mind with me. We'll work through any differences or
difficulties we might have....
</P>
<P>
   ``He should be in the game. He's the star of this ballclub,''
Rambis said. ``We're not gonna go anywhere without him. He's gotta
step up and deliver. And I have to put him in that environment
where he feels secure that he can and will deliver.... He knows he
has a challenge in front of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Rambis believes O'Neal is ``capable of being between 65 and 70''
percent from the line. O'Neal says he's working on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to shoot 70 percent. But... one game, I just
want to be down by one, shoot 'em both and make 'em, flip the crowd
off, get a tech (technical foul) and go into overtime,'' he said,
then added on a more serious note, ``I realize I have to step that
part of my game up, and I will.''
</P>
<P>
   And as for Rambis' decisions, O'Neal said, ``Whatever he decides
to do, I'm always going to be behind it. In any relationship you're
going to have arguments.''
</P>
<P>
   Reinforcements: In an anticipated move, the Lakers activated
rookie point guard Tyronn Lue from the injured list Monday. The
transaction bolsters a thin backcourt _ only three guards were on
the active roster _ and provides an instant infusion of quickness
from the speedy Lue.
</P>
<P>
   To make room, the Lakers placed forward Travis Knight on the
injured list with a sudden onset of left Achilles tendinitis. The
Lakers are overloaded with big men, and Knight hadn't played in
four of the last five games.
</P>
<P>
   Lue had been on the injured list since Feb. 19 because of a
lower back strain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
