<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
MAGIC BEAT CELTICS 
</HEADLINE>
 BKN-CELTICS-MAGIC-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Rick Pitino stood against a wall Monday night
and smiled. He said he loved the way the Celtics played against the
Magic. If his team continues to play as it did at Orlando Arena,
the coach predicted, several wins will emerge from the 18 games
left on the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Since we have told you that, you naturally want to know how the
Celtics beat the Magic. You want to know the key stretch that
enabled them to defeat the top team in the Eastern Conference. Did
they hold Penny Hardaway scoreless again? And how did the 17,248
people in the building react to losing to a team without its
starting point guard?
</P>
<P>
   Well, the Celtics didn't actually win. They lost their 22d game
of the season, 106-99. The last time they played the Magic, Feb.
24, they pounded them at the FleetCenter. It was a win that had
fans talking playoffs. Not now.
</P>
<P>
   This loss pushes them even closer to the NBA's unwanted May
vacation spot, Secaucus, N.J., and the lottery.
</P>
<P>
   But with the way the Celtics were talking Monday night, that
won't happen. Why? Because, they say, they're going to win a lot if
they keep playing like this.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played with as much heart as I've seen all season long,''
Pitino said. ``I loved the way we played. I loved the style. I
loved the ferociousness of both teams. I liked the fact that it was
a high-pitch game. If we can get after it like that all the time,
we'll be good.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the ``if'' that has the Celtics scarcely floating above
the basement of the Atlantic Division. Pitino certainly had reason
to be pleased with the play of Ron Mercer, who had 29 points, 7
assists, and 6 steals. ``That's the player I want to see,'' the
coach said. He also got a strong game from Paul Pierce (23 points
and 6 rebounds).
</P>
<P>
   Magic players said the big lineup the Celtics started _ in the
absence of Kenny Anderson _ surprised them.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why they got out to that big lead,'' Horace Grant said,
referring to a 12-point Boston advantage in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The surprise wore off in the second quarter, when the Magic made
68 percent of their field goals. You might be telling yourself that
no one makes 68 percent of their shots, even when they are standing
alone in gyms shooting 15-footers. You're right. The Magic were no
exception. They mixed dunks and layups with open 3-pointers by
6-foot-1-inch guard Darrell Armstrong. That led to a 60-49 halftime
lead.
</P>
<P>
   It was only a few years ago that Armstrong played in the United
States Basketball League and the Spanish League. Now he is the
leading candidate for the NBA's Most Improved Player award after a
19-point second quarter and a career-high tying 28 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love his game,'' Mercer said.
</P>
<P>
   And Hardaway? The last time he saw the Celtics, he spent most of
his time sitting on the bench with ice packs on his knees. He
didn't score a point and said afterward that he couldn't seem to
find any fire against them. He sat for only six minutes Monday
night and produced 24 points, 7 rebounds, and 7 assists.
</P>
<P>
   So what did Pitino see that he liked so much?
</P>
<P>
   You can start with the way the team handled not having Anderson.
The plan was for Antoine Walker to be a ``point forward,'' bringing
the ball up most of the time with relief off the bench from Dana
Barros. But Walker got into foul trouble, picking up three
first-half fouls and getting a technical. He was whistled for his
fourth barely three minutes into the third and the Celtics were
quickly down by 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you see what a great job my teammates did during that
time?'' Walker said. ``I was out of the game for, like, nine
minutes and they did a great job.''
</P>
<P>
   What they did was slice a 14-point deficit to 5, 79-74, entering
the fourth quarter. Mercer had 10 points in the quarter. That gave
the Celtics a chance in the final 12 minutes. Barros was passing
well (nine assists) and Walker had come back in to help the Celtics
go up, 86-83, with 8:40 left.
</P>
<P>
   That would be the best the Celtics could do. Hardaway made a
20-footer, Armstrong made a three and Grant put in a layup. A
3-point lead had become a 5-point deficit in 90 seconds. It was
obvious another loss was coming. Later, the only consolation would
be that they played well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
