   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BARBIE-BARAD (Undated) _ Mattel's earnings have slumped, and its
stock price has tumbled. For Mattel, the question is whether its
chief executive, Jill E. Barad, who is primarily identified with
Barbie, the company's flagship toy, can turn the company around at
a time when the toy industry is undergoing rapid change. By Dana
Canedy.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic has
been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ASSESS (Tokyo) _ Since March, a slew of Japanese companies
have unveiled extensive overhauls, job cutbacks and internal
realignments, which were previously considered taboo in corporate
Japan. A news analysis. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   DIVX-MARKETPLACE _ With consumers spending freely, Circuit City
Inc. looks poised to cash in on the growing interest in all things
digital. But there is a chink in Circuit City's armor: its gamble
on Divx, a technology that allows consumers to pay a small fee for
video movies that do not have to be returned. By Sharon R. King.
</P>
<P>
   ACQUISITIONS-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ Two big agency companies are
on the acquisition trail again in deals that underscore the urgency
with which the global giants are seeking to expand their services.
By Stuart Elliott.
