</P>
<P>
   BBN-BERKOW-COLUMN (St. Louis) _ Sports of The Times column on
the Cardinals' Mark McGwire. By Ira Berkow.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-MASTERS-DUVAL (Undated) _ Kicking off Masters week with a
feature on David Duval. By Clifton Brown.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE TIMES (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WRITING-ORIGINS (Undated) _ When it comes to explaining the
origins of writing, scientists are largely at a loss. But many at a
recent symposium favored a broad explanation of writing's origins
in the visual arts, pictograms of things being transformed into
increasingly abstract symbols for things, names and eventually
words in speech. Their views clashed with a widely held theory that
writing grew out of the pieces of clay that Sumerian accountants
had used to keep track of livestock and stores of grain. Scholars
assembled also conceded that they had no definitive answer to the
question of whether writing was invented only once and spread
elsewhere or arose independently several times in several places,
like Egypt, the Indus valley, China and among the Olmecs and Maya
of Mexico and Central America. By John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic has
been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-RESEARCH-SECRECY (Undated) _ The strings that often come
with private research money _ the publication delays while patents
and profits are pursued, the proprietary findings _ hold the
pernicious potential to impede the free exchange of information
that speeds scientific progress, experts warned during a conference
on ``Secrecy in Science'' held by the American Association for the
Advancement of Science and the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology. By Carey Goldberg. (1600 words)
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ASPERGERS-SYNDROME (Undated) _ Asperger's syndrome, a
condition that is generally considered a less severe form of
autism, remains little known, but the number of diagnoses has
soared since psychiatric authorities formally defined it five years
ago. Recent survey data suggest that under some definitions as many
as 1 in 500 people have the condition, higher than the estimate for
classic autism. By John O'Neil. (1925 words)
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-COMPUTER-MEMORY (Undated) _ Heralding an era that will blend
the speed of the microelectronic world of silicon with the
permanence of the magnetic world of computer disks, a group of
I.B.M. researchers said last week that they had successfully
designed the building blocks of a new kind of computer memory that
could fundamentally alter computer design early in the next
century. Chips based on this new technology, known as tunneling
magnetic junction random access memory, or tmj-ram for short, would
be ultrafast, consume very little power and retain stored data when
a computer was shut down. By John Markoff. (ART ADV: Graphic has
been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-RNA (Undated) _ New theories on how life might have
originated on earth involve RNA, not DNA. By Nicholas Wade. (800
words)
</P>
