<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS BEAT CANADIENS 
</HEADLINE>
 HKN-BRUINS-CANADIENS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was something he'd never had happen to him. He'd heard it in
other rinks, in other years, but for other players. For the first
time Monday night, the fans were chanting his name, over and over
in the third period as the seconds ticked away.
</P>
<P>
   Bruins goalie Byron Dafoe was so moved and so excited that with
14.7 seconds remaining, he fired the puck into the FleetCenter
stands and received a penalty for delay of game. It was Boston's
first and only penalty of the game, but it didn't hurt as Dafoe
smothered the Montreal Canadiens, 3-0, to earn his league-leading
10th shutout of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pretty touched,'' said Dafoe. ``In all my years of
playing hockey, whether it be the minors or whatever, I've never
had a whole building saying my name at once. It got me so jazzed up
that when I got the puck I wanted to fire it down and I fired it
into the stands. It's really special. The fans, that was
unbelievable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, winning is the bottom line. The shutouts are great
but the wins are more important. To get my 10th . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had more than two or three in my entire life in a
season. I credit the guys in front of me. I didn't get a lot of
tough shots but they played so well in front of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe, who was making his 20th straight start, is the first
Bruins goalie to post 10 shutouts since Frank Brimsek in 1938-39.
It was the second time Dafoe has posted consecutive shutouts this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe, who had 25 saves in earning victory No. 29, has a shutout
streak of 160 minutes 11 seconds. The last goal he gave up was
Thursday in Montreal to Brian Savage at 19:49 of the first period.
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe doesn't expect to receive much consideration for the
Vezina Trophy, much the way he was overlooked at All-Star time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost the same as the All-Star thing,'' said Dafoe. ``If
I get a chance to win it, that's even better. But just the fact
that people mention my name around, that's good enough for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Not much went right for the fading Canadiens, and for the
Bruins, nothing seemed to go wrong. The loss to Boston, coupled
with a Buffalo victory, eliminated the Canadiens from making it to
the postseason. Boston finished the season series with a 4-0-1
record against Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe received a lot of help from his teammates Monday night.
Sergei Samsonov, who has scored decisive goals in the past two
games, tallied the only offense Boston would need at 15:08 of the
first period during a power play.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Ray Bourque started the action with a shot from the
point that caromed off a couple of sticks. Center Joe Thornton took
a whack at it and Samsonov was there to bang in the rebound for his
24th of the season.
</P>
<P>
   In the second, Boston added two more. Don Sweeney set up the
score perfectly with a pass to Rob DiMaio in the slot. DiMaio, who
missed the last game because of a forearm injury suffered in
warmups, fired a wrister over the glove of goalie Frederic Chabot
for his sixth of the year at 6:17.
</P>
<P>
   Carter made it a three-goal cushion with his 18th of the year at
15:43 as Boston converted on a three-on-two. Center Jason Allison
dished the puck from the right side to Carter in the slot. Carter
one-timed a shot past Chabot to the stick side.
</P>
<P>
   The Habs had chances, especially early in the period. Center
Saku Koivu had a good one with a backhand shot about three minutes
in. But after Dafoe made the initial save and the rebound sat
there, Bourque cleared it before any Hab could get to it. During
that same shift, Bourque delivered three punishing hits to Koivu,
knocking him to the ice. When Koivu went to the bench, he slammed
the door and banged his stick in frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know some of the Montreal media picked us to finish dead
last in our division and not make the playoffs,'' said Burns. ``So
obviously it backfired in their face a little bit. That probably
makes me happy more than anything else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
