<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-ROBLEDO-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUGH TIMES FOR PREKI
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It seems so long ago, but it has been just a year since the U.S.
faced Yugoslavia in the first round of the 1998 World Cup in
France.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more pleasant stories of that tournament centered
around U.S. midfielder Preki Radosavljevic. His father -- still
living in Belgrade, where Radosavljevic was born -- was profiled in
an ABC interview featuring the pair before the U.S.-Yugsolavia
match.
</P>
<P>
   Radosavljevic, once a member of the Yugoslavian Army, arrived in
the U.S. in 1985 and recently received his U.S. citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   Radosavljevic, known simply as Preki to those who saw him dazzle
fans with his fancy footwork for the MLS Kansas City franchise, is
constantly checking the internet these days and keeping a close eye
on his television set as NATO bombs continue to fall on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, one of Preki's friends and MLS teammates, Refik
Sabanadzovic, is a Muslim who also was born in Belgrade. He has
family and friends who live in the Yugoslavian province of
Montenegro, which borders Kosovo to the west.
</P>
<P>
   Preki, a Serb, has family in the Serbian capital of Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   If these two were still at home, there's a good chance they
would be bitter enemies. In their current situation, they are left
to pray for their families while B-2 Bombers are launched daily
from Whitman Air Force Base, just a short drive from where they
train in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Preki is a Serb, I am a Muslim,'' Sabanadzovic told
Cybersoccer. ``It's not a problem between us.''
</P>
<P>
   The only time Preki or Refik (as he's commonly known) get a
chance to take their minds off their families is while they're
training or playing. Other than that, life is difficult these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been following the situation very closely and I'm on the
internet all day,'' said Preki, constantly worrying about his
parents and sister. ``It's always on my mind. When I come to
practice it somewhat slips away, but as soon as you mention it, I
remember.''
</P>
<P>
   Refik, who played for Red Star Belgrade during the 1980s, was a
member of Yugoslavia's 1990 World Cup team. He had the tough task
of marking Argentina's Diego Maradona during the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Refik tells of horror stories when he calls home to check on his
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``After every game I call my family to ask if everything is
okay,'' said Refik. ``Many people are leaving Yugoslavia. They have
no money, no food. It is difficult for kids. Many kids are getting
killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the civil wars, Refik said he had friendships throughout
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have friends from Bosnia, Croatia, Serbia ... before (the
civil wars) it was never a problem,'' Refik said. ``I played for
Red Star Belgrade in the 80's for four years. Now it is a problem
after the change of leadership from Tito to president-for-life
Slobodan Milosevic. It changed the people. We all used to have the
same passport. Now there are five or six passports.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kosovo region, despite its large Ethnic Albanian and Muslim
population, holds a strong significance for the Serbs. Any talk of
autonomy for the Kosovo region prompts strong feelings from Preki.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, that's always been ours, so why should we give
that up?'' Preki said. ``We are allowing terrorists to basically
take a part of the country away, and this whole country (USA) is
supporting that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine if Miami wanted to become part of Cuba? What
would the U.S. government say about that? The bombing is not going
to help. Serbia will never give up that part of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Surely, the last thing Preki and Refik are worried about is
Kansas City's 0-3 start. The team is yet to score a goal this
season -- but that is certainly understandable under the
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   If the Rose Bowl loses the Galaxy as a tenant, don't blame the
Los Angeles franchise for leaving town. Under the direction of new
owner Philip F. Anschutz, the Galaxy spent $500,000 to build a
weight room and new offices and rebuild the locker room -- all
luxuries the Rose Bowl will keep should the Galaxy leave.
</P>
<P>
   Anschutz was also willing to spend $300,000 to build a new
practice facility in a parking lot on the Rose Bowl grounds.
Apparently, the Rose Bowl wanted the Galaxy to spend an additional
$250,000 to replace parking stalls lost for UCLA football. The
practice site would have been used for youth soccer tournaments and
teams participating in the Rose Bowl as well as local high schools.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
