<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 02:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7321 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      04-06 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUDACIOUS MARINERS ASK FANS FOR PATIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baseball's opening night is all about freshness, renewal,
spring, all that giddy stuff.
</P>
<P>
   But six rookies on the Mariner pitching staff? That's beyond
newness. That's an expansion team.
</P>
<P>
   Woody Woodward, dean of big-league GMs, says he doesn't think
he's ever opened a Mariner season with a half-dozen greenie
pitchers. Lou Piniella says he's never managed such a collection.
</P>
<P>
   But that's what was trotted out Monday through the fireworks
smoke at the Kingdome, on the day that the Public Facilities
District announced yet another leap in cost, to $517 million, of
the most expensive ballpark in U.S. history, and on the heels of
news the Mariners, because of the new park, had the steepest
one-year ticket price hike in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Audacious, these Mariners. If the team plays with half the guts
of management, the American League West race will be over by the
Fourth of July.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners have put their money into stadiums and the starting
eight, leaving the exchequer empty for pitchers much beyond high
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to be patient with the pitchers,''
Piniella said. ``We have to live with them and grow with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Remember, this was from a guy who last summer set a major league
record for cap kicking (distance as well as attempts).
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the capacity of his manager to handle the
assignment, Woodward stifled a quick smile and drew serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lou and Stan (Williams, pitching coach) know they have a
teaching job to do,'' he said. ``I have complete confidence in them
to get it done.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had discussions and meetings on this topic. We let
everyone know we put our money into the starting lineup and we have
to work with young pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   How all these meetings will work out when one of the rooks walks
the bases full remains to be seen. Personally, I wouldn't want to
be Piniella's cap that day, but maybe Williams is under orders to
lock Piniella in the wine cellar.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, the first of the prodigies, Brett Hinchliffe, was
trotted out after starter Jeff Fassero put the Mariners in a 6-2
hole. Hinchliffe gave up two more runs, and the Mariners lost to
the Chicago White Sox 8-2. But hey, look at it this way _ it wasn't
the fault of the kids.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness, the preposterous preponderance of youth may not
last. Veteran relief pitcher Mark Leiter will return from the
disabled list soon, and Ken Cloude will be brought up from AAA
Tacoma once he finds his misplaced pitching brains.
</P>
<P>
   It also must be said that in Hinchliffe, Freddy Garcia, John
Halama, Jose Paniagua, Eric Weaver and Mac Suzuki, the Mariners
have a group with talent somewhat above the expansion line.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, let Ken Griffey Jr., something of an authority on
pitching, say it: ``These guys can throw.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodward, who was prevented from going after expensive, veteran
pitching this winter by ownership's insistence on making a profit
in 1999, said the Mariners have, apparently by luck as well as
skill, stumbled upon a handful of helpers.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the rookies we run out there will play in the major
leagues,'' he said firmly. ``From the standpoint of talent, I'm not
worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``The part you don't know about is how they'll respond by
pitching in the big leagues, on the road, things like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The best news about this group is that none of them is Bobby
Ayala, traded Saturday to Montreal. Once our Canadian neighbors
multiply his ERA by the exchange rate, expect thousands of
Quebecois to storm over the U.S. border seeking revenge.
</P>
<P>
   But that's OK. Better to let them pillage some village in
upstate New York than have Ayala sent out to protect a 7-2 Mariner
lead in the Kingdome. Casualties will be fewer.
</P>
<P>
   The remarkable thing about the young pitchers is that five of
them are in the bullpen, which has no one from last season's
debacle who pitched more than 25 innings. So none carry the
emotional scars of being booed merely for crossing their legs, a
visceral response by Mariner fans fearful of any movement along the
bullpen bench.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella said he made no requests of Woodward this spring to get
more veteran help, saying he's fully prepared to accept the hand
he's dealt, particularly since the key man in the pen, closer Jose
Mesa, is 32 and tougher than a sawdust candy bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``This situation is no surprise,'' he said. ``We started this
transition with the Randy Johnson trade, so we knew where we were
heading. Mesa is unequivocally the leader. He won't shy away from
the task.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodward insisted that his volatile field boss, burned by the
charges he can't handle young pitchers, is capable of throttling
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lou's a performance guy,'' he said. ``If you play well, he's
great to play for. But he knows this season will require
patience.''
</P>
<P>
   Patience.
</P>
<P>
   There's that word again. At one time there was a Mariner owner
who was condemned for the phrase, ``Patience is for losers.'' Now
it's the franchise watchword.
</P>
<P>
   In a half-billion dollar park funded mostly by the public, which
will also pay a hefty daily tab at the gate, the request is for
patience.
</P>
<P>
   As was said, an audacious enterprise, these Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-99 0224EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
