<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: YANKS PLAY AGAINST 125 ALL SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs to KILL 4th graf; column was transmitted prematurely with a
final score. Game is actually delayed on account of rain; subs 12th
graf to correct first reference to Roger Clemens.) (sw) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ It's nice to be king.
</P>
<P>
   While baseball's underclass trudges hopelessly in small
television markets, the Yankees and a few select franchises
actually have aspirations for this new season.
</P>
<P>
   The soft underbelly of baseball has to answer questions like:
``Do you think you'll open the upper deck at all this season?'' and
``Will you sell your best player in June or July?''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, on the other hand, have to deal with the weighty
issue of whether they can win 125 games all over again this season.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Cashman, the youthful general manager, has said he hopes
Roger Clemens will take the Yankees to ``the next level.'' One
could only fear what the next level might entail, but Cashman
explained it all before Clemens opened the season here on Monday
night against the Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year is history,'' Cashman said. ``We won the 1998 World
Series, but this is 1999. We hope Roger can take us to the next
level this year, which is winning this year's Series.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Yankees ask the world not to be obsessed with the
number 125.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever it takes,'' said Don Zimmer, who was still the
interim manager despite having issued a transcontinental bark at
George Steinbrenner last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer just wanted to preside over a few victories before his
pal Joe Torre comes back from cancer surgery and takes over the
terrible burden of managing for Mr. Mood Swing.
</P>
<P>
   There were flashbacks for Zimmer of just how crazy it can get
for Yankee managers. Last year the Yankees won only one of their
first five games on their opening West Coast swing, and the
tabloids were already listing Torre's replacements.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't lose four out of five on the West Coast this time,''
Zimmer predicted. ``We only play three games.''
</P>
<P>
   This is true. By some quirk in the schedule, the Yankees play
three games in Oakland before heading home. Plus, they had the
strapping Roger Clemens, who sought the pressure by lusting after
the Yankees, after being one of their major enemies of this
generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're either a hero or a dog,'' Clemens said, ``but you can't
come back the next day and get two hits. You have to wait. I don't
know if you can ever expect 125 again. If 95 wins is the ticket, so
be it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ninety-five victories will not win a World Series, not in this
triple-tiered playoff era, but the Yankees are not asking Clemens
to carry them to any specific total.
</P>
<P>
   ``You keep hearing the Yankees are a cinch,'' Zimmer said
Sunday. ``There is no such thing. We're just trying to go out and
win the Eastern Division. That's our first goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a good bunch of guys last year. The way Joe handled
three left fielders was great. You know if you have three guys all
wanting to play, something's going to get said, sooner or later,
but with Joe, it never happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the Yankees had five left fielders _ Darryl
Strawberry, Tim Raines, Ricky Ledee, Chad Curtis and Shane Spencer,
in no particular order. They got to play more because Chili Davis
missed most of the season at designated hitter, but Torre still
defused any potential squawking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe is Joe; you wouldn't have to write all these stories if
Joe were here,'' Zimmer added, referring to the delightful
man-bites-Boss stories over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good team, it will win a lot of games,'' Zimmer
said. ``I don't project championships. That's not me. We did
something last year that was never done before, but nobody is going
to give you anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, it's not the same ball club. Everybody says, `Well,
you traded David Wells for Roger Clemens,' but have you looked at
our roster? This is not the same ball club.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know how many times last year we were in a tie game in
the eighth inning and we sent Homer Bush in to run and we said,
`Homer, steal second base?' Homer Bush helped us win a lot of
games. Tim Raines is still a professional hitter. Straw used to
pinch-hit for Girardi and hit home runs. Last year we had two
left-handers in the bullpen, this year we have one. Andy Pettitte
is on the disabled list. We're still a good ball club, but we're
not the same one.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Wells and Graeme Lloyd are in Toronto. Raines is with
these very Athletics. Pettitte and Strawberry are recuperating.
Doesn't matter. The Yankees will be measured against 125 victories.
Such a problem.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
