<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 02:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7329 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      04-06 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS START OUT FLAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE -- When the all-time home run king throws out the first
pitch, long balls might be in the forecast.
</P>
<P>
   And so it was Monday night as the Mariners and Chicago White Sox
met in the last Kingdome opener. Ken Griffey Jr., the man Hank
Aaron thinks is most capable of breaking his record of 755 home
runs, dutifully delivered, crushing a James Baldwin pitch over the
scoreboard in right-center field to give the Mariners a lead in the
third inning.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't last long, because this home run derby was open to
all. Darrin Jackson and Paul Konerko slammed two-run homers off M's
starter Jeff Fassero, leading the White Sox to a 8-2 victory before
51,656.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was around the plate all night long, locating where I wanted
it except on maybe four or five pitches,'' said Fassero, who
allowed six runs on eight hits and a walk in six innings. ``Only
one of them hurt me.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the homer by Jackson, off a forkball Fassero left up in
the strike zone. Mechanically, he said he felt fine, altering his
delivery so he picked up the catcher's target immediately instead
of during the windup, which had caused him to tilt his front
shoulder and lose control in two rough spring outings.
</P>
<P>
   His counterpart Monday night, Baldwin, was effective in escaping
trouble. He allowed solo homers to Griffey and second baseman
Carlos Guillen in the third, but left Mariners in scoring position
in four of his six innings.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey's homer was the seventh of his career on opening day, a
total reached only by Hall of Famers Frank Robinson (the
record-holder, with eight), Eddie Mathews, Willie Mays, Babe Ruth
and Carl Yastrzemski. It also was Griffey's 351st career homer,
lifting the center fielder to 50th on the all-time list, tied with
Dick Allen and Gary Gaetti.
</P>
<P>
   As for chipping away at Aaron's all-time mark, Griffey dismissed
such talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still 404 behind,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But catching Aaron's first pitch was something special.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means something if I don't catch a lot of first
pitches,'' Griffey said afterward. ``If it weren't for guys like
him, would I be sitting here?''
</P>
<P>
   Guillen was the first Mariner to homer in '99, smacking a 3-2
pitch out to right for the first of his career. Guillen, a rookie
who drew raves by hitting .393 this spring, briefly raised his arm
in celebration as he slowed to a trot.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can play,'' Piniella said. ``We're not worried about
Carlos. He's one of my least concerns here.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay Buhner had been a major concern. At the end of last season,
Piniella figured Buhner would be playing first base Monday night.
Buhner was not expected to return to right field until the All-Star
break after having ``Tommy John'' elbow surgery last September 9.
</P>
<P>
   But he started there Monday night. During introductions, the
surgically repaired right fielder bounded toward third base to give
a bear hug to trainers Rick Griffin and Tom Newberg before taking
his place among the starters, lined up closer to home plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys will tell you, `Thank you,' and say they
appreciate your help, but for him to do that meant a lot to us,''
said Griffin, who thought Buhner was simply starting at the back of
the line to high-five each member of the team. ``He went from
having surgery to playing in a big-league ballgame in less than
seven months. I don't think anybody else has done that, that I know
of. Whether it's a pitcher, outfielder or catcher, the fact that he
went out there and did it, made two throws and got a hit _ that's
pretty amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   The baseball gods must have been watching, because the first
batter of the season, Ray Durham, lined one into Buhner's corner.
He slipped on the warning track going after it, and Durham had a
triple, scoring on a ground out by Mike Caruso.
</P>
<P>
   Durham, an All-Star in '98, is one of the few recognizable names
on the re-building White Sox. The biggest, of course, is Frank
Thomas, and the Big Hurt had a big hand in Monday night's game. He
had a single and two doubles, each hit factoring in a scoring
rally. The last, a two-run double, brought the Sox their final
runs, in the seventh off rookie reliever Brett Hinchliffe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
