<SLUG> BC-BBA-KINGDOME-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGDOME GETS CLOSURE IN OPENER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A sentimental journey accelerated Monday night when
more than 50,000 Mariner fans watched the 23rd _ and last _ opening
night in Kingdome history.
</P>
<P>
   They came to say hello to a new baseball season. And to start
saying goodbye to a facility that has weathered an earthquake,
falling ceiling tiles and enough local and national criticism to
give it an inferiority complex.
</P>
<P>
   The Dome's $517 million replacement, standing tall and proud
only a Ken Griffey Jr. home run away, is the jewel the Dome never
was. Indeed, Safeco Field, which debuts on July 15, will have just
about everything the Kingdome doesn't, including real grass and a
roof that will let the sun and moon shine in.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday night, the Mariners' ballpark took its final opening
night bow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been the home to this organization since the beginning
and knowing that this is the last (opening night), it will be
nostalgic,'' said Mariner manager Lou Piniella before Monday
night's season opener against the Chicago White Sox. ``But like
every dinosaur, it's time for new and better things.''
</P>
<P>
   For its final opening night dance, the Kingdome was decked out
with red, white and blue bunting on the facades of all three
seating levels. The dirt cutouts around home plate, bases and
pitching mound were raked smooth, and the big screen in left field
displayed brilliant color.
</P>
<P>
   Although the official farewell party is being saved for the
team's final homestand in June _ prior to the All-Star break _
Monday night provided a chance to look back and reflect.
</P>
<P>
   If the Kindome could talk, what would it say?
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have tears in its eyes and might be too choked up to
talk,'' said Mariner broadcaster Dave Niehaus, who has seen all 23
of the regular-season home openers. ``This has been a very good
place for the Seattle Mariners and the fans. We wouldn't have a
(major league) franchise if it wasn't for the Kingdome.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Piniella: ``It think it would say, `Enough! I'm worn
out.'''
</P>
<P>
   Carol Keaton, the Kingdome public relations director, said,
``The purists say let's play ball (in an open-air stadium), but for
most of the kids, this is the biggest building they've ever been in
and it has been a fun place to watch the Mariners. Especially the
past few years.''
</P>
<P>
   But the purists are looking forward to mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't miss the Kingdome,'' said Frank Davidson, of Renton.
``I saw enough games here to make me a non-baseball fan.''
</P>
<P>
   He prefers fresh air, sun and natural turf.
</P>
<P>
   All three are coming and then the Kingdome becomes baseball
history.
</P>
<P>
   Regarded as a wart throughout the baseball fraternity for most
of its life, the Kingdome blossomed late in life to become one of
the best home-field advantages in the game. During the Mariners'
improbable late-season charge in 1995, which ended two wins shy of
the World Series, the noise generated during the month-long joy
ride drew favorable national attention.
</P>
<P>
   But prior to '95, most of the biggest crowds came on opening
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember my first one, because it was my first one,'' said
Griffey, who debuted against the White Sox in 1989 with a home run
off Eric King.
</P>
<P>
   Other opening nights also stand out.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)In 1986, Jim Presley hit a two-run homer in the ninth
inning to tie the California Angels, and then won it in the 10th
with a grand slam.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Last season, the M's gave ace left-hander Randy Johnson a
9-3 lead after five innings. But Cleveland came back to win 10-9.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)The first opening night, in 1977, drew 57,762 fans _ the
largest regular-season crowd until 1994.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)The '96 opener, when the franchise's first American League
West championship banner was hoisted to the rafters, is catcher Dan
Wilson's favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Kingdome would be appreciative of the fans and
their support over the years,'' Wilson said. ``The best times in
franchise history happened right here, but I think everyone is
looking forward to the move (into Safeco Field).''
</P>
<P>
   Fans agree.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Hopkins was 14 years old when she attented the first
opening night and returned Monday night with her husband, Hoover,
and 2-year-old son, Webb.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted him to see his first Mariner game in the Kingdome,''
Hoover said. ``This is where all the history of the team is.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of sad to see it go,'' said Jim Fursman of Burien,
``but I'm looking forward to the new stadium. I introduced my wife
(Barbara) to baseball at the Kingdome in '97.''
</P>
</TEXT>
