A7354 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CENSUS-SAMPLING-SFCHR     04-06 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-SAMPLING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 U.S. CENSUS SEEKS MORE MINORITY DATA  &HT;     By RAMON G. MCLEOD 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ The head of the Census Bureau said Monday
that he is going to set aside money to conduct a controversial
survey to correct for an expected minority undercount in the 2000
census, despite hostility from the Republican-controlled Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Prewitt, who was recently appointed director of the U.S.
Bureau of the Census, told a Stanford University audience that he
planned to include the $200 million cost of a sampling technique as
part of what is expected to be a budget topping $7 billion for the
2000 Census.
</P>
<P>
   What was once a civic exercise done at the start of each decade
has evolved into a political volcano that involves high-stakes
issues of power, money and racial identity.
</P>
<P>
   Minority groups, he said, have been pushing hard for sampling
and adjustment because ``the statistical system is at the heart of
the politics of race and ethnicity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Numbers determine who matters and who is visible,'' he said.
``The African American population is worried about becoming a
minority of the minorities when historically that community has
always been the largest minority.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you mix in the money involved and the power involved,
along with identity politics, that is something worth fighting
about,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And at the center of the fight is sampling.
</P>
<P>
   All sides in the battle agree that adjustment would almost
certainly increase the number of minorities reported in the
official government statistics.
</P>
<P>
   After the 1990 census, using a statistical technique similar to
that proposed for the 2000 census, it was determined that about 4
million U.S. residents _ including 1 million in California _ were
not counted because they refused to cooperate, had moved, were
missed because of incompetence by census-takers and myriad other
reasons. An estimated two-thirds of those not counted were
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have opposed the technique because of concern that
it would result in fewer Republican seats in Congress and in state
houses because states heavy in minorities, who tend to vote
Democratic, would pick up seats. California would have gained an
extra congressional seat _ most likely in Riverside County _ had
the 1990 Census been adjusted.
</P>
<P>
   In late January, the Supreme Court sided with Republicans,
prohibiting sampling and census adjustment for the purpose of
congressional apportionment.
</P>
<P>
   But apportionment, which is the distribution of the 435 seats in
the House of Representatives, is not the only important use of the
Census.
</P>
<P>
   The government numbers are also used to decide how to split up
$180 billion a year in federal funds, and the Supreme Court left
open the question of whether sampling is appropriate for that
purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt said the bureau believed it could conduct its sampling
program _ called accuracy and coverage evaluation _ and come up
with adjusted numbers by April 1, 2001. That is the deadline to
provide states with what he called ``the official numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, if we don't get the money to do the (sampling), we
can't do that, and we haven't got the money yet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The budget for the 2000 Census will be presented to Congress in
July. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
