<HEADER>
A7428 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-INTERNET-PRESCRIP     04-06 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-INTERNET-PRESCRIPTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISPENSING OF DRUGS ON INTERNET STIRS DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(mk) 
 By LISA NAPOLI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. James De Yarman specializes in performing hair transplants
at his clinic in San Diego. Last September, he took his expertise
online, setting up a site on the World Wide Web called
DrPropecia.com. There, he offers information about the drug
Propecia, which promotes hair growth in men. Prospective patients
can fill out an online medical history form, which De Yarman
reviews for a $50 fee. If he determines that the drug would be
useful for a patient, he then prescribes it and sells it to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to assume they're telling me the truth,'' he said.
``I'm not a drugstore. I look at this as providing a service, going
online to sell it. What would I do different if they were to come
into the office?''
</P>
<P>
   De Yarman and others, who essentially function as both physician
and pharmacist online, are just one example of the ways in which
the World Wide Web is changing how prescription drugs are changing
hands. In other cases, international pharmacies, which sell drugs
without prescriptions that may not be regulated in this country,
offer online signposts for their wares. And, in the freewheeling
climate of the Internet, patients are exchanging information and
selling leftover drugs to one another.
</P>
<P>
   These activities are raising questions about how drug
transactions should be regulated _ and about how, with the
borderless, seemingly infinite shape of the online medium, they can
be.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet has leaped ahead of the agencies that govern
prescription drugs in the United States. Typically, drugs are
approved for use by the Food and Drug Administration, prescribed by
doctors who are licensed by state medical boards, and dispensed by
pharmacies licensed by state pharmaceutical boards. But by using
the Internet, people can often purchase drugs from sources not
licensed by these agencies. These activities have long gone on
off-line, but have been difficult to detect. Now these practices
seem to be booming online.
</P>
<P>
   One concern stems not from the well-advertised Internet
drugstores like Drugstore.com or Soma.com, both of which require a
patient to fax a prescription from a doctor to have it filled
online, but from sites like MDpharmacy.com, Net-Dr.com and
US-care.com. These sites, like De Yarman's, circumvent the
traditional medical relationships by allowing a patient without a
prescription to fill out a consultation form online, pay a fee for
its review and, if approved, receive drugs through the mail.
</P>
<P>
   While the American Medical Association said it was not a
violation of its code of ethics for a doctor to sell prescription
drugs, it is an ethical violation to sell drugs without a
face-to-face consultation. State law in California, where De Yarman
does business, prohibits the sale of drugs without an examination.
But most laws and codes which govern medicine were written before
the Internet, said Greg Abrams, legal counsel to the California
Medical Society, and do not factor in the questions raised by the
medium.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Lamb, who lives in Columbus, Ohio, recently purchased
oxycodone, a potentially addictive pain reliever classified as a
controlled substance in the United States, from a Spanish pharmacy
he found over the Internet, because no doctor he visited locally
would prescribe the drug for his back pain. ``Foreign pharmacies
willing to ship without prescription are a growing source who has
seized on this gap because their countries do not regulate drugs
the way the U.S. does,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Randy Wykoff, the associate commissioner for operations at
the FDA, said the sale of illegal or unapproved products is, of all
the violations made possible by the Internet, of particular concern
to the agency. In recent years, he said, several staff members who
would typically investigate medical fraud have been redeployed to
look for fraudulent practices online.
</P>
<P>
   Besides buying from foreign-operated Web sites, some Internet
users swap drugs, facilitated by bulletin boards and other Web
areas that foster a flea market environment online. One participant
in an online infertility group, for example, offered to sell
``leftover'' drugs she had purchased from Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Determining which actions to take and which policies to rewrite
to acknowledge the vast impact of the Internet on the sale of
pharmaceuticals will take time. The House Commerce Committee last
month commissioned the General Accounting Office to conduct a study
on the scope of the prescription drug trade online.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Boards of Pharmacy, the trade group
for pharmacies, announced last month that it is developing a seal
of approval for online pharmacies to help customers determine which
ones are legitimate. The first seals are expected to be issued by
May.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not concerned about the economics, but about patient
safety,'' said Carmen Catizone, the executive director of the
pharmacy association.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Dr. De Yarman sees more benefits than pitfalls in
extending his medical practice online. ``This is the future of
medicine,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
