<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 09:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7433 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-WRITING-ORIGINS-A     04-06 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WRITING-ORIGINS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN NO ONE READ, WHO STARTED TO WRITE? 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers may make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(Eds., in 5th graf, the double parentheses should be set as
brackets) 
(The Science Times) 
(HLW) 
 By JOHN NOBLE WILFORD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The Sumerians had a story to explain their
invention of writing more than 5,000 years ago. It seems a
messenger of the king of Uruk arrived at the court of a distant
ruler so exhausted from the journey that he was unable to deliver
the oral message. So the king, being clever, came up with a
solution. He patted some clay and set down the words of his next
messages on a tablet.
</P>
<P>
   A Sumerian epic celebrates the achievement:
</P>
<P>
   Before that time, writing on clay had not yet existed,
</P>
<P>
   But now, as the sun rose, so it was!
</P>
<P>
   The king of Kullaba ((Uruk)) had set words on a tablet, so it
was!
</P>
<P>
   A charming just-so, or so-it-was, story, its retelling at a
recent symposium on the origins or writing, held here at the
University of Pennsylvania, both amused and frustrated scholars. It
reminded them that they could expect little help _ only a myth _
from the Sumerians themselves, presumably the first writing people,
in understanding how and why the invention responsible for the
great divide in human culture between prehistory and history had
come about.
</P>
<P>
   The archeologists, historians and other scholars at the meeting
smiled at the absurdity of a king's writing a letter that its
recipient could not read. They also doubted that the earliest
writing was a direct rendering of speech. Writing more than likely
began as a separate and distinct symbolic system of communication,
like painting, sculpture and oral storytelling, and only later
merged with spoken language.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the story, the Sumerians, who lived in Mesopotamia, the
lower valley of the Tigris and Euphrates Rivers in what is now
southern Iraq, seemed to understand writing's transforming
function. As Dr. Holly Pittman, the Pennsylvania art historian who
organized the symposium, observed, writing ``arose out of the need
to store information and transmit information outside of human
memory and over time and over space.''
</P>
<P>
   In exchanging interpretations and new information, the scholars
acknowledged that they still had no fully satisfying answers to the
most important questions of exactly how and why writing was
developed. Many of them favored a broad explanation of writing's
origins in the visual arts, pictograms of things being transformed
into increasingly abstract symbols for things, names and eventually
words in speech. Their views clashed with a widely held theory
among archeologists that writing grew out of the pieces of clay in
assorted sizes and shapes that Sumerian accountants had used as
tokens to keep track of livestock and stores of grain.
</P>
<P>
   The scholars at the meeting also conceded that they had no
definitive answer to the question of whether writing was invented
only once and spread elsewhere or arose independently several times
in several places, like Egypt, the Indus Valley, China and among
the Olmecs and Maya of Mexico and Central America. But they
criticized recent findings suggesting that writing might have
developed earlier in Egypt than in Mesopotamia.
</P>
<P>
   In December, Dr. Guenter Dreyer, director of the German
Archeological Institute in Egypt, announced new radiocarbon dates
for tombs at Abydos, on the Nile about 250 miles south of Cairo.
The dates indicated that some hieroglyphic inscriptions on pots,
bone and ivory in the tombs were made at least as early as 3200
B.C., possibly 3400. It was now an ``open question,'' Dreyer said,
whether writing appeared first in Egypt or Mesopotamia.
</P>
<P>
   At the symposium, Dr. John Baines, an Oxford University
Egyptologist who had just visited Dreyer, expressed skepticism in
polite terms. ``I'm suspicious of the dates,'' he said in an
interview. ``I think he's being very bold in his readings of these
things.''
</P>
<P>
   The preponderance of archeological evidence has shown that the
urbanizing Sumerians were the first to develop writing, in 3200 or
3300 B.C. These are the dates for many clay tablets with a
proto-cuneiform script found at the site of the ancient city of
Uruk. The tablets bore pictorial symbols for the names of people,
places and things for governing and commerce. The Sumerian script
gradually evolved from the pictorial to the abstract, but it was
probably at least five centuries before the writing came to
represent recorded spoken language.
</P>
<P>
   Egyptian hieroglyphics are so different from Sumerian cuneiform,
Baines said, that they were probably invented independently not
long after Sumerian writing. If anything, the Egyptians may have
gotten the idea of writing from the Sumerians, with whom they had
contacts in Syria, but nothing more.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, the writing idea became more widespread at the
beginning of the third millennium B.C. The Elamites of southern
Iran developed a proto-writing system then, perhaps influenced by
the proto-cuneiform of their Sumerian neighbors, and before the
millennium was out, writing appeared in the Indus River Valley of
what is now Pakistan and western India, then in Syria and Crete and
parts of Turkey. Writing in China dates back to the Shang period
toward the end of the second millennium B.C., and it dates to the
first millennium B.C. in Mesoamerica.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Some scientists pointed to other, subtler dangers. What, for
example, of the incentive for professors who need research money to
gear their work toward areas with the greatest potential commercial
applications, rather than the greatest inherent scientific worth,
in hopes of attracting corporate sponsors? And what of the
temptation to sign contracts with sponsors all but giving away the
shop, by, say, long delaying publication?
</P>
<P>
   A study by Massachusetts General Hospital policy analysts of
more than 2,000 life-sciences researchers published in 1997 found
that about 20 percent reported having delayed publication of their
results for more than six months, or not publishing at all, mainly
because of their relationships with private sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Although the study in the Journal of the American Medical
Association said the withholding of data was less than widespread,
it said it had affected a significant number of faculty,
particularly the most productive and entrepreneurial.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing wrong with money, Alan Hartford, a
Massachusetts General Hospital research fellow, told the
conference, but ``what we must guard against is the loss of
professional values.''
</P>
<P>
   There is another, strong side to the issue that emphasizes the
good that is done by private money: studies have found that
professors with private financing publish more, teach a bit more,
and serve more as department chairs and journal editors. Indeed,
when this topic has come up in science publications, there has been
a solid chorus of voices from professors who say they see private
money as an overwhelming good, and feel unconstrained by the
agreements they negotiate with companies.
</P>
<P>
   But the Massachusetts General report also found that privately
financed researchers kept more secrets, and were three times as
likely as non-commercial professors to delay publication and to
deny colleagues access to their data.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, said Martin Michaelson, a lawyer specializing in
representing universities, the academic world seems to be divided
into two types of professors, one doing largely unappreciated
research without much funding, the other a kind of academic
rainmaker who brings in industry money and becomes ``a reigning
prince.'' And the problem, Michaelson said, is that ``they are
often not talking to each other.'' And frequently when such
entrepreneurial professors do talk about their work, they want to
reveal only enough to titillate potential investors.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem, too, said Charles M. Vest, MIT's president,
is that the boundary between science and technology is increasingly
blurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``And because technology frequently is tied directly to
commercial interests,'' he said, ``it presents an even fuzzier
picture.''
</P>
<P>
   So, what to do? Proposals varied, from calls for faculties and
administrations to defend information flow more vigorously, to more
concrete suggestions that universities refrain from taking equity
positions in companies or rein in professors tempted to sign what
they should not.
</P>
<P>
   Lita L. Nelsen, director of MIT's Technology Licensing Office
described one kind of clampdown. Sometimes, she said, ``faculty who
need money to do research to get tenure have to be told, `You
cannot sign that agreement; we will not honor it.'''
</P>
<P>
   She said she had the general impression that there was a
``drifting tide,'' at work, the attractive force of money, and not
enough of a counter-force. Maybe, she said, the conference would
get that countervailing force going.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be wonderful,'' said Howard K. Schachman, a
biochemist at the University of California at Berkeley, ``to return
to the era when collegiality and sharing took precedence over
commercial interests.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-99 0914EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990406.0055 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 09:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7435 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-RESEARCH-SECRECY-     04-06 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-RESEARCH-SECRECY-ART-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN PRIVATE MONEY MEANS SECRET RESEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ In the old, Cold War days, when gathered
university scientists would turn to complaining about how secrecy
strictures sometimes kept them from sharing their work, they
usually meant pesky national security restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   These days, they tend to mention non-disclosure agreements,
worldwide patent rights, royalty streams, intellectual property
fights _ in a word, money. And all the commercial hindrances to
open science carried by the powerful wave of private capital that
has been washing into the country's research universities in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   The strings that often come with private research money _ the
publication delays while patents and profits are pursued, the
proprietary findings _ hold the pernicious potential to impede the
free exchange of information that speeds scientific progress,
speaker after speaker warned last week at a conference on ``Secrecy
in Science'' held by the American Association for the Advancement
of Science and the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, private research financing is also undeniably good
for scientific progress, many noted, from the biotechnology
companies' bankrolling academic gene research to the start-ups
owned by professors who work that much harder in the hope of
getting rich.
</P>
<P>
   At MIT, one official said, private capital has gone from paying
for about 5 percent of research 15 years ago to nearly 25 percent
today. But, conference organizers worried aloud, at what price?
They called for a national dialogue to explore just how much the
secrecy requirements imposed by private finance cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commercialization of science,'' said Irving A. Lerch,
chairman of the science association's Committee on Scientific
Freedom and Responsibility, ``has resulted in a new regime of
secrecy which is very concerning to the scientific community,
something which we have to deal with.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nature of the scientific enterprise _ which depends
greatly on its own control, on its openness and exchange _ and the
need of our commercial patrons to recover their investment, those
create tensions that are tremendously important.''
</P>
<P>
   Concern over the commercial influence on science is not new, but
the advent of the biotechnology era seems to be bringing it to a
head. Compared with other industries, biotechnology companies rely
very heavily on academic work for the scientific underpinnings of
their products.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, said Robert Cook-Deegan, director of the
National Cancer Policy Board, private investment in health-related
research surpassed the public money put into it, and biotechnology
companies report that about a quarter of them are heavily dependent
on academic research, and another quarter are somewhat dependent.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, said Nelson Y.S. Kiang, a professor emeritus at MIT, the
committee ``has come across a number of cases that all had the same
characteristics: someone had a scientific result that he or she was
enjoined from making public because it went against the interests
of a third party, either government or a commercial business.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These were not aberrations,'' Kiang continued. ``It looks like
this is a pattern which is built into our social institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Among cases brought up at the conference was that of Dr. David
Kern, a Brown University occupational health specialist who
described the pressure he encountered not to publish his findings
of a new, potentially fatal occupational lung disease he had
identified among workers at a local textile company that had hired
him as a consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Kern had signed no scientific non-disclosure agreement, he said,
but the company insisted that he had and pressured his employers,
Memorial Hospital in Pawtucket, R.I., and Brown University, to
silence him. After Kern published anyway, his employers dissolved
his program, Rhode Island's only occupational health center, he
said, and barred him from treating the company's employees. They
also eliminated his tenurelike position. His contract with Memorial
was not renewed, and will run out in three months.
</P>
<P>
   Also attending the conference and put forth as a cautionary
example was Dr. Nancy Olivieri, a researcher at the University of
Toronto and the Hospital for Sick Children in Toronto. She recently
received a settlement and was reinstated by her employers after a
three-way dispute between her university and a Canadian drug
company, Apotex, Inc., over the publication of her studies of a new
drug for thalassemia, a genetic blood disorder.
</P>
<P>
   A third case was that of Dr. Betty Dong, a pharmacy professor at
the University of California at San Francisco whose research showed
that generic thyroid drugs worked as well as their brand-name
equivalents.
</P>
<P>
   Because she had signed a confidentiality contract with the drug
company that financed her work, Boots Pharmaceuticals, it took
almost seven years for Dr. Dong's results to be published in a top
medical journal. In that time, the paper's authors estimated,
Americans could have saved about $365 million a year by using the
cheaper generic drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The behavior of universities and scientists is sad, shocking
and frightening,'' said Dr. Drummond Rennie, another committee
member, who described Dr. Dong's case and the University of
California's failure to defend her. ``They are seduced by industry
funding and frightened that if they don't go along with these gag
orders, the money will go to less ethical institutions.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, many doctors give a diagnosis of nonverbal
learning disorder because it qualifies a student for more help,
said Ms. Fling, who lives in Hamilton Township, N.J. In Texas,
children with Asperger's are often labeled high-functioning
autistic for the same reason.
</P>
<P>
   Treatment is usually a mix of speech and occupational therapy
combined with behavioral training focused on social skills, Dr.
Weiss said.
</P>
<P>
   Volkmar called the overall goal using childrens' strengths _
intelligence and verbal ability _ to overcome their deficits.
Judith Rivkin, the mother of a Manhattan 9-year-old with
Asperger's, Sam D., described the process as breaking down behavior
that most people master without thinking into discrete fragments
that can be learned by rote.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a lot of practicing what you could say,
practicing taking the other person's point of view,'' Ms. Rivkin
said. ``Things like, `Do I have to look him in the eye?' `Yes, but
just a little bit to let him know you're listening.'''
</P>
<P>
   Many parents have found music and pets helpful. Ms. Willey
called music a ``salvation'' in her own childhood. ``When you're
really obsessing on something, it's as if music makes something
click, and gives your brain permission to say, `Ah! I can float
away on this!'''
</P>
<P>
   Adolescence is particularly hard for children with Asperger's.
Many teachers find it hard to believe that a bright student who is
disrupting class is not doing it on purpose, Volkmar said. Until
recently, that often meant that students with Asperger's were
lumped in with aggressive students in special classes for
troublemakers, a practice that he said amounted ``to putting the
perfect victims in with the perfect victimizers.''
</P>
<P>
   Adam S.' mother, Lori, has dealt with the trauma of teasing both
with her son and as president of Aspen Inc., a New Jersey group
that offers support to parents in the New York region. ``Because
our kids are so bright, they have a lot of self-awareness. They're
aware that the thing is to blend in, and that they don't _ and that
can lead to depression.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, Adam's district has assigned him a ``shadow'' aide,
who helps guide him away from inappropriate behavior as well as
keep him working smoothly in his mainstream classes. And his recent
victory in his school's geography bee is the kind of positive side
to his intense focus that his family and teachers can use to help
bolster his self-esteem. ``I was very worried about his starting
middle school,'' his mother said. ``But it's turning out to be his
best year.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Adam sometimes comes home crying, frustrated by his
inability to connect. Volkmar recalled one teen-ager with the
syndrome who tried to translate emotions into equations and offered
to give up a watch that was his prize possession if he could get a
girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   But children can be helped to connect. Ms. Rivkin said her son
has ``learned to have friends and to care about his friends.'' He
recently gave a rundown on his classmates ``all about how he likes
her, but she doesn't like him, and how this one likes me,'' and
wrapped it up by declaring ``and that's the Love Report!''
</P>
<P>
   Even adults who have overcome the most isolating elements of
Asperger's say they still struggle with the consequences of things
like having a poor grasp of what to say _ or not to say _ when.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people tell me I'm just a little weird,'' said Ms.
Willey, who has published a memoir, ``Pretending To Be Normal.''
``Other people think we're quirky and cute. Well, our quirkiness
keeps us from getting jobs, from making friends, keeps us on
antidepressants. We're screwed up.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Kirby, the creator of an Internet resource site for
Asperger's called the Oasis, said she gets messages regularly from
adults who hear a description of the syndrome and think it matches
them. Dr. Bristol-Power said many people receive diagnoses as
adults, but cautioned that the label could easily be overapplied.
``Where do you draw the line between a syndrome and diversity of
personality types, which you want?''
</P>
<P>
   The active role on the issue being taken by some adults with
Asperger's has made a push for greater acceptance for
``non-neurotypicals'' a central goal. David Spicer, a North
Carolina computer programmer who received an Asperger's diagnosis
at the age of 46 in 1994, says he is often asked if he wishes he
could be cured.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as if there's my autism, and then there's me,'' he
said. ``I don't exist separate from my autism.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Willey's daughter with Asperger's, Meredith, 8, is well
aware of the difficulties Asperger's imposes, from recognizing word
sounds to being easily overwhelmed by the bustle of a mall. But she
sees another side as well. ``When I find something I like, like
horses and Shakespeare and Winnie the Pooh,'' she said, ``I like
them a whole lot more than other people like their things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
