   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ Shorts on science: Items on Uranus's
seasons, red glows known as sprites in electrical storms and using
electricity in the ground to reduce contamination. (650 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LAUNDRY (Undated) _ Laboratory scientists are tackling the
rigors of the domestic battlefield known as the washing machine.
The goal is to eliminate a common laundry-day disaster, when a
washerful of white clothes is forever tinted by one colored item
that, like a rogue agent, has infiltrated the load. By Henry
Foruntain. (740 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ The Personal Health column: At
least a third of high school seniors have been drunk and heavy
drinking even occurs in junior highs and middle schools. Binge
drinking remains a serious problem on college campuses. But surveys
indicate that parents can play the biggest role in shaping the
children's drinking habits. By Jane E. Brody. (1150 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LIVER-TRANSPLANTS (Undated) _ In some cases, people are
dying because HMO's are basing medical decisions on the science of
the '70s, not what's known today. Specifically, HMO's and state
governing agencies have neglected to update guidelines on liver
transplants for people with hepatitis, because in the early phases
of liver transplants, recipients with the disease could not
survive. But that changed years ago, while guidelines did not. By
Holcolm B. Noble.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-INTERNET-PRESCRIPTIONS (Undated) _ Prescribing drugs, like
Viagra and Propecia, on the Internet is creating a whole set of
problems and regulatory agencies are unsure what to do. By Lisa
Napoli. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-TELEMEDICINE (Undated) _ The practice of telemedicine, in
which patients sit at home in front of computerized machines that
monitor their body functions, is increasing around the country and
proponents say it may actually cut costs and increase the medical
attention a patient receives. By Eric Nagourey. (970 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FIBROID-TUMORS (Undated) _ A new, minimally invasive
operation for shrinking fibroid tumors by blocking their blood
supply is becoming an increasingly popular alternative to surgery,
even though it is not yet an established treatment. By Susan
Gilbert. (1175 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
