<SLUG> BC-R-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIVACY RIGHTS CAN SHUT THE DOOR ON THE FIRST AMENDMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the 
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.) 
(gm) 
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   c. 1999 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   A
Fourth Amendment case before the U.S. Supreme Court has caused a
rancorous debate among First Amendment advocates. The question
argued before the court on March 24, asked: Do law enforcement
agents violate the Fourth Amendment when they allow members of the
news media to accompany them on searches?
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some First Amendment advocates say no _ that the news media has
a right to accompany police on searches of homes where there is
probable cause to suspect criminal activity has taken place and to
record the arrest of suspected criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. The Fourth Amendment, if anything, strongly implies the
home is a sanctuary of privacy: ``The right of the people to be
secure in their persons, houses, papers, and effects against
unreasonable searches and seizures, shall not be violated, and no
warrants shall issue, but upon probable cause, supported by oath or
affirmation, and particularly describing the place to be searched,
and the persons or things to be seized.''
</P>
<P>
   To paraphrase an English adage credited to William Pitt, Earl of
Chatham (1708-1778): The home is a castle, and not even the King of
England can cross the threshold without invitation. When the Fourth
Amendment was created by the Founding Fathers, it was to stop the
kind of abuses carried out by the king's henchmen in the colonies
when they went house-to-house breaking down doors and searching for
seditious material.
</P>
<P>
   The Fourth Amendment allows law enforcement officials to enter
private property and homes in order to conduct a search or a
seizure only after a warrant has been signed by a judge _ unless
the police are in active pursuit of a criminal suspect.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Code expands the Fourth Amendment so that it allows
officers of the law to bring along a third party who is acting ``in
aid of'' law enforcement _ an informant to identify a suspect, a
translator if necessary, someone who can identify stolen goods. In
other words, the amendment only allows government agents to enter a
private home. It was meant to protect our privacy. The media has no
constitutional right to ``ride-along'' into our homes with police
on raids.
</P>
<P>
   Fox network's ``Cops'' violates the privacy rights of all those
who are in their homes when police execute warrants and the
program's film crews follow police into homes. But the two cases,
consolidated and argued before the high court, did not involve the
Fox program.
</P>
<P>
   In the Hanlon vs. Berger case, agents of the U.S. Fish and
Wildlife Service were issued a search warrant to look for evidence
of killing protected wildlife on Paul Berger's ranch in Montana.
Unknown to the federal magistrate who signed the warrant, USFWS
agents had made an agreement with Cable News Network to film the
search. One of the agents actually carried a hidden microphone that
transmitted all conversations to the CNN technical crew. The
Bergers were not informed of the hidden microphone.
</P>
<P>
   The Bergers filed suit against the USFWS, claiming the federal
agency had violated their constitutional rights by allowing CNN to
be involved in the search. A jury acquitted Berger of all charges,
except for the misuse of a pesticide, a misdemeanor. CNN aired a
portion of the film footage of the raid in its story concerning the
protection of endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   In the accompanying case, Wilson vs. Layne, U.S. marshals and a
local sheriff department attempted to execute an outstanding arrest
warrant against Dominic Jerome Wilson. Before dawn, a Washington
Post reporter and photographer accompanied the officers to the
fugitive's last known address, the home of his parents in
Rockville, Md. Charles Wilson was dressed only in his underwear and
his wife, Geraldine, was wearing a sheer nightgown when the
officers, reporter and photographer entered their home. The
reporter took notes; the photographer took pictures. The fugitive
son was not at his parents' home. The photographs were not
published. But the Wilsons sued the federal and state law
enforcement agents, asserting their Fourth Amendment rights had
been violated.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for the law enforcement officials in these cases argue
that allowing the media to accompany officers helps ensure accurate
news coverage. The 24 news organizations, who filed briefs siding
with law enforcement, argued that such ride-alongs fulfill the
media's role as a watchdog. It is naive to think that a reporter
accompanying law enforcement officials is going to be a witness to
police brutality.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters from the New York Times, the Associated Press, the
Houston Chronicle and the Hearst Newspapers who covered the oral
argument at the Supreme Court were in agreement that at least six
justices showed their skepticism about the rationale law
enforcement officials gave for inviting along the media when
executing warrants. And, indeed, they should have.
</P>
<P>
   If police can invite a reporter along, why not a relative? Why
not a neighbor? The U.S. Supreme Court has never granted the media
greater First Amendment rights than any citizen. So why not invite
a friend to peer into the privacy of someone's home when a warrant
is served?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the friend can publish what he or she sees on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, a line must be drawn. And the front door of our homes
is the proper and precise place to draw that line. Privacy is
essential to all human beings, to all families. The sense that your
home is your castle, no matter how humble, allows us to live more
fully, more intimately, more securely, in sum, more humanly.
</P>
<P>
   The First Amendment cannot trump the legitimate expectations of
privacy we all have when we shut the front door against the world.
Expect the high court to reinforce that great principle.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
