<HEADER>
A7514 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES0     04-06 0248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHORTTAKES: Makes you feel all historic
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Funny thing, I suddenly have a feel for how the Austrians must
have felt in 1914. It was in June that year, a Serbian nationalist
named Princip decided to gun down the Austrian Archduke Francis
Ferdinand in the streets of Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
   That is all ancient history, but everything that happened more
than three weeks ago is ancient history these days. The Austrians
didn't take kindly to death by archduke. Germany thought that was
jolly, and we were off on what came to be called World War I. The
autocratic Austrians probably thought they represented rationality
and order in that part of the world. Never get in the way of
contending rationalities.
</P>
<P>
   Now we're bombing the daylights out of Serbia, and thinking we
represent rationality and order in that part of the world.
Actually, we may, but this is a case where the outcome, death,
dislocation and destruction, is just about as bad as the cause,
death, dislocation and destruction.
</P>
<P>
   If Bill Clinton, the anti-war activist of the Vietnam era, has
any taste for irony, he must be struck by the similarity of his
situation to that of Lyndon Johnson, who also hoped bombs, more
bombs, just had to work.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
