<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLACK-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACIFISM WON'T HELP KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CARY CLACK  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ On the cold rainy night of Jan. 15, 1991, I
marched in an anti-war demonstration, the only one I've ever
participated in. The Persian Gulf War had begun, and I joined
several hundred people in the march from Atlanta's Piedmont Park,
down Auburn Avenue to the crypt of Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. at
the King Center.
</P>
<P>
   That was to be expected of someone who'd studied nonviolence at
the center and who has returned there each summer and January to
teach workshops, as I have done.
</P>
<P>
   Yet today, eight years later, I support, reluctantly, the NATO
bombing of Yugoslavia. I'm no more bellicose than I was back then.
For almost half my life I've advocated nonviolence; I've written
about it, spoken about it and, more important, tried _ while often
failing _ to live it.
</P>
<P>
   I believe, more strongly than ever, that only through a
commitment to nonviolence can the scourges of poverty, war and
hatred be overcome, that only nonviolence can break the manacled
chain of violence.
</P>
<P>
   But whereas the war against Iraq was about the salvation of an
oil supply, the attacks on Yugoslavia are about the salvation of
people. For all the tremendous admiration I have for pacifists, I'm
not one because I can't categorically say that force is never
warranted.
</P>
<P>
   I believe that the first goal of nonviolence is to stop
unnecessary pain and suffering, such as the ethnic cleansing
campaign the Serbs are waging on Kosovo's ethnic Albanians. But
what options were left once diplomacy with Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic had repeatedly failed?
</P>
<P>
   The theologian Reinhold Niebuhr described classical pacifism as
the kind where one is concerned about one's own purity and not
responsibility, ``and the great ethical divide is between people
who want to be pure and those who want to be responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   The ethical divide that must be crossed by individuals, nations
and multilateral alliances is whether the international community
has a responsibility to stop the slaughter of innocent people,
whether the victims are Albanians in Kosovo, Bosnian Muslims,
Serbs, Rwandans or Sudanese.
</P>
<P>
   If not, then how in the name of God, Allah, Jehovah or whatever
religious or spiritual tenets we embrace, can we justify doing
nothing? At what point does our conscience become so assaulted with
the suffering of other human beings that we choose to no longer
respond?
</P>
<P>
   Kitty Genovese's name is a symbol of neglect and dereliction of
responsibility. In New York City in 1964, she was stabbed to death
in a 45-minute attack that was witnessed and heard by 38 people,
who did nothing to help. This has been called ``bystander effect,''
in which many bystanders are present at a crisis but everyone
leaves the responsibility of action to others.
</P>
<P>
   The international community has a shameful history of waiting
too long to respond to genocide, whether it was the Holocaust,
Bosnia or Rwanda. Are moral obligations to help those in need
limited by their distance from us?
</P>
<P>
   The torrents of war roll through history in a bloody cascade of
innocent people. Finding a way to reduce that torrent to a trickle
remains, perhaps, our greatest challenge.
</P>
<P>
   That a Serb child will be killed so that a Kosovar Albanian
child won't isn't a just or logical equation. Somehow, although I
still believe the answer lies in nonviolence, we have to find a way
where we won't have to make that choice.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Cary Clack is a columnist for the San Antonio Express-News,
P.O. Box 2171, San Antonio, TX 78297.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
