<HEADER>
A7622 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKEES-ZIMMER-HN     04-06 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-ZIMMER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINCH-HITTING FOR JOE TORRE NO DREAM JOB FOR YANKEE MANAGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ Don Zimmer was going to have to call in sick. It
was only an exhibition game, but he was going into the hospital,
leaving the New York Yankees yet another manager short.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer shrugged, and made it a point to immediately assure
everybody there was no need to start a vigil. Just a routine
follow-up to monitor an ulcer that doctors discovered over the
winter.
</P>
<P>
   Other than being 68 and hobbling on a surgically repaired right
knee and worrying about dear friend Joe Torre and being in George
Steinbrenner's line of fire, Zimmer couldn't be better.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the diseases around here,'' Zimmer said, ``shoot, there's
nothing wrong with no little ulcer.''
</P>
<P>
   Mention anything about doctors in the vicinity of the Yankees
these days, and people get more nervous than a left-handed hitter
facing Randy Johnson. Torre is on leave due to prostate cancer
surgery. Darryl Strawberry is trying to re-establish himself as a
big-leaguer and is undergoing treatment for colon cancer.
Minor-league catcher Jaime Torres is recuperating from thyroid
cancer treatment. Third baseman Mike Lowell, whom the Yankees
traded out of their minor-league system this past winter, is on the
mend from testicular cancer surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Until further notice, then, Zimmer is the interim manager.
</P>
<P>
   Is he having fun?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no, no,'' Zimmer said. ``For many, many reasons. One of
them is, I was crippled when I took the job and got more crippled
being on it. When I say `crippled,' I mean hurting. Hurting bad (in
the knee, which doctors have drained several times). That took the
fun out of it for me. I couldn't be where I was supposed to be at
different times. I did the best I could, and I just kept injuring
it more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus, taking over a club _ I don't care what club _ for a guy
who's laying in a hospital after a cancer operation, there's no way
that I could be at ease at any time. You hear so many things. Who
should manage the team? Who should do this? Those things get on
your mind, but I can't worry about nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be nobody in the world _ including Ali, his
(Torre's) wife _ who will be happier when he comes back.''
</P>
<P>
   As it so happens, Zimmer is overseeing a club that won 114 games
during a 1998 season that was highly irregular.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees stormed through the American League playoffs, swept
the San Diego Padres in the World Series, and took their bows after
finishing with a major-league-record 125 wins.
</P>
<P>
   When the Yankees acquired five-time Cy Young Award winner Roger
Clemens at the start of spring training, things looked almost too
good to be true.
</P>
<P>
   Things were too good to be true.
</P>
<P>
   At best, the Yankees began the season Monday night in Oakland
without the man who has led them to World Series titles twice in
the past three years. At worst ... Nobody wants to contemplate
that. (The A's beat the visiting world champions 5-3 in the
rain-soaked opener.)
</P>
<P>
   Doctors say the prognosis for Torre is as promising as the
Yankees' prospects of reaching the postseason. Early indications
are that the cancer did not spread.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this team has a lot of strength,'' said third baseman
Scott Brosius, the MVP of the '98 World Series. ``To be quite
honest, it's really not a team issue. It's not a baseball issue.
It's strictly an issue of a person who has a disease that he's
fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to go about our business, do the things we do and
continue on a personal level to keep praying that everything goes
well for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre, 58, eased some concerns by beginning to drop by Tampa's
Legends Field training complex near the end of camp. He wanted to
show the players that he is fine, that he's resting and recovering
as fast as he can.
</P>
<P>
   Until he returns, his trusted right-hand man _ a cross between
Popeye and Yoda _ is in charge.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer began his professional baseball career in 1949. He has
managed the San Diego Padres, Texas Rangers, Boston Red Sox and
Chicago Cubs. He got married on the field before a 1951 game in
Elmira, N.Y., then got in uniform and played.
</P>
<P>
   Other than one Social Security check that Zimmer cashed when he
thought he had retired after the 1995 season, he hasn't earned a
dollar outside of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   All that experience, and none of it prepared Zimmer for his
current situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even know how to explain the feeling I have here,
because I'm not the manager, in a sense,'' said Zimmer, who has
been the Yankees' bench coach since Torre brought him out of a
brief retirement before the 1996 season. ``I don't think I've ever
managed a team where I wasn't at ease. But here, it's different.
It's not my team. We're here to try and do the best we can until
our man gets back.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Torre always seemed to know the right thing to do and say.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I have a meeting, for any reason, I'm not Joe Torre,''
Zimmer said. ``Joe Torre is a very soft-spoken individual. Kind.
Loves everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not Joe Torre. If I'm going to have a meeting, I can't
tell Joe to put it on a tape and let me play it for the players. If
I'm going to have a meeting, I've got so say it the way I want to
say it. It's not going to be Joe Torre. I am what I am, whether you
like it or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Brosius calls Zimmer ``the ultimate encyclopedia of knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's no way of knowing how the Yankees will respond to
Zimmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got some professionals in here,'' Yankees pitcher David
Cone said. ``Guys are taking care of themselves, getting ready to
go. We just deal with everything that comes. I'm glad he's here. We
thought he might retire after last year. Ironically, he's here when
we need him the most.''
</P>
<P>
   He's here, because, well, a dear friend needs him to be here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 68 years old,'' Zimmer said. ``I don't want to manage
anymore, except in this situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Joe.''
</P>
</TEXT>
