<HEADLINE>
FINDING THE RIGHT NOZZLE TO FIT YOUR GARDEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ A pass through the garden section of any home
center or hardware store will confirm that watering your lawn,
shrubs, flowers and garden has become both art and science.
</P>
<P>
   A variety of garden hose spray nozzles can meet your every
watering need, and in most cases they are all contained in one
hand-held adjustable tool. These nozzles often feature a large
round head with a selection of spray functions. With each turn,
there is a different nozzle opening, offering a different spray
pattern _ from mist to soaker, shower or jet.
</P>
<P>
   Now you can water delicate flowers with a subtle mist rather
than risk blowing their petals off with a blast tantamount to a
fire truck hose.
</P>
<P>
   The shower spray allows you to water more than one plant at a
time.
</P>
<P>
   Turn to the jet spray for cleaning debris from the driveway,
washing windows or house siding.
</P>
<P>
   Similar to traditional hose nozzles, the squeeze-grip handle
features a lock bar, so the water stays on, without having to
constantly maintain a strong grip on the handle.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the manufacturer, adjustable hose nozzles come in a
variety of materials, from chrome-plated to rubber and high-impact
plastic. The price will vary between manufacturers, materials and
number of jet options. But most adjustable sprays range in price
from approximately $4.79 to $20.
</P>
<P>
   To keep a nozzle in good working order, always wipe off dirt and
any grease after each use. If spray openings become clogged from
hard water and its mineral deposits, soak the head in a
lime-cleansing solution, which is available at most hardware
stores.
</P>
<P>
   It's also advisable to keep plastic nozzles out of direct
sunlight on a daily basis, as the exposure may eventually cause the
plastic to become brittle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
