<SLUG> BC-FIBER-DIET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VARYING TYPES OF FIBER IMPORTANT TO BALANCED DIET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Doctors have known for decades that fiber is the
foundation of any healthy diet, and can help reduce the risk of
cancer, heart disease and diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The science is solid,'' said Joyce Bagyi, a clinical dietitian
at the Albany Medical Center here.
</P>
<P>
   More recent research, however, shows that while fiber is good,
not all fiber is the same. The soluble fiber found in oats,
psyllium (the stuff of Metamucil), beans, lentils and some fruits
work best at reducing artery-clogging cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
   Other insoluble fiber, found in wheat bran, seeds, whole grains,
and the skins of vegetables and fruits, is also good but serves a
different purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Most nutritionists say their primary goal is to encourage people
to increase their total fiber intake, regardless of the specific
type.
</P>
<P>
   The American diet, rich in processed and fast foods, provides
only 12 to 14 grams of fiber per day, about half the recommended
amount.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even diets including the recommended servings of grains,
fruits and vegetables may not provide adequate soluble fiber,''
said Joanne Slavin, a professor in the Department of Food Science
and Nutrition at the University of Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Soluble fiber remains longer in the intestines and thus absorbs
more cholesterol. Insoluble fiber absorbs water, which increases
the speed at which waste passes through the body.
</P>
<P>
   Both types of fiber serve an important function in the body, but
to reduce the risk of heart disease, it's worthwhile to note the
difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we think of soluble fiber, we really think of cholesterol
lowering,'' Slavin said.
</P>
<P>
   Adding a bowl of oatmeal and a bowl of split pea or black bean
soup is a good way to start adding soluble fiber to the diet.
</P>
<P>
   But it's only part of the story. ``The oatmeal can't work
alone,'' Bagyi said. ``It's really getting people to eat a more
balanced diet.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are some easy changes to make: Pick whole-grain bread over
white, add a fruit item to every meal, eat a salad or other
vegetable with lunch and dinner.
</P>
<P>
   A good rule of thumb, courtesy of the American Dietetic
Association, is five servings or fruits and vegetables daily, and
legumes at least once or twice a week. High fiber snacks include
Triscuits or air-popped popcorn.
</P>
<P>
   Another source of soluble fiber is psyllium, found in Metamucil
and other natural laxatives. While there's no harm in supplementing
a diet with regular Metamucil, nutritionists say the preferred way
to get fiber is through a healthy diet.
</P>
<P>
   Yet psyllium, which comes from a plant, is such a good source of
natural fiber that some food manufacturers, including Kellogg's,
have begun adding it to their products as a way to boost overall
fiber content.
</P>
<P>
   For those who are not used to eating a lot of fiber, go slowly
at first. The body needs time to adjust or the higher-fiber diet
may cause unwanted gas.
</P>
<P>
   Slavin often hears from people who give up on fiber because they
feel it makes them too flatulent. ``That's really a barrier for
people,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Gelder-Kogan is a fiber fan and not just because she
likes the taste of fruits and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come from a family with heart disease and cancer, so as a
sheer survival strategy, I've tried to become a healthy eater,''
said Gelder-Kogan, who lives in the Albany suburb of Menands.
</P>
<P>
   Gelder-Kogan, 45, believes her high-fiber diet has helped lower
her cholesterol from 325 to 204 during the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   She stays away from fast food and eats fruits instead of sweets.
``I can't remember the last time I had a chocolate fudge sundae,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   In her family, eating fiber has become part of the daily
routine, like exercise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's both changing your thought process and adjusting to
making something with a little more fiber,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-99 1321EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
