<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNIVERSITY-MARKETING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL HOPES TO BOOST ITS PROFILE WITH AD CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANDREW BROWNSTEIN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TROY, N.Y. _ ``Where's the beef?'' ``Got milk?'' To these
indelible advertising questions, Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute
hopes to add ``Why not change the world?''
</P>
<P>
   That's the centerpiece of the largest marketing blitz in the
university's history, aimed at making RPI a legitimate competitor
of research powerhouses like Stanford University and the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   Following a year's worth of research showing that RPI suffers
not so much from a poor image as a lack of image, print ads will
appear throughout the country in newsmagazines and television spots
will air on CNN, CNBC and MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is part of a national strategic campaign to gain
international renown for RPI,'' said Robbee Kosak, RPI's vice
president for institute advancement. ``We don't have the visibility
we think we deserve based on the quality of education we deliver.''
</P>
<P>
   The $250,000 campaign creates a singular look to go along with
the message. Gone are the autumnal tones, fresh faces and
ivy-covered buildings of the typical college brochure. The RPI ads
have a hard-edged, almost science fiction-like feel.
</P>
<P>
   The television spot begins with a close-up of Earth, electric
guitar reminiscent of Norman Greenbaum's ``Spirit in the Sky''
playing in the background. As the shot widens, viewers see Earth is
in the shape of a light bulb _ which fizzles and turns black.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many universities does it take to change the world?'' an
announcer asks. ``Just one,'' he answers. The light returns and the
screen fills with the RPI logo and directions to the school's Web
site.
</P>
<P>
   The six print ads feature innovative research conducted at RPI,
including Brutus.1, the computer that writes novels, and Map-Info
Corp., a student project that turned into a $60 million company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to get away from the ivy-covered image of most
universities and look to the future,'' said Dick Shultz, the
president of Media Logic, the Albany company that designed the ads.
</P>
<P>
   With increased competition for students and grants, universities
are beginning to turn to strategic marketing to enhance their
images. According to Kosak, RPI and Texas Christian University in
Fort Worth are among the first.
</P>
<P>
   ``The larger universities, particularly the ones with richer
histories, have never had to go on the marketing bandwagon,''
Schultz said. ``But increasingly, universities are seeing the
importance of having a brand and protecting that brand, rather than
just leaving it to tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign appears part of a synergy of measures designed to
boost the national profile of RPI, a 175-year-old upstate New York
school with an enrollment of 6,300.
</P>
<P>
   First, there was the selection of Shirley Ann Jackson, head of
the Nuclear Regulatory Commission, as the university's next
president. And, more recently, there was the announcement that RPI
would join a handful of elite institutions that require their
students to own laptop computers.
</P>
<P>
   Shultz thinks those actions would resonate for the ad campaign's
target audience, those he calls ``influence peddlers'' among alumni
and business people.
</P>
<P>
   An article in the current issue of RPI's alumni magazine said
the ads were aimed at ``a better-educated, more affluent and more
influential marketplace.'' Though the ads will run in national
outlets, they will be focused regionally in areas where technology
and enrollment is strong: upstate New York, Northern California,
New York City and northern New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign will last 10 weeks, to be followed by a study that
will examine its effectiveness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
