<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7645 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-06 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING THE SENSE BENEATH THE SURFACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   `Im having trouble understanding the phrase humanitarian
catastrophe,'' writes Joan Zomberg of Rockland, Maine. ``A
situation can be a catastrophe, a disaster, a natural disaster,
maybe a human disaster, but a catastrophe that is humanitarian,
that `promotes human welfare'? . . . Can the phrase be defended in
English, and how does it translate into French or Italian?''
</P>
<P>
   The catastrophe Zomberg refers to is, of course, the plight of
the fleeing Kosovars; humanitarian disaster is a frequent
alternative. And either one, if humanitarian is read as an
adjective, can sound absurd.
</P>
<P>
   But yes, the phrase can be defended. In fact, it needs no
defense: English, with its freedom to mix and match parts of
speech, is full of similar compounds. An English paper is not
``English'' in the same sense as your cousin from Birmingham; an
insane asylum is a place to house the mentally ill, not an
unbalanced building; a juvenile court may be centuries old.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, we take these words for granted, but
``occasionally someone notices that the first element in one of
these compounds can be read as an adjective,'' note Bergen Evans
and Cornelia Evans in their 1957 usage dictionary. ``This is all
very well as a source of innocent merriment,'' they allow _ and
indeed, such innocent merriment has made language maven Richard
Lederer famous, with his jokes about the semantic absurdity of
civil war and death benefit. But jokes aside (where they belong),
such compounds are normal English.
</P>
<P>
   Humanitarian catastrophe is a relatively new one; it's not
widespread in journalism until the '90s, after the Gulf War, though
the keen-eared John Updike had characters using it in his 1978
novel ``The Coup.'' We haven't yet assimilated it, so its
oxymoronic potential is more apparent than that of, say, criminal
justice. But read humanitarian as part of a compound noun and you
get the common-sense meaning _ that in humanitarian terms, with all
that word can encompass, the situation is catastrophic for the
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Politically, too, the term has its uses; it avoids the
inflammatory genocide (while officials debate the facts and
definitions), and it gets around ethnic cleansing, such an odious
euphemism it can only be used with sanitizing quotation marks. It
also blames nobody, allowing each interest group to pick its own
villain.
</P>
<P>
   As for the French and Italian, they're using the same words in
the newspapers _ and having the same linguistic debate. Le Monde
reports on the catastrophe humanitaire, Corriere della Sera on the
catastrofe umanitaria. But a letter to the editor of the Italian
paper makes exactly the same point as Zomberg does: If humanitarian
has to do with improving the human condition, ``come e possibile
parlare di `catastrofe umanitaria?' '' _ ``how is it possible to
speak of a humanitarian catastrophe?'' Word watchers of the world,
unite! (And how do you say nitpick in Italian?)
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, back in the American-speaking world, the crisis in
Europe has put a lid on bloviate, which was enjoying a revival in
the waning days of Monicagate. But for readers who inquired about
it during those windbaggy weeks, here's the scoop: Bloviate is an
American coinage meaning ``to orate pompously,'' according to
William Safire's New Political Dictionary, and dates to about 1850;
it's widely associated with President Warren G. Harding, apparently
an adept in the art. Michael Quinion's highly recommended World
Wide Words web site (http://www.quinion.com/words) suggests that
bloviate, like Harding, is an Ohio native.
</P>
<P>
   The real mystery is why the lexicographers ignored bloviate for
so many years. It's in my 1997 Webster's New World College
Dictionary, but readers searched other recent dictionaries without
success. Like disconnect, bloviate somehow eluded the radar of most
slang compilers as well as straight lexicographers.
</P>
<P>
   The peak of its current flowering may have been a George Booth
cartoon in the Jan. 25 New Yorker, in which Congressman Blowviatt
demands ``no more half-truths, no more spins, no more
taradiddles,'' then retires to his room with a copy of Hustler
magazine. It may be lying low while the bombs fall, but I have a
feeling bloviation will be back with us long before the current
humanitarian catastrophe has ended.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(What's the word? Write or e-mail yours to Jan Freeman at The
Boston Globe, PO Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378;
freeman(at)globe.com. Please include a hometown and phone number.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
