A7647 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-NOTES-BOS &LR;      04-06 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THESE AUSSIE EXPRESSIONS ARE EXTRA GROUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While dining in Australia recently, we heard a woman at the next
table order steak and seafood, then tell her friends, ``In America,
they call that surf and turf!'' True enough, but why bother
mentioning it: When it comes to colorful expressions, Americanisms
can hardly compare to Aussie talk. Here, from Australian airline
Qantas and down-under travel specialist Austravel, are some of the
memorable words and phrases.
</P>
<P>
   --We say ``hard work'' _ they say ``hard yakka.''
</P>
<P>
   --We say ``trousers'' _ they say ``strides.''
</P>
<P>
   --We say ``pay up'' _ they say ``hit your kick.''
</P>
<P>
   --We say ``thank you'' _ they say ``ta.''
</P>
<P>
   --We say ``goodbye'' _ they say ``ta ta.''
</P>
<P>
   --We say ``try it'' _ they say ``give it a burl!''
</P>
<P>
   --We say ``dispute'' _ they say ``barney.''
</P>
<P>
   --We say ``outstanding'' _ they say ``extra grouse.''
</P>
<P>
   --We say ``cookie'' _ they say ``bickie.''
</P>
<P>
   --We say ``slot machines'' _ they say ``pokies.''
</P>
<P>
   We hear some of these expressions may be fading, especially in
urban areas, with one reason being the ubiquitous and sometimes
insidious influence of American pop culture. Let's hope not: We
think ``tube and tucker'' (a can of beer and food) beats ``surf and
turf'' any day.
</P>
<P>
   (For more information on Qantas, call 800-227-4500. For more
information on Austravel, call 800-633-3404.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: Where can you celebrate Thanksgiving in October,
Remembrance Day in November, and Boxing Day in December? (Answer at
end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Fascinating fact: At 3,212 feet high, Angel Falls in Venezuela is
nearly 20 times taller than Niagara Falls, whose Horseshoe Falls is
158 feet high and American Falls 167 feet. (With thanks to
uselessfacts.net via frequent contributor Mike Schuster of
Foxborough, with additional research by us. A lot of work goes into
these little items, folks.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: The automobile known in the United States as the Hyundai
Elantra is called the Lantra in Europe and Australia. What happened
to the ``E''? &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``Living in Hollywood is like being in high school _ only
with money.'' _ Robin Williams. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Snappy slogan: CityWalk, the dining-entertainment complex at
Universal Studios Escape in Orlando, Fla., advises visitors to
``Get a Nightlife.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
How's that again? Sign in Pamukkle, Turkey: ``Entering the garden
is not allowed and do not leave any garbage.'' (With thanks to
Barbara Gilliland of North Quincy.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Don't believe it! You've probably read several times in several
places (but not this column) that all the hotels at Walt Disney
World are sold out for the year 2000 celebration. But it's not so:
There is still room at the Walt Disney World Swan and Dolphin
Resort, known for its combination of luxury with whimsy. With
prices starting at $575 per room per night, the resort is offering
a ``Millennium Holiday Spectacular'' package that features cocktail
parties, a special party for youngsters, nightly entertainment that
includes laser shows at the Dolphin, a ``Taste of 2000'' breakfast
celebration, and other amenities and gifts for adults and children.
But you've got to stay at least seven nights, from Dec. 26 to Jan.
3. For more information, call 800-227-1500, fax 407-934-4710, or
visit www.swandolphin.com. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mailbag: We recently wrote about a unique tour vehicle in Lake
Dora, Fla. called the Doodlebug. That struck a happy note with
pupil Matt Forance and the entire second-grade class of Suzan
Stamas at the Memorial School in Natick. Matt writes us that class
members have named themselves the Doodle Bugs after characters in
``The Leaf Men,'' a book by William Joyce. Their motto: ``Tiny of
body but brave of heart, we always finish what we start.'' Way to
go, kids! &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? At your friendly neighbor to the north, Canada.
(With thanks to Travel Weekly.)
</P>
