<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-AIRLIFT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRLIFT CHALLENGE: THE RETURN TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Evacuation of 100,000 ethnic Albanians from the chaotic camps to
which they have fled from Serbia's Kosovo province would require
the largest civilian airlift in history, but it is well within the
ability of the United States and its NATO allies.
</P>
<P>
   The real challenge to the allies, say current and former
officials of refugee-assistance agencies, is to return the refugees
to the communities from which they were driven. Otherwise, the
officials say, the evacuation will have helped Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic achieve his goal of emptying Kosovo of its
non-Serb residents.
</P>
<P>
   Already, families and communities that fled together are
splintering, reducing the chances they will return eventually to
their homeland. Restoration of previously existing communities has
never been accomplished in the bloody years since 1991, when the
disintegration of multi-ethnic Yugoslavia began.
</P>
<P>
   Little specific information about NATO's evacuation plans is
known, other than that Germany has agreed to receive 40,000
refugees; the United States and Turkey, 20,000 each; Greece,
Norway, and Canada smaller numbers. Administration sources said
Monday that details of when the airlift will begin, and how it will
be organized, are still being worked out.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of preparation _ coupled with the speed with which the
allies were able to pump over a million rations of food a day into
the region _ was widely interpreted as indicating that NATO badly
underestimated the likely size and speed of the exodus from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   This leaves the alliance facing what has long been a nightmare
scenario _ creation of hostile Albanian Muslim refugee camps in
Macedonia, which could give Milosevic a pretext for invading that
former Yugoslav republic.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew S. Natsios, who was director of the US Office of Foreign
Disaster Assistance in President Bush's administration, said Monday
that the evacuation of 100,000 people would be a massive
undertaking, requiring hundreds, perhaps thousands, of flights. The
disaster assistance office would be a lead agency in any such
effort.
</P>
<P>
   Natsios, who is now Massachusetts secretary of administration
and finance, said he did not believe the US government would run
the flights itself, but would rely on the Geneva-based
International Organization for Migration. That organization, formed
after World War II to help refugees return home, is supported by
annual donations from member states.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the US, NATO, or the migration organization runs the
flights, ``it can be done,'' said Natsios, who helped plan and
execute refugee relief efforts in Bosnia, Somalia, and Iraq. ``The
question is not that, but if you move them to other places, will
they ever go back? . . . The farther they go, the longer they're
gone, the less chance they will go back.''
</P>
<P>
   Natsios said that for any relief effort to succeed, the
countries leading the effort must have clear, constant objectives
and a strategy for realizing them. In this respect, he said,
``watching this unfold has been painful'' because the objectives
have changed several times and the evacuation does not appear to
have been part of the strategic planning.
</P>
<P>
   The impending evacuation dwarfs the dramatic airlift of US
personnel and allied South Vietnamese from Saigon on the closing
day of the Vietnam War. The 70 helicopters that operated
continuously between the city and US ships waiting offshore moved
only about 7,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Samantha Power, director of the Human Rights Initiative at
Harvard's Kennedy School of Government, said there is nothing in
the announcement of the refugee evacuation that indicates the US
administration foresaw the potential size of the exodus from
Kosovo, or contemplated the need to move refugees from the region
to prevent Macedonia and Albania from being overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were so busy focusing on protection of NATO pilots and on
political objectives, that this was quite far from people's
minds,'' said Power, who has been both a journalist and a relief
worker in the Balkans. ``There was also a feeling that the best
thing was to keep people at the border because one of the lessons
of Bosnia is'' that when people settle in far-away places, ``they
do not go home.''
</P>
<P>
   Refugee-assistance agencies are alarmed at the possibility of a
broad dispersion of the refugees. But they also say the refugees
must get relief from the chaos and horrific conditions in which
they are now mired.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a terrible mistake to move people out of camps to other
places where resettlement is not a real option,'' said Leonard
Rubenstein, executive director of Physicians for Human Rights, an
internationally active human rights organization based in Boston.
US military bases at Guantanamo, Cuba, and on the Pacific island of
Guam, where the US may shelter refugees, ``are not for resettlement
at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``These refugees have been subjected to cataclysmic human rights
abuses, and one of the major abuses is forcible removal from their
homes,'' Rubenstein said. Places like Guam and Guantanamo, which
are isolated from normal society, ``will really disrupt their lives
even more, unless people are aware what kind of places they are,
and want to go there.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Sheri Fink, a member of the physicians' group who is working
with refugees in Blace, Macedonia, said divisions within families
and communities who fled Kosovo together already are occurring, and
she fears evacuation will widen the divisions and lessen the
chances of returning the refugees to their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   But, Fink said in a telephone interview Monday, the airlift is
positive because ``these people have to get out of the situation
they are in now.''
</P>
<P>
   She said hypothermia, severe diarrhea, seizures, and mental
distress already are commonplace, and there will be a threat of
cholera if the weather warms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is indescribable how they're living in this field, sinking
in mud and human waste,'' Fink said. ``Most of them are city
people, and they don't know at all what to do. They sit there and
say, in English, `Help me, please. Get me out of here.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
