<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans 4 pages of stories, photos and graphics
on the continuing crisis in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Washington) _ Ledeall: Yugoslavia declares a
unilateral cease-fire, starting tonight, for Orthodox Easter. The
U.S. rejects it as a ``half measure''; NATO steps up its military
operations.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERBIA (Aleksinac, Yugoslavia) _ At least 5 civilians are
killed and 20 or more wounded after a NATO attack aimed at military
barracks hits a residential area in this coal-mining town 125 miles
south of Belgrade. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Skopje) _ Refugee developments: Macedonia is
apparently deporting Kosovo refugees against their will to Turkey.
In the process, families are being separated as they are being put
on buses and taken to airport. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Kukes, Albania) _ Refugee developments:
Refugees say that the police in Kosovo have said that their orders
have changed, perhaps as a result of the cease-fire announced in
Belgrade. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALBANIA (Tirana) _ Albania says it will take the ethnic
Albanian Kosovo refugees that Macedonia won't. By Steve LeVine.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ISRAEL (Tirana, Albania) _ The scene as Holocaust
survivors and others from Israel bring in aid to the Kosovo
refugees. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ECON (Frankfurt, Germany) _ A look at the impact on
European commerce of the destruction of Danube River bridges in
Yugoslavia. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   We are also considering, among others, stories on diplomatic
maneuvering on Kosovo and a look at the U.S. bases at Guantanamo
and Guam where refugees might be taken.
