<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-BANKS (Tokyo) _ Hakuo Yanagisawa, who runs Japan's newly
established Financial Reconstruction Commission, is seen by both
his fans and his detractors as the personification of change in
Japan's banking industry, as the charioteer who is alternately
exhorting and whipping his horses to pull the nation's financial
system out of the bog in which it has been mired for half a dozen
years. Views are mixed about whether the new efforts will actually
get the chariot moving again, but the market seems reassured that
someone is at least firmly in command of the effort. By Sheryl
WuDunn.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   MCI-NEXTEL (Undated) _ Folo reports that MCI is holding
preliminary talks about acquiring Nextel but that the two phone
companies have yet to reach agreements on basic terms and a deal
may never be reached.
</P>
<P>
   MURDOCH-LIBERTY (Undated) _ As expected, Liberty Media Group and
the News Corp. announce transactions that will result in the
cable-programming company's acquiring 8 percent of the global media
concern. Liberty, which is run by John Malone, will swap its half
interest in the Fox/Liberty Networks sports venture for $1.43
billion of non-voting News Corp. ADRs. Separately, Liberty will buy
half of MCI Worldcom's 5 percent stake in the News Corp. for about
$700 million in cash. The transactions will give Liberty, a unit of
AT&AMP;T, the second-largest stake in the News Corp., behind the family
of the chairman, Rupert Murdoch. By Geraldine Fabrikant.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-BANKS (Frankfurt, Germany) _ The boards of Societe
Generale and Paribas meet today to discuss the unwanted takeover
attempt by BNP. As a defensive measure, Societe Generale is
expected to sweeten its offer for Paribas. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-SALES (Detroit) _ Ford's sales rose about 14 percent in
March, exceeding expectations. Car sales increased 6.1 percent and
light-truck sales 19 percent.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   XEROX-APPOINT (Undated) _ As expected, Xerox names G. Richard
Thoman as chief executive. He is taking over at a time when the
copier wars are heating up. By Claudia H. Deutsch.
</P>
