<SLUG> BC-TASTE-OJ-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The San Francisco Chronicle's panel
of  professional tasters tries a different product available in 
 supermarkets.    TASTER'S CHOICE: Mollie's Squeezes Out Other Orange Juices  
   
   
   
 By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  For many people, the day just can't start without
orange juice. In recent years, fresh-squeezed brands with shorter
shelf lives have gained in popularity, with many people touting
their superior taste.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's panel tasted five brands of orange juice labeled as
fresh-squeezed. We also included one popular brand of orange juice
not-from-concentrate to see if there was a significant difference
in taste. And there was: Panelists scored the fresh-squeezed brands
as many as 57 points higher than the not-from-concentrate variety.
</P>
<P>
   Prices between fresh-squeezed orange juice and pasteurized
brands that are not from concentrate vary dramatically. There's
also a significant price range among the brands of fresh-squeezed.
But the panel's results suggest you get what you pay for.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Mollie Stone's &LR;  (1/2 gallon, $6.99 at Mollie Stone's) _ the
most expensive brand _ took top honors. One panelist described it
as ``a beauty;'' others noted the balance of acidity to sweetness
and pleasantly strong orange aromas. One panelist, however, did not
like the bitter aftertaste from the orange pith. Four would buy it;
one would not.
</P>
<P>
   Second place went to another brand that's squeezed at the
store: &UR; Whole Foods &LR;  (1/2 gallon, $6.29 at Whole Foods). Three
panelists commented on the superior balance of flavors. One
detected notes of orange blossom. Four would buy it; one might.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Odwalla &LR;  (1/2 gallon, $5.49 at many supermarkets) scored just
two points lower than Whole Foods. One panelist thought it was too
sweet; another described it as ``excellent but not as exciting'' as
Mollie Stone's and Whole Foods. Three would buy it; two might.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth place went to &UR; Naked  &LR; (1/2 gallon, $4.59 at Whole Foods).
Three panelists liked the balance and freshness, but others thought
it was too thin in texture and flavor. Three would buy it, one
might buy it, and one would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Wiman's  &LR; (1/2 gallon, $4.59 at Whole Foods) came in fifth.
Panelists complained about the bitter finish and lack of balance.
One panelist also thought it had too much pulp. One would buy it,
two might buy it, and two would not.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Panelists were John P. Carroll, cookbook author; Shelley Handler,
consultant and food writer; Donna Katzl, chef-owner, Cafe For All
Seasons, San Francisco; Roland Passot, chef-owner, La Folie in San
Francisco and Left Bank in Larkspur and Menlo Park; and Kirk
Webber, chef-owner, Cafe Kati, San Francisco. All products are
tasted blind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
