<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOODNEWS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   EDITORS NOTE: Food, nutrition and health studies bombard us, but 
 the seemingly endless information is often as confusing as it is 
 enlightening. Starting today, with Food in the News, The 
 Chronicle's Food staff aims to change that. This regular 
 round-up column will make practical sense of the latest 
 nutrition-related studies _ as well as offering offbeat but 
 tantalizing snippets of other food news to put on your plate. 
 &HT;       
   
 FOOD IN THE NEWS: Salmonella Infection Declines Nationwide  
   
   
 By Kim Severson  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Some good news about food contamination:
Salmonella infections are dropping _ particularly cases involving
tainted eggs.
<P>
   The Department of Health and Human Services reported last month
that the number of cases involving salmonella enteritidis _ the
type of bacterium associated with eggs _ dropped 44 percent between
1996 and 1998. Other salmonella infections dropped 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the good news doesn't end there. The report shows a 15
percent drop in the number of cases caused by campylobacter, the
most common disease-causing bacteria in the U.S. food supply.
</P>
<P>
   The Centers for Disease Control attributes the drop to new
strict inspection guidelines enforced by the U.S. Department of
Agriculture and the Food and Drug Administration. In part, the
rules require meat and poultry plants to keep scientifically
structured records of things such as refrigerator temperatures and
sanitation schedules.
</P>
<P>
   The report is based on the number of cases of infections
reported to five data-collection sites around the country,
including one that covers San Francisco and Alameda counties. The
sites reflect a health sampling of 20.5 million people.
</P>
<P>
   There is one piece of bad news, however: The rate of E. coli
infection continues rising and falling like a roller coaster. The
numbers of reported cases of infection by  &LR; E. coli 0157:H7 &LR; , the
strain that's most virulent, rose to 2.8 per 100,000 people last
year. In 1996, the number was 2.7 cases per 100,000 people; in
1997, it dropped to 2.3.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Exclusive Vegetables &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A tiny seed of an effort between organic farmers and the
government could result in the comeback of obscure, century-old
fruits and vegetables _ some of which may end up in Bay Area
restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   The group of farmers, researchers, seed producers and social
activists _ a California contingent among them _ met last week with
USDA representatives in Oregon to figure out how to make better use
of the government's 27 public seed and plant-material repositories.
</P>
<P>
   The government ``libraries'' contain about 437,000 species of
fruits, nuts and seeds. For example, researchers at the National
Plant Germplasm System repository for pears in Corvallis, Ore.,
have material from a 150-year-old tree in Massachusetts. California
repositories include heirloom and wild tomatoes, as well as samples
of rare dates and almonds. Other U.S. seed libraries hold Egyptian
onions, Turkish legumes and unusual spices, like black cumin.
</P>
<P>
   Although the material is free for the taking, farmers rarely tap
it. That's because samples are handed out in quantities too small
for farming. Many of the varieties never have been tested
commercially, which also keeps farmers away. And many who farm
organically are simply unfamiliar with the varieties at the
repositories.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the libraries are aimed at research-and-development
scientists, who use the material to breed crops with certain
traits, such as higher yields or pest resistance.
</P>
<P>
   The government is asking the new coalition of farmers to grow
some of the varieties stored in the libraries as long as they keep
records about how the plants perform.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, the farmers can market the seeds through a
cooperative, as well as sell the fruits of their labors.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers could see the early results on the plates of local
restaurants. Jim De Quattro of the USDA's Agricultural Research
Service envisions chefs contracting with farmers to grow exclusive
lines of herbs or vegetables based on material found in the
government libraries.
</P>
<P>
   ``As organic farming has taken off in the past five years,
people have more choices. And they continue to want more choices
when they go to restaurants,'' he said. ``I could envision a grower
hooking up with a chef to supply a certain type of, say, red
garlic. Let's face it, when you go to a fancy restaurant, you want
something new and different.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Toward a Better Berry &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Richard Rominger, deputy secretary for agriculture, was in Davis
last week to tout a promising alternative to methyl bromide, a
chemical fumigant that is being phased out by 2001 because it
damages the earth's ozone layer.
</P>
<P>
   The state's strawberry farmers, who rely heavily on methyl
bromide to keep weeds and soil-borne diseases at bay, are eager to
find new ways to keep crops healthy. At stake is an industry
providing about 80 percent of the nation's fresh strawberry crop,
or about 1 billion berries each year.
</P>
<P>
   USDA researchers working test plots in Salinas believe a compost
mixed with plastic mulch, beneficial microorganisms and corn gluten
might offer a solution. The mixture appears to stimulate a plant's
own defenses against pathogens and helps it get more water and
phosphorus. Phosphorus is essential for heathy plant growth.
</P>
<P>
   The California strawberry test is one of several around the
country conducted by scientists scrambling to replace methyl
bromide. Among them: an ultralow oxygen storage system in Texas
that could protect grapefruit from fruit flies and mold, a breed of
bell peppers in South Carolina that might resist root infection and
a natural plant extract being used as a fumigant in West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   About 23,000 acres in California are planted in strawberries
every year. The season begins in January in Southern California and
peaks in April and May, when strawberry growers all over the state
harvest. Northern growers continue to harvest berries into
November.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-99 1345EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
