<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7659 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-06 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOPEFUL NEWS ON MEDICARE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and k coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON &UR;  &LR; _ The sky, it turns out, isn't falling. But this is
a place where not even good news is viewed free of the blinders of
politics, so the fresh fact that Medicare is nothing like the
basket case portrayed is being processed as if it still were.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is that much of the politics of the government's vital
entitlement programs continues to be trapped in the vanished
atmosphere of huge budget deficits.On the right, Newt Gingrich's
minions manipulated the chimera of impending doom to push for
privatization via vouchers _ ending Medicare, in effect, in order
to save it. They did it in their attempted revolution of 1995, and
they were back with a vengeance two years later.
</P>
<P>
   Each time they were defeated in their own Congress and by
President Clinton's veto actions and threats.But they're still at
it, and they have allies in the center who continue to push
cost-cutting ideas that originated in the era of $200 billion
deficits, when tough-minded opinion argued that the hemorrhage
could not be stopped unless all programs absorbed a fair share of
the pain.
</P>
<P>
   Time for some new thinking to take account of new realities.
Time to understand that the real problem is less Medicare per se
and more its place among competing national priorities over the
next generation.The occasion is last week's annual report of
Medicare and Social Security's trustees, shaped around the
bipartisanly accepted calculations of its professional actuaries.
</P>
<P>
   Until last week, D-Day (as in depletion of the hospital
insurance fund in Medicare was supposed to occur in nine years; to
nearly universal surprise, the report tacked on another seven
years, to 2015, five years into the retirement of the baby boomers.
The report called this ``a substantial improvement.'' Even more
significant, it showed that this improvement was as much a function
of cost-restraining steps taken two years ago and other
improvements in Medicare operations as it was of the flourishing of
the economy.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, the encouraging news is not likely to end with the
latest report. The new D-Day of 2015, for example, is based on a
midrange assumption of annual economic growth over the period
averaging 1.5 percent, far below current trends and historical
experience.Moreover, since the final steps were taken to balance
the federal budget two years ago (which included hefty Medicare
savings from cuts), the long-term deficit for the program as
estimated by its actuaries has been slashed by two-thirds. It's
still there, but, in perspective, the country has resolved far more
difficult problems, beginning with the fiscal red ink of the 1980s
and early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the most serious problem the government faces over the
next decade is not the entitlements by themselves, but the task of
balancing them in the face of other priorities. The real problem,
in other words, is the budget itself.
</P>
<P>
   Consider: In the unlikely event the just-passed congressional
budget resolution were actually to take effect, with its $800
billion tax cut and add-ons to military spending, the impact on the
rest of the government would have to be gigantic. Indeed, by a
decade from now, all spending other than the Pentagon, debt
interest, and entitlements would have to be slashed by nearly 30
percent.
</P>
<P>
   That includes everything from law enforcement and education, to
job-training, health research, air travel safety and child
nutrition. But before our friends on the left yell too loudly, it
needs to be recognized that the implications of Clinton's budget
proposals as fleshed out would only reduce that gutting of the
operating functions of the government by half in 2009.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, income-tax cuts are properly seen by most people
as low priority, given the pressures of the next two decades. In
addition, earmarking 15 percent of any surplus over the next decade
to Medicare, on top of the 62 percent for Social Security, will
relieve even more of the fiscal pressure. And reforms should be
targeted and fair, not masks for wholesale slashing that hurts the
vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Raising the insurance cost for the highest-income beneficiaries
is prudent and fair; raising the eligibility age is crude. More
choice and more managed care for the healthy elderly is sensible,
but phony choices designed to herd people are only disguised burden
shifts onto backs of the less well-to-do, who already are paying
more out of pocket every year.
</P>
<P>
   It helps to remember that roughly 10 percent of Medicare's
beneficiaries account for nearly three-fourths of its expenditures.
It also helps to remember that Medicare currently doesn't cover
drugs, eyeglasses, and hearing aids, nor does it have caps on what
individuals have to pay out of pocket in situations that are
covered.Reform, in short, must expand and reform the program to
work.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the conventional wisdom is correct that the good actuarial
news takes the steam out of any drive to accomplish reform this
year or next. And maybe that means that Medicare and Social
Security will have to be a major element in next year's pivotal
presidential campaign. Great idea.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
