<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUICKCOOK-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   EDITORS NOTE: Here is a recipe to make on the weekend, with 
 enough leftovers to use throughout the week in two other recipes 
 plus suggested ideas for other dishes. Recipes follow, plus 
 suggestions in optional trim.  
   
   
   
   
   
 THE WEEKEND COOK: Here a Chickpea, There a Chickpea  
   
   
   
 By Maria Cianci  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  As a child, one of my favorite dishes was pasta
with sauteed onions and chickpeas. I loved the flavors of the sweet
onions and the salty grated cheese together. But the texture of the
chickpea really hooked me _ a creamy, dense ball that collapsed
under a little pressure from teeth and tongue. The flavor of the
chickpea wasn't something that I could describe easily, but it was
something I easily liked.
<TEXT>
<P>
   And I'm not alone. The chickpea is a popular bean in
Mediterranean and Indian cuisines. Its blandness makes it a perfect
match for herbs, spices and numerous other ingredients. Its bulk
makes it a good choice for appetizer, entree or side dish.
</P>
<P>
   The cook easily can open a can of chickpeas. But cooking dried
chickpeas yields a more interestingly textured bean and a cooking
liquid that has all sorts of good uses, especially when you cook
the chickpeas on the weekend and use them throughout the week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; MASTER RECIPE: VERSATILE CHICKPEA STEW &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds dried chickpeas (about 5 cups)
</P>
<P>
   4 fresh thyme sprigs
</P>
<P>
   3 bay leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 large rosemary sprig
</P>
<P>
   5 large garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   5 carrots, cut into 1/2-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   4 inner celery ribs, cut into 1/4-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   3 onions, cut into 1/4-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   1 pound salt pork, quartered
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon salt
</P>
<P>
   11/2 tablespoons chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   4 thick slices crusty, toasted garlic bread
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Freshly grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Place the chickpeas in a large bowl and pour in warm water to
cover by 4 inches. Soak for 24 hours; drain.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the chickpeas to a large soup pot; pour in water to
cover by 2 inches. Bring to a boil; boil for 10 minutes, skimming
from time to time. Drain.
</P>
<P>
   Return the chickpeas to the pot and add 18 cups cold water.
Bring to a boil over high heat. Bundle together the thyme, bay
leaves and rosemary; tie with kitchen string. Add this bouquet
garni and the garlic to the pot. Reduce heat and simmer for 30
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the carrots, celery, onions and salt pork; simmer for 30
minutes. Add the salt and simmer until the chickpeas are very
tender and the liquid is cloudy and slightly thickened, about 2
hours total cooking time.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen minutes before the chickpeas are done, remove the salt
pork. Finely chop and reserve all the meat. Finely dice a small
piece of the fat and add to the meat. Discard remaining fat.
</P>
<P>
   When the chickpeas are cooked, discard the bouquet garni.
Transfer about 7 cups of the chickpeas and vegetables and about 5
cups of the liquid to a heated soup tureen. Stir in the reserved
meat and the parsley.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; st  &LR;   &UR; To serve:  &LR; Place a slice of garlic toast in each serving
bowl, then ladle in the stew. Dust with pepper; serve with the
grated cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   Drain the remaining chickpeas and vegetables, reserving the
cooking liquid. Cool chickpeas and liquid to room temperature, then
store in separate covered containers in the refrigerator. Will keep
for up to 5 days.
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 15 cups chickpeas and 11 cups liquid.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 615 calories, &LR;   &LR; 20 g protein, 70 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 29 g fat (9 g saturated), 25 mg cholesterol, &LR;   &LR; 1,182
mg sodium, 14 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; WEEKNIGHT RECIPE: CHICKPEA &AMP; SHAVED CELERY SALAD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   Inner ribs and some leaves from 1 bunch celery, very thinly
sliced
</P>
<P>
   6 large scallions, including almost all green, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pint Sweet 100 tomatoes, halved
</P>
<P>
   1 cup (lightly packed) parsley leaves, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (packed) mint leaves, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3 cups cooked chickpeas (from Master Recipe)
</P>
<P>
   4 slices of toast
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the celery and scallions in a large bowl. Add the
tomatoes, parsley, mint, vinegar, salt and pepper. Toss thoroughly.
Add the oil; toss again. Add the chickpeas and gently but
thoroughly toss the mixture. Cover and refrigerate for at least 15
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add additional salt, pepper, oil or vinegar, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Serve the salad piled on top of the toast.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 435 calories, &LR;   &LR; 16 g protein, 58 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 15 g fat (2 g saturated), 0 mg cholesterol, 535 &LR;   &LR; mg
sodium, 12 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; WEEKNIGHT RECIPE: FISH WITH MEDITERRANEAN FLAVORS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   13/4 pounds Chilean sea bass, or other thick piece of mild white
fish, cut into 8 pieces
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt + salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon freshly ground pepper + pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 pound ripe tomatoes, sliced into fairly thick wedges
</P>
<P>
   1 large onion, halved lengthwise, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 cups cooked chickpeas heated with 11/2 cups liquid (from
Master Recipe)
</P>
<P>
   6 kalamata olives, pitted and chopped
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 550 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Lightly season the fish with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the tomatoes and onion in a 141/2 x 93/4 x 2-inch
roasting pan. Toss with 1/4 teaspoon salt and pepper and the oil.
Roast the vegetables until you hear them sizzle, about 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Stir in the chickpeas and their liquid and the olives. Space the
pieces of fish in the liquid. Cover with aluminum foil and bake
until the fish is just cooked through, 15 to 18 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Serve in warm bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 475 calories, &LR;   &LR; 43 g protein, 29 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 22 g fat (3 g saturated), 137 mg cholesterol, 439 &LR; 
 &LR; mg sodium, 8 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; More Ideas for Leftovers &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR; Cooked chickpeas and chickpea liquid become fast weekday dishes,
including:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Tuna-Chickpea Salad. &LR;  Marinate thinly sliced red onion in a
balsamic vinaigrette for 15 minutes. Add diced red, yellow and
green peppers, diced cucumbers and drained canned tuna. Toss
thoroughly but gently. Add leftover cooked chickpeas. Serve on
watercress leaves.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Roasted Lamb with Chickpea Sauce. &LR;  Marinate lamb chops in oil,
lemon juice, chopped garlic, salt and pepper for 20 minutes. Grill
or broil. Place them on a sauce of pureed leftover chickpeas
thinned with some of their reserved cooking liquid and seasoned
with a little cayenne pepper.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Cucumber-Hummus Sandwiches. &LR;  Process some reserved cooked
chickpeas with garlic until the chickpeas are pureed. Season with
salt, lemon juice and tahini (sesame paste). Seed and chop a
cucumber. Season it with salt and let stand for 15 minutes. Drain
and fold the cucumbers into the hummus. Pile the mixture into warm
pita bread halves. Top with sliced tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Chickpea Pasta. &LR;  Saute a chopped onion and minced garlic clove
in olive oil until the onion is caramelized. Add 2 cups cooked
chickpeas and 3/4 cup of their reserved cooking liquid, chopped
basil and red pepper flakes to taste. Simmer until the chickpeas
are hot and the mixture is slightly soupy. Toss with a cooked short
pasta. Serve with grated cheese.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Chickpea-Zucchini Stew. &LR;  Saute an onion and some garlic until
the onion is wilted. Add diced zucchini; saute until it is wilted.
Add cooked chickpeas and reserved cooking liquid. Simmer until the
zucchini is tender. Serve over rice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
