<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLASSIC-CHEE-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   EDITORS NOTE: Bay Area Classics profiles food-related 
 businesses more than a half-century old. 
 &HT;       
 BAY AREA CLASSICS: Marin French Specialty Cheese Ripe for 
 Choosing  
   
   
 By Karola Saekel  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; PETALUMA, Calif. _ &LR;  The French have a saying that a baker needs to
get a hand into the dough.
<P>
   At the Marin French Cheese Co., that old saw could be altered to
``you have to get a hand into the curds.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter how scientifically precise a machine might be, owners
Jim and Chris Boyce say, there is nothing like the hand of an
experienced cheese maker to determine when milk curds are exactly
the right consistency for making soft-ripened cheeses.
</P>
<P>
   And there is nothing as individualistic as a hand-shaped,
hand-wrapped cheese. It is to mass-produced cheese what a baguette
is to a loaf of sliced bread in a plastic bag.
</P>
<P>
   Except for Brie, which many companies produce, the Boyces claim
they are the only producers in North America to make Camembert,
schloss and breakfast cheese (a slightly firmer, milder cousin of
Camembert that's sliced rather than spread), all European
varieties.
</P>
<P>
   The cheeses are marketed under the Rouge et Noir label and have
been produced on the same site in Marin since 1865 (some sources
claim 1854) from milk provided by herds grazing in the surrounding
rolling pastures.
</P>
<P>
   The cows cannot claim quite as long a pedigree. In the 1930s,
disease nearly wiped out the main dairy herd, leaving just 27 head
of cattle. So a herd of Jersey cows was purchased in Oregon,
shipped by rail to Novato and driven over country roads to their
new home. Their descendants grazing at Dolcini farm, just down the
road from the cheese factory, provide Rouge et Noir with milk for
cheese. The cheese makers prefer these Jerseys, with milk at 4.5
percent butterfat, to Holsteins, with milk at 4.3 percent fat. The
more milk fat, the richer the cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Until a year ago, members of the Thompson family, pioneers who
started Rouge et Noir on a Spanish land grant, continued to operate
the cheese factory. When the last in the line, Bob Thompson,
decided to go on to other pursuits, the Boyces, who operate cattle
and feed ranches in Eastern California and Nevada, took over.
</P>
<P>
   The cheese factory, unlike most of the Boyces' enterprises, is
not certified organic. But since the Dolcinis never joined the
stampede to give their cows hormones and other chemicals, and since
the cheese factory relies on purified local rainwater exclusively,
the cheeses certainly are natural.
</P>
<P>
   The Boyces, whose association with Rouge et Noir goes back six
years, have some plans for expansion, but things basically will
stay as they have been for generations: The picnic area by the
bucolic duck pond will stay open to the public, and free guided
tours will continue. The tasting/sales room, which long has offered
a limited selection of salads, sandwiches, crackers and wine, is
being expanded into a full-service deli showcasing other local
foods.
</P>
<P>
   The Boyces also hope to expand distribution beyond the West
Coast, which would raise production from the current average of
2,000 pounds a day. Quark, a European soft fresh cheese, is being
added to the lineup in small quantities, and premium ricotta will
follow.
</P>
<P>
   These will be the biggest innovations since the introduction
five years ago of flavored Bries (garlic, jalapeno, peppercorn,
tomato basil and pesto), which won a quick following.
</P>
<P>
   The Boyces don't know if their son, Max, 22, an agricultural
economics major at the University of California, Davis, will take
over Rouge et Noir, even though he sometimes makes cheese on the
weekends. But they have a feeling of mission about their business:
The cheese factory will thrive as long as the local dairies
prosper, which in turn will guarantee the agricultural future of
the land. It is, says Jim Boyce, ``a symbiotic relationship.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-99 1346EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990406.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7662 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-GIDE-BOS &LR;      04-06 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-GIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIOGRAPHY SHARES THE PLEASURE OF GIDE'S COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
ANDRE GIDE 
A Life in the Present 
By Alan Sheridan 
Harvard University Press, 709 pp., illustrated, $35 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was a time when every undergraduate room came equipped
with a copy of Andre Gide's ``The Counterfeiters.'' An English
translation of the novel remains in print, but only one bookstore
in Harvard Square currently carries it. Of Gide's vast output, only
``The Immoralist'' is still widely available in English
translation.
</P>
<P>
   In France, of course, Gide remains a towering figure. Even
people who are not part of literary culture admire Gide as part of
their national glory. Partly this is because some of his work has
been translated into the popular media; also, his refusal to submit
to convention or authority in any sphere, most especially those of
morality and religion, makes him perennially attractive to young
readers. (For a time, it earned his complete works an honorable
place on the Vatican's Index of books it was a mortal sin to read.)
</P>
<P>
   Gide's life was one of his great achievements; it was unusual
and particular, but through everything, he stood for something _ a
great many things actually, so he became a worldwide symbol even to
people who never read a wrote he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   When Gide died, in 1951, at 81, he had lived through two world
wars and countless social upheavals, political crises, and literary
controversies. He owned settled residences but could never really
be said to ``live'' anywhere. He traveled constantly throughout
Europe, to North Africa and the Congo, and to the Soviet Union,
where he eulogized Gorky in Moscow with Stalin standing on the
platform; for a time he was the most popular European writer in the
Soviet state, until he wrote a book critical of the USSR. He knew
virtually everyone of interest in the Europe of his time, and his
lifelong friends were a luminous group _ and so were his enemies,
some of whom were former friends like Paul Claudel. (One of
Claudel's grandsons brought a copy of the published Claudel-Gide
correspondence for Gide to autograph. Claudel has already signed
it, ``With my regret at being found in such bad company.'' Gide's
response was to write ``Ditto.''). Still, Gide the man, as opposed
to Gide the writer, seems to have gotten along with nearly everyone
_ except for Jean Cocteau, whose poses distorted in the clear
mirror of Gide's intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   For Gide, sex and love were separate categories. Gide loved his
wife, his cousin Madeleine, with a pure and spiritual love, but
they had no sexual relations. It was Oscar Wilde, no less, who
confirmed Gide's homosexual identity; Gide's successful pursuit of
sexual adventure among younger men was lifelong. He wrote more
openly of his own sexual identity than any writer since the
Renaissance, and his Socratic dialogue about homosexuality,
``Corydon,'' became an underground classic, passed from hand to
hand, but kept under lock and key in many libraries. The love of
his life was Marc Allegret, whom he had known since childhood
(Allegret was the son of a family friend); Allegret became one of
France's most important film directors, and despite his own basic
heterosexuality, remained close to Gide throughout his life.
</P>
<P>
   Other women loved Gide with a passion born of frustration; the
saddest and most ridiculous of them was Dorothy Bussy, the sister
of Lytton Strachey (who therefore should have known better); Bussy
became Gide's principal English translator. His closest female
friend was probably the ``Petite Dame,'' Maria van Rysselberghe,
the wife of the painter Theo Rysselberghe. Later Gide responded to
a request from the Petite Dame's free-spirited daughter and
fathered a daughter of his own.
</P>
<P>
   Through all of this Gide wrote serious books and jeux d'esprit;
he wrote plays, libretti (Stravinsky's ``Persephone''),
translations, and theatrical adaptations (``Hamlet,'' ``Antony and
Cleopatra,'' and Kafka's ``The Trial''); he wrote travel books and
books of social and political advocacy. Everything he wrote was
marked by lucidity, honesty, and a refusal to oversimplify anything
complex or to accept any received truth. He was a founder of the
influential Nouvelle Revue Francaise and played a role in the
development of one of the world's great publishers, Gallimard.
Nearly everything that happened to him or that he thought of went
into a journal he kept most of his life and that stands as one of
the major achievements of 20th-century literature. His vast
correspondence fills many volumes. He was a mentor to many, an
exemplar to more _ a major figure in the memoirs and journals of
his contemporaries; some votaries wrote down everything the master
said in their presence.
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, it was left to an Englishman, Alan Sheridan, to
write the first full-scale life of Gide. Sheridan has the
credentials for the job _ the mastery of two languages; the grasp
of political and cultural as well as literary history; the
patience; the sympathy; the sheer industry. He has assimilated all
this material and handles it with easy familiarity, taste, and wit.
Sometimes he runs on for pages that catalogue places visited and
people met without much comment or commentary, but he writes with
insight about the life, the works, and their interconnections, and
he can suddenly cut straight to the marrow. Writing of Gide's
self-delusion about the ``limitless purity'' of his marriage,
Sheridan observes, ``This is not an intelligent man of 1998
speaking, but it doesn't sound like an intelligent man of 1919
either.'' Sheridan has no ax to grind, no theory to impose; he
allows us to share the pleasure he takes in Gide's company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
