<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7667 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROFILE-EPPS-2TAKES-A     04-06 1688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-EPPS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAN ARCHIE EPPS: POINT MAN ON CAMPUS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ A story outgoing Harvard College dean of
students Archie C. Epps III relishes telling:
</P>
<P>
   ``This happened, oh, maybe 20 years ago,'' Epps begins, sitting
in his ground-floor University Hall office.
</P>
<P>
   ``A senior tutor called a professor and said he was sending
along a student of his who was having trouble academically,'' he
says. ``The professor told the tutor to have the student wait
outside his office. When he opened the door, there were two
students sitting there. One black, one white. He beckoned the black
student in, and of course he had picked the wrong one.''
</P>
<P>
   Epps, dapper as always in his customary pinstriped suit and
jaunty bowtie, pauses to take a sip of tea. The afternoon sunlight
pours into his office, warm and comforting as an old tweed coat. If
these walls could talk, they would probably break into a chorus of
``Fair Harvard, we join in thy jubilee throng.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The point is, that's what the professor expected to find. A
black student having difficulty,'' continues Epps, who is stepping
down this spring after 29 years in the dean's chair, closing a
remarkable chapter in Harvard history. During the period under
discussion, Epps was upbraiding his own admissions office for
letting in too many unqualified black students _ a position that
cost Epps, Harvard's first African-American administrator, dearly
in campus popularity polls.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Epps was appointed to the post in 1970. Without seeking to be
initially, he was often cast as the college's point man on racial
issues, particularly during the tumultuous decade from 1969-79. By
1980, when Epps began to play a more organized role in articulating
racial policy, the college had reversed course and adopted a more
selective approach to minority admissions. One of Epps's arguments
to the admissions office then was that his office was forced to
deal with the failed experiments, the misguided gestures toward
inclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harvard was promising these students an experience it could
not deliver,'' Epps reflects. ``And it had certain expectations of
these students that they could not deliver, either.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Epps says, he began speaking out against
racial separatism on campus. He opposed the creation of a third
world center when other elite universities like Yale and Stanford
embraced the idea, unapologetically calling himself an
``old-fashioned integrationist.'' Militant students accused Epps of
being an arch-conservative masquerading as a brother, or worse.
Epps, who could have gone elsewhere (job offers were not a problem
for a young black Harvard dean with strong academic credentials),
chose to stay. Perhaps no official in Crimson history has taken
such abuse while deriving such personal joy from his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question to be asked now is, what good did I do?'' resumes
Epps, virtually interviewing himself now. ``Because you either
climb the ladder and pull it up after you, so no one else can
follow. Or you put it down so others can climb up too.''
</P>
<P>
   Epps folds his hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' he says, ``people here have trouble with that. Peter
Gomes'' _ minister of Harvard's Memorial Church _ ``was once asked
if I was being used by the Harvard administration. And Peter said,
`Maybe it was a double game. Maybe Harvard was using Archie, and
maybe Archie was using Harvard.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Epps leans forward, quivering with laughter. ``My response is,
maybe I am Harvard in some sense. Maybe it was my game all along!''
</P>
<P>
   His eyes dance with merriment. The tea table totters. On the
subject of his own legacy, at least, Epps seems determined to have
the first laugh as well as the last.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime allies of his say that is how it should be, too. That
the Epps hustled out of University Hall by student protesters in
1969, and flogged by black students for being too apolitical in the
1970s, deserves to be recognized as one of modern Harvard's great
humanizing forces.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Archie presents an incongruous figure,'' says government
professor Martin Kilson, Harvard's first tenured black faculty
member, who is also retiring this spring. ``He brought Malcolm X to
Harvard in the 1960s, yet in many ways he typifies the
old-fashioned black college administrator with his gentlemanly
ways. With Archie, what you see is not always what you get.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Kilson, Gomes contends that Epps has often been
underestimated, if not unappreciated. Do not mistake his innate
courtliness for lack of conviction, Epps's friends say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be fashionable to say he's suffered'' from the
personal attacks, says Gomes. ``But I don't think he has. Annoyed,
maybe. But Archie possesses an inner ballast that is absolutely
unshakable.''
</P>
<P>
   In Gomes's view, Epps's devotion to Harvard is not some
byproduct of his ``playing the company man'' but of something
deeper in Epps, who when he got to Harvard 40 years ago thought
seriously about becoming a preacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Archie held onto his own core values when others in this
community did not,'' says Gomes. ``And ironically, he's among the
few to enjoy vindication in his own lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: Prior to its 25th reunion in 1994, the class of
1969 sent a delegation to make peace with campus officials who
still bore the scars of the '69 strike. Calling upon Epps, one of
the few holdovers from that era, the group proposed it was time to
forgive and forget. According to Gomes, Epps drew himself up and
said, ``Gentlemen, while it is quite likely we can all forgive, I
shall never forget.''
</P>
<P>
   The story delights Gomes no end. ``Archie came here from afar
and bought the Harvard myth lock, stock, and barrel,'' he says.
``That's the great irony of Archie. At Harvard he's out-Yankeed the
Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time and infirmity have taken their toll on the 62-year-old
Epps. In 1995 he underwent double-bypass heart surgery. A few
months later he received a kidney transplant, both procedures the
result of his struggle with diabetes. The kidney was donated by his
wife, Valerie, a professor at Suffolk Law School. Anyone who knows
Epps will be unsurprised to learn that each operation has generated
a minimum of one punch line.
</P>
<P>
   His retirement in July is to ``protect my bride's investment in
me,'' quips Epps whenever the subject comes up. Discussing his
heart surgery, Epps says he looked up from the operating table and
recognized a former student of his.
</P>
<P>
   `` `I was in your office a lot,' the student said,'' Epps
deadpans. ``And I said, `Let's not talk about that now.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Epps, who has two sons, both Harvard men (Josiah, '98, and
Caleb, a freshman this year), is not really retiring, either,
although health problems have forced him to relinquish his
day-to-day duties.
</P>
<P>
   On July 1, Epps will assume a part-time position as college
ombudsman, mediator, senior class adviser, and mentor to younger
administrators. He will also teach a freshman seminar on race and
diversity he helped design and pursue other pet projects as his
health permits. Among these are a new student activity center (a
campaign he claims to be losing), redrafting Harvard's policy on
sexual violence (an issue that rocked the campus earlier this
year), and making sure that conservative speakers feel as welcome
on campus as liberals do (contrary to Harvard's repution beyond zip
code 02138).
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Epps era is inarguably reaching its denouement. Later
this month a banquet, church service, and concert in Harvard Yard
will be held in Epps's honor. The Harvard Crimson broke news of his
retirement last fall in headlines suitable for a papal visit.
``While many undergraduates couldn't pick Harvard's top
administrators out of a lineup,'' the paper eulogized, Epps ``cuts
a recognizable figure'' as both a ``sympathetic ear . . . and an
authority figure'' to thousands of Harvard students, present and
past.
</P>
<P>
   Incumbent Crimson managing editor Georgia Alexakis covered
Epps's office for three semesters. Being recognizable and
accessible ``doesn't sound like such a great accomplishment,'' says
Alexakis, ``but in the context of the Harvard administration, it's
significant. He's also been the point person on issues like housing
randomization and race relations, things that don't rate high on
the university's agenda. I think most students respect him for
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Epps summed up his own accomplishments in a Thanksgiving letter
to the community. Highlights: having presided over a threefold
growth in undergraduate organizations; helping establish the
Harvard Mediation Service, which assists in racial conflict
resolution; and participating in Harvard's often heated (but seldom
dull) conversation about race and diversity. Epps closed with a
quote from Emerson about the ``long winding train'' of men and
women who have ably served Harvard over the centuries.
</P>
<P>
   The quote was apt, not only because Epps is part of that
tradition but because Emerson's (Class of 1820) Harvard was
probably more like the one Epps first encountered than today's
version. When Epps arrived at the divinity school, in 1958, the
college had only 30 black students _ and no black faculty members.
Radcliffe and Harvard were separate entities, and the era of sex,
drugs, and radical politics was safely in the distance. The
Afro-American Studies department, today one of Harvard's academic
crown jewels under the leadership of Henry Louis Gates Jr., was 10
years away from conception.
</P>
<P>
   The college presents a vastly different face in 1999, with a
student body that is 34 percent minority and strongly (6 percent)
international in flavor. Minority representation on the faculty and
administrative staffs hovers near 20 percent. Could Harvard choose
its first African-American president sometime in the next century?
``Oh absolutely, that's within reach now,'' says Epps.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
