<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990406.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7668 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROFILE-EPPS-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     04-06 1816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-EPPS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 CAMBRIDGE, Mass.: ... says Epps.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One recent survey found that 80 percent of Harvard's 6,500
undergraduate students have mixed-race friendships, 60 percent live
in multiethnic dorm groupings. (A 1997 survey sponsored by the
Crimson painted a less rosy portrait of race relations on campus,
although Epps contends that the tone and wording of the
questionnaire had much to do with that.) College housing recently
went to a random assignment system, further breaking down ethnic
barricades. Multiculturalism is also reflected in the more than 70
ethnic and cultural organizations on campus, from the Armenian Club
to Latinas Unidas.
</P>
<P>
   Brandeis University historians Morton and Phyllis Keller are
writing a history of Harvard from the 1930s to the present, the
theme of which is the university's evolution from Brahmin preserve
to an international, meritocratic institution. Phyllis Keller calls
the race issue central to this evolution and credits Epps with
helping lead what has (mostly) been a quiet revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some students did not think Archie was going fast enough or
far enough,'' says Keller. ``He was not an appeaser. But Archie was
on the line with the students, day in and day out. And in the end,
the consensus he helped shape did prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Morton Keller, ``To me it's interesting that the first
black Harvard administrator was Old Harvard in style, from the teas
to the Glee Club. At Harvard, that can be very useful.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Epps did not set out to be a pioneer, to be sure, much less the
Jackie Robinson of Harvard Yard.
</P>
<P>
   Raised in Lake Charles, La., a mixed-race town of 70,000, Epps
and his twin brother, now a track coach at Jackson State
University, attended Catholic school. Their father, a former
football star, owned a local dry cleaning company and provided his
family with a comfortable, middle-class existence.
</P>
<P>
   Matriculating to Talladega College, Epps majored in philosophy
and psychology and was steered toward Harvard or Yale, neither of
which he could locate on a map.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not very sophisticated about race or much else,'' he
recalls. ``In the late '50s, the battle lines were just being drawn
anyway. I was frightened out of my mind when I got to Harvard, but
I made friends easily. I stayed here one summer to enter an essay
contest, and I remember sitting in Widener Library one afternoon
thinking, Oh, this is my life.''
</P>
<P>
   As the civil rights movement gathered steam _ Epps led a group
down to Washington for the historic march of 1963 _ so did Epps's
Harvard career. He was appointed senior tutor in Leverett House and
assistant Glee Club conductor, an outgrowth of his love of choral
music. Long interested intellectually in Islam, he taught a seminar
on the civil rights and black nationalist movements. Malcolm X,
James Baldwin, and Ralph Ellison were among the speakers whom Epps
brought to campus. Epps and Kilson became advisers to the fledgling
Association of African and Afro-American Students. In 1963, dean
John Monro recruited Epps as assistant dean after Epps had been
rejected for another administrative position.
</P>
<P>
   Was he marginalized in the early going?
</P>
<P>
   ``I had enough authority to get them in here to see me if I
needed to,'' Epps says. ``Also, if you talk to a faculty member
who's had too much to drink and said something he shouldn't have,
you can see him the next day and ask, `Do you know what you said to
me last night? We should talk about it.' I've turned many people
around simply by my length of service here.''
</P>
<P>
   The first phase of Epps's career ended with the retirement of
Harvard president Nathan Pusey, who drew fire from many quarters
for ordering state troopers in to break up the occupation of
University Hall. Pusey was succeeded in 1971 by Harvard law school
dean Derek Bok. From then on, says Epps, his mission was to help
restore order _ not at the cost of free speech but in celebration
of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Internally there was a great struggle over how Harvard should
be governed,'' says Epps. With Bok's presidency came an expansion
of the Harvard bureaucracy, growing from one vice-president to
seven. Epps and others labored to keep the college competitive
among all the other constituencies clamoring for the university's
attention _ and resources. In 1980, Epps published a study
concluding that minority students were ``separatist in
orientation'' and ``isolated from the mainstream.'' Bok responded
with a pronunciamento endorsing a new foundation committed to
diversity and a recommitment to affirmative action. Among Epps's
closest allies was Kilson, proof that institutional politics indeed
makes strange bedfellows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marty and I are totally different personalities,'' Epps
concedes. ``He's an eccentric and a socialist. I'm a conservative
Democrat. Yet on questions of race we agreed.''
</P>
<P>
   Kilson remarks that there are two types of administrators.
``Those who operate from personal vision,'' he says, ``and those
who operate like weathervanes. Archie always concerned himself with
the college's relative place in the larger university. And he was
doing that when he was a relative nobody.''
</P>
<P>
   In the '70s, says Gomes, a student committed suicide over
Christmas break. At the time, Harvard was trimming energy bills by
shutting off heat in the dorms when they were allegedly vacant. Bok
and other officials were badly shaken by the suicide, says Gomes.
With Bok's blessing, Epps drew up a plan to ensure that every
student on campus over the holidays got invited to parties at,
among other venues, Epps's home. Even black students who scorned
Epps publicly ``came to Archie under cover of night,'' says Gomes,
``wondering, `How does this man cope in an environment that's
killing me?' ''
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, Epps was interviewed for job of the dean of the college
but failed to get it. Some minority students raised the race issue,
which Epps characteristically preferred to sidestep. ``I was
disappointed,'' he admits, ``but I didn't encourge the protests
because that's not my style.'' Was race a factor? ``No,'' says
Epps. ``Knowing Henry Rosovsky'' _ dean of the faculty, who made
the decision _ ``I don't believe it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Epps was also thrust, not always civilly, into other
controversies in the '80s and early '90s. One was the debate on
whether Harvard should divest from companies doing business in
South Africa. Another concerned the college's final clubs _
Harvard's equivalent of nonresidential fraternities _ which had
held the line at admitting women and where alcohol abuse was a
vexing issue to Harvard authorities. Concerned about their
exclusionary policies, Epps led a movement to sever ties between
the college and the clubs. The divorce became final 15 years ago.
Epps has seldom met an undergraduate organization he did not like,
but in this case he made an exception.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was against their discriminating by gender, but I was also
tired of waiting by the phone for a call that another student had
been hospitalized because of drinking,'' Epps explains. At the same
time, he stepped up pressure on local law enforcement officials to
exercise more caution about randomly stopping young people of color
near the Harvard campus. Harassment of minority students was a
focal point for student protests early in the '90s. If the police
mistakenly detain a minority student today, says Epps, ``they know
the next phone call is coming from my office, requesting an
explanation.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Epps's authority over racial issues was broadened. He
published Harvard's first handbook on race relations, a resource
that is updated annually. Tensions also flared that year when
Leonard Jeffries was invited to speak at Harvard. Jeffries, a New
York professor known for his inflammatory views on Jewish
complicity in the African slave trade, ignited a fresh debate about
race and free speech on campus. The conservative Epps again found
himself in the middle of it. In the media and elsewhere, questions
were raised about Epps's contribution to racial progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason Harvard hired Epps for this job was to keep the
students in check,'' charged Zaheer Ali, president of the Black
Students Union. Ali, who graduated in 1994, told the Crimson last
fall that his view of Epps had softened over time. As dean, said
Ali, Epps had a right to question the group's invitation to
Jeffries. ``But as Archie Epps,'' Ali added, ``he understood.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Neil Rudenstine's presidency and the revitalization of
Afro-American Studies have helped put the finishing touches on what
Epps hoped to realize 30 years ago. While Epps played no direct
role in recruiting Gates, he kept the pressure on key figures like
Bok and Rosovsky to rescue the floundering department. Rudenstine
finished what Bok began by getting Gates here, followed by Cornel
West, William Julius Wilson, and others. Af-Am Studies is now among
Harvard's hottest academic departments.
</P>
<P>
   About Epps, Rudenstine says, ``His longtime devotion to the
college and its students has left an indelible imprint on Harvard,
and for me he has been a continuing source of friendship, helpful
advice, and judgment born of experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Epps, ``In my life as a black man at Harvard, it has always
been the people at the top who made the difference. Every black
person at Harvard who has worked in a senior position has his or
her scars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us won't tell'' how those scars were inflicted, he
adds with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   And conceivably Epps never will. A few days ago, however, he was
meeting in the basement of University Hall with a group of young
administrators. Epps was there to reminisce about his career with a
group that as much as any symbolizes the new face of Harvard.
Everyone at the table but Epps was a woman of color. Most were not
even out of grade school when he was heaved out of the same
building by angry student protesters. The sum total of their
institutional memory could have fit in Epps's boutonniere. And that
is no slight to them.
</P>
<P>
   After listening to Epps for an hour, some of the women raised
their hands and said that the Harvard they knew was not always as
accommodating as the one Epps had been describing. Specifically,
they told Epps, if you talked differently, dressed differently,
spoke up too loudly, or wore your hair in some
less-than-fashionable fashion, Harvard could be a fairly
unforgiving place.
</P>
<P>
   Epps listened patiently for several minutes. Finally he said
that while anyone had a right to speak out on these matters, he
preferred to take the long view and change the system from within.
Rising to leave, Epps mentioned that one of his retirement projects
will be a memoir of his Harvard years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell my colleagues it will be based on the secret diaries
I've been keeping all these years,'' he said, laughing. ``And when
I mention that, their faces go white.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
