<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7671 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-06 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEHRENS LIKELY HEADED FOR MASSCAP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Silverbulletday is cq)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   April has just begun and already a top horse is pointing for the
May 29 running of the Massachusetts Handicap at Suffolk Downs.
According to trainer H. James Bond, Behrens, who captured the
$750,000 Oaklawn Handicap with ease Saturday, is headed straight to
the $600,000 MassCap.
</P>
<P>
   A 5-year-old son of Pleasant Colony, Behrens added his Oaklawn
victory to a tally in the Gulfstream Park Handicap, and runner-up
finishes in both the Donn Handicap (behind Puerto Madero) and
Broward Handicap (behind Sir Bear), all run at Gulfstream, to stand
4-2-2-0 on the year. The $450,000 purse he captured at Oaklawn
raised his earnings to $775,000 for 1999 $1.7 million overall, with
a career record of 14-6-3-1. In the National Thoroughbred Racing
Association poll, taken before the Oaklawn Handicap, Berhens was
rated the fifth-best thoroughbred in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Behrens took the Oaklawn Handicap by 2 1/2 lengths under regular
rider Jorge Chavez in the quick time of 1:47 3/5 over a sloppy
track, returning $5 to win as the 3-2 choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me, `Don't get in any trouble,' '' said Chavez.
``The horse did everything. I never rode him on a sloppy track, and
I didn't know how he was going to handle it. But it was
sloppy-fast, and he just kind of skipped over it.''
</P>
<P>
   A top 3-year-old in '97, when he was beaten just a nose (by
Deputy Commander) in the Travers at Saratoga, and then won the
Pegasus at Meadowlands, Behrens went on to have a rough 1998
campaign. He went to Dubai for the World Cup in March, finished
fifth behind Silver Charm, and came back exhausted. He ran only
once more that season, finishing ninth in the Brooklyn at Belmont
in June, and finishing the year a dismal 4-0-0-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``This colt was outstanding as a 3-year-old,'' said Bond.
``After he finished seventh in the Breeders' Cup Classic, everybody
kind of wrote him off, and 1998 was a disaster after Dubai. Now, he
has come back, and we have something to build on.''
</P>
<P>
   Assuming good health, the next building block will be the
MassCap. Bond is friendly with Suffolk vice president Lou Raffetto.
They keep in regular contact, and Bond, who is based in New York,
enjoyed the hospitality here when his Will's Way ran third behind
Skip Away and Formal Gold, respectively, in the 1997 MassCap. With
22 points, Behrens is the leader in the NTRA handicap series, which
concludes with the Pacific Classic in August and offers rich
bonuses; the MassCap has 6 points to contribute to the winner.
</P>
<P>
   Behrens was favored in the Gulfstream Park Handicap, as well as
at Oaklawn, and unless a real heavy hitter, such as Free House or
Silver Charm, shows up, Behrens will be favored in the MassCap.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A big weekend
</P>
<P>
   It's been a roller coaster ride for trainer Bob Baffert, but the
Silver Fox is back in the lead on the road to the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   The most important thing to note on what was a sensational
weekend for Team Baffert is that he has not ruled out running
outstanding filly Silverbulletday in the Derby. Silverbulletday has
won 9 of 10 career starts and $1.75 million. She has consistently
earned higher speed figures than the 3-year-old males, and she
might well be favored in the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   After Silverbulletday took Saturday's $500,000 Ashland Stakes at
Keeneland by 7 lengths in another impressive performance against
fellow fillies, Baffert said, ``If we went with a filly in the
Derby, it would be Silverbulletday.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert has committed his other top filly, Excellent Meeting,
who tallied in the $250,000 Fantasy Stakes at Oaklawn Friday and
now has a career mark of 11-7-3-1 and $1.1 million in earnings, to
the Kentucky Oaks April 30. He doesn't need to run both fillies to
win the Oaks. If Silverbulletday races in the Derby, it will give
high-profile Mike Pegram a chance to become the fist owner to win
the Derby back-to-back since Penny Tweedy's Meadow Stable did it
with Riva Ridge and Secretariat in 1972-73.
</P>
<P>
   Not only were Baffert's outstanding fillies victorious over the
weekend, but his colts, General Challenge and Prime Timber, ran
1-2, respectively, in the $1 million Santa Anita Derby Saturday.
Baffert's fillies never failed him, but at one point, he had lost
his top 3-year-old colt, Exploit, to injury, Finder's Gold and
Straight Man had flopped, and General Challenge (in the Louisiana
Derby) and Prime Timber (in the San Rafael) had been beaten.
</P>
<P>
   Now, everything's coming up roses for Baffert, especially if he
starts Silverbulletday in America's greatest race.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Quick turnaround?
</P>
<P>
   Desert Hero, who had won both of his starts, including the San
Rafael, was mildly disappointing in the Santa Anita Derby,
finishing third, beaten a total of 7 lengths, behind the Baffert
duo. In what would be an intriguing move, trainer Richard Mandella
may run Desert Hero in the Derby Trial at Churchill, a 1-mile prep
race April 24. Because he has run only three times in his career,
Desert Hero might be fresh enough to run in the Trial and the Derby
one week later, which would be very unusual for a serious
contender. If not, he could run in the Trial and go to the
Preakness at Pimlico May 15. ``We have no plan right now,'' said
Mandella. ``Anything's possible. We'll watch him for a week and
see. The Derby Trial is a possibility.'' . . . If you're looking
for a long shot in Saturday's Blue Grass at Keeneland, you could
take a shot with Lemon Drop Kid. A promising 2-year-old, Lemon Drop
Kid has run only once this year, winning an allowance at Gulfstream
Feb. 27. However, his trainer is very high on him. ``He really
loves this racetrack,'' said veteran conditioner Scotty Schulhofer
after Lemon Drop Kid zipped 5 furlongs Saturday in :58 3/5, out 6
furlongs in a rapid 1:10 3/5. ``He did it so easily. We didn't ask
him, he did it all on his own. He's as good as I can get him right
now. He's feeling awfully good. I'll tell you the truth. I think
this colt is as good as any horse I've ever had. Maybe he hasn't
won the big races or proven it yet, but I really think he is the
best. He is so professional. He eats and he sleeps and he runs.'' .
. . Suffolk will award a patron a trip for two to the Kentucky
Derby if he or she can win the ``Derby Prep Pick Three'' contest
Saturday. A fan must pick the winners of the Blue Grass, Wood
Memorial at Aqueduct, and Arkansas Derby at Oaklawn that day. If
more than one person picks all three, a drawing will determine who
gets the trip. You must be present to win.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Material from publicity departments at various racetracks was used
in this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
