<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7674 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FREAKNIK-FIZZLE-BOS &LR;      04-06 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREAKNIK-FIZZLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREAKNIK 1999 MAY BE NO-SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CURTIS WILKIE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As the third weekend in April approaches, Atlanta is
waiting to see if Freaknik, a boisterous rite of spring for black
college students, will be gone with the wind.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since the event began in 1982 as a
spontaneous gathering of fewer than 100 revelers, eventually
growing into an annual attraction for tens of thousands, there are
signs that the party might not materialize here this year.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Freaknik Web site promises that the 1999 celebration
``will attract over 450,000 visitors to Atlanta Centennial Olympic
Park April 16-18,'' city officials say that no one associated with
the event has applied for permits for outdoor activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has not been the level of interest this year as much as
in previous years,'' said Nick Gold, press secretary for Mayor Bill
Campbell. ``That does not mean, by any means, that young people are
not coming.''
</P>
<P>
   The annual Sweet Auburn Spring Fest, in Martin Luther King Jr.'s
old neighborhood, has been scheduled to coincide with the Freaknik
date this year to offer ``something meaningful'' for student
visitors, Gold said.
</P>
<P>
   But the word on the grapevine from predominantly black campuses
says the scene may shift to Los Angeles or Florida. That would be
in keeping with the haphazard nature of Freaknik, which has always
been something of a moveable feast.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta event is a variation of the old student invasions of
Florida, when thousands of collegians swamped Fort Lauderdale and
Daytona during spring breaks. Like the Florida frolic, Freaknik has
been a study in disorganization.
</P>
<P>
   The Freaknik Web site did not respond to queries for more
information, and no one could be found to speak authoritatively for
the event this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I know, it's going to happen,'' said Seth Coleman, a
spokesman for Morehouse College in Atlanta. But Coleman
acknowledged that Freaknik ``has been pretty much killed off''
since he was a Morehouse student earlier in the decade and the
April weekend in Atlanta was in riotous bloom.
</P>
<P>
   In another sign that Freaknik may be disappearing here, George
Hawthorne, last year's chairman of the city's Black College Spring
Break Committee, told the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, ``All the
indications say that the event is going to be a nonevent.''
</P>
<P>
   Freaknik went into decline last year after the 1997 affair
resulted in more than 500 arrests, 535 traffic summonses, and three
shootings. The year before, a young man from Ohio who came to
Atlanta for the spring break was shot to death. Freaknik's
reputation also suffered from looting rampages.
</P>
<P>
   From its peak in 1994, when an estimated 200,000 students poured
into Atlanta, causing gridlock on the streets and pandemonium in
parts of the city, the crowds dropped to about 50,000 last year.
</P>
<P>
   Since one of the main activities involves cruising in cars,
Freaknik became synonymous with monumental traffic jams.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Wolfe used the event to set a comic scene in ``A Man In
Full,'' his best-selling novel. The traffic on Piedmont, a major
Atlanta thoroughfare, Wolfe wrote, ``came to a complete, utter,
hopeless, bogged-down glue trap halt, both ways, northbound,
southbound, going and coming, across all four lanes.'' As wealthy
whites attending a party at the Piedmont Driving Club watched
incredulously, ``black boys and girls began popping out . . . of
convertibles, muscle cars, Jeeps, Explorers, out of vans, out of
evil-looking little econo-sports coupes, out of pickup trucks,
campers, hatchbacks,'' dancing and singing, ``Ram Yo' Booty!''
</P>
<P>
   To the Atlanta establishment, Freaknik is one big headache,
though few are willing to complain publicly because of the event's
racial identification. When other Southern capitals were engulfed
in civil rights turmoil, Atlanta liked to be called ``the city too
busy to hate.'' Black mayors have governed for more than 20 years,
white business leaders have encouraged racial reconciliation, and
Atlanta is sensitive to racial slights.
</P>
<P>
   But with Freaknik spinning out of control, the city's black
leadership moved to crack down on the crowds in the last few years.
Following the arrest of hundreds of visitors two years ago, Police
Chief Beverly Harvard, a black woman, was critical of the ``lewd''
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the prospect that Freaknik will not happen here this
year, Atlanta police and traffic control authorities are prepared
for another visitation, according to Gold, the mayor's spokesman.
Asked about Campbell's position on Freaknik, Gold said:
``Everyone's welcome. There are no restrictions _ provided they
obey the law.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
