<HEADER>
A7676 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TE     04-06 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE EXCITING LIFE AND TIMES OF RICHARD HARDING DAVIS STILL
ENTERTAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   During a foray to Archer City, the small town in North Texas
that author-bookseller Larry McMurtry is putting on the literary
map of the world, I spent most of an afternoon with Richard Harding
Davis.
</P>
<P>
   The Davis shelf found in one of McMurtry's four Booked Up
buildings showed novels, short-story volumes, plays, reportage,
autobiographical writings, and several biographies of Davis penned
long ago, when or just after he was the most celebrated American
among those with writing professions.
</P>
<P>
   That's right. Richard Harding Davis (1864-1916) was a household
name before the century's turn and until his premature death, which
was the likely issue of excesses.
</P>
<P>
   Davis was the original Arrow collar man. Beheld as the most
handsome and debonair fellow of his time, he took the show away
from old Mark Twain. The Philadelphia-born Davis defected to New
York, becoming a regular in Manhattan's cafe society, and his
romantic odyssey was popular newspaper fodder before there were
movie stars to track.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Harding Davis was the son _ and absolute pride and joy _
of Rebecca Harding Davis, herself a journalist and novelist of
considerable note. Although the son's fame far outstripped the
mother's, Rebecca Davis is today considered a more significant
figure in the pageant of American literature, as both muckraker and
feminist. Her son was a writer for his time but not for all time.
</P>
<P>
   Davis at age 21 began a fabled reportorial career with the
Philadelphia North American and Inquirer and in 1888 joined the
staff of the New York Sun and won instant fame for his ``specials''
_ reportage of sensational events in Gotham, dramatized for effect
with considerable poetic license. At age 25, he was managing editor
of Harper's Weekly; and very soon afterward, he became the first
superstar of a new journalistic breed, the war correspondent.
</P>
<P>
   Like his great contemporaries Stephen Crane and Frank Norris
(and then much more famous than either), Davis covered the
Spanish-American War for newspapers in the United States and
Britain. His saga was the stuff of grand opera: At different times
he also reported the Boer War, the Russo-Japanese War, and the
Greco-Turkish War. In Europe, he covered the early battles of World
War I and died before our country's involvement in that ``war to
end wars.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis belonged to an age when authors wrote ... and wrote and
wrote, and wrote some more. He produced eight novels, a dozen story
collections, and was a successful dramatist with 25 plays performed
in New York. Indeed, Richard Harding Davis is the very translation
of ``sic transit gloria mundi.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Davis still can provide enjoyable light reading. Many of his
stories concern Courtlandt Von Bibber, a New York dandy closely
resembling Davis himself. ``Soldier of Fortune'' (1897), Davis'
best-known novel, reads like a streak. It is set mainly in a
fictional South American country, as is the play ``The Dictator,''
a great success for the young John Barrymore, who in 1915 made it
his silent-movie debut vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   My reading acquaintance with Davis was slight before our
rendezvous in McMurtryland, but long ago I read and enjoyed ``The
Bar Sinister'' (1903), a novel whose autobiographical narrator is a
bull terrier.
</P>
<P>
   In 1955, during the waning glory of MGM, ``The Bar Sinister''
was a delightful movie. Today an enterprising screenwriter could
hardly do better than conceive a film based on the tumultuous life
of Richard Harding Davis.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Swindell is books editor emeritus for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
