r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     04-06 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBC'S AILING THURSDAY LINEUP GETS LIFE SUPPORT FROM `WILL &AMP; GRACE'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They're still wedged in the Nielsen ratings' Top 10, still
sitting pretty in the protected cocoon of a Thursday night
supposedly devoted to sophisticated humor. But the only funny thing
about ``Jesse'' and ``Veronica's Closet'' these days is watching
promos that trumpet the pair as ``Must-See TV.''
</P>
<P>
   There were times when I sat still for both shows, keying in on
every story line and subplot, every character, every joke, trying
to figure out why viewers didn't simply bail. Until it hit me that
they probably do. Nielsen ratings numbers register television sets
tuned in to network channels, but Nielsen has yet to devise a
tracking system for, say, extended potty breaks, phone calls,
nose-hair clippings, dog-walkings, and so on.
</P>
<P>
   And if you look at the ratings, a clear pattern of avoidance
emerges. Look at how many viewers start the night with ``Friends''
and exit when ``Jesse'' emerges. They return for ``Frasier'' and
disappear as ``Veronica's Closet'' appears, then return in bulk for
``ER.'' Thing is, the number staying put is enough to keep eyeballs
away from the programming of rival networks, which continue to send
forth perfectly adequate programs on suicide missions.
</P>
<P>
   It's fair to acknowledge that NBC's blockbuster Thursday has
always had weak links _ remember ``Caroline in the City'' and
``Suddenly Susan?'' But none was as obviously dependent on
coattails as the current bunch. And never before have networks like
the WB and ABC stated publicly that the Thursday-night juggernaut
is vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the network known for sophisticated comedy, from
``The Cosby Show'' to ``Cheers'' and now ``Frasier'' and
``Friends,'' has taken one nasty little creative spill.
</P>
<P>
   At 8:30 p.m. CST on Tuesdays, NBC offers for our midseason
consideration ``Everything Relative,'' yet another formula comedy
delving into the world of nitwit parents. (It's displacing ``Will &AMP;
Grace,'' which moves to, yes, Thursdays.)
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Rahm is Leo, a comedy writer under siege from his neurotic
mother, played by Jill Clayburgh, and his eccentric father, Jeffrey
Tambor. Judging from the opening episode, it's some drop from the
wit and wisdom of ``The Larry Sanders Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Mom and Dad have been divorced for 20 years, but Clayburgh's
Mickey, a clinical therapist who claims to have written a
graduate-school thesis on obsessive relationships, is dangerously
obsessed with her ex-husband. She spends the first part of the
debut episode looking deranged, the other part suicidal. Who knows
what that bulge in her purse might be?
</P>
<P>
   The show's only surprise is that it's produced by Paul Junger
Witt, Tony Thomas, Nina Wass and Mitchell Hurwitz, whose combined
credits include ``The Golden Girls'' and ``John Larroquette Show,''
among others.
</P>
<P>
   NBC would love to see this series work, because that would allow
it to keep rookie success ``Will &AMP; Grace'' in ``Jesse's''
post-''Friends'' spot. Then NBC could ship the Christina Applegate
vehicle to another night or ``into'' the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesse'' has never ventured beyond limiting and lifeless story
lines about a single mother and the Latin lover who pursues her.
``Will &AMP; Grace,'' by comparison, is the network's most successful
newcomer this side of ``Providence.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the series looks and behaves like so many other sitcoms,
the originality at the center of ``W&AMP;G'' was questioned early on.
Its gay/straight subject matter was considered gimmicky, and its
``Friends''-like pacing was seen as a rip-off. Still, there's
something about a funny show that makes you forget about such
pickiness.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder ``W&AMP;G'' now looms as a suitable fit for NBC's
Thursday-night block. Hilarity aside, it idealizes young, white,
single New York urbanites who spend an inordinate amount of time
talking and chatting and pontificating on every pop-cultural moment
imaginable.
</P>
<P>
   ``W&AMP;G'' moves along like a freight train behind schedule,
offering up such lightning-quick dialogue that you miss half of the
show's zippy one-liners and snappy comebacks if you're not careful.
(No potty breaks here.) Eric McCormack, as Will, and Debra Messing,
as Grace, have managed to go through their paces with charm and
great chemistry, and producers Max Mutchnick and David Kohan should
thank the casting gods for scene- stealers (and savers) Sean Hayes
(Jack) and Megan Mullally (Karen).
</P>
<P>
   ``W&AMP;G'' also has proved to be somewhat ingenious in introducing
a gay lead and gay supporting characters. This early in the
post-''Ellen'' universe, you'd have expected a backlash, but the
producers' decision to spoon-feed the audience, virtually taking
sex out the equation, makes Will less threatening and thereby more
acceptable. Some might call this a less-than-truthful, manipulative
maneuver with red-flag mixed messages _ one being that gay men
don't have sex lives.
</P>
<P>
   You be the judge of whether this is progress. But Mutchnick, who
is gay, didn't want to go the beat-them-over-the-head way of Ellen
DeGeneres. Now, a Thursday-night slot might be his big payoff.
</P>
<P>
   With ``Friends'' kicking it up a notch, ``Frasier'' smoothing
out early season mistakes and ``ER'' being less than fabulous but
still better than most, NBC could actually lay a formidable
foundation for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   Now if only it would clean out that ``Veronica's Closet.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-99 1355EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
