<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7680 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     04-06 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 
AND AFTER THAT POSSIBLE GROUND WAR, THEN WHAT? (For use by NYTimes
News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A reader called to take issue with what she interpreted in a
recent column as my endorsement of Sen. John McCain's contention
that U.S. involvement in an all-out ground war will be necessary to
effectively finish what NATO started in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   It certainly was not my intention to make any such endorsement.
In fact, I don't believe that McCain has endorsed a ground war. He
has simply said that the use of ground troops should not be ruled
out as an option _ and that the American people should understand
that their country may already be so deeply involved in Yugoslavia
that a ground war is virtually unavoidable.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has been saying in interviews and newspaper commentary
that U.S. participation in airstrikes against Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic has put the world's lone remaining superpower in
a difficult situation: If the airstrikes do not achieve the
intended results, the United States and the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization might be forced to take the next step _ a ground war _
or risk forfeiting their credibility in future confrontations with
potential enemies.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's point is a valid one _ and it's one that deserves to be
debated as publicly as possible before President Clinton commits
our nation to further military intervention in a part of the world
where war never ends and peace never lasts.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Clinton is far less inclined than true statesmen
such as McCain and ex-Sen. Bob Dole to level with the American
people about the possible perils of meddling in the Balkans.
Clinton has said again and again that there are no plans for a
ground war in Yugoslavia, which might mean that there are no plans
or that there are plans piled on top of plans.
</P>
<P>
   It all depends on Clinton's definition of ``plans.''
</P>
<P>
   Would anyone be shocked or even slightly surprised if it turned
out that Clinton has known from the start that airstrikes wouldn't
get the job done but withheld that information from the public in
the expectation that he could drum up public support for all-out
warfare later on?
</P>
<P>
   What? Bill Clinton mislead the American people? Perish the
thought.
</P>
<P>
   For the sake of the American people, and especially our fighting
men and women in the armed forces, let's hope that the president
actually believes that the airstrikes will work _ and that his
belief is well-founded.
</P>
<P>
   The dual purpose of the bombing is to shut down Milosevic's
campaign of ethnic cleansing against ethnic Albanians in Kosovo and
to force him to allow a NATO peacekeeping force to occupy his
country. The dual result, so far, has been the opposite: Ethnic
cleansing is worse than ever, and Milosevic appears to be no closer
to accepting a peace agreement than he was before the first cruise
missile was fired.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the concern of McCain and others that bombing won't work
and that ground troops will be needed to win the peace against
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   That reader who called wondered if the good guys would be able
to win a ground war, given the deterioration of military
preparedness that has occurred during Clinton's tenure as commander
in chief. It's a legitimate concern, although most of those
military ``consultants'' who work as analysts for the various TV
networks seem to believe that a NATO invasion force would prevail
in decisive fashion.
</P>
<P>
   But ground war or no ground war, the overriding question about
U.S. involvement in Yugoslavia remains the same: If we win, what
will we have won?
</P>
<P>
   The short answer: We will have won the right to occupy a foreign
country whose internal disputes have defied solution for centuries
_ and whose problems, serious though they are, have no impact on
U.S. security.
</P>
<P>
   The even shorter answer: We will have won nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe all-out war is inevitable. Maybe it's what Clinton has
been planning all along. And if it is what he's been planning,
maybe he'll get around to sharing those plans with the American
people one of these days.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, let's hope and pray that the airstrikes succeed. The
quagmire is getting deeper by the hour.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
