<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7687 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     04-06 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMC CORP'S $67 BILLION MARKET VALUE OVERTAKES GILLETTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Massachusetts has a new stock market champ.
</P>
<P>
   EMC Corp., a Hopkinton technology firm, Monday became the
Massachusetts company with the greatest market value, a title held
for the past seven years by Gillette Co. When trading ended at 4
p.m. Monday, the total value of EMC's shares _ what you would have
to pay if you were to buy the entire company _ topped $67 billion,
compared to about $64 billion for Gillette. A year ago Gillette's
market value was more than three times greater than EMC's.
</P>
<P>
   If you invested a dollar in EMC stock at the beginning of this
decade, it would be worth nearly $500 today.
</P>
<P>
   The changing of the guard says something about the two
companies. EMC is hot; Gillette is not. But it speaks more to the
kind of changes sweeping the economy and the stock market. In the
new economy, technology is king. Investors are convinced that
technology is remaking the world and that a handful of electronics
companies will lead the way.
</P>
<P>
   In response, they have bid up the price of technology stocks to
incredible _ some would say ridiculous _ levels. Microsoft's market
value is almost as great today as the entire gross national product
of Canada. ``Anyone who thinks these stocks aren't vulnerable to a
major correction isn't being realistic,'' says Thomas O'Neill,
chief investment officer of Fleet Financial Group.
</P>
<P>
   But even those who are skeptical about today's stock prices are
not skeptical about EMC's prospects. Although it is far from a
household name, on Wall Street the company is mentioned in the same
breath as the technology elite _ Microsoft, America Online, Dell
Computer, Cisco Systems. ``They are about as dominant as anyone in
technology in their space,'' says Rob Joseph, an analyst with State
Street Research in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   EMC's specialty is storage; it makes devices that hold
information. The company's products are often referred to as the
file cabinets of the electronic age. It sounds boring and
unimportant. It isn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people have recognized that storage is as important as
the computer itself,'' says Mark Fredrickson, a spokesman for EMC.
``It may be more important because it is where data lives. And
there is not a company out there that doesn't generate more
information every day.''
</P>
<P>
   EMC provides storage systems to companies like Cisco, Delta
Airlines, and Visa. Its customers also include big Internet players
such as Amazon.com, the electronic bookstore, and Charles Schwab,
the nation's leading discount broker.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet may be a big part of the company's future, but
EMC's rise largely predated the rise of the World Wide Web. Simply
put, the company recognized the importance of storage before the
rest of the world and used that edge to beat the pants off its
competition.
</P>
<P>
   EMC long ago knocked off IBM, the old leader in storage. The
company became the top player in storage for mainframe computers
and then did the same thing in the storage market for smaller
machines. From practically nothing, EMC has built a software
business that will top $500 million in sales this year.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street has noticed. Over the past 10 years, EMC's stock has
done better than all the stocks in the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index
with the exception of Dell Computer. Last year the stock climbed
209 percent. In 1999 the stock has risen another 56 percent. In
1990 you could have bought the whole company for $136 million.
Monday EMC would have cost you $67 billion.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to the stock market, Gillette has not exactly been
a slacker. Since 1981 its stock has risen roughly sixtyfold.
Between 1987 and 1997 Gillette's share price rose an average 33
percent per year.
</P>
<P>
   The stock's rise has created great wealth on Wall Street and
within the ranks of the company's work force. Gillette recently
said that more than 300 of its employees own more than $1 million
worth of Gillette stock. Some of those employees are blue-collar
workers who make less than $50,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   But in the past two years, Gillette has had to contend with the
ups and downs of the world economy. Economic woes in Asia and
Russia have made it more difficult for people to buy Gillette's
razors and batteries.
</P>
<P>
   Just Monday Gillette said its earnings in the first quarter of
1999 would be slightly below Wall Street's expectations, a
development the company blamed on weak sales in Latin America.
``Gillette is fighting a world recession,'' says Ned Riley, chief
investment officer at BankBoston Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette's stock fell Monday and analysts expect more of a
dropoff today. Gillette is still a much larger company than EMC.
Its sales topped $10 billion in 1998; EMC's were slightly less than
$4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   It goes without saying that the stock market is a fickle friend.
Investors assign prices to stocks by peering into crystal balls and
imagining what the future will look like. When unexpected events
occur _ like Monday's announcement by Gillette _ the view of the
future can go from sunny to cloudy very quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout most of the 1980s Digital Equipment Corp. was
Massachusetts' leader in stock market value. In the early 1990s,
the computer company stumbled badly and Gillette moved into the
number one slot. Monday the shaving king passed the crown to the
computer storage giant.
</P>
<P>
   About the only thing you can say with certainty is that someday,
EMC will give way to another challenger.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-99 1356EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990406.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7684 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     04-06 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AND AFTER THAT POSSIBLE GROUND WAR, THEN WHAT?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A reader called to take issue with what she interpreted in a
recent column as my endorsement of Sen. John McCain's contention
that U.S. involvement in an all-out ground war will be necessary to
effectively finish what NATO started in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   It certainly was not my intention to make any such endorsement.
In fact, I don't believe that McCain has endorsed a ground war. He
has simply said that the use of ground troops should not be ruled
out as an option _ and that the American people should understand
that their country may already be so deeply involved in Yugoslavia
that a ground war is virtually unavoidable.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has been saying in interviews and newspaper commentary
that U.S. participation in airstrikes against Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic has put the world's lone remaining superpower in
a difficult situation: If the airstrikes do not achieve the
intended results, the United States and the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization might be forced to take the next step _ a ground war _
or risk forfeiting their credibility in future confrontations with
potential enemies.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's point is a valid one _ and it's one that deserves to be
debated as publicly as possible before President Clinton commits
our nation to further military intervention in a part of the world
where war never ends and peace never lasts.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Clinton is far less inclined than true statesmen
such as McCain and ex-Sen. Bob Dole to level with the American
people about the possible perils of meddling in the Balkans.
Clinton has said again and again that there are no plans for a
ground war in Yugoslavia, which might mean that there are no plans
or that there are plans piled on top of plans.
</P>
<P>
   It all depends on Clinton's definition of ``plans.''
</P>
<P>
   Would anyone be shocked or even slightly surprised if it turned
out that Clinton has known from the start that airstrikes wouldn't
get the job done but withheld that information from the public in
the expectation that he could drum up public support for all-out
warfare later on?
</P>
<P>
   What? Bill Clinton mislead the American people? Perish the
thought.
</P>
<P>
   For the sake of the American people, and especially our fighting
men and women in the armed forces, let's hope that the president
actually believes that the airstrikes will work _ and that his
belief is well-founded.
</P>
<P>
   The dual purpose of the bombing is to shut down Milosevic's
campaign of ethnic cleansing against ethnic Albanians in Kosovo and
to force him to allow a NATO peacekeeping force to occupy his
country. The dual result, so far, has been the opposite: Ethnic
cleansing is worse than ever, and Milosevic appears to be no closer
to accepting a peace agreement than he was before the first cruise
missile was fired.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the concern of McCain and others that bombing won't work
and that ground troops will be needed to win the peace against
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   That reader who called wondered if the good guys would be able
to win a ground war, given the deterioration of military
preparedness that has occurred during Clinton's tenure as commander
in chief. It's a legitimate concern, although most of those
military ``consultants'' who work as analysts for the various TV
networks seem to believe that a NATO invasion force would prevail
in decisive fashion.
</P>
<P>
   But ground war or no ground war, the overriding question about
U.S. involvement in Yugoslavia remains the same: If we win, what
will we have won?
</P>
<P>
   The short answer: We will have won the right to occupy a foreign
country whose internal disputes have defied solution for centuries
_ and whose problems, serious though they are, have no impact on
U.S. security.
</P>
<P>
   The even shorter answer: We will have won nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe all-out war is inevitable. Maybe it's what Clinton has
been planning all along. And if it is what he's been planning,
maybe he'll get around to sharing those plans with the American
people one of these days.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, let's hope and pray that the airstrikes succeed. The
quagmire is getting deeper by the hour.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
