<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNDERGROUND-TANKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY CITES PROBLEMS WITH NEW GAS STATION TANKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAY KAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A multibillion-dollar, decadelong government
campaign to seal underground fuel tanks at gas stations across the
country has sprung a leak.
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline and the possibly cancer-causing fuel additive MTBE
continue to ooze from some tanks and pipes that were repaired or
replaced at the owners' expense to meet a 1998 legal deadline,
according to a yearlong study by the State Water Resources Control
Board in California.
</P>
<P>
   Faulty tank installations, poor maintenance, improper operation,
inferior equipment and upgrades that didn't comply with
requirements are the main causes, the study found.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inspections revealed there was leakage from upgrades,'' said
Allan Patton, manager of the state's underground tank program and
chairman of the study advisory panel. ``Are they all leaking? No.
What we don't know is if there's a widespread problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a complex system, and things can go wrong. It could be a
national problem,'' Patton said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigations at 23 sites in three California counties _ Santa
Clara, El Dorado and Sacramento _ by a team from industry, water
districts and municipalities found problems at 18 stations.
</P>
<P>
   Most commonly, gasoline was dripping from pipe connections
beneath pumps. There were also cases in which gas was escaping from
pipes connected to a turbine pump in the fuel tank, which moves gas
to the gas pump. Or gas was seeping from joints in underground
pipes.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the Environmental Resource Council, a Santa
Rosa-based group of business owners organized to deal with the law,
were dismayed at the results. Members of the council include small
gas stations and contracting, equipment and electrical companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now they tell us that the new systems leak. We're back to
square one. Again, it's the tank owner holding the bag. We're the
ones who have to pay for new upgrades,'' said Kirk Veale, a founder
of the group, who was required to replace the tanks at his former
car dealership in Santa Rosa.
</P>
<P>
   ``The saddest part of the story is that so many people have
already gone out of business. Unlike the big oil companies, the
small owners can't recoup their loss by adding to the price of
their product,'' Veale said.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Sutley, a senior policy adviser for the U.S. Environmental
Protection Agency, said the study raised questions about the
effectiveness of the underground tank regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to understand how this happened, and find common-sense
ways to address the potential for leakage,'' Sutley said. ``Now
we're starting to get some information. We have to figure out what
it means, and what we need to do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   She said there was no suggestion of ``another whole set of
regulations and expenditures at any level of government.''
</P>
<P>
   But in California, a state panel will look at the study and
others to decide whether new regulations are necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before any regulatory improvements are recommended one way or
another, we want a thorough diagnosis of the problem. We don't need
regulatory window- dressing. We need real solutions,'' said David
Fogarty, a spokesman for Western States Petroleum Association, an
oil industry trade group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the problems are with the older systems that don't
comply,'' he said. ``That doesn't mean we don't have to be vigilant
to ensure that underground tanks don't leak.''
</P>
<P>
   Retailers have expressed concern that their costly efforts are
not sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   Skip Amick, operator of Civic Center Shell in San Jose, said
that although Shell paid for tank improvements, closing his station
during installation cost him $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been very expensive for me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that, even after the work, fuel appeared to be
leaking, possibly from piping under the gas pumps.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of MTBE in the ground water measured 280,000 parts
per billion last April, exceeding by 56,000 times a drinking water
warning level proposed by state health officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do everything they (the regulators) tell us to do,'' Amick
said. ``They keep changing all the time, and we're trying to keep
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Late last month, Gov. Gray Davis declared MTBE a ``significant
risk to California's environment'' and ordered the compound removed
from the state's gasoline supply by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since before World War II, fire departments and other agencies
encouraged burial of fuel and chemical tanks to prevent
catastrophic fires.
</P>
<P>
   But in the early 1980s, hydrologists were finding widespread
plumes of solvents and gasoline spoiling wells and other
underground water supplies.
</P>
<P>
   California adopted requirements in 1984 to coat or line tanks
and contain leaks by such means as plastic liners.
</P>
<P>
   The high cost of the regulations drew objections from industry
and small businesses. They battled against environmentalists who
wanted a phase-out of single-wall tanks.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, the federal government passed regulations requiring
double-wall tanks, structures to contain seeps, and monitoring
devices to detect leaks. The government banned single-wall steel
tanks, but to ease the financial burden, grandfathered in those
that were fiberglass or specially coated.
</P>
<P>
   After Dec. 22, 1998, oil companies were prevented from
delivering fuel to stations that did not have a blue-and-white
upgrade placard. Violators faced daily fines of $5,000 per tank.
</P>
<P>
   The failure to prevent leaks has produced widespread
environmental degradation, in some cases spoiled drinking water
supplies.
</P>
<P>
   By last year, the state had identified 32,409 sites of leaking
underground tanks. In 13,278 cases, fuel had reached ground water.
</P>
<P>
   In at least 10,000 California sites, according to a Lawrence
Livermore National Laboratory study, ground water is contaminated
with MTBE, which is added to gas to make engines burn cleaner.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the findings of the state study:
</P>
<P>
   _ Leaks are the result of improper installation, operation or
maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   _ Most leaks are pipe joints under the gas pumps, in fittings
throughout the system and where pipes connect to the fuel tank.
</P>
<P>
   _ There is inadequate enforcement against owners who don't
comply with leak-detection requirements or who fail to follow up on
suspected releases.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tank owners aren't conducting leak-detection tests at all or
frequently enough.
</P>
<P>
   _ There's no standard procedure to test the soundness of
containment structures designed to capture leaks beneath gas pumps
or at connections to the tanks.
</P>
<P>
   _ Older tank systems leak more frequently. They are more likely
to be poorly installed, contain outdated technology or have
corroded pipe connections.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tank owners don't have highly qualified inspectors checking
initial installations or continuing to catch problems.
</P>
<P>
   _ Owners fail to maintain the systems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
