<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Wednesday, April 7,
1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO CRISIS
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MAIN _ WASHINGTON _ More U.S. weapons are on the way to
the Balkans as humanitarian groups struggle to care for the growing
number of ethnic Albanian refugees. Developing. (Deans, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-KLA _ DURRES or TIRANA, Albania _ Ethnic Albanian exiles
here are recruiting fighters for the Kosovo Liberation Army,
preparing a ragtag army to eventually force the Serbs out of what
they consider their homeland. A look at the KLA's recruiting and
training operations. (Roughton, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-GITMO _ MIAMI _ In normal times, the U.S. Navy base at
Guantanamo Bay, Cuba is a sleepy place where 3,500 seamen assist
the Navy with operations across
</P>
<P>
   Latin America. But if the United States decides to airlift
ethnic Albanians there, the base will have to be transformed to a
hodge-podge metropolis of tents and field latrines to serve up to
20,000 desperate refugees. People familiar with the base say the
transformation would be a logistical nightmare, and they question
whether it's a good idea to bring Kosovars used to cold weather to
such a hot spot in the Caribbean that's nearly 5,000 miles from
their homeland. Refugee experts say the Kosovars should be housed
closer to home. (Emling, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   SPENDING _ When Congress set campaign contribution limits in
1975, gasoline sold for $.50 a gallon and a McDonold's hamburger
cost $.20. Gas, burgers and everything else has increased since
then but federal contribution limits have remained frozen at $1,000
_ a third what it would be worth today if adjusted for inflation.
But after 25 years, there are the first glimmers that Congress
might be ready to bump up the limits. While proponents say it will
ease the fundraising burden on candidates, campaign reform
advocates say that it will only further swamp a system that is
awash in too much cash. (Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   LEVITT-FUNDS _WASHINGTON _ SEC to announce new 'tool' to help
investors calculate mutual fund costs. (McNaughton, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   EVERGLADES _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A mere 63 years after
Marjory Stoneman Douglas proclaimed the Everglades' ``11th hour,''
the Army Corps of Engineers will finally end the decline of
Florida's most precious marsh system _ in 2010. That's the promise
of the corps' newest version of its $7.8 billion restoration plan,
which hits the Internet and the libraries on Wednesday. (King, Palm
Beach Post). 20.
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-ANALYSIS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Historical analysis
of hurricane damage in the U.S.: what would happen if the big
storms of the past were to hit in the vastly developed coastline
today? When adjusted for 1995 dollars, the 1926 storm that hit
Miami would have been the costliest to hit Florida: $72 billion.
Andrew's damage in 1992 was $21.6 billion (in 1995 dollars and
considering property values and growth, that cost would have jumped
to $33 billion). The 1928 Lake Okeechobee storm would have cost
nearly $14 billion in 1995 dollars. We'll look at the 10 most
expensive storms to hit South Florida, based on a report presented
to the hurricane conference Thursday. (Kleinberg, Palm Beach Post).
15.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-ELDERLY-WILL _ LANTANA, Fla. _ Before all the trouble began,
Ruth Turgeon was the sort of gentle elderly soul who lives alone,
dotes on her cats, feeds stray animals and sends money to humane
societies. A little forgetful, maybe, but who isn't when they're
well past 80? Neighbors in her little waterfront community watched
out for her, took her meals, ran in to check on her. Then the state
abuse hot line got a call saying Turgeon was being exploited,
something about her giving money to a friend who picked up stray
animals and sent the vet bills to her. A state investigator checked
it out and made some startling discoveries. The frugal,
sweet-natured woman who'd been a secretary for the Postal Service
and a co-founder of the Jeanne Craig Foundation for stray animals
had a fortune of $2.5 million in stocks, bonds and cash _ and no
will. That was the end of Ruth Turgeon's quiet and privacy. For the
past 18 months, she's been enveloped in chaos and anxiety as the
state, the neighbors, three nieces _ and everybody's lawyers _
battled for control of her body, her mind and her money.
(McLachlin, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: A hearing was scheduled for Monday, April 5; updates will
follow.)
</P>
<P>
   BAXTER-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ There's currently some academic debate
about how fast the state's Hispanic population is growing _ with
implications that are not at all academic for the future of Georgia
politics. (Baxter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
