<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-FRAUD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS OVER NET POSES RISK OF FRAUD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GABRIELLE CRIST 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ It might have been too good to be true, but
for at least a dozen folks across the country, it was too good to
pass up.
</P>
<P>
   They are, after all, a little berserk over Beanie Babies. So
when they saw an advertisement for some hard-to-find stuffed
critters on an Internet auction site at low prices, they took a
chance.
</P>
<P>
   Arlene Pilch, a Virginia mother of five, got a cash advance from
her credit card and sent $3,000 to a Fort Worth man who placed the
advertisement. Michigan resident Vicki Geiss sent about $220.
Roberta Wells, who also lives in Virginia, sent about $100.
</P>
<P>
   All paid in cash, but none received anything in return. No
charges have been filed against the seller, and he said he plans to
make good with all his customers.
</P>
<P>
   But the case points out the dangers of doing business on the
Internet. And it's a lesson more people learn every day as they
surf the Net, looking for that really good deal.
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Worth man, who calls himself ``31 and dumb,'' said his
intentions were always good. There was a delay in the delivery of
Beanie Babies to him, he said. Then, a main satellite malfunctioned
and his order didn't transmit, he said. Then, the prices of the
Beanie Babies increased and he didn't have enough money to pay for
them.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, he told some of the buyers that someone had stolen
his supply. That was ``a lie just to buy some time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he said he will do whatever it takes to return their money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably will, more than likely, get a job,'' said the man,
who is not being identified because he has not been charged with a
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Less than confident that they will be repaid, some of the people
who sent the man money have filed a complaint with the Postal
Service, which investigates mail fraud cases. Officials there would
not confirm whether they were conducting an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Complaints to Internet Fraud Watch, a division of the National
Consumer's League, have tripled in the past seven months, and about
half of the reports involved a cash payment, said Cleo Manuel, the
consumer organization's vice president for public affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Web has become a huge yard sale,'' Manuel said. ``More
people are going online, and as more people go online, more people
are going to be victims of fraud.''
</P>
<P>
   Geiss, who figures her $220 is gone for good, said she feels
foolish for her lack of caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I put my faith in the Web site when I shouldn't
have,'' Geiss said.
</P>
<P>
   That's how a lot of people are becoming victims, Manuel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a false sense of trust because technology is viewed as
something pure,'' Manuel said. ``They're not used to being
skeptical online.''
</P>
<P>
   Manuel said online auctions are a great place to wheel and deal
for most people, but they are also a favorite spot for con artists.
Sites such as eBay, Up For Sale and Auction Universe allow sellers
to post items for sale, and consumers place bids on them.
</P>
<P>
   Manuel remembers one woman who purchased a lightweight
wheelchair in an online auction. She got a metal folding chair on
casters, Manuel said.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, Beanie Babies are a popular product, Manuel
said. One woman paid more than $1,000 for Quackers, a yellow duck
that comes in two versions _ with wings or without. The woman
thought she was paying for the one without wings, which is more
expensive.
</P>
<P>
   She received a Quackers that once had wings, but they had been
plucked off.
</P>
<P>
   Auction sites will kick sellers off if it can be determined that
they are misrepresenting their products or not sending the
merchandise. The Fort Worth man said he was kicked off eBay, Beanie
Nation, Auction Universe and Up For Sale.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Kirksey, an inspector for the Southwest Division of the
Postal Service, said complaints concerning Internet mail fraud are
rapidly growing.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, complaints were virtually unheard of. In the past
several months, inspectors have received four complaints that
resulted in investigations, Kirksey said.
</P>
<P>
   As the popularity of the Internet increases, so will the cases,
she said. And new laws are needed to address the problem, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Several laws concerning the Internet have been proposed, but
most do not specifically address Internet fraud. Rep. Robert
Weygand, D-R.I., has introduced a bill that would amend the federal
criminal code to include penalties for Internet telemarketing
fraud.
</P>
<P>
   But that won't help the people who mailed their money to the
Fort Worth man.
</P>
<P>
   Wells said she was suspicious of the deal to begin with, so she
sent less money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of knew what I might have been getting into,'' said the
44-year-old Wells. ``I'm ashamed, but it was greed.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells said she did learn one thing from the ordeal:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a sucker,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the people who sent money said they will continue to
browse for bargains on the Net. They'll just do it a little more
cautiously.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
