<DOCNO> NYT19990406.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 14:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7738 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDECISIVE-WOMAN-LADN     04-06 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDECISIVE-WOMAN-LADN </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(Also ran in ``l'' lifestyle news file).  
By CAROL BIDWELL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Paper or plastic?
</P>
<P>
   Baked potato or french fries?
</P>
<P>
   Liquid detergent or powdered?
</P>
<P>
   Don't ask Mary Lord. These are some of the most perplexing
decisions in her life.
</P>
<P>
   But confessing on the Internet that she was ``decisionally
challenged'' _ to the point where she flipped a coin to decide
whether to get married _ won the Hollywood woman the dubious title
of Least Decisive Person in America.
</P>
<P>
   Lord, a free-lance researcher, can't quite decide how she feels
about the iffy honor, awarded after her 250-word essay was chosen
over 4,000 others in a contest sponsored by Microsoft's MSN
Sidewalk online guide to travel, entertainment, shopping and more.
But she's pleased that it came with a round-trip airline ticket to
anywhere in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The hope of winning a trip, after all, was the reason she
entered.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing the depths a person will sink to for a free plane
ticket,'' Lord said, still surprised she won. ``I don't know why I
entered the contest. It was just a late-night, Internet kind of
thing, a late-night confessional moment. At some point, after
keeping my indecisiveness to myself all these years, it was
satisfying to confess, a cathartic moment.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other end of the contest scale _ the most decisive
person, who won a trip, too _ was Ben Silverman, 23, of Bethesda,
Md., who woke up one morning two years ago and decided to quit both
college and his job. Within 24 hours, he'd started his own record
company (Meddle Records), designed a company logo, found his first
client and hired an accountant.
</P>
<P>
   ``That day taught me the value of making a decision based on
knowledge, experience, personal happiness and the idea that making
tough decisions is what ultimately leads to success,'' Silverman
wrote in his winning essay.
</P>
<P>
   That sort of whirlwind decision-making scares the daylights out
of Lord, who's regularly befuddled when trying to choose from the
10,000 or so items on the shelves in most supermarkets _ and
eternally grateful when a parking lot has only one space left,
making it unnecessary for her to pick a spot.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the day-to-day things that confuse her, or the big
moral questions. For the ordinary stuff, she's got a routine; for
the other, right weighs out over wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm indecisive, not a moron,'' she says sharply.
</P>
<P>
   Where she gets in a quandary is when confronting two things of
equal importance: whether to order prime rib or chicken in a
restaurant, whether to buy a Ford or a Toyota, whether to go to the
movies or rent a video.
</P>
<P>
   At the supermarket, she'll sometimes stand for 15 minutes in the
detergent aisle, comparing labels, or in the deli, trying to choose
from among dozens of cheeses.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many kinds, I can't decide. Sometimes I'll just
grab any old vile thing because somebody is watching. It's
embarrassing.''
</P>
<P>
   Indecisiveness has dogged her all her life, perhaps taught
subtly by her father, who ``had a variety of careers'' because he
couldn't decide what he really wanted to do in life. Her mother was
the decision maker in the family, and both husband and daughter
were relieved to have somebody else take charge.
</P>
<P>
   Lord didn't realize that being wishy-washy could cause problems
until she entered school.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real torture was ... those multiple choice questions,''
she recalled. ``How could you pick just one answer? I liked essay
questions where you could write what you knew.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time she entered college, she began to feel that being a
fence-sitter was perfectly OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I began to be proud that I didn't want to do what
everybody else was doing. I signed up for lots of classes, knowing
that I could drop some later _ and that that gave me longer to
decide which I really wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Lord lives a well-ordered life, working out of a tiny,
tidy office in a book-lined apartment reminiscent of old Hollywood.
A job delving into history suits her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the past because it's already happened,'' she said.
``No decisions to make there.''
</P>
<P>
   Lord can only recall making one impulsive decision in her life _
buying a jar of mushroom tapenade in a supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was disgusting,'' she said. ``This taught me to hesitate.''
</P>
<P>
   And what's so bad about giving choices some extra thought
anyway?
</P>
<P>
   ``In this world, a lot of bad things were done impulsively,''
Lord says. ``One of the biggest pieces of claptrap in our society
is, `He who hesitates is lost.' There ought to be people like me as
buffers. If our president had not been impulsive, you think he'd
have been fooling around with that little cookie? We're not going
to send the world catapulting into disaster. We're not going
anywhere fast.''
</P>
<P>
   But even with careful deliberation _ and an appeal to fate or
luck _ things don't always work out, she's learned.
</P>
<P>
   Chief among those things is her marriage to a New York rare
books dealer she had dated for several years.
</P>
<P>
   He proposed; she waffled.
</P>
<P>
   He proposed again; she hesitated.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, she hauled out her lucky 50-cent piece. She doesn't
know how she chose 30 as the magic number, but after 30 tosses,
``it came out overwhelmingly that I should marry him. I thought,
`Oh, what the hell.'''
</P>
<P>
   They wed. And after 13 years, she's now ``in the middle of the
divorce from hell,'' that propelled her across country so she could
be on her own again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have tossed that coin 31 times,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Lord's got another big decision to make: Where will she go
on the trip she won in the contest?
</P>
<P>
   ``Hawaii,'' she says decisively, then pauses. ``Maybe New York
... or maybe not. Oh, I don't know _ someplace.''
</P>
<P>
   She's got until Dec. 31 to decide. That's National Make Up Your
Mind Day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
