<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7740 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      04-06 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRING ON BALLPLAYER BILLBOARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - As the baseball season begins, Major League officials
are negotiating with the professional players association over the
placement of 1- to 1{-inch advertising patches on uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   It's an absolutely despicable idea. It's disrespectful. It's
disgusting. It's degrading. Not to ballplayers, of course, but to
fans.
</P>
<P>
   There's simply no way guys like me can read a 1-inch patch from
the third tier of Bank One Ballpark. If the league is going to put
ads on uniforms, then it must give us something we can see from the
cheap seats.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than use postage stamp-size patches, baseball teams
should simply expand upon existing uniform signage.
</P>
<P>
   Like the names stitched across the back of each player's
uniform, in big bold easy-to-read letters.
</P>
<P>
   This past off-season, our hometown Arizona Diamondbacks spent
almost $120 million on free-agent players. An astounding $52.4
million of that was part of a four-year deal to sign pitcher Randy
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   You've got to figure it'll take a little extra advertising
revenue to pay for fat contracts like that.
</P>
<P>
   Given that, Arizona's $52 million man should be more than happy
to help raise the dough.
</P>
<P>
   He could do so simply by getting sponsorship from a big-time wax
company and having the back of his jersey changed to Randy Johnson
&AMP; Johnson. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Signage opportunities &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And that's just the first step.
</P>
<P>
   Each player provides advertisers with unique opportunities for
signage.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks' all-star third baseman could team up with a
yuppie California catalog company to become Matt Williams-Sonoma.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe a well-known paint manufacturer might like the sound of
Matt Sherwin-Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Some players have almost limitless po tential. Arizona's hot
young first baseman, who already looks like a walking billboard for
the American ideal, likely would land several major accounts.
</P>
<P>
   One day, he might wear a uniform with Travis Lee Jeans stitched
across the shoulders. The next, it could read Travis Lee Optical.
The next, Travis Lee Myles Transmissions.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the Diamondbacks' highly paid second baseman certainly
would become the darling of local automobile dealerships,
alternately identified on his back as Jay Bell Ford, Jay Bell Road
Toyota, Jay Bell Dodge, and so on.
</P>
<P>
   The team's new lead-off hitter, acquired from the Pittsburgh
Pirates, would be Tony Womack Truck.
</P>
<P>
   Or Tony WomackDonald's. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Some need flexibility &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some of the lesser known ballplayers may be required to
demonstrate a little flexibility in the use of their names.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Omar Daal might have to settle for a shirt reading Omar
Dolly Madison Cakes.
</P>
<P>
   Or Omar Dollar Rent-A-Car.
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder David Dellucci may be stuck with David Del-Lou Grubb
Chevrolet. Or David Del-Lucent Technologies. Or David Del-Luby's
Cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   There's no more shame in than that than in demanding truckloads
of cash to play a kids game.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, would it kill a pitcher making $32 million to
alter his name just a little from Todd Stottlemyre to Todd
Oscar-Meyer?
</P>
<P>
   Nor would the team's manager be exempt. I'm thinking, here, of
Starbucks Showalter.
</P>
<P>
   Clever ad salesmen could even collect double duty by simply
expanding the facility's name to Bank One Ballpark Franks.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the Diamondbacks owner would be willing to set the
example, identifying himself on a uniform as Ben &AMP; Jerry Colangelo.
</P>
<P>
   Or, maybe, Jerry Colangel-Lotions &AMP; Potions.
</P>
<P>
   Near as I can tell, the only drawback to baseball's new
advertising scheme is that, in the end, owners will find a way NOT
to use new profits to create savings for customers. Which means
we're not likely in the near future to spot a jersey reading Jerry
Colangel-Low Cost Ticket Prices. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-99 1432EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
