<DOCNO> NYT19990406.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 14:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7755 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WILSON-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      04-06 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILSON-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASTER COMPUTERS WON'T MAKE US SMARTER, MORE CREATIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use b N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE WILSON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Bill Gates is smarter than I am. He's smarter than you
are. He ranks as the richest man in the world with a fortune in the
neighborhood of $80 billion. He didn't make it on looks.
</P>
<P>
   So when Gates writes about how to get ahead _ as he has in a new
book, ``Business (at) the Speed of Thought'' _ I'll bite.
</P>
<P>
   Velocity, he says, has become the key to success in the digital
age. Companies whose computers move information the fastest and
most efficiently will thrive; those that still communicate on paper
will perish.
</P>
<P>
   Information of all kinds should be passed through e-mail to a
wide range of people within an organization, he says. Sharing
knowledge broadly breeds a more collaborative workplace, connects
more minds and allows quicker decisionmaking.
</P>
<P>
   Most of this seems sensible, and Gates explains how digital
technology has advantaged the likes of Boeing, Coca-Cola, General
Motors and McDonald's.
</P>
<P>
   But Gates' boundless passion for faster communication annoys me.
His obsession with electronic speed comes off as self-serving as
well as overstated. Who do you suppose will sell most of the
software necessary to turbo-charge your company's information
system?
</P>
<P>
   While I was reading Gates' book, I recalled a favorite passage
from Henry David Thoreau, written 150 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Walden,'' he observed:
</P>
<P>
   ``Our inventions are wont to be pretty toys, which distract our
attention from serious things. They are but improved means to an
unimproved end. . . . We are in great haste to construct a magnetic
telegraph from Maine to Texas; but Maine and Texas, it may be, have
nothing important to communicate.''
</P>
<P>
   Thoreau was wrong about the telegraph _ he saw technology moving
people farther away from nature, which he regarded as divine _ but
his larger point is well-taken. Communicating more quickly can make
people feel more connected, but it does nothing to improve the
substance or value of the information being shared.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Cantoni, a Scottsdale, Ariz., management consultant, knows
Thoreau was on to something. He conducted a study last year at a
multibillion-dollar, high-tech company and found that the average
worker wasted 43 minutes a day reading and writing unnecessary
e-mail. Based on an average salary of $53,000, he estimated the
annual cost of lost productivity at $8.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Employees griped about workloads, he said, but bragged about
their e-mail volume, as if it were a sign of their importance. Very
few made a connection between spending time on trivial e-mail and
finding it hard to get their work done. Some workers came to
believe that exchanging non-essential e-mail _ commonly to impress
others in the organization _ is vital work.
</P>
<P>
   Computers enable us to share more information with more people
with greater speed. But the more we think of ourselves as
``information processors,'' the more we may come to regard the mere
act of communicating rapidly to be as important as the content of
the messages.
</P>
<P>
   As computer networks rise in priority, so does the risk that we
will become ``tools of our tools'' _ another memorable phrase from
Thoreau.
</P>
<P>
   I don't mean to sound anti-computer.
</P>
<P>
   I can write, retrieve information, and correspond more quickly
with one. I admire its efficiency. Still, I'm aware that faster
isn't smarter or more creative or more insightful or more decent.
The computer gives me no better reasoning or evaluation skills. Nor
does it make me more human. Since it has the effect of reducing
face-to-face and voice-to-voice interactions, it leaves me a little
more detached from other people.
</P>
<P>
   While faster access to information can do many good things _ and
may, for a time, enable Company A to outsell Company B _ it can
never have the same impact as sound, non-computerized judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Gates says business success today is all about speed, and I say
Gates knows better. Moving information more rapidly can make a big
difference, but seldom as much of one as sharper thinking. He
understands that. There just isn't as much money in saying it. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Steve Wilson can be reached at steve.wilson(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
