<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 14:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7761 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUFUSWAINWRIGHT-HNS &LR;      04-06 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUFUSWAINWRIGHT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE VEIN OF NILSSON, RUFUS WAINWRIGHT'S SONGS PROPELLED BY
OFFBEAT MELODIES &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By RICK MITCHELL 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   Many male songwriters of his generation might dream of becoming
the next Beck or R. Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   Rufus Wainwright has no such grand ambition. He'd settle for
being known merely as ... the next George Gershwin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just between you and me,'' he said, tongue only half in cheek.
``Well, whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   Wainwright's self-titled 1998 debut album has established him
as, if not the next Gershwin, at least the next Harry Nilsson. The
album's orchestrated, piano-based parlor songs seem like an odd fit
in the modern pop landscape of Eminem, the Offspring and 'N Sync.
</P>
<P>
   But Wainwright's offbeat melodies and oblique lyrics give his
music an unmistakably contemporary edge, while his elastic singing
integrates influences from opera and cabaret into the inventive
pop-rock vocal tradition of the Beatles and Brian Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   The critics at Rolling Stone magazine liked the album well
enough to proclaim Wainwright the best new artist of 1998, and
Wainwright's name turned up on many other year-end best lists.
</P>
<P>
   Wainwright, 24, is the child of two acclaimed
singer-songwriters. His father is Loudon Wainwright III, who
decided that after three generations of Loudons, it was time for a
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it,'' says Rufus of his unfashionable first name.
</P>
<P>
   His mother is Kate McGarrigle, of Canada's McGarrigle Sisters.
His parents divorced when he was very young, and Rufus was raised
in Montreal with his mother and his sister Martha, who sings
harmonies on the album.
</P>
<P>
   He developed a fondness for the stage, performing family variety
shows in his home, and then touring with his aunt, mother and
sister as the McGarrigle Sisters and Family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely got a rush from it and developed an addiction to
it from a very young age,'' he says. ``I really couldn't keep
myself away from being onstage.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was about 14, Wainwright discovered opera. While
attending a private boarding school in upstate New York, he
envisioned himself as ``the little Mozart guy, playing the piano
and singing.''
</P>
<P>
   He says he often incorporates tricks learned from studying
classical music into his pop song structures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things like having introductions to songs, certain
modulations, and also things like counter-motion. But in the end I
try to judge it like some 15-year-old skater kid who knows nothing
about that stuff. It's great to use it, but it has to be kind of
hidden in order for it to be accessible.''
</P>
<P>
   Wainwright's immersion into opera provided him with an escape
from the personal drama he experienced growing up gay. Several of
the songs on his debut album were inspired by a pair of tragic
romances _ one with a straight man who did not respond to his
affection in kind, and one with a young heroin addict who later
killed himself.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the album's release, some folks at his record label
suggested that his press kit delete any references to his sexual
orientation. Wainwright wasn't having any of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't advertise it, but I don't hide it,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The same record label advisers _ who no longer work there, by
the way _ warned him that he'd never appeal to more than a gay-male
cult following. Wainwright has indeed built a cult following, but
it includes a sizable number of straight females, particularly
teen-age girls.
</P>
<P>
   Wainwright figures these fans must know he's gay, but it doesn't
matter to them. They can relate to what he's singing about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's really a lot of kinship between gay men and
young girls,'' he says. ``It's a male person who's not really
threatening to them, who's approachable and can teach them
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Wainwright spent two years working on his debut album. He
credits Dreamworks' executive producer Lenny Waronker with giving
him the time and space he needed to develop as an artist. He worked
with such proven co-producers as Jon Brion (Fiona Apple, Aimee
Mann), Pierre Marchand (Sarah McLachlan) and Van Dyke Parks (Brian
Wilson and the Beach Boys).
</P>
<P>
   Parks, also responsible for the album's audacious string
arrangements, was the first to point out the similarity of
Wainwright's style to that of Nilsson. While the latter is best
remembered for his Midnight Cowboy version of Fred Neil's folk song
Everybody's Talkin', he also wrote such charmingly eccentric early
'70s pop songs as Jump Into the Fire and Coconut.
</P>
<P>
   One singer-songwriter Wainwright is rarely compared to is his
father. But Rufus says both his parents have had an enormous
influence on his artistic outlook.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father is really unappreciated in many ways. He sort of has
this jokey side, but he's a really serious songwriter. Some of his
material is really potent and poetic, and his stage persona is one
of the tightest acts you'll ever see. I learned a tremendous amount
from that.
</P>
<P>
   ``And my mother is one of the greatest women songwriters of our
times. I hold both my parents in the highest regard, and feel like
I'll never quite be as good as they are in certain ways. There will
always be the Loudon thing and the Kate thing, but there's also the
Rufus thing.''
</P>
<P>
   And how would he prefer to see ``the Rufus thing'' described?
</P>
<P>
   ``Say that I'm one of the most beautiful people of the century,
the Jackie Kennedy of gay men. Something completely moronic like
that. I've said everything else.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
