<HEADER>
A7764 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDENING-COL-HNS &LR;      04-06 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENING-COL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRING MEANS IT'S CALADIUM TIME 
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By KATHY HUBER 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   Is it time to plant caladiums? Do I need to dig them up at the
end of the season? &QL; 
_ M.B.H., Houston &QL; 
 &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A: &UR;  &LR; The holiday calendar can be an easy bulb-planting reminder.
Around Easter each year, it's time to purchase caladium tubers.
Soon after, when soil and air temperatures are in the 70-degree
range, we plant. Tubers planted in too cold a soil are prone to
rot.
</P>
<P>
   While some caladium varieties, such as the strap-leaf types, are
more sun-tolerant, we usually associate these members of the aroid
family with shade and use them to brighten and color the shadier
areas of the garden with their fancy foliage. The heart-shaped, or
fancy-leaf, caladiums mature to 20 inches in height, and those
planted in masses make a good show in the landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Look for firm tubers as you shop for caladiums, or buy plants
when available if you want a more immediate impact.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare the soil well before you plant. Caladiums thrive in a
well-draining, organically enriched, slightly acidic soil. Add a
little sharp sand to improve drainage if necessary. Mix a little
bone meal or superphosphate in the soil around each tuber. Use
superphosphate if squirrels have a tendency to dig up your efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Plant caladium tubers about a foot apart and 1{ times as deep as
the thickness of the tuber. Pick the flowers as they appear. It's
colorful foliage you're after. Keep the soil moist through the
summer. Watch for snails and slugs during rainy periods.
</P>
<P>
   Caladiums make decorative container subjects on a porch or
patio.
</P>
<P>
   Energetic gardeners remove the tubers in October when the tubers
stop producing new foliage. They dust the tubers with sulfur to
discourage fungal problems and store them in a flat of dry material
in a well-ventilated, dry area where temperatures are in the 55- to
65-degree range. Some gardeners simply hang the tubers in a mesh
bag in the garage. Watch for any decay.
</P>
<P>
   Most caladiums return the following year, although my experience
is that they are smaller. Fertilization helps. I'll admit I don't
lift the tubers; I just add new ones as I want them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Q: As in many subdivisions, our builder planted two trees in
the front yard, a pine and an oak. Each tree is approximately 15 to
20 feet tall and has the same northwest sun exposure. I put a
6-inch raised bed under each tree. Whatever I plant under the pine
does well, but I can't get anything to grow in the bed under the
oak. Everything begins to look either stunted or weak. We've tried
changing the pH, (currently it is neutral), increasing the
fertilizer and planting different flowers. Do you have any
suggestions? &QL; 
_ M.Y., Houston &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A: Except for the `Katie' ruellia, the flowers you listed do
best with sun. The `Katie' works in sun or shade. I'm not sure how
much light your flowers are receiving, but the canopy of your live
oak could be blocking the light required for bushier, stronger
plants that bloom well. Does the pine cast shade, too, or block
sidelight from hitting the area beneath the oak? Also, the roots of
an oak are fairly close to the soil's surface, and they could be
robbing your plants of moisture. Check the soil to determine if it
is too dry.
</P>
<P>
   If you feel inadequate sunlight is a problem, go with more
shade-tolerant plants. Summer annuals that take shade include
impatiens and torenia, or wishbone flower, which grows about a foot
tall and often is covered in cupped blooms that may be white-edged
in blue or rose or blue-edged in a darker blue. Peacock gingers are
only inches tall, with beautifully marked foliage. These perennials
go completely dormant in winter, but return in mid to late spring.
They produce flat, iridescent lavender blooms all summer. Persian
shield is another foliage plant for bright shade. Prune to promote
bushiness. You could also brighten the bed with caladiums. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Azaleas: Don't wait too long after azaleas have finished
flowering to prune to shape and fertilize. The shrubs will set buds
for next spring during the summer months.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Miracle of the monarch: H.P. of Sugar Land recommends butterfly
weed as an Easter present. She enjoys watching the life cycle of
the monarch butterfly at home by growing butterfly weed (Asclespia)
in her garden. The plant is the host for the butterfly. Mother
monarchs lay their eggs on the butterfly weed. These hatch into
caterpillars that eat the leaves, but the foliage grows back in
short order. The caterpillars then spin their cocoons, and before
long sleepy butterflies awaken and the life cycle begins again. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, garden editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston, Texas 77210. The bulk of mail
prevents individual replies to all unpublished letters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXXXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
