<HEADER>
A7831 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$A     04-06 1356
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAYING SAFE IN THE WILD 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., April 11) 
(jt) 
 By BETSY WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When injuries happen on trips in the wild, or even on casual
outdoor vacations, a case can sometimes be made for blaming the
victim. Failing to wear a helmet on a bike, skipping vaccinations
before going camping, throwing stones at a bear, jumping off a boat
in the middle of a lake: Such actions, or inactions, are
invitations to danger.
</P>
<P>
   While eco-tourism and adventure travel in remote parts of the
world have grown exponentially in the last decade, safety is also a
serious concern on familiar ground.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. National Parks and recreation areas offer a case in
point. Deaths from injuries in the areas supervised by the National
Park Service have not grown faster than the use of the parks, but
the major causes are shifting, and park experts are concerned that
the use of alcohol may be creating a rise in preventable deaths. In
last year's 146 fatal injuries, the major category was
water-related deaths, and personal watercraft played a big role
here. Nine years ago, auto crashes ranked first. Elaine Sevy, a
spokeswoman for the National Park Service, said that the service is
increasingly concerned about people who arrive in the parks and
consume alcohol before engaging in a potentially hazardous
activity.
</P>
<P>
   The Lake Mead National Recreation Area on the Colorado River in
Nevada and Arizona recorded 25 accidental deaths last year.
Twenty-two were water-related: 9 were injuries involving boats, 3
were drownings associated with boats and 10 were other drownings.
In 1997, there were only 12 accidental deaths here.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the nine ``boating'' fatalities involved personal
watercraft like Jet Skis. According to Karen Whitney, a spokeswoman
for the recreation area, managed by the National Park Service, one
person ran into the shoreline at night while under the influence of
alcohol; another ran over and killed a swimmer; one was riding a
watercraft that stalled and his son, behind him on another one ,
struck the father, killing him, and the last left his watercraft to
go swimming and was presumed drowned.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, the National Park Service reported 6,638 search and
rescue efforts in 1998. Of the 146 deaths, in all areas under the
jurisdiction of the service, The water-related total was 56 _ of
which the Lake Mead area, with its 9 million to 10 million visitors
a year, had the biggest portion. Of the total in the parks, 20
deaths involved boats, including personal watercraft, and 36 were
drownings. Motor vehicle fatalities numbered 39. The next major
category was falls, mostly while climbing, which caused 29 deaths.
</P>
<P>
   These numbers are low when measured against the 287 million
people who visited the places managed by the Park Service. But Dick
Powell, risk manager for public safety in the Park Service, says
the boom in personal watercraft is causing a significant increase
in water-related accidents and that curbs on such craft were being
discussed. Wanting `the Real Thing'
</P>
<P>
   At Lake Mead, Ms. Whitney said, the 1998 total of 25 deaths
represented a particularly bad year; in 1997 only 12 were recorded.
``It jumps up every other year,'' she said. ``People read the news
of the deaths and are careful for a year. Then we get a new group
of people who don't know, and the total rises again.''
</P>
<P>
   Dangerous situations have an allure for some people. Dr. William
Davis, the former head of safety for the Park Service, said: ``When
you challenge nature, you are a risk seeker. You want that edge,
that happiness. You want those endorphins to run around.''
</P>
<P>
   At Grand Canyon National Park, fatalities can be attributed to
many causes, including suicide. According to Sandra H. Perl from
the superintendent's office, in 1998, there were 346 search and
rescue efforts and seven fatalities: three falls from the rim, two
suicides, one probable drowning and one death from an unknown
cause. Fatalities over the last eight years do not vary much,
except for 1995, when 22 died, 8 in a plane crash.
</P>
<P>
   However, Ms. Perl said that after 1996, when a record number of
search and rescue efforts were required _ 482 _ the park began
preventive efforts, putting rangers on the trail to counsel hikers
about where they might enjoy going and what they were able to
manage.
</P>
<P>
   All U.S. National Parks make efforts to enhance the safety of
visitors engaging in outdoor activities such as rafting, hiking and
climbing, biking or camping out. All outfitters with concessions to
operate in or into the parks must have minimum liability insurance
of $500,000 per occurrence, according to Judy Jennings of the
concessions department. They are also required to give safety
lectures.
</P>
<P>
   An ``acknowledgment of risk'' form is also given to the visitor
to sign, she said. It usually notes the inherent risks in the
activity _ that boats can turn over, people can fall out, hikers
can stumble, wild animals can attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wake-up call, from mosquitos to white-water hazards,''
Ms. Jennings said. In no way, however, does the form absolve the
operators of liability, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the parks, this may not be true. I have seen and signed
forms that said I held the operator free of liability, even in the
event of negligence. Except in Alaska, these waivers do not usually
stand up in court against evidence of gross negligence, but they do
warn the consumer to possible dangers in the same way that those
used in the park do.
</P>
<P>
   If the operator gives a skimpy safety lecture and the equipment
looks insecure, ask to see the releases before you get under way,
or before you are in a remote area where access is difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Medical Concerns
</P>
<P>
   Many dangers of disease can be avoided or reduced through proper
medical preparation. Leaving aside shots needed before going
abroad, which depend on the destination, there are inoculations
that families should have before any trip, including one to a
national park, or for children, a camp vacation. Dr. Elaine Jong,
founder and co-director of the Travel and Tropical Medicine Service
at the University of Washington in Seattle, says that parents of
children going off to camp should be particularly vigilant about
shots. Children will be in close contact with many others and will
be eating food prepared by others in places where emergency help
may not be around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   Jong said that tetanus and diphtheria shots should be routine
for families involved in outdoor activities. Adults should get
boosters every 10 years. Hepatitis A vaccine is particularly
important for children, Jong said, and may be free in many states
to children under 18.
</P>
<P>
   The measles, mumps and rubella vaccine is usually given to very
young children, but the measles shot should be boosted, she said. A
booster should be given once in adult life to people born in 1957
or later. ``We like to see the second dose completed before primary
school,'' Jong said, ``and even if the children are going camping
some place no more exotic than Fort Lauderdale.''
</P>
<P>
   Chickenpox is so contagious that unless people know they are
immune through having had the disease, the course of two shots
should be given. Healthy people over 13 who have not been immunized
or had chickenpox should consider this immunization because the
disease is becoming more common in this age group.
</P>
<P>
   Jong recommends the new Lyme disease vaccine for travelers over
15 going hiking or camping in areas of frequent tranmission. This
is an expensive shot; at the Traveler's Medical Service in New York
City, it costs $78. Though young children are principal victims,
tests on children under 15 are not complete.
</P>
<P>
   Jong stressed modifying behavior rather than relying totally on
a vaccine, particularly one, like the Lyme vaccine, that is not
believed to confer 100 percent immunity. ``It is important to wear
appropriate clothing,'' she said, ``and to soak clothing in the
insecticide permethrin.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a behavioral aspect to travel health, beyond the
vaccines,'' Jong said.
</P>
<P>
   That goes double for safety.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
