<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7836 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEVITT-FUNDS07-COX     04-06 0343
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVITT-FUNDS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SEC OFFERS HELP IN COMPARING EFFECT OF MUTUAL FUND FEES
 &HT;    By DAVID McNAUGHTON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Comparing the fees charged by different mutual
funds became easier Tuesday when the Securities and Exchange
Commission added a cost calculator to its Internet site.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC's new tool (http://www.sec.gov/mfcc/mfcc-int.htm),
allows investors to type in information on a fund's upfront sales
charges _ if any_ deferred sales charges _ if any _ and annual
operating expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The investor has to select an investment period, an investment
amount, and estimate an annual return. Average returns over the
past 30 years for stocks, money market funds and bonds are shown,
but investors can pick any number they want.
</P>
<P>
   The cost calculator then displays the total fees paid over the
selected time frame, how much potential earnings are lost because
of money paid in fees, and the dollar value of the investment at
the end of the period.
</P>
<P>
   As an example, the SEC used two real, but unspecified funds that
are comparable, but carry different fees. Based on an investment of
$10,000 and assuming a 12 percent annual return, one would be worth
$50,771.10 after 15 years, the other $45,732.82. The cost of fees
and forgone earnings would be $3,964.56 in the first case, and
$9,002.84 in the second.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like unit pricing in supermarkets, which lets consumers view
the price per ounce of products that come in different sizes, the
cost calculator will allow investors to understand the real cost of
owning a particular fund, without being the slightest bit confused
by the fund's packaging,'' said SEC Chairman Arthur Levitt.
</P>
<P>
   Another benefit of the calculator, said SEC Chief Economist Erik
Sirri (CQ), is that it will encourage investors to read a fund's
information-packed prospectus. That's because the fee information
investors need to plug into the cost calculator is in the
prospectus.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
