<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BATLAWSUIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAT ACCIDENT PROMPTS LAWSUIT AGAINST METS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RON NISSIMOV 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ As the baseball season gets under way, Sterling
Lapinski of Houston has no desire to hear the crack of the bat.
</P>
<P>
   Not after what happened almost two years ago, when a bat cracked
his head open at a game at Atlanta's Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm probably never going to go to another baseball game,'' he
said. ``Even the prospect of being hit by a ball worries me. You're
not really safe anywhere in the stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the mishap, Lapinski, a 29-year-old energy
commodities broker, is taking a few swings at America's favorite
pastime.
</P>
<P>
   In an action that could change the way fans watch a game,
Lapinski is suing the New York Mets, who he said showed a ``pattern
of negligence'' for allowing catcher Todd Pratt to continue batting
in a July 11, 1997, game even though he lost his grip on his bat
three times that night.
</P>
<P>
   The second time it happened, the bat crashed into Lapinski's
face in the fifth inning after Pratt swung and missed on a pitch by
Atlanta's Tom Glavine. Pratt also inadvertently flung bats into the
stands in the third and eighth innings after missing pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Lapinski, who is seeking unspecified damages, needed surgery to
mend his fractured skull, broken nose and crushed nasal cavity.
Doctors told him he would have been dead if he had not turned his
head around to allow his forehead to bear the brunt of the force.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew angrier and angrier the more I thought about it,''
Lapinski said about his decision to sue. ``Especially since they
never called to say, `We're sorry.'''
</P>
<P>
   Lapinski, who lived in Atlanta at the time, said he grew
especially irate after seeing Pratt joke about the incident on
television, saying he missed the pitches but ``took out a few
fans.''
</P>
<P>
   An Atlanta federal judge dismissed the suit, but Lapinski is
appealing to the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, also in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Lapinski's lawyer, Bill deGolian of Atlanta, says U.S. District
Judge Jack Camp mistakenly threw out the suit because he failed to
distinguish between flying bats and flying balls.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, courts have ruled that spectators at baseball
games assume the risk of being hit by foul balls and home runs, and
cannot seek damages for injuries inflicted by a ball. But deGolian
says that in the only other lawsuit filed in the country by a
spectator hit by a bat, a 1938 California court ruling held that
bats are not a risk spectators can expect.
</P>
<P>
   California and Pennsylvania appellate courts have cited that
ruling in declaring spectators have a right to sue for some types
of accidents at sporting events, deGolian said.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta federal judge followed Georgia law in reaching his
decision, deGolian said, but judges frequently rely on rulings from
other jurisdictions if there is no precedent in their own.
</P>
<P>
   A 1949 Georgia appellate ruling dismissed a lawsuit filed by a
woman hit by a foul ball. The decision said the judges had reviewed
a number of cases filed by people injured by ``foul balls, flying
bats and other like missiles,'' but the final ruling only said fans
should presume they could be hit by ``wild balls.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Marshall, a winner of the Cy Young Award for pitching in
1974 who later earned a doctorate in exercise physiology, filed an
affidavit on Lapinski's behalf, saying there is ``clear evidence''
Pratt handled his bat ``in a manner inconsistent with what is
taught and expected of a professional baseball player.''
</P>
<P>
   Lapinski's attorney said his client has taken heat from baseball
purists who say he is trying to change the look of the game. But he
said his client is not asking _ at this point _ for nets or other
barriers to be erected at ball parks, although he added that might
become an issue if he sues Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney for the Mets could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Lapinski bears no readily visible traces of the accident, other
than a couple of small bumps on his forehead. But his hair conceals
an ear-to-ear scar where his skin was peeled back to repair his
forehead and nasal cavity.
</P>
<P>
   Lapinski said his insurance paid for the surgery and related
costs.
</P>
<P>
   He said some friends who were with him at the game coaxed a fan
who caught the bat to give it to Lapinski. He still has it at his
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep it around for self-defense,'' he joked. ``I know how
much damage it can cause.''
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
