<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUAIL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OH, TO NIBBLE ON QUAIL, MINUS THE BONES 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
(Editors: recipes at end of article) 
 (bl)  
 By ELAINE LOUIE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For tiny birds, quail have always had a big problem. Their
little bones can make anyone tackling them with knife and fork feel
like Gulliver in Lilliput _ and wonder whether the bother is worth
the flavor.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few years, though, partly boned quail have started
turning up at butcher shops and even in supermarkets. Without the
breastbones and backbones, the sweetly flavored, tender fowl are as
fast and easy to cook _ and eat _ as chicken cutlets. But the
subtly gamy flavor and succulence make the meat far more
satisfying, tempting enough, in fact, to warrant picking up the
little legs in public and nibbling them clean.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eight years ago,'' said Anstice Carroll, a Manhattan caterer,
``if you asked people what they thought of a quail, they would say:
`Oh, it's too little. Oh, it's not enough meat.''' Today, though,
she has no trouble selling them as a first course.
</P>
<P>
   Manchester Farms in Dalzell, S.C., which processes 7 million
quail a year, sells 5 million partly boned, up from 2.5 million
five years ago. Bill Odom, the owner, says the demand has come from
chefs. They save time in the kitchen by buying partly boned birds,
which are easier to sell on a menu.
</P>
<P>
   D'Artagnan in Newark, N.J., sold 20,000 of these partly boned
birds in February, said co-owner Ariane Daguin, who called deboning
a meticulous craft. Of Manchester Farms, she said: ``I've seen his
best guys do it in six seconds. I need at least five minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Once it's partly boned, a quail generally weighs all of three to
four ounces, so it cooks in six minutes or less, and it can be
eaten with a fork or fingers. The Ottomanelli meat markets in
Manhattan now sell 75 percent of their quail partly boned, said
Jerry Ottomanelli, an owner. (No wonder.)
</P>
<P>
   Convenience has a cost. At Ottomanelli, frozen quail, sold four
to a package, is $11 for partly boned, compared with $7 whole
(fresh quail, sold singly and whole only, are $2.50 each). At
D'Artagnan, which sells fresh quail only, a package of four is
$21.20 for partly boned, compared with $13 whole.
</P>
<P>
   To those whose families hunt, the quail is a toothsome childhood
memory and a taste that lingers. Caroline Cox, an actress and
ecumenical minister in Blauvelt, N.Y., remembers her grandfather
hunting quail outside Kansas City, Kan. ``My grandmother would
clean them, pluck them, whack them in half _ and just fry them up
in a little oil and herbs,'' she said. She herself fries quail,
seasoned with salt, pepper, ground rosemary and garlic, for three
minutes a side.
</P>
<P>
   Food historian Waverley Root described the flavor of quail as
hovering between the blandness of barnyard fowl and the wildness of
high-flying birds like mallards and geese. Unlike chickens, quail
can fly, and a little exercise makes them taste meatier. But they
never fly far. As Root wrote in ``Food'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, 1980),
when faced with danger, quail would rather run than fly, ``a
suicidal habit they share with pheasants.''
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Williams, the executive chef at the Berkeley Bar &AMP;
Grill, to open in May in midtown Manhattan, grew up in Houston and
started hunting the bobwhite quail on the family ranch at age 7 or
8. For breakfast, her father would grill the birds, seasoned with
only salt and pepper, and serve them with cornmeal mush (what she
now offers as polenta).
</P>
<P>
   Today, Ms. Williams uses a Tuscan technique traditionally
applied to chicken. She wraps two bricks in triple layers of
aluminum foil and stacks them on a single quail while pan-frying it
for two minutes a side. The skin turns crisp almost immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Batali, the chef and a co-owner of Babbo, grew up near
Yakima, Wash., where his family hunted deer, moose, elk, pheasant
and quail. But he said he ``never shot a thing _ I didn't have it
in me.'' At Babbo, he marinates quail, and then grills it.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Cost, a partner in Big Bowl, a group of Chinese
restaurants in Chicago and Minneapolis, has an Asian variation of
cooking called red roasting, which is usually applied to duck or
squab. He rubs the quail in soy sauce, marinates it with a toasted
blend of salt, Sichuan peppercorns, cinnamon (cassia), star anise
and cloves, and dries them at room temperature for an hour or two.
``The cassia and the star anise were used for curing meat centuries
ago,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cost then deep-fries the quail for about three minutes and
serves them with the extra seasoned salt ground and on the side for
dipping. Cut into quarters, they couldn't be more approachable.
</P>
<P>
   CHINESE-STYLE QUAIL WITH SEASONED SALT
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Bruce Cost
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1{ hours
</P>
<P>
   8 partly boned quail
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Sichuan peppercorns
</P>
<P>
   1 star anise
</P>
<P>
   1 small fragment cinnamon stick (about 1/3 inch)
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons dark Chinese soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1\ teaspoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   Peanut oil for frying
</P>
<P>
   Fresh coriander sprigs for garnish.
</P>
<P>
   1. Check quail for any stray bone fragments or feathers. If
there are V-shaped grilling pins protruding (these shape the partly
boned birds), leave them in place. Rinse, and pat dry with paper
towels.
</P>
<P>
   2. In small skillet or saute pan, combine salt, peppercorns,
star anise and cinnamon. Place over high heat, and stir or shake
until peppercorns begin to smoke. Set aside, and allow to cool.
</P>
<P>
   3. Place soy sauce in mixing bowl, add quail, and turn until
they are lightly coated. Sprinkle a little of the salt mixture
(avoid the whole spices) inside the quail, and somewhat liberally
outside. Put quail on a rack to dry at room temperature for 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   4. While quail are drying, remove whole spices (peppercorns,
star anise, cinnamon) from the salt, and grind them in spice
grinder to a coarse powder. Add all of the remaining salt to the
powder, and continue to process until finely ground. Transfer
mixture to small serving bowl. Add sugar, and mix well. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   5. In large, wide saucepan over medium-high heat, add peanut oil
to a depth of at least 2 inches, and heat to about 375 degrees. Add
quail, in batches if necessary, and saute until lightly golden,
about 3 minutes. Remove, and drain on paper towels.
</P>
<P>
   6. To serve, remove grilling pins. Use large chef's knife or
cleaver to cut each bird in half lengthwise and then diagonally
under each thigh. The meat should be slightly pink. Arrange on
large platter, and garnish with coriander sprigs. Pass the ground
seasoned salt separately for dipping.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   GRILLED QUAIL  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Mario Batali &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 minutes, plus 2 to 24 hours for marinating
</P>
<P>
   8 partly boned quail
</P>
<P>
   \ cup balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons honey
</P>
<P>
   { cup loosely packed thyme sprigs
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon freshly ground black pepper.
</P>
<P>
   1. Check quail for any stray bone fragments or feathers. If
there are V-shaped grilling pins protruding (these shape the partly
boned birds), leave them in place. Rinse, and pat dry with paper
towels.
</P>
<P>
   2. In large mixing bowl, combine vinegar, olive oil, honey,
thyme and black pepper. Add quail, and toss gently to coat. Cover,
and set aside in a cool place for 2 hours, or refrigerate
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   3. Preheat grill or broiler. Remove quail from marinade, and
place near hottest part of grill or broiler. Cook until exteriors
are browned and meat is just pink when sliced at the leg bones,
about 3 to 5 minutes a side. Remove grilling pins, and serve
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
