<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7854 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT &LR;      04-06 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RHUBARB COBBLER 
</HEADLINE>
  This is the second of eight columns by Claudia Fleming, the pastry
chef at Gramercy Tavern in Manhattan. Her collaborator on these
columns is Melissa Clark. 
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I love the complex taste of rhubarb. Its mix of sweet and sour
reminds me of the harshness and warmth of spring itself. Using it
in a cobbler seems perfect; it's like a hint of the brilliance of
the coming season cloaked in a wintery sort of dessert.
</P>
<P>
   In my cobbler, tender cream biscuits rest on top of the pieces
of rhubarb, and the dish is baked until they melt into a bubbling
pale red compote and the biscuits turn golden brown.
</P>
<P>
   To add another sort of contrast, I garnish the steaming cobbler
with something cool. At the restaurant, I make goat's milk yogurt
sorbet scented with rose water; at home, you can get a similar
effect for much less effort with a cool rose clabbered cream.
Either way, the rose accents a touch of rose water that scents the
rhubarb.
</P>
<P>
   The combination was inspired by a pot of rhubarb-rose jam that a
waiter brought back from London. I ate it by the spoonful, straight
from the jar. The rose stirred memories of the crumbling stone
walls I saw in England, which were covered with brave pink flowers
and tiny brown shoots.
</P>
<P>
   To me, rose adds a little bit of romance wherever I use it. Now,
I can't think of rhubarb without thinking of reaching for the rose
water. To best distribute the rose water _ and the vanilla bean
that I also use in this dish _ I like to first rub them on the
palms of my hands, then massage them into the rhubarb pieces. On
days when I'm overwhelmed, it's a very calming, sensual way to
spend a few minutes.
</P>
<P>
   RHUBARB COBBLER WITH ROSE CLABBERED CREAM &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour 20 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the rhubarb &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds rhubarb, trimmed and cut into {-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   2{ tablespoons cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   1 2-inch piece of vanilla bean, split lengthwise
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon rose water
</P>
<P>
   For the dough  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   12/3 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   3{ tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   1{ tablespoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   [ teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons cold unsalted butter, cut into {-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup plus 1 tablespoon heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon turbinado (raw) sugar.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 375 degrees. In a large bowl, toss together
the rhubarb, sugar and cornstarch. Scrape the seeds from one side
of the vanilla bean (reserve other side for another use). Sprinkle
rose water on your hands and smear the vanilla seeds into one palm.
Rub your hands together to distribute seeds. Gently rub the rhubarb
with your hands to coat the pieces with vanilla and rose water. (Or
in a small bowl, stir together the rose water and vanilla seeds,
and toss with rhubarb). Let the rhubarb macerate for 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Meanwhile, prepare cobbler dough. In the bowl of a food
processor or an electric mixer fitted with the paddle attachment,
combine the flour, sugar, baking powder and salt. Pulse or mix to
combine. Add the butter, and pulse or mix until the flour resembles
coarse meal. Add the 2/3 cup of the cream, and mix or pulse until
dough starts to come together, scraping down the bowl and dough
paddle when necessary.
</P>
<P>
   3. Turn the dough onto a lightly floured surface and gently pat
it together, incorporating any stray crumbs. Using a small ice
cream scoop or a large spoon, form the dough into 2-inch balls,
then flatten them slightly into biscuit shapes.
</P>
<P>
   4. Put rhubarb in a shallow 2{-quart casserole in an even layer.
Arrange biscuits on top, leaving about an inch in between them.
Brush biscuits with remaining tablespoon of cream, and sprinkle
with turbinado sugar. Bake cobbler until rhubarb is bubbling, and
biscuits are golden brown, about 40 to 45 minutes. Serve warm, with
rose clabbered cream.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   ROSE CLABBERED CREAM  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 5 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 cup clabbered cream
</P>
<P>
   \ cup rose jelly.
</P>
<P>
   Place clabbered cream in an electric mixer set on medium-high,
and beat until it thickens somewhat. Add jelly, and continue to
beat until stiff peaks form. Use immediately or chill.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 1{ cups.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
