<HEADLINE>
OUT OF THIS NETTLE, PLUCK FLAVOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (editors: recipe at end of article) 
 (bl)  
 By RICHARD W. LANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nettle soup, a dish from my childhood, is a ritual of spring and
early summer that I have steeped my own offspring in _ over their
original objection that ``no one else eats this stuff!''
</P>
<P>
   The soup is usually preceded by my lecture on how in the old
days, most people who starved to death did so in the spring. Spring
was deceptively deadly, bursting out into bloom and new growth,
while everyone's food stores had been devoured in winter, and
nothing remained.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritious nettles, cooked like spinach, did the trick. People
ate nettle soup and nettle pie. My uncle even made nettle beer.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, I always find myself discoursing to an empty kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   So this year, even I am surprised that stinging nettles have
gone almost mainstream. Everyone else is eating these weeds.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, At EQ in Greenwich Village, Dennis Foy serves
braised nettles with sauteed turbot. David Waltuck at Chanterelle
in Tribeca fills ravioli with nettles, while Mario Batali at Babbo
in the Village teams nettle tagliatelle with asparagus.
</P>
<P>
   The nettles, with an almost peppery taste like a cross between
artichokes and Jerusalem artichokes, are shipped in from the
Pacific Northwest at this time of year and are also available in
specialty food stores.
</P>
<P>
   But how they are sold is certainly telling: Gourmet Garage, for
example, has a large sign in the produce department warning of the
plants' propensity to sting and directing customers to the deli
department, where nettles are sold only by request from under the
counter, in the manner of questionable magazines.
</P>
<P>
   At one time, nettles' painful sting was put to medicinal use.
The word urtication, for the nettle genus of Urtica, historically
meant the flogging of a paralyzed limb with nettles to stimulate
it.
</P>
<P>
   Pam Brundage, a herbalist in Hampton, Conn., said that arthritic
joints were at one time rubbed with nettles, which injected formic
acid, histamine and other chemicals into them.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting acute pain became a counterirritant, overriding
the chronic pain of the arthritis, sometimes for hours or even
days.
</P>
<P>
   Cooking, fortunately, removes the sting from the plants. But
they should still be handled with care: wear gloves or at least
sheath your hands in plastic bags while trimming the tough stems.
</P>
<P>
   The end of April through early June is the time to harvest
nettles if you're daring enough to forage for them. The leaves must
be young and tender, or they will taste gritty when cooked.
</P>
<P>
   Freshly picked, they're full of vitamins A and C, not to mention
enough iron to build a battleship.
</P>
<P>
   Having a preference for soil enriched by horse manure, nettles
were once common along roadsides, but they can be found in almost
any sunny area that has been frequented by livestock over the
years.
</P>
<P>
   The stinging nettle is a perennial with a strong underground
root system. And once it is established, it will sprout spring
after spring in the same spot, just like mushrooms.
</P>
<P>
   If you're going to gather your own nettles, look for young
plants that have not yet flowered. The flowers are almost dustlike
and droop from the joints, where leaves and stems meet.
</P>
<P>
   Pick only the tender top half of plants that are less than a
foot and a half tall.
</P>
<P>
   Nettle shoots can simply be broken off, but it is best to cut
them with garden shears. If you pull and break, quite often the
young plants will come up, roots and all, scattering dirt that
clings irresistibly to the small hairy leaves, which makes them
difficult to wash.
</P>
<P>
   A plain brown paper grocery bag will make a good harvesting bin.
Pack it loosely about two-thirds full with nettle plants, and you
will have enough leaves after discarding the stems to make soup for
four.
</P>
<P>
   NETTLE SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Time: { hour
</P>
<P>
   2 cups beef stock
</P>
<P>
   8 cups lightly packed young nettle leaves, including the upper 6
inches of stems, rinsed well
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   Finely ground white pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 hard-cooked eggs, for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Freshly snipped chives, for garnish.
</P>
<P>
   1. Combine broth and 2 cups water in a large pot, and bring to a
boil. Add nettles, reduce heat, and simmer covered 3 to 4 minutes.
Puree cooked greens and liquid in a blender in two or three
batches, being extra careful because the liquid will be very hot.
Return mixture to pot, and set over low heat.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a separate small pan over very low heat, melt butter. Add
flour, whisking until smooth and thickened. Whisk into the puree,
and continue cooking until thick and creamy. Add white pepper to
taste.
</P>
<P>
   3. Slice the hard-boiled eggs crosswise. Ladle the hot soup into
bowls. Place half an egg's worth of slices in the center of each
bowl, and garnish with chives.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   TURBOT WITH BRAISED NETTLES
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Dennis Foy of EQ
</P>
<P>
   Time: 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Zest of a quarter of a lime, in strips
</P>
<P>
   { pound nettles, picked over and washed
</P>
<P>
   5 teaspoons best-quality butter
</P>
<P>
   1 small clove garlic, peeled and sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 medium shallots, peeled and sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 cup best-quality chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   Salt and ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil for sauteing
</P>
<P>
   4 6-ounce fillets of turbot (sole or flounder may be
substituted).
</P>
<P>
   1. Bring a large pot of water to a rolling boil. Add lime zest,
and blanch 30 seconds. Remove with slotted spoon. Slice into very
thin julienne, then mince. Set aside. Add nettles to pot, and cook
until they are just tender but still bright green, about 2 minutes.
Drain well in a colander, then transfer to a bowl filled with ice
water. Drain again. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. Heat 1 teaspoon butter in a large saute pan over medium heat.
Add garlic and shallots, and sweat, covered, until they are
translucent. Add nettles, chicken stock and lime zest. Season with
salt and pepper. Stir to combine. Simmer 1 minute uncovered. Remove
from heat, and keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   3. Heat just enough olive oil to coat the bottom of a large
skillet over medium-high heat. Season turbot with salt and pepper
to taste. Lay turbot into skillet, and saute about 1 to 2 minutes
on each side, until done to taste. Swirl in remaining butter.
</P>
<P>
   4. Divide nettles among 4 serving plates. Lay turbot on top, and
spoon butter over. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
