<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEAK, TWICE ON THE FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (editors: recipe at end of article) 
 (bl)  
 By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cooking a steak simply, and to perfection, is easy _ as long as
you have a grill. Cooking a steak in the broiler or oven usually
means sacrificing a good crust, and using the stovetop can set off
the smoke detector.
</P>
<P>
   It's simple enough to get a crust on a steak before smoke fills
the house, but unless you like raw steak, this is not the ideal
solution. If you sear the steak quickly, though, then remove it
from the pan before building a quick sauce, you can finish cooking
it in that sauce. The trick is to heat the skillet _ a cast-iron
one is best, but anything heavy, whether stainless steel or
nonstick, will work _ until it begins to smoke. Then quickly brown
the steak on both sides, remove the meat and turn off the heat so
that the pan cools down before you add the ingredients for the
sauce.
</P>
<P>
   This procedure reduces smoke while increasing flavor and
juiciness. It is such a good technique, with so many options, that
you may forget the grill entirely.
</P>
<P>
   Butter is not vital to the sauce, but a small amount, maybe a
little more than a teaspoon a person, adds not only creaminess but
rich flavor. And in this particular dish, that flavor combines with
soy sauce to produce an unusual, countertraditional marriage that
is, in its odd way, decidedly American.
</P>
<P>
   But the technique is not dependent on butter, ginger or soy.
Each of these ingredients can be swapped or varied until the dish
you create has nothing in common with the original recipe except
the steak and the procedure used to cook it.
</P>
<P>
   It is best to use fairly thin steaks here. Judging the doneness
of thicker ones can often be tricky, and the sauce is so nominal
that it inevitably evaporates before the meat is cooked through.
(If the liquid evaporates before the steak is done, just add a
couple of tablespoons or so of water to the skillet.)
</P>
<P>
   The ideal purchase for four people is four small, boneless
steaks, cut from the top blade, sirloin or rib-eye. But two larger
steaks will work nearly as well, as long as they're thin.
</P>
<P>
   STEAK WITH GINGER BUTTER SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 to 1{ pounds boneless top blade, sirloin or rib-eye, cut into
2 or 4 steaks } inch thick or less
</P>
<P>
   1{ tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced ginger
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons soy sauce.
</P>
<P>
   1. Heat a large, heavy skillet over medium-high heat until it
begins to smoke. Add the steaks, and cook until nicely browned, 1
or 2 minutes. Turn, and brown the second side, another minute or
two. Remove the skillet from the heat and the steaks to a plate.
</P>
<P>
   2. When the skillet has cooled enough so that no smoke is
rising, return it to medium heat. Add butter, and when it melts,
add ginger. About 30 seconds later, add soy sauce and stir to
blend. Return steaks to the skillet, along with any accumulated
juices. Turn heat to medium, and cook the steaks a total of 4
minutes, turning 3 or 4 times. (If pan juices dry out, add a couple
of tablespoons of water.) At this point, they will be medium-rare;
cook a little longer if you like, and serve, with pan juices
spooned over.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Variations on a Steak Theme
</P>
<P>
   By changing the ingredients in the sauce, the flavor of the
steak can be varied in any number of ways. Substitute extra virgin
olive oil for the butter, garlic for the ginger, lemon juice for
the soy, and it's a whole new dish. Or stay with the butter, but
use garlic or shallots and a few leaves of tarragon instead of
ginger, and vinegar in place of the soy.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few other variations.
</P>
<P>
   For the ginger: Substitute any minced member of the onion
family, lemongrass or anchovies. Finely chopped mushrooms,
especially reconstituted porcini, are also good.
</P>
<P>
   For the butter: You can omit this entirely, or substitute any
oil. Olive and peanut are the most distinctive.
</P>
<P>
   For the soy: Red wine, lemon juice, lime juice, vinegar or nam
pla (fish sauce) are possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Add minced herbs, at about the same time you return the meat to
the skillet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
