<HEADLINE>
HEARING FROM CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``I would far rather be standing here answering
these (tough) questions...than I would be standing here having you
ask me why we are permitting a wholesale ethnic slaughter and
ethnic cleansing and the creation of hundreds of thousands of
refugees and not lifting a finger to do anything about it,''
President Clinton said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Well put.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the administration's clumsy handling of the Kosovo
crisis and the uncertainties surrounding NATO's military response,
Clinton is belatedly demonstrating the moral leadership we have
every right to expect of our presidents.
</P>
<P>
   Don't laugh.
</P>
<P>
   The words ``moral leadership'' are not usually associated with
the president. He lost his way with Monica Lewinsky when it came to
his own personal morality.
</P>
<P>
   But public policy is quite another matter. Great civilizations
confront questions of war or peace that call not only for a sense
of strategic interests but a national conscience committed to
battle outrageous crimes against humanity _ such as the massive
rape, pillage and murder in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   A president who turned his back on the hounded, starving Kosovo
refugees would not be worthy of holding his job. Now that would
REALLY be grounds for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   All those who think Clinton has already shown he is not worthy
of the presidency will never approve of military intervention in
Kosovo because they do not trust his motives. But voters who can
see beyond Clinton the man to the larger humanitarian issues
involved will understand that being the world's greatest superpower
carries responsibilities as well as rewards.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton is considering abandoning his resistance to using
U.S. and other NATO members' ground troops to clear out the Serbian
butchers, he will have to shape public opinion in support of such a
dangerous move. In fact, he has already begun an education campaign
leading that way with repeated speeches and television appearances.
It seems to be having some success.
</P>
<P>
   A new Washington Post-ABC News poll taken after the weekend's
horrifying television images of the refugees' plight indicates a
growing public consensus behind risking U.S. lives for the Kosovar
victims. The poll shows 55 percent of those surveyed in favor of
troops as well as 68 percent behind continuing the airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate political question for Clinton, however, is what
Congress may do when members return next week from their two-week
Easter vacation. Both houses are likely to debate resolutions to
either signal their support for continuing airstrikes and potential
future ground warfare or deny funding for such purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Presidents never like to bother with winning over all those
inflated egos and uninformed minds in Congress. It takes valuable
time and they can't control the outcome. Besides, presidents
consider Congress to be needlessly interfering by butting into
foreign policy decisions.
</P>
<P>
   But involving Congress directly can in the long run be
politically useful. It tends to neutralize the opposition.
Legendary Oklahoma Sen. Bob Kerr once explained succinctly the way
it works: ``I'm against any deal I'm not in on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After Iraq's Saddam Hussein invaded Kuwait, President George
Bush tried to block the Senate from debating and voting on his
plans to wage war against Iraq to force a retreat. Despite strong
opposition and heated argument, the Senate approved the invasion
and Bush could proceed without fear of having the legislative rug
abruptly pulled out from under him at home.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is not going to be thrilled with a congressional orgy of
complaints about his handling of the Kosovo problem either. The
situation has drastically changed since March, when both houses
narrowly approved the use of a U.S. peacekeeping force in Kosovo if
a treaty would be signed with the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   To judge by scattered comments from their vacation abodes,
however, congressional Republicans are deeply divided over the
Balkan crisis. Those who are unhappy with the prospect of sending
troops have thus far had no good alternatives to offer. The
Democrats are also divided, but a majority seems to be willing to
support the president's policy, whatever it may turn out to be.
</P>
<P>
   A congressional debate will be healthy and cannot be avoided in
any case. It will offer the president a golden opportunity to
address the concerns only now surfacing. And if he can't answer
those tough questions, it is better to find out sooner rather than
later.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
