<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., May 11)  
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   O'Keeffe Still Lifes At Phillips Collection
</P>
<P>
   From April 16 through July 18, the Phillips Collection in
Washington will be full of petunias, autumn leaves, green apples,
shells, crosses, doors, bones _ all the subjects of artworks in
``Georgia O'Keeffe: The Poetry of Things.'' The exhibition, which
includes 69 paintings and works on paper dating from 1908 to 1963,
focuses solely on her iconic still life paintings.
</P>
<P>
   O'Keeffe's still lifes were radical works. Instead of portraying
everyday objects in their familiar domestic surroundings, O'Keeffe
defied traditional notions of setting, space, scale, perspective
and time. She painted close-ups of her subjects, placing them in
indefinite, infinite space.
</P>
<P>
   ``Details are confusing,'' O'Keeffe wrote in 1922. ``It is only
by selection, by elimination, by emphasis that we get at the real
meaning of things.'' Her depictions of a single object,
face-to-face with the viewer, opened many eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Among the highlights of the exhibit, which is drawn from 50
private and public collections around the United States, are
``Black and Purple Petunias,'' ``Pelvis with Pedernal'' and ``Green
Apple on Black Plate.'' To give the works context, the exhibition
includes photomurals of the places where she lived and worked,
several objects similar to the ones O'Keeffe painted and books from
her library.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets, which are dated and timed, cost $12.50, including the
audio guide, and are available through Ticketmaster at (800)
551-7328.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillips Collection, 1600 21st St., N.W., is open Tuesday
through Sunday. It is closed Mondays and will also be be closed on
July 4. Information: (202) 387-2152.
</P>
<P>
   ``Georgia O'Keeffe: The Poetry of Things'' will be on view at
the Georgia O'Keeffe Museum in Sante Fe, Aug. 7 through Oct. 17;
the Dallas Museum of Art, Nov. 7 through Jan. 30, 2000, and the
California Palace of the Legion of Honor in San Francisco, Feb. 19
through May 14, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Sound and Light At a London Theater
</P>
<P>
   The 16th-century Rose Theater _ the first Elizabethan theater on
London's Bankside, now an archeological project _ will be the site
of a new sound and light show, narrated by the actor Ian McKellen.
The 20-minute exhibition, which focuses on the history of the
theater, will open on Wednesday for a run of about two years, to
raise public awareness and funds. A re-creation of the Rose was
recently featured in the movie ``Shakespeare in Love.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Shakespeare's first plays were performed at the Rose,
built in 1587, including ``Titus Andronicus'' and ``Henry VI, Part
I.'' Christopher Marlowe's ``Tamburlaine the Great,'' ``Dr.
Faustus'' and &QC; ``The Jew of Malta'' were also staged at the Rose.
</P>
<P>
   The remains of the theater were discovered by the Museum of
London in January 1989 during an exploratory dig on the site of a
proposed office building on the south side of the Thames River at
Southwark Bridge. The developers altered their designs so that the
remains would be accessible.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the discovery, a campaign to save the Rose was
launched by British actors, including the late Laurence Olivier and
Peggy Ashcroft, as well as Judi Dench and Ian McKellen. English
Heritage, a government conservation body, is overseeing the
protection of the site.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, about two-thirds of the Rose has been excavated
and is being preserved beneath a layer of sand and a crust of
concrete, with a pool of water on top. Eventually, the Rose Theater
Trust hopes to finish the excavation.
</P>
<P>
   During the show, the pool will serve as a sort of screen on
which images of the theater in its heyday will be projected, using
a range of technologies employed by the theater designer William
Dudley. Viewers will watch the spectacle while standing in a
gallery overlooking the water.
</P>
<P>
   The Rose Theater exhibition, 56 Park Street in London, will be
open daily; &QC; admission $4.95, at $1.65 to the British pound.
</P>
<P>
   Five Airlines Join In a New Alliance
</P>
<P>
   Smoother transfers and enhanced frequent-flier partnerships are
the main goals of Oneworld, an alliance among five international
airlines.
</P>
<P>
   The Oneworld alliance recently became operative among American
Airlines, British Airways, Canadian Airlines, Cathay Pacific
Airways and Qantas Airways. Iberia and Finnair expect to introduce
Oneworld services later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Routes and schedules of member airlines have been designed to
complement one another. Oneworld is not a code-sharing alliance,
although some members do have a code-sharing relationship.
Personnel at transfer and customer-service desks marked with the
Oneworld logo, a blue circle, can help passengers from any of the
alliance airlines. In particular, connections between Oneworld
airlines are intended to become easier.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Participants in a frequent-flier program of any member airline
can earn miles or redeem awards on any of the others (with one
exception: Participants in American's AAdvantage plan and British
Airways' Executive Club cannot earn and redeem miles on each
other's trans-Atlantic routes).
</P>
<P>
   Because airlines use different names for various membership
tiers in their frequent flier programs, alliance members will use
emerald, sapphire and ruby to designate advanced plan levels.
Frequent-flier plan identification cards have been reissued with
the new logos to help members receive the appropriate privileges
regardless of which airline they fly.
</P>
<P>
   Access to airport lounges determined by frequent-flier level or
class of service is reciprocal across all member airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Information: oneworldalliance.com, or through American Airlines,
(800) 433-7300.
</P>
<P>
   Charleston Arts
</P>
<P>
   Charleston, S.C., has been making news in the performing arts
since it staged America's first opera in 1735, and this spring, the
300-year-old city will welcome dancers, musicians and actors and
their audiences for the 23d Spoleto Festival U.S.A.
</P>
<P>
   This spring's opera lineup includes a rare presentation of
Giacomo Puccini's trip-tych, ``Il Trittico,'' in its entirety
(which includes ``Il Tabarro,'' the redemptive ``Suor Angelica''
and ``Gianni Schicchi,'' the amusing misadventures of the
quintessential con man), and the American premiere of ``Die
Burgschaft,'' Kurt Weill's dark fable about immorality in the
mythical land of Urb.
</P>
<P>
   The Spoleto Festival Orchestra will perform Stravinsky's
``Firebird,'' Charles Ives's ``Unanswered Question,'' Gabrieli-
Maderna's ``Canzone in Tre Cori'' and Witold Lutoslawski's
``Concerto for Orchestra'' at the Gaillard Municipal Auditorium.
There will also be a joint performance of Maurice Durufle's
``Requiem'' and Haydn's ``Lord Nelson Mass'' by &QL; 
the Spoleto Festival Orchestra and the Westminster Choir,
accompanied by the Charleston Symphony Orchestra Chorus.
</P>
<P>
   Other events include performances of the theatrical drama
``Mamba's Daughters'' by DuBose and Dorothy Heyward; ``Ricky Jay
and His 52 Assistants,'' directed by David Mamet; Kwaidan, a
retelling of three Japanese ghost tales, directed by Ping Chong;
two mixed-media presentations of ``Moby Dick'' by the performance
artist Laurie Anderson, and an evening of jazz with the saxophonist
Sonny Rollins.
</P>
<P>
   Dance programs will feature the Miami City Ballet; the flamenco
star Antonio Canales and his ensemble; works by the choreographer
Ronald Kevin Brown, and the Brazilian company Quasar Companhia de
Danca.
</P>
<P>
   The festival finale, including performances of Ives, Gershwin
and Copland works by the Spoleto Festival Orchestra, will be at
Middleton Place, an 18th-century plantation on the Ashley River.
</P>
<P>
   The Spoleto Festival U.S.A. runs from May 28 through June 13.
Information: (843) 722-2764. Tickets: (843) 723-0402. On the
Internet: www.spoletousa.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
