<HEADLINE>
SOME TAX ADVICE FROM THE IRS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOHN HIELSCHER   
 Sarasota, Fla., Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most people would rather work overtime on weekends or give
speeches in public than confront the annual task of doing their
federal income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   But taxes are inevitable, as the saying goes, and April 15 is
fast approaching.
</P>
<P>
   If you're one of the millions who simply can't complete your tax
forms by the deadline _ or you can't afford to pay your tax
liability right away _ here's some advice from the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   For an extension, you must file Form 4868 by April 15. That
one-page form asks taxpayers to estimate what they owe and to send
along the payment.
</P>
<P>
   Filing the form will save you money. If you fail to file, the
IRS will assess 5 percent interest on what you owe, plus additional
penalties. By filing the form, even without a payment, the interest
will be 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The extension gives taxpayers another four months, until Aug.
15, to file their complete tax returns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest penalty is failure to file,'' said Bob Firman,
communications specialist with the IRS South Florida District.
``That's why it's important to at least get this extension form in
by April 15.''
</P>
<P>
   Some 7.4 million taxpayers, or 6 percent of the 123.3 million
filers last year, sought extensions. This year, the IRS estimates
that 7.9 million out of 126 million taxpayers, or 6.3 percent, will
ask for more time.
</P>
<P>
   The percentage of late filers has steadily increased since 1993,
when the IRS softened its rules on extensions. Previously,
taxpayers had to send along their projected tax payments or their
extension requests were automatically rejected. Now, the payment is
not mandatory.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have figured out their taxes but can't afford to pay
should file Form 9465 with their regular return. That is an
installment agreement request the IRS will review and respond to
within 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   It will allow the taxpayer to make monthly payments on the taxes
owed; in most cases, the tab must be paid off within one year.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS suggests that those who owe taxes should review their
weekly withholdings, a W-4 form with employers, and increase it to
cover their tax liability. Taxpayers also have the option of making
quarterly payments during the tax year.
</P>
<P>
   As of March 19, some 57.28 million taxpayers had filed their
individual income tax returns. The average refund was $1,609, up
$212 from last year.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS Web site (www.irs.ustreas.gov) is proving a popular
source of information. The agency counted 531.3 million hits at the
site between Jan. 1 and March 21, surpassing the 444 million hits
during the entire '98 tax season.
</P>
<P>
   The site offers hundreds of tax forms, publications and other
information that can be downloaded _ more than 24 million were
accessed in January and February.
</P>
<P>
   Taxpayers are also taking advantage of electronic filing in
record numbers. Computer e-filing by tax preparers or from home
computers is 22 percent ahead of last year.
</P>
<P>
   Refunds are processed in about 21 days through electronic
filings, compared to as long as six weeks or more for paper
filings, Firman said.
</P>
<P>
   Taxpaying remains an onerous task for many Americans. A recent
survey by Lutheran Brotherhood, which asked people to rate how they
liked or disliked several activities, found that only washing
windows ranked below doing their taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The survey respondents said they'd rather go to work on
weekends, pay bills and balance their checkbooks or clean their
basements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Income taxes aren't a job you can put off,'' said Rick
Edinger, an assistant vice president with the Minneapolis-based
insurance provider. ``The pressure to make the tax deadline
probably contributes to why tax preparation is one of the least
favorite activities.''
</P>
<P>
   But despite dreading the chore, most Americans don't
procrastinate. In the survey, 64 percent said they start preparing
their taxes in January or February, 18 percent begin in March and
only 7 percent wait until April.
</P>
<P>
   People do tend to file later. While 49 percent mail their
returns in the first two months of the year, 21 percent file in
March and 23 percent file in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who mail their taxes at the last minute probably have
completed their tax forms, but are waiting to mail them because
they owe money,'' Edinger said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's actually smart financial planning to owe a reasonable
amount of money on April 15 _ rather than get a refund _ because
the money can earn interest until it's due,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota, Fla., Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
