<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-BITS&AMP;BYTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOST COOKBOOKS OF THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By S.A. BELZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   An American living in Japan was looking for a copy of the 1946
``Woman's Home Companion Cook Book,'' which his mother cooked from
when he was a child. He sent an e-mail to Around the Kitchen, an
Internet cookbook store in Connecticut run by Louise Pennisi
(www.aroundthekitchen.com). She found him a copy. He sent another
e-mail, asking for a copy to send his sister in Illinois as a
surprise, so that they could cook the same dishes. Ms. Pennisi
described the ending, by e-mail: ``He later wrote, telling us he
could hardly understand her through her tears when she phoned him
to thank him.''
</P>
<P>
   This small tale illustrates the emotional hold that food and
cookbooks can have, but also the emergence of the Internet as the
largest book market the world has known. Ms. Pennisi's is only one
of a half-dozen Net shops specializing in out-of-print cookbooks.
</P>
<P>
   Computers, far from killing off books, may actually be reviving
them. It isn't even necessary to go trekking electronically from
shop to shop on line. Sites that are search engines allow users to
comparison-shop among thousands of bookstores in minutes. The big
three are Advanced Book Exchange in Victoria, British Columbia
(www.abebooks.com), with 4,700 dealers and 11 million books;
www.bibliofind.com in Cambridge, Mass., with about 4,000 dealers
and 9 million books, and Alibris (www2.alibris.com) in the San
Francisco area, with 800 booksellers and more than 4 million books.
There is also a search engine of search engines,
www.bookfinder.com, run by students at the University of California
at Berkeley. It includes Advanced, Alibris, Bibliocity, Amazon.com
(handy for knowing if a book can be bought new) and Powell's Books
in Portland, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   As Bibliofind.com discusses, these are the places
Barnesandnoble.com and Amazon.com shop for out-of-print books (at
markups to the customer of up to 50 percent).
</P>
<P>
   You can type in as little as an author's last name or a word or
two from a book title. Type in ``Great Chefs of France,'' and the
Net will scoop up, besides that 1978 book, ``The Master Chefs of
France Recipe Book'' and ``Favorite Recipes of the Great Women
Chefs of France.'' So be sure you're ordering the book you want. A
search for that book turned up eight copies _ one in Britain, one
in Australia _ from under $10 to $40.
</P>
<P>
   Search results give author, title, publisher, date,
illustrations, bookseller, price and condition. (``Vg/vg'' means a
book in very good condition in a very good dust jacket.) Ordering
can be done by credit card on a secure server, by e-mail or phone.
</P>
<P>
   Among other Web cookbook stores is Jessica's Biscuit
(www.jessicas.com), run by David Strymish, who maintains that
Jessica's (named for ``a very sweet golden retriever'') has the
largest inventory of cookbooks in the world, with about 10,000
titles and a million books. The site offers new and used cookbooks,
and the company has branched out into Biscuit Books, which reprints
classic cookbooks.
</P>
<P>
   In Portland, Ore., Johan and Kay Mathiesen run Food Words, a
catalog and Internet business that can be found at the book search
engine sites. Carolyn George of Carolyn's Cookbooks
(members.aol.com &QC; /cgcookbks) can be found at the Denver Book Mall,
but she keeps most of her stock of more than 3,000 cookbooks at
home. Janet Jarvits has a store devoted to cooking and wine in
Burbank, Calif., but said Internet sales make up 30 to 70 percent
of her business (www.abebooks.com/home/JJARVITS/). Her customers
include aficionados of old cookbook illustrations.
</P>
<P>
   Babette Polzer, who runs a catalog and Internet business in
Fairfax Station, Va., called the Squirrel's Nest (searchable on
Bibliofind.com), is one of the dealers who mention the demand for
the original edition of Irma Rombauer's ``Joy of Cooking.'' A Net
search turned up two copies of the 1931 self-published volume for
upward of $2,000; three copies of the 1936 Bobbs-Merrill first
trade edition for $200 to $500, and a facsimile reprint from
Jessica's Biscuit for $20.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for a book on line can be every bit the nostalgia trip
of a good old-fashioned bookstore browse, but much more satisfying
because you almost always find your book.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
