<SLUG> BC-USATTORNEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW U.S. ATTORNEY CHOSEN FOR SOUTHERN DISTRICT OF TEXAS &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By ED ASHER 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   Career prosecutor Mervyn M. Mosbacker Jr. of Brownsville has
been sworn in as the new U.S. attorney for the Southern District of
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Mosbacker, 45, who was born in Mexico, replaces interim U.S.
Attorney James DeAtley, who had held the position since Gaynelle
Griffin Jones resigned in October 1997.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Filemon Vela administered the oath of office
Monday at the federal courthouse in Brownsville.
</P>
<P>
   Mosbacker, who could not be reached for comment, has been a
prosecutor since receiving his law degree from the University of
Texas in Austin in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   He served as an assistant district attorney in Cameron County
from 1982 to 1988, when he joined the U.S. Attorney's Office. Until
Monday, he was the assistant U.S. attorney in charge of the
Brownsville office.
</P>
<P>
   Mosbacker takes over as the chief federal law enforcement
officer for one of the largest and most active of the nation's 94
federal judicial districts.
</P>
<P>
   The Southern District, which has its headquarters in Houston,
consists of 43 counties from Huntsville to Laredo. These include
the Texas Gulf Coast, Padre Island National Seashore and Wildlife
Preserve, the King Ranch and a 300-mile stretch of the U.S.-Mexico
border from Brownsville to Laredo.
</P>
<P>
   Mosbacker will be in charge of a staff of 134 assistant U.S.
attorneys and a support staff of 134.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Ciudad Victoria, Tamaulipas, Mosbacker has lived in
Brownsville most of his life. His mother is a native of Ciudad
Victoria.
</P>
<P>
   The White House announced last month that it was forwarding
Mosbacker's nomination to the Senate. That announcement came nearly
a year after a Texas congressional delegation had recommended
Mosbacker to the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure it will be a challenge, but I look forward to that
challenge,'' Mosbacker said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to say whether he planned any changes for the
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's proper for me to comment on any of the
internal operations in the office at this point,'' he said last
month.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department decided not to submit the congressional
delegation's first choice, Houston attorney Roland Garcia Jr., to
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, who had little prosecutorial experience, was the
apparent shoo-in for the job until it was learned that his brother,
Edgar Arnold Garcia, had pleaded guilty in federal court to a
drug-related murder in Florida. During the sentencing hearing,
Roland Garcia asked the judge to give his brother a light sentence.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Gene Green, D-Houston, who nominated Garcia, praised
the White House's decision on March 10 to send Mosbacker's
nomination to the Senate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
