<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Wednesday, April 7. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Washington) _ Ledeall: Yugoslavia declares a
unilateral cease-fire, starting tonight, for Orthodox Easter. The
U.S. rejects it as a ``half measure''; NATO steps up its military
operations. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ Despite better weather, NATO did not
hit any vehicles or troops on Monday. By Michael R. Gordon and Eric
Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERBIA (Aleksinac, Yugoslavia) _ At least 5 civilians are
killed and 20 or more wounded after a NATO attack aimed at military
barracks hits a residential area in this coal-mining town 125 miles
south of Belgrade. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Skopje) _ Confusion and a desperate anxiety
has spread through the Kosovo Albanian refugees here, as Macedonian
authorities pressed on with their shipment of people abroad and
Serb police forced refugees still stuck in Kosovo to return back to
the capital Pristina. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ISRAEL (Tirana, Albania) _ The scene as Holocaust
survivors and others from Israel bring in aid to the Kosovo
refugees. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BASES (Washington) _ The White House said today it had
selected the American naval base at Guantanamo Bay in Cuba as a
temporary home for 20,000 refugees from Kosovo. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NUKE-LAB-SECURITY (Washington) _ Security concerns and fear of
espionage have forced the Energy Department to suspend use of
classified computers at three of the nation's top research labs.
The shutdown affects the Los Alamos National Laboratory, Sandia
National Laboratories in Albuquerque and the Lawrence Livermore
National Laboratory in California. By James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-INCA-MUMMIES (Undated) _ American and Peruvian archeologists
have discovered three frozen Inca mummies on a peak in northern
Argentina, near the Chilean border. The bodies are in an unusually
well-preserved state, including all organs and even blood in the
veins. By John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
