<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV13-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
13.) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 SOMEWHERE TO THE RIGHT OF ITALY   (For release Tuesday, April(mk) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I wanted to write about the war in Kosovo but what do I know
about Kosovo?
</P>
<P>
   I wanted to worry about the grandmother fleeing in a wheelbarrow
and all the others running for their lives, but all I can say is,
``those poor people.''
</P>
<P>
   I'd like to have an intelligent discussion about what's
happening in that part of the world but it's too complicated.
</P>
<P>
   I don't like being stupid about the Balkans, but there are so
many of those little countries.
</P>
<P>
   I can't understand how your neighbor could suddenly turn on you
because you have a different ethnic background. I don't even know
my neighbors' ethnic background. You can't tell by looking. We look
pretty much the same, but so, I've heard, do many Christian Serbs
and Kosovo Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   I'm confused as to why so many people there and here are mad at
America for intervening when for so long they complained that we
weren't doing anything.
</P>
<P>
   I guess I could leave it up to those who know more than I do,
but how do I know that they know what they're doing? Or the real
reasons for it.
</P>
<P>
   I have skeptical friends. Someone said, look for the money. What
are the economic reasons for the U.S. to be involved?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's face-saving. Or maybe it is purely humanitarian.
Don't you have to step in when you hear that they're executing
people, burning villages, killing children?
</P>
<P>
   People say if we'd had the media we have now during World War
II, we could have stopped the Holocaust. Now we get daily atrocity
updates, so don't we have to do something? But is bombing a way to
stop killing?
</P>
<P>
   If we don't rescue people being tortured and murdered in Tibet
or Africa for their political and religious beliefs why are we
doing it in the Balkans?
</P>
<P>
   I don't know, but if you fail to respond in a humanitarian way
in one place does it mean you never try again?
</P>
<P>
   Future generations may untangle the mysteries of Balkan violence
from a historical novel or a Steven Spielberg movie. But we need to
know now. So far we've been too lazy to study what's going on in
those countries. All we know is they're somewhere to the right of
Italy and they have a tumultuous history.
</P>
<P>
   A cynical friend suggests we appeal to the writers of Ally
McBeal and get her to defend a Serb-American neighbor who set fire
to the house of her Kosovar-American landlady. Then, maybe we would
get it.
</P>
<P>
   Another bets that more Americans know the brand name of Monica's
lipstick and Linda Tripp's literary agent than the capital of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Pristina. I looked.
</P>
<P>
   I know I'm in the majority with my ignorance, otherwise I
wouldn't be so public about it, but when your country starts
bombing a part of the world and captured American soldiers appear
on Serb TV, the right to remain stupid ends.
</P>
<P>
   I think it's time to get smart and do our homework. We've been
told for so long that Balkan history and politics are beyond
understanding, you wonder if it's in someone's interest for us not
to try to understand.
</P>
<P>
   Familiarizing yourself with the region is merely a matter of
geography. If you were planning a vacation to the Adriatic you'd
figure out the borders.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the war, there's an immersion course _ with maps _
served up every day in the media. But what is news and what's
Belgrade spin, Washington spin and NATO spin? You have to pay
attention to a lot of different voices to sort it out.
</P>
<P>
   A peace worker from Sonoma County forwarded an e-mail from a
woman in Belgrade who is a member of the Women in Black peace group
that has long opposed Serbian nationalism.
</P>
<P>
   She writes that Radio Belgrade is filled with partisan songs and
people are led in chants that say death is better than surrender.
There is no appeal, she says, ``for calm and common sense.''
</P>
<P>
   She spoke with a friend by telephone in Kosovo who can't leave
because of her ill father. The Kosovar asked her Belgrade friend
for news. ``What are they saying? What are the predictions?'' The
Belgrade woman writes she has no answers, only words of
consolation.
</P>
<P>
   Both are desperate for news. It's ironic that we, who are 8,000
miles away from them, can seemingly find out more about their war
than they can. But from the same e-mail comes hope that in spite of
the news reports, some rational minds do prevail. The Kosovar woman
told her friend that in a few buildings Serbian and Albanian
neighbors still speak and have, in fact, made pacts. If the police
come for the Albanians, the Serbs will speak up for them. If the
Kosovo Liberation Army comes for the Serbs, the Albanians will
speak for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fear and terror have brought them closer,'' the woman
writes from Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   We haven't heard much about that.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
