<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA GAS PRICES UP DESPITE RISE IN OUTPUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KATHLEEN SULLIVAN and GEORGE RAINE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Although oil refineries in California are
producing more gasoline than a year ago, the age-old law of supply
and demand, plus upcoming summer vacations, are expected to keep
prices high.
</P>
<P>
   The California Energy Commission reported Monday that the
state's refineries had boosted production to 953,500 barrels a day
by April 2, compared with 926,000 barrels a day a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   But the production spike won't result in lower pump prices
anytime soon, said Rob Schlichting, a commission spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will take a while for prices to come down, particularly at
the retail level,'' he said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In the last month, gasoline prices have surged 30 cents or more
per gallon in some parts of the state, the sharpest price increase
in more than 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   The average retail price Monday of a gallon of regular, unleaded
gas was $1.59, compared with $1.46 a week ago, the commission said.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the American Automobile Association reported that
the average price for regular self-serve unleaded gasoline was
$1.08 per gallon nationally. The cost in Hawaii was $1.54, the
nation's highest, and in California, $1.48.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the increase in California is linked to problems that
have reduced supply, including fires at two refineries and
mechanical problems at a third.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Gorell, a spokesman for the Chevron Corp., said he was
surprised to hear that statewide production was up, given the
industry's problems. He said production at Chevron refineries was
down 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Gorell said production was only one of the many factors to take
into account in analyzing the movement of gas prices.
</P>
<P>
   He said gas prices had already begun to climb before the recent
refinery accidents. Demand was up too, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The price of crude oil, the raw material of gasoline makers,
rose in late March after the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries decided to trim production.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last couple of weeks, the cost of our raw material
increased 12 to 13 cents a gallon,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gorell said demand was expected to surge as summer approached
and vacationers took their gas-guzzling sport utility vehicles on
the road.
</P>
<P>
   While industry executives cite the law of supply and demand to
explain recent price surges, Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., has
again asked the Federal Trade Commission for an inquiry and
regulatory action.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC is already investigating gasoline pricing practices in
the California oil industry, responding to a request by Boxer a
year ago. Now, she has asked the agency to add the supply issue to
the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer has asked the FTC to require major oil companies to
maintain an adequate supply of fuel in California, so that prices
can be held down during emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   She also asked the FTC to require companies such as the Exxon
Corp. and the Mobil Corp., as well as BP Amoco and Atlantic
Richfield, which are seeking approval to merge, to sell to
independent marketers and refineries at fair prices.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the recent price increases Boxer wrote: ``While
external events have certainly contributed to these increases, I
believe their effects have been magnified and exaggerated by a lack
of fair competition in the California marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennis DeCota, director of the California Service Station and
Automotive Repair Association and operator of Unocal stations in
Greenbrae and San Anselmo, has long argued that the Department of
Energy should require oil companies to maintain a much more
significant supply of fuel than is available.
</P>
<P>
   ``The oil companies have lobbied against that supply so well,
but any retail business keeps an adequate supply on hand, and it
should be no different in the oil industry,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not all independent distributors agree with Boxer, particularly
large independent oil companies like San Jose-based Coast Oil.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Boxer is wasting her time, taxpayers' time, the time
of the oil companies,'' said owner Jerry Cummings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems she could figure it out,'' Cumming said. ``There is
no conspiracy. We're getting product. It's expensive. It's supply
and demand. One thing this industry does not need is more
government regulation or government investigations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
