<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Beast, thy name is Beauty
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANGELINA COUNTY, Texas _ I brought my Catahoula girl dog home
from the vet this week after having her fixed so as not to further
perpetuate the species.
</P>
<P>
   I consider it my contribution towards the betterment of mankind.
</P>
<P>
   This Catahoula is a truckload of dog and then some.
</P>
<P>
   They're the cajuns of the canines, the national dog of South
Louisiana, what some people call a brown heeler, so named, I'm
told, for their style of herding cows, nipping at their heels.
</P>
<P>
   Our Catahoula my wife named Beauty because she was so ugly a
little puppy.
</P>
<P>
   This is the dog that my wife brought home blind and deaf. A poor
family had her and couldn't afford to have her treated.
</P>
<P>
   Everything turned out OK. Beauty was suffering from a virus akin
to distemper, in that it attacks the nervous system. Fortunately,
it was treatable and Beauty is just fine.
</P>
<P>
   She sees all, hears all and eats all.
</P>
<P>
   She ate two pairs of my eyeglasses that I kept on the night
stand by the bed.
</P>
<P>
   She ate the controls off our electric blanket.
</P>
<P>
   She ate the remote to the TV.
</P>
<P>
   She ate the legs off one of the kitchen chairs.
</P>
<P>
   She ate the Nativity scene at Christmas. (Mary was rescued,
literally, from the jaws of the beast, but there were tiny body
parts scattered everywhere.)
</P>
<P>
   She ate a hundred-dollar bill that my wife had left on a table.
That one, also prized from her jaws, we managed to piece back
together.
</P>
<P>
   She ate most of the Book of Revelation from my wife's family
Bible, including the passages about the mark of the beast.
</P>
<P>
   (Isn't that one of the signs that we're in the end times? When
the Catahoula shall eat from the Book of Revelation?)
</P>
<P>
   And, most recently, she ate the face off of one of the
grandchildren's stuffed Easter bunnies.
</P>
<P>
   But what bothers me most is the way she's been eyeing my little
poodle.
</P>
<P>
   Beauty's a good dog. At least I'm pretty sure she's a dog. What
with the size and shape of her snout, she sometimes reminds me of
an alligator.
</P>
<P>
   Of course all cajuns have a little alligator in them at one time
or another, lunchtime or dinnertime.
</P>
<P>
   Cajuns and Catahoulas _ where else but South Louisiana?
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Catahoula is a revered name in the bayou country.
</P>
<P>
   There's a Catahoula Parish and, also, the Catahoula National
Wildlife Refuge, where, I suppose, the Catahoulas are free to roam
wild.
</P>
<P>
   Not that I ever think about driving Beauty to South Louisiana
and setting her loose.
</P>
<P>
   Well, hardly ever.
</P>
<P>
   I'm hoping she'll begin to settle down as she grows older. At 9
months, she's little more than a puppy.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, she's a lot more than a puppy _ a good 60 or 70 pounds
and still growing.
</P>
<P>
   It's not for nothing they're called cow dogs.
</P>
<P>
   That's about the size they get to.
</P>
<P>
   But I doubt Beauty could ever be an actual, working cow dog.
</P>
<P>
   One nip at their heels, and she wouldn't quit until she'd eaten
the whole herd.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)lcc.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
