<HEADLINE>
GRAPEFRUIT JUICE IS BOOMING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MATT SAUER   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRADENTON, Fla. _ After years of bumper crops that drove prices
into the ground and sluggish sales, the sometimes ugly duckling of
Florida's citrus industry has taken on new life.
</P>
<P>
   Grapefruit juice sales this season are 6.7 percent ahead of last
season, despite the fact that prices have risen about 7 percent, to
$4.63 a gallon. Florida growers control about 75 percent of the
$400 million U.S. grapefruit industry.
</P>
<P>
   The growth in sales is coming after growers abandoned 6 million
boxes of the fruit last year when the bottom fell out of the
market.
</P>
<P>
   Citrus advocates say the industry is putting out a better
product as it has shifted to packaging the juice in popular
ready-to-drink cartons rather than in cans of frozen concentrate or
reconstituted juice. Growers also have largely replanted groves
with red grapefruit, a sweeter version of the fruit. Ruby Red
accounts for 90 percent of all grapefruit sold in stores.
</P>
<P>
   Bradenton's Tropicana Products Inc. puts out a Grovestand Ruby
Red Grapefruit Juice with extra pulp. The company also has added a
calcium-fortified grapefruit juice to tap health-conscious
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Health concerns have helped. Florida's Department of Citrus has
tapped into campaigns touting the cholesterol-free and fat-free
nature of grapefruit juice.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota, Fla., Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
