<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH FASHION FALLS TO FATHERHOOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA ANDERSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I've always been a dreamer. Even before dreams were fashionable,
I had visions of what my life would be like once my mother let me
stay out after 9 p.m. When you're young and bereft of a social life
or cable television, you must rely on your imagination. Like most
of the young girls I knew, and none of the boys, I spent a lot of
time thinking about my family-to-be.
</P>
<P>
   We would live in the perfect house on the perfect street, me, my
husband and my two darling children, Jon Pierre and Fauntleroy. Oh,
I loved Frances Hodgson Burnett's story of 7-year-old Little Lord
Fauntleroy with his wonderful velvet suits and matching shoes. Like
him, my boys would be trendsetters. They would wear knickers and
sailor suits with cute little hats and monogrammed socks. In fact,
we would all wear matching outfits; always, even our bedclothes.
</P>
<P>
   As we gallivanted about, people would point and whisper, ``There
they go. Is that velvet? Oh my. Don't they always look so grand?''
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, it occurs to me that perhaps I might have
benefited from a little more time in the sunshine. Nevertheless, I
had plans _ big plans. Then I met the perfect man and told him all
about my hopes and dreams. He just smiled. I have since learned not
to interpret that smile as a yes. Not once did he rain on my
parade. He listened patiently and merely nodded when I told him
that I liked that French version of Jon without the ``h.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, when I became with child and the ultrasound confirmed
that we were having a male heir, the rain started. One evening as
we were putting up a border in the nursery he said, ``You know, I
always wanted to name my son after me. My friends have all named
their first-born son after them. I know you like that French name,
but I kind of think Jon Pierre won't go over too well in Texas,
especially if he plays sports, like me. It's just not a very
intimidating name. Think about it. `Starting at defensive end, a
6-3, 280-pound sophomore; Jon Pierre Anderson.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he won't play sports,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, my husband started hyperventilating, and I had to get
him a paper sack to breathe into. At that point, I knew that
Fauntleroy was out of the question. Well, at least I can dress him
in velvet knickers, I thought.
</P>
<P>
   Would you believe it? The kid was allergic to velvet. He hated
it from the day he arrived. It made him itch like crazy. And my
husband wouldn't wear the bright purple blazer I bought him. So
either I was sentenced to a wardrobe of blue, black and brown or I
would have to give up my lifelong dreams of coordinated clothing.
Ultimately, I decided that I did not want to appear to be in
mourning every day, and really, his black suit doesn't clash with
my yellow dress.
</P>
<P>
   As for Junior and his brother, Junior II, they wear blue jeans
with holes in them every day and haven't matched since they learned
to dress themselves. But life goes on. And, oh yes, they both play
lots of sports. However, I do have the loveliest T-shirts to match
their jerseys. That velvet gets a little hot, though, during the
soccer games.
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. You can call her at (817) 548-5564, or write in
care of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St.,
Arlington, TX 76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
