<HEADLINE>
JOHN TRAVOLTA'S SON RECOVERED FROM ILLNESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Where can I write to John Travolta? I understand he has a son
with Kawasaki syndrome, which my son also has.
</P>
<P>
   _ C.M., N. Grafton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to Travolta in care of the William Morris Agency, 151
El Camino Drive, Beverly Hills, CA 90212.
</P>
<P>
   Jett, the son of Travolta and Kelly Preston, contracted a form
of Kawasaki syndrome after exposure to chemicals used to clean
their home's carpet, said publicist Michelle Bega.
</P>
<P>
   He's now 6 and fully recovered, Bega said. Travolta discussed
the experience during interviews about ``A Civil Action,'' his film
about children who die from drinking chemically tainted drinking
water.
</P>
<P>
   Kawasaki syndrome, a vascular illness with an undetermined
cause, strikes approximately 1 in 10,000 children under age 5 in
the Unites States. It has become the leading cause of acquired
heart disease among children.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is ``lite'' beer light because of reduced calories or light
because of reduced alcohol?
</P>
<P>
   _ M.M., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: A little of both, though the caloric reduction is much
greater.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, light beer is made by reducing the natural sugars
present in malting barley and reducing the alcoholic content by 10
percent, said Jeff Waalkes, Miller Brewing Co. communications
manager.
</P>
<P>
   A 12-ounce can of Miller Lite has 96 calories, with 4.5 percent
alcohol, compared with Miller Genuine Draft and High Life's 143
calories and 5 percent alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Waalkes wouldn't say how much calorie reduction comes from
reduced alcohol rather than reduced sugar. ``That starts to give
out our recipe,'' he said. ``Recipes are any brewery's most closely
guarded secrets.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I write to David E. Kelley of ``The Practice''? I'd
like to contact him about show ideas.
</P>
<P>
   _ M.T., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to David E. Kelley Productions, 1600 Rosecrans,
Manhattan Beach, CA 90266.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley is the creator and executive producer of ``The
Practice,'' ``Ally McBeal'' and ``Chicago Hope.''
</P>
<P>
   He was working as a lawyer in the early '80s when he sold the
script for the 1987 movie ``From the Hip.'' This led to a staff
position at ``L.A. Law,'' where he wrote numerous scripts and
became executive producer.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he writes both ``The Practice'' and ``Ally McBeal.''
Kelley married Michelle Pfeiffer in 1993, and they have two
children.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
