<SLUG> BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGE ROVER IS TOUGH AS RAWHIDE, LUXURIOUS AS MINK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the world's most capable, most luxurious and, yes, most
expensive sport-utility vehicles is back for 1999 with the most
significant changes since it was completely redesigned for 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Among the changes are improvements to the base 4.0-liter engine,
the interior and the stereo system, as well as the addition of
four-wheel traction control, side air bags for front-seat occupants
and seat-belt pretensioners.
</P>
<P>
   All that adds up to an even better package for a vehicle that
can take its passengers to the fanciest country club or to the most
remote mountain ski hideaway.
</P>
<P>
   Range Rover vehicles, built by Britain's Land Rover (now a
subsidiary of Germany's BMW), were introduced to the United States
in 1987 to give Americans an upscale version of the original
British exploration vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   This model is a few cuts above the Land Rovers the Brits used to
traverse the Australian Outback and other far-reaching and
less-developed areas of the former British Empire. The Range Rover
is so fancy that it is sold only in North America; less-fancy
models bearing the Land Rover name are sold worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Our test vehicle was the base model, known as the 4.0 SE. It's
also the least-expensive Range Rover, with a base price of $58,000
plus $625 transportation. Two other models are offered: the 4.6 HSE
at $66,000, with a slightly larger (4.6-liter) 222-horsepower V-8;
and the limited-edition Callaway 4.6, with 240 horsepower, listing
for a whopping $78,000.
</P>
<P>
   For consumers on a budget, there is the Land Rover Discovery II,
however, with a base price of just $34,150 (about $40,000 with all
the trimmings).
</P>
<P>
   The Range Rover 4.0 SE is definitely aimed at the country club
set, and even though it is perfectly capable of going just about
anywhere that a Jeep could go, it's rare to find a Range Rover
owner willing to risk damaging the vehicle on backwoods trails.
</P>
<P>
   The exceptions are people such as entertainer Jimmy Buffett, who
owns several of these vehicles, including a stretch-limo model that
he uses to take his friends hunting. I once drove an off-road
course in California with Buffett, who had come to town for some
off-road training in his newest Range Rover.
</P>
<P>
   As with most SUVs, fewer than 10 percent of owners ever take
their Range Rovers off road, and that's a shame. You can take these
vehicles into the wild without damaging them if you know what
you're doing, and Land Rover offers some off-road driving training
programs to help their customers get the most out of these truly
capable vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The ruggedness of the Range Rover comes from its aluminum body
on boxed-steel ladder frame arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   The permanent four-wheel-drive system has a viscous-coupling
unit that allows for seamless transfer of power among the four
wheels for smooth driving in all conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The 4.0 SE's V-8 engine cranks out 188 horsepower and 250
foot-pounds of torque. The transmission is an electronic four-speed
automatic, and there is a low range for serious off-road driving
and hill-climbing. The floor-console shifter allows the driver to
choose quickly between high-or low-range modes.
</P>
<P>
   Range Rover's unique air-suspension system puts the vehicle on a
cushion of air. There are five height selections: access, which
automatically lowers the parked vehicle for easy entry and exit;
low, which is automatically selected for highway driving; standard,
for around-town cruising; high, for better off-road clearance; and
extended, a superhigh mode that is automatically engaged when the
vehicle senses that it is high-centering (straddling the center of
a dirt road).
</P>
<P>
   Four-wheel, four-channel antilock brakes are standard, and the
new four-wheel traction control works with the antilock braking
system to detect and prevent wheel slippage by applying brake
pressure to the wheel that is slipping.
</P>
<P>
   The ride is quite comfortable for a vehicle that is really just
a truck, and the interior is elegant, with leather seats and
dual-zone automatic climate control included (well, of course you
wouldn't expect any less at this price).
</P>
<P>
   Other amenities include 10-way adjustable, heated front bucket
seats with separate two-position memory for each seat; cruise
control with steering-wheel-mounted controls; tilt-and-slide sun
roof with shade; universal remote transmitter for garage doors and
security gates; factory security system with engine immobilization
feature; power windows, mirrors and door locks with remote control;
tilt-and-telescoping steering column; quartz halogen headlights
with wipers and washers; power steering and much more.
</P>
<P>
   The Range Rover can tow a trailer of up to 6,500 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Off-road clearance is 8.4 inches under the differential, and the
angle of approach and departure can be a maximum of 34 degrees, an
important feature when coming down a steep hill into a creek or
going up the next hill upon leaving the creek. The vehicle can tilt
45 degrees to one side without tipping over.
</P>
<P>
   The only option offered is a GPS satellite navigation system for
$2,995, a nice feature for around-town driving, highway cruising or
exploring off the beaten track.
</P>
<P>
   Five passengers can travel comfortably in the Range Rover along
with 18.5 cubic feet of gear. With the rear seat folded out of the
way, cargo capacity soars to 58 cubic feet. You could almost set
the tent up inside the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   EPA fuel-economy estimates are about average for this class: 13
miles per gallon in the city and 16 mpg on the highway. The tank
holds 24.6 gallons of gas, and premium fuel is recommended.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   At A Glance:
</P>
<P>
   1999 Range Rover 4.0 SE
</P>
<P>
   THE PACKAGE: Full-size, four-door, full-time four-wheel-drive,
V-8 powered, luxury sport-utility vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   HIGHLIGHTS: The most prestigious line of sport-utility vehicles
can go to the country club in style or cross the wildest areas of
North America. It's the fanciest, yet one of the most capable, SUVs
on the market.
</P>
<P>
   NEGATIVES: High price tag, no third seat.
</P>
<P>
   MAJOR COMPETITORS: Toyota Land Cruiser/Lexus LX 470, Lincoln
Navigator.
</P>
<P>
   EPA FUEL ECONOMY: 13 miles per gallon city, 16 highway.
</P>
<P>
   BASE PRICE: $58,000 plus $625 transportation.
</P>
<P>
   PRICE AS TESTED: $58,625, including transportation.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE ROAD RATING: A.
</P>
<P>
   (G. Chambers Williams III writes on transportation issues for
the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. His mailing address is
Star-Telegram/Northeast, 3201 Airport Freeway, Suite 108, Bedford,
Texas 76021; his E-mail address is chambers(at)star-telegram.com.
Fax: (817) 685-3883. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
 &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
