<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ John McCain is a smart man, an excellent U.S. senator,
a courageous human being and _ compared to President Clinton, at
least _ an expert on military matters. McCain knows about war,
having endured the hell on earth of being a POW during the Vietnam
War. Clinton never served in the armed forces and in fact
demonstrated against the very war that inflicted so much misery on
McCain. So it seems perfectly reasonable that the former Navy
pilot/current GOP presidential hopeful should see fit to offer
advice on the subject of warfare to the former war
protester/current president. By BILL THOMPSON. Story has moved in
``k'' commentary category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ A reader called to take issue with what she
interpreted in a recent column as my endorsement of Sen. John
McCain's contention that U.S. involvement in an all-out ground war
will be necessary to effectively finish what NATO started in
Yugoslavia. It certainly was not my intention to make any such
endorsement. In fact, I don't believe that McCain has endorsed a
ground war. He has simply said that the use of ground troops should
not be ruled out as an option _ and that the American people should
understand that their country may already be so deeply involved in
Yugoslavia that a ground war is virtually unavoidable. By BILL
THOMPSON. Story has moved in ``k'' commentary category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WRIGHT-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ An old man has certain things in common with an old
car. At some point, the body parts begin to wear out and need
fixing _ or replacing. But the profound, too-little-appreciated
difference between the old clunker and the old geezer is the human
body's capacity, still only vaguely recognized, to regenerate
itself. Rebuild. Regrow. This recurring physical phenomenon has
been my preoccupation during the past three weeks of professionally
guided rehabilitation at the University of Texas M.D. Anderson
Cancer Center in Houston after a complex, multi-pronged surgical
procedure on March 12 that took 13 hours and doubtless saved my
life. By JIM WRIGHT. Story has moved in ``k'' commentary category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
</P>
