<HEADER>
A7997 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-CERABINO-MARLINS-     04-06 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CERABINO-MARLINS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sounds of joy mark Marlins' opener
 &HT;    By Frank Cerabino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The post-Huizenga era of the Florida
Marlins got off to a hot start Monday on an opening day thick with
nostalgia and thin on expectation.
</P>
<P>
   Pro Player Stadium sparkled with a fresh coat of teal as
summer-like heat gave a preview to the months ahead. The Marlins,
hoping for a year that sees more team building than collapsing,
were hotter than expected too, as they easily trounced the visiting
New York Mets 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   But don't get your hopes up.
</P>
<P>
   The new paint job on the roof of the Marlins' dugout puts this
season in perfect perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of having the Marlins name on it, the dugout roof now
reads ``Your Home Team.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a good reminder, considering that many fans _ including
the thousands of boisterous Mets fans at Monday's game _ will come
to the park to root against the mediocre-at-best Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   But what I particularly like about the dugout roof is the
punctuation. It doesn't just say ``Your Home Team''. It says ``Your
Home Team'' and then has a ``.'' after it.
</P>
<P>
   Your Home Team. Period.
</P>
<P>
   It may be the only dugout roof in the majors with punctuation.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose that if the Marlins were expected to be pennant
contenders, the punctuation mark might be an exclamation point:
Your Home Team!
</P>
<P>
   Or if former owner Wayne Huizenga still ran the team, his
efforts to squeeze some public money for a new stadium might have
prompted a ``Your Home Team?'' on the dugout roof.
</P>
<P>
   I like the period, though. It has a Zen-like calmness to it. It
basically says, at least to me, to accept things in their imperfect
form, which isn't that bad.
</P>
<P>
   It's baseball. It's driving distance to your home. And we
promise, we're trying the best we can. Your Home Team. Period.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing to shout about. But nothing to question, either.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of shouting, I brought a sound meter to the game
Monday, to quantify the relative enthusiasm and loyalty of the
38,983 fans who showed up.
</P>
<P>
   I half expected the visiting Mets, a team with pennant
expectations this year, to get most of the noise from the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   But the good news for Marlins new owner John Henry is that even
against a team with a huge South Florida following, his Marlins
were still very much the home team Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Mets outfielder Bobby Bonilla got the biggest applause (95
decibels) of all the players announced on either team. But the fans
were applauding Bonilla's great year with the Marlins two years
ago, when the team won the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   I know, because the crowd responded with a nearly equal
94-decibel ovation when Bonilla popped out to end a Mets' threat in
the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd spared no applause for any member of the 1997 Marlins'
World Series championship team.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Counsell, who wasn't starting Monday's game but scored the
winning run in the World Series, got a 92-decibel applause, more
than any Marlin except Alex Fernandez, who was also a member of
that 1997 team.
</P>
<P>
   There were other ways to gauge the Marlins fans' loyalty to
their team.
</P>
<P>
   When the teams first scored, it was the Marlins (97 decibels)
who drew more applause than the Mets (86 decibels.) To put that in
perspective, this was tempered enthusiasm. Rock concerts can crank
up to 140 decibels and a solo jackhammer can get to 100 on its own.
Even a noisy electric razor can generate 85 decibels, and most of
the sound was somewhat less than a low-flying jet (90 decibels) can
produce.
</P>
<P>
   But at least most of the noise went the Marlins' way. For
example, when Mets superstar Mike Piazza, who played five games as
a Marlin last year, was announced, he got a 92-decibel applause.
And he got a 93-decibel applause when Fernandez struck him out in
the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' greatest moment, a homer by first baseman John Olerud
rated 86 decibels, far less than a sparkling double-play turned by
Marlins shortstop Alex Gonzalez (100 decibels.)
</P>
<P>
   The sound meter produced a few scary results too.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the introduction of mascot Billy the Marlin (83
decibels) drew as much noise as the introduction of Hall of Fame
players Stan Musial and Whitey Ford, and 9 decibels less than the
crowd's reaction to a fan catching a foul ball in the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   The moment of silence for Joe DiMaggio: 61 decibels.
</P>
<P>
   The blaring Jumbotron pregame video blared with an ear-numbing
94-decibel soundtrack _ only three decibels less than the roar of
the crowd that accompanied the Marlins' first run.
</P>
<P>
   The umpires did pretty well _ only rating an 82-decibel boo
after calling ball four on a close pitch to a Mets player. This
turned out to equal the indifference the crowd showed to the ``If
you're happy and you know it clap your hands'' song played by the
stadium organist.
</P>
<P>
   When the last out was made, fireworks popped in the sky beyond
centerfield, to celebrate a Marlins victory, the team's fourth
opening day win in seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody's talking World Series this year. But at least
mathematical elimination got pushed back one more day on the
calendar.
</P>
<P>
   And at least until tonight, it sounds like the Marlins are still
South Florida's home team.
</P>
<P>
   Period.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Cerabino writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
