<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AND NATO SPURN CEASE-FIRE IN YUGOSLAVIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton spurned a cease-fire appeal from
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic on Tuesday and vowed to
continue the U.S.-led bombing campaign until Yugoslav troops leave
Kosovo and NATO troops can escort refugees back to their homes.
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart announced the decision
by the president and NATO leaders barely two hours after the
Yugoslav leadership declared a unilateral, five-day suspension in
the murderous, house-to-house onslaught that has uprooted 1.1
million of Kosovo's 1.8 million ethnic Albanian Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia's campaign of ``ethnic cleansing'' has driven more
than 500,000 refugees into neighboring Albania, Montenegro and
Macedonia _ with 250,000 refugees entering Albania alone.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslavs' cease-fire declaration did not mention NATO by
name and did not include a reciprocal demand that NATO halt its
14-day bombing campaign. Nor did Yugoslav authorities promise to
halt anti-aircraft fire against allied bombers .
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Yugoslav Prime Minister Vuk Draskovic said, however, he
hoped that NATO would respond by halting the bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``If NATO continues to bombard Serbia after today's decision, it
would be very clear ... NATO is against peace,'' Draskovic said.
</P>
<P>
   The cease-fire took effect at 2 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart repeated Clinton's hard-line terms for ending the
bombing: Milosevic must withdraw 40,000 soldiers, police and
paramilitary vigilantes from Kosovo, accept deployment of a
28,000-troop international security force, clear the way for
refugees to return to their homes and accept creation of an
autonomous Kosovo province under local control.
</P>
<P>
   ``A mere cease-fire is clearly not sufficient to meet these
conditions,'' Lockhart said, adding: ``NATO operations will
continue until either Milosevic accepts these conditions, or we
will seriously diminish his capacity to maintain his grip and
impose his control on Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart added: ``You don't have a deal until you have a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen, calling the Yugoslav cease-fire
``absurd,'' said he was flying to NATO headquarters in Belgium to
consult with allied military and political leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, a former GOP senator from Maine, said he would take 11
lawmakers from Capitol Hill on his trip to NATO headquarters and on
to the Aviano air base in Italy. The group included Sen. John
McCain, R-Ariz., a 2000 GOP presidential aspirant who has urged the
use of allied ground troops in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials said they attributed Milosevic's declaration of a
cease-fire to the impact of 14 nights of allied air attacks.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials warned on Monday that they expected
Milosevic to propose a cease-fire. The Yugoslav government, in a
statement broadcast on Belgrade television, declared a five-day
cease-fire through the Orthodox Christian Easter on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials said it was unclear whether the Yugoslav proposal
was merely for a pre-Easter cease-fire or for a permanent
cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either way, it's not sufficient,'' Lockhart said at the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Clinton administration officials and NATO leaders in
Brussels expressed regret for an allied air attack that went badly
wrong, when bombs missed a facility housing a Yugoslav artillery
brigade in the central Serbian town of Aleksinac. The weapons
instead hit a civilian apartment house by mistake in the mining
town of about 17,000 people 100 miles southeast of Belgrade,
killing an unknown number of civilians.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department issued a daily update on so-called ethnic
cleansing by Yugoslav forces that reported unrelenting ``forced
expulsions throughout Kosovo'' accompanied by robberies, extortion
and looting.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department report said refugees continue to report
that Serbian forces are ``systematically separating military-aged
men'' from evicted groups of refugees, carrying out mass executions
and using ethnic Albanian captives as human shields in combat with
Kosovar Liberation Army forces.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department said that refugees were reporting that more
than 200,000 ethnic Albanians were being detained in the Kosovar
capital of Pristina without food, water, medicine or shelter
awaiting transportation out of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the cease-fire offer, Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright consulted with her counterparts from Britain,
France, Germany, Italy and Russia. The nations' foreign ministers
agreed to meet in Brussels within the next few days to review the
allied air campaign and to reaffirm the conditions that Milosevic
must meet to win cessation of allied air attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe a sustained air campaign can accomplish the
objectives we have laid out,'' Albright told a forum at the
Brookings Institution in Washington. Albright added: ``We are going
to continue in this intensive air campaign and we will do so until
all the Serb forces are out'' of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The embattled Yugoslav province of Kosovo _ barely larger than
greater Los Angeles _ has been dominated for centuries by ethnic
Albanian Muslims who forged ties with their Turkish Ottoman
overlords who controlled the Balkans for six centuries before being
ousted during World War I.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon announced that the United States will provide
temporary refuge for 20,000 Kosovar refugees at the U.S. Navy base
at Guantanamo Bay, Cuba, as part of an allied commitment to provide
safe haven for 100,000 of the ethnic Albanian Muslim refugees who
have overwhelmed Yugoslavia's neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart announced that the United States will provide temporary
refugee status to Kosovar citizens who have been in the United
States since last June, to enable them to remain in the United
States at least for another year.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton plans to meet with congressional leaders next week after
Congress returns from the Easter recess.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
