<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7999 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TB-HNS &LR;      04-06 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TB-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(EDITORS: LAST WEEK CQ) &HT;    
 &HT;    NEW CASE IN RIO GRANDE VALLEY SPOTLIGHTS BATTLE AGAINST TB
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By JAMES PINKERTON 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   LOS FRESNOS _ For 33 students and two teachers, the discovery of
tuberculosis in their middle school will mean months of taking
antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   But the detection of an active case of tuberculosis in a
14-year-old student, which came to light during spring break,
underscores the complexity of combating a dread lung disease more
prevalent along the border than in most parts of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Health workers say they may never know how the girl was exposed
to the disease. Tuberculosis is sometimes associated with poverty
and overcrowded conditions, but in this case the sick teen comes
from a middle-class family with parents who work as professionals. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``Basically it is a persistent problem and it's been present
(on the border) at double the state rate for many years, and it
continues to be a public health problem that we have to maintain a
great deal of vigilance to deal with,'' said Dr. Brian Smith,
director of &UR;  &LR; the Texas Department of Health's Region 11 in
Harlingen.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said immigration, along with social and medical factors,
have combined to produce high tuberculosis rates on the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have poverty, overcrowding, and you have lifestyle
problems with alcohol and drug use, and you have a fairly large
foreign-born population that would have been exposed to
tuberculosis sometime in the past,'' Smith said, referring to
higher rates of the disease in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The other big factor, he said, is diabetes _ another problem on
the border _ because that makes people more susceptible to
tuberculosis.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials say that since 1992, when more resources and
different strategies were devoted to tuberculosis prevention, the
rates in Texas and the border areas have been steadily declining.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the number of tuberculosis cases statewide has fallen
9 percent from 1997, with a total of 1,820 cases last year.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the rate along the border has fallen from its peak of
40 cases per 100,000 in 1992 to less than 20 per 100,000 today. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; But it is still not surprising, officials say, for the disease
to turn up in local schools, jails, hospitals or nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation in Los Fresnos is not unusual. Most school
systems sooner or later have a case of tuberculosis,'' Smith said.
``The main thing to remember is to watch for the symptoms and treat
the patients as quickly as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Los Cuates Middle School in Los Fresnos, principal Andres
Lopez said his staff did just that.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez said the case came to light on March 18, during the
school's spring break, when the private physician treating the
eighth-grader called the school and the county health department to
report the active case of tuberculosis.
</P>
<P>
   Four days later, county and state health workers interviewed
teachers and determined the student had, during her classes and
athletic activities, come in close contact with 134 students,
teachers and coaches. Skin tests were administered to the risk
group, and 34 tested positive for exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Last week a mobile laboratory from the state Health Department
came to the school, and technicians took chest X-rays of those who
had tested positive. Lopez said the X-rays showed none of the
students or teachers had developed tuberculosis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was done in a expeditious manner, the problem was
addressed, and everything is safe,'' Lopez said.
</P>
<P>
   What remains a mystery, health officials say, is how the student
contracted the disease. School officials say the student, who had
attended school in Los Fresnos since the first grade, was current
on her required vaccinations and tuberculosis test.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't been able to find who might have infected her,''
said Juan Uribe, a registered nurse who is the tuberculosis
coordinator for the Cameron County Health Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``We checked her immediate family and everyone came out fine.
She might have contracted the germ five or six years ago, and it
has just now become a disease.''
</P>
<P>
   Uribe said the student, who is taking her classes at home, has
responded well to a combined therapy of four antibiotics and is
expected to return to school in a few weeks. Her classmates during
the next nine months will take a daily dose of isoniazid, an
anti-bacterial drug, while the adults will undergo six months of
similar treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Health workers say 10 percent of those testing positive for
exposure to tuberculosis eventually develop the disease, usually
much later in life when their immune systems begin to weaken. But
taking the drug therapy after exposure reduces the chance of
developing tuberculosis by 90 percent, health officials said.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
