<DOCNO> NYT19990406.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8003 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-KOSOVO-AZR &LR;      04-06 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-KOSOVO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON NEEDS TO EXPLAIN HOW GOALS WILL BE REACHED  
 (ADV: THIS EDITORIAL APPEARED IN THE APRIL 6 ARIZONA REPUBLIC) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Monday's brief update by President Clinton on events
in Kosovo illustrated the chief executive's sense of what the
American mission in this bloody region ought to be. He dispensed
the toll-free number Americans can call to contribute to the
refugee-relief effort on behalf of Kosovars in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   While this military mission to the Balkans has not yet devolved
into a Jerry Lewis telethon, precisely what it is, and what it will
become, remains obscure.
</P>
<P>
   With the air attacks against the institutions of Serbian
strongman Slobodan Milosevic approaching their third week, and with
calls for ground troops becoming louder and more seriously
presented, it is time for the president and his advisers to begin
responding to some of the questions being shouted from the press
gallery.
</P>
<P>
   A good place to start would be to illustrate with some precision
and clarity why we fight.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the March 24 bombing campaign, Clinton offered a
number of often rambling explanations for launching the missiles
and planes. One rationale, presented at a union gathering, involved
some vaguely defined economic imperative. Later, the primary
motivator evolved into protecting the Kosovars from exactly the
kind of industrial-strength ethnic cleansing that now appears to be
occurring (begin ital) because (end ital) of the airstrikes. Which
leads us to the next point the president needs to make:
</P>
<P>
   Are we winning?
</P>
<P>
   If the president and his associates in NATO intend to continue
this air campaign _ and by every indication they do _ then they
need to explain whether or not it is working.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps absolute conclusions are unfair after just two weeks,
but it would appear that even many supporters of the NATO
airstrikes believe the strikes are failing to beat Serbia into
submission.
</P>
<P>
   Not only are they failing, but they look to be producing
precisely the outcome they were designed to protect against.
Clinton argues stridently that the Serbian attacks on
ethnic-Albanian Kosovars would have taken place regardless of the
campaign, but that just raises the question: Why place any American
lives at risk in a campaign that was designed to produce no better
results than doing nothing?
</P>
<P>
   In point of fact, the tactics of this NATO incursion into the
Balkans are resurrecting many of the pale apparitions of war they
were supposed to suppress: Gen. Curtis LeMay's one-legged theory of
victory by air power . . . President Lyndon Johnson's
victory-frustrating incrementalism (Today, Apache attack choppers.
Tomorrow?) . . . dread of the ``domino effect'' . . . and, the
appalling capacity of ruthless Third World despots to simply ignore
the rising body count while they wait you out. Sound at all
familiar?
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the president declared our short-term goal as the
provision of refugee relief. Long-term goal: ``Give them the right
to return.''
</P>
<P>
   It would behoove us all if the president would explain in some
detail exactly how he expects to get from here to there. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-99 1734EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
