<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8007 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-TALK-ART-700&AMP;ADD     04-06 1130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-ART-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINE WINES FROM VALPOLICELLA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Years ago in this country, long before Beaujolais was the wine
of choice among first-time drinkers, Valpolicella, a red Italian
wine that can be equally light, fruity and fragrant, was enormously
popular _ and just as importantly, affordable. A staple in
neighborhood Italian restaurants, it was frequently the wine that
inspired people to make their first foray into the wine aisle of a
liquor store or into one of the few wine shops that existed then.
</P>
<P>
   As American tastes grew more sophisticated, Valpolicella was all
but forgotten, a symbol of an era as obsolete as drive-in movie
theaters and cars with fins. It deserved to be. Vastly
overproduced, it was by the 1970s an insipid, forgettable wine.
</P>
<P>
   Now, all of that has changed, thanks to a new generation of
Italian winemakers, many of whom were trained at the Agricultural
Institute in San Floriano in the Valpolicella district in
northeastern Italy. These winemakers are determined to place
quality ahead of quantity, and because of their efforts,
Valpolicella is beginning to take its place among Italy's better
wines.
</P>
<P>
   The Valpolicella region has long been known for its amarones,
extraordinary wines produced from dried grapes. In fact, amarone
will probably always be the region's greatest wine. Where the most
striking improvements have been made in recent years has been in
the traditional table wines, particularly those from the
Valpolicella classico district.
</P>
<P>
   By seeking out the best grapes, by adopting the most modern
viticultural techniques and, mostly, by severely limiting crop
yields, the new generation of winemakers has produced table wines
of a depth and elegance never even dreamed of. What's more, these
winemakers have given new distinction to amarone, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Valpolicella (the word means ``valley of many cellars'' in
Italian) is an extensive area lying between the Bardolino vineyards
along the shore of Lake Garda, northwest of Verona, and the
vineyards of Soave to the east. To the north looms Mount Lessini,
one of the southernmost outcroppings of the Alps.
</P>
<P>
   Between the mountain and Verona are flat plains that still
produce dull wines reminiscent of Valpolicella's worst years. But
on the hills northwest of the city, where breezes from Lake Garda
temper the heat on the terraced slopes, are vineyards whose grapes
go into the best traditional wines, both Valpolicella classico and
amarones.
</P>
<P>
   The small, serious winemakers who labor on these hillsides still
have to battle the prevailing economic attitudes of the big wine
companies, which pay growers for high production. In good years, as
many as 5 million cases of Valpolicella are produced, much of
lesser quality. While serious growers limit their yields to three
tons of grapes an acre, the more commercially minded may bring in
three times that.
</P>
<P>
   Producers like Allegrini and Zenato have in recent years made
intense Valpolicella classicos, wines that make most commercial
Valpolicellas seem thin and acidic. Limiting yields means less but
better wine and inevitably higher prices. There are still
inexpensive Valpolicellas on the market, but a good classico from a
single vineyard can cost $20 or more.
</P>
<P>
   Valpolicella is made from four grapes: corvina, rondinella,
molinara and negrara. Corvina, sometimes called corvina Veronese,
is the most important grape, as it is in Bardolino.
</P>
<P>
   To produce amarone, the winemakers take bunches of especially
ripe grapes, mostly corvina, spread them out on trays and then
store them indoors for three or four months until they are shrunken
and dehydrated. The loss of water concentrates the sugar and flavor
elements in the grapes, which, when crushed in late winter, yield a
wine with high alcohol and intense flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike traditional Valpolicella, amarone is aged for three, four
or more years in oak casks. The result is one of Italy's most
powerful red wines, in a class with some Barolos and brunellos. The
names comes from amaro, the word for bitterness, but the wine is
not bitter at all. In fact, it can give the impression of sweetness
because it is so concentrated. Some amarone lovers compare it to
tawny port in richness and flavor.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In recent years, the more innovative producers have come up with
yet another variation on the Valpolicella theme, a wine they call
ripasso. It's made by combining the traditional, light-bodied
Valpolicella with the pomace of amarone. Pomace is the sludge of
skins and seeds left in the presses after the grapes have been
crushed. Adding it to the finished wine restarts fermentation and
produces a stronger, fuller wine that in style is somewhere between
the traditional Valpolicella and the rich, intense amarone.
</P>
<P>
   To confuse things a bit more, there is also a sweet version of
amarone, known simply as recioto della Valpolicella. The grapes for
recioto are dried in the same manner as those used for amarone, but
for several additional months. Recioto is necessarily more of an
aperitif than a table wine.
</P>
<P>
   The best-known names in Valpolicella are Bertani and Bolla,
major wine producers whose labels are known worldwide. They produce
traditional Valpolicellas, as well as amarones. But it is the
less-known producers whose wines have led to renewed interest in
the wines of Valpolicella. In addition to Allegrini and Zenato,
names to look for include Masi, Santi and Tommasi.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more interesting wines from the Valpolicella area is
Allegrini's La Poja, which is made entirely from the corvina grape.
As a result, it can't be called Valpolicella, but it displays much
more body and finesse than most traditional Valpolicellas. It sells
for around $40, when most traditional Valpolicellas are less than
$20.
</P>
<P>
   Also from Allegrini is a single-vineyard Valpolicella called La
Grolas. This is a full-bodied red with intense flavor and a good,
long finish. It sells for about $20.
</P>
<P>
   Amarones vary in price from about $25 _ Beretta's Terre di
Cariano 1990 is about $30 _ to well more than $100. A surprisingly
good 1990 from Bolla is about $35, while a Riserva Sergio Zenato
1990 from Zenato is about $70. A 1991 from Dal Forno Romano was
listed for $135.
</P>
<P>
   These wines are made to accompany roasts, especially game, and
powerful cheeses. At the other end of the line, a simple
Valpolicella, not a classico, from Zenato _ a pleasant table wine
to match with hamburgers or pasta _ costs only $7. There is, truly,
a Valpolicella for everyone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-99 1739EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
