<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLECTOR DREAMS OF RV MUSEUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - A man's dreams are as unique as his DNA code. So it's
inevitable that some are a little strange.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, David Woodworth hopes to open a museum devoted to
recreational vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a major part of American history that no one knows much
about,'' he explained Monday afternoon from inside _ what else? _
an RV. Woodworth was parked at the Welcome Home RV campground in
Phoenix, a stop on the National RV History Tour, which is sponsored
by the Recreation Vehicle Industry Association.
</P>
<P>
   He greeted a trickle of visitors from inside a 1999 Winnebago, a
34-footer worth $125,000 that has a full bedroom, a couch, a
television (with VCR) and bathroom with enough water stored for a
week's worth of showers and washing. The bedroom and living room
double in width with the push of a button. It's a neat trick that,
when done in reverse, makes you feel like the victim in one of
those movies where the walls squeeze in menacingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Considering it's a vehicle, it's really not too shabby,''
Woodworth said.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was the 1921 Lamsteed Kampkar he's towing along with him. It
sleeps four, has a two-burner stove, a pantry, a clothes chest and
running water (although you could park the entire thing inside the
living room of the Winnebago). &QL; 
 &QL; 
Inaccurate stereotype &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But still. An entire museum dedicated to RVs? We see a lot of
them in Arizona, and they conjure up a familiar image: A giant land
cruiser driven by a geezer with wraparound sunglasses, plodding
along at 25 mph in the passing lane of the interstate, emergency
lights blinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not accurate,'' Woodworth said of the image. In fact,
according to a University of Michigan study, which Woodworth quotes
with ease, 40 percent of RV owners are 55 and older while 45
percent are between 35 and 54. The Recreation Vehicle Industry
Association says that the average age is 48.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see a lot of people coming down here in the winter months
who are retired,'' said Woodworth, who is 58 and retired (he was a
minister) but assures he drives the speed limit. ``That helps skew
the image.''
</P>
<P>
   And increase the blood pressure, but that's another story.
</P>
<P>
   To say that Woodworth is an RV enthusiast is to say that Dick
Vitale has a passing interest in basketball. When a few people
gathered in his mobile living room, he said, ``Let me give you a
quick history lesson.'' And he did, including a brief reading from
a dusty, well-worn book on the subject. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Road warrior &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some visitors were looking for advice, others for RVs. Katy
Koivastik of Phoenix hoped Woodworth could hook her up with a
silver 1950s teardrop model for some desolate property.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it would be neat to have one sitting out in the
middle of the desert,'' she said, laughing. ``For guests. Leave 'em
out with the coyotes.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodworth owns a home in Tehachapi, Calif., that doesn't have
wheels, but it's what else he owns that tips you off to his
interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only own 30 (RVs) right now,'' he said, ``but I am looking
for more.''
</P>
<P>
   Did I say interest? Make that obsession. But obsession is
sometimes what it takes to make dreams come true.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I really need is someone that will co-op with me,'' he
said of his museum plans. Certainly, his collection forms the basis
for a good start, including a 1914 trailer model that carries this
gem of a slogan: ``It follows you like a shadow and unfolds like
the night.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodworth is confident his dream will be realized. Witnessing
the glee he gave off in the living room of the Winnebago made that
seem likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't take you long to get used to this,'' he said,
sweeping an arm around the room. ``It's like saying, `I'm not used
to living with a million dollars in my checking account.' I
guarantee you'd get accustomed to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The money, yes. The RV, probably. The wraparound shades . . .
those are a tougher sell. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Contact Bill Goodykoontz at bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
