<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESTAURANT-TIPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIPPING GUIDELINES: A HELP OR ARM-TWISTING 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Restaurants aren't sure that customers get the idea about tips.
Customers seem to have this notion that they're voluntary, a show
of appreciation, something that's only done because they feel like
doing it.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the tip is just part of the game _ and a growing number
of restaurants are trying to lay down the rules and make it easier
for diners to do what they are expected to do.
</P>
<P>
   Some restaurants _ like the new Coach House in New York _ have
tried calculating a 15 percent tip and adding it on to the bill,
just like an extra appetizer or entree.
</P>
<P>
   Others _ like Lula in Santa Monica, Calif. _ are printing
``gratuity guidelines'' on their checks, and calculating what a 15
or 20 percent tip should be.
</P>
<P>
   A few _ like Restaurant Daniel _ are setting mandatory tips of
20 percent on groups as small as six.
</P>
<P>
   And many more places _ including the Union Square Cafe and the
Palm Court in New York _ are determindly looking for ways to
provoke diners into leaving a large-enough tip, while not provoking
them so much that they'll never come back.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a bumpy experiment so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans don't like to be told what to tip,'' said Barry
Wine, a New York restaurant consultant. ``We the customer want the
power to reward good service and penalize bad service.''
</P>
<P>
   But restaurateurs aren't giving up.
</P>
<P>
   The ``gratuity guideline'' or a ``suggested gratuity'' is the
most common ploy so far. The restaurants list a variety of tips _
usually 15, 18 and 20 percent _ calculated from your bill. The tip
is not added to the total but the implication is clear: tip within
the given range.
</P>
<P>
   Offering tip calculations, said Karen Kraushaar, a spokesperson
for the National Restaurant Association, is ``quicker for the
customer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easier,'' she said. ``It's a convenience, there's no
question.''
</P>
<P>
   But that is not quite the reaction most diners have. ``It's kind
of tacky,'' said Jay Goswick, an anesthesiologist in Los Angeles.
When he and his wife recently had dinner at Lula and the bill came
with a gratuity guideline, Goswick was taken aback. You can only
patronize the patron so much.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was funny to see that this was the tip they thought you
should leave,'' Goswick said. ``It would make me more critical,
make me question do they deserve that much?''
</P>
<P>
   Z-Tejas Grill in Austin, Texas, has been telling diners how much
to tip for six months. ``You kind of get mixed reviews,'' said Doug
Young, the general manager at the restaurant. Some diners have
complained, he said, saying that the restaurant is trying to force
them into leaving 15 percent. The servers, however, like the
system. ``It has 20 percent on there,'' Young said, ``and if you
give good service then you usually get 20 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeping servers happy is important during a time when they are
in great demand _ and short supply. Tips generally make up at least
80 percent of a server's salary, so they are built into the
restaurant economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tipping does vary,'' Ms. Kraushaar said. And calculating tips
for diners ``is a way of trying to establish some consistency in
tipping _ that's why it could be worth trying.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies that make the software used to calculate guest checks
and print credit card receipts say there is a growing interest in
programs that calculate tips. American Express developed a gratuity
calculation feature on its terminals last year. ``Merchants wanted
it,'' said Judy Tenzer, a company spokeswoman. Restaurants can
request the feature, and can then choose the tip levels they want
printed on the check.
</P>
<P>
   Micros, a maker of sales terminals with more than 1,400
restaurant clients in New York and New Jersey, has received several
requests for the program over the past nine months. One of them was
from the Union Square Cafe, which has for years been at the
forefront of service in American dining.
</P>
<P>
   An employee at the restaurant saw a gratuity guideline on a
check at a small Chinese restaurant in northern New Jersey, and
brought it to the attention of the management. They immediately
took an interest in the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem it's trying to solve is universal,'' said Paul
Bolles-Beaven, a managing partner at the restaurant. ``Sometimes
people leave a low tip and it's not an indication of poor service.
Maybe they're having a bad math experience or they've had a little
more wine than is normal.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, they had considered ways of incorporating tips into
the price of the meal. They discussed this new idea for several
months and asked Micros to develop a way to integrate it into their
current system. ``On the positive side, we felt it could feel like
a service to the guest, '' Bolles-Beaven said. ``On the negative
side, we felt it could take what is currently a discretionary thing
and add some arm twisting to it.''
</P>
<P>
   When they asked some of their regular guests if they thought
they should proceed with the program, though, the response was a
unanimous no. And the idea was promptly buried.
</P>
<P>
   But restaurateurs and consultants say that New York is unique in
respect to tipping. First of all, calculating tips is made easier
by New York state tax, which, if doubled, equals 16{ percent. But,
also, said Steve Hanson, the owner of Ruby Foo's Dim Sum and Sushi
Palace and several other restaurants on the Upper West Side, New
Yorkers consider themselves more sophisticated.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can calculate what two percent points can be,'' he said.
And they don't want to be told.
</P>
<P>
   The one exception used to be that parties of eight or more were
charged a set tip, usually 15 percent. Now, in many Manhattan
restaurants, like Le Bernardin, Bolo and Gotham Bar &AMP; Grill,
parties of just six are charged an automatic gratuity, and often as
high as 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   When the new Coach House recently opened, the restaurant, which
has a fixed priced menu, tried tagging on a 15 percent service
charge to all checks. ``It was a way of establishing that you come
in and you know this is what you're going to pay for a meal,'' said
Kirk Reed, the general manager of the restaurant. ``It was trying
to simplify things but it ended up making things less simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Some diners failed to notice the service charge _ which was
listed on the bill along with other food and beverage charges. So
they added a second tip. A blank line below the total, marked
``gratuity,'' didn't help matters.
</P>
<P>
   But the other drawback to this was that, in New York, when
service charges are added to a bill, they must be added before tax,
which means that the tip is taxed.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant has since gone back to a traditional
discretionary tipping system.
</P>
<P>
   For many years, Michael's restaurant, in New York City and Santa
Monica, added 15 percent service charges to all checks. Michael
McCarty, the owner of the restaurants, converted back to an
optional tipping system last year. To his surprise, the average tip
in both locations is now closer to 20 percent. ``All these years we
gave our clients a bargain at 15 percent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He remains adamant that service charges are a more civilized way
of doing business, but is tired of trying to win over diners.
``You're really wasting your time, if you're trying to dictate to
people what to leave,'' he said. ``People are independent.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States is one of few countries where voluntary
tipping is customary. In Europe, a tip of 10 to 15 percent is
almost always included in the bill. Many travelers visiting the
United States for the first time simply do not know to tip.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
