<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, April 7, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday afternoon, heavy snow driven by gusty winds
dramatically lowered visibility in the mountains east of Los
Angeles as a potent low pressure system in the cold upper
atmosphere drifted overhead. On Wednesday, the formidable but
lethargic disturbance will be encouraged to move eastward by a
rainy disturbance headed toward the West Coast from the Gulf of
Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   A powder keg of humid air surging into the southern Plains from
the Gulf of Mexico will heighten the risk of powerful thunderstorms
Wednesday night from western Kansas to northwestern Texas as the
disturbance approaches Wednesday evening. The storms will erupt
along a dry line, a boundary that marks the separation of humid air
from the Gulf of Mexico and dry air from the Rockies. A few of the
storms could reach severe levels, spawning tornadoes, large hail or
damaging straight-line winds. Wednesday afternoon, a few storms may
ignite along the dry line, but they will be rather isolated and
probably not sufficiently strong to spawn severe weather.
</P>
<P>
   Rain will develop in western Washington and Oregon on Wednesday
and then spread south to California later Wednesday and Wednesday
night as the disturbance from the Gulf of Alaska plunges
southeastward.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, warmer air will spread to much of the Eastern states
in the wake of a disturbance lifting northeastward across eastern
Canada, though northern New England will stay rather chilly. Winds
from the west will average 15 to 25 mph with higher gusts along the
Northeast seaboard. Isolated thunderstorms will sprout in the
Southeast states.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: April Tornadoes
</P>
<P>
   With regard to the monthly tally of tornadoes, May is the most
active, on average, with over 160 twisters nationally. June is a
close second. But April holds the dubious distinction of spawning
more killer tornadoes. With the speedy jet stream continuing to
derive energy from large north-south temperature contrasts in
April, robust Pacific disturbances still come ashore and then forge
slowly east toward the Plains. Ahead of the system, humid air
streams inland from increasingly tepid waters of the Gulf of
Mexico. When potent disturbances meet high humidity, killer
twisters can result.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
