<HEADER>
A8018 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUTH-PACIFIC-ANNIVER     04-06 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTH-PACIFIC-ANNIVERSARY-ART-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A `SOUTH PACIFIC' REUNION 50 YEARS AFTER ITS BROADWAY OPENING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By BILL DEYOUNG   
 The Gainesville (Fla.) Sun   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ Wednesday afternoon, between the matinee and
evening performance of ``Phantom of the Opera,'' Jacqueline Langee
will step onto the stage of New York's Majestic Theatre for the
first time in nearly half a century. When she closes her eyes,
Langee will be able to hear the quiet roar of anticipation from her
opening night audience, April 7, 1949. That was some enchanted
evening.
</P>
<P>
   It was on that night, 50 years ago, that Rodgers and
Hammerstein's ``South Pacific'' made its Broadway debut, and made
musical theater history. Jackie Langee _ now a resident of
Gainesville _ was part of the cast.
</P>
<P>
   The reunion is being organized by the New York-based Rodgers &AMP;
Hammerstein Organization, keen to commemorate one of the duo's most
beloved collaborations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have four people coming in from England, one from
Australia, and there are 14 or 15 coming from the coast,'' said
Langee, 73. ``It's very exciting, but it's also sad. Fifty years is
a long time, a lifetime practically for a lot of people, and some
of them aren't there anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Gone are the four leads, all of whom won Tony Awards for the
show: Ezio Pinza, Mary Martin, Myron McCormick and Juanita Hall.
Composer Richard Rodgers, lyricist Oscar Hammerstein, producer
Leland Heyward and director Josh Logan have passed away, too.
</P>
<P>
   Based on James Michener's World War II collection of short
stories, ``Tales of the South Pacific,'' the musical concerns a
company of Naval men and women stationed on an island not far from
Japanese territory. Nurse Nellie Forbush (a tomboyish Martin in the
original cast) falls for older man Emile DeBeque (Pinza, then a
popular bass with the Metropolitan Opera), a French planter living
on the island.
</P>
<P>
   Rodgers and Hammerstein's score was at once ethereal, gritty and
hummable, including the now-classic songs ``Some Enchanted
Evening,'' ``There is Nothing Like a Dame,'' ``Bloody Mary'' and
``Bali Hai.'' One of Langee's favorites, ``You've Got to Be
Carefully Taught,'' backed up a secondary plotline about a romance
between a white American lieutenant and a native girl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rodgers said backstage that someone had raised eyebrows at the
dark skin/light skin romance,'' Langee recalled. ``Racial prejudice
was a major theme of the show. Rodgers and Hammerstein were very
idealistic people.'' Raised eyebrows notwithstanding, ``South
Pacific'' was awarded the Pulitzer Prize for drama in 1950.
</P>
<P>
   Langee _ she was Jacqueline Fisher then _ played nurse Genevieve
Marshall. One of her big numbers, with Nellie and the other women,
was ``I'm Gonna Wash That Man Right Out Of My Hair.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great company,'' she said. ``There was almost a
family feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Langee's own family came from Miami. She was born there, and
lived near Miami Beach until the hurricane of 1926. Her father had
a drugstore and some real estate. ``After the storm there was no
roof on the house, and all that was left of the drugstore was a
tile floor,'' she said. So the Fishers moved to Parkersburg, W.
Va., where they had relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Jackie's alto voice was a source of pride in the family. At age
16, she was accepted into the Cincinnati Conservatory of Music. She
graduated four years later and moved to New York City, where she
found work singing classical music.
</P>
<P>
   Her first Broadway show, ``Inside U.S.A.,'' was a musical revue
with Beatrice Lily and Jack Haley. Nine months into it, in 1948,
she auditioned for ``South Pacific.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodgers and Hammerstein, known at the time for ``Oklahoma!'' and
``Carousel,'' needed a hit. Their last show, ''Allegro,'' had been
only a modest success.
</P>
<P>
   Langee said she had five auditions for the show. The composers
attended all the auditions, along with director Logan and producer
Heyward. Rodgers told her they heard 2,500 women sing, before
choosing six nurses.
</P>
<P>
   Langee was 23 when she won the part and stayed with ``South
Pacific'' a little less than two years. The show ran for 1,925
performances. And a hit it was: ``As lively, warm, fresh and
beautiful as we had all hoped it would be,'' raved Brooks Atkinson
in The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   After ``South Pacific,'' Langee continued to sing in New York,
including several seasons as a soloist at Radio City Music Hall.
She married Harvey Langee during the run of ``South Pacific'' and
moved to California in the late '50s when he was accepted to
Stanford Medical School. After a decade in Palo Alto, Calif., the
Langees _ four children in tow _ moved to Gainesville, where
Harvey, a psychiatrist, joined the University of Florida faculty.
</P>
<P>
   Jackie Langee earned master's and specialist degrees in
counselor education at UF, and sang often at campus events during
the '70s and '80s. She also ran the office for her husband's
private practice, from which he retired in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Among her treasured mementos from ``South Pacific'' is a small
silver box given to each cast member by the composers, producer and
director on the show's first anniversary. It is inscribed with
their signatures.
</P>
<P>
   Looking into its reflective surface, Langee can go back 50
years, back to that spring New York night when she helped make the
magic happen, when Broadway made ``South Pacific'' the toast of the
town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must say that being on the Majestic stage again, just to
stand there, is exciting,'' she said. ``One of my friends, when I
told her we were going to do it, she said she got tears. Well, I
got chills.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Gainesville, Fla., Sun is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
