<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-TEXAS-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTIN, IN THE BIG TIME, GETS AN AIRPORT TO MATCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., April 11) 
(jt) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Robert Mueller Municipal Airport is three miles
from the state capitol. That's what's good about it. Otherwise,
it's small, overcrowded and poorly laid out, and parking is almost
impossible.
</P>
<P>
   As this bucolic university town and government center has grown
and mutated over the last decade into one of the country's leading
high-tech centers, home to Dell Computers and a galaxy of other
technology firms as well as more than a million residents, the old
infrastructure _ the hotels, the highways and the airport _ has
become strained and clogged.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why many who live in Austin, and many more who travel
to it on a regular basis, are eagerly awaiting the opening next
month of the gleaming new Austin-Bergstrom International Airport,
built on a shuttered air base eight miles southeast of the capitol.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything at the new airport is different,'' said Jamy
Kazanoff, the airport's chief spokeswoman. ``The old problems
regarding parking are over. You'll have twice as many parking
spaces, twice as many baggage carousels, 25 gates compared to 16,
parallel runways to allow simultaneous takeoffs and landings, a
covered garage and a split upper and lower roadway so all the
curbside congestion at Mueller shouldn't happen.'' At its opening,
the new airport will be able to handle twice the current level of
17,000 passengers a day.
</P>
<P>
   Development is a bit of a dirty word in Austin, a brainy and
laid-back city at the edge of the Texas Hill Country where a slow
and easy quality of life is cherished. But even the city's
pro-green mayor, Kirk Watson _ his slate's slogan was: ``Austin or
L.A.? Our City. Our Choice'' _ has embraced the new airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have been talking about what to do about Mueller
Airport since the 1970s,'' Ms. Kazanoff said. ``Then when the
federal government closed down Bergstrom Air Force Base in 1990,
the city saw it as a real opportunity. The mayor likes to say we
made lemonade out of lemons. Base closures typically depress a
community, but we're using one to build our community.''
</P>
<P>
   Mueller Airport opened in 1930 and was expanded several times
until it had filled its 711 acres and just couldn't expand any
more. It also suddenly found itself in a growing neighborhood where
some 30,000 residents were living in the airport's noise zone. (The
new airport, in the middle of the old military base, should rattle
no one's china, Ms. Kazanoff says.)
</P>
<P>
   Passenger traffic at the old airport grew with the city. Last
December, Mueller celebrated the arrival of its six millionth
passenger of the year, which is millions more than the airport
would have handled a decade ago. From 1997 to 1998, air cargo
traffic to Austin also increased about 40 percent, to 2.4 billion
pounds of cargo, most of it high-tech stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Austin voters approved a bond issue for the new airport in 1993,
and construction, with a budget of $585 million, is just about
finished. Cargo planes have been using the new field since June of
1997, and the first passenger flight is expected to arrive at the
grand opening on May 2.
</P>
<P>
   Now, instead of coming into the confusing labyrinth of Mueller
Airport, visitors will arrive at the crescent-shaped Barbara Jordan
Passenger Terminal, a sun-filled space of granite and glass that,
designers promise, will be easy to navigate. At 600,000 square
feet, the four-story terminal is triple the size of the old one.
</P>
<P>
   Bergstrom's longest runway _ a 12,250-footer inherited from the
air base _ is now long enough for the largest jumbo jets and for
nonstop flights overseas, both impossible at Mueller.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, Ms. Kazanoff said, Bergstrom will have room to
expand, to as many as 55 gates.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with the city's high-tech role, a central Market
Place will include, along with outposts of local restaurants like
Schlotzsky's Deli and the Salt Lick for barbecue, the Highland
Lakes Bar, with internet access, where travelers can check e-mail
or work while they wait.
</P>
<P>
   The one thing that the new airport will not have when it opens
is adequate highways. ``The highway projects are under way, but
they take longer to get finished than an airport does,'' Ms.
Kazanoff said.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest concern among Austin residents and cabdrivers is
that some of the traffic in and out of the airport will pass
through what is already among the most congested highway
intersections in the city: the junction of Highway 71 and
Interstate 35 just south of downtown.
</P>
<P>
   This could force traffic headed into the city to forsake I-35
and use the surface streets of East Austin. But the problem will be
solved when the airport-related highway projects are completed.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Ms. Kazanoff said, most of the people traveling to the
airport are coming from the high-tech centers and neighborhoods on
the city's north and northwest sides. Only about 20 percent come
from the southwest of the city, the area that faces the bottleneck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traffic in Austin is a problem any way you look at it,'' Ms.
Kazanoff said. ``It's a headache for some, but it means Austin is
growing. We've lazed along the Colorado River for years and now
we're a high-tech center. So that comes with the territory.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
