<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8032 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-BEREZOVSKY-NYT     04-06 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BEREZOVSKY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER YELTSIN ALLY SCOFFS AT ARREST WARRANT 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia's chief prosecutor issued an arrest warrant
Tuesday for Boris Berezovsky, the tycoon and political mover who
has taken a sensational tumble from the graces of Russian high
finance and of President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in the prosecutor's office said Berezovsky and Nikolai
Glushkov, a former senior official of the Russian airline Aeroflot,
had been charged with money-laundering and ``illegal
entrepreneurship'' for allegedly diverting foreign currency from
Aeroflot to a company in Geneva that they control.
</P>
<P>
   Berezovsky has long been said to be a dominant figure in
Aeroflot, although he denies owning even one share of stock in
either the airline or in the Geneva company, Andava. Tuesday's
charges, the first from a fusillade of recent government
investigations of Berezovsky's business empire, would seem to
signal that his days as a political and financial power are, at
best, numbered.
</P>
<P>
   But then virtually nothing done by Russia's house-of-mirrors
government can be taken at face value. And with the prosecutor's
office itself at the epicenter of a seamy sex-and-blackmail
scandal, some suggest that Berezovsky's downfall was staged to keep
him from trying to implicate Yeltsin's inner circle in the sex
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   That appears unlikely, though skeptics noted that prosecutors
chose to issue the warrant while Berezovsky was in France, beyond
the immediate reach of the flaccid arm of Russian law.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's spokesman said Tuesday that Yeltsin had not known that
an arrest warrant would be issued for Berezovsky.
</P>
<P>
   Berezovsky, in an interview with journalists in Paris, greeted
the warrant with contempt. He called his accusers ``shameless and
dimwitted'' and dismissed rumors that he would seek asylum rather
than return to face criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   Berezovsky, a onetime car dealer who somehow parlayed currency
trading into a fortune in the wild early days of post-Soviet
Russia, was a principal backer of Yeltsin's 1996 re-election
campaign and at one time a close adviser. A year ago Yeltsin named
him secretary of the Commonwealth of Independent States, the frayed
alliance of most of the nations that had been part of the old
Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   But as Yeltsin's health and power have ebbed, Berezovsky has
became a target both of corruption inquiries and of Yeltsin's
critics _ especially Communists _ who considered Berezovsky a prime
example of the seamy excesses of Russian-style capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor general, Yuri Skuratov, who has strong Communist
backing, was among the investigators. After Yeltsin sought
unsuccessfully to fire Skuratov early this year _ and the
state-controlled television broadcast videotape of the prosecutor
cavorting in bed with two prostitutes _ Communists and some other
critics accused Yeltsin's office of trying to quash probes into
Berezovsky's dealings.
</P>
<P>
   They have suggested that Berezovsky holds secrets that could
ruin the Yeltsin presidency. And when audiotapes surfaced this
winter of private conversations between Berezovsky and Yeltsin's
daughter Tanya Dyachenko, who is her father's close adviser, some
took it as a veiled warning from Berezovsky that efforts to topple
him could bring down Yeltsin's family, too.
</P>
<P>
   But Yeltsin has since dismissed Berezovsky from his post as
commonwealth secretary, and outwardly the estrangement between the
president and the tycoon appears real. While Yeltsin recently
ordered _ again _ that Skuratov be removed, corruption inquiries
under Skuratov's deputy seem to continue apace.
</P>
<P>
   The Communist Party leader, Gennady Zyuganov, suggested Tuesday
that Berezovsky will never be arrested and that the warrant against
him was timed so that it could not be enforced. Had prosecutors
``been sticking to their principles more strictly, they would have
sanctioned Berezovsky's arrest while he was in Russia,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Communist legislators in the lower house of parliament plan
hearings on Wednesday into Skuratov's dismissal. Tuesday night some
said news of the warrant might lead them to expand the scope of the
hearings to cover his motives.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Skuratov's office said they issued the warrant
after trying and failing repeatedly to question Berezovsky about
Aeroflot. They also said they might ask Interpol to help detain
Berezovsky and return him to Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night Berezovsky scoffed at that, too. ``I think that
the law in the West is much stronger than in Russia,'' he said,
``and that Interpol won't take part in a spectacle started by the
Communists and their like-minded brothers in the general
prosecutor's office.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
