<HEADER>
A8050 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-GITMO-0407-COX     04-06 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-GITMO-0407-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. PREPARES TO PROVIDE SAFE HAVEN IN CUBA FOR 20,000 KOSOVO
REFUGEES
 &HT;    Moving in (i) international and (w) Washington categories
 &HT;    with KOVOSO-MAIN and KOSOVO-KLA
 &HT;    with file photos
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI -- Tents that will house up to 20,000 Kosovo refugees
starting going up at Tuesday at the U.S. Navy's base at Guantanamo
Bay, Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Putting up those shelters can be done in hours, according to
U.S. military officials. But they said it may take weeks to provide
other things that are needed -- such as latrines and dining areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have the facilities to handle 20,000 or even 10,000
refugees at this time,'' said Lt. j.g. Herb Josey, spokesman for
the Navy's Atlantic Fleet in Norfolk, Va. ``There is basically just
a bunch of land there, with no real large-scale facilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Tents and barracks designed to house Cuban and Haitians in the
mid-1990s were dismantled in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the task of transforming the scrub-dotted base
into a tent city, there were questions about whisking people
accustomed to cold weather to a hot, humid location nearly 4,700
miles from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where are they going to find translators? How are these people
going to deal with summer, when the temperature rises to over 90
degrees every day?'' asked Guarione M. Diaz, who spent several
months at the base in 1994 as President Clinton's ombudsman for the
Cubans housed there.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a hard place to be even for Cubans who were used to
the strong sun, so I think the Kosovars, who also will feel so
isolated, will be extremely restless and depressed there,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In April, temperatures in Cuba can climb to 87 degrees and the
humidity to 70 percent. By comparison, Kosovo has highs in the '50s
and the humidity is about 45 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The desalination plant can accommodate only 5,000 people,''
Diaz said. ``Most of the roads aren't paved, so the dust is just
awful.''
</P>
<P>
   Also on the horizon is hurricane season, which begins in June.
</P>
<P>
   The news that the United States would temporarily house the
refugees in Cuba came Tuesday. But U.S. officials said it could
take several days to begin transporting them there.
</P>
<P>
   The refuge will be only a temporary one, emphasized White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fully intend the Kosovars will ultimately return to their
homes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials said the Kosovar Albanians will be given
``temporary protective status'' at Guantanamo for up to 18 months,
although the goal is to return them to Kosovo within six months.
</P>
<P>
   Some 3,000 to 4,000 military personnel will be sent to
Guantanamo over the next few weeks to help the refugees, according
to the U.S. Southern Command. The command directs U.S. military
activity in Central and South America and in the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   The Guantanamo base is normally home to about 1,100 seaman and
2,400 dependents and private contractors. It has a civilian-run
McDonald's, a bowling alley, a pizza parlor, a nine-hole golf
course, an 11-bed naval hospital, and a small mall with a
barbershop and a beauty parlor.
</P>
<P>
   (optional trim follows)
</P>
<P>
   The 45-square-mile base, established in 1903 after the
Spanish-American War, has a history of handling refugees.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, it provided shelter for 34,000 Haitians who fled a
military coup.
</P>
<P>
   But it gained real notoriety in 1994, when the base became a
massive tent city for more than 50,000 Cuban and Haitian migrants.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Haitians, who had attempted to escape political and
economic turmoil at home, eventually returned to Haiti. Most of the
Cubans wound up relocating to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The base, which currently houses about 50 Cubans intercepted at
sea and awaiting deportation to third countries, still has the feel
of a prison facility, surrounded by barbed wire and U.S. guards.
</P>
<P>
   (end optional trim)
</P>
<P>
   The Kosovars who will transported to Guantanamo are part of
about 120,000 who will be offered temporary refuge in a number of
countries. There are critics who argue that the refugees should
remain closer to the Balkans so they can return home more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``By sending these Albanians around the world, the likelihood
they'll ever return home becomes infinitely smaller,'' said David
Ray, associate director for the Federation for American Immigration
Reform in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Other critics say keeping the refugees away from the American
mainland sends the wrong message to the Kosovars and the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sends a baffling signal to these poor, traumatized refugees
that the United States does not really want them,'' said Dennis
Grace, vice president of Refugees International, a Washington-based
advocacy group. ``It would be more hospitable for the United States
to bring them to the mainland where they won't be so confined.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, housing refugees in Cuba is bound to irritate Cuban
leader Fidel Castro, who considers the U.S. occupation of
Guantanamo Bay illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba agreed to lease the area, on the island's southeast coast,
to the United States in 1934. Because the lease may be ended only
if Washington so wishes, it remained in American control even after
Castro came to power in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   But the Cuban government refuses to cash the $4,085 rent check
the U.S. government sends each year (cq) under the lease agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every action that's taken at Guantanamo Bay is regarded by the
Cuban government as illegal,'' said Roberto de Armas, a spokesman
in Havana for the Cuban government.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Cuban government has not responded formally to the
U.S.' plans, although in the past it has strongly condemned U.S.
and NATO attacks on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   A State Department spokesman said U.S. officials briefed Cuban
government officials in Washington on Tuesday about the Guantanamo
plan.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
