<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8066 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOP-KOSOVO-HNS &LR;      04-06 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-KOSOVO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS VOICE DIVERSE VIEWS ON BALKAN CONFLICT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One Republican presidential contender, conservative
commentator Patrick Buchanan, wants to pull all U.S. forces out of
the Balkans and labels President Clinton's policy on Kosovo a
``felony.''
</P>
<P>
   But another GOP hopeful, Sen. John McCain of Arizona, says NATO
forces must prevail over Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and
no one should rule out deployment of ground troops. Faltering would
set a dangerous precedent because despots in places like Iraq and
North Korea ``pay attention'' to U.S. actions overseas, McCain has
said.
</P>
<P>
   The two views represent what American University history
professor Allan Lichtman calls ``the Alpha and Omega'' of
Republican approaches to the Kosovo crisis. The GOP's internal
differences also reflect the American public's wide variety of
views toward the U.S.-led warfare against the Yugoslav Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have the Alpha of Pat Buchanan defining the extreme
nationalist, isolationist approach, and then you have the Omega of
John McCain saying (we should) go in with machine guns blazing and
ground troops,'' Lichtman said. ``You have within the Republican
Party the two extreme positions, and those, ironically, have been
getting the most play (in news reports).''
</P>
<P>
   The other GOP candidates fall somewhere in between, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic politicians have seemed far less divided on the
subject, and their comments have so far been muted.
</P>
<P>
   With the presidential field shaping up earlier than ever before,
Kosovo presents the prospective candidates with their first crucial
issue test. It could prove to be an opportunity for self-definition
or an abyss from which some might not emerge.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans' disagreement ``truly reflects some internal
confusion on the part of the American people at this time,'' said
Stephen Hess, a governmental studies scholar at the Brookings
Institution, a Washington think tank. ``To the degree you have both
Buchanan and McCain coming from very different points of view, you
may create a very good debate in the Republican Party. That's very
valuable for the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   The frontrunners, Texas Gov. George W. Bush and former American
Red Cross President Elizabeth Dole, have been ``the missing players
in all this,'' Lichtman said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was one of the last of the Republican candidates to speak
out on Kosovo after NATO bombs and missiles started falling on
Serbia on March 24. Fellow Republicans criticized his statements as
vague and timid, and the conservative Wall Street Journal editorial
page characterized them as ``Clintonian.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Monday with the Washington Post, Bush declined
to call Clinton's approach a failure. But he said U.S. policy
should be to ``win,'' and that ``all options ought to be on the
table.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If military briefers say it's important to use troops to
achieve the mission, I would be supportive, if two things exist:
first, a strong commitment to win, and second, a clear exit
strategy,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Dole said much the same thing on options _ none
``should be taken off the table,'' she said. ``What we're doing is
the right course and we must not shrink from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Drawing on her experience with the American Red Cross, she urged
Americans to make donations to ease the suffering of Kosovo's tide
of refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Two more conservative candidates, activist Gary Bauer and Sen.
Robert Smith, R-N.H., are close to Buchanan in saying U.S. forces
have no business in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio, has mainly questioned the U.S. role in
Kosovo: ``This is not a matter of whose heart bleeds more for
innocent people being brutalized or killed. It really is a matter
of the responsibility of a great power.'' When the United States
overextends itself, he added, ``the world becomes less secure ... I
don't even know what our goal is.''
</P>
<P>
   Publishing magnate Malcolm S. ``Steve'' Forbes and former Vice
President Dan Quayle have directly criticized Clinton, saying
previous White House inaction on Kosovo precipitated the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The same spectrum of debate covers Republican lawmakers on
Capitol Hill. If a consensus is to be reached, it may come in the
form of a vote next week on a war powers resolution urged by Rep.
Tom Campbell, R-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a war, and only Congress can declare war,'' Campbell
said in a letter last week to House Speaker Dennis Hastert.
</P>
<P>
   For Republican strategists, criticism of Clinton may be the only
unifying element of their party's approach to Kosovo. One
conservative consultant, who asked not to be identified, said, ``In
the long term, this is an opportunity because most (Republicans)
believe Clinton's policies will not succeed and those failures will
be laid at the feet of (Vice President) Al Gore going into 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the GOP's differing views, Clifford May, communications
director of the Republican National Committee, said the candidates
are engaged in ``a healthy debate. I don't think it is the job of
Republicans to march in lockstep.''
</P>
<P>
   But pitfalls remain. Months before the Kosovo crisis loomed,
Republicans made it clear that in the 2000 election, foreign policy
would be a key ingredient of their assault on Democrats. They said
Clinton's indecision in troublespots from China to Haiti has made
the post-Cold-War world a more volatile place.
</P>
<P>
   But one political expert said Republican's disunity on Kosovo
may hinder their effort to convince voters they are better able to
handle global entanglements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we find kind of international issue that defines what
we're likely to face over the next decade, and the Republicans are
having a hard time figuring out which way to go,'' said Donald
Kettl, director of the La Follette Institute of Public Affairs at
the University of Wisconsin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
