<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8078 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEFIBRILLATE-SURVIVAL     04-06 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEFIBRILLATE-SURVIVAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY DETAILS VALUE OF SPEEDY DEFIBILLATOR USE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Getting heart attack victims on a defibrillator within 8 minutes
increases their odds of survival by 33 percent. It goes up another
25 percent if the patient is given CPR before being hooked up to
the defibrillator.
</P>
<P>
   Those findings, outlined in two studies published Wednesday,
will pose a huge challenge for communities considering the costs of
CPR training and equipping all fire departments, ambulance services
and other public agencies with defibrillators. But doing so could
yield huge rewards: saving thousands of lives among the 250,000
people who die each year in America of sudden cardiac death outside
of hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a community had widespread CPR training of citizens and
fire and police officials, and very rapid defibrillation, you could
possibly double or triple cardiac survival rates,'' said Dr. Ian G.
Stiell, associate professor of medicine at the University of Ottawa
and lead author of the defibrillation study in the current Journal
of the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are very inexpensive and low-tech approaches to
resuscitation,'' he added. ``They certainly could save thousands of
lives a year, there's no question it would be in the thousands.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Leonard A. Cobb, primary author of the CPR study and a
professor of medicine emeritus at the University of Washington, was
equally enthused: ``I think you can make a good thing better by
trying to optimize the interaction between CPR and
defibrillation.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors have known for years that defibrillators save lives by
shocking the heart back into beating, which is why they've pushed
so hard to get them in ambulances, fire trucks, airplanes and other
public places. But the new report makes clear how those
defibrillators can be used more effectively to raise the dismally
low odds of survival for people who suffer heart attacks outside
the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers zeroed in on 19 urban and suburban communities
around Ontario, looking at survival rates before and after the
communities reduced delays in dispatching ambulances, gave
defibrillators to firefighters and took other steps that resulted
in a 21 percent increase in the number of heart attack victims they
reached within 8 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The results were dramatic: a one-third jump _ from 3.9 percent
to 5.2 percent _ in patients who survived the attack and eventually
were discharged from the hospital. That translates into 21 lives
saved each year in the 19 participating cities.
</P>
<P>
   And if it works well with the 8-minute limit, it probably would
work even better if the response time could be cut to 6 minutes or
less, said Stiell: ``We could probably double the survival rate if
we could get defibrillators to the scene that quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   The second study looked at a second way to raise the odds for
heart attack victims: giving them cardiopulmonary resuscitation for
about 90 seconds before hooking them up to a defibrillator.
Researchers tried the approach on 478 patients in Seattle, which
has pioneered the widespread use of defibrillators.
</P>
<P>
   Again, the results were impressive: a 25 percent jump in
survival.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Washington authors say they aren't sure why
CPR seems to make defibrillation more effective, but they think it
jump-starts the flow of blood to the heart, the brain, or both.
They note that it works primarily in cases where there is a delay
of 7 or 8 minutes before the victim is hooked to the defibrillator,
and that while they used 90 seconds of CPR, future studies may show
more time _ or less _ works better.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, the result ``really is quite
revolutionary,'' said Dr. Peter Stone, chairman of the CPR
Committee at Brigham and Women's Hospital in Boston. ``I think we
will start doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Training the public to do CPR will be a substantially tougher
task, as will be getting defibrillators out to all the
emergency-response personnel who don't have them.
</P>
<P>
   Training enough members of the public in CPR to have someone on
hand to help anytime someone else suffers a heart attack, is ``a
massive public health challenge,'' said Stone. ``The CPR done in
the study by Cobb was done by experienced personnel using
ventilatory equipment as well as chest compressors. That's much
harder for the general population to provide.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the absence of that equipment mouth-to-mouth resuscitation
is the only thing possible, and it's potentially more difficult.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
