<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8082 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CELLTOWERS-COX     04-06 1545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELLTOWERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The powers of the towers: Changing the world of communication
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ They are the earthbound hardware that makes the
wireless magic happen. But they are also expensive and ugly _
unless properly disguised. They are the cell phone towers.
</P>
<P>
   Around metro Atlanta, about 1,200 towers are scattered in a
variety of trappings, most obvious but many concealed or
camouflaged. Some are designed to look like pine trees, billboards
or utility poles, and others are hidden inside church steeples.
Hundreds more just look like the stark, metallic eyesores they are.
</P>
<P>
   For years, resistance by some neighborhoods to installation of a
tower has paralleled the growing urge to use cell phones _ often in
the same neighborhoods. Areas of Atlanta's Buckhead neighborhood,
for example, are rife with cell phone users and also a lousy place
to get a connection. Increasingly, there has been both a
proliferation of cell phone towers and a greater effort to mask
their appearance.
</P>
<P>
   But when the nation's nearly 70 million wireless phone users hit
the talk button on their mobile phones, completion of the calls
depends on being close enough to one of those cell sites. If the
range is right, they are linked to a cell site on some tower, and
the signal passed along via wire or by another wireless signal and
the call is connected.
</P>
<P>
   Close enough can mean three to six miles _ or somewhat farther
away if you are driving relatively flat stretches of an interstate
highway. And if you are stuck in traffic, punching your phone pad
along with others alongside you, be warned that a typical cell site
can handle only about 50 or 60 calls at once. But a tower can hold
many cell sites from different companies.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, one of the nation's top five wireless cities with at
least one cell phone for every three people, the towers get a lot
of use. Most people, including many wireless customers, probably
give the towers no thought _ unless there is a plan to put one in
the neighborhood. Some people don't even realize that towers are
carrying the signals, believing instead their words are bouncing
off satellites high above the earth.
</P>
<P>
   But the increasingly ubiquitous wireless phone depends on
transmitters much closer to the ground. And the ownership of the
towers themselves is a business, like owning the wires that carry
land-line calls.
</P>
<P>
   Like the wires that carry local calls, most cell towers were
first built and owned by the company selling the service to the
consumer. In Atlanta, the only two wireless competitors for more
than a decade were BellSouth and AirTouch Communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the early going, you wanted the best possible location
because there were only two of us,'' said Jeff Battcher, BellSouth
spokesman. ``It was a competitive, strategic issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The field has since grown more crowded, and tower dynamics have
shifted.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the Federal Communications Commission has been
auctioning off more wireless licenses using new parts of the
spectrum. Now, Atlanta has seven providers: the originals plus
Powertel, AT&AMP;T, Sprint, Nextel and Southern LINC.
</P>
<P>
   That has changed the business of towers.
</P>
<P>
   It took more than a century for phone lines to start carrying
calls for rival companies, and it still happens only on a fraction
of calls. By contrast, the cellular industry is barely two decades
old and the towers are increasingly being shared by competitors.
Find a tower in a place where lots of people use cellular phones
and chances are, it will hold transmission equipment from several
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Maintaining a tower costs money, but by leasing out space to
various wireless providers, the owner can often reap far more in
revenue. The average wireless company pays between $1,200 and
$1,800 a month to lease space on another company's cell tower.
Those leases can add up.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, a cell site in Pittsburgh owned by Crown Castle
International reportedly has more than 100 different companies and
agencies leasing space. The result is well over $1 million per
month in revenue for just one tower.
</P>
<P>
   But even a more modest setting, where a tower holds, say five
sites, means income of $6,000 to $9,000 a month. Maintenance of a
cell tower can be minimal: cut the lawn, paint the tower, change
the lights. ... The chance to make a killing seems clear _ so why
would companies be selling their towers?
</P>
<P>
   And selling them they are _ for some big money.
</P>
<P>
   In December, Houston-based Crown Castle bought 1,400 Bell
Atlantic towers for $610 million. Two months later, Nextel sold
about 2,000 towers to SpectraSite for $560 million in cash and 17
percent ownership of the company (ownership of SpectraSite, that
is.) In March, BellSouth sold 1,850 of its towers to Crown Castle.
Only days later, West Point-based Powertel sold 650 towers for $275
million, also to Crown Castle.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those deals call for the tower company to build hundreds
or even thousands of additional towers for the carrier. For the
cellular customer, the transaction will be invisible. Calls go
through as usual. The phone companies will keep their cell sites on
the towers, but will lease space back from the tower company.
</P>
<P>
   Powertel will pay $1,800 a month for use of each tower it has
sold to Crown Castle. Nextel will pay $1,600 a month to
SpectraSite. BellSouth will pay Crown Castle $1,200 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Spokespersons for Crown Castle in Houston and American Tower
Corp. in Boston were unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The industry evidently sees towers as a good investment _ but
not a certainty. Find a good spot, where there is lots of phone
traffic or where it's hard to get permission for a second tower _
and sit back to count a healthy stream of cash from a tower crowded
with competitors' equipment. Yet many towers are a lot lonelier
than that.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth has more than 300 towers in metro Atlanta, and more
than half are home to BellSouth equipment only. So why would Crown
Castle be so eager to buy those towers? The answer seems to be that
a tower company might not be profitable now, but it can get funding
from investors who expect a big payoff. On the other hand, a
cellular company might prefer to have the cash now, especially if
the deal will mean stable, predictable costs.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Lockwood, editor of Wireless Week, said the increasingly
cutthroat competition for wireless customers puts a premium on good
coverage, so many carriers are frantically expanding the
``footprint'' in which they provide service.
</P>
<P>
   That expansion is costly. Construction of a new tower costs an
average of $185,000, Lockwood said. ``I think it's mostly a
financial consideration.''
</P>
<P>
   By that measure, a new carrier's desire to duplicate the towers
in metro Atlanta would cost more than $220 million. As an added
bonus, the leasing strategy lets the carrier avoid costly,
time-consuming fights with neighborhood groups and zoning boards
for the right to erect a new tower.
</P>
<P>
   To meet the surge for wireless demand, a company might build a
tower. But it's quicker and cheaper to co-locate, that is, to put
cell sites on someone else's towers _ assuming there are towers in
the area the company wants to serve.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, a company that already owns towers can see in
them a quick way to pick up cash _ lots of it, Lockwood said.
``It's every important to use whatever cash is available to build
out the system. There is a white-hot competition and coverage is a
very important factor for consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth apparently wanted its money up-front, deciding it was
distracting, expensive and maybe even counterproductive to look for
more revenue by marketing space on its towers to competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is still a business that is very young and speculative,''
said BellSouth's Battcher. ``Why not sell the tower to another
company and let them take the risk?''
</P>
<P>
   Kristin Brinkman, marketing manager for Nextel in Georgia, said
the company made the decision to sell after realizing that its core
business was phones.
</P>
<P>
   Nextel is more interested in building its nationwide business
now rather than trying to find long-term income from leasing space,
she said. ``If we can co-locate _ like any good business would _ we
will be able to reduce costs. It's more cost-effective. Others have
more expertise in regards to towers than we would.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, some companies have tenaciously held their
towers.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint, for example, has more than 2,000 towers and other cell
cites already. The Kansas City, Mo.-based company plans to build
more than 1,000 more, according to Bill D'Agostino, vice president
of Sprint's tower organization.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which is trying to build a nationwide service, is
looking for ways to put its sites on existing towers. When it
builds its own, it is happy to have the added income from rivals
leasing space, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think there is still tremendous upside in remaining in the
tower co-location business. That way we can retain some control
over the assets for Sprint's future use.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-99 1838EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990406.0236 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8083 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHERRYCOKE-GAME-COX     04-06 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHERRYCOKE-GAME-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke hopes to catch teens in web gameBy Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For the second year, Coca-Cola will attempt to build
brand recognition and loyalty with an interactive online game. This
time it is using the Web to market Cherry Coke to teenage soda
drinkers.
</P>
<P>
   The game called ``Time Tremors,'' will officially be available
to consumers Thursday from the Cherry Coke Web site
(www.cherrycoke.com) or MTV's Web site
(www.mtv.com/nav/introtremors.html.)
</P>
<P>
   Master marketer Coca-Cola has always understood the power of the
Web to engage consumers and potential consumers with online games
and contests to keep users logging on and typing Coke URLs over and
over again for the duration of each contest. In the past the
company has used the hot twentysomething TV show ``Friends'' and
the Grammy Awards to promote Diet Coke online. Last year, Cherry
Coke offered up ``The Lost Island of Alanna,'' a Myst-like game
that had players searching for clues on soda bottles and the Web to
navigate their way through the game.
</P>
<P>
   With last year's Alanna, there were a few problems, including
programming bugs and Cherry Coke's hope that Alanna would become
the Web's hottest game simply by word of mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strategy with Alanna was that it was an underground way to
reach kids and tell them about the new Cherry Coke,'' says brand
manager Tim Halloran. However, while the game did have avid
players, it never vaulted into mainstream Web consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Cherry Coke sales slumped slightly last year, according to
Beverage Digest Editor and Publisher John Sicher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cherry Coke is one of the larger small brands,'' says Beverage
Digest's Sicher. ``In 1998 , 64.8 million cases down from 66.8 in
1997. By way of example, Sicher says Diet Coke sold 852 million
cases in 1998. But Halloran still says that ``Alanna'' was a
success. ``It became a much cooler brand in their minds.''
</P>
<P>
   Coke has learned from Alanna, according to promotions manager
Christy Barrineau. One key lesson was is that in the Web's
hyper-competitive commercial environment, building a site and
waiting for eager gamers to show up isn't going to make it. This
time Cherry Coke is coming out of the blocks with traditional
marketing firepower, including print ads in gaming magazines,
banner ads on popular online gaming sites such as SonyOnline, and a
huge advertisement on MTV's Web site. Then of course, there are the
bottles themselves which tout the game. The more bottle caps users
collect, the more time they'll have to play the game.
</P>
<P>
   While it is possible to play Time Tremors without ever buying or
even looking at a bottle of CherryCoke, you won't be able to
complete the game without buying at least one bottle of the soft
drink. Halloran says that lots of research with its 13-18 year old
demographic revealed that kids don't mind having to buy cola to
finish the game. ``They said they were going to be drinking soda
anyway, so it might as well be Cherry Coke,'' Halloran says.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we learned from last year, is that you are reinventing
the wheel to get teens to your site when you are a packaged goods
company. We decided to go to places on the Web where teens already
are. With MTV, we found we had some great opportunities,'' she
says. ``They will let users download Time Tremors from their site
and they are also giving us some great promotion. They are offering
game players the opportunity to share hints and tips.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Time Tremors'' is a role playing game where players choose a
character, male or female, and head off on a field trip only to
wind up in time capsule travelling though more than 100 different
worlds trying to keep the space-time continuum from being altered
forever. Each player will have a different gaming experience, which
is also part of Cherry Coke's master plan to associate the soda
with the idea of being creative and different.
</P>
<P>
   Internet analysts and pundits can literally talk for days about
the need for marketers to get customers involved with the brand.
There are a few companies on the Web who understand how to do this,
such as Land's End with it's interactive ``paper dolls'' that let
users try on its apparel; CoverGirl, which let's users experiment
with make up shades on various models, and Coca-Cola which uses the
Web expertly to help users connect with the brand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to get kids to experience being creative and being
different and what we really have seen is that it builds up the
brand in the minds of the people who play the game,'' Halloran
says. ``It's not like showing them a TV ad or talking to them on a
radio ad. We have kids interacting with our brand for two or three
hours at a time,'' he says. ``If you provide teens with an exciting
online experience, they'll think more highly and much more
positively about the brand.''
</P>
<P>
   We're not just putting up an electronic billboard that says buy
our stuff,'' Barrineau, ``We are giving them an experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
