</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORVALDS-QA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q and A with inventor Linus TorvaldsBy Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Linus Torvalds, is the inventor of the Linux computer
operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Never heard of Linux? Well, don't worry, Microsoft has. Linux,
long a favorite of business users and advanced computer hobbyists,
is becoming a realistic worry for Microsoft. Many consider the
system to be more stable than Windows and less demanding of
hardware.
</P>
<P>
   Torvalds, 29, will speak to the AIIM International trade group
April 12-15 at the Georgia World Congress Center.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are you going to say next week?
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't tend to prepare my talks very much in advance. It's
going to be a fairly regular Linux talk. I will tell them what is
important is networking and stability _ that is fairly important if
you expect to retain your documents.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where do you see Linux getting used now?
</P>
<P>
   A: At the extreme high-end. There are some people on desktops
who use Linux but only in certain environments. Like for a really
large database. Linux doesn't tend to scale to the 64 CPU mXXXX
that some people are using.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who shouldn't be using Linux?
</P>
<P>
   A: When the main use of a machine is Windows applications, it's
probably better to use a Windows operating system, however painful
that is to me.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are we going to see Linux retooled for desktops, where most
computer users are and where Microsoft Windows really dominates?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's certainly a goal to make it accessible to a real Windows
user. I think that is two or three years away from it being a real
alternative. For your average technophobe ... maybe it's two or
three years away.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is this what you expected for Linux when you designed it?
</P>
<P>
   A: None of it was quite as I expected. It started as a program
for my own use. I was blown away by how many people there were with
similar needs. It certainly has grown faster than I thought it
would. I have been doing this for eight years. The last six months
have not been that surprising because I was already starting to see
what was happening. It was obvious to me that there were a lot of
companies that wanted Linux, but were held back by worries about
its market acceptance. A lot have been held back by nervousness
about the lack of applications. The next hurdle is when the
application houses start jumping in.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why do people use Linux?
</P>
<P>
   A: Different people have different reasons ... The technology
appeals to many .... Like scientists or artists, who aren't out for
dollars. They are out for the appreciation of their peers. There
are moral issues, too. The ability to have a user customize his
system by giving him the power to do what he wants to do, by giving
him the source code....
</P>
<P>
   The lesson is that this is really is a powerful way of doing
development. The Internet allows the kind of connections that
people haven't had access to before.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Since the system code is on the Net, since it is given away,
what is in it for you?
</P>
<P>
   A: My satisfaction is basically doing something and something
well. The act of doing Linux is immensely satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are you doing now? Where do you work?
</P>
<P>
   A: The company I work for is extremeley secretive. We are in
Santa Clara, and all I can say is that the office line is Transmeta
does cool stuff.
</P>
<P>
   I like my work and I want to do my work in my spare time too. I
do Linux as a hobby but some people think that means it is not
important. They don't get the message.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How old are you?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm 29.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you mind being called a visionary?
</P>
<P>
   A: I am not the kind of visionary who wants to have his message
out to the masses. The difference between a visionary and a person
with strong ideals is that a visionary tries two impose his ideals
and persuade others. The proof is in the doing, and I am happy
talking about it, but I don't want to preach.
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
