A8086 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-GEORGIA-COX     04-06 0388
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-GEORGIA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Threat of job losses has Y2K workers on alert
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia Governor Roy Barnes recalled for an audience
Rotarians how he told his department heads earlier this year that
anyone who missed the year-end deadline in fixing the millennium
bug would be fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our compliance has gone way up since then,'' said Barnes, who
was addressing a meeting of the Atlanta Rotary earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said he felt compelled to make his ultimatum because the
state had been lagging behind others in upgrading its vast computer
systems to recognize any dates beyond Dec. 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Georgia technology was antiquated and we had to throw a bunch
of it away,'' said Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   That fact was highlighted in a recent survey conducted by CIO, a
magazine that caters to government and corporate chief information
officers. The magazine's survey found that only 36 percent of the
state's computer systems and software had been made Y2K compliant
as of Dec. 31, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Worse yet, the state had already spent $152 million to fix the
problem, according to CIO. Another $170 million has since been
allocated to Y2K, bringing total allocated expenditures for the
problem to $322 million.
</P>
<P>
   In comparison, said CIO magazine, Nebraska has ``virtually''
fixed its state computers and spent only $21 million to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia state officials criticized CIO's survey on Tuesday.
``Its out of date,'' said Ted Fisher, a consultant who is secretary
of the Governor's Y2K Task Force.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher added that, as of the committee's last meeting on March
5, Y2K compliance at state agencies had jumped to 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say we were ahead of the pack now,'' said Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   Y2k is a potentially serious problem for state governments,
which have computerized many operations. For example, most, if not
all government disbursements such as monthly welfare checks are
computerized. Also computerized are things such as child abuse
reports.
</P>
<P>
   An uncompliant social service system might, for example, fail to
recognize a report on a child abuse incident after Jan.1 , 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Haddad writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
