u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-TYCOON-BOS &LR;      04-06 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-TYCOON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYCOON LINKED TO YELTSIN SOUGHT BY PROSECUTORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted as Russia-Roundup)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Prosecutors Tuesday ordered the arrest of an
influential Russian tycoon with close links to President Boris N.
Yeltsin, turning up the pressure on the embattled Kremlin leader a
week before he faces an impeachment vote in parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The warrant went out for Boris Berezovsky, a longtime confidant
of Yeltsin's family, whose reputed influence over Kremlin policy in
recent years has been outdone only by the alleged worth of his
shadowy business holdings.
</P>
<P>
   One of the seven so-called ``oligarchs'' who backed Yeltsin's
reelection campaign in 1996 and later claimed to control half of
Russia's economy, Berezovsky came to epitomize the New Russian
business magnates who have parlayed Kremlin ties and easy access to
state property into huge industrial, oil and media empires.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators suspect Berezovsky of setting up a Swiss company
to hide the hard currency earnings of Aeroflot, Russia's
state-owned airline. Aeroflot is one of several prominent Russian
companies in which Berezovsky, once believed to be one of the
world's most wealthy men, reportedly has a stake.
</P>
<P>
   The move against Berezovsky comes during a murky power struggle
among Moscow's political elite that has distracted attention in
Russia from Moscow's diplomatic efforts to halt NATO's airstrikes
against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest order also comes as a corruption probe backed by
Yeltsin's Communist foes in parliament has implicated members of
his family and inner circle in alleged misuse of state funds.
Yeltsin, meanwhile, has been trying to fire Russia's Prosecutor
General Yury Skuratov, who launched the investigations.
</P>
<P>
   It is a murky tale with no heroes. Skuratov, who had served
Yeltsin loyally since 1995 before turning against him this year,
has been criticized for sitting on evidence that was available four
years ago. Yeltsin has been accused of trying to shut down
legitimate corruption investigations. Yeltsin's opponents in
parliament have been criticized for pushing their impeachment case
at a time when Moscow has been trying to show unity over Kosovo.
And Berezovsky is one of Russia's least popular figures.
</P>
<P>
   In a flurry of activity Tuesday, Skuratov tendered his
resignation as federal prosecutors issued an arrest warrant for the
commercial director of Aeroflot, Berezvovsky associate Nikolai
Gluzhkov.
</P>
<P>
   A warrant was also issued for another ``oligarch'' and former
backer of Yeltsin's 1996 campaign, banker Alexander Smolensky, on
charges related to a seven-year-old embezzlement case.
</P>
<P>
   Berezovsky has been in France since he was removed last week
from his job as secretary of the loose alliance of Russia and 11
other former Soviet republics, a position that carried immunity
from prosecution. Tuesday, he said the charges against him were
trumped up by the prosecutor's Communist ``soul mates'' in
parliament, and he told the Russian news agency Interfax his
enemies ``don't have a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   But like his fellow ``oligarchs,'' Berezovsky's once-legendary
power has diminished significantly since last August's financial
collapse.
</P>
<P>
   His empire, built largely on his connections with Yeltsin's
family, has been losing a struggle with the increasingly powerful
prime minister, Yevgeny M. Primakov. In February, police raided the
offices of Aeroflot and other companies Berezovsky allegedly
controls.
</P>
<P>
   Last month parliament slapped down Yeltsin's request to have
Skuratov removed. It was a humiliating defeat made all the more
embarassing when a sex video starring someone who resembled
Skuratov was shown on state television in what looked like a clumsy
and sleazy Kremlin effort to remove the prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a Moscow city prosecutor opened a criminal case
against Skuratov, charging that he had given favors to a
businessman who paid for his sessions with prostitutes. The Kremlin
said the evidence came from one of the women in the sex video;
Yeltsin's critics charged that the case was fabricated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
