A8100 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETBANK-SIDE-COX     04-06 0422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETBANK-SIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Net.Bank system user-friendly, competitive
 &HT;    (EDS: Sidebar to main NETBANK story.)
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Higher interest rates on money market and CD accounts
are driving the popularity of Internet banking.
</P>
<P>
   ``The virtual banks have been most competitive on those deposit
rates,'' said Brian J. O'Connor, managing editor of Bank Rate
Monitor, a Florida-based surveyor of banking services and fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not paying for services you don't need,'' O'Connor
said, `` and they're passing the savings along to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's Net.Bank has remained prominent in that competition.
For example, it offers a six-month certificate of deposit paying
5.25 percent, according to Bank Rate Monitor's figures. The
national average was 4.25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Net.Bank's yield on money market accounts _ 5.13 percent _ is
``as much as some longer-term CDs,'' O'Connor said.
</P>
<P>
   The competition is becoming increasingly stiff, he added. Scores
of banks, savings and loans and credit unions offer online
services. They range from the big national banks, such as First
Union and Citibank, to smaller local ones.
</P>
<P>
   Customers typically set up an account at the online bank's Web
page. Deposits can be made through the mail or electronically, by
direct deposit.
</P>
<P>
   They can get to their accounts _ to pay bills and conduct other
business _ from any computer with an Internet connection.
</P>
<P>
   To get actual cash, the account holder usually visits an ATM
operated by a regular bank.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the higher rates, Bank Rate Monitor listed other
advantages of online banking:
</P>
<P>
   _ Access to accounts any hour of the day or night.
</P>
<P>
   _ And nearly instantaneous execution of the customer's
transactions.
</P>
<P>
   But there are also disadvantages:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The big disadvantage is that the things you want to do in
the lobby are not going to happen,'' said O'Connor. That includes
buying travelers checks or money orders.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you get cash from another bank's ATM, you will probably
have to pay that bank a fee of $1.50 or $2.
</P>
<P>
   _ You may have to put in considerable time entering data to set
up an account via a computer.
</P>
<P>
   _ If the computer is down, so is access to your account.
</P>
<P>
   For extensive information about on-line banking, check out Bank
Rate Monitor at http://www.bankrate.com/brm/rate/ebankhome.asp.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Ezell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
