<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-LEONSIS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Information conference to address Net topics
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Association for Information and Image Management
(AIIM) International comes to Atlanta's World Congress Center April
12-15 for its annual conference and trade show for people in the
information management community.
</P>
<P>
   The conference will address a variety of topics including
Knowledge Management, XML, Linux, workflow on the Web, enterprise
document management and electronic commerce. Ted Leonsis, president
of AOL Interactive Properties, will be the keynote speaker for the
conference. In a recent interview, he shared some of his thoughts
on AOL and electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has the Internet changed consumers' habits?
</P>
<P>
   A: Defintely. The Internet has moved past being just a media
phenomenon. It's moved beyond just a way to get information or
entertainment to becoming a part of people's lives.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What do you think has contributed to the Net's becoming so
important to consumers in such a relatively short time span?
</P>
<P>
   A: People are doing things online better and faster than they
could offline. Besides gathering information and socializing, they
are also shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the key to turning AOL users or Web users in general
from online browsers to online buyers?
</P>
<P>
   A: We are very selective about how we recruit (e-commerce)
partners because standards are higher on the Internet than they are
offline. You have to have a service that is easy to use. From the
marketing side, you have to make the first impression count _ you
really have to work at it.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers come to an e-commerce site thinking they should be
getting things faster, cheaper and better because they are getting
them from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So what do you do to make the online shopping experience more
enjoyable?
</P>
<P>
   A: We've always believed in making areas ``stickier'' _ we say
to our partners, `Don't think you are just in the sales business.
You have to develop a relationship with the customer.'
</P>
<P>
   For example, this past weekend, I happened to be down in Florida
with my family and we were down by the pool and this great song
came on the radio by this great band called Sugar Ray. Later that
afternoon, I'm checking e-mail and my son says can we buy that CD,
and I'm a member of CDNow and I ordered it. A few seconds later I
got the e-mail saying my order was received and it told us about
another CD by Sugar Ray. So we listened to the Real Audio samples
and we liked that, too, and we bought it.
</P>
<P>
   Here I was able to buy the product right away. I didn't leave my
house and CDNow sold two CDs. I'm a happy consumer.
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
