<HEADER>
A8109 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-GREENJACKET-COX     04-06 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GREENJACKET-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A year after Masters win, O'Meara's life is good
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _He doesn't come to Augusta National this week as
the player everyone is buzzing about, but it won't bother Mark
O'Meara. After all, even in the last hour of last year's Masters,
before the 20-footer that fell to change his life, people lining
the fairways still were thinking more about Fred Couples or David
Duval.
</P>
<P>
   Mark O'Meara likes it that way. Forget about the old man, the
guy with the silver in his temples, and he just might putt you into
the ground.
</P>
<P>
   David Duval has the planet in an overlapping grip with 11 wins
in 34 tries. He is the prohibitive Masters favorite and might be
similarly installed all summer.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Meara has the Masters trophy, a Claret Jug and the new
house in Orlando disguised as a Ritz-Carlton. As Duval concedes,
all the BellSouth Classics and Michelob Championships in history
would not compare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life,'' O'Meara said, ``is pretty darn good.''
</P>
<P>
   The 20-footer, of course, changed everything. One minute O'Meara
is the King of Pebble Beach, a master of the corporate outing and a
top-five man on the career money list. A few seconds later at the
18th green, the ball is tracking toward its target, breaking to the
left just as he figured.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the 41-year-old O'Meara is nervous. Watching video
tapes since then, he said, ``I look at my face, and I don't look
nervous, but I knew how I felt inside.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara takes a few deep breaths and tells himself, `Hey, this
is what we play for. How many guys would die for one putt to win
the Masters? Why not close the deal right there?' ''
</P>
<P>
   With the ball two-and-a-half feet off the putter, O'Meara tells
himself, `Man, I hit a good putt.'' With it three feet from the
hole, as necks start to stretch along the ropes at 18, O'Meara's
heart begins to hammer in his chest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Geez,'' he thinks, ``it's going to go in.''
</P>
<P>
   As it was six inches away, O'Meara finds himself thinking,
``Please don't lip out.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't. Just barely. O'Meara's arms shot up as though
signaling a last-second field goal. Chest out, he is stunned,
staggered and very proud all at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   And now here is today, a little sad that his year is up to keep
the green jacket in his closet but excited to settle his spikes in
the rye grass as defending champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, I want to play well, but at last I've experienced that
one time, no matter what happens in the future,'' he said. ``I know
that at least one time I put on that coveted green jacket. If I
don't play well, I'll be disappointed, but I'm not going to let it
spoil all the great things that have happened to me over this past
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Monday, speaking with reporters for the first time as the
official on-site defender, he said, ``It gives you goose bumps even
with 80-degree weather.''
</P>
<P>
   You might find a soul or two of the opinion that Mark O'Meara
applies the corporate-speak a bit heavily. However, you can't find
anyone who didn't feel good for O'Meara, sometimes forgotten as a
former U.S. Amateur champion _ 1979, when he beat John Cook _ who
found a Masters and a British Open in the same year and then became
player of the year. Even Duval and Fred Couples, who were passed by
the Californian when he birdied three of the last four holes at the
1998 Masters.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara has loved the basking period. He brought the trophies to
the PGA Merchandise Show in Orlando in January and allowed fans to
pose with them. Close to many of the Orlando-based Golf Channel
personalities, he co-hosted the network's Golf Central show last
year. He played a brisk worldwide schedule, adding England's
prestigious World Match Play championship to his season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not perfect, by no means,'' O'Meara said. ``I probably
played as much or more world-wide golf over the last 18 years as
anybody has. Unfortunately, I've probably sacrificed more on being
a father and home life because I've been so competitive. . . . You
do pay a toll.''
</P>
<P>
   Before O'Meara, only two players, Arnold Palmer and Sandy Lyle,
had birdied the last hole to win the Masters. O'Meara used to watch
old Masters replays on TV and ponder how pressure-packed that would
be, standing over a putt, for so much. Ian Woosnam's 8-footer in
1991, for example.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, it's funny,'' he said. ``I used to think, `How could
anybody drum up enough courage to make that putt?' I wondered what
it would be like to make that putt. I wonder if I could do that.'''
If buddy Tiger Woods has learned from O'Meara about common sense on
the PGA Tour and course management, the old man has fed off the
kid's enormous energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Tiger definitely deserves some of the credit,''
O'Meara said. ``I think he's had an influence on my game. We
compete a lot together at home, and he's definitely pushed me.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods is envious of the player whose game he helped to raise _
and not only of O'Meara's consistently sound putting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the way he shallows out his plane in his golf swing,''
Woods said. ``He's got a very shallow arc through the ball, and
that's something I've always worked on. That's one reason why he
controls his distances so well.''
</P>
<P>
   Well enough to contend again? The serious betting money this
week has to go on Duval and Woods. Some will filter to Fred
Couples, Davis Love III and Ernie Els. There might not be a
groundswell of repeat support.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's fine,'' the champion said. ``The game doesn't owe me
anything.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Sheeley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
