<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAVIDIANS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRANCH DAVIDIANS SEEK REDUCTIONS IN SENTENCES &HT;    
 &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By THADDEUS HERRICK 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ In an attempt to win a shorter sentence for
followers of David Koresh, lawyers Tuesday argued once again that
five Branch Davidians neither used nor carried automatic weapons in
a deadly 1993 shootout with federal agents.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the five cult members are serving 40-year sentences _ 10
years for manslaughter and another 30 years tacked on by Judge
Walter Smith when he ruled that the Davidians wielded machine guns
in the firefight rather than basic firearms. The judge gave the
fifth defendant a 10-year sentence on the use of an automatic
weapon.
</P>
<P>
   But lawyers for the cult members say evidence is scant that the
five employed automatic weapons. More importantly, they say, the
five should have been formally charged with the weapons violation
and Smith should have left the decision to the jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel the judge does not have the decision-making power,''
said Steven Rocket Rosen, a Houston lawyer representing one of the
five. ``The jury does.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers appealed the decision in 1996, two years after 11 Branch
Davidians were tried in San Antonio. In that case, all 11 were
acquitted of conspiracy and murder but eight were convicted on
lesser charges.
</P>
<P>
   Of those, six appealed, and upon hearing their arguments the 5th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in New Orleans asked Judge Smith to
reconsider whether the cult members used automatic weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Smith ruled that they had, at which point lawyers for five cult
members appealed the decision yet again, bringing them Tuesday to
San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the difference between dying in federal prison or
getting out and having a little time to live,'' said Richard
Ferguson, one of the lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers say a recent decision by the U.S. Supreme Court
bolsters their case. That case involved a carjacking in which a
judge tacked on 25 years to the defendant's 15-year sentence
because the incident resulted in serious bodily injury.
</P>
<P>
   But the high court said the bodily injury decision should have
been made by the jury, not the judge.
</P>
<P>
   Four agents of the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms were
killed in a gun battle at the Branch Davidians' fortified compound
near Waco on Feb. 28, 1993. The agents had sought to arrest Koresh
on weapons charges.
</P>
<P>
   Six followers of Koresh were killed in the fight, which led to a
stalemate that lasted 51 days before fire engulfed the compound,
killing Koresh and 78 others.
</P>
<P>
   Those appealing their cases Tuesday were Renos Avraam, Brad
Branch, Jaime Castillo, Graeme Craddock and Kevin Whitecliff.
</P>
</TEXT>
