<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-OWNERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    League will say no to Redskins deal
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Never in league history have NFL owners vetoed a bid
to purchase an existing franchise. Barring an upset, that unusual
streak will end today when the owners, convening here at an
airport-area hotel, will reject the $800 million proposal from the
group headed by Howard Milstein to buy the Washington Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding the vote of the Redskins, who are legally bound to
support Milstein's efforts, he needs 23 endorsements and appears to
be well short of that number. Despite providing Milstein an extra
three weeks to address problem areas, owners apparently will arrive
here with many of the same concerns they voiced last month at the
league meetings in Phoenix, where the league's finance committeewas
split on the bid.
</P>
<P>
   The committee will huddle again this morning before the general
session. In Phoenix, three members of the committee favored
Milstein, three opposed him, and two others were undecided. Most
owners thought the proposal, which would represent the record price
for a professional sports franchise, is too heavily leveraged.
Several owners also have been critical of the way in which Milstein
has operated the NHL's New York Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   If the bid is rejected, the league probably would ask the
trustees operating the franchise to reopen the process. John Kent
Cooke, son of late owner Jack Kent Cooke, would then continue to
run the team until he or another buyer is selected. Milstein has
not given any indication that he would sue under those
circumstances, but it is a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   He was in New York on Monday to meet with NFL officials and has
told friends that he thinks he has sufficient votes for approval.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly: The Steelers signed unrestricted free-agent offensive
tackle Wayne Gandy, a five-year veteran and starter his entire
career with the Rams, to a four-year contract worth $14 million. .
. . Heisman winner Ricky Williams had an unspectacular workout for
league scouts Tuesday in San Diego, clocking in the low 4.6s
against the wind and low 4.5s with the wind. . . . Former Georgia
defensive end Phillip Daniels, a restricted free agent with
Seattle, re-signed for the one-year tender of $429,000.
</P>
<P>
   Len Pasquarelli writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
