<HEADLINE>
CLASSICS JOINING TNT'S MOVIES  
 VH-1, POPULAR PROMOTIONAL VEHICLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Looking to raise the prestige ante in a continuing challenge to
HBO for supremacy in made-for-cable television movies, TNT, the
main entertainment channel of the Turner Broadcasting empire,
announced a schedule of movies for the next television season that
is conspicuously heavy on the literary classics.
</P>
<P>
   Among the titles to receive movie adaptations are these:
</P>
<P>
   _ George Orwell's ``Animal Farm,'' a partly animated version
with Patrick Stewart (Napoleon), Peter Ustinov (Old Major), Julia
Louis-Dreyfus (Mollie), Julia Ormond (Jesse) and Kelsey Grammer
(Snowball) providing some of the voices.
</P>
<P>
   _ Charles Dickens' ``Christmas Carol,'' with Stewart again, as
Scrooge, and Joel Grey as the Ghost of Christmas Past.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dickens' ``David Copperfield,'' a four-hour miniseries version
with Sally Field, Anthony Andrews and Michael Richards, in his
first post-Kramer television role, as Micawber.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cervantes' ``Don Quixote,'' with another big-name cast headed
by John Lithgow as Quixote, Bob Hoskins as Sancho Panza, Isabella
Rossellini as the Duchess and Vanessa Williams as Dulcinea.
</P>
<P>
   TNT, which has had a successful track record with westerns, is
also remaking a classic western, ``The Virginian,'' starring Bill
Pullman and Dennis Weaver.
</P>
<P>
   The channel will have some movies from original material,
including a mob movie (the hottest topic in television, it appears)
starring Chazz Palminteri.
</P>
<P>
   William Macy stars in a comedy thriller called ``A Travesty,''
about an amoral film critic whose behavior catches up to him. Glenn
Close is producing a new film about members of a family whose lives
are changed when they find an abandoned infant on their doorstep.
</P>
<P>
   ``David Copperfield,'' ``Don Quixote'' and ``A Christmas Carol''
are all co-productions of the increasingly busy Hallmark
Entertainment production company, which has generated both ratings
and prestige for NBC and CBS in recent television seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Many of next season's projects are intended to produce both
bigger audiences for TNT and bigger prizes for the channel, which
several years ago set out to compete with HBO for things like Emmy
Awards. The efforts paid off in the film ``George Wallace,'' which
did win an Emmy.
</P>
<P>
   The Turner sister channel TBS also announced a slate of movies,
the first time that channel has gone fully into the movie arena.
(This season, it presented its first original movie ever.) The TBS
movies tend to be much more action- and adventure-oriented, with
titles like ``Thrill Seekers'' (about time travel) and ``Sinkhole''
(a colossal sinkhole threatens to swallow New Orleans).
</P>
<P>
   Musical Teamwork
</P>
<P>
   The cable channel VH-1 is becoming a favorite promotional
vehicle for broadcast networks like NBC and ABC. The reason: The
music on VH-1 dovetails perfectly with the mainstream taste that
generates big ratings for network shows.
</P>
<P>
   That was proved twice this season as both an NBC movie, ``The
'60s,'' and an ABC movie, ``And the Beat Goes On: The Sonny and
Cher Story,'' scored hit ratings after being extensively promoted
on VH-1.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday ABC announced the latest deal with VH-1, a
co-promotion of a music-heavy film it has scheduled for May called
``Double Platinum.'' This one may be the biggest success yet in the
growing genre of television movie musicals.
</P>
<P>
   That's because of its star power. The film is headlined by Diana
Ross and Brandy, playing mother and daughter music superstars who
are separated just after the daughter is born and then reunited.
</P>
<P>
   The film, to be shown on May 16, will be extensively promoted on
VH-1 from now until then, with music from the movie, highlights of
the careers of both stars and a clip trailer from the film done in
the style of a music video that will feature a duet composed for
the two stars by a Grammy-winning songwriter, Diane Warren.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Benson, the senior vice president for advertising and
promotion for ABC, said that the network approached VH-1 about the
Sonny and Cher project last year and that ``the results were just
phenomenal.'' VH-1 ran promotions for the film along with
retrospectives of the singers' careers before its broadcast. It was
one of the highest-rated films of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Benson said, ``This movie is even more a natural for VH-1.''
Among the reasons he cited were that Ms. Ross is an even bigger
music icon than Sonny and Cher and that Brandy is such a star for
VH-1 that she is being included in that channel's second annual
``Divas Live'' special on April 13.
</P>
<P>
   Brandy, of course, was also the star of ABC's ``Cinderella''
movie last season, the highest-rated movie of the year. She has a
successful album out now on the Atlantic label, with four songs she
will sing in the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ross will release her own new album on the Motown label in
conjunction with the movie. It too has four songs from the movie.
(The stars' duet will appear only in the film; it is not on either
album)
</P>
<P>
   Benson said both record labels would also be extensively
promoting the movie.
</P>
<P>
   But what does VH-1 get out of all of this? It gets what it most
wants: the movie. VH-1 is doing all this promotion in exchange for
rerun rights to ``Double Platinum.'' After ABC's run in May, the
film will become the property of VH-1 for a window of runs in
December. The channel already has the right to rerun the Sonny and
Cher movie in August.
</P>
<P>
   John Sykes, the president of VH-1, said: ``We don't mind driving
our viewers to a network like ABC for one night if we can reward
them with a movie they'd like to see several times. The networks
are in the premiere business. We're in the cumulative audience
business.''
</P>
<P>
   He said VH-1 was now talking to several networks about future
projects, ``in which we would get involved on the creative end.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
