<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service is moving the following
arts/entertainment and travel stories this week for release on
Sunday, April 11.
</P>
<P>
   _ ARTS &AMP; ENTERTAINMENT (Moving in `e' category)
</P>
<P>
   _ Special package on the Berlin cultural scene
</P>
<P>
   BERLIN-WALKING (Berlin) _ It's safe to go walking again in
Berlin. It was here, in the early 20th century, that the practice
of strolling leisurely around a big city just to take in the sights
came into its own as a modern art form. By Herbert Muschamp.
</P>
<P>
   BERLIN-IDENTITY (Berlin) _ A phoenix rises on the rubble of
history. This is the sixth German state that Berlin will be the
capital of, following the Prussian, imperial, Weimar, Nazi, and
communist periods. Some of its identity will be new, some of it
will reflect the past. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   BERLIN-CULTURE (Berlin) _ Reunified Berlin is bursting at the
seams with music, opera and theater. As a condition of German
reunification in 1990, the West was obliged to preserve the
cultural institutions of the East. By Anne Midgette.
</P>
<P>
   BERLIN-SUBCULTURE (Berlin) _ The `Cabaret' days are gone; now
it's shades of gray. Berlin's artistic and musical underground
still exists, but it's not quite as interesting as one might hope.
By Ed Ward.
</P>
<P>
   BERLIN-REDEVELOP (Berlin) _ Building a capital where triumph is
taboo: Berlin steps cautiously amid the bogs of provincialism and
the quicksand of memory. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   BERLIN-ARCHITECTURE (Berlin) _ Expressing government power
without pomposity: a look at design challenges in the new Berlin.
By Michael Z. Wise.
</P>
<P>
   BERLIN-VOICES _ A sampling of opinion about the city's future as
a cultural capital.
</P>
<P>
   _ Film
</P>
<P>
   HITCHCOCK-FILM (New York) _ Perhaps the most famous film
director in history, Alfred Hitchcock remains synonymous with
suspense and an entire film genre. The Museum of Modern Art is
about to begin a Hitchcock centennial retrospective. By Peter
Bogdanovich.
</P>
<P>
   SLEEPY-HOLLOW-FILM (London) _ It may seem odd to find a movie
version of `Sleepy Hollow' shooting not in New York's Hudson Valley
but in the counties around London. That's where director Tim Burton
and stars Johnny Depp and Christina Ricci are, as Burton creates
another of the singular and self-enclosed worlds for which he is
known. By Matt Wolf.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-FILM (Istanbul) _ Turkey, relenting, shows the works of a
Kurdish nationalist. Probably no Turkish film has had the worldwide
impact of Yilmaz Guney's `Yol,' a harrowing look at what is
portrayed as a land of harsh military rule and feudal codes. By
Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   GORDON-SOUNDTRACK (London) _ In art, too, the sound is spooky:
video artist Michael Gordon has separated the soundtrack music of
Hitchcock's `Vertigo' from the movie and then brought them together
again in unexpected ways. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   _ Theater
</P>
<P>
   WAR-KIDS-THEATER (New York) _ Yolanda King, daughter of the Rev.
Martin Luther King Jr., will share the stage with five actors in
the world premiere of a multimedia production, `The Road Home:
Stories of Children of War.' It dramatizes interviews with
survivors of war and social conflicts from Bosnia and Cambodia to
America's inner cities. By Randy Gener.
</P>
<P>
   CANBY-THEATER (New York) _ British playwright David Hare is
making his debut as a professional actor playing himself in his own
play, `Via Dolorosa,' at the Booth Theater. By Vincent Canby.
</P>
<P>
   GUARE-THEATER (New York) _ Zero degrees of separation: In the
world according to playwright John Guare, the more things change,
