<HEADER>
A8124 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-SHAMAN-AZR &LR;      04-06 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-SHAMAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MYSTERY WRAPPED IN MYSTICISM  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
Shaman Winter 
Rudolfo Anaya (Warner, $24) 
 
 By GRACIELA SEVILLA  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pick up the reading list for any college Chicano literature
class and Rudolfo Anaya's ``Bless Me, Ultima'' is certain to be on
it.
</P>
<P>
   With the penning of the now-classic story, Anaya earned the
mantle of guru among Chicano authors. A native of New Mexico, he
has a love and feel for Southwestern folklore that comes through in
his writing. For his novel ``Albuquerque,'' he won the PEN Center
USA West Award for Fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he jumps headlong into mysticism and magic with his latest
book, ``Shaman Winter.'' The publisher is promoting the book as a
mystery novel, but that plain-vanilla label is like describing
``The X-Files'' as a detective show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaman Winter'' is more of a mystical fantasy built around the
adventures and dreamworld of Sonny Baca, a private investigator
with roots in the barrio. With elements of time travel, sorcery and
confrontation between good and evil, it does not resemble a mystery
as much as science fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Baca is a likable character who laces his conversations with
plenty of Spanglish. When the book opens, he is in a wheelchair,
recovering after a fight with the villain, Raven, who is bent on
destroying Baca.
</P>
<P>
   While convalescing, Baca begins reading New Mexico history and
having vivid dreams about his ancestors' 16th century journey from
Mexico across the Rio Grande.
</P>
<P>
   In conversations with a kindly old shaman, Don Eliseo, Baca
begins to learn how to interpret his dreams and harness spiritual
powers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A dream is a way to enter the world of the spirits,'' Don
Eliseo tells him. ``It is also a way to enter history. If you want
to return to a place and a time in which your ancestors lived, you
must dream about that place.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the book, Anaya lays out Southwestern history,
complete with names, dates and battles that add texture to the
story. There are cameo appearances by such historical figures as
Pancho Villa and Kit Carson. However, Baca's dreamworld and reality
soon become intertwined in a heavily embroidered story.
</P>
<P>
   Young women begin to disappear in Sonny Baca's dreams and in his
waking hours. When four black feathers are found at each of the
scenes, Baca realizes that his nemesis, Raven, is behind the
kidnappings and is haunting his reality as well as his dreams.
</P>
<P>
   With help from Don Eliseo, Baca figures out that the women
disappearing from his historical dreams are Baca's ancestors and
that Raven can destroy him by erasing his history.
</P>
<P>
   To fight Raven and preserve his family line, Baca must learn to
enter the spiritual realm and control his dreams, Don Eliseo tells
him.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that Baca and Raven, the Bringer of Curses, are
ancient enemies who've battled it out through the centuries. This
classic theme of the struggle between good and evil lends itself to
Anaya's use of Latin-style magical realism in the storytelling.
However, the author can't resist the temptation to heap on plot
decorations, and here he slips into the realm of the fantastic.
</P>
<P>
   Raven, it seems, wants more than just to kill Baca. He is also
bent on destroying the world and is building a nuclear bomb. The
FBI calls on Baca to help stop Raven, who is on the loose,
terrorizing New Mexico with a plutonium pit and vials of the ebola
virus.
</P>
<P>
   A tangle of conspiracies, high-speed chases, murders and chaos
unravels at a fast pace to the end of the book. Although some
scenes are entertaining, many smack of overkill and add little to
the story except to muddy the dream sequences.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of fantasy, science fiction or New Age junkies may enjoy
this book. Others who prefer the simpler and poetic narratives of
``Bless Me, Ultima'' may find ``Shaman Winter'' as jumbled and
strange as the visions that sometimes enter our own heads when we
sleep. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
