A8125 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-BRADFORD-AZR &LR;      04-06 0454
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-BRADFORD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANNE PERRY'S DETECTIVES AGAIN ON THE CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
Bedford Square 
Anne Perry (Ballantine, $24.95) 
 
 By SUE DOERFLER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   An Anne Perry novel is a delight to read as much for its
Victorian era details as for the mystery it unfolds.
</P>
<P>
   Perry, who has written 28 books set 100 years ago, captivates
readers with her vivid descriptions of a time that often was
thought virtuous, but in reality was plagued with problems and
scandals like those prevalent today.
</P>
<P>
   She intertwines the characters and their lives _ their daily
routines, hardships and emotions _ into a suspenseful tale that
always tackles a social issue. Without getting preachy, she draws
in readers so they become engrossed and even outraged at the trauma
at hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bedford Square,'' the bestselling author's latest mystery,
follows the long-established formula. In this case, blackmail, lies
and innuendo are the issues. Police Superintendent Thomas Pitt and
his adventuresome wife, Charlotte, are the main characters.
</P>
<P>
   Perry, who lives on the eastern coast of Scotland in a barn that
she has converted into a home, will be in the Valley later this
week to talk about and sign copies of ``Bedford Square.''
</P>
<P>
   In the book, a shabbily dressed man is discovered dead on the
doorstep of Gen. Brandon Balantyne's home. A rare snuffbox,
belonging to the general, is found in the dead man's pocket, but
the retired military officer denies knowing him.
</P>
<P>
   Pitt begins an investigation into the man's identity and
discovers that blackmail is at the heart of the situation. Many
high-placed, honorable men, including Balantyne and Assistant
Police Commissioner Cornwallis, are being accused of impropriety
and offenses that if made public would cause them to be ostracized
by London society.
</P>
<P>
   The connection among the men eludes Pitt, his associate, Sgt.
Tellman, and even Charlotte, who, as in previous books, devises her
own investigations. But to the reader, it is readily apparent _ and
a disappointment that Perry hasn't realized how obvious it is.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, knowing the connection doesn't mean the reader
will be able to discern the outcome or resolve the inevitable
whodunit. Nor does it detract from the pleasure of the read.
</P>
<P>
   The Pitts were featured in Perry's first novel, ``The Cater
Street Hangman,'' which was published 20 years ago and made into a
made-for-TV movie that aired on A&AMP;E in December.
</P>
<P>
   Perry generally writes two novels a year, one about the Pitts
and the other featuring William Monk, a former police inspector who
has amnesia. The latter also is set in Victorian times and delves
into social issues. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-99 1905EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990406.0257 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8127 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR &LR;      04-06 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTABLE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A survey of recently published books:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; THE HANDYMAN &QL; 
 &UR; Carolyn See (Random House, $22.95)
</P>
<P>
   We know from the prologue of this novel that its protagonist
will become a famous artist, that his work will be studied and
collected, and that his life will be grand. The prologue takes the
form of a grant application made in 2027 by an art historian who
has devoted himself to the work of Robert Hampton. But when we move
to the first chapter, we are back in 1996 and Hampton is not yet
successful but is still ``Bob,'' an aimless 28-year-old who fails
to find artistic inspiration in Paris and so returns to Los Angeles
and invents a life for himself as an unskilled handyman. There's an
air of the mundane about this story as the good-natured Bob
ventures out again and again in answer to calls for his services
and finds a collective role as savior/anchor/confessor in his
clients' lives. One of those clients is Hank, a young man who has
come from Ohio with his boyfriend, only to find that Ben has AIDS
and is deteriorating so fast that Hank has neither the skill nor
the courage to care for him. So, he summons Bob the Handyman _ ``I
had to call somebody,'' he says. ``If I didn't call someone, I was
afraid I might leave. Just walk out the door.'' Another client is
Angela Landry, whose toddler is saved from the bottom of a swimming
pool by Bob, an act that sets the stage for a new life for all
three of them. Appearances to the contrary, none of this seems
terribly dramatic. See unfolds each chapter in Bob's network of
needy clients with a wry, understated wit and the gentle suggestion
that inspiration is sometimes an accident of everyday life. Bob's
artistic talent changes as it becomes his response to the quirky
needs of his clients. This story is very Californian _ deceptively
simple, easy to read, with some sex thrown in to sweeten the deal. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; GOD IS A BULLET &QL; 
 &UR; Boston Teran (Knopf, $24)
</P>
<P>
   Melodramatic, intense, gory and un relenting _ here's a nice
book to settle down with on a Sunday afternoon. This first novel is
not for the squeamish or for those want finesse in their fiction,
but if you like violent bravado, you can't beat it. It begins with
the 1970 murder of an eccentric woman in an isolated trailer in the
California desert, then moves to the 1995 kidnapping of a
14-year-old girl and the brutal slaying of her mother and
stepfather. The crimes are connected, although we do not know how
thoroughly until later. The missing girl's father is Bob Hightower,
a cop who works a desk job and has little experience investigating
such things. But as time passes with no sign of his daughter, he
desperately accepts the help of Case, a recovering heroin addict
who has seen news reports of the double slaying and recognizes the
violent trademarks of a cult to which she belonged for 17 years.
Case leads Hightower to Cyrus, a Mansonesque character and the
book's main source of evil, depravity and seriously wacky dialogue.
Cyrus and his cohorts often seem more like the roving gangs of the
``Mad Max'' movies than characters in a novel, and this takes some
of the edge off their dastardly deeds (which involve, among other
things, a letter opener, a cactus, a rattlesnake and numerous
Lugers). There aren't really a lot of surprises, plot- driven or
otherwise _ after a while you realize that if you think something
dreadful is about to happen a character, you're probably right _
but Teran shows depth in his fiction debut. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; TELLER OF TALES: THE LIFE OF ARTHUR CONAN DOYLE &QL; 
 &UR; Daniel Stashower (Holt, $32.50)
</P>
<P>
   Stashower opens this biography with the story of his trip to the
shop of a London rare-book dealer, where a saleswoman showed him a
first edition of Arthur Conan Doyle's ``The Hound of the
Baskervilles.'' Stashower held it reverently, but it was too
expensive. The saleswoman said she would check with the manager to
see whether there might be other Conan Boyle material in a back
room. Moving around the shop, Stashower was close to the manager's
office and heard the woman tell him that a customer was interested
in Conan Doyle. ``Oh, God,'' came the answer. ``It must be an
American.'' This reaction is not unusual, Stashower says. When he
presents himself in Britain as a collector of Conan Doyle material,
``the response is invariably polite, but it generally carries a
quiet note of sympathy, as though I'd just confessed some exotic
intestinal complaint.'' Conan Doyle has had the misfortune of being
eclipsed by his creation and by his own odd interests. ``Sherlock
Holmes was brilliant,'' people would say to Stashower, ``but Doyle
went a bit potty at the end, didn't he? Fairies, ghosts, and
that.'' Indeed, during the latter part of his life, he believed in
mediums and psychics. ``He became the living embodiment of the
spiritualist craze,'' Stashower says. ``His outspokenness, weighed
against the cool logic of Sherlock Holmes, seemed to invite public
scorn.'' Stashower looks without derision at Conan Doyle's devotion
to spiritualism, his books, his friendships with George Bernard
Shaw and Harry Houdini, his appeal to American audiences and his
feelings for the fictional character that cast the long shadow from
which he could never truly escape. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; TENDER AT THE BONE &QL; 
 &UR; Ruth Reichl (Broadway, $13)
</P>
<P>
   Storytelling, in Reichl's family, was highly prized, which is
one of the reasons this memoir, new in paperback, is so much fun to
read _ because nothing in life, Reichl says, is as important as a
good story. Somehow that doesn't seem odd, coming from a woman who
traveled incognito as restaurant critic for the ``New York Times.''
Here she chronicles her early years and the people who influenced
her (including her mother, who would say, ``Oh, it's just a little
mold,'' before she scraped the stuff off the food and served what
was left for dinner). Reichl discovered that food was a way of
making sense of the world. In that spirit, she has dropped some of
her favorite recipes throughout the book, which now becomes a
souvenir of sorts: Reichl just this week wrote her farewell column
in the ``Times.'' She soon takes the helm as editor of ``Gourmet''
magazine. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Reach correspondent Anne Stephenson at
amstephenson(at)worldnet.att.net, via e-mail.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-99 1906EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
