<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ADVISORY-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (REPEATING, WITH HOLDS)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans 4 pages of stories, photos and graphics
on the continuing crisis in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Washington) _ Ledeall: Yugoslavia declares a
unilateral cease-fire, starting tonight, for Orthodox Easter. The
U.S. rejects it as a ``half measure''; NATO steps up its military
operations. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERBIA (Aleksinac, Yugoslavia) _ At least 5 civilians are
killed and 20 or more wounded after a NATO attack aimed at military
barracks hits a residential area in this coal-mining town 125 miles
south of Belgrade. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels, Belgium) _ Despite better weather, NATO
did not hit any vehicles or troops on Monday. By Michael R. Gordon
and Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLO (Washington) _ Diplomatic maneuvering over Kosovo.
By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Skopje, Macedonia) _ Confusion and a desperate
anxiety has spread through the Kosovo Albanian refugees here, as
Macedonian authorities pressed on with their shipment of people
abroad and Serb police forced refugees still stuck in Kosovo to
return back to the capital Pristina. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ISRAEL (Tirana, Albania) _ The scene as Holocaust
survivors and others from Israel bring in aid to the Kosovo
refugees. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Kukes, Albania) _ Refugee developments:
Refugees say that the police in Kosovo have said that their orders
have changed, perhaps as a result of the cease-fire announced in
Belgrade. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-AIRLIFT (Washington) _ As the refugee crisis continued to
explode, with tales of chaos and disease along the Kosovo border,
NATO said Tuesday it would assume all responsibility for getting
food, relief supplies and medical care to the refugees as well as
fly them to their temporary homes away from the battlefield. By
Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALLIES (Washington) _ NATO resolved Tuesday night to keep
bombing in Yugoslavia until the Yugoslav President, Slobodan
Milosevic, agreed to withdraw all his attacking forces from Kosovo,
to let refugees back in with an international military force to
protect them, and to negotiate a political settlement for the
province, Western diplomats said. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BASES (Washington) _ The White House said today it had
selected the American naval base at Guantanamo Bay in Cuba as a
temporary home for 20,000 refugees from Kosovo. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
