<DOCNO> NYT19990406.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8130 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ZHU-HNS &LR;      04-06 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZHU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    PREMIER'S VISIT COMES AT TUMULTUOUS TIME IN CHINESE-U.S.
RELATIONS
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
(EDITORS: Second reference to Minxin Pei should be Pei. It is his
surname.) &HT;     &HT;    By JENNIFER DAY 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji arrives Wednesday with a
full agenda, but many experts believe the visit will merely be a
chance to help bolster tenuous U.S.-China relations in a tumultuous
political environment.
</P>
<P>
   Although both Chinese and U.S. officials had hoped to announce
progress toward China's admission into the World Trade
Organization, American negotiators said Tuesday that a number of
critical issues were still undecided.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an important relationship with China, and I think
regular contact is useful in and of itself,'' White House spokesman
Joe Lockhart said. ``I'm not going to try to advance any specific
breakthroughs or announcements, but it is an important
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   That relationship has been seriously strained during the past
few months, starting late last year with a report concluding that
China had stolen U.S. nuclear secrets during the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional pressure against China mounted, especially after
crackdowns by Beijing on pro-democracy activists. The crackdowns
spurred the Clinton administration last month to reintroduce a U.N.
resolution to condemn human rights violations committed by the
Chinese. The resolution angered officials in Beijing, who last year
signed a human rights covenant in exchange for the United States
dropping a similar resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, China condemned NATO airstrikes led by the United
States against Yugoslavia, calling it a threat to international
security and sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu's nine-day, six-city tour of the United States comes just
days after reports surfaced that China's military intelligence
chief may have ordered Democratic fund-raiser Johnny Chung to
contribute $300,000 to President Clinton's 1996 re-election
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart declined to comment on the report, which is being
investigated by the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   It may be a difficult time in Sino-American relations, but Liu
Xiaoming, deputy chief of mission for the Chinese Embassy, said Zhu
is ready to deal with the challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``With regard to the storms, I think we have been used to it,''
he said. ``Whenever there's an important event between China-U.S.
relations, we are bound to see some storms, because there are
always some people who are not very happy with the improvement of
relations between our two countries.''
</P>
<P>
   But in such a hostile environment, many experts say, not much is
expected to result from Zhu's visit, the first made by a Chinese
premier in 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   At most, said Minxin Pei, senior associate for the Democracy
Project at the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace, minor
agreements may be made on some trade issues, but an agreement is
unlikely on the key issue of membership in the World Trade
Organization, which enforces international trade rules and settles
disputes.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the United States is demanding better access to
Chinese markets to reduce the $57 billion trade deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must not overload these visits with unrealistic
expectations,'' said Arthur Waldron, director of Asian Studies for
the American Enterprise Institute. ``I would like to see this visit
lead to some honest talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the issues expected to be discussed during the premier's
visit are a proposed missile defense program off Taiwan's coast,
the allegations of espionage, WTO membership, human rights
violations and environmental concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu's meeting with President Clinton comes as Chinese officials
are preparing themselves for the 10th anniversary of the Tiananmen
Square massacre.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu's visit is the latest in a series of high-level exchanges
between Washington and Beijing. Chinese President Jiang Zemin
visited Washington in the fall of 1997 for a full-pomp state visit
that also included a strong, public debate with Clinton on human
rights. Clinton went to Beijing last June as part of the first
visit of a U.S. head of state to China since the 1989 Tiananmen
incident.
</P>
<P>
   In April of that year, hundreds gathered in Beijing's Tiananmen
Square to mourn the death of a liberal Communist Party secretary.
The gathering soon turned into a student-led demonstration for
democracy but it ended on June 4, 1989, when troops and tanks were
ordered to silence the movement, killing hundreds of protesters.
</P>
<P>
   It was this same year that Zhu made a name for himself as mayor
of Shanghai, when he refused to send in troops to put down
demonstrations that had spread from Tiananmen.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Pei said, he persuaded protesters to return to work and
school.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Zhu _ who was forced into ``re-education'' in the
countryside during the Great Proletarian Cultural Revolution of the
1960s _ has been viewed as a moderate.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL ADD END)
</P>
<P>
   Although Zhu has won international respect and popular support
with his pragmatic approach, direct demeanor and good sense of
humor, he is not considered too ambitious in China nor does he have
a strong power base, Pei said. In fact, if anything, his attempts
at economic reform have hurt his relationships with party bosses,
Pei said.
</P>
<P>
   But Waldron of the American Enterprise Institute said
privatization is not nearly as far along as it should be and that
Zhu still has misplaced faith in state-run industries.
</P>
<P>
   John Holden, the president of the National Committee on
U.S.-China Relations, said many did not realize how difficult the
problems were, but that Zhu should be welcomed as a man who has ``a
keen appreciation for where Americans are coming from.''
</P>
<P>
   Waldron, however, said it would be unwise to pin all hopes on
one leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that a single czar could deal with the problems China
has is simply wrong,'' Waldron said. ``We shouldn't kid ourselves.
China faces severe problems. Highly intelligent people, people of
good will don't know what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   XXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
