<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8131 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CEASEFIRE-ANALYSIS-BO     04-06 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CEASEFIRE-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CEASFIRE OFFER ESCALATES PROPAGANDA WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN YEMMA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are three wars raging in Yugoslavia right now _ the Serb
terrorization of ethnic Albanians, the NATO bombing against Serb
targets, and a hearts-and-minds battle between Serb leader Slobodan
Milosevic and President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The third war _ the propaganda war _ just escalated.
</P>
<P>
   The Milosevic government's announcement Tuesday of a unilateral
cease-fire to honor the Orthodox Easter holiday was a move clearly
meant to split the NATO alliance, say Balkan specialists. NATO
officials Tuesday quickly rejected the offer as insufficient.
</P>
<P>
   They had expected this. Aware that he might try something along
these lines, officials in the Clinton administration launched
pre-emptive diplomacy over the weekend, contacting allied leaders
and putting out word on Monday that they would not accept a ``phony
peace deal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is completely part of the pattern,'' said Peter
Galbraith, who served as US ambassador to Croatia from 1993-98 and
was deeply involved in negotiations during that period. ``Having
accomplished what he wants, he calls for a cease-fire _ `Great,
let's negotiate. Now that we've driven everyone out, please stop
the bombing.' . . . I've gone gray with these kinds of
negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost certainly, there will be more Milosevic calls to end the
war in the days to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Milosevic has in mind is fracturing the unity of the NATO
alliance, which is probably a mile wide and an inch thick right
now,'' said Robert Pfaltzgraff, a security studies specialist at
Tufts University's Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   Having substantially achieved his objectives of forcing ethnic
Albanians out of Kosovo, Milosevic can afford to play peacemaker,
said Pflatzgraff. If NATO does not try to roll back his gains, he
will have ``codified a great victory.''
</P>
<P>
   While waging war in the Balkans is proving militarily and
politically difficult for Clinton, it will be even harder if
Milosevic succeeds in remaking himself as a man of peace while the
United States and its European allies look like war hawks.
</P>
<P>
   If anybody can pull off such as metamorphosis, it is Milosevic,
who throughout the decade has alternated between fiery nationalist
and cerebral peace broker, touching off wars in Croatia and Bosnia
and then sitting down at the bargaining table. British diplomat
David Owen, who negotiated with Milosevic throughout the first half
of the decade, has described the Serb leader's media skills as
``formidable.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Europeans, Asians, and many Americans who have misgivings
about the NATO bombing campaign _ especially with the possibility
of more civilian casualties as occurred in air raids Monday night _
the Serb cease-fire declaration may strike a chord. Italy and
Greece, in particular, may begin to lobby for ending the
hostilities.
</P>
<P>
   It ``is clearly a way to solidify Orthodox Christian support for
him and shore himself up in the Balkans,'' said Dietrich Orlow, a
specialist in European history at Boston University. ``He has a
long history of promises like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Going back to the war with Croatia in 1991-92 and his 1992-95
proxy campaign in Bosnia, Milosevic's style is stop-and-go warfare,
said Orlow and other analysts. In each case, he has allowed Serb
paramilitaries to terrorize and uproot a population, then sent in
army regulars to roll up control on the ground before offering to
begin negotiations aimed at normalizing the new state of affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Often he will even make concessions, having taken more territory
than he intends to keep. With Serb military domination of Kosovo
now well advanced, expect Milosevic to make even more offers to
stop hostilities and commence peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know that a new situation has been created,'' said
Jasminka Vdovicki, co-editor of ``Burn this House: The Making and
Unmaking of Yugoslavia.'' In both Croatia and Bosnia, she said,
Milosevic ``conquered great swaths which allowed him to negotiate
from a position of strength. Now his forces can be gallant and
withdraw from part and say they will keep the rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Short of a ground invasion by NATO, the West is unlikely to
force Milosevic to capitulate, pull his forces out of Kosovo, and
allow Albanians to return to their homes. And that means the
propaganda war will get more and more tricky for NATO in the days
to come.
</P>
</TEXT>
