<HEADER>
A8133 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISSING-ATHEIST-HNS &LR;      04-06 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSING-ATHEIST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-CON WITH TIES TO MISSING ATHEIST INDICTED ON WEAPON CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MacCORMACK  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A possible suspect in the case of missing
atheist Madalyn Murray O'Hair was indicted Tuesday on two federal
weapons charges.
</P>
<P>
   The federal grand jury indictment came nearly two weeks after a
dozen federal agents and the police raided the apartment of David
R. Waters, the former office manager for the atheist organizations
run by the vanished O'Hair.
</P>
<P>
   Waters, 52, is suspected by federal authorities of having a role
in her disappearance in 1995, although he has not been charged with
any crimes relating to O'Hair and denies knowing anything about her
fate.
</P>
<P>
   Waters has been jailed since his arrest March 24.
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities ``think he knows a whole bunch, but he has
no clue what they are talking about and I'm just as baffled,'' said
Patrick Ganne, an Austin lawyer representing Waters. ``He's looking
to me for answers, and I can't give any.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's somewhat depressed. He's concerned that the whole weight
of the federal government is coming down on him. Everyone seems to
be pointing fingers at Waters, but their hands are empty,'' Ganne
said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators declined to comment beyond a single-page statement
announcing the indictment. Waters is accused of being a felon in
possession of a firearm or ammunition and of interstate transport
of guns and ammunition by a felon.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment said federal agents found 119 rounds of
ammunition in Waters' apartment on March 24. The second charge
alleges that sometime in the past two months, Waters shipped two
handguns and some ammunition to his home state Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   According to the indictment, the weapons he shipped were a
Browning 9mm semi-automatic pistol and a .357 Magnum revolver.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted of those charges, Waters could face 20 years in
federal prison and a $500,000 fine. He is set to appear Thursday
morning in the federal court in Austin for a bond hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Waters has four felony convictions, including murder and
battery.
</P>
<P>
   Although authorities investigating the September 1995
disappearance of O'Hair, her son Jon Garth Murray and daughter
Robin Murray O'Hair have not mentioned Waters, sources say he is a
prime suspect.
</P>
<P>
   A second man, Gary P. Karr, 50, of Novi, Mich., is also
suspected of a role in what authorities believe was a kidnapping
and murder. Karr, also a convicted felon, has been charged with
federal weapons violations in Michigan and with transporting stolen
property in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Karr met Waters in Illinois prison a decade ago, according to
his lawyer, public defender Richard Helfrick of Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   At a March 26 hearing in federal court in Detroit, FBI agent
William O'Leary testified that Karr had admitted involvement in
four homicides in Texas, but had said he did not kill anyone.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth person, Danny Fry of Florida, disappeared at the same
time that the O'Hair family did.
</P>
<P>
   Fry was an old friend of Waters' who went to Texas in the summer
of 1995 at Waters' behest, according to Fry family members.
</P>
<P>
   Fry's nude body, minus head and hands, was dumped by a river in
eastern Dallas County on Oct. 2, 1995, and was not identified until
genetic testing was performed earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Helfrick said Tuesday: ``I saw him (Karr) this morning. We're
just waiting for the next thing to happen, whatever is going to
happen, and we really don't know.
</P>
<P>
   ``I represent him on a gun case, so that's all I'm concerned
with, the gun case, and if anything else arises in Texas, he can
get a public defender there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of federal agents spent Friday, Saturday and Sunday
searching for the bodies of the O'Hair family on a ranch near Camp
Wood, a tiny town 120 miles west of San Antonio. The FBI did not
announce any results.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Holmes, an FBI spokesman in San Antonio, said a second
search of the site has not been ruled out, but none will happen
soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The authority under which we executed the search warrant on
Friday was for a period of 10 days. We completed our search in two
and a half days, and we do not have any immediate plans to return
under that original authority,'' Holmes said.
</P>
</TEXT>
