<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8134 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEEMAY-COLUMN03-COX     04-06 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEEMAY-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spring's power overwhelming
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Spring is the most demanding season; it jumps in your
face, shouts your name, forces you to participate in its seductive
unveiling, knowing from experience that its raging beauty is
irresistible, its fresh youth undeniable.
</P>
<P>
   If you do not succumb to this season, you have a hole in your
soul.
</P>
<P>
   Gardeners, of course, are the easiest to seduce, the weakest of
all. I am a gardener, and I am weak.
</P>
<P>
   Strange, the power of spring. Nothing could be more predictable
than leaves appearing, buds opening, fronds unfurling. At the same
time, nothing could be so amazing, so mysterious. Each year, when
this season gets its speed up and tumbles into lushness, I go out
of doors and lose all sense of time _ lost in the season's
reassuring sameness, yes, but also jolted by its surprises.
</P>
<P>
   What a great leveler this season is: Commoners impress as much
as rare breeds. The oft-disparaged ligustrum furiously puts out new
green growth, and its pregnant buds inspire as much anticipation as
any plant in my garden. Similarly, the wisteria rambling along the
railing on the back porch promises its best crop of blooms ever as
purple clusters grow bigger by the minute, swelling and storing
fragrance that will burst free any day now. And the two
chinaberries broke out in bright green leaves the other day,
showing that they, like the rest of us, had survived another year.
</P>
<P>
   After enjoying the ocean of colorful plantings last weekend at
Callaway Gardens' newly unveiled Azalea Bowl, I came home,
inspired, to my little bushes blooming with familial zeal. And to a
banana shrub that enjoyed the mild winter and went from tight buds
to yellow blooms overnight.
</P>
<P>
   I've not seen a better year for Carolina jessamine, despite the
cold hit it suffered. While jessamine is as tough as a pansy, a
once-lovely white camellia grew tired of freezing in mid-bloom and
just gave up recently, leaving a dry, forlorn little trunk.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of victims, can it be that my only dwarf bamboo (in a
pot, the only way to contain this plastic grass) has fallen on hard
times? I kept it as a reminder of my war on this ground cover,
potting up one clump. Now, it seems wan. My heart is not big enough
to hold sympathy for it.
</P>
<P>
   On a happier note, a potted rosemary has come to flower. After
five years of providing countless sprigs that added dash to dishes
such as pork, lamb, beans and seafood, this great fragrant plant
decided to bloom a whitish shade of pale lavender.
</P>
<P>
   An even greater surprise awaited, however.
</P>
<P>
   For several years, I grew a tree-form rose in a wooden tub.
Three feet tall, its trunk was capped during good times with a
canopy of white blossoms, fragrant, inviting. Last summer, the rose
died. After a decent interval, I pulled out the dead plant and
filled the tub with chrysanthemums. In the warm weather, the mums
have grown thick.
</P>
<P>
   The other day I noticed that, amid this growth, there was, yes,
the fuzzy, reddish stalk of a rose, about 6 inches tall. It is
filled with reddish-green leaves and the promise of more days of
roses. I love thinking they will come again, but have already
enjoyed the possibility.
</P>
<P>
   So goes spring. It grabs you by the collar, shakes you, wakes
you with its big show, then shows you a tiny surprise that holds a
world of hope. What an awesome, comforting exercise of gentle
power.
</P>
<P>
   Lee May writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
