<HEADLINE>
VIOLENCE THREATENS EAST TIMOR PEACE EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ Three months before a scheduled vote that
many thought would bring a peaceful close to more than 23 years of
armed struggle for independence in the Indonesian province of East
Timor, a new round of violence threatens to unravel those hopes.
</P>
<P>
   Separatist rebels Tuesday reported new clashes with
government-backed forces and said they would heed the call to arms
issued Monday by jailed East Timor guerrilla leader Xanana Gusmao.
Gusmao abandoned his two-month-old cease fire in frustration,
saying his forces had to protect civilians from escalating attacks
by militias allegedly backed by the Indonesian military.
</P>
<P>
   The renewal of armed struggle threatens to undermine both the
United Nations-brokered peace talks scheduled for next week in New
York and a vote in early July to choose between autonomy or
independence for East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   A renewed guerrilla struggle in the troubled territory is the
latest of several worrisome signs that Indonesia, the world's
fourth most populous nation, faces the threat of splintering,
Yugoslavia-like.
</P>
<P>
   For 32 years, the nation's authoritarian leader General Suharto
_ like the late dictator Josep Tito in Yugoslavia _ kept a tight
lid on separatist movements in this vast and diverse archipelago
nation of 17,500 islands. But a severe economic crisis sparked
popular uprisings that forced Suharto from power last May, and
fueled secessionist sentiments in the provinces of East Timor, Aceh
and Irian Jaya. Ethnic and religious rivalries have flared on
several other islands, claiming hundreds of lives and creating
thousands of refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Continuing clashes Tuesday between Christians and Muslims on the
eastern Moluccas Islands brought the week's death toll there to 66,
Reuters reported. Thousands of women and children have reportedly
fled their villages since January, while men roam streets armed
with machetes, spears, and axes. More than 250 have been slain
there this year in religious violence.
</P>
<P>
   On the northern island of Borneo, nearly 200 people have been
killed since February in gruesome clashes between ethnic Malay,
Dayak and Chinese allied against settlers from Madura island.
</P>
<P>
   The latest flash-point is once again East Timor, a former
Portuguese colony invaded by Indonesia in 1975 and annexed the next
year. Indonesia's rule in East Timor was never recognized by the
United Nations or most countries, and Jakarta is blamed for the
deaths of an estimated 200,000 people during a military crackdown
and famine that followed, and for human rights abuses ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Since the fall of Suharto, Indonesia's new president, B.J.
Habibie, has said he would consider independence for East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Habibie moved rebel leader Gusmao to house arrest
from prison, where he was serving a 20-year term for leading the
armed revolt, and said he wanted the East Timor issue resolved by
the end of the year. Last month, Indonesia and Portugal agreed to a
U.N.-supervised vote that would allow residents to choose autonomy
or full independence.
</P>
<P>
   So why the escalation of conflict now?
</P>
<P>
   There are those who believe pro-Indonesia forces in East Timor
have sparked violent incidents to provoke guerrillas into renewing
the civil war, thereby squelching chances of a peaceful vote that
might bring about independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``These incidents are done deliberately by people to get this
kind of a reaction from Xanana,'' said Carrascalao. ``The Army is
strong enough to prevent these kinds of conflicts, but they are
choosing not to act. There are vested interests in East Timor who
do not want the situation to be solved.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, pro-independence groups reported clashes,
arrests, deaths and civilians fleeing violence in six cities,
including Liquisa, 1,250 miles east of Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesian officials strove to calm the renewed tensions. Dewi
Fortuna Anwar, assistant minister/state secretary for foreign
affairs, called for ``calm and peace, so . . . there will be a
conducive climate for East Timor people to discuss and vote with an
open mind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of East Timor have sacrificed for 23 years. They
should wait for at least three more months to see what happens,''
said Mario Carrascalao, former governor of East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   But Gusmao's lawyer, Johnson Panjaitan, said the rebel leader
would only back off if the UN agrees to send peacekeeping forces _
an unlikely scenario _ and the military stops supporting militias.
Witnesses in Dili, East Timor's capital, reported seeing new troops
arriving Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
