<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8143 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOGS-HNS &LR;      04-06 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARRIS COUNTY TO KEEP SELLING POUND ANIMALS FOR RESEARCH &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOE STINEBAKER 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Harris County Commissioners Court voted Tuesday
afternoon to reject a proposal that would have banned the sale of
pound animals for medical research.
</P>
<P>
   But Commissioner Steve Radack, who has pushed for such a ban for
several years, said he will continue to try to end the practice by
taking the issue before voters in November.
</P>
<P>
   Radack had hoped to get the court to agree to the ban and,
failing that, to allow the issue to be placed on the Nov. 2 ballot.
But County Attorney Michael P. Fleming told Radack that the county
lacks the proper authority from the state to conduct such a
referendum.
</P>
<P>
   So instead, Radack is trying to get a rider attached to a bill
in the Texas Legislature that would give the county the authority
to hold a referendum on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Radack placed a call to Mike Toomey, a county lobbyist in
Austin, immediately after Commissioners Court adjourned. Despite
the setback on Commissioners Court, Radack is now hoping for
support in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's worth a phone call,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The court's 3-2 rejection of the ban comes as another bitter
loss to animal-rights activists, who have flooded court members
with mail and calls seeking approval of the ban. It also comes as
welcome news to many in the county's medical community, who have
lobbied to continue the sales.
</P>
<P>
   The county has contracts to sell hundreds of animals, mostly
dogs, to Baylor College of Medicine, the University of
Texas-Houston Health Science Center, the University of Houston
Animal Care Operations and Texas A&AMP;M University for $40 each. The
schools use the animals for medical research and training.
</P>
<P>
   The animal sales continue to be one of the court's most
controversial issues each year. Supporters on both sides of the
controversy piled into Commissioners Court Tuesday to press their
case.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the sales got a boost from Dr. Michael DeBakey,
the world-renowned pioneer in heart surgery. DeBakey told the court
that animal research has led to such medical breakthroughs as heart
bypass surgery and a polio cure, which have saved countless human
lives around the world.
</P>
<P>
   And Baylor has spent millions of dollars updating and improving
its animal research center, he told the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd be glad to be in it yourself,'' he said. ``The animals
get treated better than some of the patients.''
</P>
<P>
   More than a dozen doctors from the various medical schools sided
with DeBakey, saying the research animals were treated humanely.
And Dr. Richard Ermel, of Texas A&AMP;M's College of Veterinary
Medicine, told the court that without the county's sale of research
animals, the school would have to rely on using animals
specifically bred for research.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents of the sales were equally adamant, saying research
on animals was no longer necessary, that most other local
governments, including the city of Houston, had banned the sale of
pound animals for medical research.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
