</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-GROUNDTROOPS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANS SEEM TO BE WARMING TO PROSPECT OF GROUND TROOPS IN
KOSOVO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton says he has no plans to send
ground troops to Kosovo, but most Americans seem to be warming to
the idea.
</P>
<P>
   In a marked turnabout from earlier findings, recent polls show
growing support for a ground war in the Balkans. A deployment that
had been almost unthinkable two weeks ago is now considered an
acceptable option, according to some national surveys.
</P>
<P>
   A Washington Post poll of 509 adults found that 55 percent
support the use of ground troops. Nearly 68 percent said they
expect Clinton to send troops against Serbia despite his announced
intention to avoid such a move.
</P>
<P>
   New York pollster John Zogby, who hopes to complete a Kosovo
poll Wednesday, said his early results show 60 percent support for
ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   A White House spokesman said the shift in public opinion will
not alter Clinton's opposition to the use of ground forces in
Kosovo. Two weeks of NATO bombing have failed to curb Serbian
attacks on ethnic Albanians in the rebellious Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in the second week of an air campaign that we are
confident will succeed,'' spokesman Joe Lockhart said. ``He has no
intention of introducing ground troops. He's made his decision with
the best advice he has from his military and foreign policy
advisers.''
</P>
<P>
   The growing public acceptance of the possibility of a ground war
contrasts with the mood when Clinton and NATO launched the air war
two weeks ago. Although a bare majority of Americans endorsed the
bombings, they strongly opposed the use of ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   Experts attribute the shift to several factors, including the
capture of three American soldiers by Serbia and numerous reports
of atrocities committed against ethnic Albanians. Disturbing video
footage of ragged refugees fleeing the violence has also helped
give the far-off conflict a human face.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the longest time, Kosovo was not on the radar because
there was not enough video. There's been a lot of video in the last
week.'' Zogby said. ``The cause is becoming clearer.''
</P>
<P>
   Polls conducted for CBS found that support for the use of ground
troops increased from 33 percent to 41 percent after the three
Americans were captured by Serbia. The latest CBS poll was
conducted April 1.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Post poll, conducted Monday, also found
increasing support for the bombing campaign. About 68 percent of
Americans support the airstrikes but an equal proportion expressed
doubts that they would deter Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
and his followers in their campaign against ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   The poll had a margin of error of 5 percentage points, meaning
that the results could be off by that much in either direction due
to sampling errors.
</P>
<P>
   Many observers question the depth of support for ground combat,
a variable that has not been tested in recent polls. The last major
ground campaign, the 1991 Persian Gulf War, resulted in 148 combat
deaths for U.S. forces. The Vietnam War cost more than 47,000
American lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Success tends to bring support, but failure can cause
problems,'' said John Mueller, a political science professor at the
University of Rochester in Rochester, N.Y., who specializes in
wartime public opinion. ``There may be support, but it may wane
fairly quickly if casualties start coming in.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
