A8150 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFLDRAFT-RECEIVER     04-06 0492
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLDRAFT-RECEIVERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For Edwards, football isn't a war of words
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Stoic on the field and soft-spoken in interviews,
North Carolina State star Torry Holt apparently missed the
directive that transferred to this year's wide receivers the gift
of gab normally associated with mouthy cornerbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Irked by years of verbal abuse from defenders, several of the
wideouts in the '99 draft, most notably Troy Edwards of Louisiana
Tech, have countered with filibusters of their own. But for Holt, a
dynamic playmaker whose stock continues to rise, touchdowns are
more important than taunts. He has become the Marcel Marceau of
receivers, with his college deeds speaking volumes about his NFL
potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that talking takes too much energy,'' Holt said during the
combine in February. ``My goal is to shut everybody else up.''
</P>
<P>
   During his ACC career, Holt rendered speechless such renowned
orators as Virginia safety Anthony Poindexter and cornerback Dre
Bly of North Carolina. Nothing, however, compares with the
collective mute button he laid on the Florida State secondary in
his junior season.
</P>
<P>
   In the first quarter, Holt had a clean drop, and Seminoles
corner Samari Rolle immediately jumped his case. For the next two
possessions, Rolle and his secondary mates blistered Holt's
eardrums. And then Holt blistered them, catching 12 passes and
scoring five touchdowns in a performance that catapulted him into
the national spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   He finished his career in Raleigh with 191 catches for 3,379
yards and 31 touchdowns and also returned punts and kickoffs. He
and David Boston of Ohio State, who also has return abilities,
clearly have separated themselves from the rest of the wide
receivers in this draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Holt doesn't need to call attention to himself,'' said Bob
Ferguson, Arizona Cardinals vice president of personnel. ``He kind
of kills you softly, you know?''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Edwards plays with a chip on his shoulder and never
would finish second in a debate. Even the imposing Boston, whose
father, Byron Boston, is an NFL line judge, has been known to
skirmish verbally with defenders.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, who caught 21 passes for an NCAA-record 405 yards and
three touchdowns in a 1998 loss to Nebraska, is shorter than some
teams like. He certainly talks a big game, though, and more often
than not backs up his words. At the combine, Edwards bragged to
reporters that no defensive back could ever check him one on one
and noted that he had accomplished in three years what it took
Jerry Rice four years to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm never going to be bashful,'' Edwards said.''Wide receivers
have been taking (abuse) from defensive backs a long time. It's
time to give some back.''
</P>
<P>
   Len Pasquarelli writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
