<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-HUMMER-MASTERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    You may not notice, but Masters has changed
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Augusta National has grown a little hair. You
wouldn't call the stuff now collaring the Augusta Natioinal
fairways exactly rough. More like mild inconvenience. The CBS crew
could well whisper on Thursday, ``Oh, my, Greg Norman just pushed
his tee shot into the grassy annoyance.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not cabbage. It's kinder than spinach. More in the
watercress or wheat grass family.
</P>
<P>
   A ``second cut'' is the accepted term for the new growth, which
sounds more like an all-day prime rib than a hazard.
</P>
<P>
   It measures exactly 1 3/8 inches in height, this new addition to
the Masters landscape. And not a micron more. How much it will
impact play is debatable. John Huston spoke of dropping a few balls
into the first cut for practice, and ``I had no trouble spinning
the ball.'' You can lose farm equipment in U.S. Open rough. Here,
it's much more subtle, just a slightly darker shade of green.
</P>
<P>
   Still, any change seems significant at a tournament that used to
be known for its rigidity. The fact is, the Masters and Augusta
National undergo small, constant change that adds up over time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The yardage books never last more than year around here,''
Stuart Appleby said.
</P>
<P>
   When they construct the windmill on No. 6 green and stack some
railroad ties on the property, then you'll know the transformation
is complete.
</P>
<P>
   And while we're at it, when is this country club going to get a
swimming pool and some tennis courts?
</P>
<P>
   We go through this annually, taking inventory of the tweaks and
tucks done in the name of progress and then somberly debating them.
Every alteration is as serious as taking a surgeon's knife to
Cameron Diaz.
</P>
<P>
   For every change is a possible affront to history. ``I don't
like to see this, because I like to step up on the tee and say,
`Gene Sarazen did this or Byron Nelson did this,' and feel the same
history under your feet as what those guys played on,'' Greg Norman
said. Trouble is, those guys did it without clubs that could have
been made on the planet Krypton and with golf balls that weren't
radioactive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish they hadn't had to make (the course changes) because of
the equipment,'' rued Jack Nicklaus, out of this tournament due to
some major course redesign on his hip.
</P>
<P>
   Other alterations will change the profile of this Masters far
more than the rough. They've tinkered with the format, playing
Thursday and Friday in threesomes instead of twosomes to
accommodate larger fields, making everyone's round a little longer.
And they have adopted the idea that the old course needs to be let
out a little.
</P>
<P>
   So, they bumped back the tee boxes at the par-5 second and par-4
17th. They planted an instant forest along the par-5 15th. They
have played the role of a heavy-handed God.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, it seemed the moves were a response to the way
Tiger Woods overpowered the course two years ago. The man himself
says bring on the length. ``All the changes are beneficial to all
the long hitters, no doubt about it,'' Woods said. The shorter
hitters have the greatest adjustment to make _ that's the current
working theory.
</P>
<P>
   To really penalize the young limberbacks, you see, they should
have made the course shorter. Turned Augusta National into a
par-68. Not to give them any more ideas, but it would make a lovely
executive course.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Hummer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
