<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLF-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUVAL'S MASTERY LEAVES EVEN TIGER IN AWE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Because of cultural ramifications, David Duval's
recent pillaging of the PGA Tour has not triggered the type of
global giddiness that evolved into Tigermania in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Nor should it.
</P>
<P>
   What Woods did in his first full season as a professional golfer
transcended the game because of his multi-ethnic background. Woods
became a Pied Piper in pleated pants, leading minority golfers to
the nation's driving ranges and municipal courses, many of them for
the first time.
</P>
<P>
   But as well as Woods played that season, he never displayed the
total command on the golf course that Duval has shown over the past
18 months. With 11 victories in his past 34 starts, capped by a
.500 winning percentage this season, Duval heads into tomorrow's
opening round of the Masters Tournament as the world's top-ranked
golfer.
</P>
<P>
   Already, he has set a PGA Tour season-earnings record, with
$2,598,300. And he has played in only eight events, winning four.
Included was Sunday's triumph at the BellSouth Classic, an event
Duval entered primarily to hone his swing for Masters week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy's gotten to the point he's winning his warm-ups,''
Brad Faxon said. ``That's scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Watching Duval play this season, Greg Norman said, reminds him
of a stretch during his prime when Norman would walk to the first
tee wondering who would finish second to him at that event.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not from arrogance or being egotistical. That's pure
confidence,'' Norman said. ``And you can see that with David right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   With good reason. Duval is enjoying the type of stretch unseen
on the PGA Tour since the heyday of Jack Nicklaus.
</P>
<P>
   Consider: Woods won five times in his first seven months on
tour, including the 1997 Masters and 1997 GTE Byron Nelson Classic.
But he failed to continue the torrid pace and has only three
victories in the 23 months since his Nelson triumph.
</P>
<P>
   Until Duval, the hottest streak of the 1990s belonged to Nick
Price. The former Colonial champ won 10 events in 38 starts,
including two majors, in 1993-94. Duval's 11 victories in his past
34 events include triumphs in every near-major on the golf
calendar: The Players Championship, the Tour Championship and the
World Series of Golf.
</P>
<P>
   If he adds to his roll at the Masters, which would mark Duval's
third consecutive victory, he could be laying the groundwork for a
stretch unseen since Nicklaus captured 14 titles, including three
majors, in 37 starts from 1972-73.
</P>
<P>
   Woods sees something in Duval's arsenal that was missing when he
made his dizzying run in 1997: consistency. Duval leads the PGA
Tour in six of 10 statistical categories. During his closing round
of 59 at the Bob Hope Chrysler Classic, Duval's 11 birdie putts and
one eagle putt traveled a combined 54 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, Woods never has displayed that type of control with
his irons.
</P>
<P>
   ``David plays with so much control. That's something I'm getting
better at,'' said Woods, who described himself as ``a much better
player now'' than in 1997 because he has eliminated a regular
infusion of 78s and 77s from his scorecards.
</P>
<P>
   Duval is playing so well that Woods said yesterday he is
``cool'' with the notion of being ranked No. 2 in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fine,'' Woods said. ``Everybody's going to have their
runs. David's having his right now.''
</P>
<P>
   But without the accompanying hysteria, which is the way Duval
prefers it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm becoming a golf star, but I'm still not like Tiger,''
Duval said. ``Tiger is a star outside the game. Just because I've
surpassed him in one respect, I don't think I've surpassed him in
the other. I don't think I'd want to.''
WESTWOOD PLANS DELAY OF DAVID'S CORONATION
</P>
<P>
   Scan the list of Masters champions in the past two decades and
you'll notice more residents of Europe (10) than the United States
(nine). Of the past 11 Masters winners, seven have jetted in from
the other side of the Atlantic Ocean to pick up their green
jackets.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the talk heading into tomorrow's opening round has centered
on the anticipated shootout between two young Americans _ David
Duval, 27, and Tiger Woods, 23 _ who rank No. 1 and No. 2,
respectively, in the world golf rankings.
</P>
<P>
   Such talk brings a smile to the lips of Lee Westwood, a
25-year-old from Worksop, England, who is No. 7 in the world
rankings. As such, he is the highest-ranked European in a
tournament that Europeans have won more often than not since 1980.
</P>
<P>
   And, considering that the past two Masters champions have hailed
from the United States, there is the line of thinking that suggests
a European is due to haul home another green jacket. Westwood
embraces such logic, as well as the notion that the world rankings
are skewed toward enhancing the status of U.S. players.
</P>
<P>
   ``My game, right now, is fairly strong. If you look at the top
of the world rankings, although David and Tiger may be the two best
at the moment, I'm not as far behind as the rankings may suggest,''
said Westwood, who finished sixth in his last outing, at The
Players Championship (March 25-28). ``I've not played that much
this year \Rsix events\S, but I'm looking to start winning
tournaments from this week on, really. Whether I'm the European
favorite or not doesn't concern me. I'm trying to beat the rest of
the field.''
Memorable menu
</P>
<P>
   For a second consecutive year, golf legends experienced a unique
culinary experience at last night's Masters champions dinner. With
the menu selected by the defending champion, Mark O'Meara opted for
... sushi and fajitas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not much of a fish eater, in terms of cooked fish, but I
like raw fish. And I've always liked chicken and steak fajitas,''
said O'Meara, who grew up in Southern California and developed a
taste for Mexican food while living there. ``So I said, `What the
heck. It's never been served before, so we'll give it a try.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Tiger Woods' bill of fare included cheeseburgers,
french fries and milkshakes.
</P>
<P>
   Tough ticket
</P>
<P>
   Those who question whether a Masters ticket is the toughest in
sports need only check with Buck Moore, a former Augusta National
caddie who trolled the course yesterday in search of three tickets
to today's par-3 tournament. The projected recipients? His son,
Connecticut point guard Ricky Moore, and two teammates from the
Huskies' NCAA championship basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   Buck Moore, the regular caddie for Nike Tour participant Kelly
Gibson, said he was optimistic he could fill Ricky's request but
admitted he could ``use a little help'' from players or fellow
caddies in his quest.
</P>
<P>
   An Augusta native, Ricky Moore waited tables in the Augusta
National clubhouse as a teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   Tour Championship tickets
</P>
<P>
   For the second time in three years, the PGA Tour has scheduled
its final U.S.-based event of the season in Texas, when the 1999
Tour Championship visits Champions Golf Club in Houston (Oct.
28-31).
</P>
<P>
   Tour officials announced this week that 23,000 tickets to the
event are available on a first-come, first-served basis. For
information, the toll free number is (877) 250-5747.
 &LR; revheds:INSIDE THE NUMBERS  &LR; subheds:Sunday swoons Wonder why Phil
Mickelson, a 13-event winner, has yet to hoist any hardware at
Augusta National? In the five Masters where he has survived the
36-hole cut, Mickelson has averaged 69.2 strokes in the opening
round and 73.2 on Sunday. A breakdown: Season First Rd. Final Rd.
