<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8163 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPENDING-COX     04-06 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPENDING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An adjustment for inflation may lift limit on donations
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Few subjects inflame the passions of Washington
more than efforts to change the way elections are financed.
</P>
<P>
   The latest sparks are flying from calls to increase the federal
contribution limits to parties and candidates, which have stayed
flat at $1,000 since limits were first established in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lawmakers have suddenly defined reform as making it easier for
them to raise money,'' bristles Ellen Miller of Public Campaign,
which advocates publicly funded elections. ``That's deform, not
reform.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some loonies on the left who think we ought to
reduce contribution limits to $100,'' counters Norm Ornstein, a
scholar at the American Enterprise Institute who favors increased
limits and other reforms. ``You have to provide opportunities for
candidates to raise money, and that means higher limits.''
</P>
<P>
   Such extremes usually add up to one thing in Washington:
stalemate. But a variety of observers, including Ornstein and
Miller, believe that higher contribution limits could become law
this year as part of a larger deal to ban or limit soft-money
donations to the parties.
</P>
<P>
   Soft money is unregulated donations that flow to the political
parties from unions, corporations and wealthy individuals. Such
contributions are supposed to be used for generic ``party
building'' activities such as new offices or voter registration,
but soft money has emerged as the most effective end run around
contribution limits, funding tens of millions of dollars of party
``issue'' advertising and direct mail.
</P>
<P>
   No deal on soft money and contribution limits has been offered,
much less made. But the temptation to forge such a deal is becoming
irresistible, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, many of whom oppose contribution limits of any
kind, have argued for years that the current limits have not kept
up with inflation. Adjusted for inflation, the $1,000 contribution
limit should now be about $3,300.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mitch McConnell (R-Ky.), who rallied Senate Republicans to
filibuster a ban on soft money last year, held a hearing last month
on raising contribution limits _ the first signal that legislation
may be in the works.
</P>
<P>
   Reform advocates may stomach higher contribution limits in
exchange for a ban on soft money.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a commitment, especially among the advocates of
reform, to get a reform bill this year,'' says Colby College
professor Anthony Corrado, an expert on campaign finance.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, part of the reason higher contribution limits are
gaining currency on Capitol Hill is that a number of independent
experts, including Corrado, have come to believe that the $1,000
limit is simply too low.
</P>
<P>
   While incumbents generally have an easier time of raising money,
even they are chaffing under the requirement of raising money in
$1,000 increments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money chase has gotten out of hand,'' says former Sen. Dan
Coats (R-Ind.), who supports raising the limits. ``You have
senators announcing when they retire that they are just tired of
dialing for dollars,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There is much disagreement about who would benefit most by
bumping up the limits, but some evidence suggests Republicans have
the most to gain. In 1997 and 1998, Republicans captured about 54
percent of the $1,000 donors, according to the Center for
Responsive Politics.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at individual campaigns, Corrado and Ornstein argue that
challengers would be the biggest beneficiaries even though
incumbents generally enjoy a fund-raising advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``If challengers could raise more money from the people they
knew, it would be much easier for them to build up that seed money
to launch successful campaigns, or at least competitive
campaigns,'' says Corrado.
</P>
<P>
   Corrado says the problem is particularly acute for presidential
candidates, who, on average, now have to raise the maximum $1,000
contribution from four times the number of donors than a candidate
in the 1970s did.
</P>
<P>
   Ornstein blames the eroding value of contributions and the
escalating costs of campaigns for the rise in soft money, ``sham''
issue advertising from third-party groups and other dodges to the
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``When supply stays flat and demand goes up you end up with a
black market or a temptation for corruption that becomes
overwhelming,'' Ornstein says.
</P>
<P>
   Only 0.1 of 1 percent of the American public, or about 235,000
individuals, give the maximum $1,000 contribution. Reform advocates
concede that higher limits won't likely increase the numbers of
Americans who give. Those who can afford to give will simply give
more.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the problem, says Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``Candidates will not spend less time raising money,'' she says.
``You are still going to have the arms race mentality, but instead
of raising money in $1,000 chunks they will raise it in $3,000
chunks.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Simon, president of Common Cause, notes that even the higher
limits are misleading because an individual can give to a candidate
in the primary, and then the general election, campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Married couples can double their contribution, meaning that if
the limit was raised to $3,000, a couple could give $12,000 _
almost half the average annual income for a family of four.
</P>
<P>
   ``By raising the contribution limits you are sending a message
that it's money that counts and big money counts the most,'' Simon
says. ``Twelve-thousand dollars is a huge sum of money to most
citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Simon says, Common Cause could buy into higher limits
in exchange for other reforms such as a ban on soft money. ``It
depends on what the whole package looks like,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Foskett writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
