<SLUG> BC-BOSTON-REIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON REIT TO BUY 53 PROPERTIES FROM MGI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD KINDLEBERGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The real estate investment firm of Boston Capital
surfaced Tuesday as the buyer of 53 commercial properties being
sold by MGI Properties Inc. in a deal expected to bring at least
$400 million.
</P>
<P>
   MGI, a real estate investment trust based in Boston, is
liquidating its properties in an unusual move aimed at addressing a
share price it has considered depressed, and thereby maximizing the
company's value for shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   The broker in the deal, Robert Griffin of Fallon Hines &AMP;
O'Connor, Tuesday confirmed industry reports that Boston Capital
had been selected as the buyer. Boston Capital, which as of last
September owned 88,000 units of affordable housing and ranked
fourth nationally in that category, has agreed in writing to
purchase MGI's New England portfolio, Griffin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of a New England transaction, it's one of the largest
that's ever taken place,'' Griffin said.
</P>
<P>
   The New England portfolio, estimated to represent about 80
percent of MGI's value, contains few trophy properties. But its
office, research, and retail properties enjoy high occupancy and
are seen as well run. Boston Capital is in a due diligence period
after agreeing to buy the portfolio three weeks ago. Griffin
predicted the deal would close in 35 to 45 days.
</P>
<P>
   George J. Fantini Jr., a partner in the mortgage banking firm of
Fantini &AMP; Gorga, was surprised to learn Boston Capital was the
buyer even though he noted it had branched out from its core
business of syndicating tax credits for the development of
affordable housing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This in my judgment is clearly going to be the biggest
transaction they've ever done,'' Fantini said. ``They probably had
a competitive advantage because I understand they have been able to
access liquidity, which of course is a struggle for some of the
REITs these days.''
</P>
<P>
   A sell-off of REITs that started a year ago reduced the share
price of many of the publicly traded companies to the point they
were foreclosed from raising capital with secondary offerings.
</P>
<P>
   MGI, founded in 1971 and one of the oldest REITs, has been held
back by not having enough size to attract the attention of
institutional investors, Fantini said.
</P>
<P>
   He praised MGI's management, led by chief executive Pearce
Coues, for having the foresight to recognize the company's dilemma
and act on it.
</P>
<P>
   Coues declined to confirm that Boston Capital was the buyer. But
he said ``things do seem to be proceeding'' on the planned sale and
MGI continues to expect investors will net $29 to $30 per share
once the portfolio is sold. The 14 properties outside New England
are still on the market.
</P>
<P>
   MGI last week amended its bylaws to allow billionaire investor
Warren Buffett to increase his stake in the company to up to 15
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Griffin said Tuesday Buffett, who raised his stake to 10.3
percent, wanted more because ``he loves the way these people
operate this company.''
</P>
<P>
   MGI closed at 27 1/16, down 1/8.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
