A8167 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETBANK-COX     04-06 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETBANK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Net.Bank symbolizes change to come in bankingBy Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When she worked at Consumer Credit Counseling Service,
Jessica Long didn't pay much attention to the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Now that she's at Net.Bank, one of metro Atlanta's latest mega
creators of paper wealth, she checks it a little more regularly.
</P>
<P>
   Long keeps a stock quote function on her desktop computer screen
to track her shares in the company. When Net.Bank climbs 34 percent
like it did earlier this week, she pulls out her calculator to
update her net worth. She'll repeat the routine periodically
throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``On my way to lunch the other day, I was thinking how grateful
I am,'' said Long, who runs one of the Alpharetta, Ga. company's
fastest-growing departments _ new accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable, really. It's so exciting to see that stock
price go up and up and up, and just when it's at the point where it
can't go any higher, it just doubles practically,'' Long said
Tuesday. ``It's like winning the lottery. Who gets this chance?''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of the online banking company are up almost 270 percent
since Jan. 1. The stock hit a high of $106 after the company
announced Monday it added 8,000 accounts in the first quarter. The
company now has 24,634 accounts, nearly three times the number it
had a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Net.Bank closed Tuesday at $97.87 1/2, down $3.81 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Financial Officer Bobby Bowers said the performance of
Net.Bank's stock ``obviously had something to do with a crazy stock
market for Internet companies. But we really are just doing what we
said we were going to do.'' That's provide banking services more
cheaply than its competitors.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which has a workforce of only 40 people, offers a
range of traditional banking services. They include free checking,
money market accounts, certificates of deposit, electronic
bill-paying, debit and credit cards, mortgage loans and securities
brokerage services.
</P>
<P>
   But the bank doesn't have the overhead costs associated with a
traditional brick-and-mortar institutions and can pass along the
savings to customers in the form of higher interest rates for their
deposits and investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``This does represent what I believe is a permanent change in
how banking is going to be done,'' Bowers said. ``We're not big
enough to where we've got Wells Fargo or NationsBank worried. But
it's naive to think they haven't taken notice. ``The banks have
this problem, it's called overhead,'' Bowers added. ``It's the
traditional delivery channel, and banks can't just walk away from
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Net.Bank was created in October 1996 with the idea of starting
the nation's first federally insured bank to operate solely on the
Internet. The company went public in July 1997. It held a second
public offering of 2.4 million shares in February.
</P>
<P>
   On CNBC Tuesday, Chief Executive D.R. Grimes said he expects
profits to grow at a healthy clip this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The analysts' expectations this year are for about 100 percent
earnings per share growth and about 90 percent next year. We have
no reason to doubt that,'' Grimes said while being interviewed at a
TV station in Raleigh, where he was visiting colleges with his son.
</P>
<P>
   The bank earned $4.46 million last year, compared with a loss of
$5.58 million in 1997. In the first quarter, it is expected to earn
9 cents a share, according to First Call.
</P>
<P>
   Grimes owned 179,062 shares in the company as of March 29,
according to an Securities and Exchange Commission filing. That
stake was worth $17.5 million at Tuesday's closing price.
</P>
<P>
   Net.Bank's growth has been rapid and massive. In 1998, deposits
grew from $58.7 million to $283.6 million. Total assets climbed
from $93.2 million to $388.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Net.Bank now has more than $500 million in assets. The company
has not yet released data deposits.
</P>
<P>
   The average daily balance for a typical traditional bank account
is between $4,000 and $5,000. Net.Bank's average daily balance for
a typical account is $14,000. The company, however, doesn't allow
more than $100,000 in any one account.
</P>
<P>
   Net.Bank is strengthening its marketing efforts to make the name
``Net.Bank'' more widely known. Its marketing budget was bumped
from $695,000 to $3.6 million this year. The company is advertising
in newspapers, magazines and on banking and finance Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Keane, an analyst with BancBoston Robertson Stephens, said
Net.Bank's continued success will hinge on its ability to
cross-sell other services and products to its customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what's important to understand is what they can do to
create a financial portal, a powerhouse,'' Keane said. ``Consumers
have always said they feel more secure doing e-commerce with their
bank. Net.Bank has started cross-selling, with credit cards and
insurance. I expect to see that increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where the sizzle is going to come from,'' Keane added.
``It just makes a lot of sense for people to start at the site
where their funds are held.''
</P>
<P>
   Net.Bank's offices take up 7,500-square-feet of a one-story
brick office off North Point Parkway in Alpharetta. Reflecting its
growth, the company is moving this summer into 19,000 square feet
of space at another location about a mile away.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 40 people employed at the company, about 20 are in the
call center. The jobs pay between $22,000 and $40,000.
</P>
<P>
   Bowers said Net.Bank expects to add 40 more jobs this year, 20
of which will be in the call center.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Clothier writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
