<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-TEACHERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLEGE GROUP ADMITS FAILURES IN PRODUCING TEACHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The state's largest association of colleges Tuesday
conceded for the first time that its schools are largely to blame
for the stunning failure rates on the Massachusetts teacher
certification tests, and vowed to work with state officials to
improve the quality and quantity of public school teachers.
</P>
<P>
   The association's recommendations on how to improve the teacher
force dovetailed with those supported by state officials, but
marked a sharp contrast to a summit meeting last summer where the
colleges did little more than argue that state leaders were
unfairly bashing them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The colleges and universities share the concerns of the
citizens about teacher preparation,'' said Marjorie Bakken,
president of Wheelock College and head of the Association of
Independent Colleges and Universities of Massachusetts, which
released the report including the recommendations Tuesday. ``Do we
need standards? Yes. Do we need testing? Yes. The colleges
presidents and members of the faculty agree with everyone in the
Commonwealth that teaching standards are something we believe in; .
. . we are prepared to do something, we want (our schools) to be
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet almost as fast, members of the 55-college association, known
as AICUM, continued to do what they have done since the teacher
test results were released a year ago: criticize the test itself
and call for a different one to be administered. They also faulted
state leaders for not giving test takers enough information about
the exam in advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``A part of what we are doing is owning up to the problem, But
having said mea culpa, let me assure you there is enough culpa to
go around.'' said AICUM president Clare Cotton.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he acknowledged, ``We need to cut off the circle of
blame.''
</P>
<P>
   The report's recommendations agreed with state officials that
there should be a test for teachers, and that the state should
decertify teacher education programs where too many graduates can't
pass the test. The colleges also asked for more time to improve
their programs before the state begins decertifying. Under
regulations passed last fall, any program where at least 80 percent
don't pass over two years will lose state certification, meaning
its graduates cannot be hired in state schools. The test, of basic
literacy and subject knowledge, has been given four times over the
past year, and each time, about half the candidates failed.
</P>
<P>
   The report asked for five years, and suggested 80 percent may be
too high a rate to expect at first, proposals Chancellor of Higher
Education Stanley Z. Koplik agreed were worth considering.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm encouraged by this,'' Koplik said. ``I think the fact that
they've said `We've identified some things we can do within our own
institutions' is progress.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the colleges turnaround is a product of necessity.
Under new federal law, students in programs that lose certification
will not be eligible for most financial aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``No institution, public or private, can afford the consequences
of running a program in which students can't benefit from federal
student financial aid,'' said Diana Pullin, a professor of
education at Boston College and a co-author of the report.
</P>
<P>
   While the report agrees with the need for a test, it argues that
the test the state used may not be a reliable measure of teachers'
skills. The authors said it was hard to judge the validity of the
test because the state had released so little information about it.
It suggested the company that designed the test produced it so
quickly that it could not be properly scrutinized. The report
suggests the test, which was designed specially for Massachusetts,
be replaced by the Praxis test, a test used in other states.
</P>
<P>
   The authors stopped short of saying the test was unfair.
However, Pullin said, ``There needs to be a better definition of
what teachers need to know and do. There needs to be some comfort
that the tests are valid.''
</P>
<P>
   Dominic Slowey, a spokesman for the company that designed the
test, National Evaluation Services of Amherst, Mass., said the test
had been developed over almost 18 months, from the time the company
first bid. The company asked about 5,000 educators across
Massachusetts to help determine what the test should measure. It
showed test questions to 300 college faculty members, and
pilot-tested those questions with 1,500 students.
</P>
<P>
   ``These same people who are complaining have seen the test,''
Slowey said. ``There is ample information out there about it. It is
not shrouded in secrecy.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, at a press conference to release the report,
association members seemed eager to criticize the test while at the
same time insisted it was time to move beyond criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every college president I have talked to has said `Maybe we
weren't doing all that we should have.','' Cotton said. ``Nobody
has said `We were doing it perfectly.''
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged the colleges were late arrivals to the
discussions about improvement, but explained, ``It's a new high
stakes world. It takes a while to adjust to this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
