u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-BANKS-ART-2TAKE     04-06 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-BANKS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MR. FIXIT FOR JAPAN'S BANKING SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By SHERYL WuDUNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ As a samurai, Hakuo Yanagisawa would have never bothered
to sheathe his sword. He spends his time feinting and darting and
backing his adversary _ Japan's banking system _ against the wall.
The establishment seems ready to yield.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after Yanagisawa took over as chief regulator of
Japan's banking system in October, word raced through town that two
bank presidents had committed suicide. It wasn't true, but it
captured the fear felt by bank executives that Yanagisawa's demands
on them would be unbearably taxing and that their jobs might no
longer be secure.
</P>
<P>
   Yanagisawa has suggested that he wants fewer banks. He has
bullied five banks into pulling out completely from international
business. And others have caved in to his demand that they abolish
the deeply ingrained practice of ``sodanyaku,'' in which former top
executives continue to draw large salaries and retain a
company-paid car and driver until the day they die.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Yanagisawa, a 63-year-old member of Parliament,
shrugs off the talk of suicides and undue pressure. He argues that
his rule is harsh only in comparison to the Finance Ministry
officials who, he says, governed the banks for years ``tenderly,
like a mother.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are absolutely not giving the Japanese financial
institutions the cruel treatment or giving them an impossible or
unsolvable agenda,'' he said. But, he added pointedly, ``I am
convinced that this is a time of change.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Resolution Trust Corp. in the United States, which
simultaneously shut down numerous savings institutions and bailed
out many others, the Financial Reconstruction Commission that
Yanagisawa heads will rely on a combination of carrots and sticks.
</P>
<P>
   Yanagisawa and other government officials say the banks wiped
off all the bad debt from their books on March 31, the end of the
fiscal year. They set aside $77 billion, enough both to cover the
bad debt and provide a cushion for good debt that might go bad.
</P>
<P>
   The day before, the banks buttressed their weak cushion of
capital when the government funneled in large chunks of cash in a
bid to restart the recessionary economy. The government hopes that
the infusion of $64 billion will encourage banks to take more
lending risks, thus easing the credit squeeze.
</P>
<P>
   Yanagisawa is attaching some strings to the money. He demanded
agendas for restructuring, which now include cutting one in three
board directors on average.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, when banks distribute their preferred shares to the
government, in return for taxpayers' money, they will have to watch
their stock prices closely. If a bank's stock slides, then the
government could increase its stake when it converts its preferred
shares, which do not carry voting rights, into common stock. In
some cases, like that of Daiwa Bank, the government could start
stepping up its voting stake beginning as early as June.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time in Japanese banking history that the
share price is important to management,'' said Robert Zielinski, a
banking analyst at Lehman Brothers in Tokyo. ``If they let the
share price drop, they might be owned by the government.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Yanagisawa is hardly a radical. A former Finance
Ministry official, he rose in the bureaucracy as an elite graduate
of Tokyo University. As a politician he has defended farmers, a key
constituency. He rarely drinks more than one beer at a time and he
does not play golf. His idea of a good time is a walk through a
modern art museum with his wife, a woodblock artist.
</P>
<P>
   And though his aides leap when Yanagisawa calls, especially to
nightly meetings that often end at 10 p.m., they say he takes good
care of them, sometimes ordering take-out for those who work until
2 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Yanagisawa contends that Japan is near the end of its eight-year
battle with bad debt, and an increasing number of financial experts
_ while still worried about Japan's enormous economic problems _
are encouraged by the growing sense that banks will not collapse
and throw the system into shock.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Yanagisawa has been winning plaudits where it
counts _ in the marketplace. The stock market is up some 20 percent
from its low in October and bank shares have leapt about 60 percent
since then. Some overseas hedge funds and other investors are
betting that the worst has passed and that the potential for gains
now outweighs the risk of further losses.
</P>
<P>
   The changes inside the banking system may seem to come slowly,
but progress is being made. Bank executives are losing their
bonuses, salaries are being cut, and more and more employees are
afraid of being fired. Banks are re-evaluating their customers,
writing off loans, calling in others or demanding partial
repayment. They are unloading unwanted real estate, as well as
selling some bad loans.
</P>
<P>
   The Financial Supervisory Agency, which Yanagisawa's commission
oversees, says it plans to set up an electronic monitoring system
at the banks over the summer, and it is considering sending in
full-time inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there has been a lot more talk than action, and
Yanagisawa has critics. For one thing, no one believes that the
banks' books are clean just yet. The present estimate of $77
billion in bad debt is only a tiny fraction of the various
estimates that previously made the rounds _ $650 billion and higher
_ though it is unclear whether previous estimates were too high or
the present one too low.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts say the banks need to anticipate at least another
$85 billion in bad-debt disposal next year, and even more public
money, especially if the economy retreats again.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've put some stability under the tottering structure, but
they haven't repaired it,'' said Alicia Ogawa, managing director at
Nikko Salomon Smith Barney. ``They have a lot of good policy out
there. The question is: Is the government really going to enforce
it? Judging from recent history, there's not a lot of good hope.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
