<SLUG> BC-GA-LEGIS-TRANSPORTATION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Barnes: GRTA no miracle cure
 &HT;    By Kathey Pruitt
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Apowerful new state agency to tackle metro Atlanta's
traffic and pollution problems became law Tuesday with a flourish
of Gov. Roy Barnes' pen.
</P>
<P>
   But Barnes cautioned Atlantans weary of gridlocked commutes and
blankets of smog hanging over the downtown skyline not to expect
immediate relief from the new Georgia Regional Transportation
Authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the end of our problems. I want to make sure
everybody understands that up front,'' Barnes told a cheering group
of business and community leaders gathered to witness the event.
``It's not even the beginning of the end. But it does give us the
tools to begin with.''
</P>
<P>
   Just how those tools will be used _ and who will use them _ are
the unknowns that will determine whether GRTA actually helps
improve traffic congestion and air quality or becomes simply
another acronym in the alphabet soup of state agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes has yet to announce any members to the 15-member GRTA
board, saying the appointments will come within the next 45 days.
He expects the authority to begin working with the state Department
of Transportation and Atlanta Regional Commission planning body
this summer to produce a transportation plan by the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   But until the board is in place, GRTA can't begin to determine
how aggressively it will approach commuter gridlock and reigning in
the urban sprawl that continually expands Atlanta's regional
boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a very tough task,'' said John Williams, the
Metro Atlanta Chamber of Commerce chairman and likely GRTA
candidate. ``GRTA could be required to negotiate in a very tough
way with local governments and neighborhoods. Sometimes people
don't like to do things differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes, for one, expects an expanded network of High Occupancy
Vehicle (HOV) lanes and more bus service linked with passenger rail
corridors. In addition, he said he wants GRTA to recommend a
package of tax cuts and other incentives for business and
individuals to encourage use of transportation alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he hasn't talked with Barnes about an appointment,
but is open to an offer. Also considered potential candidates are
Ray Weeks, a developer and head of the Regional Business Coalition,
Pete Correll, the Metro Atlanta chamber official who pushed the
state to address traffic and pollution, and DeKalb County CEO Liane
Levetan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't go on the way we have, with gridlock and
development,'' said Levetan, an early supporter of the initiative.
But she acknowledged that county officials may have to accept some
tough decisions as the new authority gets into its work.
</P>
<P>
   Other more cautious supporters agreed. ``This was the easy
part,'' House Minority Leader Bob Irvin (R-Atlanta) said of the
tussles to pass the legislation ``The hard part is what it's going
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   GRTA, which Barnes made the cornerstone of his legislative
agenda this year, has broad powers. It can start and run a new mass
transit agency, levy $2 billion in revenue bonds, influence local
zoning decisions and prod local governments into raising money _
including taxes _ to pay for regional transportation projects.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, GRTA will have final say on transportation projects
in 13 metro Atlanta communities now facing a loss of federal
highway funds because of chronic pollution, but it will expand to
cover other areas of the state as their pollution problems grow.
Governments that refuse to comply could lose a variety of state
grants, a major change in policy that gives teeth to previously
unenforced regional plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tremendous first step, almost a leap,'' said Mark
Woodall of the Georgia Sierra Club.
</P>
<P>
   Kathey Pruitt writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
