<HEADER>
A8173 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-BANKS-ART-2NDTA     04-06 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-BANKS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 TOKYO: good hope.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Others complain that key decisions about the banks were based on
hasty inspections. Teams of 10 inspectors from the Financial
Supervisory Agency spent more than two months pouring over the
books of each bank, but their work may be suspect because many had
previously worked in the Finance Ministry, which has been seen as
too gentle on the banks.
</P>
<P>
   Yanagisawa has been trying to boost the credibility of his
watchdogs, and he refused to move into the same office compound as
the Finance Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese bankers themselves are skeptical about rapid change.
One Japanese executive said real change could come only when his
generation retired. Another banker said that unless senior
management sets a good example, it would be hard to impose changes
in pay scales, eradicate lifetime employment or curb pension and
other benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``My worry is that by the time the FSA says they will fire
management, I think it will be too late,'' said the banker. ``The
problem that many banks face is that they can't make the tough
decisions to invest in new businesses when their mission now is to
fire and get rid of the bad loans.''
</P>
<P>
   Japan's banking system faces a number of obstacles before it
regains its balance, much less before it becomes internationally
competitive. Banks need to catch up in technology _ they are not
even fully linked to the Internet _ and transform the way they
perceive and perform their business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem in the Japanese banking system now is that they
are not making money,'' said a senior official at the Financial
Supervisory Agency. ``The challenge they face is to look for new
businesses where they can expect higher profitability.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time in Japan, there are new young entrepreneurs,'' he
added, speaking on the condition he not be identified. ``I hope the
banks would help people take over old traditional sectors and
enterprises in Japan, so that each enterprise becomes more active
in taking risks.''
</P>
<P>
   While some analysts are encouraged by the new direction, they
say Yanagisawa's commission, which is supposed to oversee the
supervisory agency for another two years before its mandate
expires, must keep up the pressure. Otherwise, the banks will lapse
into old habits.
</P>
<P>
   One worry is that the financial supervisors are stretched too
thin. With banking reform on track, the agency now wants to turn to
the problems at smaller, local financial institutions, as well as
to the billions of dollars in bad debts burdening the insurance
industry. But it cannot afford to ignore the banks.
</P>
<P>
   The government demanded detailed plans from the banks on how
they would refocus their businesses, but Yanagisawa was
disheartened to find that almost all of them chose the same path:
to strengthen their retail business. The problem, he says, is that
banks still aim to protect stakeholders _ employees in particular _
rather than the shareholders who nominally are the owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can call it the Japanese character if you want, but I can
definitely say that all of corporate management, not just the
management at banks, is stakeholder management, not shareholder
management,'' said Yanagisawa. ``And they are inclined all to look
at what other banks are doing. They want to be in a stable
condition together. And considering the future of the Japanese
industry, that is a little bit of a headache.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone acknowledges that any progress will be slow. Hideichiro
Hamanaka, deputy commissioner at the supervisory agency, lit some
incense _ perhaps for good luck _ and likened Japanese banks to
aircraft carriers, which require time to adjust to a new heading.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new direction for the Japanese financial companies has
been set,'' he said. ``One or two years down the road the new
direction will be evident.''
</P>
</TEXT>
