<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGES BROADENING OF HATE-CRIMES LAW &HT;    
 &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, linking the ethnic slaughter in
Yugoslavia to hate crimes in the United States, urged Congress on
Tuesday to add women, homosexuals and the disabled to those covered
by a federal hate-crimes law.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very humbling, I think, for those of us who think we have
brought the modern world and prosperity and rationality to all of
human affairs to see what is going on in the Balkans and to see
these terrible examples here in our own country,'' Clinton said in
endorsing bipartisan legislation. ``We have to be, in the United
States, absolutely resolute about this.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed 1999 Hate Crimes Prevention Act, pending in both
houses of Congress, would broaden the U.S. hate-crime statute by
making violence against women, gay men and lesbians, and disabled
people a federal offense.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the law applies to violence only against racial and
religious minorities.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, identical to one that died in Congress last year,
would also remove a provision that limits federal jurisdiction to
instances when the violent act interfered with the victim's
exercise of a federally protected right, such as voting.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said in a White House speech that the Justice and
Education departments will develop with private companies an
educational program for middle-school students to teach them the
evils of intolerance and the value of diversity, the president
added.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice and Education departments will also begin to include
data on hate crimes among youngsters in the agencies' annual
reports on school safety, Clinton said. The Education Department
also will collect data on hate crimes and bias on college campuses,
he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another cruel irony, isn't it?'' Clinton said. ``College, the
place where we're supposed to have the most freedom, the place
where we're supposed to be the most rational, the place where we're
supposed to be able to think the highest thoughts with the greatest
amount of space, we have significant hate-crime problems there. And
we need to shine the light on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's endorsement of the legislation and his call for more
information about campus violence followed the killings last year
of James Byrd Jr., a 49-year-old black man from Jasper, Texas, and
Matthew Shepard, a gay 21-year-old University of Wyoming student.
</P>
<P>
   One white supremacist has been convicted and sentenced to death
and two others face murder trials in the June 7 death of Byrd, who
was beaten, tied to the back of a pickup truck and dragged for
nearly three miles.
</P>
<P>
   In the Shepard case, Russell Arthur Henderson pleaded guilty
Monday to kidnapping and murdering the student. Wyoming District
Judge Jeffrey Donnell sentenced Henderson to two consecutive life
terms in prison.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL ADD END)
</P>
<P>
   Despite its bipartisan support, the legislation has spurred
controversy in legal circles over whether Congress can outlaw
violent crime, historically subject only to state criminal law.
</P>
<P>
   To make a state offense a federal crime, Congress must cite a
power it has under the Constitution. To satisfy this requirement,
the bill cites Congress' authority to regulate interstate commerce
as the basis for allowing U.S. lawmakers to federalize hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the bill point to the compelling need for federal
officials to assist cash-strapped states in prosecuting hate
crimes. Opponents counter that, while the bill has a noble intent,
it may be unconstitutional and would further burden an already
overworked federal judiciary.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
