<HEADLINE>
SCOTLAND FORMALLY CHARGES TWO LIBYANS IN LOCKERBIE BOMBING 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MARLISE SIMONS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMP ZEIST, Netherlands _ In a short session that the United
States and Britain had awaited for more than a decade, the Scottish
police formally charged two former Libyan intelligence agents on
Tuesday with the bombing of Pan Am Flight 103 over Scotland in
1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``The men were charged with conspiracy, murder and contravention
of the Aviation Security Act of 1982,'' a court official said.
</P>
<P>
   The listing of the charges included one other step: A police
officer read out, one by one, the names of the 270 people who died
in the air and on the ground after the jet exploded over the
Scottish village of Lockerbie. The victims, from 21 nations,
included 189 Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing of the aircraft, believed to have been ordered by
Libya, brought severe U.N. sanctions against the country in 1992,
including an air embargo and a freeze of foreign assets. The
sanctions were suspended on Monday, hours after Libya handed over
the two suspects to a U.N. envoy in Tripoli, the Libyan capital.
</P>
<P>
   The two Libyans suspected of planting the bomb, Abdel Basset
al-Megrahi and Al-Amin Khalifa Fahima, arrived in the Netherlands
on Monday. They now await trial by three Scottish judges, who will
hear the case without a jury on a former air base here.
</P>
<P>
   The base will be considered Scottish soil for the duration of
the process, which is likely to take more than a year. It was an
agreement to hold the trial in a country other than Britain or the
United States that finally ended Libya's resistance to handing over
the two men.
</P>
<P>
   The two Libyans were also brought separately before a Scottish
judge. A court official said that each defendant was accompanied by
his lawyers and an interpreter, who translated the proceedings into
Arabic. Neither man made a plea or a declaration, court officials
said. Both men have said in the past that they are innocent.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants' appearance before the police and the judge were
part of closed pretrial proceedings. The trial itself will be open
to the public. Under Scottish law, authorities have until April 15
to commit the defendants to trial, and the trial should then begin
within 110 days. But the start may be postponed for several more
months, Scottish officials here said, because defense lawyers have
asked for extra time to prepare their case.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy security surrounded Tuesday's events at Camp Zeist, a
former military base near Utrecht in the center of the country. The
base, set in quiet woodlands, is tightly sealed by metal fencing
and patrolled by Scottish police officers with heavy weapons and
trained dogs.
</P>
<P>
   The suspects are being kept in temporary cells until a more
permanent prison is finished. If they are convicted, they will
serve their sentence in Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   Several other buildings on the base are being converted for the
procedures. A police station and quarters for the more than 100
Scottish police officers and guards who have arrived here are
ready. But work is only just starting to convert a former school
into a courthouse and to adapt other quarters for offices and a
press center.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of converting the base and holding the trial has been
estimated at close to $200 million, which will be shared by Britain
and the United States. Dutch officials said that some of the work
was held off until the Scottish authorities were reasonably sure
that the two men would be handed over.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, many police officers and two prosecutors arrived here
from Scotland only this weekend. Scottish officials have not
announced who the judges will be.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
