A8179 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES07-CO     04-06 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves bullpen takes another hit
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The bullpen woes continue.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday afternoon the Braves put left-hander Mike Remlinger
on the 15-day disabled list for a pulled muscle in his back,
retroactive to last Friday. Remlinger's back had bothered him the
past few times he'd thrown but when he warmed up in the bullpen
during the Braves game Monday night it got worse.
</P>
<P>
   After throwing for trainers on Tuesday, the Braves activated
minor league left-handed pitcher Derrin Ebert, who was on his way
to Class AAA Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was probably the last thing I wanted, but it's probably the
smartest thing,'' said Remlinger, who will be eligible to return on
April 18. ``We don't have the luxury of being able to say `Let's go
a couple days and see where we are.'''
</P>
<P>
   This time of year starters aren't able to go as long, so manager
Bobby Cox needs as many innings out of his relievers as possible.
Ebert will be used in the same situations as Remlinger.
</P>
<P>
   This on the heels of Kerry Ligtenberg's season-ending arm injury
and Mark Wohlers' continued struggles is not what Atlanta needs.
</P>
<P>
   Remlinger, who came to the Braves from the Cincinnati Reds as
part of the Denny Neagle-Bret Boone deal, made nine appearances in
spring training with a 5.28 ERA and 13 strikeouts in 15.1 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Remlinger said he doesn't feel the twinge in his latissimus
dorsi muscle throwing fastballs but it bothers him on his breaking
pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time it happened I thought I had a cramp,''
Remlinger said. ``Once I got loose it went away.''
</P>
<P>
   Ligtenberg surgery
</P>
<P>
   Reports from Birmingham, Ala. were that Ligtenberg had
successful ``Tommy John'' surgery on his elbow Tuesday afternoon.
In the process, Dr. James Andrews discovered Ligtenberg had nearly
a complete tear of his medial colateral ligament. Andrews
transplanted a tendon from Ligtenberg's wrist to repair his elbow.
Ligtenberg is expected to need a full year to recover.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a pretty good-sized tear, pretty much all the way
through,'' Braves trainer Dave Pursley said. ``It probably never
would have healed (on its own), so we were way ahead of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ligtenberg figures to be ready at the start of next season.
</P>
<P>
   Ebert excitement
</P>
<P>
   Ebert's big league call-up came on his cellular phone in a Rack
Room shoe store at the Haywood Mall in Greenville, S.C. He was with
his wife Stacy, who was shopping for shoes to wear in a friend's
wedding when Richmond trainer Jim Lovell called to tell Ebert to
head south on I-85 for Atlanta instead of north toward Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   ``(At first) I thought I was traded to Florida in the
player-to-be-named later,'' said Ebert, referring to the recent
deal in which the Braves acquired pitcher Justin Speier.
</P>
<P>
   After sleeping for about three hours, Ebert woke up Tuesday
morning and drove to Atlanta. He showed up at the ballpark at 10:30
a.m. to find no one around. So he checked into a hotel and came
back around 1 p.m. He was excited.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been playing professional baseball for almost six years
now,'' Ebert said. ``I want to make it on my ability not because
I'm a filler, but if this is the best way to break in, I'll take
any chance I can to pitch on that mound.''
</P>
<P>
   Ebert got word that he would in fact be activated after batting
practice on Tuesday when Remlinger walked up and shook his hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't ask for anything better,'' said Ebert, a native of
Anaheim, Calif. ``I've dreamed of this every since I was 4 years
old. And the best part is I get to make the trip and (I may get to)
go home and play in L.A.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves will play in Los Angeles April 19-21. That's one day
after Remlinger is eligible to come off the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Ebert made one start with the big league club this spring when
Tom Glavine had a cut finger and responded with three scoreless
innings against the Indians, striking out five of the 11 batters he
faced. Last year in Richmond, Ebert went 9-9 with a 4.51 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ETC.
</P>
<P>
   Said rookie reliever Kevin McGlinchy about his major league
debut on Opening Day against the Phillies: ``I was fired up all
day. When they played the Star-Spangled Banner, I felt like I could
got to war for my country.''
</P>
<P>
   McGlinchy said by the time he got out on the mound in the
seventh inning, he had relaxed, but he made a point not to look up
in the crowd. ``I was totally focused,'' he said. So much so that
he didn't realize who the hitter was until after he coaxed a pop-up
from Scott Rolen on his third consecutive fastball....
</P>
<P>
   New second baseman Bret Boone celebrated his 30th birthday on
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
