<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-IMF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA STARTING KEY TALKS WITH IMF 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By NEELA BANERJEE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The International Monetary Fund and the Russian
government will begin a critical round of negotiations later on
Wednesday that is aimed at completing an economic program and loan
package to avert a threatened default on Russia's foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
   Its Treasury and central bank reserves vastly depleted by the
financial crisis that began last August, Russia hopes to get the
fund to refinance about $4.8 billion in loans coming due this year,
most of that in the second and third quarters.
</P>
<P>
   The country also needs an economic program approved by the IMF
to successfully restructure nearly $17 billion in debt payments it
owes to a group of Western lenders.
</P>
<P>
   If it fails to get the fund's approval, Russia is likely to
default on all its foreign debt payments. ``Time is running out for
Russia,'' said Christopher Granville, a strategist for the Russian
subsidiary of Robert Fleming, a British brokerage firm.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has been wrangling with the fund for months to win new
loans to refinance its debts. A breakthrough of sorts came last
week when Michel Camdessus, the IMF's managing director, and Prime
Minister Yevgeny Primakov issued a joint statement after a meeting
in Moscow that noted that both sides had agreed to a primary budget
surplus of 2 percent of the gross domestic product in 1999 ``and
most of the measures needed to achieve it.''
</P>
<P>
   It is now up to the IMF delegation of economists that arrived
here on Tuesday and the Russian Cabinet to work out the details of
those measures, which are of a sort that is consistently among the
toughest obstacles to completing aid packages.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the problem is a budget shortage of around 30
billion rubles, or $1.2 billion, Moscow economists estimate. To
reach an agreement with the monetary fund, Moscow must find ways to
raise enough revenue to fill the gap, including taking such
unpopular steps as imposing a tax on gasoline or export tariffs on
metals and other raw material.
</P>
<P>
   Changes in the tax code must be approved by the
communist-controlled lower house of Parliament, which vigorously
opposes legislation linked to the IMF.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's strained relations with the West, especially the United
States, over NATO attacks in Yugoslavia will make things even
harder. Indeed, the Russian legislators recently undermined IMF
talks by voting for a cut in the value-added tax, which accounts
for nearly half of budget revenue, according to the
Russian-European Center for Economic Policy, a research group here.
</P>
<P>
   Skittish so far about entering into a long battle with
Parliament, Primakov's Cabinet has taken ``a salami-slicing
approach to negotiations with the IMF,'' said a Western diplomat,
speaking on condition of anonymity. ``Instead of developing a few
major efforts to discuss with the IMF,'' the envoy said, ``the
Russians come up with 400 nickel-and-dime measures that grind down
their opponents across the table. It shows a political weakness.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the government's waffling, most economists in Moscow
believe that the IMF and the Russians will announce an economic
program in the coming days, and that the IMF's board will approve
the new credits at its meeting at the end of this month. Clearly,
neither side wants a default. Russia owes the IMF $19 billion,
making it one of the lender's largest debtors.
</P>
<P>
   For Moscow, default could cause another round of possibly
disastrous economic and political upheaval. For the IMF and its
major contributing nations, a default by Russia would signal the
failure of their efforts to nurture market capitalism here.
</P>
<P>
   But after lending Russia money for years, often on the strength
of just its promises, the IMF is expected to be much tougher this
time. It may insist, for example, on a trial period to see if
Russia can make good on the conditions of the economic program
before the first installment of aid is released.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the differences from the past is that the IMF is
demanding that certain laws be passed before the money is
released,'' said Rudiger Ahrend, director of the Russian-European
Center for Economic Policy. ``The IMF doesn't want to be seen as
giving money to countries heading for another failure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
