<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8191 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO-SUIT-NYT &LR;      04-06 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TAKES STEP TOWARD TOBACCO SUIT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn.)   (nk) 
 By BARRY MEIER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Justice Department said on Tuesday that it had hired a law
firm that represented Minnesota in its lawsuit against cigarette
makers to consult with government officials as they consider legal
action of their own against the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   The hiring of the firm, Robins, Kaplan, Miller &AMP; Ciresi, of
Minneapolis, is a signal that the government is intensifying its
preparation of a lawsuit that would seek to to recover Medicare
costs from tobacco producers.
</P>
<P>
   The firm played the lead role in a lawsuit filed by Minnesota in
1994 to recover Medicaid costs spent treating smoking-related
illnesses. The case was settled for $6.5 billion last May, just as
it went to a jury. The sum was the biggest recovery per capita for
any state that sued the cigarette makers.
</P>
<P>
   The firm, one of several hoping to snare the high-profile role,
is held in high regard by both anti-tobacco advocates and tobacco
lawyers for the quality of its work and intensive pretrial
preparation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have devoted thousands of hours to uncovering and
learning the facts relating to tobacco litigation,'' the acting
assistant attorney general, David W. Ogden, who heads the
department's tobacco litigation task force, said in a statement.
``Their extraordinary experience in this area will be very valuable
to the department's tobacco litigation team.''
</P>
<P>
   In January, President Clinton said in his State of the Union
message that the Justice Department would file an action seeking
the recovery of federal money, from Medicare and other programs,
spent on smoking-related illnesses. He said the money would be used
to strengthen Medicare, the federal program that provides health
care to the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last two years, the tobacco industry has reached
settlements to resolve state claims for Medicaid reimbursements
worth $246 billion. Federal officials have tried unsuccessfully to
recover the federal share. Now, the federal government is
contemplating recovering costs from a different pool of federal
money, Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Williams, a tobacco industry spokesman, said that
producers did not believe that the Justice Department had the legal
grounds to bring a tobacco claim and that the appointment of the
Minnesota firm suggested that it was turning to plaintiffs' lawyers
as a political step.
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration has handed the keys to the Justice
Department over to the trial lawyers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials said that the law firm had agreed
to advise and assist agency lawyers through June 30 at a rate of
$75 per hour plus travel costs and expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials said they also did not contemplate a future
contingency fee arrangement under which the law firm would get a
portion of any money that the Justice Department won if the
government pursued a lawsuit and prevailed in court or settled the
case.
</P>
<P>
   In the Minnesota case, the firm had a contract which would have
paid it 25 percent of the $6.5 billion, or $1.6 billion. The
lawyers agreed to take $427 million, or 7.1 percent, though under
an arrangement that paid them more quickly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
