A8197 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MASTERS-NOTES07-C     04-06 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-NOTES07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Masters Notebook: Nicklaus gone fishin'
 &HT;    By Michelle Hiskey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ A Masters without Jack Nicklaus is like ``losing
the diamond out of the wedding ring,'' Greg Norman said Tuesday,
and golf fans feel the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Recovering from hip replacement surgery ended the Golden Bear's
streak of 40 straight Masters (he won six). The last time he spent
this week elsewhere, he was a freshman at Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   Cards and calls from other players have been nice, he said.
``Twenty years ago, they'd be happy to see me go,'' he said, with
no trace of sentimentality. He's not that emotional about missing
Augusta, he said, because it's part of a more significant streak of
146 majors that ended last summer when hip pain forced him to miss
the British Open.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus will fly to the Bahamas Wednesday for a fishing
vacation, and expects a return to ``solid golf'' in a few weeks, in
time for his Memorial Tournament next month.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday threesomes
</P>
<P>
   The unusually large field of 96 players is scheduled to go off
in threesomes Thursday for the first time since 1962. That's only
happened a few times at Augusta, and usually because of weather. On
Friday, those groupings will remain the same, only their teetimes
will be reversed so the early groups play late and the late groups
play early. On past Fridays, players were paired by first-round
scores. The changes have been made to accomodate a field that is
expected to grow larger in the future. 1992 winner Fred Couples
said playing with an extra partner could help him with club
selection on par 3's or reading a putt on a similar line, but he
expects the duration of the rounds to increase by 45 minutes
because threesomes will take longer to putt out.
</P>
<P>
   Unlucky 13
</P>
<P>
   Couples says he's not haunted by finishing second last year, so
let's just say he's thought a lot about it. ``It's probably
bothered me for a year and 10 days so far, and it's climbing,'' he
said. ``And it'll bother me because I'm sure Thursday I'll hit a
perfect 3-wood on 13 and hit an iron into the green.'' That's the
hole that undid him last year, when he hooked his drive, chipped
out of the woods, hurriedly smacked a 6-iron into the water and
double bogeyed. He caught a break, though, when preparing this
week: he missed Friday's cut at the BellSouth Clasic . ``A
blessing,'' he called it, because of the arduous trek around the
TPC at Sugarloaf in Duluth. He hurt his back earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   You're unbelieveable
</P>
<P>
   Amateur Hank Kuehne's massive drives have put him in a class
beyond even Tiger Woods and John Daly, according to Nicklaus. He
watched the U.S. Amateur champion on the back nine par 5's, and
Kuehne flew the trees on the dogleg 13 and hit a wedge into 15.
``Unbelievable,'' said Nicklaus, watching from a cart with
tournament chairman Hootie Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The Toms Zone
</P>
<P>
   David Toms walked off the 18th green with a new appreciation of
the 64 he shot in last year's final round. He fired a 29 on the
back nine, including six birdies in a row. ``I'm not sure how I did
it, to be honest with you,'' he said. ``You just get it going and
get in a zone.'' Did he predict a repeat of that low score this
year? ``Absolutely not,'' he said. But after a tie for ninth at the
BellSouth, he wouldn't be a bad player to have in the office pool.
</P>
<P>
   Kuchar's weakness
</P>
<P>
   Matt Kuchar's Masters smile finally has dimmed. It took a
persistent virus to bring down the Georgia Tech amateur, a
sensation last year because of his play and disposition. Kuchar
managed only nine holes of his practice round with Steve Pate and
Ben Crenshaw Tuesday before leaving the course to seek medical
attention. He had fallen ill during last weekend's Carpet Capital
Collegiate in Rocky Face, Ga., and has yet to rally. ``He had a
tough time just walking up No. 8,`` said his father, Peter Kuchar,
who once again is serving as caddy. ``It really has sapped his
strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Multicultural dining
</P>
<P>
   Defending champion Mark O'Meara served sushi and sashimi
appetizers followed by steak and chicken fajitas, as the host of
Tuesday night's Champions Dinner. ``Sandy Lyle (of Scotland) had
haggis (or sheep stomach),'' O'Meara said. ``I know you've got to
put hot sauce up there for the haggis.''
</P>
<P>
   Round numbers
</P>
<P>
   Some featured groupings for Thursday and Friday: David Duval,
Nick Price and Bob Tway (1:23 p.m., 10:27 a.m.); Tiger Woods,
Sergio Garcia and Tim Herron (10:38 a.m., 1:34 p.m.); Mark O'Meara,
Hank Kuehne and Lee Westwood (1:12 p.m., 10:16 a.m.); Tom Watson,
Matt Kuchar and Stuart Appleby (10:16 a.m., 1:12 p.m.).
</P>
<P>
   Here today, gone tomorrow
</P>
<P>
   You might see players in practice rounds who won't be around for
the tournament They are honorary invitees, mostly players who have
major championships and are not eligible for the Masters field. For
example, New Zealand's Bob Charles, who won the 1963 British Open,
played a practice round Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Hiskey writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. Glenn Sheeley and Steve Hummer contributed to this
report
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
