<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8199 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REFUGEES-DECISION-BOS     04-06 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFUGEES-DECISION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US FACES TOUGH SELL IN MOVING REFUGEES TO GUANTANAMO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD AND TERESA MEARS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The massive US airlift of refugees to Guantanamo
Bay could begin by the weekend, provided relief workers can
convince the Kosovars it is in their best interest to leave their
homeland and family members behind for an undetermined stay at
military base in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   J. Brian Atwood, the head of the US refugee operation,
acknowledged Tuesday that relocating as many as 20,000 Kosovar
Albanians to the US naval base at Guantanamo ``is not an ideal
solution.'' He said it is a temporary, emergency measure aimed
primarily at saving lives and easing a humanitarian crisis in the
countries where Kosovo's ethnic Albanians have fled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We clearly don't like the notion that we have to relocate
people, but there is no other way . . . except to move families
away from the area for a temporary period of time,'' Atwood said in
a telephone interview with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of them want to leave the region, all of them want to
return home,'' Atwood added. ``We are going to have to do a bit of
an education job to explain how important this is. It is a major
logistics task.''
</P>
<P>
   In its effort to lead an international effort to relocate
120,000 refugees temporarily, the White House announced Tuesday the
US military was preparing to receive 20,000 at the ``safe haven''
of Guantanamo Bay, the large naval base that housed as many as
51,000 Cubans and Haitans in the early 1990s. Atwood said within 72
hours the military would erect a tent city and provide personnel,
food, and medical services for refugees who agreed to be airlifted
out of the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Atwood said the task is complicated by the fact that many of the
refugees have been separated from family members as they fled to
makeshift camps in Macedonia and Albania and in many cases, have
lost track of husbands, sons, or brothers left behind in Kosovo.
Atwood, the administrator of the US Agency for International
Development, said his ``top priority'' is keeping Kosovar families
and communities together.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are trying to do is send a message to the refugees and
to Mr. (Slobodan) Milosevic that this a very temporary solution to
this problem, and we want to do the kind of preparation that will
enable them to live as close to a normal lifestyle as possible,''
Atwood said.
</P>
<P>
   But while US policymakers predict NATO's bombing campaign will
pressure the Yugoslav president to reverse course and let the
ethnic Albanians return, no one can predict how long the refugees
might remain at Guantanamo. Those who know it call it a steamy,
boring base that has not been very hospitable to refugees in the
recent past, and was the scene of some rioting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guantanamo is absolutely inappropriate and unsuitable,'' said
Cheryl Little, executive director of the Florida Immigrant Advocacy
Center and an advocate for Haitian refugees. ``It's hot, it's dry,
it's isolated, and most important, it's a prison camp. It's already
proven to be unsuitable as a refugee camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Little said the military was not equipped to provide schools,
counseling, recreation, and other services the refugees will need.
Maria Dominguez, executive director of the Human Rights Institute
at St. Thomas University in Miami, monitored conditions at
Guantanamo during the 1994-95 refugee crisis and said the camps
initially lacked running water, air conditioning, or any way for
refugees to communicate with family off the base.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Herb Josey, spokesman for the Navy's Atlantic Fleet in
Norfolk, Va., said Guantanamo could accommodate 1,300 people
immediately. ``As more refugees come in, we will continue to
build,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A number of refugees at Guantanamo attempted suicide Dominguez
said, and the military needs to provide more psychological support
this time: ``The issue is hopelessness, because they don't know how
long they are going to be there,''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a place you want to keep people for very long,''
said a spokesman for the Senate Judiciary Committee, which oversees
immigration and refugee issues and is expected to have a hearing
next week on the Kosovo crisis. ``Senators generally support what
the administration has done, but they will want to know how long
the refugees will be there, living in tents, with nothing to do.
This is not a long-term solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Atwood said US officials had reviewed the record of refugee
unrest at Guantanamo and were convinced the Kosovars ``are not
going to be there that long, and they will be be treated as
guests.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, that is exactly what they will be. US officials
confirmed Tuesday that refugees will not be protected under US
immigration law and will have no rights, including the right to
petition for political asylum, because they are not being housed on
US territory. Kosovar refugees in the United States may stay in the
country for 18 months and can apply for asylum and permanent
resettlement during that time.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Stein, executive director of the Federation for American
Immigration Reform, a group that advocates stricter immigration
policies, said airlifting Kosovo refugees out of the region is a
``knee-jerk response that will lead to bad results,'' including
eventual permanent relocation of thousands to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we take people, they never go,'' Stein said, noting it
would be more cost-effective and consistent with sound refugee
policy to house the Kosovars closer to home and an eventual
repatriation.
</P>
<P>
   Atwood could not put a pricetag on the relocation, but he said
it will be ``a very costly operation.'' So far, the United States
commitment to take 20,000 refugees matches that of Turkey, and
exceeds other NATO countries, including Germany (10,000), Canada
(5,000), and Greece (10,000).
</P>
<P>
   According to most recent State Department figures, more than
450,000 Kosovar Albanian refugees have left their homes in the last
two weeks. Some 284,000 are in Albania and 136,000 are in
Macedonia, including many thousands still waiting to cross the
border. Atwood predicted the total could rise to 1 million.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Mary Leonard reported from Washington; Teresa Mears reported from
Miami.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
