<HEADLINE>
NATO AIRSTRIKES TO CONTINUE DESPITE MILOSEVIC'S CEASE-FIRE &HT;    
 &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic declared a
unilateral cease-fire in the Kosovo conflict Tuesday in observance
of the Orthodox Easter holiday, but NATO leaders said airstrikes
would continue until he capitulates to the alliance's terms.
</P>
<P>
   The cease-fire announcement was made in Belgrade as the NATO
campaign entered its 14th day with more intense attacks on military
targets across Yugoslavia and on Serb army and security police
positions in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials reported that clearing weather had enhanced
visibility, enabling its aircraft to fly more missions and making
it easier to pick out targets. Thirty targets were hit repeatedly,
including bridges, roads, and Serb troops and weapons in the field
and at staging areas in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   At the Pentagon, Rear Adm. Thomas R. Wilson told reporters that
the Serbian air defense system ``is still a threat'' to NATO planes
but that more missiles sites and Russian-made MiG fighter aircraft
have been destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   He said that NATO is beginning to see evidence of ``declining
morale'' in the Yugoslav army as increased sorties are flown
against Serb troops and police in Kosovo. He said strikes early
Tuesday morning that destroyed the headquarters in Belgrade of the
Yugoslav special forces and security police had had a devastating
effect on key elements of the Serb military operations.
</P>
<P>
   But he acknowledged, as did NATO officials in Brussels, that the
allied campaign has yet to grind down the Yugoslav military
defenses to a level that that would allow NATO planes to conduct
lower and more focused attacks on key positions.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Wilson, the director of military intelligence for
the Joint Chiefs of Staff, said the NATO strikes had interrupted
food, fuel, and equipment resupply routes, making it increasingly
difficult for Yugoslav forces to rout the predominantly ethnic
population of Kosovo and drive them from the country.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear, however, whether the bombing campaign had
contributed to Milosevic's decision to implement a unilateral
cease-fire in Kosovo where ethnic Albanian rebels have continued to
engage Serb forces. He also did not say how long the cease-fire
would last.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, the United States and the 18 other countries in the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization rejected Milosevic's call for an
end to the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen, who left Tuesday for a meeting
in Brussels with his NATO counterparts, called the cease-fire
``completely unacceptable'' and ``absurd.'' President Clinton,
meanwhile, stressed that the bombing campaign would only intensify
until the Yugoslav dictator withdraws his forces from Kosovo,
accepts the creation of a democratic government there and allows
the resettlement of ethnic Albanian refugees under the protection
of an international security force.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States would never choose force as anything other
than a last option,'' Clinton said during a White House event on
hate crimes. ``Mr. Milosevic could end it now by withdrawing his
military police and paramilitary forces, by accepting the
deployment of an international security force to protect not only
the Kosovar Albanians, most but not all of whom are Muslims, but
also the Serbian minority in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's announcement of a cease-fire was expected, and
Clinton conferred with other NATO leaders over the weekend and
again on Monday in anticipation of it. The alliance leaders
decided, according to a senior White House official, to respond
with a determined and united front in order to drive home the point
to Milosevic that the time for negotiations has long passed and
that ``half measures'' aimed at stopping the bombing will not be
acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has made clear what we expect ... a mere
cease-fire is clearly not sufficient to meet these conditions,''
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said in his daily briefing for
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   As the NATO campaign entered its second week, a bomb aimed at a
military facility fell on the Serb coal mining town of Aleksinac
100 miles southeast of Belgrade, killing four civilians and
injuring more than 20. In Brussels, NATO Air Commodore David Wilby
said it was ``possible that one of our weapons fell short of the
target'' due to a guidance system problem or fire from Serb
defenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever the reason, any unintended damage to civilian
property or loss of life is very much regretted,'' Wilby said at
NATO's daily briefing.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance has been careful to emphasize that it is targeting
military sites associated with Milosevic's government and has no
quarrel with the Serb people. But the strikes have hardened
sentiments among the Yugoslav population.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday evening as the air campaign continued, residents of
Belgrade could be seen linking arms and forming a human chain in
the streets and across bridges in the city. Many of them wore
targets pinned to their clothing.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL END)
</P>
<P>
   The strain also was evident in U.S.-Russia relations Tuesday.
Moscow joined with Milosevic's government to condemn the attack on
Aleksinac. In an effort to ease tensions, Vice President Al Gore
telephoned Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov and urged him
to use his influence with Milosevic to get him to agree to NATO's
terms for ending the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, administration officials said Gore urged
Primakov to intercede on behalf of the three U.S. Army soldiers
captured last week by Serb forces while patrolling along the border
of Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
