</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAV MILITARY SEEMS TO HAVE MASTERED THE ART OF HIDING FROM
NATO ATTACKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Military analysis) 
(See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-SERBIA, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA,
KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-ISRAEL, KOSOVO-ALLIES, KOSOVO-AIRLIFT,
KOSOVO-DIPLO) 
(ac) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON with ERIC SCHMITT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ When the skies cleared over the Balkans on
Monday, it seemed to be a promising day for NATO's high tech
warplanes to attack Yugoslav tanks and armor in Kosovo. But
alliance officials acknowledge that few, if any, heavy weapons were
hit.
</P>
<P>
   As they reviewed photos of the day's targets, NATO experts were
unable to confirm the destruction of a single tank or military
vehicle, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav military's ability to conceal its tanks and heavy
weapons from attack _ hiding them in churches, barns, forests and
towns _ has considerably complicated NATO's air campaign, pointing
to some of the self-imposed limits of air strikes alone.
</P>
<P>
   If the Yugoslav military truly believed it faced a land attack,
it would have to position its tanks and armor to cut off the roads
and other avenues of attack. This would give the NATO pilots
something to shoot at.
</P>
<P>
   An allied ground force would also make it possible for military
teams in Kosovo to call in and direct air strikes to their targets
with greater precision.
</P>
<P>
   Further, many of the Serb attacks are being carried out by
relatively small bands of soldiers with automatic weapons. They
would be no match for American ground forces, but they are hard to
find and target from the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they are doing is low-tech,'' a NATO military expert
said. ``They can send 20 guys in a truck to terrorize a village.''
</P>
<P>
   But the allies have ruled out sending ground troops into Kosovo
until the fighting stops, largely to avoid political dissent at
home. Paradoxically, the absence of a credible threat to use land
forces may prolong the air campaign and subject NATO to more
political strain.
</P>
<P>
   President Slobodan Milosevic appears to be husbanding his
military in hopes that NATO will call off the air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic has already accomplished a lot of his objectives in
terms of ethnic cleansing,'' a senior NATO diplomat said. ``Now
Serbs are concealing themselves and preserving themselves to fight
another day. It is going to be a prolonged campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, NATO's relentless bombing is beginning to take its
toll. Allied warplanes have also pounded fuel depots, dropped
bridges, cratered airfields and pummeled surface-to-air missile
sites from one end of Yugoslavia to the other.
</P>
<P>
   But allied warplanes have had only mixed success so far bombing
the Serbs forces involved in assaulting the ethnic Albanians in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon announced Tuesday, for example, that it had
launched an intensive series of raids against the Yugoslav Third
Army, which has been spearheading the offensive in Kosovo. While
Pentagon officials said they had struck the army's ammunition and
fuel, as well some forces in the field, they provided no account of
how many tanks, artillery and other heavy weapons might have been
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Rooting out Serb armored units, by all accounts, is not a simple
proposition.
</P>
<P>
   British Air Commodore David Wilby, NATO's military spokesman,
said, for example, that the Serbs are familiar with the pattern of
allied take-offs from Aviano, Italy, and other NATO airbases. They
try to time their assaults against the ethnic Albanians to the
lulls in the bombardment, according to Commodore Wilby, and hide
when they know allied warplanes may be on their way to bomb them.
</P>
<P>
   Even when allied warplanes catch Serb forces in the act of
rounding up ethnic Albanians, they often cannot attack them for
fear or hurting the Albanians or inciting the Serbs to take out
their frustrations on civilians.
</P>
<P>
   That was the case when an allied reconnaissance plane detected
Serb armored forces ringing the village of Glodane in Kosovo. The
Serb aggression was noted, but an attack was ruled out, at least
until the ethnic Albanians were shipped out.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There are also technical difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   Allied warplanes used infra-red targeting devices to find Iraqi
tanks during the 1991 Persian Gulf War. Though the tanks were dug
up to their turrets in the desert, allied targeting equipment
detected the heat from the tanks against the cool desert night.
After finding the tanks, allied warplanes blasted with them
laser-guided bombs, a technique known as ``tank plinking.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kosovo is not a desert. Western military officials have to
careful about bombing civilian buildings since they cannot always
tell if civilians are inside. And because the Serbs often turn tank
engines off to conserve fuel, they often do not produce enough heat
to be detected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tank plinking is not efficient,'' Maj. Gen. Charles Wald, the
vice director of strategic plans and policy for the U.S. Joint
Chiefs of Staff, said in an interview Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   NATO planes can unleash a punishing blow if they find convoys on
the road, and they did blast one Tuesday, according to the Western
European diplomat familiar with classified military briefings.
</P>
<P>
   Allied planners also hope that fuel and other shortages will
force Serb units to relocate, giving NATO warplanes a change to
catch them on the move.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over time, they'll have to move to sustain themselves,''
General Wald said. ``Time is on our side.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Many Serb units, however, have done their best to hunker down.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are hiding armored vehicles in barns, churches, forests
and population centers,'' the Western European diplomat said. ``It
is not easy to attack them even when we know they are in there
because we don't know if civilians are also there.''
</P>
<P>
   The British encountered the problem earlier this week. Now that
the weather has improved, they were hoping their Harrier planes
could strike Serb ground forces, but many of the warplanes were
forced to return to base without dropping bombs because they could
not find any Serb ground units to hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We suspect the Serbs realize the advantage the better weather
gives us and are going to great lengths to hide their heavy
equipment and escape,'' said Vice Admiral Sir Ian Garnett, the
chief of joint operations for Britain's Defense Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, NATO was unable to confirm the destruction of a single
tank or military vehicle on Monday, according to NATO's military
spokesman, Air Commodore David Wilby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the good weather we have not achieved the level of
damage on these forces that we should have liked,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The commodore insisted, though, that Tuesday's strikes appeared
to be more successful. The Serbian tactics, in fact, does not mean
that the allies cannot uncover Serbian tanks and artillery.
</P>
<P>
   Allied forces are flying unmanned Pioneer drones over the
battlefield and are trying to use them to target Serb units. Apache
helicopters may also improve the alliance's striking powers. Apache
crews, using night vision systems can hover to the earth and attack
Serb forces with laser-guided Hellfire missiles.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, allied officials sought to put the best face on
the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``So long as they are hiding they are not killing,'' said
British Defense Minister George Robertson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
