</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-TOBACCO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE URGES PHILIP MORRIS TO STIFFEN ANTI-SMOKING ADS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- As Massachusetts launches a fierce media attack on the
tobacco industry, it is joining 16 other states in calling on
Philip Morris Cos. to kill its current anti-smoking ads and replace
them with a more aggressive message.
</P>
<P>
   State officials are telling the nation's largest cigarette maker
that its $75 million media campaign, which is mandated as part of
last year's national tobacco settlement and is aimed at
discouraging teenage smoking, is not effective.
</P>
<P>
   Officials cite a study by a Chicago firm, Teenage Research
Unlimited, which found from 20 focus groups that teenagers are not
influenced by the Philip Morris ads and that their messages do not
offer compeling reasons not to smoke.
</P>
<P>
   The Philip Morris ads show kids in various settings being lured
to take a cigarette but rejecting the offer. One teenager is on a
school bus, another is on stairs in a school building, and third is
on a playground.
</P>
<P>
   The company's ads, which trumpet the theme ``Think. Don't
Smoke'' and began last December, were tested in the research groups
against smoking prevention ads produced by Massachusetts,
California, Arizona, and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The research firm, which was hired by the states to conduct the
focus groups, concluded that ads aimed at teenagers should not be
developed with so-called ``choice theme'' and in fact such a theme
may dilute the impact of harder anti-smoking ads aired by state
public health officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would appear that Philip Morris's decision not to reveal
the health consequences of smoking has severely impaired the
effectiveness your youth campaign,'' Howard K. Koh, commissioner of
the state Department of Public Health, said in a letter sent this
week to Geoffrey Bible, Philip Morris's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Koh and the other 16 public health officials said they wanted
the cigarette company to hire an independent media company to
develop new ads _ a proposal Philip Morris Tuesday rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Merlo, senior vice president for Philip Morris USA, said
the tobacco giant, whose brands include Marlboro and Virginia
Slims, had no intention of dismantling its current ad campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think, from our research, that our message does communicate
the message not to smoke and communicates it effectively,'' Merlo
said.
</P>
<P>
   Merlo also noted that as part of the settlement agreement, the
industry would provide $206 billion over the next 25 years to the
states that will allow them to develop their own anti-smoking
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the company said Mayor Thomas M. Menino's office had
requested to the Philip Morris commercials to present at an
upcoming teen summit. Merlo said federal public health officials
say that using messages with multiple themes to discourage smoking
is very effective.
</P>
<P>
   The move comes as Massachusetts prepares a hard hitting
television and billboard ad campaign. It is called the ``Outrage''
campaign and attempts to further sully the industry's already
tarnished public image.
</P>
<P>
   The media blitz, which begins Thursday, will run for several
months. For the first month, the department is spending $400,000
for the production and airing of the ads, which will appear mostly
on news public affairs and sports programs and selected popular
dramas.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-second spots attack cigarette makers for referring to
cancer as a ``public relations problem.'' They charge the
executives are not out to make a profit but rather a ``killing,''
and then cite statistics showing that 470,000 Americans die each
year from smoking-related diseases. The ads also charge that
environmental laws would prevent the dumping of many of the
additives in cigarettes into a public landfill.
</P>
<P>
   ``With these ads were are going right at the tobacco industry,''
said Mark Leccese, spokesman for the Massachusetts Department of
Public Health. ``The actions of the industry in the past 20 years
have been outrageous and we want people to get outraged.''
</P>
<P>
   Merlo said Philip Morris could not respond to ads that she nor
anyone else at the company has viewed.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I can tell you as an tobacco corporation executive I have
never made those statements,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
