<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8206 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ALLIES-770&AMP;ADD     04-06 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ALLIES-770&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO DECIDES IT WILL KEEP BOMBING, REJECTING MILOSEVIC'S TRUCE
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-SERBIA, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA,
KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-ISRAEL, KOSOVO-AIRLIFT, KOSOVO-DIPLO) 
(nk) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ NATO resolved on Tuesday night that it will
keep bombing Yugoslavia until President Slobodan Milosevic agrees
to withdraw all his attacking forces from Kosovo, to let refugees
return with an international military force to protect them, and to
negotiate a political settlement, Western diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   The allies rejected Milosevic's announcement Tuesday of an
immediate unilateral cease-fire for the Orthodox Easter on Sunday
as ``a propaganda ploy,'' in British Defense Secretary George
Robertson's words, unless it is accompanied by compliance with
their other conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to get diplomacy restarted in a series of meetings here
this week, the allies have moved away from their earlier insistence
that before anything else can happen, Yugoslavia must sign the
accords on autonomy for Kosovo that were presented at negotiations
at Rambouillet Castle in France last month.
</P>
<P>
   NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana said Tuesday night that his
conditions for an end to bombing are ``the return of all refugees
and therefore the deployment of an international security presence,
the withdrawal of Serb military, police and paramilitary forces,
and putting into place a political framework for Kosovo on the
basis of the Rambouillet accords.''
</P>
<P>
   Only after a peace agreement is reached, according to the
allies' original plan, will the alliance be willing to send a
NATO-led peacekeeping force of 28,000 soldiers into Kosovo, a
province of Serbia, which is the major entity remaining in
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the Rambouillet agreement made largely inapplicable by
Milosevic's expulsion of hundreds of thousands of ethnic Albanians
from the province in the last two weeks, European diplomats said
the allies are willing to send in peacekeepers to escort the
returning refugees before a final settlement is negotiated.
</P>
<P>
   But NATO still insists that the fighting has to stop before it
will send in allied troops, and it is not planning to order
soldiers to fight their way into Kosovo, diplomats say. Military
commanders say that if the allied bombing campaign goes on long
enough, the Serbian forces will eventually be unable to put up much
resistance. But for the moment, the Serbian forces are still
driving the ethnic Albanian majority out of the province.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unilateral announcement of a cease-fire by Yugoslavia is
essential but insufficient,'' German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder
said in a statement Tuesday night. ``What is decisive is the actual
behavior of Yugoslavian troops on the ground in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder said NATO still demanded an immediate end to all
military activity and killing, a retreat of Serbian forces from the
region and the stationing of international forces in the region to
allow refugees to return home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only by meeting these conditions can the humanitarian
catastrophe come to an end and lead the way to a peaceful,
multi-ethnic and democratic Kosovo, where its inhabitants can live
in peace,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Russia welcomed Milosevic's cease-fire announcement and has
repeatedly demanded an end to the NATO bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In deference to vigorous Russian objections, allied officials
said, the alliance would not insist on plastering the NATO label
over the international force they eventually hope to send to Kosovo
to enable the ethnic Albanian population to return home. The allies
also still hope Russia will agree to take part in such a force.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that if NATO participates in a peacekeeping force, it
should lead it, but we don't think we need to say that if it
irritates the Russians,'' a European diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to get Russia to resume cooperating with Western nations
to put pressure on Milosevic to agree to peace terms acceptable to
the allies, Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott and four
high-level European officials plan to meet in Brussels Wednesday
with Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Aleksandr Avdeyev.
</P>
<P>
   This will be the first meeting of the ``contact group''
countries _ Russia, the United States, France, Britain, Germany,
and Italy _ since NATO began bombing Serbian military targets March
24 in response to Milosevic's refusal to accept the Rambouillet
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what the allies expected from the meeting with Avdeyev, a
European diplomat responded, ``To get a sense of whether the
Russians are still willing to work with us.'' Russia stopped all
cooperation with NATO after the bombing started, and Prime Minister
Yevgeny Primakov, on his way to the United States, turned around in
midair and canceled the visit.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Officials of the six contact group nations, plus Canada and
Japan, also plan to meet this week in Dresden, Germany, to discuss
the Kosovo crisis, a meeting requested by Russian President Boris
Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   German Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer said on Tuesday night
that if the diplomatic meetings went well enough, a meeting of
Russian and Western foreign ministers on Kosovo, including
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, could be held in Europe by
the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
   The allies and European Union officials also hope to get Foreign
Minister Aleksandar Dimitrov of Macedonia to agree to speed up his
country's acceptance of ethnic Albanian refugees from Kosovo when
they meet with him in Brussels Thursday and Friday, officials here
said.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonia, with a delicate ethnic balance between Orthodox
Christians and Muslim Albanians, barred an estimated 65,000
Albanian refugees from crossing into Macedonian territory from
Kosovo at one border point this week out of fear of being
overwhelmed. European diplomats at NATO said they hoped that the
European Union and international financial institutions would step
up financial aid to Macedonia to encourage it to accept more of the
refugees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
