<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATLANTA-AIRPORT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hartsfield International to get busier
 &HT;    By Gary Hendricks
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A dramatic 22 percent increase last year in overseas
air travel has prompted Hartsfield International Airport officials
to add four new gates to the international passenger Concourse E,
the airport's chief planner said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Designs are expected to be completed and bids taken this summer
on the project estimated to cost between $20 and $25 million, said
Hartsfield Assistant Manager Andy Bell. The project should be
finished in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The gates are the first major addition to the 24-gate,
1.3-million-square-foot concourse that was built in 1994 at a cost
of $304 million.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to be out of gate space on E this summer,'' Bell
said. ''We really need them.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the number of international passengers increased to 4.3
million annually, up from 3.5 million in 1997 and spurred mainly by
Delta Air Lines adding five South American cities and a new Tokyo
flight to its schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Delta also will inaugurate four new European routes this summer
to Barcelona, Athens, Rome and Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, with us expanding this summer with the European
routes, it would justify the airport adding the gates,'' said Delta
spokesman John Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Hartsfield officially gained the title of world's busiest
airport Tuesday when Airports Council International, a Geneva-based
industry group, reported that 73.5 million passengers used the
Atlanta airport in 1998, an increase over 1997 of nearly 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Hartsfield surpassed Chicago's O'Hare airport, which had 72.3
million passengers, and Los Angeles, which had 61.2 million.
London's Heathrow airport was in fourth position with 60.7 million
passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Bell said the four gates would be added to Concourse E and the
existing gates will be reconfigured to accommodate new, wider
aircraft, such as the Boeing 777. Delta took delivery of the first
of 13 777s in late March and the plane will figure prominently in
the airline's international service.
</P>
<P>
   The airport already has taken a stop-gap measure to handle
increased international passenger volume. Three ground level doors
have been added to each end of Concourse E so that passengers can
be shuttled to planes on the tarmac in a huge tram, called a
Planemate, that rises on hydraulic lifts to the cabin level of the
plane. Planemates were used extensively during the Atlanta Olympics
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Some gates on Concourse E also serve domestic flights during
lulls in international traffic. The peak period for international
flights occurs between mid-afternoon and early evening at
Hartsfield. All the airlines schedule flights to arrive and depart
at the same time. But unlike domestic traffic with high turnover of
planes at gates, international planes sit for several hours at a
gate, preparing for an extended flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``A plane sitting on the ground for four hours eats up gate
space,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Hendricks writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
