<SLUG> BC-2000BABY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What to do to conceive the first baby of 2000
 &HT;    By Pat Thomas
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ If you are thinking it would be nice to deliver
your next child on Jan. 1, 2000, stop reading and get busy.
</P>
<P>
   Friday has been determined to be the optimal day to conceive if
you're aiming for a due date of 1/1/00. Well, the optimal date give
or take a couple of weeks, human gestation being a somewhat
imprecise process.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of couples around the world are so entranced with the
idea of a millennial baby that an infant industry has sprung up.
There are television documentaries in the works, dozens of
newspaper and magazine articles, thousands of baby-making tips,
even a Millennium Conception Kit that can be yours for $49.99 (it
includes candles, massage oil and a pregnancy test).
</P>
<P>
   And yes, we know all about how the millennium really starts on
Jan. 1, 2001, but why let the facts get in the way of hype? Radio
stations will give prizes to the first Y2K baby and some hotels are
offering special rates for couples hoping that a change of scenery
will get something started.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site www.babycenter.com is one of a number of Internet
sources for all things newborn. Under its ``Millennium Baby
Overview,'' it offers topics such as ``Women Who Want Millennium
Babies,'' ``Media Coverage of Millennium Babies'' and ``Y2K
Worries'' _ after all, you don't want the delivery room lights to
fail just as the doctor says, ``Push!''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some advice to would-be millennial moms and dads gets
a whole lot more specific, but it's best to leave some things up to
the imagination. Web sites: www.having-a-baby.com/millenium.htm
www.babycenter.com www.babyzone.com www.babynames.com (Potential
millennium baby names include Millie, Milo, Century . . . you get
the picture.) Books:
</P>
<P>
   The Unofficial Guide to Having a Baby by Ann Douglas and John
Sussman, M.D. (Macmillan, $15.95)
</P>
<P>
   Pat Thomas writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
