<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8214 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MASTERS-NUHN-COX     04-06 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-NUHN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For Duval, it's all in a day's work
 &HT;    By Gary Nuhn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ It took two questions. The media, in all its
assembled majesty, can be quicker than a snake and as subtle as a
hammer.
</P>
<P>
   So first David Duval fielded a question on how it feels to win
one of every three times, then this: ``There's kind of a perception
out there that you're somewhat of a dullard,'' a man said to the
world's current No. 1 golfer. ``Why do you think that is?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You tell me,'' Duval said evenly. ``Is that your impression?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You haven't clarified whether you're talking about my
personality or my golf game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Personality,'' the guy said.
</P>
<P>
   And then Duval defined himself. ``If that's a perception,'' he
said, ``then that's fine. That's how I try to play. I try not to
make mistakes. I try to make it a very stress-free round.''
</P>
<P>
   And a stress-free interview.
</P>
<P>
   I can think of 100 players who would either have stood up and
left the room when that grenade was rolled up, or leaped over the
table and made like Stone Cold Steve Austin with the questioner.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in that brief exchange, Duval showed the traits that have
brought him to the top of the world golf rankings. He defused it
with a shrug.
</P>
<P>
   Bogey? Big deal.
</P>
<P>
   Insult him? Big deal.
</P>
<P>
   He has composure. Bank it.
</P>
<P>
   And in this game, you put composure along with an average drive
of 287.5 yards; laser irons and the putting touch of a painter and
you've got a guy with a future.
</P>
<P>
   Reminiscent of. . .let's see, Nicklaus, Watson, Hogan. Yes.
</P>
<P>
   Duval is 27, but could still pass for a college kid _ 6-foot,
180 pounds with closely cropped blond hair.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the 54-minute exam, he was asked, ``If you hit a bad
shot, it doesn't bother you. You're called a dullard and it doesn't
bother you. What does it take to get you to lose your cool? Do you
remember losing your cool?''
</P>
<P>
   He smiled for a moment, then said, ``I have, I'm sure.''
</P>
<P>
   The room roared. How could he not remember the last time he
flipped?
</P>
<P>
   ``To be successful out here,'' he said, ``you have to find the
demeanor and personality under which you perform your best. For me,
that's not worrying about stuff. I can't do something over. I can't
re-hit a shot. I can only move forward. So that's what I try to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharks only move forward.
</P>
<P>
   Duval has been a shark for a year-and-a-half. He has won 11 of
the last 34 times he put his tee in the ground, which is like a
baseball player hitting .500.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a blank line on his resume: Eleven wins, but no
majors.
</P>
<P>
   So here he is at his fourth Masters, coming off consecutive
victories the past two weeks. He knows in golf a man's career is
measured in majors, and he is ready to start collecting his.
</P>
<P>
   If only it were that easy.
</P>
<P>
   Someone mentioned that when Greg Norman was at the top of his
game, he used to stand on the first tee and wonder, ``Who's going
to finish second?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever get that feeling?'' Duval was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. Unh unh. No.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Larry Bird. He used to show up for the
three-point shooting contest at the All-Star game and ask the other
players, ``Which one of you is going to finish second?''
</P>
<P>
   ``But the Bird quote I like best,'' Duval said, ``is when he was
asked if Michael Jordan was the best player ever. He said, 'Well,
one of the two best.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Duval isn't made of that stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you chosen your clothes for Sunday?'' someone asked,
implying something that would go with the green coat given to the
champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clean ones,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Nuhn writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
