<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-ANDERSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL IS HARMONY, ANDERSON, PITINO AVOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- After listening to Rick Pitino and Kenny Anderson
downplay the point guard's one-game ``timeout'' for unprofessional
behavior, all that's left to wonder is when they're going to pick
out the living room furniture together.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson was back at practice Tuesday, one day after he missed a
game at Orlando for what both individuals insisted was nothing
major. On four occasions, Pitino called the transgression either
``extremely minor'' or ``no big deal'' while Anderson did the same.
Both men also swore that they were sympatico on everything as well.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson: ``It's ludicrous for someone to say that he doesn't
like me or that I don't like the system. We have utmost respect for
each other. I love playing for Rick Pitino. I love being in Boston
with the Celtics. There's no dislike at all. It's frustration, the
wear and tear. A miscommunication, one of those incidents.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitino: ``I like the way he plays. Off the court, (he's) one of
the nicest guys on the team. I couldn't like a person any more than
him. On the court, (he's) like everybody else in a losing
situation: we have to get better. . . But he's a good guy.''
</P>
<P>
   There you have it. Now, how about those Wizards?
</P>
<P>
   No one heard any laugh tracks as the two men spoke. No noses
appeared to grow. Pitino insisted that Anderson was singled out
only because he had told the team a few weeks back that any future
dust-ups would be dealt with in such a fashion. Anderson, he
insisted, was Test Case 1.
</P>
<P>
   But, of course, it wasn't the first time. Anderson and Antoine
Walker had a very public spat against the Wizards earlier this
season in Washington, during a game, and both men were fined.
Pitino said it wouldn't happen again. Apparently it did last
Sunday, when Anderson did not think he should be spending as much
time on the bench. There also had been a prior ``miscommunication''
as to Anderson's defense against Mark Jackson the previous Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Both men said there was no swearing. It was more a challenge to
Pitino's authority and that is a no-no. In this instance, it meant
not going to Orlando and missing a game, a very public reprimand.
</P>
<P>
   Pitino, of course, went out of his way to say it could have been
anyone on the team. Or even him. In fact, the coach said other
players have done it, but did not get similarly spanked because
there was no punishment system in place. The coach said he told his
team a month ago, or three weeks ago &UR;  &LR; -- he said both Tuesday --
that he now expected his men to act like Alistair Cooke on the
court. (Since that time, Walker has gotten seven technicals.)
</P>
<P>
   ``What he (Anderson) did is nothing what some other guys haven't
done to each other on the court, or in a situation that is very
unprofessional,'' Pitino said. ``This is a professional basketball
team. With people watching, from children to media to everyone
else. Everyone has to act like pros at all times. Regardless of
whether we're up 20, down 20, playing great or playing poorly, your
frustrations must be kept behind closed doors.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitino said Anderson would be in the starting lineup Wednesday
night against the Wizards when the Celtics begin their first
three-in-three situation since December 1979. He said had the
Celtics been in a playoff chase, he might have taken Anderson on
the trip, but felt that it was more beneficial for the 28-year-old
to stay home and ``reflect on his frustrations about losing and
come back very positively.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson did that. He was the second player on the floor and
smiled all the way through early stretching exercises and layup
drills. Who knows what happened for the 90 minutes behind closed
doors? Afterwards, Pitino said the practice went well, that he was
``100 percent'' satisfied that Anderson had learned his lesson and
that all was well and swell, except for the 10-22 record, of
course.
</P>
<P>
   Same for Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just one of those things,'' he said. ``It shouldn't be
taken out of context or blown up out of proporton. The whole season
is wearing on everybody . . . I'm one of the oldest players on the
team. A veteran. I'll take the slap, the slap on my wrist, the slap
on my face. If that means he's going to set an example, whatever,
I'll take that and deal with it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
