<SLUG> BC-GLF-WOODS-O'MEARA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS, O'MEARA BECOME PART OF EACH OTHER'S STRENGTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Tiger Woods considered the question, shrugged his
shoulders and said yesterday that he was ``cool'' with the idea of
being replaced by David Duval as the world's top-ranked golfer.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Mark O'Meara urged journalists to discount Woods'
attempt to downplay his recent loss of status heading into
tomorrow's opening round of the Masters Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does it bother him? Probably, yes,'' O'Meara said. ``He wants
to be the man. He wants to get that No. 1 ranking back.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus ended another session with golf's version of the Odd
Couple: two neighbors from Orlando, Fla. with widely differing ages
and backgrounds who believe they know each other well enough to
clarify the other's unfinished thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   They also play pretty decent golf, as evidenced that O'Meara,
42, is the defending Masters champion and Woods, 23, won the title
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Each credits the other with helping him make improvements in
dealing with life on the PGA Tour. O'Meara points to Woods, who is
single, as a catalyst toward regaining competitive fires. That
allowed O'Meara, in 1998, to record the first two major
championships of his 19-year career.
</P>
<P>
   Woods cites O'Meara, who is married and the father of two, as a
sounding board for helping him in off-course matters.
</P>
<P>
   It was O'Meara, for instance, who first counseled Woods about
curbing his penchant for throwing or slamming clubs. It was O'Meara
who urged Woods, on the way to the 1998 Masters, to stop airing
complaints about his busy off-course schedule because the public
had little sympathy for the time demands on a young millionaire who
enters less than 50 percent of the tournaments on the PGA Tour
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, Woods has taken O'Meara's advice to heart. As a
result, Woods points to 1999 as his most enjoyable season on the
PGA Tour, although he has just one victory and has been supplanted
by Duval as the game's top player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm actually having more fun this year than ever before,''
said Woods, who won five times in his first seven months on the PGA
Tour and topped the 1997 money list with $2,066,833. ``I understand
a lot more about the tour, about how things work, about myself ...
and Mark has been part of that. And it's a beautiful thing right
now because I understand.''
</P>
<P>
   What Woods understands about his golf game is that he has
adopted some of the self-control and discipline that marks
O'Meara's game. Woods' driving distance (291.9-yard average) may be
down by five yards per pop from last season, but he's hitting more
greens in regulation (71 percent) and his putting is better. He
does have only one victory, but he has cracked the top 10 in seven
of eight starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, God, yes,'' Woods said, when asked if he considered
himself a better player today than in 1997. ``I'm more consistent
all around, and that's what you want to do. My bad round isn't 78
or 77 any more ... it's 70 or 69. I've learned that, when I'm not
on, to accept pars and accept trying to get up and down for bogey
if I hit the ball in the trees. That's improving my overall game.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara, in turn, has watched his game blossom since Woods moved
to the neighborhood in 1996. After falling short in his first 56
attempts to win major championships, O'Meara won both the Masters
and the British Open, along with player of the year honors, in
1998. Asked if he believed he would have won a major championship
without nurturing their relationship, O'Meara said, ``Probably
not.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think spending time around Tiger helped me dramatically,''
O'Meara said. ``It helped me from the standpoint that his burning
desire to want to win tournaments ... told me, `Hey, man, I am
running out of time here.' It rejuvenated me. I know when I'm
playing with him, he has oodles more talent than I've got, but it's
challenging to try and find ways to beat him. Doing that has
elevated my game.''
</P>
<P>
   All the way to the point that O'Meara, ranked No. 4 in the world
golf rankings, joined Woods yesterday in fielding questions about
pursuing Duval for the top spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, that's not a burning desire,'' O'Meara said. ``For
Tiger, I think it motivates him.''
</P>
<P>
   Just another example of how golf's Odd Couple are similar, yet
different.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
