<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-TV-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROMINENT FAMILY SELLS STAKE IN MEXICAN BROADCAST NETWORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ In a momentous but amicable parting of ways by two
of Mexico's most powerful business dynasties, the Aleman family
announced Tuesday that it was selling its 14 percent stake in the
holding company that controls Grupo Televisa SA, the largest
broadcast network in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The Aleman family's decision was disclosed at a ceremonious news
conference by the two scions who recently ascended to the command
of their family empires. Miguel Aleman Magnani, 32, is a Televisa
vice president who is the grandson of a former president of Mexico,
and Emilio Azcarraga Jean, 31, is Televisa's chairman and the son
of a legendary entrepreneur who built the company from a string of
radio stations into a huge conglomerate.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of the Alemans' share of Grupo Televicentro SA de CV,
the holding company, decisively consolidates the dominance of the
Azcarragas in Televisa, reinforcing the control of Azcarraga Jean
in a sometimes uncertain transition after the death of his father
in April 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Both Aleman Magnani and Azcarraga Jean took pains to insist that
their separation was friendly. They ended their statements with a
bearhug that drew applause from Televisa employees in the audience.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, dispelling the rumors of quarrels between the families,
whose Televisa partnership dates back 30 years, appeared to be a
far more significant priority Tuesday than disclosing the financial
details of the transaction. Azcarraga Jean said that since
Televicentro was a private company, the families had agreed not to
disclose the share price to be paid for the Aleman holding.
</P>
<P>
   Nor would he say how Televicentro, which is carrying $533
million of debt after a revamping in February, planned to finance
the purchase, valued at about $200 million based on Tuesday's
Televisa share price. He said only that several options existed and
that the Aleman family was not pressing for a quick decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be very surprised if there is any more debt capacity
there,'' said Tim Baker, head of research for Warburg Dillon Read
in Latin America. The agreement with the Alemans leaves open the
door for a major new partner.
</P>
<P>
   Xavier Von Bertrab, a Televisa executive, said there was ``no
way'' that minority shareholders would be hurt by the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Aleman Magnani said it was his choice to leave Televisa to start
a new group of Aleman businesses. He will resign from his post as
of May 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's my turn,'' he said, recalling how he had agreed to
stay in Televisa to help Azcarraga Jean secure his grip after his
father's death. Aleman Magnani did not say what kind of enterprise
his new group would undertake.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the dais was Alejandro Burillo Azcarraga, a cousin who
owns 14 percent of Televicentro. He assured Aleman Magnani that
Televisa ``remains your home.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Tuesday Azcarraga Jean and his family owned 72 percent of
Televicentro, which controls 26.5 percent of the voting shares of
Televisa.
</P>
<P>
   Aleman Magnani dismissed speculation that his father, Miguel
Aleman Velasco, wanted to get out of Televisa to stifle any
possible criticism if he runs for president of Mexico next year.
Opposition parties complained that favorable coverage of Aleman
Velasco by Televisa helped him win election as governor of the
state of Veracruz last year.
</P>
<P>
   Working against steep odds, Azcarraga Jean has surprised many
analysts with the turnaround he achieved at Televisa, which his
father ran as a personal fief. Azcarraga Jean pared the work force
to 16,500 from a high of 23,000 and shaved other costs while
widening Televisa's ratings advantage over Television Azteca, its
main competitor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
