u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COUCH-BENGALS-COX     04-06 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COUCH-BENGALS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Couch eyeing Bengals in case No. 1 pick is not him
 &HT;    By Chick Ludwig
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ After everything went down Tuesday, University of
Kentucky quarterback Tim Couch pronounced himself ready to be a
Bengal if he doesn't become a Cleveland Brown.
</P>
<P>
   He toured the Bengals' Spinney Field practice facility, visited
Cinergy Field and the new Paul Brown Stadium site, met team
president Mike Brown and most of the coaches, had a brief Xs-and-Os
session with offensive coordinator Ken Anderson and lunched on ribs
at the Montgomery Inn Boathouse.
</P>
<P>
   Most importantly, Couch discovered that, NFL-wise, the Queen
City isn't so bad after all, and that falling to the Bengals, who
have the No. 3 overall pick in the April 17-18 NFL Draft, isn't the
end of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' he said in his Bluegrass drawl when asked if he could
see himself in a Bengals uniform when the new stadium is completed
for the 2000 season. ``I think it would be great.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being so close to Lexington, it would be a great situation for
my family and Kentucky fans that would also become Cincinnati fans.
If I do come here, I'd just be worried about being the best player
I can be. It wouldn't be pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Couch still wants to be the Browns' No. 1 overall pick. But it
won't crush him if he doesn't go first.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice,'' Couch said. ``But I don't think it's the
most important thing to me. Whoever wants me, wherever I end up,
I'm just going to make the best out of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think they've (the Browns) got a big investment to make
in whoever they pick with the first pick, and they want to make
sure they can see everything they can out of a player.''
</P>
<P>
   Oregon quarterback Akili Smith is also high on the Browns' list.
So is University of Texas tailback Ricky Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, the Heisman Trophy winner who shed 20 pounds to reach
his 224 playing weight, ran a series of 40-yard dashes for NFL
scouts during a workout in San Diego on Tuesday. He had wind-aided
times of 4.4 and 4.52 seconds. Against a stiff breeze, he ran
between 4.6 and 4.72.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a three-horse race now,'' Browns head coach Chris Palmer
said in a conference call.
</P>
<P>
   Couch, who will conduct a second workout for the Browns on
Sunday in Lexington, said he hasn't been informed about the format.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'll just show up with a ball and ask 'em what they
want to see _ like meeting out in the backyard with your buddies,''
Couch said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just said they wanted another workout. So I don't know
exactly what I've got to do. I guess just go out and throw the ball
accurately with a lot of velocity. If I come out and put on a
strong show, I think it'll help me a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer then challenged Couch, who will be awfully glad he didn't
order a second slab of ribs here.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll get his money's worth,'' Palmer said. ``He better make
sure he's rested. I have no place to go Sunday except to see him.''
</P>
<P>
   Some in Bengals management were perplexed that Couch, who
originally wanted to fly from Lexington to Cincinnati, insisted on
being driven back and forth. Assistant trainer Billy Brooks served
as the chauffeur.
</P>
<P>
   A prima dona? Maybe. But one with talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got plenty of arm strength _ believe me,'' Bengals head
coach Bruce Coslet said. ``That's been the knock on him. But he can
throw the deep ball. He wasn't asked to do it a lot in college, but
he's got the ability to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Chick Ludwig writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
