<DOCNO> NYT19990406.0311 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8226 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MAIN-COX-07     04-06 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MAIN-COX-07 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NATO, DISMISSING CEASE-FIRE BID, HAMMERS TARGETS ACROSS
YUGOSLAVIA ON WEDNESDAY
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON Dismissing Belgrade's latest cease-fire bid as an
empty gesture, NATO hammered dozens of targets across Yugoslavia
early Wednesday in the most intensive strikes yet in the 15-day air
war.
</P>
<P>
   Multiple explosions rocked the area near a military airport
outside of Belgrade around 1 a.m. (6 p.m. EDT). State-run
television in the capital reported other attacks underway to the
southwest and in the industrial town of Cacak, 50 miles south of
Belgrade, where NATO says its planes have hit a major ammunition
factory in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's attacks began hours after Defense Secretary William
Cohen rejected a cease-fire proposal by Serb leader Slobodan
Milosevic, president of Yugoslavia. Cohen, who labeled the offer
``absurd,'' left Tuesday night for Brussels, where he hopes to
shore up NATO support for continuing the air war.
</P>
<P>
   On a second front, U.S. and NATO food, tents and medicine poured
into desperately overcrowded refugee camps in Albania and
Macedonia. The White House announced plans to begin within days to
send 20,000 ethnic Albanians forced from Kosovo to temporary
quarters at the U.S. naval base at Guantanamo Bay, Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Under operation ``Sustained Hope,'' the U.S. portion of what has
become a global humanitarian mission, officials plan to deliver
half a million tons of food, medicine, tents, cots and sleeping
bags into Albania and Macedonia by this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Taking advantage of a third straight night of clear skies, NATO
beefed up its armada of warplanes, adding 50 strike jets from the
USS Roosevelt aircraft carrier. That brings the number of NATO
combat and support planes in the attacks to roughly 600, half of
them American.
</P>
<P>
   State-run television in Yugoslavia showed footage Tuesday of a
destroyed housing complex where several civilians were reportedly
killed in a Monday air raid outside the city.
</P>
<P>
   NATO air commodore David Wilby said a bomb intended for a
military barracks apparently fell some 600 yards short of its
target, but he would not confirm the civilian deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said U.S. officials were
investigating the incident, in which a 500 pound laser-guided bomb
dropped from a U.S. warplane apparently veered off target Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was being aimed at a military target and it appears to have
hit an apartment building,'' said Bacon. ``One reason it could have
happened was a cloud interfered with the laser-guided mechanism of
the bomb.''
</P>
<P>
   Bacon stressed that civilians are not the target of the NATO air
campaign. It is being waged to stop Serb troops, police and
paramilitary units that have conducted a brutal campaign of
repression targeting ethnic Albanians in Kosovo, a province in the
Yugoslav state of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's Wednesday attacks followed around-the-clock strikes on
Tuesday, with British Harrier jets on search and destroy missions
reportedly hitting Serb tanks in southwest Kosovo, a sign that the
air campaign has become increasingly aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the Pentagon displayed the first visual images of
damage to Serb forces in the field the blackened wreckage of a
handful of tanks along with scattered military trucks and armored
personnel carriers hit at a barnyard staging area by armor-piercing
cluster bombs dropped en mass from the supersonic B-1 bomber.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon also reported, for the first time, ``significant''
Serb military and police casualties. While officials would not
discuss numbers, the targets outlined barracks, headquarters and
staging areas among them would imply casualties in the hundreds, at
a minimum.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials said two weeks of air raids had destroyed or
seriously damaged at least 23 targets of Serb troops or police in
and around Kosovo, as well as a half-dozen critical headquarters
operations in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said those strikes, in addition to hits on scores of
ammunition dumps, fuel depots, bridges and airfields, have crimped
the ability of Serb field forces to be resupplied or to coordinate
their activities with central commanders.
</P>
<P>
   Adm. Thomas R. Wilson, intelligence director for the U.S. Joint
Chiefs of Staff, told reporters that there is growing evidence of
morale problems among the Serb forces as the air campaign bites
deeper into the marrow of their operations.
</P>
<P>
   A weekend cruise missile attack that destroyed the headquarters
of the elite Special Unit Corps of Serb forces outside of Belgrade
has apparently struck dread in the hearts of the troops, said
Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were people in it and we have evidence that there was a
morale impact as a result of this strike,'' said Wilson. ``When you
see your comrades killed in strikes in the middle of the night from
afar, it is not conducive to keeping your mind totally on the
business at hand.''
</P>
<P>
   With the NATO strikes gaining traction after Serb forces have
run nearly 1 million ethnic Albanians out of their homes across
Kosovar, Milosevic ordered a cease fire, ostensibly in preparation
for this weekend's Orthodox Christian Easter holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic said his troops would halt their offensive in Kosovo
and he would begin immediate negotiations on the return of ethnic
Albanians an estimated 430,000 of which had fled Kosovo's borders
as of Tuesday. He made a similar offer days after the NATO bombing
began March 24.
</P>
<P>
   NATO rejected the offer immediately, saying it fell far short of
the terms NATO has long proscribed: withdrawal of Serb troops from
Kosovo; a return of autonomy in Kosovo to ethnic Albanians there;
acceptance of a NATO-led peacekeeping force there; and concrete
guarantees for the safe return of refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's cease-fire proposal contained none of those
elements, and NATO gave no pause in the air campaign to so much as
consider it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want some kind of murky or shadowy sham proposal
which, in reality, would simply reward Milosevic for the mayhem
that he has caused,'' NATO spokesman Jamie Shea told reporters at
alliance headquarters in Brussels. ``A cease-fire which says, 'I
finished my work and now I'm going to go home and leave the mayhem
behind me,' is not something that we would be prepared to accept.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
