<HEADER>
A8231 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     04-06 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN UNFAMILIAR HAT IN THE RING
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Tom Walton  &LR; sends word, from a clipping in Nation's Restaurant
News, that  &UR; Herman Cain &LR; , president of the National Restaurant
Association, has decided not to run for the Senate. He has formed
an exploratory committee instead, for a possible run for the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with the Senate, he said, is that he doesn't want to
answer to single-issue voters. As president, he would be more able
to deal with the nation's ``serious leadership deficiency.''
</P>
<P>
   Cain would focus on government bureaucracy, ``which creates
barriers to success, and even worse, the system has become
intrusive, abusive and unfair.'' Although he would be running as a
Republican, he notes that ``the current political party structure
makes it difficult for a voice of common sense to emerge out of the
political paradigm.''
</P>
<P>
   Cain said he had dealt with presidential issues before, having
made face-to-face challenges to  &UR; President Clinton &LR;  during a
televised ``town hall'' meeting a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SUFFERING THE PAIN OF SUCCESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Monica Lewinsky &LR;  has been signing at least 1,000 books a day in
France and signed 2,293 one day in England, but is said to have
been a bust in Latvia. Now she's suffering from a sore shoulder,
writes  &UR; Jeannette Walls  &LR; of MSNBC. ``She has a big signature,''
said an onlooker, ``and moves her whole arm. It hurts throughout
her entire arm and shoulder.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the pain, the author is enjoying the tour, said
co-author  &UR; Andrew Morton &LR; . ``There's a celebrity side of this that
she really goes for,'' he told the German press. ``It's a welcome
relief to come to Europe, where she doesn't have to ... read how
she's a pork pie who went out for cappuccino and a piece of
chocolate cake the day before.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky is so enthusiastic about the publicity, says Walls,
that despite original plans to limit her book tour to Europe, she's
trying to get her publisher to arrange a U.S. leg.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THANKS TO THE CHURCH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Franciscan friars at St. Boniface Catholic Church in San
Francisco are hoping to gather hundreds of couples who were married
in the church, for a June 6 renewal of their vows. Couples are
asked to bring photos of their weddings, and to celebrate, after
the service, at a reception in the parish hall.
</P>
<P>
   This joyous event is being planned to honor the feast of St.
Boniface, say the friars, who admit another less sentimental and
more practical motive: to draw attention to a fund-raising drive to
restore St. Boniface. If the marriage lasted, maybe you owe them a
few bucks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Two Bay Area authors have been given $10,000 by the J. Anthony
Lukas Prize Project, which gives awards for nonfiction writing in
memory of Pulitzer Prize-winning journalist Lukas. The awards,
administrated by the Columbia University Graduate School of
Journalism and the Nieman Foundation of Harvard University, went to
historian  &UR; Henry Mayer &LR;  for ``All on Fire:  &UR; William Lloyd &LR; 
 &UR; Garrison  &LR; and the Abolition of Slavery'' and to  &UR; Adam Hochschild &LR; 
for ``King Leopold's Ghost: A Story of Greed, Terror and Heroism in
Colonial Africa.'' A $45,000 award went to  &UR; Kevin Coyne &LR; , a
free-lance writer whose ``The Best Years of Their Lives,'' a book
about six World War II veterans, is still in progress.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Former White House Special Counsel  &UR; Lanny Davis &LR; , whose new
book, ``Truth to Tell,'' describes his adventures in the Clinton
administration, reveals that one night after he was on
``Nightline'' saying that guests were invited to sleep in the
Lincoln Bedroom because they were friends, not because they had
made financial donations, his teenage son told him, ``Dad, even I
know that you know you are full of crap.''
</P>
<P>
   _ This may be the last year to hunker down, spread out and watch
your favorite team. The Wall Street Journal warns that all across
the country, people are getting bigger and stadium seats are
getting smaller. ``It's like a sardine can,'' said a Washington
Redskins fan at the team's new stadium in Maryland. ``It's good to
have someone you love sitting next to you.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Revlon makes five Colorstay hair-dye shades for men, reports
Details, and L'Oreal makes four (in the macho colors cherry cola,
gothic, bleach blonding and camel).
</P>
<P>
   _ The Freedom Forum says it was amused by Monday's list of 100
least significant news stories (Cabbage Patch crisis, 1983, for
instance) but can't take credit; the list, created by the New York
Times, was a parody of the Freedom Forum's list of 100 most
significant stories.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a pretty normal guy who all of a sudden got famous, didn't
know what it was all about, and popped right into it. ...
Businesswise, I am a product. I'd be foolish not to put on that hat
and look at myself that way.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Matthew McConaughey in Elle magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
