<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8234 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLENN-FIRSTFLIGHT-COX     04-06 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLENN-FIRSTFLIGHT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Glenn to help celebrate century of flight
 &HT;    By Timothy R. Gaffney
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Space pioneer and retired U.S. senator John Glenn
will lend his fame to Dayton's 2003 Committee, the organization's
marketing director said.
</P>
<P>
   The committee plans to introduce Glenn as its ``secretary
general of inventing flight'' at an invitation-only party it has
scheduled for April 19 at the U.S. Air Force Museum, marketing
director Lauri McFarlin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inventing Flight'' is how the committee will identify itself
from now on as it starts firming up and publicizing its plans for a
yearlong series of events to celebrate a century of flight in the
year 2003.
</P>
<P>
   The year will mark the 100th anniversary of the world's first
powered flights by Dayton brothers Orville and Wilbur Wright. The
Wrights invented the airplane in Dayton and made the first powered
flights Dec. 17, 1903, at Kitty Hawk, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   The museum bash will include live music and videos staged among
the aircraft exhibits for up to 1,700 invited guests. McFarlin said
Glenn will flip a switch to start a ``2003 countdown clock,'' one
of three that will be set up around Dayton to tick off the time
until the anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's master plan calls for a yearlong series of
educational and art events, as well as a summer gala built around
the United States Air and Trade Show. McFarlin said the latest
details in its plans will be unveiled at the party.
</P>
<P>
   A native Ohioan, Glenn is a former Marine Corps aviator and
astronaut. He became the first American to orbit the Earth in 1962,
then became the oldest person in space last October when he blasted
off on a space shuttle mission at age 77.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Glenn is one of the few people who has that same spirit
and aura'' of the Wright brothers, McFarlin said.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn has also been a big booster of Dayton's aviation heritage.
He co-sponsored legislation to create the Dayton Aviation Heritage
National Historical Park and a national Centennial of Flight
Commission, which was established to coordinate first-flight
celebration efforts.
</P>
<P>
   On last year's space shuttle flight, Glenn carried small
swatches of the fabric that covered the wings of the 1903 Wright
Flyer.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn will bring name recognition to a committee that has
received little attention outside Dayton. In North Carolina, the
First Flight Centennial Foundation has George Bush, former U.S.
president and World War II Navy combat pilot, as its honorary
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Kitty Hawk's fame as the place where the Wrights first
flew has caused many people to mistake it as their hometown.
</P>
<P>
   McFarlin said she ``had no idea'' the Wrights lived in Dayton
until she moved here from Milwaukee in January to work for the 2003
Committee. She said she doesn't have an aviation background, ``but
I haven't been an ostrich, either.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This community tends to be very modest about what its history
and accomplishments have been,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy R. Gaffney writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
