<HEADER>
A8238 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-ART-6     04-06 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-ART-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFUGEES TELL OF ATROCITIES AND CONFUSION IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-SERBIA,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-ISRAEL, KOSOVO-ALLIES, KOSOVO-AIRLIFT,
KOSOVO-DIPLO) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MORINI, Albania _ The long, ragged lines of refugees continued
to cross the border from Kosovo here as darkness fell Tuesday,
despite the cease-fire declared by the Yugoslav president, Slobodan
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The fleeing ethnic Albanians were taking their cue from the
plumes of smoke pouring from border villages set afire by the
Yugoslavs Tuesday afternoon, rather than from any diplomatic
maneuvers.
</P>
<P>
   During the day and evening, several refugees spoke of having
been told by the Yugoslav police that the policy toward them had
changed and they could go home. But the somewhat mystifying offer
did not appear to have been widely heeded.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the pace of refugees crossing the border appeared to
pick up rapidly Tuesday afternoon, and by nightfall the twisting
road leading toward the Albanian town of Kukes was jammed with
tractors pulling carts of refugees, nearly all women, children and
old men. More than a dozen horse-drawn wagons crossed Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   With the major cities of Kosovo largely emptied out, it appeared
that many of Tuesday's refugees were from outlying rural districts,
some from around Pec, in the far northwest of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Eqerim Mucaj, like several others, said his group had been told
by Yugoslav police at Szure, the village about two miles north of
the crossing that has been used as a dropping-off point for bus and
truck convoys, that they could turn around and go back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We answered: `We have nowhere to go there. We don't have
houses. We have nothing to eat,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another man said he replied, ``My direction is Albania.''
</P>
<P>
   A group of villagers from Koreshe, outside Prizren, accepted an
offer from two carloads of Yugoslav policemen to go back home. But
as they neared their village, they said, they saw the mosque being
blown up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were again frightened and came here,'' said a man still too
fearful to give his name.
</P>
<P>
   Some said that after they declined to return to their burned
villages, the Yugoslav police took down their names.
</P>
<P>
   During the day at least four refugees recounted similar stories.
But most refugees crossing the line Tuesday evening said they had
not been told they could turn back and, in any case, were unlikely
to trust such offers from the Yugoslavs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not going back,'' said Vec Gjakova from atop the tractor
he had driven toward Albania for the last four days. ``I would go
only if we would be safe.''
</P>
<P>
   As the refugees arrived, they told the strikingly similar tales
that are becoming so familiar here: of being robbed _ sometimes
told to turn over a specific sum like 100, 400 or a thousand German
marks as the price of their lives or a child's life _ of being
ordered out of their homes, of seeing the houses burned down, of
being herded together at gathering points in the larger towns and,
often, of seeing Yugoslav gunmen kill their neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Gami Bushati, an old man from the village of Lybenic who was
being treated for gunshot wounds at the jammed hospital here _
which has no anesthetics or much of any other medical supplies _
said he had survived a massacre of about 120 people.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Yugoslav forces arrived at his village about 7:15
a.m. Friday, gathered people together in a barn and began shooting.
He said he and three others had managed to survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we were lucky,'' he said, ``because we were the first that
fell down, and the others fell on top of us.''
</P>
<P>
   A second refugee on Tuesday confirmed an account of Yugoslav
forces using a backhoe to dig a mass grave at Mala Krusa, one of
two adjacent villages where a half-dozen witnesses have described
mass killings of roughly a hundred people.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The account came toward the end of a long, detailed story by the
refugee _ a warehouse accountant unwilling to give his name _ of
being rounded up with other villagers at a collection point in
Belinica.
</P>
<P>
   As his group passed Mala Krusa, he said, he saw Yugoslavs with a
backhoe digging a big pit into which they were dropping bodies in
white plastic bags. His account dovetails with that of a refugee
interviewed three days ago who followed the same route.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees arriving from Suva Reka said the Yugoslav forces had
executed people from families who had rented offices or apartments
to the observer teams from the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe stationed there.
</P>
<P>
   The observers, who monitored the attacks by Yugoslavs on ethnic
Albanians, have been withdrawn, along with all other Western aid
workers and journalists. There have been reports of similar
killings of people who worked with the observer teams in other
towns.
</P>
<P>
   All of the 57 villages in the Suva Reka area have been burned to
the ground, refugees from there said. One man added, ``It's a very
bad smell from the bodies in the burned houses.''
</P>
<P>
   With roughly 80 percent of the refugees women, children and
elderly men, according to Laura Boldrini, spokeswoman for the U.N.
high commissioner for refugees, there is growing concern for men
between the ages of 15 and 50. Some have gone into hiding in the
mountains, but many others were separated out when people were
rounded up and may have been put into holding areas by the
Yugoslavs or killed.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees reported a large concentration of young men held in a
place called Krjlan, Ms. Boldrini said. And a State Department
report said there were a number of other holding centers where
groups of ethnic Albanian men of potential fighting age were being
imprisoned.
</P>
<P>
   At 1:10 Tuesday afternoon, the Yugoslavs torched a cluster of
red-tile-roofed houses just behind their border post, forcing the
long waiting line of refugees to go through one last sight of
destruction on their way out of Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
