<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8239 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MURDOCH-MARKETPLACE-N     04-06 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURDOCH-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: MALONE MOVES LIBERTY MEDIA INTO BIG STAKE IN
MURDOCH'S NEWS CORP. 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Every time John Malone gets part of a company, the
price seem to rise.
</P>
<P>
   Malone, who sold Tele-Communications Inc. to AT&AMP;T, is acquiring
8 percent of News Corp., the media conglomerate controlled by
Rupert Murdoch. Word of those plans have driven the News Corp.'s
American depositary receipts up 15 percent, to $34 Tuesday, from
$29.50 on March 31.
</P>
<P>
   Malone remains chairman of the Liberty Media Group, which along
with TCI became part of AT&AMP;T last month. But Liberty retains a
separate market presence, traded on the New York Stock Exchange as
a tracking stock of AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of a deal announced Tuesday, Liberty is acquiring
51.8 million shares of the News Corp. in exchange for its
half-interest in Fox/Liberty Sports, which owns regional sports
cable networks.
</P>
<P>
   In a second transaction, it is paying $700 million for 28.1
million shares of the News Corp. from MCI Worldcom, which is
disposing of its entire 5 percent stake in the company. Of MCI's
remaining 28.1 million News shares, Saudi Prince Al Waleed Bin
Talal will buy 8 million, raising his total to about 2 percent of
the company; the News Corp. will buy back the rest.
</P>
<P>
   After that stock buyback is completed, Liberty will own 8
percent of the 991 million shares outstanding, including voting and
nonvoting stock, in the News Corp. _ a stake second only to the
Murdoch family.
</P>
<P>
   Though his position is reminiscent of Ted Turner's in Time
Warner Inc. after Turner sold Turner Broadcasting, Malone appears
to be taking a hands-off approach to dealing with the News Corp..
</P>
<P>
   Liberty is not getting voting stock or a seat on the board.
Malone has also agreed to hold the block of stock acquired in the
sports deal for two years and the stock acquired from MCI for nine
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Malone is taking the risk of being a passive investor,
clearly he is confident in Rupert Murdoch,'' said John Tinker, an
analyst with Nationsbanc Montgomery Securities. Investors have been
less convinced of Murdoch's direction, and the stock has lagged in
recent years after Murdoch's acquisitions brought his
family-controlled company to the brink of financial disaster in the
early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Malone, though, has a strong record. His previous success
stories include a 10 percent stake in Time Warner, whose stock is
now trading at an all-time high.
</P>
<P>
   And his latest moves have already paid off for Liberty. The
company is paying $24.75 a share for the MCI stake and, for its
Fox/Liberty transaction, Liberty gains $1.43 billion in News Corp.
stock at $27.51 a share. With the stock now at $34, each deal
represents a tidy paper gain.
</P>
<P>
   Malone could easily increase his News Corp. stake as well.
Liberty has $5.5 billion in cash on its balance sheet and the
ability to borrow easily. But his strategy has been to take
minority positions in companies and leave the operations to
existing management.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in years, the News Corp. seems to be paying
serious attention to bolstering its stock price. Its executives
have made themselves more accessible to reporters and analysts, and
it has added public relations executives to explain its strategy
better to institutional shareholders and the public.
</P>
<P>
   The News Corp., though, does not do things any more simply than
Malone does. It is buying 50 percent of Fox/Liberty Networks and
then swapping that stake for stock in Fox Entertainment, its
programming arm, which owns the other 50 percent of Fox/Liberty.
About 20 percent of Fox Entertainment was offered to the public in
an initial offering of stock in November.
</P>
<P>
   Fox Entertainment, thus, will own all of Fox/Liberty, making it
possible to fully include the profits from that operation on its
income statement. The move will ever so slightly streamline the
corporation's operations.
</P>
<P>
   Executives also sought Tuesday to allay investors' concerns
about Murdoch's spending habits. Chase Carey, co-chief operating
officer of the News Corp., for example, said that Fox would not
acquire any more professional sports teams.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves investors to fret about Murdoch's desire to create a
a company that could deliver sports, entertainment, news and
children's programming by satellite across Europe. Murdoch has gone
so far as to discuss combining his B Sky B operations with Canal
Plus of France to build an expanded European presence. ``That could
get expensive because Europe is so complicated,'' Tinker of
Nationsbanc Montgomery said.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street prefers to see the News Corp. taking on a more
conservative posture. `` Murdoch seems to have slowed down a bit of
late,'' said Jeffrey Jones, an analyst at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette. ``Right now they are in less of a shopping mode and more
of an operating mode.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
