<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8240 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-DIPLO-840&AMP;ADD-     04-06 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DIPLO-840&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADMINISTRATION ASKS RUSSIA TO ACT AS DIPLOMATIC GO-BETWEEN IN
KOSOVO CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-SERBIA,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-ISRAEL, KOSOVO-ALLIES,
KOSOVO-AIRLIFT) 
(sw) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration has approached Moscow to
serve as a go-between with Slobodan Milosevic in a new attempt to
find a diplomatic solution to the conflict in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore called Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov by
telephone on Tuesday, asking Russia's help in getting the Yugoslav
leader to take steps that would lead to a resumption of
negotiations, Gore's office said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's contacts with Russia were reported as the administration
continued to explore other strategies to resolve the conflict. One
plan under consideration would be for NATO troops to usher ethnic
Albanian refugees back into Kosovo once air attacks have
neutralized Serbian forces, NATO officials reported.
</P>
<P>
   Descriptions of the 40-minute conversation between the two
officials contrasted sharply to the dismissive attitude the
administration displayed toward Primakov's diplomatic mission in
Belgrade last week near the beginning of the NATO bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore's office did not disclose Primakov's response, an
aide to the vice president said the two talked about ``how we might
cooperate to urge Milosevic to take steps to end the conflict.''
The vice president made ``the point there is a diplomatic track and
we'd prefer diplomacy to bombing,'' the aide added.
</P>
<P>
   Using the Russians as a bridge to the Serbian president would
mean that the administration could avoid the embarrassment of
dealing face to face with Milosevic, whom some have painted as the
incarnation of evil responsible for the forced removals of hundreds
of thousands of ethnic Albanians. And Milosevic, in turn, has told
officials in Europe that he was not willing to deal directly with
the United States at this point.
</P>
<P>
   Senior administration officials said that actively involving the
Russians would help insure that Moscow, which has vehemently
opposed the NATO bombing, not become seriously alienated from the
United States in the longer term.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said the Russians would be asked to
push Milosevic to accept the four points that the NATO allies
outlined last weekend. These are: the withdrawal of Serb forces
from Kosovo, the return of refugees, the presence of an
international security force and self government for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Russians obtained the agreement, that would be good for
the Russians,'' a senior administration official said. ``And it
would be good for us because we don't have to meet with
Milosevic.''
</P>
<P>
   In announcing these four points, administration officials have
talked of an ``international security force,'' a more palatable
phrase for the Russians, and Milosevic, than the earlier term
``NATO-led'' peacekeeping force. But it would in fact be commanded
by NATO and intended to protect the returning refugees,
administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials have indicated that they now favor
making Kosovo an international protectorate, which would allow the
ethnic Albanians to return. For the moment, officials are rejecting
the idea of a partitioning of Kosovo, with the Serbs being allowed
to keep a northern portion of the province and the remaining
territory given to the ethnic Albanians. This restructuring, they
argue, would reward Milosevic for his strategy of routing the
Albanians and allow him to keep a Serb-dominated section of the
province.
</P>
<P>
   After a speech on Tuesday at the Brookings Institution here,
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said that the administration
was insisting that there be a ``permissive environment'' for the
international force.
</P>
<P>
   She reiterated that the administration had ``no plans or
intentions for ground forces in a non-permissive environment.''
</P>
<P>
   A ``signed agreement'' was the best sign that there would be a
permissive environment, she said. But she added: ``There has to be
some way to know that it is a permissive environment; so that there
has to be acceptance of the fact that there will not be Serb forces
that will attack the populations or the forces that would go in in
such an environment.''
</P>
<P>
   The first round of diplomatic meetings on Kosovo since the NATO
strikes began will open in Brussels on Wednesday, with meetings of
the representatives of the six-nation Contact Group that includes
Russia, the United States and four NATO allies. Deputy Secretary of
State Strobe Talbot was scheduled to attend, the State Department
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians had dropped their demand for a cessation in NATO
bombing before attending such a meeting, administration officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Albright is expected to attend a meeting of the foreign
ministers of the NATO allies in Brussels next Monday. If the
Contact Group meeting in Brussels goes well, it is possible that a
meeting of the group's foreign ministers will convene as well next
week. But for that to happen, a Western diplomat said, the Russians
would have to agree to the four principals laid down by NATO.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   How to deal with Milosevic for a solution to the conflict has
become a sore point for the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of Congress have said that Milosevic should be
declared a war criminal and be dealt with only from the dock at the
International Court for War Crimes in the Hague. A supporter of the
administration's policy, former Sen. Bob Dole, said earlier this
week that Milosevic should be treated as a ``suspect'' and taken to
the Hague.
</P>
<P>
   At the mid-levels of the administration, especially among those
who worked on Balkan issues during the war in Bosnia, there is also
strong opposition to negotiating with Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   As the administration works on a diplomatic strategy, which is
being spearheaded by James Steinberg, the deputy national security
adviser, officials have tried to walk a public line between
painting Milosevic as the perpetrator of the forced expulsions but
not going so far as to accuse his forces of committing acts of
genocide.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department spokesman, James Rubin, has stopped just
short of using the word ``genocide,'' saying instead that there
were ``indicators of genocide'' by Milosevic's forces in Kosovo.
Pressed last weekend on whether Milosevic was a war criminal,
Albright said that was a definition that had to be determined after
a trial at the War Crimes tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   At the State Department, one of the officials working on the
diplomatic strategy said that the administration had not ruled out
dealing with Milosevic in person. ``We dealt with Stalin for years
and years,'' the official said. ``We deal with the North Koreans.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
