<DOCNO> NYT19990406.0320 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8255 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EVERGLADES-COX     04-06 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVERGLADES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Everglades promised restorationj from Washington
 &HT;    By Robert P. King
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Sixty-three years after Marjory Stoneman
Douglas proclaimed that the Everglades was in its ``11th hour,''
Florida's precious marsh will finally see relief _ in 2010.
</P>
<P>
   That's the promise from the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers, which
goes public today with an accelerated version of its $7.8 billion
Everglades restoration plan.
</P>
<P>
   Next stop: Washington, where Congress is scheduled to receive it
July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Like the draft that Vice President Al Gore unveiled in October,
the plan calls for an overhaul of South Florida's 1,600-mile-long
drainage system to undo decades of damage. It would demolish
levees, fill canals and turn more than 200,000 acres of undeveloped
land into reservoirs, filter marshes and well fields, storing
hundreds of billions of gallons of water for the Everglades, farms
and cities.
</P>
<P>
   The price tag _ to be split by Florida and the feds _ also is
about the same as Gore's draft.
</P>
<P>
   But the proposal's latest version tries to answer criticism from
environmentalists and scientists, who said the original plan would
move too slowly and give too little water to Everglades National
Park. The new plan would finish crucial projects years ahead of the
old schedule, especially in creating reservoirs to replenish
long-parched stretches of the Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas' classic 1947 book The Everglades: River of Grass
popularized awareness of the region's problems, including the
damage wreaked by what she called an ``inadequate and confusing''
drainage system. But the corps' efforts to solve that problem after
World War II only hastened the Everglades' decline, including the
dwindling of bird colonies that once numbered in the hundreds of
thousands.
</P>
<P>
   The new proposal would do enough by 2010 to stop that downward
slide and allow a long healing to begin, corps engineer Richard
Punnett said.
</P>
<P>
   The corps would finish almost all the work by 2020, except for
two large Miami-Dade County reservoirs set for completion in 2036.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would cost as much as $460 million each year, up from
$400 million in the draft proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it really sets up an opportunity to find a way to
restore the Everglades,'' said Richard Ring, superintendent of
Everglades National Park, whose scientists had issued a scathing
critique of the old proposal. ``It's certainly a lot better than
the draft.''
</P>
<P>
   But the plan still faces skepticism from some environmentalists,
who said the reservoirs wouldn't take over enough Glades sugar cane
land to restore the natural flow of the water. Some said they'll
press for limits on residents' and farmers' water use, the removal
of more levees, and guarantees that the corps will clean polluted
water .
</P>
<P>
   ``They are sort of stepping in the right direction,'' said
Shannon Estenoz of the World Wildlife Fund. ``As far as we're
concerned, we have several weeks to continue to work on this
plan.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rod Tirrell of the Sierra Club said it has a long way to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've improved a poor plan a little bit,'' said Tirrell,
speaking for the club's Florida chapter but not its national
organization. ``We don't see restoration in the cards. We see a
water supply plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Corps restoration chief Stu Appelbaum said saving the Everglades
requires a larger water supply for the region's residents _
projected to nearly double to 12 million by the year 2050.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to set up a competition in the future where the
Everglades gets shortchanged again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other questions about the plan include:
</P>
<P>
   Technology: The plan relies on more than 300 storage wells to
trap billions of gallons of water, a method untested on such a huge
scale.
</P>
<P>
   Money: Nobody knows what mix of state and local taxes and fees
would pay for Florida's $3.9 billion share. South Florida water
managers say they could face a $2.5 billion deficit by 2020.
</P>
<P>
   Control: Legislators are proposing a bill to give the state a
greater say in the project's details. But environmentalists say the
bill could create state-federal turf battles, increase costs and
make the Everglades wait in line for water behind cities and
farmers.
</P>
<P>
   How to get the plan
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Army Corps of Engineers is making the 4,000-page final
version of its Everglades restoration plan available in the
following ways. All are free:
</P>
<P>
   1) On the Internet at www.restudy.org
</P>
<P>
   2) By phone at (904) 232-3332 _ You can order the entire report
and all appendixes on two CD-ROMs. Or you can get a printed version
of the 600-page main report.
</P>
<P>
   Robert P. King writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
