<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8260 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-POLITE-POLICE-450&AMP;     04-06 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLITE-POLICE-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. POLICE WILL GET WALLET-SIZED REMINDERS TO SAY `PLEASE' AND
`THANK YOU' 
</HEADLINE>
  (ac) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They have been praised as brave and effective, or
condemned as belligerent and brutal. But no one has ever portrayed
New York's police officers as urban Andy Griffiths, aw-shucksing
and ``Mornin' Ma'am-ing'' their way through the mean streets.
</P>
<P>
   But now Mayor Rudolph Giuliani is trying to give the city's
nearly 40,000 police officers a lesson in good manners. He
announced Tuesday that he , was distributing cards to officers
instructing them to be just a little more polite in their dealings
on the street.
</P>
<P>
   The wallet-size cards recommend that officers ``use terms such
as `Mr.,' `Ms.,' `Sir' or Ma'am.''' Teen-agers should be referred
to as ``young lady or young man.'' The cards tell officers to say
``hello'' and ``thank you,'' and urge them to ``Respect each
individual, his or her cultural identity, customs and beliefs.''
</P>
<P>
   The genteel approach is the latest in a series of initiatives by
the mayor to repair frayed relations stemming from the Feb. 4
slaying of Amadou Diallo. The unarmed immigrant was shot 19 times
by four police officers, who fired a total of 41 bullets at him.
His death prompted protests that resulted in the arrests of more
than 1,200 people.
</P>
<P>
   But in a city where gruffness is a basic characteristic of urban
discourse the plan drew a markedly unenthusiastic response from
officers on the beat on Tuesday. And some officers insisted that,
contrary to reputation, they didn't need help being nice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it hard to believe that a cop is going to have to pull
out a palm card to remember to say hello and thank you,'' said
Police Officer Vincent Martinelli, a union delegate at the 108th
Precinct in Long Island City, Queens. ``I think it's ridiculous.
With your growth as a police officer, as a professional doing a
professional job, courtesy and honesty and politeness should come
naturally.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan did earn polite praise from Letitia Baldrige, the
etiquette expert. ``Anything that is attempted is for the good,''
she said. ``Any attempt by the mayor to make things better, even if
it doesn't work, is terrific.''
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the plan at Police Headquarters, Giuliani stressed
that politeness was a two-way street, that citizens could benefit
from being a little nicer to officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to ask the people of the city to be more
respectful in dealing with the Police Department,'' he said. ``So
that people refer to police officers as `officer,' not by their
last name, not by some derogatory term. Try to figure out what all
those things on a police officer's arm and shoulder mean _ a
sergeant, a lieutenant, a captain, an inspector _ and refer to the
person as sergeant, captain and inspector. They're entitled to
that.''
</P>
<P>
   But to some, the cards seemed to be a superficial fix to the
deeper questions about the police that have arisen since the
slaying of Diallo. The four officers who shot at him have been
charged with second-degree murder in the case.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   C. Virginia Fields, the Manhattan Borough president, complained
that the new politeness campaign ignores the deeper problems on the
force. She cited the cases of several people who died or were
injured in encounters with the police, saying the plan ``doesn't
begin to get to the heart of the matter, which is how do we prevent
tragedies like the choke-hold death of Anthony Baez, the torture of
Abner Louima or the shooting death of Amadou Diallo.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fields said that she thinks the department should focus on
more substantial changes, such as better training, recruitment of
more minority officers, a requirement that officers live in the
city, and changes to improve investigations of police misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   But Police Commissioner Howard Safir insisted yesterday that the
campaign marked an important step in changing the nature of
interactions between the police and the public.
</P>
<P>
   And Safir said that he plans to dispatch a team of undercover
police officers _ a kind of politeness police _ to make sure that
their colleagues remember to use honorific titles and do not forget
to say thank you. He said that those who do well would be
commended, and those who do not would face disciplinary action.
</P>
<P>
   James Savage, the president of the Patrolmen's Benevolent
Association, raised questions about the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm really concerned about is the way they're treated _
not by the public, so much, but by their ranking officers,'' he
said. ``They are under constant pressure to get more and more
numbers, more summonses. Even though the crime rates are down they
have to maintain the same level of activity. There is very little
respect shown to police officers.''
</P>
<P>
   The initiative is an outgrowth of Commissioner Safir's Courtesy,
Professionalism and Respect campaign _ known by its initials, CPR _
that he announced in 1996 as his program to improve relations
between the police and the community.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to printing palm cards for each police officer as
well as a larger version to go into their memo books, the Police
Department is putting out a 24-page booklet about CPR and a
brochure to be distributed to the public at station houses called,
``Your Rights and Responsibilities When Interacting with the
Police.''
</P>
<P>
   In explaining the new campaign, Dennis Walcott, the president of
the New York Urban League and a co-chairman of the CPR advisory
board, drew an analogy to the Police Department's broken windows
theory _ that cracking down on small crimes and misdemeanors helps
prevent larger crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in the broken windows theory as far as officers are
concerned as well,'' said Walcott, who noted that he had been
stopped by the police himself on occasion. ``The little things can
add up to bigger things.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani appeared to anticipate a negative reaction to the plan
even as he announced it. ``I know there are going to be people who
are cynical about this,'' he said. ``I've been mayor of New York
City for too long not to realize that people will be cynical about
any good step that's made in the direction of decency.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said that he was reminded of the civility campaign he
announced last year in an effort to get all New Yorkers to be nicer
to one another. While that campaign was roundly ridiculed, he said,
he considers it successful. He noted that he has been stopped
several times recently by people telling him how nice New Yorkers
have become.
</P>
<P>
   While some critics have called the initiative superficial,
others worried about more far-ranging effects. A senior police
official who supports the plan, for instance, asked, ``What are
they going to do on `NYPD Blue' if this works?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
