<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8261 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BASES-550&AMP;ADD-     04-06 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BASES-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. CHOOSES GUANTANAMO BAY FOR REFUGEE SITE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-SERBIA,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-ISRAEL, KOSOVO-ALLIES,
KOSOVO-AIRLIFT, KOSOVO-DIPLO) 
(mk) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House said Tuesday that it had selected
the American naval base at Guantanamo Bay in Cuba as a temporary
home for 20,000 refugees from Kosovo, despite warnings from some
refugee groups that the base will be more like a prison than the
``safe haven'' described by the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Navy logistics officers set to work to prepare a tent city at
the base for the first of the ethnic Albanian refugees, who are
expected to be flown there from the Balkans later this week aboard
chartered commercial jets.
</P>
<P>
   The remote, sun-drenched base, which is a legacy of the
Spanish-American War and was leased to the United States in
perpetuity at the turn of the century, has been used repeatedly
over the last decade to house Cubans and Haitians attempting to
flee their countries.
</P>
<P>
   The White House spokesman, Joe Lockhart, said that the base
would serve as ``a safe haven to receive up to 20,000 Kosovar
refugees,'' part of a larger NATO-led effort to evacuate more than
100,000 ethnic Albanians from the turmoil along Kosovo's borders.
</P>
<P>
   He stressed that their relocation to Cuba would last only a
matter of weeks or months and that the refugees were ``fully
expected'' to return home. ``This facility will be temporary, and
we fully intend the Kosovars will ultimately return to their
homes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials said Guantanamo Bay was chosen
over other sites, including an Air Force base on the American
island territory of Guam in the western Pacific, because commanders
of the naval base had recent experience in handling tens of
thousands of refugees at once.
</P>
<P>
   The officials, speaking on condition that they not be
identified, acknowledged that the base was selected also to
eliminate the possibility that some of the refugees might be able
to claim political asylum in the United States. Under federal
immigration law, refugees can claim asylum only once they reach
American soil.
</P>
<P>
   Several relief organizations in the United States said they had
no immediate complaint with the administration's decision to place
the Kosovo refugees at Guantanamo Bay, which is hundreds of miles
from the American mainland.
</P>
<P>
   They said that it may be appropriate for now to house the
refugees outside the borders of the United States, if only to
demonstrate to President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia that the
relocation is temporary and that his campaign of ``ethnic
cleansing'' in Kosovo will not succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is Guantanamo Bay a nice place? No,'' said Bill Frelick,
senior policy analyst at the U.S. Committee for Refugees, in
Washington. ``When I've been there, it's looked like a POW camp.
But everything's relative.''
</P>
<P>
   One refugee advocate who has visited Guantanamo Bay, Cheryl
Little of the Florida Immigrant Advocacy Center in Miami, said she
was ``appalled'' at the thought that Kosovo refugees might be
forced to live in the sort of tent city that housed tens of
thousands of Cuban and Haitian boat people at the base earlier in
the decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given everything these folks have been through in Kosovo, I
don't think we should be stashing them out of sight at a military
base where they are far removed from any viable support system,''
she said. ``It's very bleak. When I was there, there was concertina
wire. It's like a jail. It's so unsuitable.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While they will be escaping the horrors of the crisis in the
Balkans, the Kosovo refugees will doubtless find the transition to
Guantanamo Bay jarring, in terms both of culture and climate.
</P>
<P>
   The tropical heat can be merciless on the 34-square-mile base,
especially during the summer months, and Cubans and Haitians who
lived in the tent cities earlier in the decade complained
constantly about sanitation, medical care, food and boredom.
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban government, which has refused since 1960 to accept
payments for the base under a lease signed in 1903, protested the
decision to move the Kosovo refugees to Guantanamo Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American aggressors in Yugoslavia have no right to bring
these people to Cuba,'' Raul Taladrid, Cuba's deputy minister of
foreign investment, told reporters in Havana. ``The refugee problem
is a European problem.''
</P>
<P>
   About 50,000 Cuban and Haitian refugees passed through the camp
earlier in the decade, at a cost to the United States of $250
million. Most of the Haitians housed there between 1991 and 1994
were shipped home when relative stability returned to their
homeland. Nearly all the Cubans housed there from 1994 through 1996
ended up in the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
