<HEADLINE>
OPENING DAY'S DANGER OF OVERREACTION FULFILLED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was baseball's Opening Day.
</P>
<P>
   I was ebullient that it again was here. I am an American. I love
Opening Day.
</P>
<P>
   In preparation, I reread all the George Will books. I memorized
six pages of Bart Giamatti poems. I rented ``Field of Dreams'' and
re-cried.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball still has a unique hold on America, and no day of the
baseball season has a tighter grip on America's heartstrings than
Opening Day.
</P>
<P>
   We rise for the national anthem. We applaud for the player
introductions.
</P>
<P>
   And whatever happens after that, we are baseball fans _ we
overreact.
</P>
<P>
   Dateline, Pittsburgh, first inning _ Rookie second baseman
Warren Morris, formerly of the Rangers, grounds into a double play
in his first big-league at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   Overreaction reaction: Told you that Esteban Loaiza trade was a
good deal.
</P>
<P>
   Dateline, Baltimore _ Cal Ripken Jr. leaves the game in the
third inning with a stiff back.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction: Slacker.
</P>
<P>
   Dateline, Kansas City _ Newest Red Sox Jose Offerman goes
4-for-5 in his Boston debut.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction: Mo Vaughn, with half the calories.
</P>
<P>
   Dateline, The Ballpark in Arlington _ Rick Helling throws the
first pitch of the Rangers' season to Detroit's Juan Encarnacion.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction: Johnny Oates must go.
</P>
<P>
   We are baseball fans. We watch Opening Day and we scan the
outfield flags for ill winds.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Curt Schilling _ can I help you?'' the voice on the
other end of the phone said.
</P>
<P>
   The voice was Doug Melvin's. The Rangers general manager was
reacting, tongue in cheekly, to the alleged crisis of the day.
</P>
<P>
   The typical Rangers fan, Melvin knows, woke up yesterday morning
wondering why the home team hadn't consummated an immediate trade
for Schilling, John Smoltz or Sandy Koufax.
</P>
<P>
   Dateline, St. Louis _ Third baseman Fernando Tatis, formerly of
the Rangers, homers for the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction: Rangers will rue the day they traded young Tatis away.
</P>
<P>
   Dateline, Los Angeles _ Kevin Brown, the $105 million man,
cuffed around and knocked out in the sixth inning of first Dodgers
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction: Worst Fox decision since ``America's Funniest Police
Chases.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin spent the day on the phone yesterday, but in a bit of a
local surprise, he wasn't trying to reach Red Adair. Melvin had
read the Opening Day box scores and noticed something.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle, Jeff Fassero, six innings, eight hits, six runs, lost
8-2.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta, Tom Glavine, six-plus innings, seven hits, five runs,
lost 7-4.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland, Roger Clemens, six-plus innings, five walks, lost 5-3.
</P>
<P>
   Seven home teams lost Monday on Opening Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose that's seven clubs out of the pennant race,'' Melvin
observed dryly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of overreaction to Opening Day,'' he conceded.
``And you see the same thing sometimes at the trading deadline.
When a club gets somebody, every team thinks that it just traded
for the pennant.''
</P>
<P>
   Dateline, The Ballpark in Arlington _ Tigers' Brian Moehler
takes no-hit bid into seventh inning against the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction: Why couldn't Melvin have traded for Albert Belle?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Rick Helling is going to battle back just fine from
Monday's game,'' Melvin offered. ``I look at Rick and see a guy who
was 4-0 and the American League's pitcher of the month last
September, and I see a guy who was 7-1 in his last 11 starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'd say that those games were a lot bigger than any
Opening Day games.''
</P>
<P>
   The reaction, however, to Helling's stunning first pitch and to
the six runs that followed is typical of what happens on Opening
Day. Melvin awoke yesterday to hear fans arguing that Helling was
ill-equipped to start a season opener.
</P>
<P>
   Dateline, Oakland _ Gil Heredia outduels Clemens and Athletics
beat Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction: ``I guess I shouldn't have gotten rid of Gil
Heredia,'' Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   He was kidding. Of course. But that's baseball. It takes a sense
of humor to survive.
</P>
<P>
   Dateline, St. Louis _ Mark McGwire homers to launch new assault
on home run record.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction: I hope the Maris family now has an unlisted number.
</P>
<P>
   Dateline, Pittsburgh, ninth inning _ Warren Morris, formerly of
the Rangers, doubles off the outfield wall.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction: Told you that Loaiza trade stunk.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin woke yesterday morning to discover that the sun, indeed,
had come up. A quick check of the newspaper confirmed another rumor
_ that the Rangers had 161 more games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guys will get over this,'' he said of the Opening Day
debacle.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction: Easy for Melvin to say. He's a Canadian.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
