u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-U.S.-TRADE-NYT &LR;      04-06 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-TRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CHINA TRADE DEAL IS NOW UP TO CLINTON
</HEADLINE>
  (With CHINA-U.S.) 
 (nk) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With 24 hours remaining before the arrival of
China's prime minister, President Clinton struggled Tuesday night
to decide whether to strike the broadest trade agreement in
Chinese-American history, in return for American agreement to usher
China into the World Trade Organization. But his top advisers were
deeply split about whether to take the deal.
</P>
<P>
   In two days of furious negotiating here preceding Prime Minister
Zhu Rongji's arrival on Wednesday night, American officials have
been locked up with China's trade minister, Long Yongtu, in an
effort to resolve a wide variety of outstanding differences.
President Clinton had several conversations Tuesday about his
bottom-line positions with his trade representative, Charlene
Barshefsky, but administration officials said he might try to
resolve the last issues directly with Zhu in their meetings on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they had already concluded accords on a series of
contentious issues involving agriculture, including a Chinese
agreement to allow in American wheat that China previously insisted
was tainted with disease. Rather than barring the wheat altogether,
China agreed to a tolerance level that will permit most of the
American-grown wheat into the country.
</P>
<P>
   But the two sides were still negotiating how large a stake
American companies will be allowed to take in Chinese
telecommunications companies. China has already said it is willing
to sell 30 percent stakes in these companies to foreigners, but
will not permit them to take controlling interests.
</P>
<P>
   As of Tuesday afternoon, both sides were arguing over how much
liberty American banks and brokerage firms would have to operate
throughout China. At the same time, American officials have raised
new issues, including a demand that the United States extend quotas
limiting the import of Chinese-made textiles until 2010, an effort
to win over some members of Congress whose constituencies are bound
to be aroused by any deal. The Chinese have protested the effort,
and _ perhaps in a last-minute negotiating ploy _ appeared to back
off Tuesday on some offers to open the market in the financial
sector and on tariff reductions for some American-made goods.
</P>
<P>
   While negotiators argue over the details, though, Clinton
appears focused on the strategic significance of a deal _ helping
to integrate China into both the global economy and a global set of
legal regulations governing trade. Clinton is also intent on
helping strengthen the authority of Zhu, whom he sees as an
accomplished economic reformer and Washington's best hope of
opening a true channel of communication with the Chinese
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   But Zhu, under pressure at home, cannot be seen to be giving in
too much to American pressure, especially at the cost of Chinese
jobs. And Clinton, as one of his advisers put it Tuesday, ``is
facing the likelihood of another Nafta fight in Congress'' _ a
reference to the vote in which Clinton defied his own party to push
through the North American Free Trade Agreement in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Congress had a direct vote on the wisdom of Nafta, and most
Democrats opposed it, saying that it would move jobs to Mexico. The
China argument, though, is far more complex. Congress does not have
a direct voice in whether the administration casts its vote to get
China into the World Trade Organization, which sets the rules of
trade and arbitrates disputes. But China's entry would require
congressional action to amend the law that creates an annual
congressional review of China's trading rights, which inevitably
becomes enmeshed in China's human rights record, its stand-off with
Taiwan and now its alleged espionage efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Officials who have sat in meetings on the negotiations say the
president is leaning strongly toward striking a deal. But the head
of the National Economic Council, Gene Sperling, has argued that
anything short of a perfect deal _ and there is no such thing in
trade negotiations _ would undercut the administration's efforts to
unify Democrats on Social Security, Medicare and other issues that
Clinton views as central to his legacy. He has received some
support from John Podesta, the White House chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night Sperling denied he was opposed to a deal, and
added, ``We're not raising the bar out of politics, but not
lowering the bar to get a deal during the trip, either.''
</P>
<P>
   The strongest advocate of a deal, National Security Adviser
Sandy Berger, has been almost entirely tied up managing the crisis
in Kosovo, the officials say, and that has cast some doubt about
how the final arguments will play out in the Oval Office. ``From
the start, Sandy has wanted this because he realizes it's the only
thing that we can get done with the Chinese before the end of this
administration,'' one White House official said recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this is a case where the most important relationship we
have is getting a lot less attention at a critical moment than it
should because of the military action under way,'' the official
continued, ``and that raises the chances for miscalculation on our
end or the Chinese end.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some of the concessions the Chinese have made so far go
beyond the road map that American officials gave Beijing three
years ago, when negotiations over China's entry into the World
Trade Organization seemed stalled. For example, China has agreed to
limit its demand that American companies provide technology to
China in return for a right to invest there. The demands for
technology have been a major issue for American companies like
Boeing, which at times have refused to provide the Chinese with
proprietary technology at the cost of large deals.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Clinton decides to sign a deal may depend on his
calculation about how strongly American businesses will support it.
Their willingness to lobby in Congress _ pointing out the benefits
to individual companies in individual congressional districts _ may
well determine the strength of congressional opposition.
</P>
<P>
   But how willing they will be to press the issue depends on what
they get from the deal, which will vary from industry to industry.
``Any deal that doesn't have the seal of approval of the business
community isn't a deal worth doing,'' Ms. Barshefsky said last
week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
