<HEADER>
A8264 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-LEGIS-NEWS-COX     04-06 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-LEGIS-NEWS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bill takes tough stand on messy protests
 &HT;    Compiled by Austin American-Statesman Staff
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ An inmate caught hurling bodily secretions _
known as ``chunking'' _ at a prison official would be committing a
third-degree felony under legislation given preliminary approval by
the House on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The bill by Rep. Dan Ellis, D-Livingston, was passed by voice
vote and still needs final approval before being sent to the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chunking just makes the worst possible kind of messes,'' Ellis
said. ``As of now it is a Class C misdemeanor and as so there is
little or no deterrent to this behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Chunking has become such a problem that guards often avoid
certain prison areas unless wearing a raincoat, Ellis said. If they
are exposed to the secretions, prison officials may have to have
medical treatment, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gun bill doesn't shoot through
</P>
<P>
   When a bill is sent from the Senate to the House, it is said to
be ``finally'' passed by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   That phrase had extra meaning Tuesday when the Senate ``finally
passed'' a bill to keep cities, counties and other government
entities from suing gun and ammunition makers for the misuse of
their products without legislative approval.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was debated four times on the Senate floor before
getting a 23-7 vote to send it to the House. The first two times
Senate Bill 717 was debated, there were not enough votes for it to
be officially considered. On the third try, and with changes to
allow the attorney general to sue without lawmakers' OK, the bill
got approval.
</P>
<P>
   Barrientos: It's not your day
</P>
<P>
   Though all Texans want state lawmakers to make them happy, Sen.
Gonzalo Barrientos spread a humorous, real-world message via a
handout Tuesday. ``I can only please one person per day. Today is
not your day, tomorrow doesn't look good either,'' the handout
said. It ended with a more pleasant note from the Austin Democrat:
``Have a wonderful day.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmaker attempts shortcut
</P>
<P>
   The reality of time constraints hit home for Senate Republicans
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Troy Fraser, R-Horseshoe Bay, asked fellow members to move
a bill from his technology subcommittee to the full Senate Economic
Development Committee. Why? Because Senate Bill 614 faces much
controversy and needs plenty of time to get through the House and
Senate, he said. Moving the bill to the Economic Development
Committee would speed things up by about a week. The session will
end May 31.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would allow juries to assess liability in civil
lawsuits to people not involved in the case, even if the people
claiming the damage cannot then sue the third party. Under current
law, juries must assign all of the liability in a case to the
defendants sued even if there is clear proof that another person
was partly to blame but cannot be found to be sued.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Carlos Truan, D-Corpus Christi, warned that if Fraser were
allowed to move the bill without a subcommittee vote, other members
would ask to do the same thing when they didn't have committee
support for their bills.
</P>
<P>
   Fraser withdrew his request after much objection. The bill will
be voted on in subcommittee this week and considered by the full
committee next week. Senate OKs interest on extra tax
</P>
<P>
   A bill to pay interest to Texas taxpayers when they overpay the
state cleared the Senate on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Bill 1321 would require Comptroller Carole Keeton
Rylander to calculate interest on tax overpayments and give it to
the taxpayer. The interest would amount to the prime rate plus 1
percentage point. Because there is no personal income tax in Texas,
most of the tax money collected by the comptroller's office comes
from businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The state charges 12 percent interest when taxpayers are
delinquent.
</P>
<P>
   Senate OKs lottery reserve cut
</P>
<P>
   The Senate voted Tuesday to move $15 million from a lottery
reserve fund to the Foundation School Fund. The lottery currently
holds $20 million in reserve just in case a lottery retailer goes
bust and can't pay for tickets it has sold. Sen. Bill Ratliff,
R-Mount Pleasant, said experience has shown that $20 million is too
much. His Senate Bill 1320 would reduce the reserve to $5 million
and move the $15 million to a fund that helps support schools. It
now goes to the House.
</P>
<P>
   Ephedrine bill advances
</P>
<P>
   It would be a crime to sell the much-abused asthma drug
ephedrine to minors without a prescription under a bill that got
preliminary Senate approval Tuesday. Doctors could prescribe the
drug, which has been marketed over the counter as a stimulant,
appetite suppressant and muscle enhancer.
</P>
<P>
   Quote of the day
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Carlos Truan, D-Corpus Christi, a member of the Senate's
Special Committee on Border Affairs: ``I assume you didn't want me
to lay out all the bills and listen to my eloquent testimony.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Eddie Lucio Jr., D-Brownsville, chairman of the committee:
``You assume correct.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Kenny Marchant, R-Coppell, on the House's relatively slow
pace this session: ``I just think this is a session where we have a
few specific things we need to do, and I don't think that any of us
feel compelled to do a lot more than those few things.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
