<DOCNO> NYT19990406.0336 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8273 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THEATER-DJERASSI-SFCH     04-06 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-DJERASSI-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAGE REVIEW: SCIENTIST DELIVERS STILLBORN `MISCONCEPTION' 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN WINN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ What's a busy career woman to do as her
biological clock ticks down? Where to dip into the gene pool if she
decides to have a child on her own? Who gets to play God in the
brave new world of reproductive technology?
</P>
<P>
   In ``An Immaculate Misconception,'' an ambitious but
dramatically sterile problem play at the Eureka Theatre,
scientist-turned-playwright Carl Djerassi wades into the morass of
questions surrounding fertility in the '90s. Djerassi, who
synthesized the first birth control pill in the 1950s, wades out
with a test-tube piece of theater.
</P>
<P>
   This 2 1/2-hour staged debate has its intriguing twists, but the
artificially induced characters never take on an absorbing sense of
life. The show raises enough issues for a course in biomedical
ethics while failing to make an audience care about the people who
play them out onstage.
</P>
<P>
   Denise Balthrop Cassidy portrays Dr. Melanie Laidlaw, the
37-year-old biologist at the heart of the story. Busy with her work
on a new procedure for injecting human sperm directly into the egg,
she's put her own romantic and reproductive life on hold.
</P>
<P>
   Then she meets Menachem (Peter Vilkin), an Israeli nuclear
scientist, and it's pure chemistry in bed. Melanie has found the
perfect biological father for her child, she thinks, but there are
problems. He lives halfway around the world. He's married. And
owing to a nuclear accident, his sperm count is too low for either
conventional fatherhood or in vitro fertilization.
</P>
<P>
   Enter ICSI _ intracytoplasmic sperm injection, a method actually
developed by a University of Brussels scientist in the early 1990s.
In her lab, a suitably drab environment by designer Mikiko Uesugi,
Melanie decides to test the procedure on herself. The only thing
missing is Menachem's seed _ that's the title of Djerassi's 1997
novel on which the play is based.
</P>
<P>
   The action turns on a series of deceptions. Menachem lies about
his marriage. Melanie uses cooing e-mail and a canister of liquid
nitrogen to secure what she's after. Her research partner Felix,
played by Paul Sulzman, plays a microscopic shell game with eggs
and sperm. In their own ways, they're all stained by a kind of
scientific original sin.
</P>
<P>
   Djerassi searches out the implications of conception without
sex. Melanie sees ICSI as a breakthrough that will liberate women
by separating sex from reproduction. Through Felix's
``testosterone-tinted glasses,'' it's a boon for infertile men.
</P>
<P>
   A prologue and epilogue by the first ICSI baby (Zach Kenney)
raise questions about the rights of the offspring. The play touches
on the meaning of paternity, the pressure to publish, scientists'
egos and the ethics of self-experimentation.
</P>
<P>
   Even the piano music used during scene changes sounds worried.
In director Edward Hastings' production, ``Misconception'' has a
lot on its mind.
</P>
<P>
   The show does invite an audience to stretch into the strange new
territory of reproductive science. Like Jonathan Tolins' gay gene
play ``Twilight of the Golds'' or Jane Anderson's adoption play
``The Baby Dance,'' it uses dramatic suspense to animate real-world
issues of personal and social responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   But Djerassi has created mouthpieces rather than characters with
real dimension. The dialogue has a chilly sense of purpose. The
plot skirts some of the story's emotional depths. Melanie's
assertion that she has wanted a child more than scientific fame is
not enough to explain the risks she takes.
</P>
<P>
   Djerassi has an unfortunate weakness for punning _ a ``widow of
opportunity,'' ``seminal role.'' Even the characters' names _ Adam
for the first ICSI baby, a kindly sperm bank operator named
Motherwell (Maxine Wyman) _ are labels.
</P>
<P>
   The actors work hard but in vain to enliven the proceedings.
Cassidy is focused and serious. Sulzman projects an unfazed sense
of entitlement. Vilkin looks wounded. But even in its stormy
confrontations, ``Misconception'' never takes off. Like the tightly
controlled dance of sperms and eggs projected on a screen, these
characters miss the clench and splendor of life.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
