<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8274 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS &LR;      04-06 1308
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US SEES `PLOY' IN MILOSEVIC CEAASE-FIRE OFFER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic declared a
unilateral cease-fire Tuesday in his campaign to crush ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo, an offer promptly rejected by US officials,
who dismissed it as a ``ploy.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the United States began preparing the US naval base
at Guantanamo Bay, Cuba, to shelter 20,000 Kosovo refugees, opting
to use it over Andersen Air Force Base on Guam. Pentagon officials
said refugees from Macedonia will be transported by chartered
aircraft with the first wave arriving in three to four days and all
of them in place within 45 days.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said Milosevic could end the bombing
immediately by withdrawing from Kosovo, accepting a peace agreement
and allowing the hundreds of thousands of ethnic Albanians who have
been forced out of Kosovo to return to their homes.
</P>
<P>
   In related developments:
</P>
<P>
   --Serb officials said a NATO attack on a coal mining town killed
12 civilians and injured dozens.
</P>
<P>
   --Refugees are arriving in Norway and Turkey, as aid flooded
into Macedonia to help with the refugee crisis there.
</P>
<P>
   --Defense Secretary William Cohen headed to Brussels with a
bipartisan group from the House and Senate to meet with NATO
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic made the cease-fire offer in honor of the approaching
Orthodox Easter. Moments after the Serb's unilateral cease-fire
took effect at 8 p.m. (2 p.m. EDT), air-raid sirens wailed in
Belgrade, heralding new NATO attacks.
</P>
<P>
   At least six explosions could be heard late Tuesday in the
direction of the Batajnica military airport just north of Belgrade
and tracer rounds from anti-aircraft were seen in the night sky.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav television stations reported further attacks  &UR; last
night &LR;  at Uzice, 75 miles southwest of Belgrade, and in Cacak, an
industrial town 55 miles to the south, where US officials say a
munitions plant is located.
</P>
<P>
   A statement on the cease-fire released by the Yugoslav
government said, ``All actions of the army and police in Kosovo''
would be discontinued ``in the expectation that this decision will
be accepted as a gesture of good will in support of a peaceful
solution.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Clinton administration, which had been preparing for
such a move by Milosevic, toughened its resolve. US officials,
joined by British Prime Minister Tony Blair demanded that the Serbs
accept the framework of the peace accord worked out at Rambouillet,
France, including the deployment of an international peacekeeping
force, self-rule for the Kosovar Albanians, and the unconditional
return of all refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We anticipated that he might try a plot like this,'' said P.J.
Crowley, a spokesman for the National Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, Clinton said Milosevic's proposal fell
short.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States would never choose force as anything other
than a last option,'' he said. ``Mr. Milosevic could end it now by
withdrawing his military police and paramilitary forces; by
accepting the deployment of an international security force to
protect not only the Kosovar Albanians, most but not all of whom
are Muslims, but also the Serbian minority in Kosovo _ everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Before departing for Brussels, Cohen said the cease-fire idea
was ``not only completely unacceptable, but it's absurd.'' In an
interview with the US government-owned Voice of America, Cohen said
it would be an ``abdication of responsibility'' by NATO to accept
it.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Kenneth H. Bacon said Milosevic's offer of a
unilateral cease-fire in Kosovo may be evidence that NATO's air
campaign is working.
</P>
<P>
   ``This offer may be one sign that he is rattled, but we are
going to continue to rattle him until he makes an offer that meets
our conditions, and he's far away from that right now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Greek prime minister, Costas Simitis, called the proposal
``a first step'' and an opening for a political dialogue with
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The cease-fire offer came nearly two weeks into the conflict, as
allied warplanes blasted fuel storage facilities, oil refineries,
police headquarters, air defense sites, Serbian armored military
units on the ground, and roads and bridges across Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Serb officials said that a NATO strike on a coal mining town of
about 17,000 people, 100 miles southeast of Belgrade, killed 12
civilians and injured dozens.
</P>
<P>
   In Brussels, NATO Air Commodore David Wilby did not confirm
those details. But referring to a military facility housing an
artillery brigade in Aleksinac, a central Serbian town, he said
there was ``evidence of some damage around about 600 meters just
short of the target.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, an advance team of 100 US Marines Tuesday moved
into Macedonia to prepare the way for 1,200 Marines aboard ships in
the Aegean Sea who are coming ashore at a Greek port and will
construct and run a refugee camp in northern Macedonia. The Marines
are from the 24th Marine Expeditionary Unit, which has been in the
Aegean for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the selection of Guantanamo Bay naval base,
administration officials said the base was a better alternative to
the base in Guam because it has been used for Haitian and Cuban
refugees. ``We've done it before there, we know how to do it,''
said one senior official.
</P>
<P>
   The US government also decided to bar all ships flying
Yugoslavia's flag or under that country's control from US ports and
territories to guard against espionage or sabotage.
</P>
<P>
   As the swirl of humanitarian and war efforts continued, the
Pentagon said the NATO airstrikes so far have failed to eliminate
the Serb's air defense threat, but evidence existed of fuel
shortages among some Serb military units in Kosovo and low morale
among Serb troops.
</P>
<P>
   But Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright ruled out sending
in US troops. ``We believe that a sustained air campaign can
accomplish the objectives we have laid out,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Albright and the foreign ministers of Britain, France, Germany,
Italy and Russia have agreed to meet in Brussels within a few days
to assess the NATO campaign and reaffirm their determination to
forge a settlement for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Vice President Al Gore talked for 40 minutes by phone
with Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov to try to smooth over
differences between the United States and Moscow over Kosovo. The
two men had not talked since Primakov abruptly cut off his planned
visit to Washington the day the bombing began.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, General Yury Baluyevsky, a senior officer of Russia's
general staff, said Moscow believed NATO would launch a ground
assault from Albania into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Increasingly, NATO favors conducting a ground operation first
in Kosovo, while locations in Yugoslavia proper will be cut off,''
Baluyevsky said. ``Air strikes will be launched against
administrative and industrial targets. The goal of such an
operation is to make the leadership of Yugoslavia accept the West's
conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   Foreign minister Igor Ivanov told the briefing that according to
his information, NATO leaders were preparing a ground assault
despite assurances that the alliance was not planning to send its
troops into Kosovo. He said troops from Germany, Italy, France and
Britain were being readied for positioning in Macedonia and
Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Baluyevsky repeated the Russian assertion that NATO's airstrikes
are being aimed increasingly at civilian targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the past 24 hours, airstrikes were carried out against 44
targets. Of them only 20 were military,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also cited unnamed NATO experts as saying that NATO's
operation in Yugoslavia ``could drag on for several years.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Filipov of the Globe staff contributed from Moscow.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
