<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALONE'S LIBERTY ACQUIRES STAKE IN NEWS CORPORATION
</P>
<P>
   Rupert Murdoch and John Malone strengthened a media alliance as
Murdoch's News Corp. agreed to take over their sports cable venture
and Mr. Malone's Liberty Media Group agreed to acquire an 8 percent
stake in the News Corporation.
</P>
<P>
   Liberty is acquiring 51.8 million shares of News Corp. in
exchange for its half interest in Fox/Liberty Sports. In a second
transaction, Liberty is acquiring 28.1 million shares from MCI
Worldcom. Reports of a deal between Malone and Murdoch have driven
News Corporation's American depository receipts up 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   AMR AND THE INTERNET STOCK FRENZY
</P>
<P>
   With investors' current frenzy to buy Internet stocks, some
people are convinced that AMR, the parent of American Airlines,
could bring its pilots union to heel by splitting off its Sabre
Group. Sabre is an information technology company that owns
Travelocity, the seller of plane tickets over the Web.
</P>
<P>
   KEATING PLEADS GUILTY TO FRAUD
</P>
<P>
   Charles Keating, the banker who mismanaged American Continental
Corp., the parent company of Lincoln Savings and Loan, pleaded
guilty to four counts of fraud in Federal court and admitted taking
almost $1 million from a company that was financially insolvent.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO SALES STRONG IN FIRST QUARTER
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every automaker closed March and the first quarter with
sales higher than last year's strong levels.
</P>
<P>
   DOW FALLS, BUT NASDAQ SETS RECORD
</P>
<P>
   Stocks fell from record levels as Gillette led consumer
companies lower after the company said its earnings would not meet
expectations because of slow Latin American sales. The Dow Jones
industrial average fell 43.84 points, to 9,963.49. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index slipped 3.23 points, to 1,317.89. The Nasdaq
composite index edged up 3.11 points, to 2,563.17, a record. In the
bond market, Treasury prices rose as the yield of the 30-year issue
fell to 5.52 percent from 5.58 percent.
</P>
<P>
   NISSAN DISCLOSES PENSION SHORTAGE
</P>
<P>
   Nissan Motor disclosed a $4.76 billion pension financing
shortage, almost twice as much as analysts had expected.
</P>
<P>
   XEROX NAMES NEW CHIEF EXECUTIVE
</P>
<P>
   Xerox named G. Richard Thoman, 54, left, as its chief executive,
replacing Paul Allaire, 60, who remains as chairman. Thoman has
been groomed to succeed Allaire ever since he joined Xerox from IBM
in June 1997, so his ascension is unlikely to touch off any
strategic or cultural shifts. Still, Thoman takes the helm at a
time of change at Xerox.
</P>
<P>
   ALEMAN FAMILY SELLS TELEVISA STAKE
</P>
<P>
   Two of Mexico's most powerful business dynasties parted ways as
the Aleman family announced that it was selling its 14 percent
stake in the company that controls Grupo Televisa, the nation's
largest broadcast network.
</P>
<P>
   FRENCH BANKS REJECT HOSTILE BIDS
</P>
<P>
   The boards of two French banks, Societe Generale and Paribas,
voted to reject Banque Nationale de Paris's $39 billion hostile
takeover bids, but analysts said there could be more negotiations
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA AND IMF IN NEGOTIATIONS
</P>
<P>
   The IMF and the Russian government will begin a critical round
of negotiations today in the hope of averting a threatened default
on Russia's foreign debt. Russia hopes the fund will refinance $4.8
billion in loans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-99 2122EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
