<SLUG> BC-MA-DOCTOR-PROFILES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHYSICIAN PROFILES LACK SIGNIFICANT DATA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The state medical board, under fire for its lax
handling of three doctors facing criminal charges, is also failing
to keep its noted on-line physician profiles updated with such
information as doctors' criminal convictions, paid malpractice
claims, and hospital discipline actions.
</P>
<P>
   A Globe review this week has found missing data on at least two
physicians convicted of Medicaid fraud in the early 1990s and one
physician whose insurer paid approximately $5 million last year in
a malpractice case involving a brain-injured baby.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a comparison of earlier versions of profiles with
more recent ones for some doctors shows an apparent whitewashing of
the record.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a 1996 profile for one physician gave ``academic
research fraud'' as the reason for his 1995 resignation from
Brigham and Women's Hospital, but a 1998 one deleted the reason for
the hospital discipline. That physician, Andrew J. Friedman, has
since had his Massachusetts medical license suspended and does not
currently appear on the board's profiles.
</P>
<P>
   The board's acting executive director, Penelope Wells, had no
explanation for that change, noting that the profiles usually use
the reason for disciplinary action cited by the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Introduced in late 1996, the first-in-the-nation on-line
profiles were created in part as a response to a Globe Spotlight
series in 1994 on medical malpractice, and have been considered the
state Board of Registration in Medicine's premier achievement. The
profiles are designed to include such basic information as
education, board certification, as well as malpractice payments
made and hospital or medical board discipline in the last 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Information had been found missing in some of the profiles early
on in their roll-out, and state officials promised in 1997 to
improve them.
</P>
<P>
   But, ``It's becoming more and more difficult to trust the
board,'' said Linda DeBenedictis, president and founder of the
Norwood-based New England Patients' Rights Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're almost at a crisis situation,'' DeBenedictis said. ``I
think the public is losing faith. How can we believe anything
they're going to tell us by their track record?''
</P>
<P>
   State officials defended the profiles, saying they rely on
malpractice insurers, doctors, and courts to provide the relevant
information. If they don't get the information, they can't include
it, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a snapshot, not a biography. There's 97 percent
accuracy,'' said Kim Hinden McDonald, spokeswoman for the state
Office of Consumer Affairs. ``The physician profile is the first
step, not the last step,'' she said. ``It should not be the last
word in choosing a doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the imperfections, Wells, who has also been the board's
long-time general counsel, said the Massachusetts physician
profiles continue to lead the nation. ``They include more
information _ by far _ than exists in any other state. Most other
states aspire to have as much information on their profiles as we
have.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells, who took over the reins from Alexander ``Sandy'' Fleming
after he resigned last month under criticism, added, ``That's the
best we can do. We're not going to certify that we have everything
on a particular physician. We can only include the information that
we have.''
</P>
<P>
   But in interviews, attorneys, physicians, and consumer advocates
familiar with the board's workings say even when the board has the
information, it fails to show up on the profiles. If incomplete or
tardy reporting by doctors, courts, or malpractice insurers is a
source of the problem, the board should crack down and enforce the
reporting requirements, they add.
</P>
<P>
   ``They shouldn't have to wait for somebody to come knocking on
their doors,'' said attorney Andrew C. Meyer, who specializes in
representing patients who have been harmed by medical malpractice.
``They stick their head in the sand.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Paul D. Weinstein pleaded nolo contendere, or no contest, to
Medicaid fraud in 1992, yet his physician profile says ``Dr.
Weinstein has had no criminal convictions in the past 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview this week, Weinstein said he reported his plea
to the board and has obeyed all requirements and regulations since
then. ``They're well aware of it, that situation,'' said Weinstein,
whose medical license was revoked by the board in 1992, but was
reinstated with probation in 1995. ``It was . . . a difficult
chapter in our life, and we've certainly complied with all the
regulations since then.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Benjamin Weinberg, was convicted of Medicaid fraud in 1991,
but the board's physician profile also says ``Dr. Weinberg has had
no criminal convictions in the past 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   The attorney who represented both Weinberg and Weinstein said
that both men have paid their dues and followed all reporting
requirements, and that the board knows of the prior convictions.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the convictions this week, Wells was surprised
to find the information missing from the public profiles. She
checked the board's internal database and found the Medicaid
conviction information there. ``This would be a glitch,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After talking with one of her staff members involved with the
profiles, Wells discovered that the off-site ``web master'' who is
maintaining the database for the board has taken all the criminal
convictions data off line for more than a week, in order to add
information about serious misdemeanors.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no notification of that in the public profiles,
only the misleading statement that there are no criminal
convictions.
</P>
<P>
   In another physician profile, for Dr. Dennis Lund of Children's
Hospital, there was no information late on Monday about a
settlement made by his insurer in a case involving a baby injured
by an apparent potassium overdose.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Meyer, who represented the baby's family, remembers
getting the settlement of about $5 million from Lund's insurer
about a year ago and was outraged that the payment hasn't yet been
reported on the board's profile. ``They're simply circumventing
every reporting requirement,'' Meyer said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, a spokesman for the Risk Management Foundation of the
Harvard Medical Institutions, which services Lund's malpractice
insurer, said the payment had been reported to the state medical
board, although he could not say when or divulge the amount.
</P>
<P>
   Upon checking with her staff late Monday, Wells said she was
surprised to find that the insurer had made the report only that
day, the same day a Globe reporter asked the insurer about it, even
though the payment was made last year. ``Yes, I wonder about'' the
timing, Wells said.
</P>
<P>
   Lund's profile was taken off line Tuesday, for about three
weeks, while that information is added and double-checked with the
physician, Wells said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
