<SLUG> BC-ZILOG-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZILOG ACQUIRES SEATTLE SILICON CORP. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL SHUKOVSKY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ ZiLog, a Campbell, Calif., company which supplies
seminconductor products for home entertainment, communication and
embedded control markets, has acquired Seattle Silicon Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The privately held ZiLog on Tuesday did not reveal terms of the
asset acquisition of the Bellevue, Wash.-based semiconductor
company that does custom design work on analog devices but said it
hopes to use its new Puget Sound base to attract talent that
prefers living in this part of the country.
</P>
<P>
   ZiLog chief executive Curtis Crawford said Tuesday that none of
the approximately 15 engineering employees at Seattle Silicon will
lose their jobs and he anticipates modest hiring of new people over
time.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford cited the analog capabilities that Seattle Silicon
brings to ZiLog as a chief reason for the acquisition. Those
capabilities will increase ZiLog's range of possible markets for
embedded microprocessor devices, he said. Products like passive
infra-red detection in home security technology and radio frequency
chips in wireless communications such as those used in cordless
phones are designed by Seattle Silicon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world is analog; it's not made of ones and zeros,'' said
Crawford. ``Having the analog, mixed-signal experience is something
we need to grow as a company.''
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition should also be welcome news for anyone who has
been roused from sleep at 5 a.m. by the backup warning beeps of a
dumpster truck. Among the analog capabilities Seattle Silicon
brings to ZiLog are intelligent sound detection devices which
adjust the volume of the backup beepers. The quieter the ambient
street noise, the softer the beeper.
</P>
<P>
   Acquiring Seattle Silicon's experienced engineers is
particularly important to ZiLog because ``these analog designers
are difficult to get and difficult to train,'' said Crawford.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle Silicon's location as a ZiLog design center will give
the company the opportunity ``to attract talent that wants to be in
this very beautiful part of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   ZiLog had revenues in 1998 of $204.7 million. It employs about
1,200 people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
