<DOCNO> NYT19990406.0345 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8286 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-AIRLIFT-615&AMP;AD     04-06 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-AIRLIFT-615&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH AID EFFORT OVERWHELMED, NATO TAKES OVER COORDINATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-SERBIA,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-ISRAEL, KOSOVO-ALLIES,
KOSOVO-DIPLO, KOSOVO-BASES) 
(mk) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO announced Tuesday that it was coordinating all
transportation of food, relief supplies and medical care to the
Kosovo refugees, as well as airlifting them to temporary camps,
after two days of relief efforts by individual member countries.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, the U.N. high commissioner for refugees,
Sadako Ogata, sent a private letter to Javier Solana, the NATO
secretary-general, saying her agency was overwhelmed by the crisis
and asking for immediate military help to bring order to the
deteriorating situation on the Kosovo border.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were overwhelmed; we needed to save lives,'' said Karen
AbuZayd, the refugee agency's representative to the United States.
``We ask the military for help only when we have no other choice
and when we had 350,000 refugees we knew we had reached that
point.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, NATO troops who were to serve as peacekeepers in Kosovo
have transformed themselves into a relief operation, working round
the clock to throw up tents at six camps in Macedonia and three
camps in Albania. NATO pilots are flying helicopters between
Tirana, Albania, and the border town of Kukes, ferrying emergency
supplies to the refugees and evacuating those who need medical
care, said Jamie Shea, spokesman for NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Now NATO will set up headquarters in Tirana to organize the
ground transportation of trucks filled with supplies _ food,
medicine, blankets, sleeping bags, even thermal underwear _ to the
refugees and to establish an airlift operating center outside
Brussels, said Lt. Col. Wilhelm Bocklet, a NATO spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   NATO earlier had announced that it would take charge of
airlifting refugees out of Macedonia and flying them to temporary
housing in NATO countries. But NATO had left it up to each
individual country among its 19 members to make contributions to
the relief effort _ be it the United States, with its logistical
support, or Italy, with its camp police. The U.N. refugee agency
had been the sole organization coordinating the relief and rescue
operations on the ground, working with at least 55 private
voluntary groups.
</P>
<P>
   Now NATO will assume military coordination of the relief convoys
overland, as well as transport of supplies by air for the refugees,
whose numbers rose by another 55,000 Tuesday, bringing the total to
480,000 people who have left Kosovo since the bombing began on
March 24, according to Kris Janowski, a refugee agency spokesman in
Geneva, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   ``The airlift in Tirana varies from day to day, about nine to
ten humanitarian flights,'' said Janowski. ``Today's biggest single
load was American military planes _ Hercules _ flying in on six
flights from Ancona, Italy.''
</P>
<P>
   The American contribution of logistical support _ from building
new airstrips in Albania to providing a mobile air traffic control
unit near Tirana _ is critical since at its core the relief
operation has to make sense out of a logistical nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   ``The airport at Tirana is very small _ it doesn't even have a
tower,'' said NATO's Bocklet. ``The U.S. air mobility
communications center is crucial.''
</P>
<P>
   As the relief effort grows in size and mission, the skies over
Yugoslavia and the Adriatic Sea have become clogged with aircraft
on combat missions over Yugoslavia and relief flights to Albania
and Macedonia, creating what the Pentagon spokesman, Kenneth Bacon,
described as a ``sequencing'' problem.
</P>
<P>
   With most of these flights originating from bases in Italy, that
country has closed down all of its civilian airports on the
Adriatic coast, said Ambassador Ferdinando Salleo of the Italian
Embassy here. ``We had to close all civilian traffic from Trieste
all the way down to the south,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Over the weekend, NATO officials took over managing the air
operations control center for the U.N. refugee agency in Geneva
because it, too, was finding it hard to manage all of the growing
air traffic, said Ms. AbuZayd. She said the congestion would only
get worse with planes carrying supplies in while others carry
refugees out.
</P>
<P>
   Among the countries that have offered to take refugees for
temporary asylum are: Germany, Turkey, Australia, Norway, the
United States, Greece, Austria, Canada, Spain, the Netherlands,
France and Britain.
</P>
<P>
   The American contribution to the airlift will include
transporting food, tents, blankets and sleeping bags, among other
supplies, to the NATO base in Ancona, where the goods will then be
loaded onto C-130 transport planes and flown into Albania and
Macedonia at the rate of 10 flights a day, said Maj. Gen. Charles
Wald, vice director of strategic plans and policy for the Joint
Chiefs of Staff.
</P>
<P>
   In Tirana itself, the United States will ``make sure the
airfield is up and running,'' said Wald, as well as oversee the
unloading of the supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Since the American government plays such a key role in both NATO
and the refugee agency, President Clinton established a special
council to coordinate all American civilian and military
contributions to the Kosovo relief effort, said Brian Atwood,
chairman of the new council.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is giving most of its donations to the refugee
agency, as are other foreign nations, including the NATO countries,
Asian nations like Japan and Pakistan, and Middle Eastern nations
like Kuwait, which on Monday donated sugar, flour, blankets and
milk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
