<HEADER>
A8289 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-LIBYA-BOS &LR;      04-06 0372
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-LIBYA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE KHADAFY CONNECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Moammar Khadafy's extradition to Holland of two Libyan
intelligence agents who are to stand trial under Scottish law for
the bombing of Pan Am Flight 103 in 1988 may signify the success of
an arduous diplomatic effort, but there remains a long way to go
before justice is done.
</P>
<P>
   It should be obvious that even if the two surrendered agents are
proved guilty as charged in an impeccable judicial proceding, there
is almost no possibility they acted on their own.
</P>
<P>
   Being officers of an intelligence agency in Khadafy's despotic
state, they could not have expected to keep their jobs, or their
heads, if they had taken it upon themselves to imperil Khadafy's
regime by blowing up US citizens in an American airliner.
</P>
<P>
   If they had acted as improvising terrorists who just happened to
be in the employ of Khadafy's security service, they would hardly
have been able to hide from the law for the past decade under the
solicitous protection of the erratic colonel who rules their
country.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives of the murdered passengers on Pan Am 103 have
expressed a justified expectation that the coming trial will not be
confined to the circumscribed question of whether or not the two
extradited suspects are guilty. True justice demands a
determination of ultimate guilt. That means pursuing a trail of
evidence and logic that is almost certain to lead to Khadafy
himself.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to believe that Khadafy finally decided to extradite
his two agents without a well-grounded assumption that they will
not implicate him before their Scottish judges. After all, he
retains the power to punish or reward the kinfolk of the two
accused terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the same leverage that compelled Khadafy to honor
the indictments of his intelligence officers could be wielded
against a regime that refuses to admit its guilt for an act of
state terrorism. Libya has been able to import and export under the
UN's economic sanctions, but it desperately needs foreign
investment to revive its oil industry. That investment should be
withheld until the guiltiest parties confess thieir crime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
