<SLUG> BC-AUTO-SALES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST-QUARTER AUTO SALES SAID TO BE FASTEST START EVER  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHELLE KREBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ When the General Motors Corp. reports its sales of
cars and trucks in March on Wednesday, the first quarter of 1999
will most likely go into the books as the best start ever to a
sales year for the U.S. auto industry.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually every auto maker closed March and the first quarter
with sales even higher than last year's healthy levels. Last week,
DaimlerChrysler, Volvo, Honda and Infiniti reported record March
sales. Kia had its best month ever, Volkswagen had its best March
since 1981, and Subaru had its best March since 1988. Audi, BMW
with Land Rover, Isuzu and Nissan also reported higher sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without even knowing GM's numbers, the first quarter has
closed with the fastest sales start in U.S. history,'' said George
Pipas, manager of sales analysis for the Ford Motor Co., which
reported higher-than-expected March sales on Tuesday. Ford said it
sold 399,908 cars and trucks through its Ford, Mercury, Lincoln and
Jaguar dealers in March, up 13 percent compared with sales in the
month a year earlier and surpassing the March record set in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   When GM's sales are added in _ and they are predicted to be
slightly higher than last year's _ the seasonally adjusted average
selling rate likely will rise to more than 17 million cars and
light trucks, an increase of about 12 percent compared with last
year's strong March results, said David Healy, an auto analyst with
Burnham Securities in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Pipas noted that the first quarter of 1999 is not a single
quarter phenomenon. The annual selling rate has been running at 16
million vehicles or more every month since last March, except for
July and August, when GM's North American assembly plants were shut
down because of a strike by workers at two parts plants in
Michigan. He sees no end in sight to strong car sales.
</P>
<P>
   What is significant is not only the sheer volume of vehicles
auto makers are selling, but what vehicles they are selling, noted
Healy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most profitable models are showing the strongest sales and
the biggest year-to-year increases,'' he said, noting sales of
Ford's Expedition and DaimlerChrysler's Dodge Durango as well as
luxury car sales are extremely strong. ``It's the best of all
possible worlds for the auto makers. For a change, Detroit is
profit city.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, auto makers have backed off from costly incentives,
and the deflation of car prices that has occurred over the last two
years appears to be ending. Prices will most likely rise and
incentives will continue to slow as auto makers find themselves in
short supply of some vehicles because of the stronger-than-expected
winter sales. March typically marks the start of the best-selling
six months of the year, and auto makers build inventories through
the winter to prepare for the spring selling season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sales have been equaling production, so the industry has built
no stock,'' Pipas said. ``That probably will help firm up prices
further.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to strong sales, auto makers have been raising their
industry sales forecasts for the year and increasing vehicle
production. Ford said on Tuesday that it would increase
second-quarter production by 20,000 trucks and 10,000 cars. In
March, after a stronger January and February than expected, Ford
raised its sales forecast for the year to between 15.5 million and
16 million vehicles, from 15 million to 15.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things would have to sink quickly in order for the industry to
slump to the low end of that range,'' Pipas said. ``While we do
expect the second half of the year to have a slower sales pace than
the first quarter, a record sales year will be on people's minds by
the end of June.''
</P>
<P>
   The previous record for annual car and truck sales was 16
million vehicles in 1986.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-99 2149EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
