<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8294 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOCKERBIE-DEAL-NYT &LR;      04-06 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOCKERBIE-DEAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW THE U.N. MOVED LIBYAN BOMBING SUSPECTS, VERY DISCREETLY, TO
COURT
</HEADLINE>
  (With LOCKERBIE) 
 (nk) 
 By JUDITH MILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The operation was intricate, complex and above
all secret. No one except Hans Corell, the chief legal counsel for
the United Nations _ not even Secretary-General Kofi Annan _ knew
the details surrounding the logistics for the surrender of the two
Libyan suspects charged with planting the bomb that downed Pan Am
Flight 103 over Lockerbie, Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews over the past two days, Annan, Corell and other
senior diplomats described eight months of intense political and
logistical maneuvering that produced the breakthrough, ending a
decadelong diplomatic impasse and giving the increasingly
marginalized United Nations a sorely needed victory.
</P>
<P>
   Annan disclosed, for instance, that all the legal and logistical
problems had been resolved by mid-November. He and Corell had even
asked Italy to lend the United Nations a Boeing 707 jet on which
U.N. markings were painted.
</P>
<P>
   Corell had located and interviewed trustworthy pilots,
personally approved the flight plan to the Netherlands and
recruited doctors and nurses to accompany the two ``passengers,''
as he called them. He had even ordered appropriate food _ no ham,
shellfish or alcohol, in light of Muslim dietary prohibitions _ and
taken steps to insure that the food would not be poisoned.
</P>
<P>
   Then Col. Moammar Gadhafi, Libya's eccentric leader, balked at
the deal that he and the Arab League had originally proposed _
putting the two suspected intelligence agents on trial in a third
country.
</P>
<P>
   So Annan orchestrated a discreet but relentless political
campaign to persuade Gadhafi, including a hitherto secret appeal by
Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov. As part of this appeal,
the United States assured Libya that the trial would not be used to
undermine the colonel's rule.
</P>
<P>
   Annan said he had realized early in his tenure as
secretary-general that Libya was slowly persuading the Organization
of African Unity, the Arab League and other countries that the two
Libyan suspects, Abdel Basset Ali al-Megrahi and Lamen Khalifa
Fhimah, would never get a fair trial in Britain or the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Chad, Niger and Gambia, among other African states, began
flouting the U.N. sanctions by flying their leaders or senior
officials into Tripoli airport. And last summer the 53 members of
the Organization for African Unity voted to stop abiding by the
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Annan said he realized that if NATO didn't find a way forward,
the economic sanctions would lose all legitimacy.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he said, by rejecting ``every Libyan
proposal,'' the United States and Britain ``had boxed themselves
into a situation of being the stubborn negative ones.''
</P>
<P>
   What Annan called the ``first crack'' in the impasse occurred
last August when first Britain then, more reluctantly, the United
States agreed to the Libyan-endorsed Arab League proposal that the
two men could stand trial in the Netherlands under Scottish law.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ultimately decided,'' one American official said, ``that
agreeing to the Libyan proposal of a trial in third country would
box Libya in.'' If Gadhafi agreed, ``the impasse would be over,''
the official said. ``If he did not accept a version of his own
proposal, he would be embarrassed and ultimately isolated.''
</P>
<P>
   Last October and November, U.N. lawyers led by Corell and a
Libyan legal team led by Kamel Hassan Maghur, a former foreign
minister, met quietly at the United Nations over several weeks to
``clarify'' the many thorny questions: Who would be authorized to
defend the Libyans in a Scottish court of law in the Netherlands?
Would the suspects would be considered ``passengers'' or
``prisoners'' on the flight from Libya?
</P>
<P>
   Corell quietly began preparing for the surrender and transfer.
All of the legal issues and arrangements were completed by Nov. 13,
Corell said, but still there was no political decision from
Gadhafi.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to work with the technicians and another to get
a political decision,'' Annan said. ``And we needed a political
decision, which is why I went to work.''
</P>
<P>
   In early December, Annan flew to Libya to meet with Gadhafi.
After several hours of one-on-one discussions in the leader's tent
outside Sirte, his desert capital, Annan said, he left convinced
that the colonel had realized that a deal ``had to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Libyan had repeatedly vowed publicly never to turn the
suspects over to a foreign court. ``So he had to manage his own
reality,'' Annan said, ``and reverse the dynamics he had created.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking no chances, Annan flew from Libya to an Arab summit
meeting in the United Arab Emirates, where he enlisted promises of
mediation and other support from President Nelson Mandela of South
Africa and Crown Prince Abdullah of Saudi Arabia and their
emissaries. In the ensuing weeks, he said, he recruited dozens of
leaders, including Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and Primakov,
to urge Gadhafi to accept the deal.
</P>
<P>
   An American official agreed that Russia, which has opposed
American policy on Iraq and Kosovo, had been ``very helpful'' in
resolving the Libyan impasse.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the diplomats interviewed said they began to believe
that Gadhafi would surrender the suspects as promised only after
Mandela announced it on March 19 in a speech at Gadhafi's side in
Tripoli. Even then, Corell was so secretive that not even Annan
knew exactly when, where and how the Libyans would be moved.
</P>
<P>
   Corell, a meticulous lawyer with a passion for bird-watching and
playing bagpipes, left nothing to chance. An experienced negotiator
and appellate court judge in his native Sweden, he and a Russian
lawyer on his staff checked off item after item on their list, from
jet fuel to devising a seating plan for the flight.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats said Corell was obsessed with security, and rightly
so, given Libya's insistence on it and warnings the United Nations
had received about people who wanted to insure that the two men
would never stand trial in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday United Nations and American officials called the
surrender a vindication of the sanctions that many complained would
never work.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time, we decided to use a multilateral-sanctions
approach on a terrorism issue,'' an American official said. ``Now
there will be a trial, and justice will be done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
