<P>
   (NYT11) BOSTON -- April 6, 1999 -- AMC-MISSION-BOS, 4-05 --
Andrew J. Falender, executive director of Boston's Appalachian
Mountain Club, in the club's old library. ``The most common
misperception about the Appalachian Mountain Club is that we run
the Appalachian Trail, and we don't,'' says Falender. The club is
responsible for only 350 miles of the 2,200 mile-long trail, though
its members do maintain 1,400 miles of other hiking trails
throughout the Northeast. (Tom Herde/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- April 6, 1999 -- PROFILE-EPPS-BOS,
4-06 -- Outgoing Harvard College dean of students, Archie Epps,
right, greets a Harvard student on campus. Epps, 62, is stepping
down this spring after 29 years in the dean's chair, closing a
remarkable chapter in Harvard history. (Tom Herde/Boston Globe
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) FAIRHAVEN, Mass. -- April 6, 1999 -- SCI-GEORGES-BOS,
4-05 -- Captain and owner Malvin Kivlhaug, left, and Arnie Aluheim,
a retired first mate, examine a fishing net on one of Kivlhaug's
scallop fishing vessels, Sandra Jane, docked in Fairhaven.
Scallops, New England's second most valuable seafood, have grown so
fat and plentiful that, despite laws forbidding it, some scallopers
risk Coast Guard seizure of their boats to plumb the mollusk-rich
waters. (Joanne Rathe/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- April 6, 1999 -- QUAIL, 4-06 -- At Babbo in
Manhattan, Mario Batali adds blood oranges and dandelion greens to
his grilled quail. In the last few years, partly boned quail have
started turning up at butcher shops and even in supermarkets.
Without the breastbones and backbones, the sweetly flavored, tender
fowl are as fast and easy to cook - and eat - as chicken cutlets.
(Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- April 6, 1999 -- EATING-WEEDS, 4-06 -- Dennis
Foy's braised nettles with sauteed turbot at EQ in Greenwich
Village. When freshly picked, nettles are highly nutritious. But
chefs like them for their tangy taste. (David Corio/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) ATLANTA -- April 6, 1999 -- BBO-HANK-HAMMER-COX, 04-06 --
Hank Aaron stands at the site where, on April 8, 1974, he hit his
715th home run - surpassing Babe Ruth as the leader in major league
home runs. Today, the site of the former Atlanta Fulton County
Stadium is the parking lot for the Braves' Turner Field. (Rich
Addicks/Atlanta Journal Constitution Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) ATLANTA -- April 6, 1999 -- BBO-HANK-CHASE-B&AMP;W-COX, 04-06
-- Hank Aaron rounds the bases after hitting his 715th home run in
Atlanta on April 8, 1974. Thursday is the 25th anniversary of the
home run which broke Babe Ruth's record. (Billy Downs/Atlanta
Journal-Constitution Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- April 6, 1999 -- NY-KOREAN-COOKING-3, 04-06
-- A waitress serves customers at Kang Suh Korean Restaurant in
Manhattan's Koreatown. Like many Korean restaurants, Kang Suh uses
charcoal at the table to fashion an indoor barbecue. (Chang W.
Lee/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- April 6, 1999 -- NY-KOREAN-COOKING-2, 04-06
-- At Han Bat restaurant in Manhattan's Koreatown, you can get Hae
Mul Pa Jun, a seafood pancake, center, and Sul Run Tang, stewed
beef broth with rice and noodles, which has been cooking for 12
hours in Ga Ma Sott, Korean traditional pots. (Chang W. Lee/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- April 6, 1999 -- NY-KOREAN-COOKING-1, 04-06
-- In Manhattan, 32nd Street between Fifth Avenue and Broadway is
the heart of Koreatown. This small street in the middle of the
garment district houses some of the best Korean restaurants in the
area. Traditionally not marketed to non-Koreans, a new, more
expansive generation of Korean-Americans are finding new ways for
non-Koreans to experience their cuisine. (Chang W. Lee/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) GUANTANAMO BAY, Cuba -- April 6, 1999 --
KOSOVO-GITMO-COX, 04-06 -- A U.S. Coast Guard cutter steams past
one of the tent cities at the U.S. Navy base at Guantanamo Bay in
January 1995 - just one of the camps used to hold asylum-seeking
Cubans and Haitians in 1994 and 1995. On Tuesday, U.S. officials
announced that 20,000 Kosovo refugees will be temporarily housed
here. (Rick McKay/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
