<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8303 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRAVEL-MINING-LADN     04-06 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAVEL-MINING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINING PLAN SPARKS CONTROVERSY IN LOS ANGELES COUNTY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JASON TAKENOUCHI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARITA, Calif. -- The country's second-largest cement
company has found gray, grainy ``gold'' inside the hills of Soledad
Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   Transit Mixed Concrete Co., a subsidiary of Houston-based
Southdown Inc., wants to use 500 acres of the canyon in north Los
Angeles County for a $336 million mining project that would be
among the largest in the region. Company officials said the site
would rejuvenate dwindling stores of Portland concrete cement
aggregates, a key ingredient for the construction boom in the
suburban Santa Clarita and San Fernando valleys.
</P>
<P>
   The county Regional Planning Commission will decide today
whether or not to delay hearings on the mining plan. Opposition has
been coalescing around the project, and an array of public and
private groups have asked for more time to study the plan's
potential environmental impact.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials have agreed that more time should be given for
analysis. But they caution that the San Fernando Valley's dwindling
supply could dramatically increase construction costs in the next
few years.
</P>
<P>
   According to California Department of Conservation estimates,
the San Fernando Valley could run out of aggregates by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a serious problem,'' said Transit Mixed spokesman Brian
Mastin. ``The San Fernando Valley is going to experience cost
increases.''
</P>
<P>
   Mastin estimates that the Soledad Canyon mining project will
save developers, including public agencies, about $170 million in
transport costs compared to alternative mining sites in Southern
California's Orange County and the Antelope Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The company also has agreed to pay the federal government $28
million in royalties. Of that money, the state would receive about
$1.1 million and the county would net $560,000.
</P>
<P>
   If approved, the 20-year mining plan would eventually produce 56
million tons of high-quality gravel and sand, also known as
Portland cement concrete aggregates.
</P>
<P>
   PCC aggregates are used in everything from freeways to schools
to house foundations. One mile of an eight-lane freeway requires
about 80,000 tons of aggregates.
</P>
<P>
   The material sells for about $6 a ton at a quarry, but that
price increases dramatically if it has to be transported.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trucking is the major way, almost the only way, of hauling
aggregate in Southern California, and it's very expensive relative
to the cost of the aggregate,'' said Russell Miller, senior
geologist with the state Department of Conservation. ``Every 35
miles equals the cost of the original aggregate.''
</P>
<P>
   Cost concerns prompted the Valley Industry and Commerce
Association to vote last week to support the mining plan.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents say the project's impact -- including traffic, air
quality and noise -- outweighs its benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have seized upon the project's environmental report as
proof that it will do irrevocable damage to the environment and
residents' health. The nearest residential area -- a small mobile
home park -- is within one quarter-mile of the project, and
thousands of people live within three or four miles of the site.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, the mining plan will create
``unavoidable significant adverse impacts'' to regional air quality
and visual beauty. The project will also use more than 700
acre-feet of water per year in its second 10-year phase. An
acre-foot is about 326,000 gallons.
</P>
<P>
   The report estimates that the mining operation will create up to
1,000 pounds of carbon monoxide and 1,770 pounds of nitrogen oxides
a day. Even after reduction measures, which the company says will
reduce emission by 40 percent, those levels exceed thresholds set
by the Southern California Air Quality Management District.
</P>
<P>
   But the company's environmental consultant, Carolyn Casavan of
West Coast Environmental and Engineering, said the average
emissions from the project will not exceed federal or state ambient
air quality standards for nearby residents.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents say seasonal winds could blow those emissions far
beyond the project area, creating problems for residents across the
valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this project will damage a lot of people,'' said
Michael Karbacher, a resident of the nearby town of Agua Dulce.
``They'll get sick, and who's going to pay for that?''
</P>
<P>
   Lynne Plambeck, a local environmentalist, agreed that the mine
would create health and environmental problems for years to come.
But she said the project and its problems speak to much deeper
development issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that if we're going to continue to build at the
rate that we're building, we're going to need aggregate,'' she
said. ``This kind of operation is one of the costs of sprawl.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
