<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 04/06/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) HANFORD, Wash. -- April 6, 1999 -- HANFORD-CLEANUP, 4-06
-- David Carbaugh, who is suing his ex-employers at the Energy
Department, before the Plutonium Recycling Test Reactor at Hanford.
The Justice Department has decided not to join the suit, a decision
often separate from the merits of the claim. (Jackie Johnston/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) NEW YORK -- April 6, 1999 -- NY-DIALLO-POLICE, 4-06 --
Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani, with Police Commissioner Howard Safir
behind him, displays a card which he would like to distribute to
the city's police force. The card offers a lesson in good manners,
instructing police to be a bit more polite in their dealings on the
street. To some, the cards seem a superficial fix to the deeper
questions about the police that have arisen since the slaying of
Amadou Diallo. (Don Hogan Charles/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) WASHINGTON -- April 6, 1999 -- HATE-CRIMES, 4-06 --
President Clinton on Tuesday explaining his views on hate crime.
``America will not be able to be a force for good abroad unless we
are good at home,'' he says Clinton, linking hate crimes in America
with the ``ethnic cleansing'' in Kosovo and adding that the United
States should at least set an example by not tolerating such bias.
(Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) OSSINING, N.Y. -- April 6, 1999 -- PRISONS-CHILDREN-3,
4-06 -- Baba Eng, serving life for murder in Sing Sing prison in
Ossining, meets with Elizabeth Gaynes, whose group sponsors
programs for prisoners and their families. Eng met his son recently
- doing time for armed robbery - for the first time in 22 years.
``It was the worst moment of my life,'' Eng recalls. ``He had tried
to imitate my life.'' (Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) SAN ANTONIO -- April 6, 1999 -- PRISONS-CHILDREN-2, 4-06
-- By attending parenting classes at the San Antonio jail, Mary
Anne Garza is allowed regular visits with her children, from left:
Anna, 4, and Briana, 9 months, and Edward, 7. ``She wants to come
to jail with me,'' Ms. Garza says of Anna on a recent visit.
(Matthew Sturtevant/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) SAN ANTONIO -- April 6, 1999 -- PRISONS-CHILDREN-1, 4-06
-- Derrick Hunt is among a small number of imprisoned fathers
taking part in programs that seek to counter the potential risks of
such separation for their children. Hunt, 23, has regular visits
with his children, Derrick Jr., 5, and Deandre, 3, in San Antonio.
(Matthew Sturtevant/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) MILWAUKEE -- April 6, 1999 -- WIS-WELFARE-MAYOR, 4-06 --
At 86, Frank P. Zeidler is the last of Milwaukee's three socialist
mayors - no other major American city has had even one - and a
living link to time when Wisconsin politics was synonymous with
safety-net expansions, like workers' compensation and unemployment
insurance. ``What you're seeing in Wisconsin is a deconstruction of
the progress we made in the first decades of the 20th century,'' he
says. (Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- April 6, 1999 -- PEOPLE'S-POETRY, 4-06 --
Kewulay Kamara, a storyteller and history-keeper from Sierra Leone.
``It's not told in a literal way, the way history in the West is
told,'' says Kamara, 45. ``Our history is very, very didactic and
it's told in the company of music.'' (Philip Greenberg/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) ROOSEVELT, N.Y. -- April 6, 1999 -- EDISON-EDUC, 4-06 --
Chris Whittle, founder of the Edison Project, whose ambitious plan
to become the first national for-profit school system has attracted
interest from educators and investors alike. ``Our cash flow is
good,'' says Whittle. The Project released a report Tuesday saying
its students are gaining ground on state and national tests
significantly faster than students in other schools. (Steve
Berman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) TOKYO -- April 6, 1999 -- JAPAN-BANKS, 4-06 -- Hakuo
Yanagisawa, who took over as chief regulator of Japan's banking
system in October, speaking to advisors in his office in Tokyo
recently. ``We are absolutely not giving the Japanese financial
institutions the cruel treatment or giving them an impossible or
unsolvable agenda,'' says Yanagisawa, 63. Yet, he adds pointedly,
``I am convinced that this is a time of change.'' (Stuart Isett/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) MORINI, Albania -- April 5, 1999 -- KOSOVO-REFUGEES,
4-01 -- A mother kisses her child in the Albanian border town of
Morini on Tuesday. The long, ragged lines of ethnic Albanian
refugees continued to cross the border from Kosovo here, despite
the unilateral cease-fire declared by the Yugoslav President,
Slobodan Milosevic. (Edward Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) SKOPJE, Macedonia -- April 6, 1999 --
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-3, 4-06 -- Ethnic Albanian refugees from Kosovo
being bundled onto planes to destinations unknown - whether they
like it or not - in Skopje on Tuesday. The Macedonians, eager to
rid their country of its burgeoning Albanian population, did not
bother to let the refugees know where they were headed. (Alan
Chin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) BLACE, Macedonia -- April 6, 1999 -- KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-2,
4-06 -- A Macedonian policeman directs ethnic Albanian refugees
from Kosovo into buses which will take them to a NATO-constructed
camp with better facilities. Confusion and a desperate anxiety has
spread through the refugees here, as Macedonian authorities pressed
on with their shipment of people abroad and Serb police forced
refugees still stuck inKosovo to return back to the capital
Pristina. (Alan Chin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) BLACE, Macedonia -- April 6, 1999 -- KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-1,
4-06 -- Ethnic Albanian refugees from Kosovo cry Tuesday as they
take a last look through a bus window at the makeshift camp in
Blace in which they spent the last week. They are being relocated
to a NATO-constructed camp with far better facilities. (Alan
Chin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) VENICE, Italy -- April 6, 1999 -- VENICE-CATS, 4-06 --
On San Clemente, a lush island in the lagoon near to Venice,
Stefania Caruso, 40, has for the last four years volunteered to
look after the 250 sick or stray cats living here. But Venice plans
to evict the cats, relocating them to a smaller strip of nearby
land. ``I shudder at the idea they will leave this haven,
especially those who grew up here,'' says Ms Caruso. ``They are
trusting, they don't understand danger.'' (James Hill/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) HOUSTON -- April 6, 1999 -- BATLAWSUIT-HNS, 04-06 --
``I'm probably never going to go to another baseball game,'' says
Sterling Lapinski. A flying bat at a 1997 New York Mets vs. Atlanta
Braves game fractured Lapinski's skull, broke his nose and crushed
his nasal cavity. He is now suing the Mets for allowing catcher
Todd Pratt to continue batting even though he had lost his grip on
the bat three times that night. (Steve Campbell/Houston Chronicle
Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- April 6, 1999 -- GYPSY-DANCE-REVIEW,
4-06 -- Patricia Ibanez Romero of Antonio El Pipa Flamenco Ensemble
from Spain during the first of two dynamic performances of ``Gypsy
Caravan'' at the Sanders Theater in Cambridge last Saturday. The
beauty of the production, whose title should be regarded as
symbolic, is that it does do away with stereotypes. (Michael
Quan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) SZEGED, Hungary -- April 6, 1999 -- HUNGARY-SYNAGOGUES,
4-06 -- The Great Synagogue in Szeged is the masterpiece of the
architect Lipot Baumhorn, who also designed many other synagogues.
An exhibition showcasing his work is being held in Budapest. (Ruth
Ellen Gruber/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- April 6, 1999 -- BRONX-RUINS-2, 4-06 --
Pepon Osorio puts the finishing touches on ``The Scene of the Crime
(Whose Crime?),'' his contribution to ``Urban Mythologies: The
Bronx Represented Since the 1960s,'' at the Bronx Museum of the
Arts. Today, the South Bronx, which had long been in decline, is on
the upswing, though its rebound has received considerably less
attention than its slide. (Chester Higgins Jr./New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- April 6, 1999 -- BRONX-RUINS-1, 4-06 -- John
Ahearn's sculpture, ``Raymond and Toby,'' part of ``Urban
Mythologies: The Bronx Represented Since the 1960s,'' at the Bronx
Museum of the Arts. Today, the South Bronx, which had long been in
decline, is on the upswing, though its rebound has received
considerably less attention than its slide. (Chester Higgins
Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
