<HEADLINE>
UNILAB TO PAY $36 MILLION FOR PHYSICIANS CLINICAL LABORATORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TARZANA, Calif. -- In a deal that expands its footprint as the
state's largest regional independent laboratory, Unilab Corp. said
Tuesday it has agreed to buy competitor Physicians Clinical
Laboratory for about $36 million in stock and cash.
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento-based Physicians Clinical Laboratory, which does
business as Bio-Cypher Laboratories, is the state's second largest
independent laboratory company in terms of annual revenue. In 1998,
the company had revenues of about $60 million.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is expected to close in 30 to 60 days, pending approval
by federal regulators, said Melissa Mahoney, Unilab's spokeswoman.
Bio-Cypher has facilities in Sacramento, Fresno and Burbank.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase includes Bio-Cypher's customer lists and about $12
million in assets, primarily accounts receivable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are certainly excited about the prospects this transaction
presents to Unilab. This acquisition of the BCL business is
consistent with our previously announced top-line growth
strategy,'' David Weavil, Unilab's chairman and chief executive,
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1998 fourth quarter, Unilab earned $2.3 million, or 6
cents per share, on sales of $55.3 million. This compares with net
income of $900,000, or 2 cents per share, on sales of $52.7 million
in the 1997 fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 results reflect costs associated with an acquisition
during the year's fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Unilab operates more than 250 facilities throughout the state.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Unilab jumped 18.75 cents to $3.25.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
