<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANFORD-CLEANUP-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWSUIT CLAIMS CONTRACTORS OVERBILLED U.S. FOR NUCLEAR CLEANUP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two federal contractors used a computerized
accounting scheme to overbill the Energy Department by at least $85
million for cleanup work at the Hanford nuclear reservation in
Washington state over the last 12 years, a former budget analyst
for the contractors charged in a lawsuit filed Tuesday in U.S.
District Court in Spokane, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   The contractors, one a subsidiary of CBS Corp. and the other a
subsidiary of Fluor Daniel, were allowed to bill 14 cents for every
dollar they paid workers in straight time, to cover vacation, sick
time and holiday pay. But, the suit says, their computerized
accounting system added the 14 percent charge to overtime wages as
well, as if working extra hours created more vacation or holiday
days.
</P>
<P>
   The contractors compounded the improper charges, the suit says,
by plugging the inflated labor costs into formulas for calculating
pension and benefit costs and general overhead. For a Hanford
worker making $50,000 in regular wages and $10,000 in overtime, the
contractors billed the government $2,967 ``in purely nonexistent
costs,'' the suit says. They kept two sets of books and never
divulged the real costs to the government, according to the suit.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, which seeks $240 million in damages, was filed by
David Carbaugh under the False Claims Act, which lets employees
collect 15 to 30 percent of any damages recovered, in order to
encourage whistle-blowers. The Justice Department has decided not
to join the suit, a decision often made separate from the merits of
the claim.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for one of the contractors, Westinghouse Hanford Co., a
subsidiary of CBS Corp., which bought Westinghouse Electric Corp.,
said Carbaugh's accusations were similar to those he made in a
lawsuit filed in 1996 and were untrue. A spokesman for the other
contractor, Fluor Daniel Hanford Inc., a division of Fluor Daniel,
said the company was not aware of Tuesday's suit.
</P>
<P>
   Carbaugh, an accountant, said in a telephone interview that some
of the money was used to pay surplus management employees who were
being laid off from other Energy Department sites as the department
went out of the business of making nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   An official with the independent panel that advises the federal
and state governments on Hanford said he believed the accusations.
The official, Gerry Pollet, chairman of a subcommittee of the
Hanford Advisory Board that considers overhead charges, said,
``We've been hounding the Energy Department on how much of our
cleanup dollars go to the contractor's overhead. It's obscene. If
you pay $1 billion a year for cleanup, you'll spend about $300
million for Fluor Daniel's overhead.''
</P>
<P>
   Board members are appointed by the Energy Department, the
Environmental Protection Agency and the Washington state Department
of Ecology.
</P>
<P>
   The General Accounting Office, which is the investigative arm of
Congress, identified the Energy Department in 1990 as ``a high-risk
area vulnerable to waste, fraud, abuse and mismanagement,'' citing
the department's ``history of weak oversight of contractors.''
</P>
<P>
   The department did not have enough personnel ``with the
appropriate skills to effectively oversee the contractors'
operations,'' the accounting office found in a February 1997
report. The accounting office said that the Energy Department had
undertaken a reform program ``unprecedented in scope'' in 1994.
Most of the abuses alleged by Carbaugh would have occurred before
then.
</P>
<P>
   Overhead expenses, also known as indirect costs, have been the
subject of a long-running struggle between the contractors and
critics, among them Pollet and Rep. Adam Smith, D-Wash. An Energy
Department report on Fluor Daniel's performance for the 12 months
ending Sept. 30, 1998, said that the company had provided financial
information to Smith ``that was inconsistent with earlier data,''
and that at one point the company had provided ``incorrect indirect
cost numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   But department officials say that although they have not seen
the complaint filed Tuesday, they had been working with Carbaugh
and had not found anything that was illegal or violated the
contract.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released by the department, Energy Secretary Bill
Richardson said, ``We haven't seen the filing yet,'' but he said
that if it contained any information suggesting that the
contractors ``improperly received federal funds, then we will
pursue it vigorously.''
</P>
<P>
   Carbaugh, 43, began as an accountant at Hanford in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Carbaugh said that the Justice Department was aware
of the suit and had indicated it might join it later. ``The
government frequently turns down cases that may be difficult to put
together,'' said Cyrus Mehri, one of the lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   But a lawyer for Westinghouse, Robert Dutton, said that if the
Justice Department did not join the case, ``it generally means
government does not believe there's merit.''
</P>
<P>
   Westinghouse ran the 560-square-mile site for the Energy
Department from June 1, 1987, until Sept. 30, 1996, when Fluor
Daniel took over. Production of weapons material stopped in 1987,
and most work at the site since then has been cleanup, with a
budget now exceeding $1.4 billion a year. According to the suit,
labor accounts for about 60 percent of that cost.
</P>
<P>
   Carbaugh, who worked for Westinghouse and then Fluor Daniel in
the same job, said he complained to his supervisors and later to
Energy Department accountants in Richland, Wash., near the
reservation. ``Some of the people I talked to,'' he said, ``it went
right over their heads.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said it did not go over the head of Westinghouse, which,
he said, retaliated by giving him impossible amounts of work and
then no work, or the head of Fluor Daniel, which fired him shortly
after it took over.
</P>
<P>
   The suit claims that the companies may not have kept all extra
money, but used the extra 14 percent to pad their cost estimates,
and then collected performance bonuses for completing work under
budget. The basic management fee was also inflated, since it was
based on the size of the budget, which itself was inflated,
according to the suit.
</P>
<P>
   The suit claims that Carbaugh was driven into depression by
harassment at work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
