<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8326 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-INCA-MUMMIES-1STL     04-06 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-INCA-MUMMIES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
500-YEAR-OLD MUMMIES MAY GIVE CLUES TO INCA RELIGION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to correct number of girl mummies found; 2 is correct)  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (HLW)  
 By JOHN NOBLE WILFORD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After climbing to the 22,000-foot summit of a volcano in
northern Argentina, archeologists have found three frozen Inca
mummies, 500-year-old remains of a ritual sacrifice, which are so
well preserved that blood is still present in the heart and lungs.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies of two girls and a boy were buried beneath five feet
of rock and dirt, amid a cache of statuettes, pottery and ornate
textiles associated with human sacrifices in the Inca religion.
They had apparently been frozen since immediately after death. Two
of the mummies were in such excellent condition, physicians said,
that all their internal organs were intact. It was as if they had
died only recently.
</P>
<P>
   Archeologists and other scholars said that the findings should
yield important insights into the religion and the worship of
sacred mountains in the Inca empire, which spanned most of the
Andes and the western coast of South America at the time of the
Spanish conquest in the early 16th century. They said the mummies
and artifacts were even more impressive than the discovery of the
Peruvian ``Ice Maiden,'' another frozen body of an Inca sacrifice
found in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The new discovery, made on Mount Llullaillaco, at Argentina's
border with Chile, was announced on Tuesday by Dr. Johan Reinhard,
an American archeologist and mountaineer who led an
American-Argentine-Peruvian expedition supported by the National
Geographic Society. He described the mummies and other finds at a
news conference in Salta, Argentina, and in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``The preservation of the mummies is just fantastic,'' Reinhard
said. ``It's eerie looking at the arms. You can still see the light
hair on their arms.''
</P>
<P>
   The archeologist said that they were the best preserved of any
mummy he had ever seen. In recent years, he has ascended the peaks
of mountains in Argentina, Chile and Peru and come down with 18
mummies, all apparent sacrifices to the sacred mountains.
Physicians so far could not establish how the three individuals,
probably between 8 and 15 years old, met their deaths.
</P>
<P>
   As far as the explorers could determine, the mummies and other
offerings to the Inca gods appeared to have been undisturbed
through the centuries. Gold, silver and shell statues, from two to
seven inches tall, were arranged on the burial platform just as
they probably were for the ritual sacrifices. Half of the statues
were clothed. Other artifacts included pottery, some of it still
containing food, and bundles of alpaca textiles that appeared to
establish the sacrifice victims as elite members of the society.
</P>
<P>
   ``The undamaged female has a beautiful, yellow geometrically
designed cover laid over her outer mantle,'' Reinhard said. She
also wore a feathered headdress.
</P>
<P>
   Below the summit, at about the 17,000-foot level, the expedition
found the stone ruins and ceramics of a camp where participants in
the rituals presumably stayed before the final ascent to the peak.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a scientific point of view,'' said Dr. Craig Morris, an
Andean anthropologist at the American Museum of Natural History in
New York City, ``these artifacts and the base camp are at least as
important as the mummies in determining the meaning of these
rituals.''
</P>
<P>
   The textiles, for example, were expected to provide clues to the
status and ethnic origins of the young people chosen for human
sacrifice, Morris said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Richard Burger, an archeologist of early Andean
civilizations at Yale University, said that the preservation of the
bodies gave medical scientists an opportunity to conduct more
revealing tests of the diet, health and genetics of the victims.
The blood should lead to DNA studies of the genetic composition of
these people.
</P>
<P>
   These and other recent discoveries, Burger said, were important
as established cases of capac cocha, or human offerings, by the
Inca because there had been a suspicion that the Spanish conquerors
had exaggerated their accounts of such practices, as well as
cannibalism and odd sexual mores, to justify their conquests.
</P>
<P>
   Reinhard had explored Mount Llullaillaco several times before,
mapping ruins and trying the trail to the top. Last month, the
expedition battled driving snow and winds near the summit. ``We had
several days of finding nothing,'' he said. ``I was about to give
up.''
</P>
<P>
   On March 16, the team found the first burial. One of the workers
had to be lowered into a hole by his ankles so that he could pull
the mummy out. Then they found the two others. One of the mummies,
a female, had been damaged on the left side by a lightning strike,
but the other two were undamaged.
</P>
<P>
   Calling ahead by cellular phones, the archeologists had
Argentine military vehicles waiting for them when the descended the
mountain with their cargo of mummies wrapped in plastic, snow and
foam insulation. The bodies were still frozen when they reached
Salta, a city about 300 miles away. Some members of the team were
from the Center for the Conservation of High Altitude Cultural
Patrimony, in Salta. Constanza Ceruti, an Argentine archeologist,
was a co-leader of the expedition.
</P>
<P>
   The mummies are to remain refrigerated in Salta for further
tests. Reinhard said he had more mountains to climb in search of
Inca sacrifices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-99 2214EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990406.0364 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8329 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-SPIRITUAL-575&AMP;A     04-06 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-SPIRITUAL-575&AMP;ADD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOVE, SUCCESS AND HAPPINESS: MORE HOW-TO BOOKS TAKING A
SPIRITUAL  BENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle news file)  
 (with BOOKS-GRAY-SFCHRON)  
 By JESSE HAMLIN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILL VALLEY, Calif. _ John Gray makes no bones about it: He
loves all the money and fame he's reaped from ``Men Are From Mars,
Women Are From Venus,'' the hugely successful gender-gap guidebook
on which he's built a lucrative empire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love material things,'' says the affable author, whose 1992
best-seller has sold 10 million copies. But all of his ``outer''
success ``would be so hollow if I didn't have the love in my life
or the spirituality,'' says Gray, touching on a central theme of
his new best-seller, ``How to Get What You Want and Want What You
Have: A Practical and Spiritual Guide to Personal Success''
(HarperCollins, $24.95).
</P>
<P>
   It's one of a growing crop of self-help books with a spiritual
bent, how-tos that promise ways to achieve worldly ambitions and
inner peace. The market for these books is booming, fueled largely
by aging Baby Boomers searching for deeper meaning in their hectic,
striving lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're definitely seeing more how-to books that have a strong
spiritual element,'' says Daisy Maryles, executive editor of
Publishers Weekly. ``It's not a new trend, but it's a trend that
has mushroomed in the past year.''
</P>
<P>
   Topping the New York Times' how-to best-seller list this week is
Oakland financial guru Suze Orman's ``The Courage to Be Rich:
Creating a Life of Material and Spiritual Abundance'' (Riverhead
Books, $24.95), which proffers that ``in order to become rich, your
self-worth has to rise with your net worth.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's ``One Day My Soul Just Opened Up: 40 Days and 40
Nights Toward Spiritual Strength and Personal Growth''
(Fireside/Simon &AMP; Schuster; $13), the best-seller by Iyanla
Vanzant, the minister, empowerment specialist and Yoruban priestess
whose ``In the Meantime: Finding Yourself and the Love You Want''
was one of last year's top 10 nonfiction best-sellers.
</P>
<P>
   So was Sarah Ban Breathnach's ``Something More: Excavating Your
Authentic Self'' (Warner Books; $20), which is still selling. Even
the Dalai Lama, bless his ancient soul, has a hit _ ``The Art of
Happiness'' (Riverhead; $22.95), ``a handbook for living'' written
with psychiatrist Howard C. Cutler that's been on the New York
Times nonfiction best-seller list for 10 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The approaching millennium and the increased stress of daily
life are ``causing a certain amount of angst, Maryles says, trying
to explain the trend. ``People are focusing on their inner lives,
their personal lives, searching for a balance. Baby Boomers are
getting older and starting to deal with bigger life issues. They're
looking for books that will offer greater meaning. In the fast
'80s, people were interested in making big bucks; now they're
searching for something more spiritual.''
</P>
<P>
   In the '60s, writers such as Alan Watts and Ram Dass popularized
the Hindu and Buddhist ideas that are being recycled in current
self-help books such as El Cerrito, Calif., writer Carol Adrienne's
1998 ``The Purpose of Your Life'' _ ``As seen on `Oprah,' says a
sticker on the new paperback edition (Eagle Brook/William Morrow;
$13) _ and spiritualist Barbara Biziou's forthcoming ``The Joy of
Ritual'' (Golden Books; $18.95), endorsed by fans such as fashion
designer Donna Karan.
</P>
<P>
   But Dass and Watts spoke primarily to the counterculture; this
current crop of New Agey books is ``reaching a much wider,
mainstream audience,'' Maryles says. ``It's a huge market.'' Last
year's big spiritual how-to's sold between 500,000 and 750,000
copies each.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Gray's new book serves up a mix of Eastern meditation,
simplified Western psychology, common sense and fortune-cookie
aphorism (``Money can't buy happiness'').
</P>
<P>
   Gray is a former personal assistant to the Maharishi Mahesh Yogi
who now works from a woodsy house in Mill Valley, Calif., north of
San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are unhappy because they've stopped wanting what they
have, they've disconnected from their essential self,'' says the
boyish, 47-year-old therapist, who lives with his wife and three
kids in a bigger Mill Valley house on three acres at the foot of
Mount Tamalpais.
</P>
<P>
   His ``Mars/Venus'' empire encompasses sequels, videos,
workshops, counseling centers, a board game and a forthcoming
cable-TV talk show. There's obviously a market for the message Gray
and other how-to authors are selling.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our society, we're not grounded in our feeling self; we
don't have this natural place of happiness that comes from within.
We believe that happiness comes from a bigger car, a bigger house,
a bigger paycheck, a better wardrobe. And if you are happy, the
material world (set ital)will(end ital) make you happier. I (set
ital)love(end ital) my nice new car (a black Lexus). But if I
wasn't already happy, it would make me miserable.
</P>
<P>
   ``My message is, you've got to start with yourself, you've got
to be happy with what you've got, then when you start getting more,
you'll be happy with that. ... Outer success magnifies your inner
state.''
</P>
<P>
   He cheerfully acknowledges that many of his ideas aren't
original and sound obvious. ``Everything I say is common sense,''
he says. ``Everything I said in `Men Are From Mars, Women Are
Venus' was common sense. ... People are always saying, `You only
said the obvious. Why did you sell so many books?' I say, `Cause
nobody said the obvious before, quite that way.'''
</P>
<P>
   Books by Gray, Vanzant and other spiritual how-to writers are
stacked prominently at Borders Books in San Rafael, Calif., where
the self-help section is hopping.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't sell many Bibles, but we sell tons of these,'' says
clerk Dennis Spillane (when a customer asked which way to the
self-help section, the witty Spillane told him he'd have to find it
himself).
</P>
<P>
   ``People want something more than their Mercedes and big houses,
they want some sense of inner happiness.'' These books touch on
some basic truths, Spillane says, ``but most of this is
surface-oriented stuff; it doesn't go very deep. They're all
selling a dream.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
