<HEADLINE>
JOHN GRAY PRAYS FOR HIS READERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: For use with BOOKS-SPIRITUAL-SFCHRON)  
 (This story also moved in the ``e'' entertainment news file)  
 By JESSE HAMLIN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILL VALLEY, Calif. _ John Gray does long-distance healing, but
he doesn't use AT&AMP;T, MCI or Sprint. He says he's plugged into a
higher power source.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can just think of the person and send them energy,'' says
Gray, a former Transcendental Meditation monk who's far more famous
for his best-selling books about male-female relationships than for
his spiritual activities.
</P>
<P>
   When not on the road, Gray does hands-on healings on Fridays at
the Tamalpais Pain Clinic in Corte Madera, Calif. He calls on the
Virgin Mary to heal certain patients, he says, ``generally women
who have self-esteem issues _ they feel unworthy, they've got
guilt.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary comes to him every week, he says, but ``she doesn't appear
like a physical being; it's a vision in your mind's eye.'' She's
just one of the spirits he's in touch with. ``If somebody has a
Hindu background, I will invite Krishna. If somebody has a Hindu
guru, I'll invite their guru in. ... I'm all religions. I see the
good in all religions.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray doesn't get into most of this stuff in his new book, ``How
to Get What You Want and Want What You Have.'' But he's spending
several hours a day doing a meditation-prayer for everyone who
reads the book.
</P>
<P>
   ``I send them healing energy and I send them blessings,'' he
says. ``The blessing is helping them to know what they want and get
what they want; the healing energy is to heal the blocks or the
sickness in their bodies. As soon as I even say it, energy is
pouring out of my fingertips. I spend half the time sending out the
energy, half the time drawing out negative energy from their lives.
It's just like I'm doing a long-distance healing on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Having soaked up all that negative energy, Gray has to
``decharge'' it out into nature. ``I sit by the pool, or sit by the
garden and put my hands out. I go for a walk in the oak forests of
Marin County, and it just pours off of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he says, ``I'm a spiritual healer. But I don't say that in
any lofty way. I mean, it's like a job.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
