<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990406.0374 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8350 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MASTERS-TIGER-HNS     04-06 1242
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-TIGER-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Woods remains calm in face of Duval's ascension to No. 1
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
AUGUSTA, Ga. _ In case anybody was worried, golf's Big Cat hasn't
coughed up a hairball just because he's not the No. 1 player in the
world anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods isn't going berserk about the sequence of events
that has propelled David Duval to the top spot in the sport. He
hasn't started smoking, developed a nervous twitch or looked for
the nearest 10th-floor ledge. No matter what you hear, Woods isn't
driving himself crazy trying to figure out how to recapture the No.
1 ranking.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, as he comes into the Masters, he says he's come to
grips with the reality of it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those things that's cyclical,'' he said.
``Everybody's going to have their runs. David's having his run now.
It's all part of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good motivation, the fact that David is playing
extremely well. But you can't get caught up in that and have that
as your only motivating factor. Whether you're No. 1 in the world
or missing cuts, you still have to try to get better and I have
been.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I can say he's good for me. I think he's good
from the standpoint that he's playing so well. And that's what we
all want to do. So as players, we want to get to where he's at
right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's playing better, no doubt about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, in his next breath, Woods proved he isn't necessarily
thrilled with the idea of having to look up to see the top of the
world rankings. He did so in the only way rock-hard competitors
can. He held up the one argument in his favor that Duval doesn't
have _ a major championship. And tacked on a little intimidating
talk for good measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps knowing that you have done it,'' Woods said of his
win at Augusta National in 1997. ``You're able to fend off the best
players in the world because you know you've won a major. That
gives you confidence down the stretch when you are a little
nervous, your hands are sweating, your eyeballs are beating.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can summon enough strength to do it again because you've
done it before.''
</P>
<P>
   Left unsaid, but clearly inferred, is the fact Duval hasn't
conquered those sweaty palms and pounding blood vessels yet.
</P>
<P>
   Gamesmanship is part of every sport. Michael Jordan, Nolan Ryan
and all the other greats didn't get to the top without mastering
the fine art of getting in an opponent's head.
</P>
<P>
   Woods didn't deny that he and many others use the same tricks if
they think it will give them a mental edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's gamesmanship being played every week,'' Woods said.
``I think that the public just doesn't know what to look at. Guys
will pull some things. Either you can't hear it or you don't see
it, but guys definitely are doing it out there. You know, Sam Snead
told me last year at the Champions Dinner that he used to cough
during guys' swings, right on the downswing. It happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seve (Ballesteros) tends to get a little sore throat every
once in a while. You know, clearing the throat. It's just part of
the game. In other sports, it's a little more apparent. But this
sport is a little more subdued. But nevertheless, it's still out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods' admission that the mind games have begun is perhaps the
truest sign that being No. 2 for the first time in his golfing life
is just a wee bit unsettling.
</P>
<P>
   He was the best when he was an amateur. He was the best when he
turned pro and ran the table at Augusta National two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   He was the best in the world for 43 consecutive weeks, according
to the world rankings.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he's Avis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating from the standpoint that I've been playing
well and not getting the victories,'' said Woods. ``If you look at
my finishes, I was always in the top five, right around the lead.
But I wasn't able to get a victory.''
</P>
<P>
   He has one this year, coming at San Diego in February. His
one-win season thus far pales in comparison to Duval, who has four
wins including the last two times he's teed it up.
</P>
<P>
   Among the PGA Tour brethren, the feeling is that Woods is primed
to make a rebuttal to Duval's strong showing of the past two years,
during which time he has won 11 of the last 34 tournaments he has
entered. Whether or not this is wishful thinking so that a bona
fide rivalry between the two evolves remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing for certain right now is that Duval is the king
and Woods is the one who has lost the throne in a hostile coup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can remember in 1994 and '95 when I was really playing well
that I walked to the first tee and wondered who was going to finish
second this week,'' Greg Norman said. ``That's not from pure
arrogance. That's from pure confidence. To be playing that well and
be that confident as David is now, it must be an unbelievable
feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   And in Woods' case, Norman believes the coming months will be
very telling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on if a person wants that spot,'' Norman said.
``Tiger will come back fighting hard. Anybody who wants to be that
No. 1 player in the world, they'll go after it. But again, it
depends on the priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods apparently has his priorities in order. He has been
working hard in the past few weeks, aiming specifically at the
Masters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (the hard work leading up to this week) has nothing to do
with the No. 1 thing,'' Woods said. ``It's because this is a major.
It's a little different story with a major than playing the regular
tour event. I really grind and get ready, because that's really
what it's all about is winning the big ones.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been a good year so far for Woods on the course, but a
tough one in other respects. Aside from losing the No. 1 ranking to
Duval, he also has come under fire from some corners (Arnold Palmer
in particular) for his emotional style on the course.
</P>
<P>
   Losing the No. 1 ranking is no big deal, Woods claims. But
questioning his etiquette is a little more damaging.
</P>
<P>
   ``My emotions are just the way they are and I can't really hide
them _ nor should I,'' Woods said. ``That's not my personality. I
play best when I let my emotions go. If I'm frustrated, I get them
out of my system. If I'm winning, I show I'm excited.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it's funny growing up and hearing the telecasts of
people saying golfers show no emotions. Then along comes people
like myself who show emotion and they're saying he shouldn't show
any emotion. I just scratch my head at that one. I think golfers
need to be themselves, whoever that is.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods has a supporter for his actions on the course _ Duval.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiger's a star outside the game,'' Duval said. ``I respect the
burden he's had to carry since he kind of burst onto the scene. I
don't think that, because I've passed him at No. 1, that I've been
given more responsibility. Some people are just more outside the
game. He's who he is.''
</P>
<P>
   And Woods is enjoying himself more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm actually having more fun (than years past),'' he said.
``I'm having so much fun out here, it's pretty scary because I
understand how things work. I understand a lot more about the Tour
and about myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say I look like I'm not having fun out there playing
because I'm not smiling. Well, I'm focused. I'm trying to win. And
you can't always smile when you're trying to win.''
</P>
<P>
   And there is no question that Woods wants to win _ now more than
ever.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
