<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8356 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MASTERS-ADVANCE-H     04-06 1531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-ADVANCE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
The stage is set for another year of high drama at Augusta National
Golf Club
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of all the places on this planet to play golf, nowhere are the
legends and the memories and the fantasies more alive than Augusta
National Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   It's the little corner of acreage that has given us so much. It
brought Jack Nicklaus to his final glorious victory, and just as
fatefully brought Greg Norman to his knees twice. It's the place in
the mental snapshot where little kids dream of making a 20-foot
putt to win the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   It has seen Gene Sarazen's double-eagle on No. 15 and Tom
Weiskopf's 13 on No. 12.
</P>
<P>
   In Caddyshack, when Bill Murray was whacking chrysanthemums with
his cutlass, he was en route to winning a mythical Masters, not the
Greater Milwaukee Open or the Ryder Cup or anything else.
</P>
<P>
   Augusta National, home of the Masters. It's golf's most
recognizable shrine. It really is a tradition unlike any other.
</P>
<P>
   Certain sporting events drip with drama. The Masters is flooded
with it. Every year, some of the world's best golfers trounce
around the world's most famous golf course and produce memories
that last generations. There's always a riveting finish or a
thrilling shot or a historic footnote at Augusta National.
</P>
<P>
   Why? It's a question that has so many answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The holes lend themselves to that sort of thing,'' says Mark
Calcavecchia, usually a contender at Augusta but never a winner.
``With the water on the back nine and those hard greens being the
way they are, there's always going to be something happening there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's historic is what it is. You always get great players. And
with those kind of conditions, weird things can happen. Sandy Lyle
birdied 16 and 18 the year (1988) he beat me. He didn't have to do
that. But that's the kind of stuff that happens at Augusta.''
</P>
<P>
   Golfers young and old on the PGA Tour and around the world know
what to expect when they pass down Magnolia Lane _ also known as
the toughest 250-yard carry in golf if you don't own a Masters
ticket or a world-class golf game.
</P>
<P>
   The unexpected is always on tap, just like the afternoon ales in
the men's grill.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got great golfers in difficult circumstances,'' says
No. 1-ranked David Duval. ``When you have that, crazy things are
going to happen _ both good and bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Creating yearly mystery and intrigue comes easy for Augusta
National. First, the former nursery is primped to beauty-contest
standards. Then, the grass is shaved off the greens, except for
little stublets that only serve to keep golf balls from rolling
away in a stiff breeze.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Augusta greens are built to require shots that land in
the correct quadrant. If not, you're left with putts up one tier
and/or down another. That simply makes putting the most
nerve-wracking business in a completely white-knuckle week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to let your tail feathers fly there,'' Hal Sutton
says. ``They say the greens there are 13 on the Stimpmeter (10 is
considered dangerously fast). But a lot of times, I think they're
faster than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have any nervousness at all, it's going to show up on
those greens. You can have a four- or five-footer and if you're not
careful, you've got a 20-footer coming back. In that respect, you
can get a lot of drama at that course. I've never played well at
Augusta, so I don't really care for some of the drama I've seen
there.''
</P>
<P>
   At all PGA Tour events, people who manage the golf course best
usually have a great chance of winning. At the Masters, you have to
manage something else _ yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not only whoever can hit the shots, but whoever can
maintain things and keep their cool,'' says Davis Love III.
``That's exactly what it's all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Who will provide us with tomorrow's memories this week at
Augusta National? Fortunately, nobody knows. It would ruin
everything if we did. But it's a sure thing that something wild
will happen.
</P>
<P>
   It could be Tiger Woods coming back strong in response to
Duval's ascension to the No. 1 position in the world and winning
for the second time in three years at the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   It could be Duval capturing his first major championship with
some sort of back-nine-on-Sunday heroics that we can only imagine.
</P>
<P>
   It could be Fred Couples or Colin Montgomerie or Nick Price
rising to the top.
</P>
<P>
   It could be amateurs Hank Kuehne or Matt Kuchar or Sergio Garcia
racing up the leader board and threatening to become the first
amateur to win the blessed event, although that seems a bit more of
a long shot than Duval or Woods or Couples wearing green on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was certainly not thinking of winning the tournament when I
was there (as an amateur in 1993),'' says Justin Leonard. ``I was
thinking about not killing somebody. I was as nervous as I could
be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose anybody can win the golf tournament because
everybody in it is a great player. But I wouldn't lay big money on
it.''
</P>
<P>
   What people will bet on is thrilling entertainment that has
become traditional. Unlike Super Bowl winners of years past, the
Masters' past glories are easy to recall.
</P>
<P>
   There was Larry Mize rolling in his 45-yard pitch shot from the
side of No. 11, a shot that stabbed Norman and Seve Ballesteros on
the second hole of a playoff in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   There was Norman crashing and burning in '96 when he threw away
a massive six-shot lead and lost by five strokes to Nick Faldo
after shooting 78. To this day, people still call the Augusta crowd
at the back nine on Sunday that year the most stunned they have
ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   There was Woods in '97 defying odds and history to become the
first black to win the tournament, and doing so in magnificent
style with a record 18-under total and 12-stroke margin of victory.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, it was Mark O'Meara making his 15th Masters
appearance, a record for number of attempts before a victory. His
20-foot birdie on the 18th beat Duval and Couples by a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   There was Nicklaus in '86, at age 46 a true master for the
Masters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very fired up to play the place,'' Ernie Els says. ``The
course, the history, the whole thing makes it a great tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Part of what makes the Masters so unique is that it confronts
the pros with a golf course for which they usually cannot prepare.
Playing Augusta National in February is not the same as playing it
during the first week in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiger got beaten up for saying that he was just gearing up for
the Masters when he was playing at the Players Championship,'' says
Love. ``But it really does take some getting used to on courses
like this. There's just nowhere to prepare for conditions like
this.''
</P>
<P>
   The Players Championship was about as close as anybody could
come. The greens were hard and fast. The fairways were closely
cropped. The rough was much worse than Augusta, even though they
have given a new head of hair to the usually absent Augusta rough.
</P>
<P>
   But there's really nothing that can prepare a golfer for
Augusta. One of the most telling stories of the place came a decade
ago when a select few media members were allowed to play the course
the Monday after the tournament. One scribe, who has played every
course from Pebble Beach to Doral, but not Augusta, was so nervous,
he left his shoes on top of his car as he pulled out of the hotel
parking lot. Others found themselves incapable of pulling the
trigger on No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   In that respect, a healthy dose of experience at Augusta is
always helpful.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything, guys who have been playing at Augusta for 10 or
15 years should have an advantage,'' Duval says. ``They've been the
ones who have seen those conditions the most and had the most
chance to work on them. The only time you really get to play in
those conditions is that week. This golf course never plays like
this except for one week out of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how many times a player tours around Augusta, it's
those dastardly greens that never can be mastered. The fastest
putting surfaces on the PGA Tour, they are always in impeccable
shape. That's why so many long putts are holed during Masters Week.
The greens are truer than any on Tour.
</P>
<P>
   But they also are more treacherous. A 30-foot putt with 15 feet
of break is not uncommon. On No. 2, the Thursday pin placement is
always on the edge of the ridge separating the upper and lower
tiers. Every year, at least a half-dozen players will run their
ball up the hill, only to see it come back down and settle inches
from the spot where they originally hit it from.
</P>
<P>
   Putts from behind the hole on No. 15 can roll into the pond in
front of the green.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greens make what already would be hard shots even
harder,'' Love says. ``And the new grass _ whether they're calling
it rough or not _ is going to compound what is already a hard golf
course.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all pointing to this time of year partly because it's
such a good test of golf. But that's what makes it tough, too.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's what makes it golf's most anticipated week. You just
know something great is going to happen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
