<HEADER>
A8357 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WIS-WELFARE-MAYOR-ART     04-06 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIS-WELFARE-MAYOR-ART-2TAKES(1,110)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFORMS PUNISH POOR, VETERAN SOCIALIST SAYS
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By JASON DePARLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ Welfare's sudden death has stunned many residents of
the central city here, but few have expressed more dismay than an
elderly gentleman on a poverty-pocked block who has been monitoring
the neighborhood's civic affairs since the Great Depression.
</P>
<P>
   At 86, Frank P. Zeidler is the last of Milwaukee's three
Socialist mayors _ no other major American city has had even one _
and a living link to a time when Wisconsin politics was synonymous
with safety-net expansions, like workers' compensation and
unemployment insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Now Wisconsin is known for a seemingly opposite passion, an
anti-welfare campaign that has cut the state's cash assistance
rolls by more than 90 percent. And Zeidler _ learned, courteous,
still sharp as a tack _ is mulling the question that may keep
political scientists busy for the next generation:
</P>
<P>
   What happened to the state's famously progressive traditions?
</P>
<P>
   ``What you're seeing in Wisconsin is a deconstruction of the
progress we made in the first decades of the 20th century,''
Zeidler said in a recent conversation at his home in Milwaukee's
poverty belt. ``It's a kind of neo-anarchism that says, `Nothing
the government can do is right,' and only the profit motive is
justified. This is one manifestation of it: `Get rid of the people
on welfare.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, the welfare restrictions have the support of some of
the city's leading Democrats, who say they are building on a
progressive past that celebrated toil and toilers. One of the most
vocal welfare critics here is the current mayor, John Norquist, a
three-term Democrat who has run each time with Zeidler's support.
As Norquist puts it, progressive reforms like unemployment
insurance were designed ``to help workers get through a tough time
and get back to work _ the idea wasn't to keep people constantly on
welfare.''
</P>
<P>
   Ideological disputes aside, most people here agree on one thing:
Zeidler is a civic treasure. A gold mine of local lore _ he
interrupted his welfare talk to help a caller trace the origins of
Milwaukee fish fries (they started in taverns in the Depression) _
Zeidler observes the attack on welfare through a unique set of
lenses.
</P>
<P>
   As an organizer, he has been working the north-side wards since
1932, when German-American factory workers formed the core of the
Socialist vote. As mayor from 1948 to 1960, he fought battles for
public housing that foreshadowed the welfare wars. And as a
central-city homeowner for 53 years, he has endured white flight,
black riots, and a rash of break-ins that now leave him sleeping
behind a saw-horse barricade and as devoted to the neighborhood as
ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moving is a terrible hassle,'' he said. ``And you don't want
to get pushed out of your own house.''
</P>
<P>
   As a Socialist mayor when a Wisconsin senator, Joseph R.
McCarthy, was busy hunting Communists, Zeidler knows that political
heritages are complex. In his view, the city's progressive
traditions have been eroding for more than four decades, partly for
racial reasons. The post-war boom brought poor Southern blacks
streaming into Milwaukee, and a white backlash soon followed.
Indeed, as a leading advocate of public housing, Zeidler himself
was an early target. ``There was a feeling that benefits were
attracting the poor and that cutting benefits would stop it,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The City Council blocked his drive to build more subsidized
apartments. (Oprah Winfrey was reared here in one, he notes with
pride.) His 1956 opponent called for time limits for public-housing
residents _ presaging the time limits on cash assistance that
followed 40 years later. And Zeidler won that race despite wildfire
rumors that he was urging blacks to move to town by posting
billboards across the South.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said I was bringing in all the blacks and secretly moving
out,'' said Zeidler, who is white. ``And here I am, 53 years in the
same house.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he is here, but votes for his views are not. Control of the
state has shifted to conservatives in the Milwaukee suburbs and
their rural allies, like Gov. Tommy G. Thompson. Indeed, Thompson,
a Republican from the small town of Elroy, has ridden an
anti-welfare crusade to an unprecedented fourth term.
</P>
<P>
   To Zeidler's chagrin, the drive to end welfare came with early
support from Milwaukee Democrats, the closest thing he has to
political heirs. As early as 1990, Norquist was denouncing welfare
as harmful to the poor and calling for its replacement with public
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed peculiar, but Milwaukee's long tradition of left-wing
politics has always been noted for its conservative quirks. The
city's Socialist pioneers were so pragmatic _ obsessed with
services like sanitation, not revolution _ that real radicals
dismissed them as mere ``sewer Socialists.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider the cry of the first Socialist mayor, Emil Seidel, at
his inauguration in 1910. ``The eyes of thousands of stricken
cities are today directed towards our Milwaukee,'' he began in
soaring fashion _ before promising the masses such consolations as
``a complete cost-keeping system'' to ``place the finances of our
city on a sound and sane basis.'' (His assistants included a
Socialist newsman, Carl Sandburg, who later turned his attention to
poetry.)
</P>
<P>
   In holding City Hall for 38 of the next 50 years, Milwaukee's
Socialists were known for clean water, more parks, strict zoning,
low debt and honest and efficient rule _ a sensibility that
elsewhere might have been known more simply as ``good government.''
Working in the state Legislature with their off-and-on allies, the
rural Progressives, they also passed the nation's first programs of
workers' compensation (1911) and unemployment insurance (1932) and
reams of business regulation.
</P>
<P>
   By 1993, the Socialists were gone and a war on welfare was under
way. In the view of the frustrated Democrats, Thompson had been
grandstanding for years _ denouncing the program without offering a
credible alternative. One of Norquist's proteges, state Rep.
Antonio Riley (a former welfare recipient himself), introduced a
bill that offered the governor a dare: abolish cash aid and create
public jobs.
</P>
<P>
   By passing the bill (with no Republican votes), most Democrats
simply hoped to goad the governor into an embarrassing veto. But
Thompson shocked the state _ indeed, the country _ in agreeing to
``end welfare'' three years before Congress followed suit. (He
vetoed the jobs provision and fudged the issue later by creating
modest community service positions for those unable to find work.)
Forced now to work for welfare, most recipients have simply left,
to find private jobs or rely on friends.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, another of Norquist's aides paid Zeidler a visit.
As a left-leaning critic of welfare, the aide, David Riemer, brings
a near-religious faith in work programs like those created in the
depths of the Depression. Indeed, it sometimes seems that Riemer
knows every building, bridge, and trail left in Milwaukee by the
public works crews of the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   Though he wants real jobs for the poor _ not community service,
where those left on welfare simply work off their checks _ he
considers the current system a good start. It is no coincidence, he
argues, that the state now offers low-income workers an impressive
array of work-related benefits: wage supplements, child care
subsidies and subsidized health insurance. Even welfare recipients
have gotten a raise since the work requirements began, to $673 a
month from an average of about $517.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once people are seen as workers, it's a lot harder to say no
to them,'' Riemer said. ``That was part of `Sewer Socialism': the
idea that people who could work, should work _ and society then
should help.''
</P>
<P>
   Politely, but firmly, Zeidler disputed the parallels with the
past.
</P>
<P>
   Socialism was a movement of the poor themselves, he said, while
the welfare reductions have mostly come ``from people who want to
punish the poor.'' Socialists and progressives stressed education,
he said, while the welfare reductions have forced many women to
leave school. The early movements protected minors, through
innovations like child labor laws. Their leaders would have been
distressed, he said, by a program that puts infants in day care
when they are just 12 weeks old.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking from nearly nine decades of experience, Milwaukee's
last Sewer Socialist warned against simple theories of the poor.
``People are poor for lots of reasons _ you have to have a net to
catch the ones that don't fit your system,'' Zeidler said. ``And I
don't see that anymore. That safety net is gone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-99 2235EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990406.0379 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8359 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MASTERS-O'MEARA-H     04-06 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-O'MEARA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
O'Meara knows duplicating last year's success a tough task
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many people wanted to say it. Greg Norman did.
</P>
<P>
   During a casual conversation a few weeks ago that was bouncing
from course design to his comeback from shoulder surgery and all
things golf-related, Norman was asked about Mark O'Meara pulling
off an encore of his sensational 1998 season, when he was the PGA
Tour's player of the year and won the Masters and British Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark's going to have an interesting year,'' Norman said. ``It
will be interesting to see how he handles '99 compared to '98. He's
a great player. And I'm sure he's going to handle it to the level
that we all know he can.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people took that as a less-than-ringing endorsement of
O'Meara. And if the truth be known, a lot of people agree with
Norman's assessment.
</P>
<P>
   The view of O'Meara this year is that he's coming off a season
in which he reached the pinnacle of his profession at a time when
he's perilously close to joining the over-the-hill club. It's a sad
reality that virtually all golfers on the PGA Tour learn to deal
with their emotions and games in their 20s, peak during their 30s,
can still capture flashes of greatness in their 40s, then move to
the white tees in their 50s.
</P>
<P>
   Some can accelerate or elongate the pattern, but it's fairly
constant.
</P>
<P>
   So O'Meara, 42, had one terrific year in 1998, perhaps a sendoff
to a rock-solid career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a dream year for me,'' O'Meara said. ``At age 41, to
finally break through and win my first major championship, when I
look back at that putt on the 72nd hole at Augusta National, it
gives me goose bumps.''
</P>
<P>
   It no doubt will again this week when O'Meara returns to the
Masters for his title defense. Given the way O'Meara is playing
this year as compared with last year, a repeat performance at the
Masters may not be in the offing. Nobody has won back-to-back
Masters since Nick Faldo in 1989-90.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara believes he's still capable of winning a tournament such
as the Masters. But he also knows that duplicating what he did last
year _ winning nearly $1.8 million and two majors _ may not be in
the cards. To that, he says a big ``so what?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gotten off to a reasonable start this year,'' O'Meara
said. ``I have been bouncing around a little bit and doing some
things. I'm not as happy as I'd like to be with the way I'm
playing. I can play better than what I am playing. I can hit the
ball better. I can feel better standing over the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I have to work on some areas. But I don't know how many
golfers are ever satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't top (player of the year). I am not going to lie to
you. Last year was a special year and if things don't go as well
this year, so what? Life is pretty darn good.''
</P>
<P>
   In spite of his glorious season last year, O'Meara said he
hasn't upgraded his expectations of himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize I don't hit the golf ball like Tiger Woods or David
Duval or some of the other younger players,'' he said. ``I know I
will never hit the ball like that. So I have to find ways to keep
improving the areas of my game like course management, patience and
understanding what I can and can't do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 42 years old. I'm not 27 or 29. I have a game plan on how
much longer I'd like to compete at the highest level and then taper
off. I want to play competitively and try to play well for the next
couple years, try to play well at the U.S. Open and the PGA
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm not out there thinking: Hey, if I don't play well,
people are going to think the Masters champion should play better
than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can always second-guess yourself. But I'm not going to do
that. I'm going to try to enjoy the things that have happened. I'm
going to try to capitalize on some of those things and whatever
happens, happens. It's not going to be the end of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing O'Meara does not want to let happen is for him to go
through the post-euphoric letdown that often afflicts players after
a big year or after they win a major.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have gotten off to a good start this year to make
sure that doesn't happen,'' he said. ``But I need time away from
golf, too. I need time to go snow skiing. I need time to do things
with my family. I think if I do that, then I will play better on
the course.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the grass is growing out there. So I need to go out there
and cut the grass while it's growing. If I was 10 or 15 years
younger and had done what I did last year, then I might have a
little different game plan.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, O'Meara wants to enjoy the international acclaim
that comes with his victories in '98. But he also wants to make hay
on the PGA Tour while his game remains in good shape.
</P>
<P>
   He also has a better perspective on the future because of his
age. He recently was asked if perhaps his name should be included
in talk about the world's best players. He quickly said Duval and
his good friend Woods have earned that position.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I played last year, I should be ranked in the top
10,'' O'Meara said. ``But the way I played today, I should be
ranked about 200th. That's the way golf is.''
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, O'Meara has the support of Woods. The two
play golf just about every day when they aren't on the Tour
together. Woods is of the opinion that O'Meara hasn't won his last
major championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``He definitely has a few left in him,'' Woods said. ``Now he
knows he can do it. Just give him a chance where he has nine holes
to go, tied for the lead, one back or in the lead. If he leads, he
doesn't ever go backward.''
</P>
<P>
   The first order of business, however, will be to get that first
victory since the British Open, which would go a long way toward
disproving anybody's thoughts that O'Meara put a lid on his career
last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
