<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8360 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MASTERS-CHANGES-H     04-06 1356
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-CHANGES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Despite critics, Augusta National changes with the times
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are two schools of thought about the changes that have
been made to Augusta National leading into this year's Masters.
</P>
<P>
   And the diverse opinions have been offered eloquently by two of
golf's best-known statesmen.
</P>
<P>
   First on the tee, Greg Norman:
</P>
<P>
   ``Augusta National has so much history. So, you know, I don't
like to see changes, because I like to step up on the tee and say,
`Well, Gene Sarazen did this or Byron Nelson did this,' and feel
the same piece of nostalgia and history under your feet as what
those guys played on. And when you change it, you change all that.
It just blows my mind. I don't understand it. I'm a bit more of a
traditionalist, I guess. I don't like to see that stuff happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Now playing, Davis Love III:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing that in the last three years or so, people have
really gotten into the changes in golf courses. But they have
changed that golf course (Augusta National) every year since the
tournament started. They shut it down, take all the sand out of the
bunkers. They rebuilt a few greens. The course has always evolved.
When you shut a course down for the summer, what are you going to
do with it? You're going to fix things. How many times has the
eighth green changed? Nobody talks about that much. You look at the
old pictures sometimes in the clubhouse _ the old black-and-white
pictures _ and there's not a hole on that course that hasn't
changed somehow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to change the way we play. The greens are
still going to be the trick.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Love and Norman have a kernel of correctness in their
assessments of the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Love is right in that the most storied course in golf has been
altered, tweaked and flat-out changed a lot through the years. In
fact, the number of documented changes to Augusta National is
staggering.
</P>
<P>
   There have been revisions 69 times, ranging from new bunkers to
new tee boxes to redesigned greens.
</P>
<P>
   But Norman also has a point. Every time there's a new wrinkle, a
little piece of history dies. That Augusta National tinkered with
one of its most famous holes during the past year is one reason for
Norman's criticism.
</P>
<P>
   The 15th hole, which is home to maybe the most famous shot in
golf history, has been made tougher this year. The par-5 hole on
which Gene Sarazen knocked a 3-wood (or 4-wood, depending on which
version of the legend you believe) 230 yards into the hole for a
double-eagle in the 1935 Masters now has more bite than it used to.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's what Masters officials hope will be the result
after they reduced the fairway mounds on the right side and added
pine trees to both sides of the fairway.
</P>
<P>
   Without the mounds, medium and long hitters no longer will be
able to carry their tee shots to the mounds, which have a slingshot
effect on balls that land on them, giving extra distance to those
drives. Now, only the longest hitters will automatically have a
chance to reach the green with their second shots.
</P>
<P>
   At hole No. 2, also a par-5, the tee has been pushed back 25
yards. Also, a fairway bunker has been shifted farther right with
the hope that fewer players will be shooting at the green in two
shots.
</P>
<P>
   Nos. 2 and 15 are the two easiest holes on the course in
tournament history. Even so, Norman doesn't like the changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been long hitters that played at Augusta National
before,'' Norman said. ``I have heard what they have done to the
second hole. But the thing about that is that the second shot,
whether it's a 7-iron or a pitching wedge, is still a tough shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played with Jack Nicklaus in a lot of practice rounds there
and he use to boom that drive around the corner on that hole and
hit 8-irons into that green. And he told me there were a number of
times when he hit 8-iron into No. 13 (with the second shot). And
they didn't change the golf course in those days.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, actually, they did. No. 13 has been modified eight times,
with the tee box being extended on three of those occasions and the
swales in the back of the green moderated once.
</P>
<P>
   But it's true that the first 65 times the course was changed
didn't receive anywhere close to the fanfare of the four major
changes this year.
</P>
<P>
   How dare they change history? That's the common refrain. In
addition to Nos. 2 and 15, the tee at No. 17 has been lengthened by
25 yards, and the green, pond and bunker on No. 11 have been raised
about a foot.
</P>
<P>
   But as far as the people who actually have to deal with the
latest changes at Augusta are concerned, the wrinkle cream they put
on the course isn't all that bothersome. It's still the Masters and
it's still the greatest golf course in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the second hole, I never birdied that hole anyway, so I
can't play it much worse than I have in the past,'' said Mark
Calcavecchia. ``That one won't bother me a bit. I hate that hole
regardless.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the only change that will bother me is No. 17. To
really play that hole now, you're going to have to hit a high hook,
and I'll probably just hit 3-wood off the tee there.''
</P>
<P>
   While the course changes were done in an attempt to equalize
Augusta for shorter hitters, Love predicts the advantage still will
go to the big-knockers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't really get it on the green anyway,'' Love said of
No. 2. ``I mean, how many people actually knocked it on in two? So
again, the advantage is to the long hitter. They can hit it to the
top of the hill, hit it down there in the right front bunker like
we always try to do and get it up and down. It will make a
difference to some people. But the longer hitters will figure out a
way to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same with 15. They keep changing the 15th green. But
guys still have figured out ways to make birdies and eagles on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. 2 tee, you used to come off No. 1 and walk one way. Now
you walk another way. We'll adjust.''
</P>
<P>
   And for other people, Augusta is a constant battle of
adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tried everything there and haven't had much success,''
said Ernie Els. ``I tried being aggressive, but that didn't work,
either. You have to drive the ball well to be aggressive on that
course. I haven't really driven it well there.
</P>
<P>
   ``On 13, for instance, most players go in there thinking of
making birdie. I'm just trying to keep it out of the creek on the
left.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a very positive way of playing that hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the changes that have been made to Augusta, the one that
might gain the most attention isn't even listed in the official
tournament guide that documents every change, however subtle, that
has been made to the course.
</P>
<P>
   Rough, which has been taboo in the past at Augusta, has
sprouted. But in true Masters tradition, they're calling it the
``second cut'' of grass instead of rough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever they are calling that stuff, it keeps the ball from
running into the trees,'' said Love. ``So maybe in some respects,
it won't be bad.''
</P>
<P>
   The new rough probably will affect only shots that miss greens.
And even that long grass won't be anything unusual for the pros,
although the combination of any rough with Augusta's
lightning-quick greens could produce tougher scoring conditions.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the rough takes away another advantage from the
long hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the appeal of Augusta is that you can hit the ball
three miles and have it go three miles left or right and not get
hurt,'' said Tom Lehman. ``Now, you may not be able to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehman hit on perhaps the most cogent point about the changes at
Augusta. In his mind _ and in many other minds, too _ they just
weren't necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Augusta, the same score wins just about every year,''
Lehman said. ``We had the one year when Tiger shot really low. But
other than that, it's always about 10 under or close to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still a very hard golf course without the rough. Now that
they are trying to give us some rough, it'll be even a shot or two
harder.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
