A8361 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-PHILS07-CO     04-06 0420
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-PHILS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Maddux does all; Phillies battered 11-7
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Braves' two-day old 1999 season took a serious
turn for the better on Tuesday evening, and Chad Ogea's took a nose
dive.
</P>
<P>
   With Curt Schillling safely out of the way, the Braves proceeded
to bully Ogea, the Phillies' next offering in the rotation, to a
11-3 win. By the time the eight-run fourth inning was over Ogea was
in the showers, because 10 batters into it Greg Maddux was
receiving a standing ovation from the Turner Field crowd on his way
to bat.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux's last trip up had come to lead off the inning, which he
did in grand fashion with his first home run as an Atlanta Brave
and the third of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Not one to disappoint, Maddux proceeded to ground a base hit off
reliever Mike Grace's shin and into right field with the bases
loaded for his second and third RBIs of the evening. That capped
off the Braves biggest offensive inning since Sept. 17, 1997 when
they scored nine runs off the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Ogea gave up seven of those runs, and for him it was the latest
in a trend. In in his last two starts of the spring, the Yankees
and the Pirates pounded Ogea for 20 hits and 13 earned runs in
eight innings.
</P>
<P>
   Also in on the offending: Brian Jordan with his second home run
in two days _ a three-run shot to follow Maddux in the fourth, and
Andruw Jones, who collected not only his first hits of the season
but first against the Phillies since 1997 after he went 0 for 37
against the Phillies last year. Ryan Klesko started it off with a
two-run home run off Ogea in the second inning, his first of the
season on his first pitch of the night.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies, meanwhile, did a little nibbling at Maddux but
only managed one run off him. They got it the second inning,
stringing together three consecutive base hits by Bobby Abreu, Mike
Lieberthal, and Desi Relaford, who pushed a 3-2 pitch into left
center field to score Abreu.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux threw 88 pitches on the night, 60 of them for strikes. In
the process, he struck out five and walked none.
</P>
<P>
   His long ball? It came on a 3-2 pitch from Ogea and went rifling
over the left field wall, rousing the 29,183 fans at Turner Field.
His last home run also came against the Phillies in April of 1992
when Maddux was a Chicago Cub.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
