<SLUG> BC-TV-STRANGERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STRANGERS WITH CANDY' IS IRREVERENT, SUBVERSIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's have the main character of ``Strangers With Candy''
explain herself, shall we?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm Jerri Blank, and I'm a 46-year-old high school freshman.
For 32 years, I was a teenage runaway. I was a boozer, a user and a
loser. My friends were dealers, cons and 18-karat pimps. But now
I'm out of jail, pickin' up my life exactly where I left off. I'm
back in high school, livin' at home and discovering all sorts of
things about my body.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk about outsidersville! Jerri makes the kids from the
chemistry club seem cooler than absolute zero.
</P>
<P>
   But such Bunsen-burning table-turning would be too tame for
``Strangers With Candy.'' Remember, this is Comedy Central
programming. And ``Strangers'' premieres Wednesday night at 10:30,
right after the third-season launch of ``South Park,'' the leader
of cable-TV's back-to-baseness initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Can you say irreverent? Can you say subversive?
</P>
<P>
   Judging from one episode, ``Strangers With Candy'' is certainly
both, though it's not nearly as vulgar as ``South Park.'' It's
infinitely funnier, too, maybe because it dares to spoof the soppy
fables of those moralistic ``after-school specials.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans of Comedy Central's sketch-comedy series ``Exit 57'' of a
few years back will recognize the key players in ``Strangers With
Candy.'' All graduates of Chicago's ``Second City'' improv
incubator, they delight in flouting convention. But they mix up
their floutage so that sometimes it's quite subtle, and sometimes
it's about as subtle as a tire iron.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Subtle: You have to look at the sign on his desk to know
that the principal of Flatpoint High School, a black man, is named
Blackman.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Not subtle: Principal Blackman (Greg Hollimon) is a
clueless despot who stands erect and speaks in Paul Robeson tones.
He solves most problems by applying tortured logic and prescribing
massive doses of vitamin supplements.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Sedaris plays Jerri Blank with a combination of lovability
and loathability reminiscent of Gilda Radner's best characters. At
46, she's your typical outcast, constantly mocked by the cool kids.
But she has an inner coolness that comes from years of living on
the streets. Or in the joint. Or with a joint. She's back home now,
living with her catatonic father and his new wife, who looks
younger than Jerri. (Jerri's mom is dead, but Jerri stays in touch,
talking regularly to the woman's ashes, which she keeps in her
bedroom.)
</P>
<P>
   Like all the after-school specials, ``Strangers With Candy''
tackles the pressing issues of adolescence: drugs, alcohol,
pregnancy, racism, illiteracy, eating disorders, and so on. Just
don't expect the easy, wrapped-in-a-bow resolutions. For instance,
after being responsible for the overdose death of a classmate,
Jerri reflects: ``They never did find out who killed Poppi, so I
guess justice was served.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, ``Strangers With Candy'' isn't mainstream
comedy. But then, most mainstream comedy isn't very funny. Nothing
wrong with a show about a high school freshman who has had a little
fun, done a little time and is just picking up where she left off,
is there?
</P>
<P>
   Education isn't just for kids, you know.
</P>
<P>
   Strangers With Candy. Half-hour comedy series about a
46-year-old woman who returns to high school after 32 years as a
runaway. Starring Amy Sedaris, Stephen Colbert, Paul Dinello and
Greg Hollimon. Premieres Wednesday night, repeats Friday at 11
p.m., on Comedy Central. Parental guideline rating: TV-14.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-99 2242EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
