<HEADER>
A8363 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN     04-06 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA BEGINS QB SEARCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA began spring practice on a wet Tuesday with
three items on its agenda: find a quarterback, install a new
defense, and find a quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Five players will compete to replace four-year starter Cade
McNown, and only one, junior-to-be Drew Bennett, has ever thrown a
college pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to come out of spring with a quarterback _ that's
everybody's biggest question mark,'' Bruins coach Bob Toledo said.
``Bennett is the leading candidate. We'll try to create a situation
where they all get the opportunity, but it's hard to get all the
guys repetitions. ''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett is 6-foot-5 and one of UCLA's best athletes. He runs a
4.6-second 40-yard dash. He's quick. He has a 38-inch vertical
jump. He's a superb basketball player, he's bright, and although
his passes flutter sometimes, he's accurate. The only thing he
lacks is experience: 11 career attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time I'm really anxious to compete,'' he
said. ``From high school to now, it's always been a situation with
Cade in which nothing was going to change unless something drastic
happened. Now, there's competition. Nothing's set in stone. The
coaches have made that clear.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett's competition is raw but talented. Sophomore-to-be Scott
McEwan, of Thousand Oaks, has a strong arm but no experience. Ryan
McCann, a Westlake Village native, and Cory Paus, from New Lenox,
Ill., sat out last season as redshirt freshmen. Toledo likes
McCann's football aptitude, while Paus is a tough leader cut from
the McNown mold.
</P>
<P>
   The final candidate is J.P. Losman, who graduated from Venice
High in February and enrolled for the spring quarter Monday. Losman
is cocky and a prodigious talent with a rocket arm, but the
adjustment to college is massive.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be in a state of shock, and he's got to have patience,''
Toledo said. ``But he has a !ital!great!off! arm.... It's not
unrealistic (for Losman to compete for the starting job), because
he has a lot of ability. We want to give him the chance, but we all
know it'll be extremely difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo and his staff have scripted every play of every practice.
They know which quarterback will take the fifth snap of the seventh
drill on the ninth day, and they plan to distribute repetitions
equally. But democracy will only get them so far. At some point,
they must whittle the field: When they break spring on May 1, there
must be a starter and a backup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, one will emerge for sure, and maybe two or three,''
Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, the Bruins will install their third system in three
years. When embattled coordinator Nick Aliotti bolted for Oregon,
Toledo promoted longtime assistant and former coordinator Bob
Field, who has scraped Aliotti's 3-4 in favor of a 4-3 alignment
(four linemen, three linebackers).
</P>
<P>
   Field has revamped the assignments and simplified the
terminology. In addition, he'll receive unprecedented input from
Toledo, who said his suggestions to Aliotti ``fell on deaf ears.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob and I work very well together,'' Toledo said. ``I think
he'll listen to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Field's priorities this month are evaluating personnel _ at
least six starting jobs are undetermined _ and infusing
fundamentals. Under Aliotti, the Bruins had trouble with the
basics: alignments, assignments, shedding blocks and tackling.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of ways you can line up and be successful in
terms of scheme,'' Field said. ``I'm not as concerned with scheme
so much as how we play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
