<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-GOVERNOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A STATEMENT FROM HIDING, MEXICAN AIDE CHARGES PLOT
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHETUMAL, Mexico _ A state governor who stunned Mexico by
abandoning his duties last month has offered his first public
explanation in a letter from the underground, saying he fled into
hiding for fear that his indictment on what he called trumped-up
drug charges was imminent.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Villanueva Madrid defended his extraordinary decision in a
letter faxed to Mexican newspapers late on Monday, hours after his
six-year term as governor of the Caribbean state of Quintana Roo
came to an end. He said his enemies within President Ernesto
Zedillo's governing party had invented the drug accusations to
punish him for his maverick political stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hounded by an investigation designed to incriminate me at all
costs, I had to take an extremely difficult personal decision:
abandon my native soil to avoid imprisonment,'' Villanueva said.
``I am not a criminal. They're persecuting me for strictly
political reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not disclose his whereabouts, which has remained a
mystery since he dropped from public view on March 26. He left his
state government in chaos after delivering a final speech to
supporters in Chetumal, the Quintana Roo capital.
</P>
<P>
   The letter confirmed what until recent days had seemed almost
unthinkable: that one of Mexico's 31 state governors and a leader
of the long-governing Institutional Revolutionary Party had fled to
avoid arrest _ and that he would publicly attack the Mexican
justice system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very probably I will be formally charged,'' Villanueva said.
He said he expected to be accused of drug use, smuggling and
trafficking as well as money laundering, illicit enrichment and tax
fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ``And who knows what else?'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Last month Villanueva was notified that he was the target of a
drug investigation, and Mexico's Special Drug Prosecutor was in
Chetumal pursuing the inquiry on Monday as Villanueva's successor
was sworn into office. Villanueva broke decades of Mexican
political tradition by failing to appear at the inauguration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't wait ingenuously for an injustice to be orchestrated
by federal prosecutors,'' he said. ``I'll plan my defense, but not
at the risk of prison or at the expense of my ability to act.
</P>
<P>
   ``They accuse me of being a cocaine addict, but I'm not, and I
can prove that objectively and scientifically,'' he said. ``They
want to destroy me physically, psychologically and morally.''
</P>
<P>
   The tenure of Villanueva, who is 53, coincided with a surge in
the smuggling of Colombian cocaine through Quintana Roo. Mexican
and U.S. officials have for a year been accusing the governor of
protecting traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet his complaint that his prosecution is politically motivated
will ring true for many here because he has quarreled publicly with
powerful party officials and because many Mexicans believe that
other senior party politicians as well as military and police
officials have profited from the drug trade without facing
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Jorge Madrazo Cuellar has been unusually dogged
in pursuing the investigation, and Villanueva contends that it is
because the Zedillo administration wants to punish him for defying
top party officials last fall during a dispute over whom the party
would nominate to succeed him in Quintana Roo.
</P>
<P>
   That was part of a broader national squabble that is still
unfolding, in which Villanueva has backed a party faction that is
challenging presidential control of the party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
