u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     04-06 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LESSONS OF FAMILY AND TEAM
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the sunshine on an otherwise funereal morning,
Donnie Walsh recalled the first time he met Harry Jackson, and the
lasting impression the father of the point guard had made.
</P>
<P>
   This was 1987, and Walsh of the Indiana Pacers by way of the
Bronx and Fordham Prep had come home to scout a St. John's player
whose foot speed was already confusing the so-called experts, few
of whom ever saw the game unfold the way Mark Jackson could.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came to see if Mark could run the fast break,'' Walsh said
Tuesday, in front of the Mount Sinai Baptist Church on Gates Avenue
in the Bedford-Stuyvesant section of Brooklyn. ``Harry sat with me
in a workout at Brandeis High School and I remember he never asked
about what I could do for Mark, or anything like that. He just
wasn't that type.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Jackson demonstrated that he could find the open man, and
Harry Jackson's quiet, confident presence gave Walsh the sense that
Harry's unorthodox kid had more going for him than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wound up taking Reggie Miller that year,'' Walsh said.
``But if Reggie hadn't been there, we would've taken Mark.''
</P>
<P>
   On this, the Pacers' president could be believed, because not
only did Walsh eventually bring Jackson to Indiana, he let him go
and admitted his mistake and reacquired Jackson for a team that has
essentially been together long enough now to be a family.
</P>
<P>
   So on the day Harry Jackson would have turned 68 but instead was
eulogized in Brooklyn and buried in Long Island, Walsh caught the
first flight out of Indianapolis, with Mel Daniels, the team's
player personnel director. They stood on Gates Avenue, saying the
Pacers would've all been there had the schedule been kinder, and
did a double-take when Alice Davis walked up to the church.
</P>
<P>
   The mother of the Pacers' rugged big man, Antonio, left her own
ailing mother in Oakland, Calif., to honor the memory of Marie
Jackson's husband, a retired New York City transit worker, who died
of cancer last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Jacksons became her close friends through the Pacers and the
players' mother's association, she said. Harry Jackson came to the
group's convention in New Orleans last summer, and never gave a
hint of being ill.
</P>
<P>
   He was the point man with security, and he loved when players
would come with their mothers and speak to the group. Antonio Davis
did, and Harry Jackson became a role model for his son's tall
teammate who, according to his mother, has had to be ``father,
uncle, whatever'' to his own younger brother.
</P>
<P>
   Antonio Davis himself made news this season for inviting Pacers
rookie Al Harrington, right out of high school, to live with him
and his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so proud of Tony for that,'' Alice Davis said. ``I know
Harry influenced him, and that tells you a lot about this team.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a team stumbling around badly without Jackson two years
ago, as if someone had left the room and turned out the light. Say
what you will about Jackson's speed and outside shot. Even as a
young, immature Knick he could always pass, always lead.
</P>
<P>
   After the Pacers beat the Knicks on Sunday in Indianapolis,
Jackson was invited by Coach Jeff Van Gundy to fly back to New York
with them. Too bad they couldn't keep him. For the Knicks, trying
again to make some sense of themselves Tuesday night against
Orlando, it must be painful to be so lacking in vision, to be
crying out for someone who just knows how to play.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, traded by Pat Riley for not having enough steak in his
defense, moved on, with the help of his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember Harry telling Mark: `You can't be bitter; the
Knicks gave you your start,' '' A.B. Whitfield, a former Dallas
Cowboy and close friend of Harry Jackson's, said.
</P>
<P>
   Reunited with his college running mate Chris Mullin, Mark
Jackson, at age 34, plays on with a chance to win it all before he
is done. Tuesday, there was more important unfinished business,
though, the point guard being introduced at Mount Sinai Baptist as
the Rev. Mark Jackson, and offering a raspy oration that had the
passion of a preacher, the sadness of a son.
</P>
<P>
   He looked through teary eyes into a congregation that included
his siblings and sons and pregnant wife, and said he would dedicate
no championship, should it be won.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone won one last year,'' Jackson said. ``Someone will win
one next year. There will never be another Harry Jackson.''
</P>
<P>
   He was more than a father, Jackson said. He was ``daddy,'' and
there is a difference, and in the church, those who knew why cried
out ``Amen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
