<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-NORMAN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARK NO LONGER OUT FOR BLOOD; TIME OFF CHANGES PERSPECTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ For years, Greg Norman circled the tank instead
of the drain, the Great White Shark leading or looming,
professional golf's most dominant figure always preparing to strike
again.
</P>
<P>
   He still has the flowing blond hair and magnetic charisma, but
Norman is 44 now, the wrinkles as evident as flaws in his game.
Mentally and physically, he has broken down in the past, but the
brassy Australian returns this week attempting to capture the
Masters at one of his most notable graveyards.
</P>
<P>
   Norman is on display at Augusta National as a
before-and-afterthought, removed from his once prominent position
but still commanding attention.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that Norman feels more settled and secure than
ever. Shoulder surgery kept him off the driving range and caused a
beneficial change in his outlook.
</P>
<P>
   ``My whole career was just being on the first tee and taking the
consequences,'' Norman said. ``It just encapsulates you so much, it
takes everything else out of your life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so engulfed in all of this stuff that when I got away
from it, I saw other things out there that I didn't see for 22
years. And now I'm still young enough to enjoy it. Let me see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman had enough money; now he spends time. With his wife,
Laura. With his kids, Morgan-Leigh, 16, and Gregory, 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I really haven't done in 16 years, and that to
me was an eye-opener,'' he said. ``I enjoy that. I wouldn't mind
doing it every weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Norman was either winning tournaments with spectacular
finishes or frittering them away with horrific meltdowns.
Recognized as the world's No. 1 player for a record 331 weeks
during two stretches of the 1980s and '90s, Norman also was a choke
artist and hard-luck loser, three times collapsing or being stunned
at the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Norman met with reporters Tuesday wearing one of
his own line of golf shirts instead of a green jacket. He is OK
with what has happened. He has won two major tournaments, both
British Opens, but squandered many others.
</P>
<P>
   Norman is the only player to have lost all four majors in
playoffs. He authored the most lasting memory here, an unfortunate
legacy that follows him and won't leave him alone.
</P>
<P>
   With a six-shot lead after three rounds of the '96 Masters,
Norman shot a 78 and lost to Nick Faldo by five strokes.
</P>
<P>
   As Norman spoke in philosophical tones Tuesday, saying he
wouldn't do anything differently, a reporter wondered: ``You
wouldn't change from a 78 to a 68?''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than bristle, Norman kept his train of thought rolling.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, that's done,'' he said. ``One thing I realize is golf is
not everything. Yes, I want to win the Masters, absolutely. But
it's not a priority.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he will return to contention this week, exorcizing the
Larry Mize chip-in in '86 or the improbable immortality of Jack
Nicklaus in '86. It's possible. His shoulder is sound, his attitude
good.
</P>
<P>
   His teacher, David Leadbetter, said he has never seen Norman
swinging this well. But his mind is on fast-forward, and there is
only a play button on the golf course. It's difficult because
Norman admits to being a ``quadruple-A personality,'' wanting
results now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where the frustration builds up, I expect things a little
quicker than they're coming,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It is all so humbling to a man with his competitive nature. At
one time, he fearlessly attacked the flagsticks with a
free-wheeling approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``You walk to the first tee and you feel like: `Who's going to
finish second this week?''' he said. ``And that's not from pure
arrogance or being egotistical. That's pure confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   From then to now, Norman is just happy to be healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can walk out to the first tee, pull out a driver and swing
it in one swing,'' he said. ``That's a huge leap forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Pain-free at last, Norman has gained yardage and perspective,
noticing more in the distance than a lonely flagstick.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I didn't have the injury, I'd still be grinding away,
hitting balls and not really spending time with my family,'' Norman
said. ``I don't have a sense of urgency anymore. I'm more in
balance. I just want things to keep going the way they are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
