<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOCTOR-ARREST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Judge says no bail for doctor in drug case
 &HT;    By Sanjay Bhatt
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. _ Dr. Barbara Mazzella, a family physician
who supporters say saved many patients' lives, was held without
bail Tuesday by a federal magistrate who charged her with operating
``a large-scale drug dealership.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 20 of Mazzella's supporters _ including her four
children _ gasped and sobbed upon hearing the order. Mazzella will
be held at a federal detention center in Miami until May 3, when
she will enter a plea of not guilty, said her attorney, Jeff
Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Harris said he will appeal U.S. Magistrate Lurana Snow's
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Mazzella, 61, was arrested Thursday at her Coral Springs, Fla.
office on charges of conspiracy, fraud, making false statements and
illegally distributing prescription drugs. Prosecutors say that
``in excess of 20 patients'' who were treated by Mazzella or
received her prescriptions had died from drug overdoses. Two Palm
Beach County residents were among them.
</P>
<P>
   Harris had asked Snow to let Mazzella post bond, saying, ``These
charges are not proven.''
</P>
<P>
   He said there was no direct link between the drugs Mazzella gave
her patients and their overdose deaths because investigators also
found drugs she didn't prescribe in the patients' bodies.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Robert Nicholson questioned whether Mazzella could
flee the country because large amounts of cash appear to be missing
from her practice; the business' bank account has a $2,000 balance.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, Mazzella faces a prison sentence ranging from 20
years to life and fines of up to $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   But Harris said it's ``mere speculation'' to say Mazzella has
piles of cash. Moreover, she would not leave the country, he said,
because she has four children, two grandchildren, a Margate
restaurant called ``Doc's'' and a Parkland house appraised at
$320,710 for tax purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Harris also offered to surrender Mazzella's medical and
prescription drug licenses. ``She will not practice medicine,'' he
said. ``That will take out (concerns of) any danger to the
community.''
</P>
<P>
   But Snow disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This defendant represents a very serious danger to this
community,'' she said. ``The fact that she may have legitimate
patients and provided good care (to them) doesn't change the fact
she's a drug dealer with her own pharmacy that is . . . the fifth
largest pharmacy in the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Tuesday that Mazzella's office pharmacy was the
nation's fifth largest buyer of drugs such as the pain-reliever
hydrocodone. Last week, officials had said the pharmacy was the
nation's largest buyer of certain drugs, but they later discovered
its purchases were less than those of Eckerd, Wal-Mart and other
national chains.
</P>
<P>
   Mazzella's friends and relatives packed the courtroom Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've received hundreds of phone calls, flowers, cards from
people in support of her, including patients of hers for the last
20 years,'' said her son Stephan Mazzella, of Boca Raton.
</P>
<P>
   The daughter of a Lauderhill man treated by Mazzella also
attended. Jessica Coccia, of Boca Raton, said her father, 56, died
of an allergic reaction to a drug prescribed by Mazzella, and the
family settled with Mazzella's insurer last spring for $212,000.
</P>
<P>
   Coccia said she's attending Mazzella's court hearings to ensure
that other patients aren't hurt: ``I don't think she truly cared
about her patients.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanjay Bhatt writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. Barbara Shapiro and Lynne Palombo contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-04-06-99 2238E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
