<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENRON-FIELD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENRON TO PAY $100 MILLION FOR HOUSTON STADIUM NAMING RIGHTS 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN WILLIAMS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Enron Corp. will pay the Houston Astros more than $100 million
over 30 years for the naming rights to the baseball stadium under
construction downtown.
</P>
<P>
   The name: Enron Field.
</P>
<P>
   The naming rights are part of an integrated agreement, expected
to be announced Wednesday, under which the Houston-based energy
giant will manage much of the ballpark's energy services.
</P>
<P>
   Enron also hopes to build an adjacent garage and sell
electricity to the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Astros Senior Vice President Bob McClaren said the team and
Enron are not prepared to announce the terms of the deal other than
it is worth more than $100 million over 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   That would fall in the top five naming rights deals companies
have made to have sports facilities named after them.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, for example, American Airlines agreed to pay the
Dallas Mavericks and Dallas Stars a record $195 million over 30
years for naming and marketing rights for an arena under
construction in downtown Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   The Bank One Ballpark in Phoenix has the highest deal in
baseball _ $66 million over 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros will pocket the money as part of the team's contract
with the Harris County-Houston Sports Authority for a new stadium
in downtown's largely vacant east side. In return for paying $4.6
million annually for rent and $2.5 million for repairs, the team
will keep all revenues, including naming rights.
</P>
<P>
   Astros owner Drayton McLane Jr. has said that playing in the new
stadium could mean at least $20 million in additional annual
revenues for the team, which faced financial problems during and
after the 1994-95 players' strike.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, McLane threatened to sell a portion of the
Astros and move them to Virginia unless a new stadium was built in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole deal allows us to be financially competitive with
other clubs,'' McClaren said. ``That is why the naming rights are
so important.
</P>
<P>
   ``It allows us now to keep our good players, who will want more
money in the future. And it will allow us to go out and get better
players.''
</P>
<P>
   The new name will replace the stadium's working name _ The
Ballpark at Union Station.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' offices will be in the adjacent Union Station, which
will be called Union Station at Enron Field.
</P>
<P>
   Enron can earn as much as $200 million over the 30 years for
managing the ballpark's energy services such as the electricity and
air conditioning, and managing all mechanical and electrical
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good business transaction from the standpoint of energy
management and facility management,'' said Enron Chairman Ken Lay.
</P>
<P>
   Lay, who threw out the first ball at Tuesday's Astros game
against the Chicago Cubs, is largely responsible for getting the
stadium built downtown.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, he put together a consortium that provided $34.7
million in a zero-interest loan to buy downtown land and help
subsidize stadium construction costs. Before then, discussion
revolved around building a new stadium next to the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this will further support the Astros and the
community, through the Astros,'' Lay said of the naming rights
deal.
</P>
<P>
   Enron, with revenue of $32.3 billion last year, is pioneering
the use of marketing contracts to gain entry into selling
electricity to ballparks and get other business from them.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the company signed a 10-year marketing
agreement with the San Francisco Giants as part of a package to
sell electricity and manage building services at the team's new
Pacific Bell Park.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Exelon Energy has signed a deal to sell electricity
to and manage the First Union Center and Spectrum in Philadelphia,
and Sempra Energy has signed a marketing deal with the Staples
Center in Los Angeles that includes electricity sales and
facilities management.
</P>
<P>
   Enron may not now sell electricity in Texas, but it is preparing
for that possibility should the Legislature deregulate the industry
and allow other businesses to compete with Reliant Energy in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   To date, 16 states have deregulated electricity, representing
service to 40 percent of the country's population.
</P>
<P>
   If Texas deregulates electricity sales, Enron-subsidiary Enron
Energy Services will have the first right to sell electricity to
the ballpark, whose retractable-roof can be closed and cool air
introduced on hot days.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Enron will manage the chilled air provided by
competitor Reliant Energy subsidiary Northwind Houston. Reliant
edged Enron in a heated contest for the chilled-water contract last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Enron will need sports authority's approval to build a 4,500 to
5,000-space garage on both sides of U.S. 59 east of the ballpark,
part of the company's agreement with the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   The sports authority must approve the garage because it would
sit on land the authority is buying. &UR;  &LR; The site was originally
proposed for a 2,500-space surface parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   McClaren said the Astros and Enron would evenly split garage
revenues on game days, and are working out an arrangement for other
events.
</P>
<P>
   Enron believes more area parking will be needed as development
goes up around the ballpark. It is also considering using such a
garage during the daytime for employees working in a new building
the company is constructing on downtown's southwest side.
</P>
<P>
   Lay said Enron is also looking for other investment
opportunities in the ballpark area, which would allow it to
maximize the parking lot and sell energy- and facilities-management
to other buildings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
