<HEADLINE>
NICKLAUS: NO MASTERS MOPING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Jack Nicklaus, the only six-time champion in
Masters Tournament history, hit his lone shot of the 1999 event
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   While touring the course with Hootie Johnson, the club chairman,
Nicklaus borrowed a 5-iron from Carlos Franco and deposited a tee
shot on the putting surface at No. 12, a 155-yard par-3. His next
competitive swing at Augusta National Golf Club, Nicklaus vowed,
will come in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus, 59, underwent hip replacement surgery in January that
will cause him to break a string of 40 consecutive Masters
appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to miss the Masters. But I'm not going to sit around
and mope,'' said Nicklaus, who placed sixth at the 1998 Masters,
the highest finish ever recorded by a player old enough to compete
on the Senior Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Nicklaus said he plans to leave today on a five-day
fishing trip to the Bahamas and will spend little, if any, time
watching the event on television. He traveled to Augusta to attend
last night's champions dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus, who completed an 18-hole round Sunday for the first
time since his surgery, has targeted the PGA Tour's Memorial
Tournament (June 3-6) as his probable return to competitive golf
... unless he plays the week before at a Senior Tour stop in
Philadelphia. He said he plans to compete in the U.S. Open, where
his string of consecutive appearances dates to 1957.
</P>
<P>
   Because his string of consecutive appearances in major
championships ended at the 1998 British Open, Nicklaus said
skipping the Masters ``is not as emotional as missing the British
Open. To me, once that streak stopped, they all came to an end.''
</P>
<P>
   Others expressed more poignant sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a Masters without Jack Nicklaus is like your wife
losing the diamond out of her wedding ring,'' Greg Norman said.
``Jack put the Masters on the map to my generation of players. This
will be a sad week.'' \Nsubheds:Praise for Kuehne Nicklaus said he
was wowed yesterday by the driving prowess of Hank Kuehne, the U.S.
Amateur champ from SMU. Kuehne hit a driver and a pitching wedge to
the green at No. 15, a 500-yard par-5, in a practice round. Kuehne
also cut the corner at No. 13, a dogleg par-5, by driving over a
tall strand of trees left of the tee box.
</P>
<P>
   ``From where his balls landed, I'd say he'll be 20 yards past
Tiger Woods,'' Nicklaus said. ``It was pretty incredible to
watch.'' \Nsubheds:Format adjusted Because of the 96-player field,
the largest for any Masters since 1966, officials announced
contestants will be grouped in threesomes, rather than twosomes,
for the first two rounds. It marks the first time since 1962 that
tournament officials have used threesomes for reasons other than
weather delays.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, contestants will not be regrouped based on
opening-round scores for Friday's second round, as in years past.
They will play the first two rounds with the same threesome.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
