</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-ROOKIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO STARS ROOKIES GET VALUABLE ICE TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Jon Sim and Brad Lukowich know all about
competition. They had to fight through a maze of challenges just to
get a chance to play in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've created a good system in which it's difficult for a
young player to crack our lineup,'' said Craig Button, the Stars'
director of player personnel. ``We are not going to be putting
players into the NHL who are not ready for the NHL. We don't have
to.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the mental conditioning of their minor-league challenges
could prove the necessary training to keep the two Stars rookies in
the NHL for the immediate future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just getting here was tough,'' said Lukowich, a 22-year-old
defenseman who has outbattled fellow prospects Petr Buzek and
Sergey Gusev to earn the chance to play the past eight games with
the Stars. ``You definitely have to prove yourself to get a chance
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukowich and Sim are Stars prospects who have been learning
their craft at the minor-league level with the Michigan K-Wings _ a
place where they were lumped into large groups of players who were
selected to fill a few small needs.
</P>
<P>
   Lukowich has battled with Buzek and Gusev, as well as
20-year-old prospect Richard Jackman, for the right to be the
Stars' next defenseman in waiting. Gusev spent most of the season
with the Stars, but Lukowich ended up winning a key battle when
Gusev was traded to the Tampa Bay Lightning last month for Benoit
Hogue. Now, Lukowich has stepped up as the immediate heir apparent
on defense.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's 3-0 loss to the Detroit Red Wings, Lukowich played
almost 10 minutes while veteran Doug Lidster was limited to just 33
seconds of ice time. Again, as small as it might have seemed,
Lukowich took another victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's played well; he's shown he can play this game at the NHL
level,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``Then again, he's a
22-year-old defenseman playing against grown men.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukowich has been trained in the same system the Stars play. He
spent four seasons of junior hockey (1992-96) with the Kamloops
Blazers of the Western Hockey League _ a team that never wavered
much from the style that Hitchcock implemented when he was coach
there from 1984-90. Lukowich also has trained for the past three
seasons in the same system with the K-Wings.
</P>
<P>
   At 6-foot-1, 195 pounds, he's a decent hitter who can also move
the puck.
</P>
<P>
   Sim is less of a known quantity for the Stars. But they like
what they've seen so far. The 5-foot-10, 175-pound left wing was
the Stars' third-round pick in 1996 and was playing his first
season with the K-Wings. A native of Nova Scotia, Sim was a natural
scorer in junior hockey, scoring 156 goals over the past three
seasons with the Sarnia Sting of the Ontario Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   Sim draws immediate comparisons to 600 goal-scorer Dino
Ciccarelli as a short, pesky presence in front of the net, and he
has already scored one goal and taken six shots in four games with
the Stars. As a left-handed shooter, he had to work his way past
Jason Botterill and Jamie Wright to get this shot with the Stars.
And Sim has made an impression in his one season with the
organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't look out of place at all,'' Hitchcock said. ``He
draws comparisons to Ciccarelli, and you can see that in him. The
thing is, he's going to have to be productive.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock has Sim scheduled to play the left wing next to Joe
Nieuwendyk tonight against the Mighty Ducks of Anaheim _ and that
means the coach is letting the rookie have every chance to be
productive.
</P>
<P>
   Because, as healthy bodies begin to return to the lineup,
Hitchcock is going to have some difficult decisions to make going
into the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Defensemen Richard Matvichuk (groin and knee) and Shawn Chambers
(hip flexor) are out with injuries but due to return to the lineup
soon. If that happens, Lukowich probably becomes a backup to be
used in case of an injury.
</P>
<P>
   With Mike Modano (hip rotator muscle) and Brian Skrudland
(chest) also expected to play three or four of the final six games,
Sim may be phased out.
</P>
<P>
   But Hitchcock said the two already have proven themselves
through a series of challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't really thought much about \Rsending them back to
Kalamazoo\S,'' Hitchcock said. ``I really see both of them as part
of the mix right now.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
