<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-FUTURE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS NOT READY TO START ALL OVER AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ This season started with so much promise for the
Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   Don Nelson, the team's coach and general manager, was confident
his team would be in playoff contention. Several Mavericks players
said the team had the ingredients to advance to the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with less than a month remaining in the regular season, the
Mavericks are where they usually are this time of the year: close
to the Midwest Division basement.
</P>
<P>
   Making matters worse, the Mavericks can't even improve their
position in the NBA draft lottery as the losses mount. That's
because Nelson traded their first-round pick to the Phoenix Suns
last summer for Steve Nash.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson was so sure Nash was going to be an immediate hit _ and
that the first-round pick would be a mid- or late-round pick _ that
he went against every general manager's mode of operation and did
not even bother to lottery-protect the first-round pick to the Suns
for at least one year.
</P>
<P>
   Nash, who has been booed this season by Mavericks fans, knows he
hasn't come close to living up to the advance billing Nelson gave
him. He also knows he is part of the reason Mavericks and their
fans are about to miss out on the postseason party once again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say anything to the fans, but I'm sorry,'' Nash said.
``I feel for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mavericks brought a lot of people here in the last year or
so. I know the record is not what they expect, but what can you
expect when this team has just been put together, and all of the
other teams are a few years ahead of us?''
</P>
<P>
   One of those teams is the Miami Heat, which plays host to the
Mavericks tonight at Miami Arena.
</P>
<P>
   All the Mavericks need is time together on the court and
everything will be OK, Nash said. Long-suffering Mavericks fans
have heard that lecture for almost a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Nash said if he were running the team, he wouldn't make
wholesale changes and start over again next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blow it up for what?,'' Nash asked. ``You blow it up to try
again?
</P>
<P>
   ``Give it some time. I'd still try to add some players. I don't
think this is the final product.''
</P>
<P>
   Center Shawn Bradley, one of the few bright spots on this
season's team, said starting over again is easier said than done,
and doesn't guarantee positive results.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take some time to rebuild,'' Bradley said. ``It
doesn't happen in one season, but we definitely need to improve and
find a steady improvement and see growth ... in order for it not to
get blown up again.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson has repeatedly said he likes this group. He blames the
Mavericks' free-fall _ they are 11-23 and have lost nine
consecutive road games _ in part on injuries to Cedric Ceballos and
Robert Pack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really like this team, but we've been inconsistent,'' Nelson
said. ``But that's nothing that wasn't expected with a young team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we were going to have some ups and downs. So a lot of
things that people are worried about, we're not as worried about
it. We just accept it as part of growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said Mavericks fans simply have to be patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans know that we've got some good players and good guys
on this team,'' Bradley said. ``I think they also know when you
blow up an organization time and time again, it's not going to get
better overnight.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
