<SLUG> BC-XEROX-APPOINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMID ALTERED COPIER LANDSCAPE, NEW CHIEF IS NAMED AT XEROX
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a move that everyone knew was coming, the Xerox Corp. named
G. Richard Thoman, 54, as its chief executive Tuesday. He replaces
Paul A. Allaire, 60, who remains as chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was preordained, part of the normal evolution,'' said
Peter J. Enderlin, an analyst with the First Albany Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Jack L. Kelly, an analyst with Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., said,
``Let's hope he executes the distribution and cost-cutting plans
that have been articulated.''
</P>
<P>
   Thoman has been groomed to succeed Allaire ever since he joined
Xerox from the IBM in June 1997, so his ascension is unlikely to
touch off any strategic or cultural shifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been a change agent,'' Thoman said in an interview
before the announcement. ``But Paul and I evolved a workable style,
so there's no need to change things.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Thoman takes the helm at a time of unprecedented change
for Xerox, which is based in Stamford, Conn. Digital technology has
blurred the line between copiers and printers, and has made it
possible to plug printer-copiers into computer networks. That has
moved responsibility for buying the hybrids out of the procurement
department _ once a Xerox stronghold _ and into the purchasing
realm of information systems specialists, who are more familiar
with computer companies.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Xerox is not only competing with traditional rivals like
Canon and Ricoh but with companies like Hewlett-Packard. It is even
up against Heidelberger Druckmaschinen A.G., the German printing
company that is buying the Eastman Kodak Co.'s copier business.
</P>
<P>
   Every contender in this emerging document processing industry is
trying to establish the densest global distribution and service
networks. And no one is ceding any ground.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Ikon Office Solutions, a large distributor of
copiers, recently stopped selling products made by the Sharp Corp.
of Japan. Since Ikon had been Sharp's primary distributor in the
United States, many analysts left the company for dead in the
American market.
</P>
<P>
   But Sharp carved a $1 billion office-equipment division out of
the hodgepodge of microwaves, videocassette recorders and other
consumer products that the Sharp Electronics Corp., its American
arm, sells in the United States. And it hired Joseph Rickard as the
first American to run it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Setting up the distribution and support to service national
and eventually, global, accounts will be my main focus,'' Rickard
said.
</P>
<P>
   If ``know thine enemy'' is good advice, Rickard was a perfect
choice: He goes to Sharp after 21 years with Xerox, many of them
running its network of independent sales representatives and
distributors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
