<SLUG> BC-NISSAN-PENSION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENSION FUND AT NISSAN HAS $4.76 BILLION SHORTAGE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The Nissan Motor Co., Japan's second-largest auto maker,
detailed the extent of its pension financing shortage Tuesday,
disclosing a gap almost twice as large as analysts had expected.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman, Masataka Saito, said the shortage in Nissan's
consolidated pension fund was 580 billion yen, or $4.76 billion at
current exchange rates, based on a relatively conservative assumed
rate of return of 3.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Saito said the shortage's size, first reported in The Financial
Times, could shrink drastically, depending on regulatory changes
the government is now considering that would diminish the effect of
new accounting rules that force companies to disclose pension
liabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that's going to cost them more money in the
future than you would have known before you had this information,''
said Christopher Richter, an auto analyst with HSBC Securities
here. ``Nissan does have a lot of other financial baggage to carry,
so it's significant.''
</P>
<P>
   Nissan is not the only Japanese company with notable shortages
in its pension funds. According to newspaper reports, the Toyota
Motor Corp.'s gap is roughly 300 billion yen, and Honda Motor has
said that its pensions are underfunded by about 220 billion yen.
</P>
<P>
   The problem extends far beyond the auto industry. Kathy Matsui,
chief strategist at Goldman Sachs Japan Ltd., who has done
extensive research into the pension problems of corporations, has
estimated that the combined deficit could reach 80 trillion yen, or
$666 billion at current exchange rates.
</P>
<P>
   That is far more than the official level of bad debts at Japan's
troubled banks.
</P>
<P>
   Based on reports about Toyota and Honda, analysts had predicted
that Nissan's pension problem would cost it about 300 billion yen.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Boardman, an auto analyst at Warburg Dillon Read here,
said the revised figures had actually been included in material
given to analysts at a meeting that followed Renault S.A.'s
announcement on March 27 that it would pay $5.4 billion for a 36.8
percent stake in Nissan.
</P>
<P>
   He said Renault explained that the value of Nissan's land
holdings would almost totally offset its pension shortage. The
French auto maker has valued Nissan's property portfolio between
400 billion and 500 billion yen, according to Boardman, although
Nissan had previously valued it around a trillion yen.
</P>
<P>
   In general, Renault appears to have sharply marked down the
value of Nissan's assets, bringing them more into line with market
realities. Nissan had estimated the value of its assets at $10.4
billion, Boardman said. But Renault cut that by roughly 40 percent,
putting the total _ including the $5.4 billion it is paying Nissan
for its stake _ at $11.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan officials have also been lowering expectations about the
company's profitability in the fiscal year that ended on March 31.
Previously, Nissan had said it expected to lose 10 billion yen, but
Tuesday, Japan's leading business daily, Nihon Keizai Shimbun,
reported that the company now expects a 35 billion yen loss.
</P>
<P>
   That would not be surprising, given the company's weak domestic
sales. In March, Nissan's sales slid 15.9 percent, according to the
Japan Automobile Dealers Association. Nissan has missed out on the
boom in ``mini-vehicles'' _ tiny cars with tiny engines that offer
owners special tax breaks and and easier parking. Toyota also had
no mini-vehicle, although its interest in Daihatsu, which does make
the little cars, effectively gave it a presence in that market. It
also sells the new Vitz, which is not technically a mini-car but
appeals to the same buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan is not planning to introduce any new models in the first
half of the new fiscal year _ the period through Sept. 30 _ which
will make it even harder for the company to improve sales. ``I'm
not worried about pension shortfalls,'' Boardman said. ``I'm
worried about sales in April, May, June, July.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
