u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAMILY-AD-COLUMN-875&AMP;     04-06 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-AD-COLUMN-875&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETERS UNITE BEHIND `FAMILY FRIENDLY' PROGRAMMING
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (nk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A serious effort by marketers to urge more ``family
friendly'' television programming has picked up speed, with more
than a score of leading advertisers now supporting plans to
stimulate producers to develop _ and networks to schedule _ such
shows.
</P>
<P>
   The progress of those plans was outlined Tuesday at the opening
of the annual Television Advertising Forum sponsored by the
Association of National Advertisers. The forum, at the Plaza Hotel
in Manhattan, drew more than 250 executives from consumer-product
companies and TV networks.
</P>
<P>
   New nudges in the push for family-oriented programming _
particularly in the first two hours of prime time _ include
meetings with the Hollywood studios and the broadcast networks;
encouraging production companies, networks and writers with
incentives like awards and scholarships; stepping up promotional
campaigns for designated shows, and paying somewhat higher rates
than usual to run commercials during programs that may not reach as
large an audience as those infused with sex, violence, frank
language and wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   Those steps were described in a presentation by Andrea Alstrup,
vice president for advertising at Johnson &AMP; Johnson, and Robert L.
Wehling, corporate officer for global marketing, market research
and government relations at the Procter &AMP; Gamble Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no desire to complain or whine or censor,'' Wehling
said. ``We are simply looking for more choices we don't have to
think twice about.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to show this programming has a market,'' he added,
``and to show it can be financially successful for advertisers and
networks.''
</P>
<P>
   The efforts began last year when 10 of them formed a coalition.
In addition to Johnson &AMP; Johnson and P&AMP;G, the marketing behemoths
involved included AT&AMP;T; Coca-Cola; Ford Motor; General Motors; IBM;
McDonald's; Nestle; Pfizer; Sears, Roebuck; Warner-Lambert, and
Wendy's International.
</P>
<P>
   These corporations wield a powerful weapon: the billions of
dollars they spend each year to pitch products on media outlets,
especially on broadcast network TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are opportunities for several advertisers to work
together,'' Ms. Alstrup said, because ``we're finding many of us
have a lot in common.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooperative ventures could include jointly producing or
sponsoring programs, she added, rather than attempting the more
difficult task of adopting common guidelines to use in screening
programs for objectionable content.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here for the duration,'' Ms. Alstrup said. ``This is not
a six-month plan; this is a long-term plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, the customers most coveted by corporate sponsors
_ the freer-spending shoppers 18 to 49 _ have generally become more
enamored of shows with content deemed too contentious by the
advertisers that have long supported family-friendly fare.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get into a lot of discussions in this industry,''
Wehling said, asserting that ``family friendly programming, by its
very nature, skews older and would not be an efficient buy for
advertisers seeking the 18-to-49-year-old audience.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe when there is viable, creatively written
family-friendly programming,'' he added, ``it can do a very decent
rating in the audience we all seek.''
</P>
<P>
   Wehling offered as examples ``Sabrina the Teen-Age Witch,'' a
sitcom on ABC that P&AMP;G helps produce; ``Touched by an Angel'' on
CBS; ``Dilbert,'' a new animated series on UPN; and ``7th Heaven,''
a series on the WB network about a minister and his large family.
</P>
<P>
   The praise for ``7th Heaven'' seemed unusual: Plot lines are
often focused on issues like drug use, adultery and sexual activity
among teen-agers. But those subjects are typically treated in a
context of the minister's teaching his children about right and
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, a family orientation ``doesn't mean we don't want to be in
dramatic programming,'' Ms. Alstrup said, ``or not be in
programming with controversial content.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to preach morality,'' she added. ``There are
younger people with younger families paying close attention to what
their kids are seeing and hearing.''
</P>
<P>
   Wehling agreed that context played an important part in deciding
which shows to embrace or eschew. ``We generally stay away from any
violence,'' he said, ``but we'd be very comfortable with
sponsorship of `Schindler's List' '' because that film about the
Holocaust ``had scenes that made you close your eyes, yet the
context is so compelling.''
</P>
<P>
   And Wehling compared P&AMP;G's concern about prime-time content with
a question from the audience about the content of the daytime soap
operas the company produces like ``Another World'' and ``As the
World Turns.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If all of you were soap watchers, I wouldn't have to do much
defending,'' Wehling said. ``The reason we're very comfortable with
our soap-opera sponsorship is that the soap opera in a very real
way is a morality play.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a soap opera, you reap what you sow,'' he added, ``and when
you as a character do something wrong, you pay for that. The viewer
knows that. And that is one of the attractions to the viewer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only question is when and how,'' Wehling said, ``and I
will admit it sometimes takes a long time.'' That remark, delivered
with a smile, elicited laughs.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As for perceptions among members of minority groups and
nontraditional families that describing programming as family
friendly or family oriented is meant to exclude them, Wehling said
that he was also comfortable with the term ``multigenerational
programming.''
</P>
<P>
   He defined such programming as shows that would be ``interesting
and entertaining'' rather than embarrassing if ``you had your
mother and your daughter with you and you were watching together.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not an easy issue for the networks,'' Wehling said,
because they ``say they have to be responsive to what they perceive
as viewer demand'' in the form of higher ratings for less
family-oriented programs and ``compete against cable and pay
programming'' with their far less restrictive rules for language
and images.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are very clear they're after the teen-age and
young adult urban audience that wants edgier programming, and
that's OK,'' he added. ``We're not trying to take away choices from
viewers, from the advertising community. All we're asking for is an
expansion of the choices available to us.''
</P>
<P>
   The awards intended to reward those who support family-oriented
programs will be given out at a luncheon planned for Sept. 9 at the
Beverly Hilton hotel in Beverly Hills, Calif. Among those to be
honored with the Family Programming Awards, to be bestowed
annually, will be ``one or more current successful family-friendly
programs,'' Wehling said, ``and one or more individuals identified
with family-friendly programming over a long period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   The awards will be co-sponsored by the advertiser consortium
along with the advertiser association, the Advertising Council, the
American Advertising Federation and the American Association of
Advertising Agencies. The advertisers hope to produce a television
special covering the awards ceremony, Ms. Alstrup said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
