<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMR-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW INTERNET MANIA COULD BRING PILOTS' UNION TO HEEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is no doubt that Internet companies can create tremendous
wealth overnight, but can the current Internet mania by investors
help management bring a labor union to heel?
</P>
<P>
   It may be a testament to Wall Street's current faith in the
omnipotence of the World Wide Web that some people are convinced it
can _ at least in the case of AMR Corp., the parent of American
Airlines, which is currently at war with its pilots.
</P>
<P>
   The idea comes in the aftermath of last week's initial public
offering of Priceline.com, which allows customers to name their own
price for airplane tickets on the Web. After less than a year in
business, during which it lost $114 million selling $35 million
worth of airline tickets, Priceline.com is valued at $10 billion,
more than the combined worth of UAL's United Airlines, Northwest
Airlines and Continental Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to American, AMR owns the Sabre Group, an
information technology company that in turn owns Travelocity, which
is the leading seller of airplane tickets over the Web. It too lost
money last year but it sold $285 million worth of airline tickets,
hotel rooms and rental cars. Depending on whom you believe,
Travelocity on its own could be worth _ pick a number _ $1 billion,
$5 billion or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best way to get at the value of Travelocity is for AMR to
divest Sabre,'' said Kevin Murphy, an analyst at Morgan Stanley
Dean Witter. ``One of the byproducts of that is that the airline
gets isolated. And if the airline is out there by itself, you would
see the poor return on investment and the lousy operating margins.
The market would force discipline on the management and then on the
union.''
</P>
<P>
   That discipline, he added, would help AMR management convince
the pilots _ as well as its other unions _ that the company cannot
afford to concede too much. ``Right now there is an intangible
situation where the airline gets refuge under the Sabre umbrella,''
Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   AMR, which currently owns 82 percent of Sabre, would not comment
on whether it plans to spin off the rest of the company. But the
move may be hard to resist.
</P>
<P>
   Since Priceline.com began trading last week, Sabre's stock price
has soared 32 percent, or $14.375 a share, closing Tuesday at $58 a
share, up $3. Likewise, AMR stock, which had suffered in recent
weeks after a Feb. protest by its pilots forced it to cancel nearly
6,700 flights, has risen sharply as well. Tuesday it closed at
$65.6875, up $1.0625, and it has increased 16 percent since last
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes the marketplace leads management's strategic
thinking,'' Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Tuesday, Michael Durham, Sabre's chief
executive, would not say whether Sabre would spin off Travelocity
but he was relishing the temptation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an old finance guy,'' said Durham, who was formerly AMR's
chief financial officer. ``If somebody tells me that I can get $10
billion for a company that is losing money, it sort of feels like
you might want to be a seller.''
</P>
<P>
   But he quickly added that separating Travelocity from Sabre
would remove many of the important benefits that it gets from
Sabre's other businesses. The company, which had $2.3 billion in
revenue last year, operates the world's largest airline computer
reservation system and has a large information-technology
consulting business. Whenever Sabre's software designers come up
with a new feature for the services it offers travel agents and
corporations, it can also add the same functionality to
Travelocity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously there is a tremendous frenzy in the marketplace
right now,'' Durham said. ``But our shareholders and board of
directors have put us here to optimize the long-term value of
Sabre.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the longer the Internet frenzy lasts, the more AMR appears
to be tugged in two different directions. Sabre now trades at about
30 times expected 1998 earnings, while AMR without Sabre might
trade at about five times earnings. Without the speculation of a
spinoff, Sabre's share price would certainly fall. (It traded as
low as $23 a share last year).
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are only getting an airline multiple for Sabre
earnings, you are hurting shareholders,'' said Samuel Buttrick, an
analyst at Paine Webber in New York.
</P>
<P>
   That is exactly why Murphy believes that a Sabre spinoff
ultimately would force American's unions to bend by isolating the
airline. But the pilots see things differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that is probably a counterproductive strategy,'' said
Brian Mayhew, vice president of the Allied Pilots Association, the
American pilots' union. ``I don't think that because they spin off
Sabre tomorrow our professional worth is less.''
</P>
<P>
   The pilots and AMR management are in mediation this week in an
attempt to settle a dispute over AMR's purchase of Reno Air, a
small carrier in the West. American's pilots were so upset with the
company for what they say are a series of deliberate contract
violations that when negotiations broke down in early February over
how to merge Reno into American's network, thousands of pilots
called in sick, stranding hundreds of thousands of passengers.
</P>
<P>
   John Pincavage, an airline analyst at Warburg Dillon Read, said
that the unions did not care that airlines were not as profitable
as Internet companies; they just see four consecutive years of
record profits, not the low fuel prices and travel agent commission
cuts that have sustained them.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the airlines making the kind of money they are making,
the unions wouldn't buy that,'' he said, referring to the market
discipline described by Murphy. ``All they know is that they gave
in the past and they are not seeing their paychecks go up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
