<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SOURCES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: BANANA JOURNALISM 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, April 7:
</P>
<P>
   In a Cincinnati courtroom this week, Mike Gallagher, a former
investigative reporter for The Cincinnati Enquirer, acknowledged
that protecting the confidentiality of a source was ``one of the
highest responsibilities a journalist has.'' Then he proceeded to
reveal to the court the name of one of his major sources. As a
former colleague of Gallagher said after witnessing the breaking of
one of journalism's most hallowed and least flexible rules,
``Gallagher sold out everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   What led to this sellout was a big investigative story gone
awry. It began when Gallagher and others at The Enquirer were
investigating Chiquita Brands International, one of Cincinnati's
most influential corporations. At some point the reporter learned
access codes to voice mail received by Chiquita executives, and
began listening to their private phone messages. He told the paper
what he was doing; the editors ordered him to stop, but Gallagher
has acknowledged that he continued accessing the phone messages in
secret.
</P>
<P>
   Last May the paper published a large section about Chiquita that
raised important questions about the company's business practices.
About two months later The Enquirer issued a broad apology to
Chiquita not only for Gallagher's unacceptable method of tapping
into voice mail but also for the ``untrue conclusions'' about the
company in his articles. The paper also paid Chiquita an unusually
large settlement of $10 million and dismissed Gallagher. Since then
the former reporter has pleaded guilty to two federal charges of
stealing Chiquita's internal communications and has agreed to
identify his sources in testimony in any other trial.
</P>
<P>
   Gallagher certainly has every right to mount a vigorous defense,
but his decision to disclose sources betrays the most basic code of
what is undoubtedly now his former profession. The contract between
a source and a journalist is one of the sacred bonds, and many a
reporter has promised to go to jail to protect such an agreement.
Gallagher's attorney has argued that when the accused reporter
revealed his source in this convoluted case, the name was already
well known to officials at Chiquita as well as the legal
authorities. Such an argument attempts to sidestep the basic
problem _ that Gallagher reneged on his word.
</P>
<P>
   The instinct to look into the operations of a powerful local
company like Chiquita was a laudable effort, but Gallagher tainted
that effort with unethical reporting techniques and then damaged
his former profession by breaking the contract between reporters
and confidential sources.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-99 2330EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
