<SLUG> BC-GOTTI-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 FACTORS, INCLUDING JURY ANONYMITY, SEEMED PIVOTAL TO GOTTI'S
PLEA 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER and JOSEPH BERGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For months, government prosecutors and lawyers for John A. Gotti
had haggled over whether the accused Mafia figure would plead
guilty in his upcoming racketeering and extortion case. And every
time he seemed on the verge of agreeing to a such deal, the talks
would collapse, and his lawyers would defiantly declare that the
government's case was weak and that they were heading to trial.
</P>
<P>
   But late last week, something happened to change the calculation
for both sides. In a closed hearing in U.S. District Court in White
Plains, prosecutors told Judge Barrington Parker that Gotti had
hired a private investigator with a history of witness tampering,
and noted pointedly that Gotti's father, John J. Gotti, was ``an
accomplished practitioner of jury tampering.''
</P>
<P>
   With those words, the prosecutors convinced Parker to keep
secret the names of jurors in Gotti's trial. Defense lawyers denied
any allegations of misconduct, but the decision cast a chill over
the defense team, one lawyer said, which feared that an anonymous
jury could create an aura of menace in the courtroom and possibly
tilt the balance against the man prosecutors called the acting boss
of the Gambino crime family.
</P>
<P>
   Gotti's lawyers resumed plea talks, and by Monday evening Gotti
was standing before Parker and admitting that he took part in a
criminal racket that used bribery, extortion and threats of
violence to earn its illicit money.
</P>
<P>
   An account of the seesawing negotiations, provided by lawyers
and government authorities close to the case, indicates that there
were three factors pivotal to the outcome beyond the strength of
the government's case: Parker's decision to keep the jurors' names
secret, word from Brooklyn that the U.S. attorney there was about
to indict Gotti for filing false tax returns, and the willingness
of the government to offer Gotti assurances that he would not be
further prosecuted on those tax charges or for any other crimes now
under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``John himself said that when he has to say goodbye to his
children he wants to do this once,'' said Gerald Shargel, Gotti's
lawyer. ``He wants to go to jail once. The life of being the prey
of law enforcement is no life for him, and he truly wants to put
this all behind him.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors said Tuesday that the plea should end the
Gotti family's control over the Gambino family, which officials say
they believe the elder Gotti was trying to run through his son from
a prison cell in Marion, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   And while experts in and out of government largely agreed that
the reign of the Gottis was over, some said the impact on the crime
family would be minimal, in part because the family was already in
disarray after years of successful prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you convict an acting boss of a major crime family,
that's really important,'' said J. Bruce Mouw, former head of the
FBI's Gambino squad in New York. But he said the younger Gotti has
essentially been absent in recent years. ``They've had no
leadership,'' he said. ``The morale is very poor. They are very
disorganized.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Lewis Schiliro, director of the New York office of the
FBI, said that putting Gotti in prison will further disrupt ``the
administration of the family,'' and lessen its influence ``in those
industries they historically controlled.''
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the plea, Gotti faces a maximum sentence of seven
years and three months and a $1 million fine. In addition, he
agreed to forfeit property and money worth more than $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   But until the government persuaded Parker last Thursday to allow
a secret jury, it looked as though there would be no plea, just a
trial. Some defense lawyers see anonymous juries as a disadvantage
because they can raise fears in jurors' minds about the defendants,
and impose a kind of presumption of guilt.
</P>
<P>
   Even with that ruling, though, the deal continued to elude the
two sides for a couple of days. A breakthrough seemed to come
Sunday night when Sarita Kedia, a young defense lawyer in Shargel's
office, talked with Carol Sipperly, the lead prosecutor in the
case.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kedia was able to forge a congenial relationship with Ms.
Sipperly, and Shargel has come to rely on her.
</P>
<P>
   According to Ms. Kedia's account of the conversation, Ms.
Sipperly suddenly said, ``I can't believe we're going to trial over
what are minor differences'' in the terms of a plea agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kedia said she tried to make clear to Ms. Sipperly that the
most important thing to Gotti was what she called ``coverage'' _
language in the plea agreement assuring Gotti that once he pleaded
guilty to specified crimes, the government would promise that he
would not be prosecuted in the future for any matters that federal
or state authorities were now investigating.
</P>
<P>
   In December, Gotti and his lawyers had come close to accepting a
prosecution offer that would have required a jail sentence of 6 1/2
to 8 years. By February, the government had improved its offer to a
sentence ranging from five years and 10 months to seven years and
three months _ identical to what Gotti finally accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Gotti continued to hold out, apparently counting on what he saw
as weaknesses in the government's case. But his attention became
focused, lawyers said, by external events, such as the ruling on
secret juries. Then, in recent days, it became clear that an
investigation by the U.S. attorney in Brooklyn of Gotti's tax
returns was likely to produce an additional indictment against
Gotti.
</P>
<P>
   With the knowledge that he could face a sentence of about 15
years if convicted at trial, Gotti decided that he could plead
guilty to reduced charges and avoid the risk of the longer term and
be assured that he would no longer be the target of prosecutors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
