A8494 &Cx1f; taf-z
u x &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-BOTTLEDWATER-NYT     04-06 0392
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BOTTLEDWATER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: TRUTH IN BOTTLING 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, April 7:
</P>
<P>
   Some people drink bottled water because they think it tastes
better, others because they think it confers special status. But
most people drink it because they believe it is safer than tap
water. Is it? A new study by the Natural Resources Defense Council,
an environmental advocacy group, says that some bottled water
contains contaminants and chemicals and that ``blanket reassurances
from the industry that bottled water is totally safe and pure are
false.'' The group recommends tighter federal oversight as well as
a higher standard of truth in advertising. It makes a compelling
case.
</P>
<P>
   The study tested 103 popular brands of bottled water. In 23 of
the cases, at least one sample violated California's strict limits
for at least one contaminant, usually arsenic or one of several
man-made chemicals. The study said that the ``immediate'' health
risks were very small. It also noted that in 1996, 1 in 10
community tap-water systems violated federal standards. But the
point is that many brands that advertise themselves as pristine are
themselves violating California law.
</P>
<P>
   Industry spokesmen noted that all bottlers met existing federal
regulations and that there had been no confirmed report of illness
or disease linked to bottled water in 37 years of regulation by the
federal Food and Drug Administration. But sales of bottled water
have tripled in the last 10 years, to about $4 billion annually,
and new brands have proliferated. With greater growth comes greater
risk. Moreover, FDA rules do not cover bottled water that is sold
within a single state.
</P>
<P>
   The report asks the FDA to make its rules as strong as
California's, the nation's most stringent. At a minimum the Defense
Council wants bottled water standards to match the federal
standards for tap water set by the Environmental Protection Agency.
The report also asks the FDA to require manufacturers to label the
bottle's contents, including bacteria levels. The FDA's response is
that ``bottled water poses no significant health risk and is,
therefore, safe to consume.'' ``So far, so good'' is not an
acceptable response from a federal health agency. A more aggressive
approach is in order.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-99 2337EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990406.0408 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 23:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8496 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-MARLINS-NYT &LR;      04-06 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-MARLINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR A NIGHT ANYWAY, THE METS GET EXACTLY WHAT THEY PAID FOR
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ So this was why the Mets opened their checkbooks during
the off season.
</P>
<P>
   One day after stranding 14 runners and going 0 for 9 with
runners in scoring position in an embarrassing opening day defeat,
the Mets' offense came alive Tuesday night, pummeling former World
Series hero Livan Hernandez for seven runs in four and two-thirds
innings en route to a 12-3 rout of the Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pretty good in must-win games,'' Mets General Manager
Steve Phillips said, taking a jab at negative press coverage in New
York following the 6-2 loss in Monday's opener. Phillips even
suggested his own headline for Wednesday's papers: ``Money well
spent.''
</P>
<P>
   While Rick Reed threw no-hit ball for four-plus innings, the
Mets went seven for their first eight with runners in scoring
position. And each member of the starting lineup contributed
something.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hit well as a team and that's the key,'' said Mike Piazza,
who drilled a hanging fast ball from Hernandez for his first home
run of the year. ``Last year, we kind of counted on one guy for one
or two weeks at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza was usually that guy, something that was not lost on him
Tuesday. Every member of the starting lineup except for Reed had at
least one hit and scored at least one run. Rickey Henderson created
three runs in one sequence, doubling home a pair before stealing
third with two out in the second inning and then scoring on an
errant catcher's throw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd probably be the king of stealing runs and creating runs if
they kept those stats,'' said Henderson, baseball's all-time stolen
base king. ``Making them throw the ball away, I'd probably be the
king of that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   For one day, the Mets' world was righted against a low-budget
team they had struggled against last season. And by the smiles in
the bullpen and the jokes in the dugout, it was clear that this was
a laugher almost from the first pitch.
</P>
<P>
   With one out in the first inning, Edgardo Alfonzo doubled off
Hernandez and scored on a John Olerud single.
</P>
<P>
   With one out in the second, Rey Ordonez delivered a run-scoring
single after Bobby Bonilla and Brian McRae walked. One out Rickey
Henderson doubled two more runs home, before stealing third and
scoring when Jorge Fabregas's throw sailed into left field.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in the fifth, one out after Alfonzo doubled off
Hernandez, Piazza drummed the Marlins' right-hander out of the game
with a two-run home run into the second deck in left. By the time
Reed allowed his first hit, a double to Todd Dunwoody leading off
the bottom of the fifth, the Mets were up by 7-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins scratched out a run in their fifth when Fabregas was
ruled safe at first on a ball that Olerud had dived for, knocked
down, and recovered almost in time to prevent Dunwoody from scoring
from third base with two out.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Ventura opened the sixth with a double off Kirt Ojala.
McRae tripled Ventura home and then scored on an Ordonez sacrifice
fly. And it was 9-1 Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Mets were feeling any pressure after the 6-2
opening day loss to the Marlins, but the last thing the players
wanted was to struggle as they head back to Shea Stadium next
Monday after three games with the Marlins and four more with the
Expos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I guarantee you, we go in there and we don't have a
pretty good record, we'll hear it,'' Bonilla said before Tuesday's
game.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Mets heard cheers from the crowd of 18,075 at Pro
Player Stadium Tuesday night, a considerable number of those in
attendance rooting for the New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   Reed cruised through the Marlin order his first time through.
The 33-year-old right-hander's control was precise. And Reed was
perfect through three, with four strikeouts after striking out the
side in the second.
</P>
<P>
   Last June he pitched six and two-thirds perfect innings against
Tampa Bay at Shea Stadium, then tossed six and a third perfect
innings against the Marlins at Shea before losing the game.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, Reed was perfect through three and two-thirds
innings after Alfonzo made a diving stab to his left to rob Alex
Gonzalez of a hit. Reed walked the next batter, Mark Kotsay. But
Reed then struck out Derrek Lee to take the no-hitter into the
fifth. By the time he was removed for a pinch-hitter in the top of
the seventh, Reed had allowed just four hits and one run with two
walks and six strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   And, thanks to a run-scoring seventh-inning single from Ventura
with the bases loaded followed by a McRae sacrifice fly, the Mets
were up, 11-1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
