<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-WIZARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS TALK BIG AFTER FOURTH IN A ROW
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Nets are rolling like a boulder down a steep
hill now and their momentum is such that nobody, in their minds,
can stop them. With 4-0 written in big, blue letters on the
chalkboard of the visitors' locker room at the MCI Center on
Tuesday night, they talked about confidence, destiny, intimidation.
</P>
<P>
   Has their winning streak gone to their head? Yes. But that might
not be a bad thing. It certainly wasn't Tuesday night, when they
defeated the Washington Wizards, 97-93, for their fourth straight
victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets' confidence, sky high for a club with a 9-24 record,
was one of the things that helped them overcome the athletic but
disheveled Wizards, who were playing their first game after firing
Bernie Bickerstaff as coach on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   After being outplayed for the better part of three quarters, the
Nets were cool down the stretch, while Washington, under interim
coach Jim Brovelli, crumbled.
</P>
<P>
   With the game tied at 87-87 and 4 minutes 18 seconds left, the
Nets held the Wizards scoreless for more than three minutes to grab
a 93-87 lead and the game. Stephon Marbury, who led all scorers
with 29 points, was again strong in the clutch, starting the
game-clinching 6-0 run with a 3 pointer. Mark Hendrickson added a
free throw and Kerry Kittles a 9-foot running jumper.
</P>
<P>
   But the Nets got plenty of help from the Wizards, who in
dropping to 13-20 were outscored in the fourth quarter for the 26th
time this season. Rod Strickland (14 points, 14 assists) made a
turnover during the key stretch and Mitch Richmond, a perennial
all-star, inexplicably lost the ball out of bounds while driving
for a wide-open layup.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall Gill, who continued his steals' spree with 5 Tuesday
night, said those were signs the Nets' were beginning to intimidate
their opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we can shut people down,'' said Gill, who has 31
steals in the last five games. ``We know people are afraid of us.
We're ball hawkers. We can see it on their faces. They're thinking
_ should I pass this or should I shoot?''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, but the Wizards blitzed the Nets' defense for 50
percent shooting and committed only 16 turnovers. Washington was
done in by its own lack of aggressiveness _ it was an incredibly
low 4 of 5 from the foul line.
</P>
<P>
   But let the Nets' bask. It has been a rough season. Things are
going so well for the Nets that they won even without Keith Van
Horn playing most of the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn (26 points, 13 rebounds) tweaked a tendon in his right
ankle with 7 minutes, 9 seconds left and the Nets ahead by 83-80.
Van Horn, who said the injury was not serious and that he would
play Wednesday against Philadelphia, returned to shoot free throws
in the clutch and made 2 of 2.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Feick assisted Van Horn on the backboards with another
strong 12-point, 10-rebound performance. Marbury outscored the
opposing point guard for the 14th time since joining the Nets 14
games ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
