<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 23:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8504 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-BRONX-RUINS-ART-2T     04-06 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BRONX-RUINS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART CAPTURES THE CHANGING BRONX 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The film ``Fort Apache, the Bronx'' begins with a
disclaimer: ``The picture you are about to see is a portrayal of
the lives of two policemen working out of a precinct in the South
Bronx, New York. Because the story involves police work, it does
not deal with the law-abiding members of the community nor does it
dramatize the efforts of the individuals and groups who are
struggling to turn the Bronx around.''
</P>
<P>
   From then on, it dramatizes a parade of prostitutes and pimps,
junkies and psychopaths, women on welfare and the men who rob them,
all doing their thing against a backdrop of rubble and decay.
Filmed in 1981, at the height of the South Bronx's ``troubles,''
the movie immortalized the borough as an unparalleled urban
wasteland, as a circle of hell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fort Apache'' was not the first movie to transfigure the
Bronx's pain into high drama or low art, nor would it be the last.
Starting in the late 1960s, the Bronx was devastated by arson and
abandonment. Its population dwindled, its poverty deepened. By the
late 1970s, politicians were making pilgrimages to the devastated
area, offering condolences but little else. It was a canvas ripe
for painting with broad strokes.
</P>
<P>
   But today the South Bronx, which was the epicenter of the
decline, is on the upswing, though its rebound has received
considerably less attention than its slide. Many of the vacant lots
and the deserted buildings have been filled or replaced with some
30,000 new homes. Some of the upturn is in the area around what was
nicknamed Fort Apache, the police department's 41st Precinct
station house. This is a heartening contrast to the once desolate
landscape, where the station house took on the name Little House on
the Prairie because of its bleak isolation. There is still ample
poverty and crime, but more and more of the Bronx is surprisingly
normal these days.
</P>
<P>
   And so it is a good time to examine how the Bronx has been
construed in art and mass media over the past three decades, and
the Bronx Museum of the Arts, in a former synagogue on the Grand
Concourse, is doing just that. On Thursday, it unveils ``Urban
Mythologies: The Bronx Represented Since the 1960s,'' which uses a
dizzying array of images to explore how the Bronx has been
perceived.
</P>
<P>
   On view are more than 150 works by about 40 artists, reflecting
the 1960s to the present. The works include film, graffiti,
documentary photography, sculpture and painting.
</P>
<P>
   With its wealth of work by Bronx-based artists, the exhibition
also shows that where the outside world saw only wanton
destruction, there was also plenty of creation. ``Even at its
moments of misery and anguish _ and in some sense, I think, because
of its misery and anguish _ the Bronx became more culturally
creative than it had ever been in its life,'' Marshall Berman, a
political science professor at the City University of New York, who
grew up in the Bronx, writes in the exhibition catalog's
introduction. All sorts of new art forms _ graffiti, hip-hop, rap,
break dancing _ were either born or exploded in the Bronx in the
1970s.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition implicitly raises this question: As the Bronx
changes, how is its art changing as well? The answer, it seems, is
that it is less dramatic, less confrontational, perhaps more
complicated, and certainly more intimate.
</P>
<P>
   And as Berman noted, there is certainly less art about the
Bronx. ``It isn't in the news very much. It doesn't signify the way
it used to. You could say the Bronx has lost its aura,'' he writes.
``Should we be sad? I don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   An exhibition that reflects the pain the Bronx endured, and the
distorted way it was often portrayed, would not have been possible
just five years ago, one of its curators, Betti-Sue Hertz, mused
recently; the terrain was just too painful, too personal. ``There
is a renaissance now,'' she said. ``We can look at the negative
imagery.''
</P>
<P>
   But things have changed, and the photographs of Camilo Jose
Vergara encapsulate just how much. Taken at the same spot every few
years, his photographs record, almost clinically, the abandonment,
decay and demolition of buildings, like those at the corner of Vyse
Avenue and 178th Street and along Charlotte Street. But the
sequences of photographs have new codas: freshly built two-story
homes or, on Charlotte Street, incongruous ranch houses.
</P>
<P>
   Like Vergara's photographs, much of the exhibition is
chronological. But the show's point is also to demonstrate that
things were never as linear, as black-and-white as they seemed,
that the ruins did not vanquish lives, love and laughter, but
co-existed with them.
</P>
<P>
   Berman quotes a passage from Grace Paley's story ``Somewhere
Else'': ``You know that nice park in the South Bronx? We have some
film if you ever want to see _ the block is burning down on one
side of the street, and the kids are trying to build something on
the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Which side you saw depended largely on what you were looking
for. Consider Mel Rosenthal, who, photographing ruins, was
confronted by a resident asking why he never took pictures of the
people. He began doing just that, and his pictures capture the joy
amid the rubble. Carlos Ortiz, a Bronx-born photographer who
watched his neighborhood along Longwood Avenue decline, also tried
to capture the decay and his neighbors' resiliency in the face of
it.
</P>
<P>
   Until the late 1960s, the Bronx was known, as the Works Project
Administration guide to New York City put it in the 1930s, for ``a
cocktail, a jeer or a zoo.'' It was not a name that carried meaning
the way Brooklyn did. But deterioration, particularly in the South
Bronx, brought an unshakable identity. It evoked analogies to
Dresden after the war and images like ``Fort Apache, the Bronx.''
</P>
<P>
   Such extremes drew outsiders, whether from Manhattan or Europe,
to work in the Bronx. Their work was often about the ordinary, not
the extreme. For example, the sculptor John Ahearn, who often
worked with a local sculptor, Rigoberto Torres, cast Bronx
residents to create spirited, expressive sculptures.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ahearn worked at Fashion Moda, a Bronx gallery founded in 1978
by an Austrian, Stefan Eins, who sought to give the spirit of
collaboration a physical space. Fashion Moda, on Third Avenue near
147th Street, attracted neighborhood residents, graffiti writers
from the Bronx and downtown artists, building a bridge between
Manhattan and the northern borough. The facade, as painted by a
graffiti artist named Crash, has been re-created at the Bronx
Museum, with artwork from some of its exhibits hung inside.
</P>
<P>
   Other artists tried to build similar bridges. For his series
``Bronx Floors,'' the conceptual artist Gordon Matta-Clark cut
pieces out of buildings hovering between abandonment and
demolition, photographing the cutouts, then making art with the
pieces and displaying it in a SoHo gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, residents living with the crime and decay were
sensitive to the artists, film crews, politicians and journalists
who traipsed through, mouths agape, staring at the burned buildings
but often overlooking the people who lived in them or once did.
</P>
<P>
   So Bronx residents created their own forms of expression, taking
the graffiti that was appearing throughout the city to a new
dimension, and creating hip-hop, rap and break dancing. The
exhibition features the work of graffiti artists like Daze and
Phase 2, who combined dystopic and utopic images, and those who
documented their work.
</P>
<P>
   Graffiti's heyday is over, but its legacy remains in the
cartoonish signage so popular in the Bronx, and in young graffiti
artists like Tats Cru, a South Bronx group that has managed to
combine the vernacular, in the form of memorial walls for local
residents (including one done for the exhibit), and the
entrepreneurial, securing corporate commissions.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over whether graffiti is art or vandalism has abated
with both sides claiming victory. But graffiti is undeniably a form
of self-expression and self-definition, such as in the way graffiti
painters choose their own names and sign them everywhere. That same
desire for self-definition _ culturally as well as geographically _
drives much of the art in the exhibition, which contrasts it with
Hollywood film clips and other myth-making machinery.
</P>
<P>
   Sophie Rivera, for example, displays large-scale photographs of
young Latinos who look into the camera, dignity intact. And Pepon
Osorio has re-created a baroque installation from the 1993 Whitney
Biennial, ``The Scene of the Crime: (Whose Crime?),'' which shows a
fabricated crime scene in a Latino home, mixing elements from
reality and Hollywood fiction. The work, Osorio said, was motivated
by the gap between the crude crime scenes he saw on film and
television, where even the victims seemed washed in sin, and those
he visited in real life, where signs of normal family life could
often be seen.
</P>
<P>
   The drive to define one's space as well as one's image motivated
Bronx community groups and activists to become involved in
architecture and urban planning in the 1980s, and the exhibition
includes several of their efforts. The members of Nos Quedamos
(``We Stay'') challenged the city's urban renewal plan for their
Melrose neighborhood, for example, and now are implementing their
own design.
</P>
<P>
   The plans are on display; so is the model for the vision of the
South Bronx Academy of Art, designed by the Italian architect Aldo
Rossi at the behest of the teacher Tim Rollins, who formed the
remarkably successful artists' collective Kids of Survival with a
group of Bronx students.
</P>
<P>
   None of these groups made it into movies like ``Fort Apache, the
Bronx'' as its disclaimer so forthrightly notes. But as this
exhibition so powerfully demonstrates, that does not mean they were
not there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-99 2350EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
