<HEADLINE>
INJURY TO ARNOTT FORCES DEVILS TO JUGGLE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENSBORO, N.C. _ A recurring hip injury to Jason Arnott forced
the Devils to break up their most productive line Tuesday night
against the Carolina Hurricanes and the loss of Arnott showed in
the scoring sheet. The Devils suffered a 4-2 loss, ending their
eight-game undefeated streak, and will now have to wait another
game or two before they clinch their third straight Atlantic
Division title.
</P>
<P>
   Arnott has been the center for Petr Sykora and Patrik Elias and
that line had produced 32 points in the previous 10 games for the
Devils, whose record slipped to 42-23-11 with six games to play.
</P>
<P>
   Sykora and Elias came up empty Tuesday night and so did Brendan
Morrison, who took Arnott's place as the center for the two wings
from the Czech Republic. Scott Niedermayer and Sergei Nemchinov
scored the goals for the Devils after Carolina had scored all its
goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played well with Mo,'' Elias said, referring to Morrison.
``We got better as the game went, but couldn't score and didn't get
any breaks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We play the same way with Arnie as we play with Mo,'' Sykora
said. ``We had chances, but their goalie was good. They also got a
couple of goals early and we started scoring a little too late.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Roberts, Keith Primeau, Jeff O'Neill and Ray Sheppard had
the goals for the Hurricanes against Martin Brodeur, who allowed
four goals on only 15 shots, hardly a typical showing for the New
Jersey goaltender. Brodeur's counterpart, Arturs Irbe, made 31
saves.
</P>
<P>
   Before Tuesday night, the Hurricanes had scored more than two
goals only twice in their previous eight games, but they had no
problem scoring early and taking a 3-0 lead after two periods.
</P>
<P>
   On the first goal, Sean Hill dumped the puck from near the
Devils' blue line in an apparent attempt to give the Hurricanes a
chance to change lines. Brodeur went behind his goal to collect the
puck, but it bounced in front directly to Roberts, who put it into
the net while Brodeur was still behind his goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it bounces off the glass, you expect it to come in front
like that, but not off the boards,'' Brodeur said of the goal that
put the Hurricanes on the path to their first victory in four
games. The victory also helped Carolina avoid a series sweep by the
Devils, who won the first four meetings.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils have six games left to become the first team since
the Philadelphia Flyers in 1987 to capture a division title for
three consecutive seasons. The Flyers could end up playing the
Devils in the first round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   But New Jersey must win all three games left on the road to
break the league record of 27 road victories set by the Montreal
Canadiens in 1977-78. The Devils' road record is 25-10-3 and their
three road games remaining are at Montreal, Buffalo and Nashville.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
